0 @N00154@ NOTE (Federigo II d'Aragon “il Simplo” king of Sicily)
0 @N00155@ NOTE geni:about_me \- <http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/federico-iv-d-aragona-
1 CONT re-di-sicilia-detto-il-semplice_(Dizionario-Biografico)/>
1 CONT
1 CONT \---------
1 CONT /!\ numbering II - III - IV : -
1 CONT <https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federico_IV_di_Sicilia> \- fu Re di Sicilia
1 CONT (formalmente, Re di Trinacria), Duca di Atene e Duca di Neopatria, dal 1355
1 CONT alla sua morte.
1 CONT
1 CONT **Federico** , come sovrano di Sicilia, avrebbe dovuto adottare il numerale
1 CONT **III** , invece assunse il **IV** , conformandosi alla scelta operata da suo
1 CONT nonno, <https://www.geni.com/people/Federico-II-III-d-Aragona-re-di-
1 CONT Sicilia/6000000000153391275?through=6000000002372843490>, che avrebbe dovuto
1 CONT adotare il numerale II, ma preferì il III, in omaggio a
1 CONT <https://www.geni.com/people/Federico-II-Hohenstaufen-Sacro-Romano-
1 CONT Imperatore/6000000000424888017>, che era stato Re di Sicilia, ma che mai si
1 CONT disse Federico I di Sicilia. A ogni modo, in alcuni elenchi dei Re di Sicilia,
1 CONT Federico il Semplice è indicato con il numerale III. ( **Federigo II** on
1 CONT MedLans Projects)
1 CONT \------
1 CONT \- <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SICILY.htm#FederigoIIdied1377> \- FEDERIGO
1 CONT of Sicily (1 Sep 1341-Messina 27 Jul 1377). Marchese di Randazzo. He succeeded
1 CONT his cousin in 1355 as Duke of Athens and Neopatras. He succeeded his brother
1 CONT in 1355 as **FEDERIGO II “il Simplo”** King of Sicily, under the regency of
1 CONT his sister Eufemia of Sicily 1355-1357. In 1357, faced with mounting
1 CONT opposition in Sicily, King Federigo proposed that Athens and Neopatras be
1 CONT transferred to his sister Leonor, wife of Pedro IV King of Aragon, in return
1 CONT for military help from the latter in Sicily, a proposal which was
1 CONT refused[428]. The dispute with the Anjou Kings of Sicily was settled at Aversa
1 CONT 31 Mar 1373, with Federigo allowed to remain in occupation in Sicily but with
1 CONT the title King of Trinacria. Federigo II resisted pressure from Pedro IV King
1 CONT of Aragon, his father-in-law and brother-in-law, to assume greater power in
1 CONT Sicily and succeeded in having his daughter recognised as his heir.
1 CONT
1 CONT   * m firstly (Catania 11 Apr 1361) Infanta doña CONSTANZA de Aragón, daughter of don PEDRO IV “el Ceremonioso” King of Aragon & his first wife Infanta doña María de Navarra (Poblet 1340-Catania Jul 1363).
1 CONT
1 CONT   * m secondly ([17 Jan 1372/26 Nov 1373]) ANTONIA del Balzo, daughter of FRANCESCO del Balzo Duca d’Andria & his wife Marguerite di Tarento [Sicily-Anjou] (-23 Jan 1374, bur Messina).
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Mistress (1): ---. The name of Federigo's mistress is not known. King Federigo II & his first wife had one child:
1 CONT Frederick III the Simple
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick III or IV (1 September 1341 – 27 January 1377), called the Simple,
1 CONT King of Sicily from 1355 to 1377, was the second son of Peter II of Sicily and
1 CONT Elisabeth of Carinthia. He succeeded his brother Louis. The documents of his
1 CONT era call him the "infante Frederick, ruler of the kingdom of Sicily," without
1 CONT any regnal number.
1 CONT
1 CONT "Frederick the Simple" is often confused with an earlier Sicilian monarch,
1 CONT Frederick II, who chose to call himself "Frederick III", even though he was
1 CONT actually only the second King Frederick to occupy the Sicilian throne, as also
1 CONT this Fredrick has been dubbed by later generations of genealogists and
1 CONT historians as Frederick III.
1 CONT
1 CONT The beginning of Frederick III's reign was plagued by intermittent wars with
1 CONT the Kingdom of Naples and also by the Black Death, to which his elder brother
1 CONT and predecessor had succumbed. In 1372 he was able to come to peace terms with
1 CONT Naples and the Papacy and was titled as a Tributary King of "Trinacria."
1 CONT
1 CONT He appointed his uncle, Roland, to act on his behalf in the Duchy of Athens
1 CONT and Neopatria.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 11 April 1361, Frederick married his first wife Constança of Aragon,
1 CONT daughter of Peter IV of Aragon. They had only one daughter, Mary. On 17
1 CONT January 1372, Frederick married secondly Antonia of Balzo. There were no
1 CONT children from this marriage.
1 CONT Preceded by
1 CONT Louis King of Sicily
1 CONT 1355–1377 Succeeded by
1 CONT Mary
1 CONT Duke of Athens
1 CONT 1355–1377
