0 @N00288@ NOTE geni:about_me ==Links:==
1 CONT
1 CONT   * [<http://geneall.net/de/name/8581/manfred-re-di-sicilia/> Geneall]
1 CONT
1 CONT   * [<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manfred,_King_of_Sicily> Wikipedia]
1 CONT
1 CONT Manfred of Sicily was the King of Sicily from 1258 to 1266. He was an
1 CONT illegitimate son of the emperor Frederick II, but his mother, Bianca Lancia
1 CONT (or Lanzia), is reported by Matthew of Paris to have been married to the
1 CONT emperor while on her deathbed.
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick himself appears to have regarded Manfred as legitimate, and by his
1 CONT will named him as Prince of Taranto and appointed him as the representative in
1 CONT Italy of his half-brother, the German king, Conrad IV. Manfred, who initially
1 CONT bore his mother's surname, studied in Paris and Bologna and shared with his
1 CONT father a love of poetry and science.
1 CONT
1 CONT At Frederick's death, Manfred, although only about 18 years old, acted loyally
1 CONT and with vigour in the execution of his trust. The reign was in turmoil,
1 CONT mainly due to riots spurred by Pope Innocent IV. Manfred was able to subdue
1 CONT numerous rebel cities, with the exception of Naples. When his legitimate
1 CONT brother Conrad IV appeared in southern Italy in 1252, disembarking at Siponto,
1 CONT his authority was quickly and generally acknowledged. Naples fell in October
1 CONT 1253 into the hands of Conrad. The latter, in the meantime, had grown
1 CONT distrustful of Manfred, stripping him of all his fiefs and reducing his
1 CONT authority to the principality of Taranto.
1 CONT
1 CONT In May 1254 Conrad died of malaria. Manfred, after refusing to surrender
1 CONT Sicily to Innocent IV, accepted the regency on behalf of Conradin, the infant
1 CONT son of Conrad. However, the pope having been named tutor of Conradin, he
1 CONT excommunicated Manfred in July 1254. The regent decided to open negotiations
1 CONT with Innocent. By a treaty made in September 1254, Apulia passed under the
1 CONT authority of the pope, who was personally conducted by Manfred into his new
1 CONT possession. But Manfred’s suspicions being aroused by the demeanour of the
1 CONT papal retinue, and also annoyed by the occupation of Campania by papal troops,
1 CONT he fled to the Saracens at Lucera. Aided by Saracen allies, he defeated the
1 CONT papal army at Foggia on December 2, 1254, and soon established his authority
1 CONT over Sicily and the Sicilian possessions on the mainland. In that year Manfred
1 CONT supported the Ghibelline communes in Tuscany, in particular Siena, to which he
1 CONT provided a corps of German knights that was later instrumental in the defeat
1 CONT of Florence at the Battle of Montaperti. He thus reached the status of patron
1 CONT of the Ghibelline League. Also in that year Innocent died, succeeded by
1 CONT Alexander IV, who immediately excommunicated Manfred. In 1257, however,
1 CONT Manfred crushed the papal army and settled all the rebellions, imposing his
1 CONT firm rule of southern Italy and receiving the title of vicar by Conradin.
1 CONT
1 CONT The following year, taking advantage of a rumour that Conradin was dead, he
1 CONT was crowned king of Sicily at Palermo on August 10. The falsehood of this
1 CONT report was soon manifest; but the new king, supported by the popular voice,
1 CONT declined to abdicate and pointed out to Conradin’s envoys the necessity for a
1 CONT strong native ruler. The pope, to whom the Saracen alliance was a serious
1 CONT offence, declared Manfred’s coronation void. Undeterred by the excommunication
1 CONT Manfred sought to obtain power in central and northern Italy, where the
1 CONT Ghibelline leader Ezzelino IV da Romano had disappeared. He named vicars in
1 CONT Tuscany, Spoleto, Marche, Romagna and Lombardy. After Montaperti he was
1 CONT recognized as protector of Tuscany by the citizens of Florence, who did homage
1 CONT to his representative, and he was chosen "Senator of the Romans" by a faction
1 CONT in the city. His power was also augmented by the marriage of his daughter
1 CONT Constance in 1262 to Peter III of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT Terrified by these proceedings, the new Pope Urban IV excommunicated him. The
1 CONT pope first tried to sell the Kingdom of Sicily to Richard of Cornwall and his
1 CONT son, but in vain. In 1263 he was most successful with Charles, the Count of
1 CONT Anjou, a brother of the French King Louis IX, who accepted the investiture of
1 CONT the kingdom of Sicily at his hands. Hearing of the approach of Charles,
1 CONT Manfred issued a manifesto to the Romans, in which he not only defended his
1 CONT rule over Italy but even claimed the imperial crown.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles' army, some 30,000 strong, entered Italy from the Col de Tende in late
1 CONT 1265. He soon reduced numerous Ghibelline strongholds in northern Italy and
1 CONT was crowned in Rome in January 1266, the pope being absent. On January 20 he
1 CONT set southwards and waded the Liri river, invading the Kingdom of Sicily. After
1 CONT some minor clashes, the rival armies met at the Battle of Benevento on
1 CONT February 26, 1266, and Manfred's army was defeated. The king himself, refusing
1 CONT to flee, rushed into the midst of his enemies and was killed. Over his body,
1 CONT which was buried on the battlefield, a huge heap of stones was placed, but
1 CONT afterwards with the consent of the pope the remains were unearthed, cast out
1 CONT of the papal territory, and interred on the bank of the Garigliano River,
1 CONT outside of the boundaries of Naples and the Papal States.
1 CONT
1 CONT Manfred was married twice. His first wife was Beatrice, daughter of Amadeus
1 CONT IV, count of Savoy, by whom he had a daughter, Constance, who became the wife
1 CONT of King Peter III of Aragon; his second wife, who died in prison in 1271, was
1 CONT Helena Angelina Doukaina, daughter of Michael II Komnenos Doukas. Manfred's
1 CONT son-in-law Peter III became also King Peter I of Sicily from 1282 after the
1 CONT Sicilian Vespers expelled the French from the island again.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SICILY.htm#Manfreddied1266B>
1 CONT
1 CONT MANFRED von Hohenstaufen, son of Emperor FRIEDRICH II & his mistress Bianca
1 CONT Lancia (Venosa 1232-killed in battle Benevento 26 Feb 1266). The Thomas Tusci
1 CONT Gesta Imperatorum et Pontificum names "[illegitimus filius
1 CONT Frederici]…Manfredus" as son of "sorore marchionis Lancee", specifying that he
1 CONT and his sister were legitimated as a result of their father's declaration at
1 CONT the deathbed of their mother[658]. The Historia Sicula of Bartolomeo di
1 CONT Neocastro names "Manfredus et domina Constanza" as the children of "dominus
1 CONT Fridericus secundus…Romanorum…imperator" and ["his fifth wife"] "domina
1 CONT Blanca…de Lancea de Lombardia"[659]. He was bequeathed the kingdom of Sicily
1 CONT and 10,000 uncias under his father's testament[660]. Matthew Paris calls him
1 CONT "Memfredum filium Fretherici naturalem sed legitimatum"[661]. At the time of
1 CONT his first marriage, his father constituted him Lord of territory from Pavia to
1 CONT Genoa. The Istoria of Saba Malaspina records that "Manfredus" was invested
1 CONT with "principatu Tarentino" by his father[662]. "Manfredus…imp. Frid. filius"
1 CONT accepted the allegiance of "Henricum…fratrem nostrum et Petrum Ruffum de
1 CONT Calabria regni Siciliæ marescalcum", on behalf of "regis…Conradi", by charter
1 CONT dated 15 Dec 1250[663]. After Pope Innocent IV named Edward of England, son of
1 CONT Henry III King of England, as king of Sicily, Manfred forced the Papacy to
1 CONT recognise Konradin's rights and his own appointment as regent in Sicily[664].
1 CONT "Manfredus…imperatoris Friderici filius…princeps Tarantinus…montis sancti
1 CONT Angeli dominus et…regis Conradi secundi in regno Sicilie baiulus generalis"
1 CONT confirmed to "domino Raynerio Zeno…Veneciarum, Dalmacie atque Chroacie duci"
1 CONT the privileges granted to Venice by his father, by charter dated Sep
1 CONT 1257[665]. He deposed his nephew in 1258, and was crowned MANFREDO King of
1 CONT Sicily 10 Aug 1258 at Palermo, although this was not recognised by the Papacy.
1 CONT The monk Conrad´s Brevis Chronica records that "dominus Manfredus princeps"
1 CONT was crowned king at Palermo 10 Aug "primæ Indictionis"[666]. Pope Urban IV
1 CONT offered the kingdom of Sicily to Charles de France Comte d'Anjou who began
1 CONT preparations to invade and claim his rights. He defeated and killed King
1 CONT Manfred at Benevento.
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** firstly (Betrothed 8 May 1246, proxy Mar 1247, contract 21 Apr 1247,
1 CONT [Dec 1248/Jan 1249]) as her second husband, BEATRIX de Savoie, widow of
1 CONT MANFREDO III Marchese di Saluzzo, daughter of AMEDEE IV Comte de Savoie & his
1 CONT first wife Marguerite de Bourgogne ([1223][667]-10 May before 1259). ... ...
1 CONT ...
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** secondly (betrothed before Feb 1258, Trani 2 Jun 1259) HELENA Dukaina
1 CONT Angelina, daughter of MIKHAEL II Komnenos Dukas Angelos Lord of Epirus & his
1 CONT wife Theodora Dukaina Petraliphaina Basilissa ([1242]-in prison Nocera before
1 CONT 18 Jul 1271[675]). ... ... ...
1 CONT
1 CONT King Manfred & his first wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT King Manfred & his second wife had five children:
1 CONT
1 CONT King Manfredo had one illegitimate child by an unknown mistress:
1 CONT KING OF SICILY 1258-1266; POSSIBLY ILLEGITIMATE
