0 @N00309@ NOTE geni:about_me -<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helena_Angelina_Doukaina>
1 CONT
1 CONT Helena Angelina Doukaina (c. 1242 – 1271, Nocera Inferiore) was the second
1 CONT wife but only Queen consort of Manfred of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT She was a daughter of Michael II Komnenos Doukas, Ruler of Epirus and his wife
1 CONT Theodora Petraliphaina. Her father was often called Michael Angelos in
1 CONT narrative sources.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was a sister of Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas and a paternal half-sister of
1 CONT John I Doukas, Ruler of Thessaly.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandfather was Michael I Komnenos Doukas, illegitimate son of
1 CONT the sebastokratōr John Doukas.
1 CONT
1 CONT John Doukas was the eldest son of Constantine Angelos by Theodora Komnene, the
1 CONT seventh child of the Byzantine Emperor Alexios I Komnenos and Irene Doukaina.
1 CONT He adopted the surname of his maternal grandmother.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and children
1 CONT
1 CONT She was married to Manfred of Sicily sometime between the death of his first
1 CONT wife Beatrice of Savoy in 1257 and his own rise to the throne on 10 August
1 CONT 1258.
1 CONT
1 CONT Manfred was Regent of the Kingdom of Sicily since 1254, reigning in the name
1 CONT of his nephew Conradin. Michael II had lost the city of Dyrrhachium to
1 CONT Theodore II Laskaris of the Empire of Nicaea in 1256. Manfred had captured
1 CONT Dyrrachium and its surrounding area within the following two years. Michael II
1 CONT still had a territorial claim at the city but at the time was preparing to
1 CONT besiege Thessalonica.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her marriage was intended to maintain peace between Epirus and Sicily since
1 CONT both Michael II and Manfred had more pressing concerns elsewhere. Her dowry
1 CONT included all rights to Dyrrhachium and its surrounding area along with the
1 CONT island of Corfu. Corfu being the only actual territorial gain for Manfred.
1 CONT
1 CONT Helena and Manfred had five children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Sicily (c. 1258 - before 1307). Married first Rainer Gherardesca
1 CONT and secondly Manfred IV of Saluzzo.
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick of Sicily (c. 1259 - last mentioned alive in 1312).
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry of Sicily (c. 1260 - 31 October 1318).
1 CONT
1 CONT Enzio of Sicily (c. 1261 - c. 1301).
1 CONT
1 CONT Flordelis of Sicily (c. 1266 - last mentioned alive in 1297).
1 CONT
1 CONT Manfred was killed at the Battle of Benevento on 26 February 1266 while
1 CONT fighting against his rival and successor Charles I of Sicily. Charles captured
1 CONT Helena and imprisoned her. She lived five years later in captivity into the
1 CONT castle of Nocera Inferiore where she died in 1271.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT \----------------
1 CONT
1 CONT -<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ALBANIA.htm#HelenaAdied1271>
1 CONT
1 CONT -5. HELENA Doukaina Angelina ([1242]-Lucera Jul 1271). Georgius Phrantzes names "Manfredum Siculorum rege et principem Peloponnesi et Achaiæ" as the two sons-in-law of "Aetolorum et Epirotarum despota Michaele"[117]. Georgius Akropolites records th
1 CONC e marriage of "Michaelis…filiam Helenam" and "Manfredo Siciliæ regi"[118]. The Historia Sicula of Bartolomeo di Neocastro records that "Manfredum" married "Helenam filiam despoti regis Thessalie" after the death of his first wife[119]. Her marriage
1 CONC  was arranged as part of her father's peace treaty with Manfredo King of Sicily in 1258, her dowry of Corfu, Durazzo, Valona and Berat being the territories which King Manfredo had already conquered[120]. The Anonymous Chronicle of Trano records th
1 CONC at "filia de lu Despotu d’Epiru…Alena" arrived 2 Jun 1259 at Trani where she married "Re Manfridu"[121]. After her husband's defeat, she was captured trying to escape to Greece and imprisoned at Naples. She died in prison.
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** (betrothed before Feb 1258, Trani 2 Jun 1259) as his second wife,
1 CONT MANFREDO King of Sicily, illegitimate son of Emperor FRIEDRICH II & his
1 CONT mistress Bianca Lancia (Venosa 1232-killed in battle Benevento 26 Feb 1266).
