1 CONT Peter III of Aragon, 1239 – 2 November 1285, was the King of Aragon (as Peter
1 CONT III) of Valencia and of Majorca (as Peter I), and Sovereign Count of Barcelona
1 CONT (as Peter II) from 1276 to his death. He conquered Sicily and became its king
1 CONT in 1282. He was one of the greatest of medieval Aragonese monarchs.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter was the eldest son of James I of Aragon and his second wife Yolanda of
1 CONT Hungary. On 13 June 1262, he married Constance, daughter and heiress of
1 CONT Manfred of Sicily. During his youth and early adulthood, Peter gained a great
1 CONT deal of military experience in his father's wars of the Reconquista against
1 CONT the Moors.
1 CONT
1 CONT On James' death, the lands of the Crown of Aragon were divided, with Aragon
1 CONT and Valencia, along with the Catalan counties, going to the eldest son, Peter,
1 CONT while the Balearic Islands (constituted as the Kingdom of Majorca), alongside
1 CONT the territories in the Languedoc (Montpellier and Roussillon), went to the
1 CONT second son, James. Peter and Constance were crowned in Zaragoza (the capital
1 CONT of Aragon) in November by the archbishop of Tarragona. At this ceremony, Peter
1 CONT renounced all feudal obligations to the papacy which his grandfather Peter II
1 CONT had incurred.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter's first act as king was to complete the pacification of his Valencian
1 CONT territory, an action which had been underway on his father's death.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, a revolt soon broke out in Catalonia, led by the viscount of Cardona
1 CONT and abetted by Roger-Bernard III of Foix, Arnold Roger I of Pallars Sobirà,
1 CONT and Ermengol X of Urgell. The rebels had grown a hatred for Peter in response
1 CONT to the severity of his dealings with them in the days of his father. Now, as
1 CONT king, they opposed him for not summoning the Catalan corts, or assembly, and
1 CONT confirming its privileges.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the same time, a succession crisis continued in the County of Urgell. When
1 CONT Count Álvaro died in 1268, the families of his two wives, Constance, a
1 CONT daughter of Pedro Moncada of Béarn, and Cecilia, a daughter of Roger-Bernard
1 CONT II of Foix, began a long fight over the inheritance of his county. Meanwhile,
1 CONT a good portion of the county had been repossessed by James and thus inherited
1 CONT by Peter. In 1278, Armengol X, Álvaro's eldest son, succeeded in recovering
1 CONT most of his lost patrimony and came to an agreement with Peter whereby he
1 CONT recognised the latter as his suzerain.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1280, Peter defeated the stewing rebellion led by Roger-Berengar III after
1 CONT besieging the rebels in Balaguer for a month. Most of the rebel leaders were
1 CONT imprisoned in Lleida until 1281, while Roger-Bernard was imprisoned until
1 CONT 1284.
1 CONT
1 CONT When the Hafsid Emir of Tunisia, Muhammad I al-Mustansir, who had put himself
1 CONT under James the Conqueror, died in 1277, Tunisia threw off the yoke of
1 CONT Aragonese suzerainty. Peter first sent an expedition to Tunis in 1280 under
1 CONT Conrad de Llansa designed to re-establish his suzerainty. In 1281, he himself
1 CONT prepared to lead a fleet of 140 ships with 15,000 men to invade Tunisia on
1 CONT behalf of the governor of Constantine.[6] The fleet landed at Alcoyll in 1282
1 CONT and the troops began to fortify themselves in. It was these Aragonese troops
1 CONT that received a Sicilian embassy after the Vespers of 30 March asking Peter to
1 CONT take their throne from Charles of Anjou.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter was the direct descendant and the heir-general of the Mafalda, daughter
1 CONT of Robert Guiscard, Duke of Apulia, the Norman conqueror, and his official
1 CONT wife Sigelgaita, daughter of a Lombard prince, Guaimar IV of Salerno. Thus, he
1 CONT stood at the end of the Hauteville succession to Sicily. After the ducal
1 CONT family of Apulia became extinct with William II in 1127, Mafalda's heirs (then
1 CONT counts of Barcelona) apparently became de jure heirs of Guiscard and
1 CONT Sigelgaita: thus Peter was dormantly a claimant to the Norman succession of
1 CONT southern Italy. More directly, he was the heir of Manfred in right of his
1 CONT wife. The Two Sicilies were to be a tenaciously-pursued inheritance for the
1 CONT Aragonese royal house and its heirs for the next five centuries.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Italian physician John of Procida acted on behalf of Peter in Sicily. John
1 CONT had fled to Aragon after Charles' success at Tagliacozzo. John travelled to
1 CONT Sicily to stir up the discontents in favour of Peter and thence to
1 CONT Constantinople to procure the support of Michael VIII Palaeologus. Michael
1 CONT refused to aid the Aragonese king without papal approval and so John voyaged
1 CONT to Rome and there gained the consent of Pope Nicholas III, who feared the
1 CONT ascent of Charles in the Mezzogiorno. John then returned to Barcelona and the
1 CONT pope promptly died, to be replaced by Simon de Brie, a Frenchman and a staunch
1 CONT ally of Charles. The stage, however, had been set for a conflict.
1 CONT
1 CONT After receiving an embassy from the people of Palermo at Alcoyll, Peter landed
1 CONT at Trapani on 30 August 1282. He was proclaimed King in Palermo on 4
1 CONT September. Charles was forced to flee across the Straits of Messina and be
1 CONT content with his "Kingdom of Naples." Simon de Brie as the new Pope Martin IV
1 CONT excommunicated both Peter and the Byzantine emperor for providing Peter III
1 CONT with 60,000 gold pieces to invade Sicily (18 November).
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter nevertheless pressed his advantage and by February 1283 had taken most
1 CONT of the Calabrian coastline. Charles, perhaps feeling desperate, sent letters
1 CONT to Peter demanding they resolve the conflict by personal combat. The invader
1 CONT accepted and Charles returned to France to arrange the duel. Both kings chose
1 CONT six knights to settle matters of places and dates. A duel was scheduled for 1
1 CONT June at Bordeaux. A hundred knights would accompany each side and Edward I of
1 CONT England would adjudge the contest; the English king, heeding the pope,
1 CONT however, refused to take part. Peter left John of Procida in charge of Sicily
1 CONT and returned via his own kingdom to Bordeaux, which, evading a suspected
1 CONT French ambush, he entered in disguise. Needless to say, no combat ever took
1 CONT place and Peter returned to a very troubled Spain.
1 CONT
1 CONT While Peter was back in France and Spain, his admiral, Roger of Lauria, was
1 CONT wreaking havoc in Italy. He routed Charles' fleets on the high seas several
1 CONT times and conquered Malta for Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter was dealing with domestic unrest at the time when the French were
1 CONT preparing an invasion. He took Albarracín from the rebellious noble Juan Núñez
1 CONT de Lara, and he renewed the alliance with Sancho IV of Castile and attacked
1 CONT Tudela in an attempt to prevent the king of Navarre, Philip I, the son of the
1 CONT French king, from invading on that front.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter held meetings of the cortes at Tarragona and Zaragoza in 1283. He was
1 CONT forced to grant the Privilegio General to the newly-formed Union of
1 CONT Aragon.[12] Also in that year, Peter's brother James joined the French and
1 CONT recognised their suzerainty over Montpellier, giving them free passage through
1 CONT the Balearic Islands and Roussillon. In October, Peter began preparing the
1 CONT defences of Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1284, Pope Martin IV granted the kingdom of Aragon to Charles, Count of
1 CONT Valois, the son of the French king, Philip III the Bold, and great nephew of
1 CONT Charles. Papal sanction was given to a war — crusade — to conquer Aragon on
1 CONT behalf of Charles of Valois.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1284, the first French armies under King Philip and Count Charles entered
1 CONT Roussillon. They included 16,000 cavalry, 17,000 crossbowmen, and 100,000
1 CONT infantry, along with 100 ships in south French ports. Though the French had
1 CONT James' support, the local populace rose against them. The city of Elne was
1 CONT valiantly defended by the so-called bâtard de Roussillon ("bastard of
1 CONT Roussillon"), the illegitimate son of Nuño Sánchez, late count of Roussillon
1 CONT (1212–1242). Eventually he was overcome and the cathedral was burnt; the royal
1 CONT forces progressed.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1285, Philip entrenched himself before Girona in an attempt to besiege it.
1 CONT The resistance was strong, but the city was taken. Charles was crowned there,
1 CONT but without an actual crown. The French soon experienced a reversal, however,
1 CONT at the hands of Roger de Lauria, back from the Italian theatre of the drawn-
1 CONT out conflict. The French fleet was defeated and destroyed at the Battle of Les
1 CONT Formigues. As well, the French camp was hit hard by an epidemic of dysentery.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip himself was afflicted. The heir to the French throne, Philip the Fair,
1 CONT opened negotiations with Peter for free passage for the royal family through
1 CONT the Pyrenees. But the troops were not offered such passage and were decimated
1 CONT at the Battle of the Col de Panissars. The king of France himself died at
1 CONT Perpignan, the capital of James of Majorca, who had fled in fear after being
1 CONT confronted by Peter, and was buried in Narbonne. James was declared a vassal
1 CONT of Peter.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter matched his father in patronage of the arts and literature, but unlike
1 CONT him he was a lover of v
1 CONT
1 CONT As well, the wars with Philip of France and James of Majorca furnished
1 CONT material for new sirventesos and during this period the sirventes was
1 CONT converted into a convenient tool of political propaganda in which each side
1 CONT could, directly or allegorically, present its case and procure sympathy
1 CONT propitious to its cause.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter died at Vilafranca del Penedès on 2 November 1285, in the same year as
1 CONT his two royal foes, Charles and Philip, and was buried in the monastery of
1 CONT Santes Creus. His deathbed absolution occurred after he declared that his
1 CONT conquests had been in the name of his familial claims and never against the
1 CONT claims of the church.
1 CONT
