1 CONT Pedro III "el Grande" Kg av Aragonien o Sicilien
1 CONT OR "PEDRO"; KING OF ARAGON 1276-1285
1 CONT He ruled from 1276 to 1285. Ih inherited his father's military genius,
1 CONT conquering Sicily and generally stirring up matters between the Aragonese and
1 CONT the Angevins in southern Italy.
1 CONT (Research):Pedro III (Peter III) Peter the Great, 1239-1285, king of Arag≡n
1 CONT and count of Barcelona (1276-85) and king of Sicily (1282-85): son and
1 CONT successor of Jaime (James) I. In 1280 he established Aragonese influence on
1 CONT the northern shores of Africa. From his marriage (1262) to Constance daughter
1 CONT and heir of Manfred of Sicily,were derived the claims of the house of Arag≡n
1 CONT to Sicily and S Italy. After the insurrection of the Sicilian Vespers against
1 CONT Charles I of Anjou, Peter was offered the crown of Sicily and took possesion
1 CONT of the island (1282). Pope Martin IV excommunicated him and declared him
1 CONT deprived of his states on the basis of Peter II's declaration of vassalage to
1 CONT the Holy See. A crusade against Arag≡n was organized by the Pope and the
1 CONT French, who invaded Catalonia but were repulsed by Peter and defeated at sea
1 CONT by Roger of Loria. Peter's Sicilian ventyre was unpopular with the Aragonese
1 CONT nobility and towns, and he was compelled to grant them with wide privileges to
1 CONT quell their opposition. He founded the first university in Arag≡n at Huesca.
1 CONT Peter was succeeded in Arag≡n by his son Alfonso III, and in Sicily by his
1 CONT second son Jaime (James), (later James II of Arag≡n.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter III CPedro III "The Great" ) Encyclopædia Britannica Article born 1239
1 CONT died Nov. 11, 1285, Villafranca del Panades, Catalonia byname Peter The Great,
1 CONT Spanish Pedro El Grande king of Aragon from July 1276, on the death of his
1 CONT father, James I, and king of Sicily (as Peter I) from 1282. In 1262 he had
1 CONT married Constance, heiress of Manfred, the Hohenstaufen king of Sicily; and
1 CONT after the revolt of the Sicilians in 1282 he invaded the island and was
1 CONT proclaimed king at Palermo, despite strong Guelph and papal opposition (see
1 CONT Sicilian Vespers). His Sicilian enterprise was unpopular in Aragon, where an
1 CONT association of nobles and some municipalities, the Unión Aragonesa, forced him
1 CONT to grant a privilege not only confirming the Aragonese fueros (legal rights)
1 CONT but diminishing some of the crown's rights. In 1285 Philip III of France
1 CONT invaded Aragon to dethrone Peter but was disastrously defeated. Peter,
1 CONT however, soon died. His great stature and physical strength were famous. Among
1 CONT his children were Alfonso III of Aragon, James I of Sicily (II of Aragon), and
1 CONT Frederick III of Sicily.
1 CONT Son of James I, Peter was known for his great stature and physical strength;
1 CONT conquered Sicily and became its King; repelled French invasions 1285; forced
1 CONT by the nobles and towns to lesson rights of the crown. Peter came to the
1 CONT rescue of the rebellious Sicilians during the war of the "Sicilian Vespers",
1 CONT while Charles of Anjou, aided by his brother King Louis IX of France, dealt
1 CONT with the rebellion against them when Charles began control after the last
1 CONT Hohenstaufen rulers became extinct. Sicily was then under the Aragonese.
1 CONT Son of James I, Peter was known for his great stature and physical strength;
1 CONT conquered Sicily and became its King; repelled French invasions 1285; forced
1 CONT by the nobles and towns to lesson rights of the crown. Peter came to the
1 CONT rescue of the rebellious Sicilians during the war of the "Sicilian Vespers",
1 CONT while Charles of Anjou, aided by his brother King Louis IX of France, dealt
1 CONT with the rebellion against them when Charles began control after the last
