1 CONT GIVN Peter III King of
1 CONT SURN Aragon
1 CONT Peter III of Aragon
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter III (Catalan: Pere, Spanish: Pedro) (1239 – November 2, 1285), called
1 CONT the Great, was the king of Aragon and Valencia (as Peter I) and count of
1 CONT Barcelona (as Peter II) from 1276 to 1285.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1262, he married Constance, daughter and heiress of Manfred of Sicily.
1 CONT Peter gained much military experience fighting in the Reconquista during the
1 CONT reign of his father, James I. On James' death, the lands of the Crown of
1 CONT Aragon were divided, with Aragon and Valencia, along with the Catalan
1 CONT counties, going to the eldest son, Peter, while the Balearic Islands (the
1 CONT Kingdom of Majorca), alongside the territories in the Languedoc (Montpellier
1 CONT and Roussillon), went to the second son, James. Peter and Constance were
1 CONT crowned in Zaragoza (the capital of Aragon) in November by the archbishop of
1 CONT Tarragona. At this ceremony, Peter renounced all feudal obligations to the
1 CONT papacy which his grandfather Peter II had incurred. Peter first act as king
1 CONT was to comlete the pacification of his Valencian territory, an action which
1 CONT had been underway on his father's death. In 1278, a succession crisis in the
1 CONT County of Urgel was settled and, in 1280, Peter defeated a stewing rebellion
1 CONT led by Roger-Berengar III of Foix. In 1284 or thereabouts, his brother James
1 CONT declared a vassal of Peter for his kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT The emir of Tunisia, Muhammad I al-Mustansir, who had put himself under James
1 CONT the Conqueror, died in 1277 and Tunisia threw off the yoke of Aragonese
1 CONT suzerainty. Peter sent an expedition to Tunis in 1280 under Conrad de Llansa
1 CONT to re-establish suzerainty. In 1281, Peter prepared a fleet of 140 ships with
1 CONT 15,000 troops to invade Tunisia on behalf of the governor of Constantine. The
1 CONT fleet landed at Alcoyll in 1282 and began to fortify themselves in. It was to
1 CONT these Aragonese troops that Sicilians sent an embassy after the Vespers on
1 CONT March 30 asking Peter to take their throne from Charles of Anjou.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter himself was the direct descendant and the heir-general of Mafalda of
1 CONT Hauteville, daughter of Robert Guiscard, Duke of Apulia, the Norman conqueror,
1 CONT and his official wife Sigelgaita of Salerno, a Langobard princess. After the
1 CONT ducal family of Apulia became extinct with William II in 1127, Mafalda's heirs
1 CONT (then counts of Barcelona) apparently became de jure heirs of the Guiscard and
1 CONT Sigelgaita: thus Peter was dormantly a claimant to the Norman succession of
1 CONT Southern Italy. The Two Sicilies were to be a tenaciously pursued inheritance
1 CONT for the Aragonese royal house and its heirs for the next five centuries. Peter
1 CONT landed at Trapani on August 30, 1282. He was proclaimed King in Palermo on
1 CONT September 4. Charles was forced to flee across the Straits of Messina and be
1 CONT content with his "Kingdom of Naples."
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter also had to deal with the French relatives of Charles, who had the
1 CONT support of the pope. His navy, under the admiral Roger of Lauria, defeated the
1 CONT invading French crusaders at Roses, and his armies crushed them in the course
1 CONT of their retreat at the Coll de Panissars in 1285.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter left Aragon to his eldest son Alfonso III of Aragon, and Sicily to his
1 CONT second son James I of Sicily. Peter's third son, Infante don Fadrique, in
1 CONT succession to his brother James, became regent of Sicily and in due course its
1 CONT king. Peter had also a daughter, Elizabeth (Elisabet), who married Denis of
1 CONT Portugal.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the Divine Comedy Dante sees Peter "singing in accord" (d'ogni valor portó
1 CONT cinta la corda) with his former rival Charles I of Sicily outside the gates of
1 CONT Purgatory.
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT James I
1 CONT
1 CONT King of Aragon
1 CONT 1276–1285
1 CONT Succeeded by:
1 CONT Alfonso III
1 CONT Count of Barcelona
1 CONT 1276–1285
1 CONT King of Valencia
1 CONT 1276–1285
1 CONT Charles I King of Sicily
1 CONT 1282–1285 James
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT References
1 CONT Runciman, Steven. The Sicilian Vespers. 1958. ISBN 0521437741 — Considered a
1 CONT classic of history.
1 CONT Chaytoe, H. J. A History of Aragon and Catalonia. [1]
1 CONT BIOGRAPHY: King of Aragon, from 27 Jul 1276 to 2 Nov 1285.
