0 @N00363@ NOTE geni:about_me -<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_II_Komnenos_Doukas>
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael II Komnenos Doukas or Comnenus Ducas (Greek: Μιχαήλ Β΄ Κομνηνός
1 CONT Δούκας, Mikhaēl II Komnēnos Doukas), often called Michael Angelos in narrative
1 CONT sources, was the ruler of Epirus from 1230 until his death in 1266/68.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael was an illegitimate son of Michael I Komnenos Doukas of Epirus and had
1 CONT gone into exile after his father's murder in 1215. After the defeat and
1 CONT capture of his uncle Theodore Komnenos Doukas by Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria at
1 CONT the Battle of Klokotnitsa he returned to Epirus and became the ruler of the
1 CONT region. It is not entirely clear whether he recognized the supreme authority
1 CONT of his uncle Manuel Komnenos Doukas of Thessalonica or of Ivan Asen II of
1 CONT Bulgaria. Michael II secured the support of local notables by marrying
1 CONT Theodora Petraliphaina, and established a close relationship with the Empire
1 CONT of Nicaea. In 1241 Michael succeeded his uncle Manuel as ruler of Thessaly. In
1 CONT 1238, Michael was visited by the Nicaean Patriarch Germanos II and in 1249 he
1 CONT received the court dignity of despotes from Emperor John III Doukas Vatatzes.
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael II's relations with Nicaea ensured his neutrality during the conflict
1 CONT in which John III Doukas Vatatzes conquered Thessalonica and penetrated into
1 CONT northern Greece in 1244. However, when he was forced to surrender Dyrrhachium
1 CONT and Servia to the Nicaeans in 1256, Michael determined to expand his state at
1 CONT Nicaea's expense. However, while he was advancing towards Thessalonica, King
1 CONT Manfred of Sicily seized Dyrrhachium and its environs. Resolved to take
1 CONT Thessalonica, Michael came to terms with Manfred and sent him his daughter as
1 CONT wife, ceding the lost towns and the island of Corfu as dowry. He also
1 CONT concluded an alliance with Prince William II Villehardouin of Achaea.
1 CONT
1 CONT The troops of the three allies overran the Nicaean possessions in Macedonia
1 CONT and in 1259 prepared to fight the Nicaean army led by John Palaiologos, a
1 CONT brother of Emperor Michael VIII Palaiologos, on the plain of Pelagonia.
1 CONT Nevertheless, the allied operation was compromised by mutual suspicion and
1 CONT Michael's illegitimate son John Doukas deserted to the enemy, while Michael
1 CONT himself abandoned his allies. The Nicaeans inflicted a crushing defeat on
1 CONT Prince William of Achaea, who was captured in the battle. While Michael fled
1 CONT to the Ionian Islands, the Nicaeans occupied Epirus but they were faced with
1 CONT so much resistance that they were forced to withdraw. Michael recovered his
1 CONT domains with further help from Manfred. After further warfare another
1 CONT Byzantine victory in 1264 forced him to accept the nominal suzerainty of
1 CONT Michael VIII Palaiologos and to strengthen the bond by dynastic marriages.
1 CONT When Michael II died in or shortly before 1268, his domains were split between
1 CONT his sons Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas of Epirus and John I Doukas of Thessaly.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT By his marriage to Theodora Petraliphaina (St. Theodora of Arta), Michael II
1 CONT had several children, including:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas, who succeeded as ruler of Epirus
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * John Komnenos Doukas
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Demetrios (renamed Michael) Komnenos Doukas
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Helena Angelina Doukaina, who married King Manfred of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Anna Komnene Doukaina, who married (1) Prince William II Villehardouin of Achaea and (2) Nicholas II of St Omer, lord of Thebes.
1 CONT
1 CONT By his mistress Gangrene, Michael II had at least two other sons:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * John I Doukas, who succeeded as ruler of Thessaly
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Theodore Doukas
1 CONT
1 CONT \-----------
1 CONT
1 CONT -<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ALBANIA.htm#MikhaelEpirusdied1267B>
1 CONT
1 CONT MIKHAEL [KONSTANTINOS] Komnenos Doukas Angelos, illegitimate son of MIKHAEL
1 CONT Komnenos Doukas [Angelos] Lord of Epirus & his mistress ---
1 CONT ([1205]-[1267/68]). The primary source which confirms his parentage has not
1 CONT been identified. Baptised as KONSTANTINOS, he was known as MIKHAEL after the
1 CONT death of his father, whom he succeeded in [1215] as Lord of Epirus, under the
1 CONT guardianship of his uncle Theodoros who exiled him with his mother to
1 CONT Peloponnesos and seized the lordship[64]. He returned to Epirus after Bulgaria
1 CONT defeated Theodoros at Klokotniça in 1230, and installed himself at Arta as
1 CONT Lord of Epirus in [1231][65]. He was awarded the title despot, probably by his
1 CONT uncle Manuel titular emperor of Thessaloniki, in the 1230s. By 1236 he had
1 CONT expanded his authority over the whole of Epirus, as well as Corfu, acting as
1 CONT an independent prince free from the control of his uncle[66]. On the death of
1 CONT his uncle Manuel in 1241, he occupied the latter's territories in
1 CONT Thessaly[67]. He concluded a treaty with Emperor Ioannes III Batatzes, sealed
1 CONT by his son's betrothal to the emperor's granddaughter, but broke the treaty
1 CONT and attacked Thessaloniki in 1251. He made peace in 1253, losing much of his
1 CONT Albanian and Macedonian territories, although his title of despot was
1 CONT confirmed[68]. Forced to surrender Durazzo to Nikaia in 1256 in order to
1 CONT secure the release of his wife, he was held hostage after attending their
1 CONT son's marriage. Mikhael launched a military campaign to regain his lost
1 CONT Albanian and Macedonian lands. He halted his attack on Thessaloniki after
1 CONT Manfredo King of Sicily occupied Corfu, Durazzo and other Albanian towns, but
1 CONT made peace with King Manfredo in return for support against Nikaia, the
1 CONT alliance being confirmed by the king's marriage to Mikhael's daughter Helena,
1 CONT whose dowry consisted of the territories which Manfredo had already
1 CONT conquered[69]. Allied with King Manfredo and Guillaume de Villehardouin Prince
1 CONT of Achaia, he attacked Nikaia in 1259 but was defeated in the valley of
1 CONT Pelagonia in Autumn 1259, largely due to disunity among the allies[70]. Nikaia
1 CONT overran Epirus, but Mikhael regrouped with his illegitimate son Ioannes and
1 CONT expelled the Nikaians by 1260[71]. Mikhael rebelled again in 1264, but was
1 CONT obliged to swear allegiance to Emperor Mikhael VIII, confirmed by the marriage
1 CONT of his son Nikephoros to the emperor's niece. On his death, Mikhael's lands
1 CONT were divided between his son Nikephoros (who inherited Epirus) and his
1 CONT illegitimate son Ioannes (who took Thessaly)[72].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** ([1230], repudiated Easter [1252/56]) THEODORA Doukaina Petraloiphaina
1 CONT Basilissa, daughter of IOANNES Petraloiphas & his wife Helena --- (bur Arta).
1 CONT Ephræmius names "Theodora Michaelis coniux" when recording that she attended
1 CONT the marriage of her son Nikephoros[73]. Her parentage is indicated by Georgius
1 CONT Akropolites who names "Petraliphas…uxoris Michaelis frater"[74]. She was
1 CONT banished by her husband in favour of his mistress, but was later restored to
1 CONT favour[75]. After attending her son's marriage to the daughter of Theodoros II
1 CONT Emperor in Nikaia in 1256, she was held hostage and only released after her
1 CONT husband surrendered Durazzo to Nikaia[76]. She became a nun, known as Holy
1 CONT Theodora of Arta, and was the subject of a hagiography by the 13th century
1 CONT monk Job (Melias Iasites)[77].
1 CONT
1 CONT **Mistress** (1): GANGRENE, daughter of ---. The primary source which confirms
1 CONT her relationship with Mikhael has not been identified.
1 CONT
1 CONT **Mistress** (2): ([1252/56]) ---. Mikhael's mistress for whom he exiled in
1 CONT his wife in [1252/56][78]. Her name is not known. However, it is clear that
1 CONT she was a different person from the mother of his three illegitimate children
1 CONT shown below, who must have been born much earlier than the date Mikhael
1 CONT repudiated his wife.
1 CONT
1 CONT Mikhael [II] Komnenos Doukas Angelos & his wife had six children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Mikhael [II] Komnenos Doukas Angelos had three illegitimate children by
1 CONT Mistress (1):
1 CONT
1 CONT \-----
1 CONT As a condition of the marriage of his son Nicephorus to Maria, daughter of
1 CONT Theodore II, Theodore demanded the towns of Dyrrachium (later Durras,
1 CONT Albinia) and Servia (in Greece). Michael was enraged at this demand and war
1 CONT broke out that continued to be waged at the time of Theodore's death in 1258.
1 CONT As a condition of the marriage of his son Nicephorus to Maria, daughter of
1 CONT Theodore II, Theodore demanded the towns of Dyrrachium (later Durras,
1 CONT Albinia) and Servia (in Greece). Michael was enraged at this demand and war
1 CONT broke out that continued to be waged at the time of Theodore's death in 1258.
1 CONT As a condition of the marriage of his son Nicephorus to Maria, daughter of
1 CONT Theodore II, Theodore demanded the towns of Dyrrachium (later Durras,
1 CONT Albinia) and Servia (in Greece). Michael was enraged at this demand and war
1 CONT broke out that continued to be waged at the time of Theodore's death in 1258.
1 CONT As a condition of the marriage of his son Nicephorus to Maria, daughter of
1 CONT Theodore II, Theodore demanded the towns of Dyrrachium (later Durras,
1 CONT Albinia) and Servia (in Greece). Michael was enraged at this demand and war
1 CONT broke out that continued to be waged at the time of Theodore's death in 1258.
