1 CONT geni:about_me **Charles II** , known as "the Lame" (French le Boiteux, Italian
1 CONT lo Zoppo) (1254 – 5 May 1309) was; King of Naples (7 Jan 1285 - 5 May 1309);
1 CONT King of Albania (1285 - 1294); Prince of Salerno, Prince of Achaea Count of
1 CONT Anjou (1254 - 1290)
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II surrendered his rights to Albania to his son Philip II in 1294.
1 CONT Philip II reigned as "Lord of the Kingdom of Albania".
1 CONT
1 CONT Predecessor: Charles I Successor: Robert Spouse: Maria of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT Issue: Charles Martel of Anjou Saint Louis of Toulouse Robert of Naples Philip
1 CONT I of Taranto Raymond Berengar John of Anjou Tristan of Anjou Peter Tempesta
1 CONT John of Gravina Marguerite of Anjou Blanche of Anjou Eleanor of Anjou Maria of
1 CONT Anjou Beatrice of Anjou
1 CONT
1 CONT Father Charles I of Naples Mother Beatrice of Provence
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II, known as "the Lame" (French le Boiteux, Italian lo Zoppo; 1254 – 5
1 CONT May 1309), was King of Naples and Sicily, titular King of Jerusalem, and
1 CONT Prince of Salerno.
1 CONT
1 CONT Biography
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the son of Charles I of Anjou, who had conquered the Kingdom of Naples
1 CONT and Sicily in the 1260s. His mother was Beatrice of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the Sicilian Vespers, he had been captured by Roger of Lauria in the
1 CONT naval battle at Naples in 1284. When his father died in 1285, he was still a
1 CONT prisoner of Peter III of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1288, King Edward I of England mediated to make peace, and Charles was
1 CONT liberated on the condition that he was to retain Naples alone. Sicily was left
1 CONT to the Aragonese. Charles was also to induce his cousin Charles of Valois to
1 CONT renounce, for twenty thousand pounds of silver, the kingdom of Aragon, which
1 CONT had been given to him by Pope Martin IV to punish Peter for having invaded
1 CONT Sicily, but which the Valois had never effectively occupied.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was then released, leaving three of his sons and sixty Provençal
1 CONT nobles as hostages, promising to pay 30,000 marks and to return a prisoner if
1 CONT the conditions were not fulfilled within three years. He went to Rieti, where
1 CONT the new Pope Nicholas IV immediately absolved him from all the conditions he
1 CONT had sworn to observe, crowned him King of Sicily in 1289, and excommunicated
1 CONT King Alfonso III of Aragon. Charles of Valois, in alliance with Castile,
1 CONT prepared to take possession of Aragon, reopening the Aragonese Crusade.
1 CONT Alfonso, being hard pressed, agreed to the conditions of the Treaty of
1 CONT Tarascon: he had to promise to withdraw the troops he had sent to help his
1 CONT brother James in Sicily, to renounce all rights over the island, and pay a
1 CONT tribute to the Holy See.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso died childless in 1291 before the treaty could be carried out, and
1 CONT James took possession of Aragon, leaving the government of Sicily to the third
1 CONT brother Frederick.
1 CONT
1 CONT The new Pope Boniface VIII, elected in 1294 at Naples under the auspices of
1 CONT King Charles, mediated between the latter and James, and the dishonourable
1 CONT Treaty of Anagni was signed: James was to marry Charles’s daughter Bianca and
1 CONT was promised the investiture by the pope of Sardinia and Corsica, while he was
1 CONT to leave the Angevin a free hand in Sicily and even to assist him if the
1 CONT Sicilians resisted.
1 CONT
1 CONT An attempt was made to bribe Frederick into consenting to this arrangement,
1 CONT but being backed up by his people he refused, and was afterwards crowned King
1 CONT of Sicily. The ensuing war was fought on land and sea but Charles, though
1 CONT aided by the pope, his cousin Charles of Valois and James, was unable to
1 CONT conquer the island, and his son the prince of Taranto was taken prisoner at
1 CONT the battle of La Falconara in 1299. Peace was at last made in 1302 at
1 CONT Caltabellotta. Charles gave up all rights to Sicily and agreed to the marriage
1 CONT of his daughter Leonora and King Frederick; the treaty was ratified by the
1 CONT pope in 1303. Charles spent his last years quietly in Naples, which city he
1 CONT improved and embellished.
1 CONT
1 CONT He died in Naples in August 1309, and was succeeded by his son Robert the
1 CONT Wise.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1270, he married Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 – 25 March 1323), the daughter
1 CONT of Stephen V of Hungary and Elizabeth the Cuman. They had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Charles Martel d'Anjou, titular King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Saint Louis of Toulouse (9 February 1275, Nocera Inferiore – 19 August
1 CONT 1298, Chateau de Brignoles), Bishop of Toulouse
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Robert the Wise, King of Naples
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. Philip I of Taranto, Prince of Achaea and Taranto, Despot of Romania, Lord
1 CONT of Durazzo, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. Raymond Berengar (1281–1307), Count of Provence, Prince of Piedmont and
1 CONT Andria
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. John (1283 – aft. 16 March 1308), a priest
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. Tristan (1284–bef. 1288)
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. Peter (1291 – 29 August 1315, Battle of Montecatini), Count of Gravina
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. John of Gravina (1294 – 5 April 1336, Naples), Duke of Durazzo, Prince of
1 CONT Achaea, and Count of Gravina, married March 1318 (div 1321) Matilda of Hainaut
1 CONT (29 November 1293–1336), married 14 November 1321 Agnes of Périgord (d. 1345)
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. Marguerite (1273– 31 December 1299), Countess of Anjou and Maine, married
1 CONT at Corbeil 16 August 1290 to Charles of Valois
1 CONT
1 CONT 11\. Blanche of Anjou (1280 – 14 October 1310, Barcelona), married at
1 CONT Villebertran 1 November 1295 James II of Aragon
1 CONT
1 CONT 12\. Eleanor of Anjou, (August 1289 – 9 August 1341, Monastery of St.
1 CONT Nicholas, Arene, Elis), married at Messina 17 May 1302 Frederick III of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT 13\. Maria (1290 – c. 1346), married at Palma de Majorca 20 September 1304
1 CONT Sancho I of Majorca, married 1326 Jaime de Ejerica (1298 – April 1335)
1 CONT
1 CONT 14\. Beatrice (1295 – c. 1321), married April 1305 Azzo VIII d'Este, marchese
1 CONT of Ferrara etc. (d. 1308); she married secondly 1309 Bertrand III of Baux,
1 CONT Count of Andria (d. 1351)
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_II_of_Naples>
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the son of Charles I of Anjou, who had conquered the Kingdom of Naples
1 CONT and Sicily in the 1260s. His mother was Beatrice of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the Sicilian Vespers, he had been captured by Roger of Lauria in the
1 CONT naval battle at Naples in 1284. When his father died in 1285, he was still a
1 CONT prisoner of Peter III of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1288, King Edward I of England mediated to make peace, and Charles was
1 CONT liberated on the condition that he was to retain Naples alone. Sicily was left
1 CONT to the Aragonese. Charles was also to induce his cousin Charles of Valois to
1 CONT renounce, for twenty thousand pounds of silver, the kingdom of Aragon, which
1 CONT had been given to him by Pope Martin IV to punish Peter for having invaded
1 CONT Sicily, but which the Valois had never effectively occupied.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was then released, leaving three of his sons and sixty Provençal
1 CONT nobles as hostages, promising to pay 30,000 marks and to return a prisoner if
1 CONT the conditions were not fulfilled within three years. He went to Rieti, where
1 CONT the new Pope Nicholas IV immediately absolved him from all the conditions he
1 CONT had sworn to observe, crowned him King of Sicily in 1289, and excommunicated
1 CONT King Alfonso III of Aragon. Charles of Valois, in alliance with Castile,
1 CONT prepared to take possession of Aragon, reopening the Aragonese Crusade.
1 CONT Alfonso, being hard pressed, agreed to the conditions of the Treaty of
1 CONT Tarascon: he had to promise to withdraw the troops he had sent to help his
1 CONT brother James in Sicily, to renounce all rights over the island, and pay a
1 CONT tribute to the Holy See.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso died childless in 1291 before the treaty could be carried out, and
1 CONT James took possession of Aragon, leaving the government of Sicily to the third
1 CONT brother Frederick.
1 CONT
1 CONT The new Pope Boniface VIII, elected in 1294 at Naples under the auspices of
1 CONT King Charles, mediated between the latter and James, and the dishonourable
1 CONT Treaty of Anagni was signed: James was to marry Charles’s daughter Bianca and
1 CONT was promised the investiture by the pope of Sardinia and Corsica, while he was
1 CONT to leave the Angevin a free hand in Sicily and even to assist him if the
1 CONT Sicilians resisted.
1 CONT
1 CONT An attempt was made to bribe Frederick into consenting to this arrangement,
1 CONT but being backed up by his people he refused, and was afterwards crowned King
1 CONT of Sicily. The ensuing war was fought on land and sea but Charles, though
1 CONT aided by the pope, his cousin Charles of Valois and James, was unable to
1 CONT conquer the island, and his son the prince of Taranto was taken prisoner at
1 CONT the battle of La Falconara in 1299. Peace was at last made in 1302 at
1 CONT Caltabellotta. Charles gave up all rights to Sicily and agreed to the marriage
1 CONT of his daughter Leonora and King Frederick; the treaty was ratified by the
1 CONT pope in 1303. Charles spent his last years quietly in Naples, which city he
1 CONT improved and embellished.
1 CONT
1 CONT He died in Naples in August 1309, and was succeeded by his son Robert the
1 CONT Wise.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Family
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1270, he married Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 – March 25, 1323), the daughter
1 CONT of Stephen V of Hungary. They had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles Martel d'Anjou, titular King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT Saint Louis of Toulouse (February 9, 1275, Nocera Inferiore – August 19, 1298,
1 CONT Chateau de Brignoles), Bishop of Toulouse
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert the Wise, King of Naples
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip I of Taranto, Prince of Achaea and Taranto, Despot of Romania, Lord of
1 CONT Durazzo, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT
1 CONT Raymond Berengar (1281–1307), Count of Provence, Prince of Piedmont and Andria
1 CONT
1 CONT John (1283 – aft. March 16, 1308), a priest
1 CONT
1 CONT Tristan (1284–bef. 1288)
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter (1291 – August 29, 1315, Battle of Montecatini), Count of Gravina
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Gravina (1294 – April 5, 1336, Naples), Duke of Durazzo, Prince of
1 CONT Achaea, and Count of Gravina, married March 1318 (div 1321) Matilda of
1 CONT Hainault (November 29, 1293–1336), married November 14, 1321 Agnes of Périgord
1 CONT (d. 1345)
1 CONT
1 CONT Marguerite (1273– December 31, 1299), Countess of Anjou and Maine, married at
1 CONT Corbeil August 16, 1290 Charles of Valois
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche of Anjou (1280 – October 14, 1310, Barcelona), married at Villebertran
1 CONT November 1, 1295 James II of Aragon
1 CONT
1 CONT Eleanor of Anjou, (August 1289 – August 9, 1341, Monastery of St. Nicholas,
1 CONT Arene), married at Messina May 17, 1302 Frederick III of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria (1290 – c. 1346), married at Palma de Majorca September 20, 1304 Sancho
1 CONT I of Majorca, married 1326 Jaime de Ejerica (1298 – April 1335)
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice (1295 – c. 1321), married April 1305 Azzo VIII d'Este, marchese of
