1 CONT (Research):Encyclopedia Charles II Charles II (Charles the Lame), 1248-1309,
1 CONT king of Naples (1285-1309), count of Anjou and Provence, son and successor of
1 CONT Charles I. In the war of the Sicilian Vespers between Charles I and Peter III
1 CONT of Aragón for possession of Sicily, Charles was captured (1284) in a naval
1 CONT battle by the Aragonese. His father died while he was in captivity and Charles
1 CONT succeeded to the Neapolitan throne, although he was not crowned until 1289,
1 CONT following his release. The war in Sicily against James (James II of Aragón),
1 CONT son and successor of Peter III, continued until James's renunciation of Sicily
1 CONT and recognition of Charles II as king in 1295. The Sicilians, however, refused
1 CONT to accept the reestablishment of French rule and set up James's brother,
1 CONT Frederick II, as king; war was resumed. Finally, in 1302, after the failure of
1 CONT a French expedition to Sicily sponsored by Pope Boniface VIII, the Peace of
1 CONT Caltabellotta was signed; Charles II and Pope Boniface VIII agreed that
1 CONT Frederick II would remain king, but Sicily was to go to Charles or his heir on
1 CONT Frederick's death.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II Charles II (Charles the Lame), 1248-1309, king of Naples
1 CONT (1285-1309), count of Anjou and Provence, son and successor of Charles I. In
1 CONT the war of the Sicilian Vespers between Charles I and Peter III of Aragón for
1 CONT possession of Sicily, Charles was captured (1284) in a naval battle by the
1 CONT Aragonese. His father died while he was in captivity and Charles succeeded to
1 CONT the Neapolitan throne, although he was not crowned until 1289, following his
1 CONT release. The war in Sicily against James (James II of Aragón), son and
1 CONT successor of Peter III, continued until James's renunciation of Sicily and
1 CONT recognition of Charles II as king in 1295. The Sicilians, however, refused to
1 CONT accept the reestablishment of French rule and set up James's brother,
1 CONT Frederick II, as king; war was resumed. Finally, in 1302, after the failure of
1 CONT a French expedition to Sicily sponsored by Pope Boniface VIII, the Peace of
1 CONT Caltabellotta was signed; Charles II and Pope Boniface VIII agreed that
1 CONT Frederick II would remain king, but Sicily was to go to Charles or his heir on
1 CONT Frederick's death. ===================================================
1 CONT Name Prefix: King Name Suffix: Ii, Of Naples "The Lame"
1 CONT Charles II of Naples
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II, known as the Lame (Fr. le Boiteux) (born c. 1248, died 5 May 1309,
1 CONT Naples) was the King of Naples and Sicily, titular king of Jerusalem, and
1 CONT Prince of Salerno. He was a son of Charles I of Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT He had been captured by Roger of Lauria in the naval battle at Naples in 1284.
1 CONT When his father died, he was still a prisoner of Peter III of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1288 King Edward I of England mediated to make peace, and Charles was
1 CONT liberated only to retain Naples alone. Sicily was left to the Aragonese.
1 CONT Charles was also to induce his cousin Charles of Valois to renounce for twenty
1 CONT thousand pounds of silver the kingdom of Aragon which given him by Pope Martin
1 CONT IV to punish Peter for having invaded Sicily, but which the Valois had never
1 CONT effectively occupied.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was then released, leaving three of his sons and sixty Provençal
1 CONT nobles as hostages, promising to pay 30,000 marks and to return a prisoner if
1 CONT the conditions were not fulfilled within three years. He went to Rieti, where
1 CONT the new Pope Nicholas IV, immediately absolved him from all the conditions he
1 CONT had sworn to observe, crowned him King of Sicily in 1289, and excommunicated
1 CONT King Alfonso III of Aragon. Charles of Valois, in alliance with Castile,
1 CONT prepared to take possession of Aragon. Alfonso, being hard pressed, had to
1 CONT promise to withdraw the troops he had sent to help his brother James in
1 CONT Sicily, to renounce all rights over the island, and pay a tribute to the Holy
1 CONT See.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso died childless in 1291 before the treaty could be carried out, and
1 CONT James took possession of Aragon, leaving the government of Sicily to the third
1 CONT brother Frederick.
1 CONT
1 CONT The new Pope Boniface VIII, elected in 1294 at Naples under the auspices of
1 CONT King Charles, mediated between the latter and James, and a most dishonourable
1 CONT treaty was signed: James was to marry Charles’s daughter Bianca and was
1 CONT promised the investiture by the pope of Sardinia and Corsica, while he was to
1 CONT leave the Angevin a free hand in Sicily and even to assist him if the
1 CONT Sicilians resisted.
1 CONT
1 CONT An attempt was made to bribe Frederick into consenting to this arrangement,
1 CONT but being backed up by his people he refused, and was afterwards crowned king
1 CONT of Sicily. The ensuring war was fought on land and sea but Charles, though
1 CONT aided by the pope, his cousin Charles of Valois and James, was unable to
1 CONT conquer the island, and his son the prince of Taranto was taken prisoner at
1 CONT the battle of La Falconara in 1299. Peace was at last made in 1302 at
1 CONT Caltabellotta. Charles gave up all rights to Sicily and agreed to the marriage
1 CONT of his daughter Leonora and King Frederick; the treaty was ratified by the
1 CONT pope in 1303. Charles spent his last years quietly in Naples, which city he
1 CONT improved and embellished. He died in August 1309, and was succeeded by his son
1 CONT Robert the Wise.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II of Naples is known in Italian history books for one particularly
1 CONT crude episode, that is for his order to one of his commanders, Giovanni da
1 CONT Barletta, to destroy the town of Lucera, the last surviving Muslim community
1 CONT in Italy, as a way to celebrate the first Jubilaeum proclaimed by Pope
1 CONT Boniface VIII. The entire population of about 20,000 Arabs and Italian Muslims
1 CONT was exterminated in the summer of year 1300, ending five centuries of Muslim
1 CONT presence on Italian soil.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1270, he married Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 – March 25, 1323), the daughter
1 CONT of Stephen V of Hungary. They had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles Martel d'Anjou, titular King of Hungary
1 CONT Saint Louis of Toulouse (February 9, 1275, Nocera – August 19, 1298, Chateau
1 CONT de Brignoles), Bishop of Toulouse
1 CONT Robert of Naples, King of Naples
1 CONT Philip I of Taranto, Prince of Achaea and Taranto, Despot of Romania, Lord of
1 CONT Durazzo, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT Raymond Berengar (1281–1307), Count of Provence, Prince of Piedmont and Andria
1 CONT John (1283 – aft. March 16, 1308), a priest
1 CONT Tristan (1284–bef. 1288)
1 CONT Peter (1291 – August 29, 1315, Battle of Montecatini), Count of Gravina
1 CONT John of Gravina (1294 – April 5, 1336, Naples), Duke of Durazzo, Prince of
1 CONT Achaea, and Count of Gravina, married March 1318 (div 1321) Matilda of
1 CONT Hainault (November 29, 1293–1336), married November 14, 1321 Agnes of Périgord
1 CONT (d. 1345)
1 CONT Marguerite (1273– December 31, 1299), Countess of Anjou and Maine, married at
1 CONT Corbeil August 16, 1290 Charles of Valois
1 CONT Blanca (1280 – October 14, 1310, Barcelona), married at Villebertran November
1 CONT 1, 1295 James II of Aragon
1 CONT Leonora, (August 1289 – August 9, 1341, Monastery of St. Nicholas, Arene),
1 CONT married at Messina May 17, 1302 Frederick III of Sicily
1 CONT Maria (1290 – c. 1346), married at Palma de Majorca September 20, 1304 Sancho
1 CONT I of Majorca, married 1326 Jaime de Ejerica (1298 – April 1335)
1 CONT Beatrice (1295 – c. 1321), married April 1305 Azzo VIII, Margrave d'Este (d.
1 CONT 1308), married 1309 Bertrand III of Baux, Count of Andria (d. 1351)
1 CONT
1 CONT
