1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Born ca. 1200/1210 in Agliano Terme, Bianca was a member of the Lancia (or
1 CONT Lanza) family of Piedmont, so-called since her grandfather Manfred I had been
1 CONT lancifer of emperor Frederick Barbarossa. There is no source which
1 CONT definitively states who her parents were, historians have offered three
1 CONT theories:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1.That she was a granddaughter of Manfred I Lancia, as daughter of his
1 CONT daughter (maybe named Bianca), by a son (name unknown) of Guglielmo di
1 CONT Moncucco and Belda di Agliano.
1 CONT
1 CONT 2.That she was a granddaughter of Manfred I Lancia, as daughter of his son
1 CONT Bonifacio di Agliano by an unknown wife.[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT 3.That she was a granddaughter of Manfred I Lancia, as daughter of his son
1 CONT Manfred II, possible from a marriage to a lady called Bianca, of the Maletta
1 CONT family.
1 CONT
1 CONT If she was a daughter of Manfred II, she had seven siblings: four brothers
1 CONT (Manfred III, Guglielmo, Galvano and Frederick) and three sisters (Beatrice,
1 CONT Agnes and Isabella). Apparently, Bianca would be the third child and first
1 CONT born daughter.[2][3] But this is only one of three competing theories.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Relationship with Frederick II
1 CONT
1 CONT Bianca lived most of her life in the Castle of Boro, the ancestral residence
1 CONT of the Lancia family. She met Frederick II, who was then married to Yolande of
1 CONT Jerusalem, in 1225 at Agliano, near Asti. Thenceforth, it is said, the two
1 CONT maintained a romantic relationship.
1 CONT
1 CONT According to some historians, Bianca was the only true love of Frederick's
1 CONT life; others consider this a romantic exaggeration. It was certainly
1 CONT beneficial to the interests of the Lancia family, who were favoured by the
1 CONT Emperor with political posts in Italy (Manfredo III was appointed Imperial
1 CONT Vicar of the Holy Roman Empire's northern Italian territories and Podesta of
1 CONT Alessandria, Milan and Chieri; Galvano became Imperial Vicar of Tuscany,
1 CONT Podesta of Padova, Prince of Salerno, Count of Fondi and Grand Marshal of
1 CONT Sicily; and Frederick was appointed Count of Squillace and Viceroy of Apulia).
1 CONT Nonetheless, the relationship of Bianca and Frederick was the longest to all
1 CONT the affairs of the Emperor.
1 CONT
1 CONT After the death of Queen Isabella of England, Frederick's third wife, in 1241,
1 CONT he endowed Bianca with the castle of Monte Sant'Angelo, located in the cities
1 CONT of Vieste and Siponto. By the terms of the will of William II of Sicily, the
1 CONT castle was the traditional dowry of the Sicilian queens consort.
1 CONT
1 CONT Bianca died either in the castle of Paternò or the castle of Gioia del Colle.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marriage and Children
1 CONT
1 CONT The Chronicle of Salimbene di Adam, and also Matthew of Paris claimed that a
1 CONT "confirmatio matrimonii in articulo mortis" ("marriage ceremony in the moments
1 CONT of death") took place between Bianca and Frederick when she was dying. Bianca,
1 CONT apparently, desired the marriage for the salvation of her soul and the safety
1 CONT of their children's future.[4][5] This marriage however was not deemed
1 CONT canonical by the Church.
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick and Bianca had three children together:
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance (1230-1307), who married the Emperor of Nicea, John Vatatzes, and
1 CONT thereupon her name changed to Anna.
1 CONT
1 CONT Manfred (1232-1266), who succeeded his father as ruler of Sicily (initially as
1 CONT regent, before usurping the throne for himself).
1 CONT
1 CONT Violante (1233-1264), who married Richard Sanseverino, Count of Caserta.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Death
1 CONT
1 CONT It is not known exactly when she died. There are several conflicting reports.
1 CONT Although the Medlands database gives 1233/1234, Medlands is not reliable for
1 CONT unsourced claims. This date lingers in various reference works but appears
1 CONT based only on the assumption that she died after the birth of her last child,
1 CONT and before the marriage of her husband to his next wife.
1 CONT
1 CONT There are credible reports that she married Frederick while she was on her
1 CONT deathbed, and that her son was 12 at this time. Bianca may have died a short
1 CONT while before the wedding of her daughter to Ioannes Batatzes in 1244.[6] One
1 CONT source states that she died 20 years after the start of her relationship with
1 CONT Frederick, however the same source states that she died 20 years before events
1 CONT that were occurring in 1256. All of these cannot be simultaneously true.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Footnotes
1 CONT
1 CONT 1.^ "The mother of Manfred, King of Sicily, was a noblewoman named Blanche, of
1 CONT the family of the Marquis of Lancia and Loreto, in southern Lombardy. She was
1 CONT the daughter of Boniface, Count of Agliano (near Asti), one of the principal
1 CONT fiefs of Lancia. Even contemporaries were unsure of the exact degree of her
1 CONT relationship with the Marquis of Lancia, who had accompanied Emperor Frederick
1 CONT II to the East. They could not tell if she were his niece or his
1 CONT granddaughter." [Reference: Source: Paul Crawford, The 'Templar of Tyre': Part
1 CONT III of the 'Deeds of the Cypriots' (Crusade Texts in Translation 6) (2003),
1 CONT pg. 18, footnote 4]. Reference provided by Douglas Richardson on
1 CONT soc.genealogy.medieval 22 January 2008
1 CONT
1 CONT 2.^ Monferrato MONFERRATO, SALUZZO, SAVONA
1 CONT
1 CONT 3.^ Genealogy of the Lancia family
1 CONT
1 CONT 4.^ Matthew of Paris, Mon. Germ. Hist. Scriptores XXVIII pp. 360-361
1 CONT
1 CONT 5.^ Cronica Fratris Salimbene di Adam, Ordinis Minorem, MGH SS XXXII p.349
1 CONT
1 CONT 6.^ By this time, Frederick II's longtime enemy, the Duke Frederick of Austria
1 CONT became his most important ally, and, by reforce this new alliance, were make
1 CONT plans to a marriage between the Emperor and the teenager niece of the Duke,
1 CONT Gertrude. She refused the marriage.
1 CONT
