1 CONT Bianca Lancia From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Bianca Lancia d'Agliano (also called Beatrice and Blanche); was an Italian
1 CONT noblewoman, who was the mistress and later wife of emperor Frederick II of
1 CONT Hohenstaufen, although the marriage, conducted while she was on her deathbed,
1 CONT was considered non-canonical.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Born ca. 1200/1210, Bianca was a member of the Lancia (or Lanza) family of
1 CONT Piedmont, so-called since her grandfather Manfred I had been lancifer of
1 CONT emperor Frederick Barbarossa. There is no source which definitively states who
1 CONT her parents were, historians have offered three theories: That she was a
1 CONT granddaughter of Manfred I Lancia, as daughter of his daughter (maybe named
1 CONT Bianca), by a son (name unknown) of Guglielmo di Moncucco and Belda di
1 CONT Agliano. That she was a granddaughter of Manfred I Lancia, as daughter of his
1 CONT son Bonifacio di Agliano by an unknown wife.[1] That she was a granddaughter
1 CONT of Manfred I Lancia, as daughter of his son Manfred II, possible from a
1 CONT marriage to a lady called Bianca, of the Maletta family. If she was a daughter
1 CONT of Manfred II, she had seven siblings: four brothers (Manfred III, Guglielmo,
1 CONT Galvano and Frederick) and three sisters (Beatrice, Agnes and Isabella).
1 CONT Apparently, Bianca would be the third child and first born daughter[2] [3].
1 CONT But this is only one of three competing theories. [edit]Relationship with
1 CONT Frederick II
1 CONT
1 CONT Bianca lived most of her life in the Castle of Boro, the ancestral residence
1 CONT of the Lancia family. She met Frederick II, who was then married to Yolande of
1 CONT Jerusalem, in 1225 at Agliano, near Asti. Thenceforth, it is said, the two
1 CONT maintained a romantic relationship. According to some historians, Bianca was
1 CONT the only true love of Frederick's life; others consider this a romantic
1 CONT exaggeration. It was certainly beneficial to the interests of the Lancia
1 CONT family, who were favoured by the Emperor with political posts in Italy
1 CONT (Manfredo III was appointed Imperial Vicar of the Holy Roman Empire's northern
1 CONT Italian territories and Podesta of Alessandria, Milan and Chieri; Galvano
1 CONT became Imperial Vicar of Tuscany, Podesta of Padova, Prince of Salerno, Count
1 CONT of Fondi and Grand Marshal of Sicily; and Frederick was appointed Count of
1 CONT Squillace and Viceroy of Apulia). Nonetheless, the relationship of Bianca and
1 CONT Frederick was the longest to all the affairs of the Emperor. After the death
1 CONT of Queen Isabella of England, Frederick's third wife, in 1241, he endowed
1 CONT Bianca with the castle of Monte Sant'Angelo, located in the cities of Vieste
1 CONT and Siponto. By the terms of the will of William II of Sicily, the castle was
1 CONT the traditional dowry of the Sicilian Queen consorts. Bianca died either in
1 CONT the castle of Paternò or the castle of Gioia del Colle. [edit]Marriage and
1 CONT Children
1 CONT
1 CONT The Chronicle of Salimbene di Adam, and also Matthew of Paris claimed that a
1 CONT "confirmatio matrimonii in articulo mortis" ("marriage ceremony in the moments
1 CONT of death") took place between Bianca and Frederick when she was dying. Bianca,
1 CONT apparently, desired the marriage for the salvation of her soul and the safety
1 CONT of their children's future. [4] [5] This marriage however was not deemed
1 CONT canonical by the Church. Frederick and Bianca had three children together:
1 CONT Constance (1230-1307), who married the Emperor of Nicea, John Vatatzes, and
1 CONT thereupon her name changed to Anna. Manfred (1232-1266), who succeeded his
1 CONT father as ruler of Sicily (initially as regent, before usurping the throne for
1 CONT himself). Violante (1233-1264), who married Richard, Count of Caserta.
1 CONT [edit]Death
1 CONT
1 CONT It is not known exactly when she died. There are several conflicting reports.
1 CONT Although the Medlands database gives 1233/1234, Medlands is not reliable for
1 CONT unsourced claims. This date lingers in various reference works but appears
1 CONT based only on the assumption that she died after the birth of her last child,
1 CONT and before the marriage of her husband to his next wife. There are credible
1 CONT reports that she married Frederick while she was on her deathbed, and that her
1 CONT son was 12 at this time. Bianca may have died a short while before the wedding
1 CONT of her daughter to Ioannes Batatzes in 1244[6]. One source states that she
1 CONT died 20 years after the start of her relationship with Frederick, however the
1 CONT same source states that she died 20 years before events that were occurring in
1 CONT 1256. All of these cannot be simultaneously true.
1 CONT
