1 CONT b. 1243, d. 1311
1 CONT
1 CONT Source / Forrás: <http://thepeerage.com/p10680.htm#i106799>
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_I_of_Aragon>
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT James I of Aragon From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT James I the Conqueror (Catalan: Jaume el Conqueridor, Aragonese: Chaime lo
1 CONT Conqueridor, Spanish: Jaime el Conquistador, Occitan: Jacme lo Conquistaire; 2
1 CONT February 1208 – 27 July 1276) was the King of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and
1 CONT Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276. His long reign saw the expansion of the
1 CONT Crown of Aragon on all sides: into Valencia to the south, Languedoc to the
1 CONT north, and the Balearic Islands to the east. By a treaty with Louis IX of
1 CONT France, he wrested the county of Barcelona from nominal French suzerainty and
1 CONT integrated it into his crown. His part in the Reconquista was similar in
1 CONT Mediterranean Spain to that of his contemporary Ferdinand III of Castile in
1 CONT Andalusia. As a legislator and organiser, he occupies a high place among the
1 CONT Spanish kings. James compiled the Libre del Consulat de Mar,[1] which governed
1 CONT maritime trade and helped establish Catalan supremacy in the western
1 CONT Mediterranean. He made Catalan the official language of his domains[2] and
1 CONT sponsored Catalan literature, even a quasi-autobiographical chronicle of his
1 CONT reign: the Llibre dels fets.
1 CONT
1 CONT Early life and reign until majority
1 CONT
1 CONT James was born at Montpellier as the only son of Peter II and Mary, heiress of
1 CONT William VIII of Montpellier and Eudokia Komnene. As a child, James was a pawn
1 CONT in the power politics of Provence, where his father was engaged in struggles
1 CONT helping the Cathar heretics of Albi against the Albigensian Crusaders led by
1 CONT Simon IV de Montfort, Earl of Leicester, who were trying to exterminate them.
1 CONT Peter endeavoured to placate the northern crusaders by arranging a marriage
1 CONT between his son James and Simon's daughter. He entrusted the boy to be
1 CONT educated in Montfort's care in 1211, but was soon forced to take up arms
1 CONT against him, dying at the Battle of Muret on 12 September 1213. Montfort would
1 CONT willingly have used James as a means of extending his own power had not the
1 CONT Aragonese and Catalans appealed to Pope Innocent III, who insisted that
1 CONT Montfort surrender him. James was handed over, at Carcassonne, in May or June
1 CONT 1214, to the papal legate Peter of Benevento. James was then sent to Monzón,
1 CONT where he was entrusted to the care of William of Montredon, the head of the
1 CONT Knights Templar in Spain and Provence; the regency meanwhile fell to his great
1 CONT uncle Sancho, Count of Roussillon, and his son, the king's cousin, Nuño. The
1 CONT kingdom was given over to confusion until, in 1217, the Templars and some of
1 CONT the more loyal nobles brought the young king to Zaragoza.[3] In 1221, he was
1 CONT married to Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and Leonora of
1 CONT England. The next six years of his reign were full of rebellions on the part
1 CONT of the nobles. By the Peace of Alcalá of 31 March 1227, the nobles and the
1 CONT king came to terms.[4] [edit]Acquisition of Urgell
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1228, James faced the sternest opposition from a vassal yet. Guerau de
1 CONT Cabrera had occupied the County of Urgell in opposition to Aurembiax, the
1 CONT heiress of Ermengol VIII, who had died without sons in 1208. While Aurembiax'
1 CONT mother, Elvira, had made herself a protegée of James' father, on her death
1 CONT (1220), Guerao had occupied the county and displaced Aurembiax, claiming that
1 CONT a woman could not inherit. James intervened on behalf of Aurembiax, whom he
1 CONT owed protection. He bought Guerau off and allowed Aurembiax to reclaim her
1 CONT territory, which she did at Lleida, probably also becoming one of James'
1 CONT earliest mistresses.[5] She surrendered Lleida to James and agreed to hold
1 CONT Urgell in fief from him. On her death in 1231, James exchanged the Balearic
1 CONT Islands for Urgell with her widower, Peter of Portugal.
1 CONT
1 CONT Relations with France and Navarre
1 CONT
1 CONT From 1230 to 1232, James negotiated with Sancho VII of Navarre, who desired
1 CONT his help against his nephew and closest living male relative, Theobald IV of
1 CONT Champagne. James and Sancho negotiated a treaty whereby James would inherit
1 CONT Navarre on the old Sancho's death, but when this did occur, the Navarrese
1 CONT nobless instead elevated Theobald to the throne (1234), and James disputed it.
1 CONT Pope Gregory IX was required to intervene.[6] In the end, James accepted
1 CONT Theobald's succession. James endeavoured to form a state straddling the
1 CONT Pyrenees, to counterbalance the power of France north of the Loire. As with
1 CONT the much earlier Visigothic attempt, this policy was victim to physical,
1 CONT cultural, and political obstacles. As in the case of Navarre, he was too wise
1 CONT to launch into perilous adventures. By the Treaty of Corbeil, signed in May
1 CONT 1258, he frankly withdrew from conflict with Louis IX of France and was
1 CONT content with the recognition of his position, and the surrender of antiquated
1 CONT and illusory French claims to the overlordship of Catalonia. [edit]Reconquista
1 CONT
1 CONT After his false start at uniting Aragon with the Kingdom of Navarre through a
1 CONT scheme of mutual adoption, James turned to the south and the Mediterranean
1 CONT Sea, where he conquered the Balearic Islands (Majorca 1229; Minorca 1232;
1 CONT Ibiza 1235) and where Valencia capitulated 28 September 1238. During his
1 CONT remaining two decades after Corbeil, James warred with the Moors in Murcia, on
1 CONT behalf of his son-in-law Alfonso X of Castile. On 26 March 1244, the two
1 CONT monarchs signed the Treaty of Almizra to determine the zones of their
1 CONT expansion into Andalusia so as to prevent squabbling between them.
1 CONT Specifically, it defined the borders of the newly-created Kingdom of Valencia.
1 CONT James signed it on that date, but Alfonso did not affirm it until much later.
1 CONT According to the treaty, all lands south of a line from Biar to Villajoyosa
1 CONT through Busot were reserved for Castile. [edit]Crusade of 1269
1 CONT
1 CONT The "khan of Tartary" (actually the Ilkhan) Abaqa corresponded with James in
1 CONT early 1267, inviting him to join forces with the Mongols and go on Crusade.[7]
1 CONT James sent an ambassador to Abaqa in the person of Jayme Alaric de Perpignan,
1 CONT who returned with a Mongol embassy in 1269.[8] Pope Clement IV tried to
1 CONT dissuade James from Crusading, regarding his moral character as sub-par, and
1 CONT Alfonso X did the same. Nonetheless, James, who was then campaigning in
1 CONT Murcia, made peace with Mohammed I ibn Nasr, the Sultan of Granada, and set
1 CONT about collecting funds for a Crusade. After organising the government for his
1 CONT absence and assembling a fleet at Barcelona in September 1269, he was ready to
1 CONT sail east. The troubadour Olivier lo Templier composed a song praising the
1 CONT voyage and hoping for its success. A storm, however, drove him off course and
1 CONT he landed at Aigues-Mortes. According the the continuator of William of Tyre,
1 CONT he returned via Montpellier por l'amor de sa dame Berenguiere ("for the love
1 CONT his lady Berengaria") and abandoned any further effort at a Crusade. I James'
1 CONT bastard sons Pedro Fernández and Fernán Sánchez, who had been given command of
1 CONT part of the fleet, did continue on their way to Acre, where they arrived in
1 CONT December. They found that Baibars, the Mameluke sultan of Egypt, had broken
1 CONT his truce with the Kingdom of Jerusalem and was making a demonstration of his
1 CONT military power in front of Acre. During the demonstration, Egyptian troops
1 CONT hidden in the bushes ambushed a returning Frankish force which had been in
1 CONT Galilee. James' sons, initially eager for a fight, changed their minds after
1 CONT this spectacle and returned home via Sicily, where Fernán Sánchez was knighted
1 CONT by Charles of Anjou.
1 CONT
1 CONT Patronage of art, learning, and literature
1 CONT
1 CONT James built and consecrated the Cathedral of Lleida, which was constructed in
1 CONT a style transitional between Romanesque and Gothic with little influence from
1 CONT Moorish styles.[9] James was a patron of the University of Montpellier, which
1 CONT owed much of its development to his impetus.[10] He also founded a studium at
1 CONT Valencia in 1245 and received privileges for it from Pope Innocent IV, but it
1 CONT did not develop as splendidly.[11] In 1263, James presided over a debate in
1 CONT Barcelona between the Jewish rabbi Nahmanides and Pablo Christiani, a
1 CONT prominent converso. James was the first great sponsor and patron of vernacular
1 CONT Catalan literature. Indeed, he may himself be called "the first of the Catalan
1 CONT prose writers."[12] James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of
1 CONT his own life, Llibre dels fets in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicle
1 CONT of a Christian king. As well as a fine example of autobiography the "Book of
1 CONT Deeds" expresses concepts of the power and purpose of monarchy; examples of
1 CONT loyalty and treachery in the feudal order; the growth of national sentiment
1 CONT based on homeland, language, and culture; and medieval military tactics. James
1 CONT also wrote the Libre de la Saviesa or "Book of Wisdom." The book contains
1 CONT proverbs from various authors going back as far as King Solomon and as close
1 CONT to his own time, such as Albert the Great. It even contains maxims from the
1 CONT medieval Arab philosophers and from the Apophthegmata Philosophorum of Honein
1 CONT ben Ishak, which was probably translated at Barcelona during his reign. A
1 CONT Hebrew translator by the name of Jehuda was employed at James's court during
1 CONT this period.[13] Though James was himself a prose writer and sponsored mostly
1 CONT prose works, he had an appreciation of verse.[14] In consequence of the
1 CONT Albigensian Crusade, many troubadours were forced to flee southern France and
1 CONT many found refuge in Aragon and Catalonia. Notwithstanding his early patronage
1 CONT of poetry, by the influence of his confessor Ramon de Penyafort, James brought
1 CONT the Inquisition into his realm in 1233 to prevent any vernacular translation
1 CONT of the Bible.[15]
1 CONT
1 CONT Succession
1 CONT
1 CONT The favour James showed his illegitimate offspring led to protest from the
1 CONT nobles, and to conflicts between his sons legitimate and illegitimate. When
1 CONT one of the latter, Fernán Sánchez, who had behaved with gross ingratitude and
1 CONT treason to his father, was slain by the legitimate son Peter, the old king
1 CONT recorded his grim satisfaction. At the close of his life, James divided his
1 CONT states between his sons by Yolanda of Hungary: the aforementioned Peter
1 CONT received the Hispanic possessions on the mainland and James, the Kingdom of
1 CONT Majorca (including the Balearic Islands and the counties of Roussillon and
1 CONT Cerdanya) and the Lordship of Montpellier. The division inevitably produced
1 CONT fratricidal conflicts. In 1276, the king fell very ill at Alzira and resigned
1 CONT his crown, intending to retire to the monastery of Poblet, but he died at
1 CONT Valencia on 27 July.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriages and children
1 CONT
1 CONT James first married, in 1221, Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and
1 CONT Leonora of England. Though he later had the marriage annulled, his one son by
1 CONT her was declared legitimate: Alfonso (1229–1260), married Constance of
1 CONT Montcada, Countess of Bigorre In 1235, James remarried to Yolanda, daughter of
1 CONT Andrew II of Hungary by his second wife Yolande de Courtenay. She bore him
1 CONT numerous children: Yolanda, also known as Violant, (1236–1301), married
1 CONT Alfonso X of Castile Constance (1239–1269), married Juan Manuel, Lord of
1 CONT Villena, son of Ferdinand III Peter (1240–1285), successor in Aragon,
1 CONT Catalonia, and Valencia James (1243–1311), successor in Balearics and
1 CONT Languedoc Ferdinand (1245–1250) Sancha (1246–1251) Isabella (1247–1271),
1 CONT married Philip III of France Mary (1248–1267), nun Sancho, Archbishop of
1 CONT Toledo (1250–1279) Eleanor (born 1251, died young) James married thirdly
1 CONT Teresa Gil de Vidaure, but only by a private document, and left her when she
1 CONT developed leprosy. James (c.1255–1285), lord of Xèrica Peter (1259–1318), lord
1 CONT of Ayerbe James also had several lovers, both during and after his marriages,
1 CONT and a few bore him illegitimate sons. By Blanca d'Antillón: Ferran Sanchis (or
1 CONT Fernando Sánchez; 1240–1275), baron of Castro By Berenguela Fernández: Pedro
1 CONT Fernández, baron of Híjar By Elvira Sarroca: Jaume Sarroca (born 1248),
1 CONT Archbishop of Huesca
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT James I the Conqueror (Catalan: Jaume el Conqueridor, Aragonese: Chaime lo
1 CONT Conqueridor, Spanish: Jaime el Conquistador, Occitan: Jacme lo Conquistaire; 2
1 CONT February 1208 – 27 July 1276) was the King of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and
1 CONT Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276. His long reign saw the expansion of the
1 CONT Crown of Aragon on all sides: into Valencia to the south, Languedoc to the
1 CONT north, and the Balearic Islands to the east. By a treaty with Louis IX of
1 CONT France, he wrested the county of Barcelona from nominal French suzerainty and
1 CONT integrated it into his crown. His part in the Reconquista was similar in
1 CONT Mediterranean Spain to that of his contemporary Ferdinand III of Castile in
1 CONT Andalusia.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a legislator and organiser, he occupies a significant place among the
1 CONT Spanish kings. James compiled the Libre del Consulat de Mar, which governed
1 CONT maritime trade and helped establish Aragonese supremacy in the western
1 CONT Mediterranean. He was an important figure in the development of Catalan,
1 CONT sponsoring Catalan literature and writing a quasi-autobiographical chronicle
1 CONT of his reign: the Llibre dels fets.
1 CONT
1 CONT Early life and reign until majority
1 CONT
1 CONT James was born at Montpellier as the only son of Peter II and Mary, heiress of
1 CONT William VIII of Montpellier and Eudokia Komnene. As a child, James was a pawn
1 CONT in the power politics of Provence, where his father was engaged in struggles
1 CONT helping the Cathar heretics of Albi against the Albigensian Crusaders led by
1 CONT Simon IV de Montfort, Earl of Leicester, who were trying to exterminate them.
1 CONT Peter endeavoured to placate the northern crusaders by arranging a marriage
1 CONT between his son James and Simon's daughter. He entrusted the boy to be
1 CONT educated in Montfort's care in 1211, but was soon forced to take up arms
1 CONT against him, dying at the Battle of Muret on 12 September 1213. Montfort would
1 CONT willingly have used James as a means of extending his own power had not the
1 CONT Aragonese and Catalans appealed to Pope Innocent III, who insisted that
1 CONT Montfort surrender him. James was handed over, at Carcassonne, in May or June
1 CONT 1214, to the papal legate Peter of Benevento.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was then sent to Monzón, where he was entrusted to the care of William
1 CONT of Montredon, the head of the Knights Templar in Spain and Provence; the
1 CONT regency meanwhile fell to his great uncle Sancho, Count of Roussillon, and his
1 CONT son, the king's cousin, Nuño. The kingdom was given over to confusion until,
1 CONT in 1217, the Templars and some of the more loyal nobles brought the young king
1 CONT to Zaragoza.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1221, he was married to Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and
1 CONT Leonora of England. The next six years of his reign were full of rebellions on
1 CONT the part of the nobles. By the Peace of Alcalá of 31 March 1227, the nobles
1 CONT and the king came to terms. Acquisition of Urgell
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1228, James faced the sternest opposition from a vassal yet. Guerau IV de
1 CONT Cabrera had occupied the County of Urgell in opposition to Aurembiax, the
1 CONT heiress of Ermengol VIII, who had died without sons in 1208. While Aurembiax's
1 CONT mother, Elvira, had made herself a protegée of James's father, on her death
1 CONT (1220), Guerao had occupied the county and displaced Aurembiax, claiming that
1 CONT a woman could not inherit.
1 CONT
1 CONT James intervened on behalf of Aurembiax, whom he owed protection. He bought
1 CONT Guerau off and allowed Aurembiax to reclaim her territory, which she did at
1 CONT Lleida, probably also becoming one of James' earliest mistresses. She
1 CONT surrendered Lleida to James and agreed to hold Urgell in fief from him. On her
1 CONT death in 1231, James exchanged the Balearic Islands for Urgell with her
1 CONT widower, Peter of Portugal. Relations with France and Navarre
1 CONT
1 CONT From 1230 to 1232, James negotiated with Sancho VII of Navarre, who desired
1 CONT his help against his nephew and closest living male relative, Theobald IV of
1 CONT Champagne. James and Sancho negotiated a treaty whereby James would inherit
1 CONT Navarre on the old Sancho's death, but when this did occur, the Navarrese
1 CONT nobless instead elevated Theobald to the throne (1234), and James disputed it.
1 CONT Pope Gregory IX was required to intervene. In the end, James accepted
1 CONT Theobald's succession.
1 CONT
1 CONT James endeavoured to form a state straddling the Pyrenees, to counterbalance
1 CONT the power of France north of the Loire. As with the much earlier Visigothic
1 CONT attempt, this policy was victim to physical, cultural, and political
1 CONT obstacles. As in the case of Navarre, he was too wise to launch into perilous
1 CONT adventures. By the Treaty of Corbeil, signed in May 1258, he frankly withdrew
1 CONT from conflict with Louis IX of France and was content with the recognition of
1 CONT his position, and the surrender of antiquated and illusory French claims to
1 CONT the overlordship of Catalonia. Reconquest
1 CONT
1 CONT After his false start at uniting Aragon with the Kingdom of Navarre through a
1 CONT scheme of mutual adoption, James turned to the south and the Mediterranean
1 CONT Sea, where he conquered Majorca on 10 September in 1229 and the rest of the
1 CONT Balearic Islands; Minorca 1232; Ibiza 1235) and where Valencia capitulated 28
1 CONT September 1238. Chroniclers say he used gunpowder in the siege of Museros
1 CONT castle.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his remaining two decades after Corbeil, James warred with the Moors in
1 CONT Murcia, on behalf of his son-in-law Alfonso X of Castile. On 26 March 1244,
1 CONT the two monarchs signed the Treaty of Almizra to determine the zones of their
1 CONT expansion into Andalusia so as to prevent squabbling between them.
1 CONT Specifically, it defined the borders of the newly-created Kingdom of Valencia.
1 CONT James signed it on that date, but Alfonso did not affirm it until much later.
1 CONT According to the treaty, all lands south of a line from Biar to Villajoyosa
1 CONT through Busot were reserved for Castile. Crusade of 1269
1 CONT
1 CONT The "khan of Tartary" (actually the Ilkhan) Abaqa corresponded with James in
1 CONT early 1267, inviting him to join forces with the Mongols and go on Crusade.[6]
1 CONT James sent an ambassador to Abaqa in the person of Jayme Alaric de Perpignan,
1 CONT who returned with a Mongol embassy in 1269.[7] Pope Clement IV tried to
1 CONT dissuade James from Crusading, regarding his moral character as sub-par, and
1 CONT Alfonso X did the same. Nonetheless, James, who was then campaigning in
1 CONT Murcia, made peace with Mohammed I ibn Nasr, the Sultan of Granada, and set
1 CONT about collecting funds for a Crusade. After organising the government for his
1 CONT absence and assembling a fleet at Barcelona in September 1269, he was ready to
1 CONT sail east. The troubadour Olivier lo Templier composed a song praising the
1 CONT voyage and hoping for its success. A storm, however, drove him off course and
1 CONT he landed at Aigues-Mortes. According to the continuator of William of Tyre,
1 CONT he returned via Montpellier por l'amor de sa dame Berenguiere ("for the love
1 CONT his lady Berengaria") and abandoned any further effort at a Crusade.
1 CONT
1 CONT James' bastard sons Pedro Fernández and Fernán Sánchez, who had been given
1 CONT command of part of the fleet, did continue on their way to Acre, where they
1 CONT arrived in December. They found that Baibars, the Mameluke sultan of Egypt,
1 CONT had broken his truce with the Kingdom of Jerusalem and was making a
1 CONT demonstration of his military power in front of Acre. During the
1 CONT demonstration, Egyptian troops hidden in the bushes ambushed a returning
1 CONT Frankish force which had been in Galilee. James' sons, initially eager for a
1 CONT fight, changed their minds after this spectacle and returned home via Sicily,
1 CONT where Fernán Sánchez was knighted by Charles of Anjou.
1 CONT
1 CONT Patronage of art, learning, and literature
1 CONT
1 CONT James built and consecrated the Cathedral of Lleida, which was constructed in
1 CONT a style transitional between Romanesque and Gothic with little influence from
1 CONT Moorish styles.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was a patron of the University of Montpellier, which owed much of its
1 CONT development to his impetus. He also founded a studium at Valencia in 1245 and
1 CONT received privileges for it from Pope Innocent IV, but it did not develop as
1 CONT splendidly. In 1263, James presided over a debate in Barcelona between the
1 CONT Jewish rabbi Nahmanides and Pablo Christiani, a prominent converso.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was the first great sponsor and patron of vernacular Catalan literature.
1 CONT Indeed, he may himself be called "the first of the Catalan prose writers."
1 CONT James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of his own life, Llibre
1 CONT dels fets in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicle of a Christian king.
1 CONT As well as a fine example of autobiography the "Book of Deeds" expresses
1 CONT concepts of the power and purpose of monarchy; examples of loyalty and
1 CONT treachery in the feudal order; and medieval military tactics. More
1 CONT controversially, some historians have looked at these writings as a source of
1 CONT Catalan identity, separate from that of Occitania and Rome.
1 CONT
1 CONT James also wrote the Libre de la Saviesa or "Book of Wisdom". The book
1 CONT contains proverbs from various authors going back as far as King Solomon and
1 CONT as close to his own time, such as Albert the Great. It even contains maxims
1 CONT from the medieval Arab philosophers and from the Apophthegmata Philosophorum
1 CONT of Honein ben Ishak, which was probably translated at Barcelona during his
1 CONT reign. A Hebrew translator by the name of Jehuda was employed at James's court
1 CONT during this period.
1 CONT
1 CONT Though James was himself a prose writer and sponsored mostly prose works, he
1 CONT had an appreciation of verse. In consequence of the Albigensian Crusade, many
1 CONT troubadours were forced to flee southern France and many found refuge in
1 CONT Aragon. Notwithstanding his early patronage of poetry, by the influence of his
1 CONT confessor Ramon de Penyafort, James brought the Inquisition into his realm in
1 CONT 1233 to prevent any vernacular translation of the Bible. Succession
1 CONT
1 CONT The favour James showed his illegitimate offspring led to protest from the
1 CONT nobles, and to conflicts between his sons legitimate and illegitimate. When
1 CONT one of the latter, Fernán Sánchez, who had behaved with gross ingratitude and
1 CONT treason to his father, was slain by the legitimate son Peter, the old king
1 CONT recorded his grim satisfaction.
1 CONT
1 CONT In his Will James divided his states between his sons by Yolanda of Hungary:
1 CONT the aforementioned Peter received the Hispanic possessions on the mainland and
1 CONT James, the Kingdom of Majorca (including the Balearic Islands and the counties
1 CONT of Roussillon and Cerdanya) and the Lordship of Montpellier. The division
1 CONT inevitably produced fratricidal conflicts. Always the home de fembres (“lady’s
1 CONT man”), he eloped with the wife of one of his vassals in his final years and
1 CONT was excommunicated for his efforts by Pope Gregory X. In 1276, the king fell
1 CONT very ill at Alzira and resigned his crown, intending to retire to the
1 CONT monastery of Poblet, but he died at Valencia on 27 July. Marriages and
1 CONT children Aragonese and Valencian Royalty House of Barcelona Aragon Arms.svg
