1 CONT [edit] Early life and reign until majority
1 CONT
1 CONT Barcelonan coin bearing James's effigyJames was born at Montpellier as the
1 CONT only son of Peter II and Mary, heiress of William VIII of Montpellier and
1 CONT Eudokia Komnene. As a child, James was a pawn in the power politics of
1 CONT Provence, where his father was engaged in struggles helping the Cathar
1 CONT heretics of Albi against the Albigensian Crusaders led by Simon IV de
1 CONT Montfort, Earl of Leicester, who were trying to exterminate them. Peter
1 CONT endeavoured to placate the northern crusaders by arranging a marriage between
1 CONT his son James and Simon's daughter. He entrusted the boy to be educated in
1 CONT Montfort's care in 1211, but was soon forced to take up arms against him,
1 CONT dying at the Battle of Muret on 12 September 1213. Montfort would willingly
1 CONT have used James as a means of extending his own power had not the Aragonese
1 CONT and Catalans appealed to Pope Innocent III, who insisted that Montfort
1 CONT surrender him. James was handed over, at Carcassonne, in May or June 1214, to
1 CONT the papal legate Peter of Benevento.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was then sent to Monzón, where he was entrusted to the care of William
1 CONT of Montredon, the head of the Knights Templar in Spain and Provence; the
1 CONT regency meanwhile fell to his great uncle Sancho, Count of Roussillon, and his
1 CONT son, the king's cousin, Nuño. The kingdom was given over to confusion until,
1 CONT in 1217, the Templars and some of the more loyal nobles brought the young king
1 CONT to Zaragoza.[3]
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1221, he was married to Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and
1 CONT Leonora of England. The next six years of his reign were full of rebellions on
1 CONT the part of the nobles. By the Peace of Alcalá of 31 March 1227, the nobles
1 CONT and the king came to terms.[3]
1 CONT
1 CONT Page from a 1343 copy of the Libre dels feyts by Celestí Destorrents [edit]
1 CONT Acquisition of Urgell In 1228, James faced the sternest opposition from a
1 CONT vassal yet. Guerau IV de Cabrera had occupied the County of Urgell in
1 CONT opposition to Aurembiax, the heiress of Ermengol VIII, who had died without
1 CONT sons in 1208. While Aurembiax' mother, Elvira, had made herself a protegée of
1 CONT James's father, on her death (1220), Guerao had occupied the county and
1 CONT displaced Aurembiax, claiming that a woman could not inherit.
1 CONT
1 CONT James intervened on behalf of Aurembiax, whom he owed protection. He bought
1 CONT Guerau off and allowed Aurembiax to reclaim her territory, which she did at
1 CONT Lleida, probably also becoming one of James's earliest mistresses.[4] She
1 CONT surrendered Lleida to James and agreed to hold Urgell in fief from him. On her
1 CONT death in 1231, James exchanged the Balearic Islands for Urgell with her
1 CONT widower, Peter of Portugal.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Relations with France and Navarre From 1230 to 1232, James negotiated
1 CONT with Sancho VII of Navarre, who desired his help against his nephew and
1 CONT closest living male relative, Theobald IV of Champagne. James and Sancho
1 CONT negotiated a treaty whereby James would inherit Navarre on the old Sancho's
1 CONT death, but when this did occur, the Navarrese nobless instead elevated
1 CONT Theobald to the throne (1234), and James disputed it. Pope Gregory IX was
1 CONT required to intervene.[5] In the end, James accepted Theobald's succession.
1 CONT
1 CONT James endeavoured to form a state straddling the Pyrenees, to counterbalance
1 CONT the power of France north of the Loire. As with the much earlier Visigothic
1 CONT attempt, this policy was victim to physical, cultural, and political
1 CONT obstacles. As in the case of Navarre, he was too wise to launch into perilous
1 CONT adventures. By the Treaty of Corbeil, signed in May 1258, he frankly withdrew
1 CONT from conflict with Louis IX of France and was content with the recognition of
1 CONT his position, and the surrender of antiquated and illusory French claims to
1 CONT the overlordship of Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Reconquista
1 CONT
1 CONT Map of the conquest of Majorca, 1229After his false start at uniting Aragon
1 CONT with the Kingdom of Navarre through a scheme of mutual adoption, James turned
1 CONT to the south and the Mediterranean Sea, where he conquered Majorca on 10
1 CONT September in 1229 and the rest of the Balearic Islands; Minorca 1232; Ibiza
1 CONT 1235) and where Valencia capitulated 28 September 1238.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his remaining two decades after Corbeil, James warred with the Moors in
1 CONT Murcia, on behalf of his son-in-law Alfonso X of Castile. On 26 March 1244,
1 CONT the two monarchs signed the Treaty of Almizra to determine the zones of their
1 CONT expansion into Andalusia so as to prevent squabbling between them.
1 CONT Specifically, it defined the borders of the newly-created Kingdom of Valencia.
1 CONT James signed it on that date, but Alfonso did not affirm it until much later.
1 CONT According to the treaty, all lands south of a line from Biar to Villajoyosa
1 CONT through Busot were reserved for Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Crusade of 1269
1 CONT
1 CONT Valencian coin with the inscription Iacobus rex Valencie (James, king of
1 CONT Valencia)The "khan of Tartary" (actually the Ilkhan) Abaqa corresponded with
1 CONT James in early 1267, inviting him to join forces with the Mongols and go on
1 CONT Crusade.[6] James sent an ambassador to Abaqa in the person of Jayme Alaric de
1 CONT Perpignan, who returned with a Mongol embassy in 1269.[7] Pope Clement IV
1 CONT tried to dissuade James from Crusading, regarding his moral character as sub-
1 CONT par, and Alfonso X did the same. Nonetheless, James, who was then campaigning
1 CONT in Murcia, made peace with Mohammed I ibn Nasr, the Sultan of Granada, and set
1 CONT about collecting funds for a Crusade. After organising the government for his
1 CONT absence and assembling a fleet at Barcelona in September 1269, he was ready to
1 CONT sail east. The troubadour Olivier lo Templier composed a song praising the
1 CONT voyage and hoping for its success. A storm, however, drove him off course and
1 CONT he landed at Aigues-Mortes. According to the continuator of William of Tyre,
1 CONT he returned via Montpellier por l'amor de sa dame Berenguiere ("for the love
1 CONT his lady Berengaria") and abandoned any further effort at a Crusade. I
1 CONT
1 CONT James's bastard sons Pedro Fernández and Fernán Sánchez, who had been given
1 CONT command of part of the fleet, did continue on their way to Acre, where they
1 CONT arrived in December. They found that Baibars, the Mameluke sultan of Egypt,
1 CONT had broken his truce with the Kingdom of Jerusalem and was making a
1 CONT demonstration of his military power in front of Acre. During the
1 CONT demonstration, Egyptian troops hidden in the bushes ambushed a returning
1 CONT Frankish force which had been in Galilee. James's sons, initially eager for a
1 CONT fight, changed their minds after this spectacle and returned home via Sicily,
1 CONT where Fernán Sánchez was knighted by Charles of Anjou.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Patronage of art, learning, and literature Aragonese and Valencian
1 CONT Royalty House of Barcelona
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso II Children include
1 CONT Peter (future Peter II of Aragon)
1 CONT Alfonso II, Count of Provence Peter II Children include
1 CONT James (future James I of Aragon, Valencia and Majorca) James I
1 CONT Peter (future Peter III of Aragon and I of Valencia and Sicily)
1 CONT James II of Majorca
1 CONT Violant, Queen of Castile
1 CONT Constance, Infanta of Castile
1 CONT Isabella, Queen of France Peter III (I of Valencia and Sicily) Children
1 CONT include
1 CONT Alfonso (future Alfonso III of Aragon and I of Valencia)
1 CONT James (future James I of Sicily and II of Aragon and Valencia)
1 CONT Frederick II of Sicily
1 CONT Elizabeth, Queen of Portugal
1 CONT Yolanda, Duchess of Calabria Alfonso III (I of Valencia) James II (I of
1 CONT Sicily) Children include
1 CONT Alfonso (future Alfonso IV of Aragon and II of Valencia) Alfonso IV (II of
1 CONT Valencia) Children include
1 CONT Peter (future Peter IV of Aragon and II of Valencia) Peter IV (II of Valencia)
1 CONT Children include
1 CONT John (future John I of Aragon and Valencia)
1 CONT Martin (future Martin II of Sicily and I of Aragon and Valencia)
1 CONT Eleanor, Queen of Castile Grandchildren include
1 CONT Ferdinand (future Ferdinand I of Aragon, Valencia and Sicily) John I
1 CONT Yolande, Queen of France Martin I (II of Sicily)
1 CONT
1 CONT James built and consecrated the Cathedral of Lleida, which was constructed in
1 CONT a style transitional between Romanesque and Gothic with little influence from
1 CONT Moorish styles.[2]
1 CONT
1 CONT First page of the Libre dels feyts, from a MS of 1325James was a patron of the
1 CONT University of Montpellier, which owed much of its development to his
1 CONT impetus.[8] He also founded a studium at Valencia in 1245 and received
1 CONT privileges for it from Pope Innocent IV, but it did not develop as
1 CONT splendidly.[2] In 1263, James presided over a debate in Barcelona between the
1 CONT Jewish rabbi Nahmanides and Pablo Christiani, a prominent converso.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was the first great sponsor and patron of vernacular Catalan literature.
1 CONT Indeed, he may himself be called "the first of the Catalan prose writers."[9]
1 CONT James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of his own life, Llibre
1 CONT dels fets in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicle of a Christian king.
1 CONT As well as a fine example of autobiography the "Book of Deeds" expresses
1 CONT concepts of the power and purpose of monarchy; examples of loyalty and
1 CONT treachery in the feudal order; and medieval military tactics. More
1 CONT controversially, some historians have looked at these writings as a source of
1 CONT Catalan identity, separate from that of Occitania and Rome.
1 CONT
1 CONT James also wrote the Libre de la Saviesa or "Book of Wisdom." The book
1 CONT contains proverbs from various authors going back as far as King Solomon and
1 CONT as close to his own time, such as Albert the Great. It even contains maxims
1 CONT from the medieval Arab philosophers and from the Apophthegmata Philosophorum
1 CONT of Honein ben Ishak, which was probably translated at Barcelona during his
1 CONT reign. A Hebrew translator by the name of Jehuda was employed at James's court
1 CONT during this period.[9]
1 CONT
1 CONT Though James was himself a prose writer and sponsored mostly prose works, he
1 CONT had an appreciation of verse.[10] In consequence of the Albigensian Crusade,
1 CONT many troubadours were forced to flee southern France and many found refuge in
1 CONT Aragon. Notwithstanding his early patronage of poetry, by the influence of his
1 CONT confessor Ramon de Penyafort, James brought the Inquisition into his realm in
1 CONT 1233 to prevent any vernacular translation of the Bible.[11]
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Succession
1 CONT
1 CONT James's sepulchre in the Cathedral of Tarragona Mummified head of James,
1 CONT exhumed in 1856The favour James showed his illegitimate offspring led to
1 CONT protest from the nobles, and to conflicts between his sons legitimate and
1 CONT illegitimate. When one of the latter, Fernán Sánchez, who had behaved with
1 CONT gross ingratitude and treason to his father, was slain by the legitimate son
1 CONT Peter, the old king recorded his grim satisfaction.
1 CONT
1 CONT In his will, James divided his states between his sons by Yolanda of Hungary:
1 CONT the aforementioned Peter received the Hispanic possessions on the mainland and
1 CONT James, the Kingdom of Majorca (including the Balearic Islands and the counties
1 CONT of Roussillon and Cerdanya) and the Lordship of Montpellier. The division
1 CONT inevitably produced fratricidal conflicts. In 1276, the king fell very ill at
1 CONT Alzira and resigned his crown, intending to retire to the monastery of Poblet,
1 CONT but he died at Valencia on 27 July.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marriages and children James first married, in 1221, Eleanor, daughter
1 CONT of Alfonso VIII of Castile and Leonora of England. Though he later had the
1 CONT marriage annulled, his one son by her was declared legitimate:
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso (1229–1260), married Constance of Montcada, Countess of Bigorre In
1 CONT 1235, James remarried to Yolanda, daughter of Andrew II of Hungary by his
1 CONT second wife Yolande de Courtenay. She bore him numerous children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda, also known as Violant, (1236–1301), married Alfonso X of Castile
1 CONT Constance (1239–1269), married Juan Manuel, Lord of Villena, son of Ferdinand
1 CONT III Peter (1240–1285), successor in Aragon, Catalonia, and Valencia James
1 CONT (1243–1311), successor in Balearics and Languedoc Ferdinand (1245–1250) Sancha
1 CONT (1246–1251) Isabella (1247–1271), married Philip III of France Mary
1 CONT (1248–1267), nun Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250–1279) Eleanor (born 1251,
1 CONT died young) James married thirdly Teresa Gil de Vidaure, but only by a private
1 CONT document, and left her when she developed leprosy.
1 CONT
1 CONT James (c.1255–1285), lord of Xèrica Peter (1259–1318), lord of Ayerbe The
1 CONT children in the third marriage were recognised in his last Will as being in
1 CONT the line of Successon to the Throne, should the senior lines fail.
1 CONT
1 CONT James also had several lovers, both during and after his marriages, and a few
1 CONT bore him illegitimate sons.
1 CONT
1 CONT By Blanca d'Antillón:
1 CONT
1 CONT Ferran Sanchis (or Fernando Sánchez; 1240–1275), baron of Castro By Berenguela
1 CONT Fernández:
1 CONT
1 CONT Pedro Fernández, baron of Híjar By Elvira Sarroca:
1 CONT
1 CONT Jaume Sarroca (born 1248), Archbishop of Huesca
