1 CONT James I the Conqueror (Catalan: Jaume el Conqueridor, Aragonese: Chaime lo
1 CONT Conqueridor, Spanish: Jaime el Conquistador, Occitan: Jacme lo Conquistaire; 2
1 CONT February 1208 – 27 July 1276) was the King of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and
1 CONT Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276. His long reign saw the expansion of the
1 CONT Crown of Aragon on all sides: into Valencia to the south, Languedoc to the
1 CONT north, and the Balearic Islands to the east. By a treaty with Louis IX of
1 CONT France, he wrested the county of Barcelona from nominal French suzerainty and
1 CONT integrated it into his crown. His part in the Reconquista was similar in
1 CONT Mediterranean Spain to that of his contemporary Ferdinand III of Castile in
1 CONT Andalusia. James first married, in 1221, Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of
1 CONT Castile and Leonora of England. Though he later had the marriage annulled, his
1 CONT one son by her was declared legitimate:
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso (1229–1260), married Constance of Montcada, Countess of Bigorre In
1 CONT 1235, James remarried to Yolanda, daughter of Andrew II of Hungary by his
1 CONT second wife Yolande de Courtenay. She bore him numerous children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda, also known as Violant, (1236–1301), married Alfonso X of Castile
1 CONT Constance (1239–1269), married Juan Manuel, Lord of Villena, son of Ferdinand
1 CONT III Peter (1240–1285), successor in Aragon, Catalonia, and Valencia James
1 CONT (1243–1311), successor in Balearics and Languedoc Ferdinand (1245–1250) Sancha
1 CONT (1246–1251) Isabella (1247–1271), married Philip III of France Mary
1 CONT (1248–1267), nun Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250–1279) Eleanor (born 1251,
1 CONT died young) James married thirdly Teresa Gil de Vidaure, but only by a private
1 CONT document, and left her when she developed leprosy.
1 CONT
1 CONT James (c.1255–1285), lord of Xèrica Peter (1259–1318), lord of Ayerbe The
1 CONT children in the third marriage were recognised in his last Will as being in
1 CONT the line of Successon to the Throne, should the senior lines fale.
1 CONT
1 CONT James also had several lovers, both during and after his marriages, and a few
1 CONT bore him illegitimate sons.
1 CONT
