1 CONT James I the Conqueror, Lord of Montpellier, Crown of Aragon, Legislator,
1 CONT Organiser. James compiled the Libre del Consulat de Mar, which governed
1 CONT maritime trade and helped establish Aragones supermacy in he Western
1 CONT Mediterranean. He developed the Catalan, sponsering Catalan literature and
1 CONT writing a quasi-autobiographical chronicle of his on reign: The Libre dels
1 CONT Fets. He built and consecrated the Cathedral of Lleida. He was a patron of the
1 CONT University of Montpellier. He founded a studium at Valencia and received
1 CONT privileges for it from Pope Innocent IV. He wrote an autobiography of "Bookd
1 CONT of Deeds". he wrote Libre de la Saviesa or Boof of Wisdom. James prevented any
1 CONT vernaculor translation of the Bible in 1233.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT James I the Conqueror[1] (2 February 1208 – 27 July 1276) was the King of
1 CONT Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276. His
1 CONT long reign saw the expansion of the Crown of Aragon to the south and into and
1 CONT across the Mediterranean as far as Naples: into Valencia to the south and the
1 CONT Balearic Islands, Sicily and the Kingdom of Naples to the east [the Aragonese
1 CONT Crown had been forced to renounce its claims to territories north of the
1 CONT Pyrenees, except for James's patrimony of Montpellier, by the Fourth Lateran
1 CONT Council of 1215]. By a treaty with Louis IX of France, he wrested the county
1 CONT of Barcelona from nominal French suzerainty and integrated it into his crown.
1 CONT His part in the Reconquista was similar in Mediterranean Spain to that of his
1 CONT contemporary Ferdinand III of Castile in Andalusia.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a legislator and organiser, he occupies a high place among the Spanish
1 CONT kings. James compiled the Llibre del Consulat de Mar,[2] which governed
1 CONT maritime trade and helped establish Aragonese supremacy in the western
1 CONT Mediterranean. He was an important figure in the development of Catalan,
1 CONT sponsoring Catalan literature and writing a quasi-autobiographical chronicle
1 CONT of his reign: the Llibre dels feyts, and made Catalan the official language on
1 CONT his domains.[2]
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT James owed his name to his mother's strange whim of placing 12 lighted
1 CONT candles, name for the 12 Apostles, around his cradle & determining that the
1 CONT last to burn out should be his patron. He was described as 'tall, muscular,
1 CONT dignified & never knew a day of illness'.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT King of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and Lord of Montpellier
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Jaime I, Rey de Aragón was born in 1205.1 He married, firstly, Eleanor de
1 CONT Castilla, daughter of Alfonso VIII, Rey de Castilla and Eleanor Plantagenet,
1 CONT in 1221.2 He and Eleanor de Castilla were divorced in 1229.1 He married,
1 CONT secondly, Yolante Arpád, daughter of Andreas II Arpád, King of Hungary and
1 CONT Yolande de Courtney, on 8 September 1235. He married, thirdly, Theresa Vidaure
1 CONT after 1251.2 He died on 25 July 1276.
1 CONT Jaime I, Rey de Aragón also went by the nick-name of Jaime 'the Conqueror'
1 CONT (?).3 He was the son of Pedro II, Rey de Aragón and Marie de Montpellier.2 He
1 CONT succeeded to the title of Rey Jaime I de Aragón in 1213.2 Child of Jaime I,
1 CONT Rey de Aragón and Theresa Vidaure
