1 CONT (Research):(James the Conqueror), 1208-76), king of Arag≡n and count of
1 CONT Barcelona(1231-76), son and successor of Peter II. After a minority was
1 CONT distributed by private wars amoung the nobles, James soon consolidated royal
1 CONT power and tried to create a new nobility dependent on him. He seized the
1 CONT Balsic Islands (1229-35) and Valencia (1238) from the Moors and helped Castile
1 CONT to recover control of Murica after a Moorish rebellion (1266). A crusade to
1 CONT Palestine (1269) with Louis IX of France, James gave up several claims in S
1 CONT France, while the french king remounced his rights to Catalonia, derived from
1 CONT Charlemagne. James's own chronicle of his reign has been translated into
1 CONT English. He was succeeded in Arag≡n by his son Peter III. Another son was king
1 CONT of Majorca as James 1.
1 CONT
1 CONT Jaime I "the Conqueror", King of Aragon 1213-1276 (1208-1276) Born 13 February
1 CONT 1208 Montpellier Died 25 July 1276 Xativa Married 8 September 1235 Barcelona
1 CONT Violante of Hungary Died 1251 Huesca In 1213, at the age of five, he became
1 CONT King of Aragon. He was a remarkable man; gallant, boastful and eccentric. As a
1 CONT young man he conquered the Balearic Islands and the rich emirate of Valencia.
1 CONT He then involved himself with French politics as the counties of Roussillon
1 CONT and Cerdagne formed part of his kingdom; and as well he had inherited
1 CONT Montpellier from his mother. He was nearly sixty when he personally led his
1 CONT army and added the emirate of Murcia to his kingdom. In his later years he
1 CONT preferred to spend his time in dalliance with his mistresses. He was the only
1 CONT monarch who accepted Pope Gregory X's invitation to make a crusade; but his
1 CONT good sense, being both too shrewd and too weary, kept him out of any
1 CONT involvement; this he preferred to leave to his son. He died in July 1276, a
1 CONT king for sixty-three years and, having preserved his vigour to the last, he
1 CONT was little troubled by his excommunication by the Pope for his last illicit
1 CONT love-affair. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT
1 CONT James I Encyclopædia Britannica Article born Feb. 2, 1208, Montpellier, County
1 CONT of Toulouse died July 27, 1276, Valencia, Valencia James I, detail of an
1 CONT illumination from the Crónica de Jaime I; in the University of ¼ Archivo Mas,
1 CONT Barcelona byname James The Conqueror, Spanish Jaime El Conquistador the most
1 CONT renowned of the medieval kings of Aragon (1213-76), who added the Balearic
1 CONT Islands and Valencia to his realm and thus initiated the Catalan-Aragonese
1 CONT expansion in the Mediterranean that was to reach its zenith in the last
1 CONT decades of the 14th century. James was the son of Peter II of Aragon and Mary
1 CONT of Montpellier. When Peter, allied with the Albigensian heretics, died
1 CONT fighting against the crusaders sent against them at the Battle of Muret, James
1 CONT was only five years old and was at Carcassonne, Fr., in the hands of the
1 CONT crusaders' leader, Simon de Montfort. James was released in April 1214 and
1 CONT recognized as sovereign in Aragon and Catalonia; placed under the protection
1 CONT of the Knights Templars at Monzón, he was cared for and educated by them. The
1 CONT regency was exercised by his great-uncle, Count Sancho of Roussillon (in
1 CONT Aragon, now in France), until 1218, when Sancho resigned in the face of
1 CONT opposition from some Aragonese and Catalonian nobles. The ensuing rebellions,
1 CONT during which the King often found himself in great danger, formed a hard
1 CONT school for the forging of his character. Fearless even as a youth, he fought
1 CONT an Aragonese noble in hand-to-hand combat, took part in the siege of the port
1 CONT of Castejón in 1222, and three years later tried to seize another port. In
1 CONT 1227 James took over the effective government of his kingdoms and at once
1 CONT began the first of his great campaigns of reconquest_that of the Balearic
1 CONT Islands. Majorca was captured in December 1229, and the occupation was rounded
1 CONT off in 1235 by the conquest of Ibiza by the Bishop of Saragossa.
1 CONT Thenceforward, the islands were a bulwark to defend the Catalan coasts and a
1 CONT base from which trade and political expansion could be launched eastward. In
1 CONT 1233 James began a second war of reconquest_against the Saracen rulers of the
1 CONT Kingdom of Valencia. The campaign lasted three long years and suffered various
1 CONT interruptions before the capital itself was captured in 1238. The occupation
1 CONT of the kingdom was completed later with the capture of other towns, and in
1 CONT 1244 a treaty was signed by which the boundaries of Aragon and Castile were
1 CONT delimited in the newly conquered areas. James I married twice. In 1221 he
1 CONT married Leonor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile, but he later divorced her
1 CONT and in 1235 married the daughter of Andrew II of Hungary, Yolande, by whom he
1 CONT had many children. In 1248 and 1262 he divided his realms among his sons but
1 CONT only succeeded in causing virulent civil strife. In the second division, his
1 CONT elder son, Peter, received Aragon, Valencia, and Catalonia, and his younger
1 CONT son, James, received the Balearic Islands, Roussillon, and other Pyrenean
1 CONT counties that he was to hold in fief from Peter. This division of realms among
1 CONT his heirs was not James's only political blunder. By the Treaty of Corbeil
1 CONT (1258) he renounced his claims to territories in the south of France, thus
1 CONT abandoning the traditional policy that the Catalan dynasty had hitherto
1 CONT pursued across the Pyrenees. He was, however, able to develop relations and
1 CONT promote trade with the states of North Africa; and, with a clear view of the
1 CONT future, he married his principal heir, Peter, to Constance of Sicily, thus
1 CONT making it easy for the latter kingdom to be added in later years to the crown
1 CONT of Aragon. Always a chivalrous soldier, James helped his son-in-law Alfonso X
1 CONT of Castile to suppress the rebellion of the Moors in the Kingdom of Murcia
1 CONT (1266); he also set out on a crusade to the Holy Land (1269), though this was
1 CONT a failure. A soldier of extraordinary courage and great gifts of leadership,
1 CONT James was a stout man, strong and handsome; he has been criticized for his
1 CONT many love affairs that caused him to be described as an home de fembres
1 CONT ("lady's man"). On balance, his reign was very beneficial. The important code
1 CONT of maritime law called the Llibre del consolat del mar was compiled; the
1 CONT Kingdom of Valencia received its own legal system; various cities, including
1 CONT Barcelona, acquired their own civic administrations; and the Cortes_the
1 CONT representative assembly_came into being. The King protected men of letters,
1 CONT inspired the chronicle that bears his name (though he did not himself write
1 CONT it), and brought his different peoples to a degree of political and cultural
1 CONT maturity that can reasonably be described as admirable.
1 CONT James I of Aragon
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT
1 CONT James I of Aragon (Catalan: Jaume I, Spanish: Jaime I) (Montpellier February
1 CONT 2, 1208 – July 27, 1276), surnamed the Conqueror, was the king of Aragon,
1 CONT count of Barcelona and Lord of Montpellier from 1219 to 1276.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the only child of Peter II of Aragon and Marie of Montpellier. As a
1 CONT child he was a pawn of power politics in Provence, where his father was
1 CONT engaged in struggles in the wars between the Cathars of Albi and Simon de
1 CONT Montfort. Peter endeavoured to placate the northern crusaders by arranging a
1 CONT marriage between his son James and Simon's daughter, entrusting the boy to be
1 CONT educated in Montfort's care in 1211, but Peter was soon forced to take up arms
1 CONT against them, and he was slain at the Battle of Muret September 12, 1213.
1 CONT Montfort would willingly have used James as a means of extending his own
1 CONT power. The Aragonese and Catalans, however, appealed to the pope, who forced
1 CONT Montfort to surrender him in May or June 1214.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was now entrusted to the care of Guillen de Monredon, the head of the
1 CONT Knights Templar in Spain and Provence. The kingdom was given over to confusion
1 CONT till in 1216 the Templars and some of the more loyal nobles brought the young
1 CONT king to Saragossa.
1 CONT
1 CONT He first married, in 1221, Leonor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile, and
1 CONT then after having the marriage annulled (though a son was declared
1 CONT legitimate), in 1235, Yolande of Hungary, daughter of Andrew II of Hungary.
1 CONT His children were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso (1229-1260), married Constance of Moncada, Countess of Bigorre
1 CONT Violant of Aragon (1236-1301), married Alfonso X of Castile
1 CONT Peter III of Aragon
1 CONT Constance of Aragon (1239-1269), married Juan Manuel of Castile, son of
1 CONT Ferdinand III of Castile
1 CONT James II of Majorca
1 CONT Isabella of Aragon, married Philip III of France
1 CONT Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250-1279)
1 CONT After a false start at uniting Aragon with Navarre through a scheme of mutual
1 CONT adoption, James turned to the south and the Mediterranean, conquered the
1 CONT Balearic Islands (from 1228 over the following four years) and Valencia (the
1 CONT city capitulated September 28, 1238).
1 CONT
1 CONT With the French, James endeavoured to form a state straddling the Pyrenees, to
1 CONT counterbalance the power of France north of the Loire. As with the earlier
1 CONT Visigothic attempt, this policy was victim of physical, cultural and political
1 CONT obstacles. As in the case of Navarra, he was too wise to launch into perilous
1 CONT adventures. By the Treaty of Corbeil, with Louis IX, signed May, 1258, he
1 CONT frankly withdrew from conflict with the French king, and was content with the
1 CONT recognition of his position, and the surrender of antiquated and illusory
1 CONT French claims to the overlordship of Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his remaining two decades, James warred with the Moors in Murcia, on
1 CONT behalf of his son-in-law Alphonso the Wise of Castile. As a legislator and
1 CONT organizer he occupies a high place among the Spanish kings. The favor he
1 CONT showed his illegitimate offspring led to protest from the nobles, and to
1 CONT conflicts between his sons legitimate and illegitimate. When one of the
1 CONT latter, Fernan Sanchez, who had behaved with gross ingratitude and treason to
1 CONT his father, was slain by the legitimate son Peter, the old king recorded his
1 CONT grim satisfaction.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Majorca Kings Palace at PerpinyàAt the close of his life King James divided
1 CONT his states between his sons by Yolande of Hungary, Peter receiving the
1 CONT Hispanic possessions on the mainland and James, the Kingdom of Majorca (the
1 CONT Balearic Islands and the counties of Roussillon and Cerdagne) and the Lordship
1 CONT of Montpellier, a division which inevitably produced fratricidal conflicts.
1 CONT The king fell very ill at Alcira, and resigned his crown, intending to retire
1 CONT to the monastery of Poblet, but died at Valencia July 7, 1276.
1 CONT
1 CONT King James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of his own life,
1 CONT "Llibre Dels Fets" in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicle of a
1 CONT Christian king. As well as a fine example of autobiography the "Book of Deeds"
1 CONT expresses concepts of the power and purpose of monarchy, examples of loyalty
1 CONT and treachery in the feudal order, the growth of national sentiment based on
1 CONT homeland, language and culture, and medieval military tactics.
1 CONT
