1 CONT [Wikipedia, "James I of Aragon", retrieved 16 Oct 07]
1 CONT James I the Conqueror (Catalan: Jaume el Conqueridor, Aragonese: Chaime lo
1 CONT Conqueridor, Spanish: Jaime el Conquistador, Occitan: Jacme lo Conquistaire; 2
1 CONT February 1208 - 27 July 1276) was the King of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and
1 CONT Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276. His long reign saw the expansion of the
1 CONT Crown of Aragon on all sides: into Valencia to the south, Languedoc to the
1 CONT north, and the Balearic Islands to the east. By a treaty with Louis IX of
1 CONT France, he wrested the Principality of Catalonia from nominal French
1 CONT suzerainty and integrated it into his crown. His part in the Reconquista was
1 CONT similar in Mediterranean Spain to that of his contemporary Ferdinand III of
1 CONT Castile in Andalusia.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a legislator and organiser, he occupies a high place among the Spanish
1 CONT kings. James compiled the Libre del Consulat de Mar, which governed maritime
1 CONT trade and helped establish Catalan supremacy in the western Mediterranean. He
1 CONT made Catalan the official language of his domains and sponsored Catalan
1 CONT literature, even a quasi-autobiographical chronicle of his reign: the Llibre
1 CONT dels fets.
1 CONT
1 CONT Early life and reign until majority
1 CONT James was born at Montpellier as the only child of Peter II and Mary, heiress
1 CONT of William VIII of Montpellier and Eudokia Komnene. As a child, James was a
1 CONT pawn in the power politics of Provence, where his father was engaged in
1 CONT struggles with the Cathar heretics of Albi on one side and the Albigensian
1 CONT Crusaders led by Simon IV de Montfort, Earl of Leicester, who were trying to
1 CONT exterminate them on the other. Peter endeavoured to placate the northern
1 CONT crusaders by arranging a marriage between his son James and Simon's daughter.
1 CONT He entrusted the boy to be educated in Montfort's care in 1211, but was soon
1 CONT forced to take up arms against him, dying at the Battle of Muret on 12
1 CONT September 1213. Montfort would willingly have used James as a means of
1 CONT extending his own power had not the Aragonese and Catalans appealed to Pope
1 CONT Innocent III, who insisted that Montfort surrender him. James was handed over,
1 CONT at Carcassonne, in May or June 1214, to the papal legate Peter of Benevento.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was then sent to Monzón, where he was entrusted to the care of William
1 CONT of Montredon, the head of the Knights Templar in Spain and Provence; the
1 CONT regency meanwhile fell to his great uncle Sancho, Count of Roussillon, and his
1 CONT son, the king's cousin, Nuño. The kingdom was given over to confusion until,
1 CONT in 1217, the Templars and some of the more loyal nobles brought the young king
1 CONT to Zaragoza.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1221, he was married to Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and
1 CONT Leonora of England. The next six years of his reign were full of rebellions on
1 CONT the part of the nobles. By the Peace of Alcalá of 31 March 1227, the nobles
1 CONT and the king came to terms.
1 CONT
1 CONT Acquisition of Urgell
1 CONT In 1228, James faced the sternest opposition from a vassal yet. Guerau de
1 CONT Cabrera had occupied the County of Urgell in opposition to Aurembiax, the
1 CONT heiress of Ermengol VIII, who had died without sons in 1208. While Aurembiax'
1 CONT mother, Elvira, had made herself a protegée of James' father, on her death
1 CONT (1220), Guerao had occupied the county and displaced Aurembiax, claiming that
1 CONT a woman could not inherit.
1 CONT
1 CONT James intervened on behalf of Aurembiax, whom he owed protection. He bought
1 CONT Guerau off and allowed Aurembiax to reclaim her territory, which she did at
1 CONT Lleida, probably also becoming one of James' earliest mistresses. She
1 CONT surrendered Lleida to James and agreed to hold Urgell in fief from him. On her
1 CONT death in 1231, James exchanged the Balearic Islands for Urgell with her
1 CONT widower, Peter of Portugal.
1 CONT
1 CONT Relations with France and Navarre
1 CONT From 1230 to 1232, James negotiated with Sancho VII of Navarre, who desired
1 CONT his help against his nephew and closest living male relative, Theobald IV of
1 CONT Champagne. James and Sancho negotiated a treaty whereby James would inherit
1 CONT Navarre on the old Sancho's death, but when this did occur, the Navarrese
1 CONT nobless instead elevated Theobald to the throne (1234), and James disputed it.
1 CONT Pope Gregory IX was required to intervene. In the end, James accepted
1 CONT Theobald's succession.
1 CONT
1 CONT James endeavoured to form a state straddling the Pyrenees, to counterbalance
1 CONT the power of France north of the Loire. As with the much earlier Visigothic
1 CONT attempt, this policy was victim to physical, cultural, and political
1 CONT obstacles. As in the case of Navarre, he was too wise to launch into perilous
1 CONT adventures. By the Treaty of Corbeil, signed in May 1258, he frankly withdrew
1 CONT from conflict with Louis IX of France and was content with the recognition of
1 CONT his position, and the surrender of antiquated and illusory French claims to
1 CONT the overlordship of Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Reconquista
1 CONT After his false start at uniting Aragon with the Kingdom of Navarre through a
1 CONT scheme of mutual adoption, James turned to the south and the Mediterranean
1 CONT Sea, where he conquered the Balearic Islands (Majorca 1229; Minorca 1232;
1 CONT Ibiza 1235) and where Valencia capitulated 28 September 1238.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his remaining two decades after Corbeil, James warred with the Moors in
1 CONT Murcia, on behalf of his son-in-law Alfonso X of Castile. On 26 March 1244,
1 CONT the two monarchs signed the Treaty of Almizra to determine the zones of their
1 CONT expansion into Andalusia so as to prevent squabbling between them.
1 CONT Specifically, it defined the borders of the newly-created Kingdom of Valencia.
1 CONT James signed it on that date, but Alfonso did not affirm it until much later.
1 CONT According to the treaty, all lands south of a line from Biar to Villajoyosa
1 CONT through Busot were reserved for Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT Patronage of art, learning, and literature
1 CONT James built and consecrated the Cathedral of Lleida, which was constructed in
1 CONT a style transitional between Romanesque and Gothic with little influence from
1 CONT Moorish styles.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was a patron of the University of Montpellier, which owed much of its
1 CONT development to his impetus. He also founded a studium at Valencia in 1245 and
1 CONT received privileges for it from Pope Innocent IV, but it did not develop as
1 CONT splendidly. In 1263, James presided over a debate in Barcelona between the
1 CONT Jewish rabbi Nahmanides and Pablo Christiani, a prominent converso.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was the first great sponsor and patron of vernacular Catalan literature.
1 CONT Indeed, he may himself be called "the first of the Catalan prose writers."
1 CONT James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of his own life, Llibre
1 CONT dels fets in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicle of a Christian king.
1 CONT As well as a fine example of autobiography the "Book of Deeds" expresses
1 CONT concepts of the power and purpose of monarchy; examples of loyalty and
1 CONT treachery in the feudal order; the growth of national sentiment based on
1 CONT homeland, language, and culture; and medieval military tactics.
1 CONT
1 CONT James also wrote the Libre de la Saviesa or "Book of Wisdom." The book
1 CONT contains proverbs from various authors going back as far as King Solomon and
1 CONT as close to his own time, such as Albert the Great. It even contains maxims
1 CONT from the medieval Arab philosophers and from the Apophthegmata Philosophorum
1 CONT of Honein ben Ishak, which was probably translated at Barcelona during his
1 CONT reign. A Hebrew translator by the name of Jehuda was employed at James's court
1 CONT during this period.
1 CONT
1 CONT Though James was himself a prose writer and sponsored mostly prose works, he
1 CONT had an appreciation of verse. In consequence of the Albigensian Crusade, many
1 CONT troubadours were forced to flee southern France and many found refuge in
1 CONT Aragon and Catalonia. Notwithstanding his early patronage of poetry, by the
1 CONT influence of his confessor Ramon de Penyafort, James brought the Inquisition
1 CONT into his realm in 1233 to prevent any vernacular translation of the Bible.
1 CONT
1 CONT Succession
1 CONT The favour James showed his illegitimate offspring led to protest from the
1 CONT nobles, and to conflicts between his sons legitimate and illegitimate. When
1 CONT one of the latter, Fernán Sánchez, who had behaved with gross ingratitude and
1 CONT treason to his father, was slain by the legitimate son Peter, the old king
1 CONT recorded his grim satisfaction.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the close of his life, James divided his states between his sons by Yolanda
1 CONT of Hungary: the aforementioned Peter received the Hispanic possessions on the
1 CONT mainland and James, the Kingdom of Majorca (including the Balearic Islands and
1 CONT the counties of Roussillon and Cerdanya) and the Lordship of Montpellier. The
1 CONT division inevitably produced fratricidal conflicts. In 1276, the king fell
1 CONT very ill at Alzira and resigned his crown, intending to retire to the
1 CONT monastery of Poblet, but he died at Valencia on 27 July.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriages and children
1 CONT James first married, in 1221, Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and
1 CONT Leonora of England. Though he later had the marriage annulled, his one son by
1 CONT her was declared legitimate:
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso (1229-1260), married Constance of Montcada, Countess of Bigorre
1 CONT In 1235, James remarried to Yolanda, daughter of Andrew II of Hungary by his
1 CONT second wife Yolande de Courtenay. She bore him numerous children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda, also known as Violant, (1236-1301), married Alfonso X of Castile
1 CONT Constance (1239-1269), married Juan Manuel, Lord of Villena, son of Ferdinand
1 CONT III
1 CONT Peter (1240-1285), successor in Aragon, Catalonia, and Valencia
1 CONT James (1243-1311), successor in Balearics and Languedoc
1 CONT Ferdinand (1245-1250)
1 CONT Sancha (1246-1251)
1 CONT Isabella (1247-1271), married Philip III of France
1 CONT Mary (1248-1267), nun
1 CONT Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250-1279)
1 CONT Eleanor (born 1251, died young)
1 CONT James married thirdly Teresa Gil de Vidaure, but only by a private document,
1 CONT and left her when she developed leprosy.
1 CONT
1 CONT James (c.1255?1285), lord of Xèrica
1 CONT Peter (1259?1318), lord of Ayerbe
1 CONT James also had several lovers, both during and after his marriages, and a few
1 CONT bore him illegitimate sons.
1 CONT
1 CONT By Blanca d'Antillón:
1 CONT
1 CONT Ferran Sanchis (or Fernando Sánchez; 1240?1275), baron of Castro
1 CONT By Berenguela Fernández:
1 CONT
1 CONT Pedro Fernández, baron of Híjar
1 CONT By Elvira Sarroca:
1 CONT
1 CONT Jaume Sarroca (born 1248), Archbishop of Huesca
1 CONT Jaime I de Aragón (Montpellier, 2 de febrero de 1208 - Alcira, 27 de julio de
1 CONT 1276) fue rey de Aragón (1213 - 1276), de Valencia (1239-76) y de Mallorca
1 CONT (1229-1276), conde de Barcelona (1213-1276), señor de Montpellier (1219-1276)
1 CONT y de otros feudos en Occitania.
1 CONT James I the Conqueror (Catalan: Jaume el Conqueridor, Aragonese: Chaime lo
1 CONT Conqueridor, Spanish: Jaime el Conquistador, Occitan: Jacme lo Conquistaire; 2
1 CONT February 1208 – 27 July 1276) was the King of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and
1 CONT Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276. His long reign saw the expansion of the
1 CONT Crown of Aragon on all sides: into Valencia to the south, Languedoc to the
1 CONT north, and the Balearic Islands to the east. By a treaty with Louis IX of
1 CONT France, he wrested the county of Barcelona from nominal French suzerainty and
1 CONT integrated it into his crown. His part in the Reconquista was similar in
1 CONT Mediterranean Spain to that of his contemporary Ferdinand III of Castile in
1 CONT Andalusia.
1 CONT As a legislator and organiser, he occupies a high place among the Spanish
1 CONT kings. James compiled the Libre del Consulat de Mar,[1] which governed
1 CONT maritime trade and helped establish Catalan supremacy in the western
1 CONT Mediterranean. He made Catalan the official language of his domains[2] and
1 CONT sponsored Catalan literature, even a quasi-autobiographical chronicle of his
1 CONT reign: the Llibre dels fets.
1 CONT , James faced the sternest opposition from a vassal yet. Guerau de Cabrera had
1 CONT occupied the County of Urgell in opposition to Aurembiax, the heiress of
1 CONT Ermengol VIII, who had died without sons in 1208. While Aurembiax' mother,
1 CONT Elvira, had made herself a protegée of James' father, on her death (1220),
1 CONT Guerao had occupied the county and displaced Aurembiax, claiming that a woman
1 CONT could not inherit.
1 CONT James intervened on behalf of Aurembiax, whom he owed protection. He bought
1 CONT Guerau off and allowed Aurembiax to reclaim her territory, which she did at
1 CONT Lleida, probably also becoming one of James' earliest mistresses.[5] She
1 CONT surrendered Lleida to James and agreed to hold Urgell in fief from him. On her
1 CONT death in 1231, James exchanged the Balearic Islands for Urgell with her
1 CONT widower, Peter of Portugal
1 CONT James was the first great sponsor and patron of vernacular Catalan literature.
1 CONT Indeed, he may himself be called "the first of the Catalan prose writers."[12]
1 CONT James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of his own life, Llibre
1 CONT dels fets in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicle of a Christian king.
1 CONT As well as a fine example of autobiography the "Book of Deeds" expresses
1 CONT concepts of the power and purpose of monarchy; examples of loyalty and
1 CONT treachery in the feudal order; the growth of national sentiment based on
1 CONT homeland, language, and culture; and medieval military tactics.
1 CONT The favour James showed his illegitimate offspring led to protest from the
1 CONT nobles, and to conflicts between his sons legitimate and illegitimate. When
1 CONT one of the latter, Fernán Sánchez, who had behaved with gross ingratitude and
1 CONT treason to his father, was slain by the legitimate son Peter, the old king
1 CONT recorded his grim satisfaction.
1 CONT At the close of his life, James divided his states between his sons by Yolanda
1 CONT of Hungary: the aforementioned Peter received the Hispanic possessions on the
1 CONT mainland and James, the Kingdom of Majorca (including the Balearic Islands and
1 CONT the counties of Roussillon and Cerdanya) and the Lordship of Montpellier. The
1 CONT division inevitably produced fratricidal conflicts. In 1276, the king fell
1 CONT very ill at Alzira and resigned his crown, intending to retire to the
1 CONT monastery of Poblet, but he died at Valencia on 27 July.
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT James I of Aragon (Catalan: Jaume I) (Montpellier February 2, 1208 -July 27,
1 CONT 1276), surnamed the Conqueror, was the king of Aragon, countof Barcelona and
1 CONT Lord of Montpellier from 1213 to 1276.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a child he was a pawn of power politics in Provence, where hisfather was
1 CONT engaged in struggles in the wars between the Cathars ofAlbi and Simon de
1 CONT Montfort. Peter endeavoured to placate the northerncrusaders by arranging a
1 CONT marriage between his son James and Simon'sdaughter, entrusting the boy to be
1 CONT educated in Montfort's care in1211, but Peter was soon forced to take up arms
1 CONT against them, and hewas slain at Muret September 12, 1213. Montfort would
1 CONT willingly haveused James as a means of extending his own power. The Aragonese
1 CONT andCatalans, however, appealed to the pope, who forced Montfort tosurrender
1 CONT him in May or June 1214.
1 CONT
1 CONT James was now entrusted to the care of Guillen de Monredon, the headof the
1 CONT Knights Templar in Spain and Provence. The kingdom was givenover to confusion
1 CONT till in 1216 the Templars and some of the more loyalnobles brought the young
1 CONT king to Saragossa.
1 CONT
1 CONT He first married, in 1221, Eleanor, daughter of Alfonso VIII ofCastile, and
1 CONT then after having the marriage annulled (though a son wasdeclared legitimate),
1 CONT in 1235, Yolande of Hungary, daughter of AndrewII of Hungary. With Yolande he
1 CONT was the father of Isabella of Aragon,who married Philip III of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT After a false start at uniting Aragon with Navarra through a scheme ofmutual
1 CONT adoption, James turned to the south and the Mediterranean,conquered the
1 CONT Balearic Islands (from 1228 over the following fouryears) and Valencia (the
1 CONT city capitulated September 28, 1238).
1 CONT
1 CONT With the French, James endeavoured to form a state straddling thePyrenees, to
1 CONT counterbalance the power of France north of the Loire. Aswith the earlier
1 CONT Visigothic attempt, this policy was victim ofphysical, cultural and political
1 CONT obstacles. As in the case of Navarra,he was too wise to launch into perilous
1 CONT adventures. By the Treaty ofCorbeil, with Louis IX, signed May 1258, he
1 CONT frankly withdrew fromconflict with the French king, and was content with the
1 CONT recognition ofhis position, and the surrender of antiquated and illusory
1 CONT Frenchclaims to the overlordship of Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his remaining two decades, James warred with the Moors inMurcia, on
1 CONT behalf of his son-in-law Alphonso the Wise of Castile. As alegislator and
1 CONT organizer he occupies a high place among the Spanishkings. The favor he showed
1 CONT his bastards led to protest from thenobles, and to conflicts between his sons
1 CONT legitimate and illegitimate.When one of the latter, Fernan Sanchez, who had
1 CONT behaved with grossingratitude and treason to his father, was slain by the
1 CONT legitimate sonPedro, the old king recorded his grim satisfaction.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the close of his life King James divided his states between hissons by
1 CONT Yolande of Hungary, Peter receiving the Hispanic possessionson the mainland
1 CONT and James, the Kingdom of Majorca (the BalearicIslands) and the Lordship of
1 CONT Montpellier, a division which inevitablyproduced fratricidal conflicts. The
1 CONT king fell very ill at Alcira, andresigned his crown, intending to retire to
1 CONT the monastery of Poblet,but died at Valencia July 7, 1276.
1 CONT
1 CONT King James wrote or dictated at various stages a chronicle of his ownlife,
1 CONT "Llibre Dels Fets" in Catalan, which is the first self-chronicleof a Christian
1 CONT king. As well as a fine example of autobiography the"Book of Deeds" expresses
1 CONT concepts of the power and purpose ofmonarchy, examples of loyalty and
1 CONT treachery in the feudal order, thegrowth of national sentiment based on
1 CONT homeland, language and culture,and medieval military tactics.
1 CONT Like his Grandfather ascended to the crown at the age of five. It wasrunby a
1 CONT regency until he came of age; and his Uncle Sanc, Count OfProvence,managed the
1 CONT finances and paid off his fathers debts.
1 CONT He later becameknown for leading military campaigns that capturedMajorca and
1 CONT otherBalearic Islands, as well as Valencia, from the Moors.
1 CONT
1 CONT Like his Grandfather ascended to the crown at the age of five. It wasrunby a
1 CONT regency until he came of age; and his Uncle Sanc, Count OfProvence,managed the
1 CONT finances and paid off his fathers debts.
1 CONT He later becameknown for leading military campaigns that capturedMajorca and
1 CONT otherBalearic Islands, as well as Valencia, from the Moors.
