0 @N00405@ NOTE geni:about_me ANDRÁS, son of BÉLA III King of Hungary & his first wife Agnès
1 CONT [Anna] de Châtillon-sur-Loing (1176-21 Sep 1235, bur Egres, Cistercian Abbey).
1 CONT The Chronicon Varadiense names "primus…dux Henricus…secundus dux
1 CONT Andreas…tertius dux Salamon et quartus…dux Stephanus" as the four sons of "rex
1 CONT Bela tertius filius Geysæ"[809]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines
1 CONT names (in order) "Haymericum et Andream…et duas reginas Constantiam de Boemia
1 CONT et Margaretam de Grecia" as children of "rex Bela de Hungaria" and his wife
1 CONT Agnes[810]. After the accession of his brother, András demanded Croatia and
1 CONT Dalmatia as an appanage but this was refused. He revolted, and by 1198
1 CONT obtained his demands and became Duke of Croatia and Dalmatia[811]. He and
1 CONT subsequent dukes acted as the king of Hungary's deputy in the kingdom of
1 CONT Croatia. "Andreas, tertii Belæ regis filius…Dalmatiæ, Croatiæ, Ramæ, Culmæque
1 CONT dux" appointed "Pharensi episcopum" by charter dated 1198, witnessed by
1 CONT "Andrea Bano, comite Macharia, comite Ioseph, comite Marco, comite Andronico
1 CONT filio Bani camerario ducis Wenceslao…"[812]. He conquered western Hum
1 CONT [Hercegovina] as far as the river Neretva in 1198[813]. The Continuatio
1 CONT Admuntensis records that he was arrested in 1203, suspected of plotting to
1 CONT take over the kingdom, and imprisoned "in palacio Strigoniensi quod alio
1 CONT nomine Gran vocatur"[814]. He ousted his nephew in 1205 and succeeded as
1 CONT ANDRÁS II King of Hungary. He played an active part in the dismemberment of
1 CONT Galich-Volynia after the death of Roman Mstislavich Prince of Galich in 1205,
1 CONT Hungary and Poland eventually agreeing the division of the territories between
1 CONT them under the treaty of Spisz in 1214, although Hungary expelled Poland from
1 CONT Peremyshl and Lyubachev in 1215/1216[815]. In 1211, King András hired the
1 CONT Order of Teutonic Knights, who had been expelled back to Europe from
1 CONT Palestine, to defend the eastern frontier of Transylvania against the
1 CONT Kumans[816], but they attempted to establish their autonomy there under the
1 CONT protection of the Pope. King András set sail from Split for Palestine on
1 CONT crusade in Oct 1217, but left Acre in early 1218 having achieved little
1 CONT besides acquiring a small collection of religious relics[817]. He returned by
1 CONT the land route, via Constantinople, but at the end of 1218 he was seized in
1 CONT Bulgarian territory and released only after agreeing the marriage of his
1 CONT daughter to Ivan Asen II Tsar of Bulgaria[818]. He threatened war with Serbia
1 CONT after Grand Župan Stefan was crowned king of Serbia by the papal legate in
1 CONT 1217, claiming that he alone had the right to this title, but did not carry
1 CONT out the threat[819]. King András's abuses caused the Hungarian nobles to rebel
1 CONT in 1222 and forced him to issue the Golden Bull, a charter defining the rights
1 CONT of the nobility and restricting the king's right to appoint foreigners to
1 CONT office without the consent of the Council[820]. According to Goldstein, this
1 CONT reform was forced by the rebellion of the lower nobility in Croatia[821]. King
1 CONT András expelled the Teutonic Knights in 1225[822] on the pretext of their
1 CONT having disobeyed his orders. In 1227, Bortz Khan of the Kumans swore
1 CONT allegiance to the king of Hungary after ordering the baptism of his people,
1 CONT rex Cumaniæ being added to the titles of the Hungarian king soon after[823].
1 CONT King András attacked north-west Bulgaria in 1232 and recaptured Beograd and
1 CONT Braničevo/Barancs which he had been forced to cede as part of the dowry of his
1 CONT daughter Maria. He crossed the Danube into Wallachia where the Hungarians
1 CONT created a Banate in the Severin region[824]. The Chronicon Dubnicense records
1 CONT the death in 1235 of "Andreas filius Bele" and his burial "in monasterio de
1 CONT Egrus"[825]. The Chronicon Zagrabiense records the death "XI Kal Oct" in 1235
1 CONT of "rex Andreas filius regis Belæ III" and his burial "in monasterio suo
1 CONT Egres"[826]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death in
1 CONT 1235 of "Andreas rex Hungarie" and his burial "in civitate Waradino"[827].
1 CONT
1 CONT m secondly (Feb 1215) YOLANDE de Courtenay, daughter of PIERRE II de Courtenay
1 CONT Seigneur de Courtenay, Comte de Nevers, d’Auxerre et de Tonnerre, Marquis de
1 CONT Namur [later Latin Emperor of Constantinople] & his wife Yolande de Flandre
1 CONT ([1200]-1233, bur Egres Abbey). William of Tyre (Continuator) specifies that
1 CONT the queen of Hungary (unnamed) was the sister of the Latin emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople[834]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines names "unam
1 CONT filiarum eius [Namucensis comitis Petri] Hyolenz" as the wife of "Andreas rex
1 CONT Ungarie"[835]. Her marriage was arranged by her uncle, Henri Latin Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople, to obtain Hungarian support for his new ally Boril Tsar of
1 CONT Bulgaria[836]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death
1 CONT in 1233 of "regina Hoilanz de Hungaria" and her burial "in abbatia de
1 CONT Egis"[837].
1 CONT
1 CONT King András II & his second wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. **IOLANDA ([1215]-Huesca 12 Oct 1251). The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña
1 CONT records the second marriage of Jaime I King of Aragon and "la filla del Rey de
1 CONT Vngria…Ardeura la qual depues huuo nombre Violant nieta del Emperador de
1 CONT Constantin noble"[871]. She was known as VIOLANT in Catalonia. The Anales
1 CONT Toledanos record the death “IV Non Oct” in 1251 of “Dña Yoles, Regina
1 CONT Aragonum”[872]. The Chronicle of the Hôtel de Ville de Montpellier records the
1 CONT death in 1251 "D. Yoles regina Aragoniæ"[873]. The Thalamus de Montpellier
1 CONT records the death in Sep 1251 at Lérida of "la dona Yoles regina dAragon
1 CONT molher del rei Jacme"[874]. m (Barcelona 8 Sep 1235) as his second wife, JAIME
1 CONT I "el Conquistador" King of Aragon, Conde de Barcelona, son of PEDRO II King
1 CONT of Aragon & his wife Marie de Montpellier (Montpellier 1 Feb 1208-Valencia 27
1 CONT Jul 1276, bur Poblet, monastery of Nuestra Señora).**
1 CONT <https://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/HUNGARY.htm#_Toc482625407>
1 CONT
1 CONT King Jaime I & his second wife had ten children:
1 CONT
1 CONT >2\. Infanta doña VIOLANTE de Aragón ([1236]-Roncevalles 1301, bur Seville).
1 CONT The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña names "la primera…Violant…la otra
1 CONT Costancia…et Isabel…la quarta…Maria" as the four daughters of King Jaime and
1 CONT his second wife, stating that Violante married "Don Alfonso filio primogenitor
1 CONT del Rey de Castiella"[394]. The betrothal contract of “dominus Infans
1 CONT Alfonsus...regis Castellæ...primogenitus” and “domina Violante filia domini
1 CONT Jacobi...regis Aragonum” is dated 26 Nov 1246[395]. Pope Innocent IV issued a
1 CONT dispensation for the marriage of “rege Aragonum...Yola nata ipsius” and
1 CONT “Alphonsus primogenitus regis Castellæ”, related “quarta consanguinitatis
1 CONT linea”, dated 23 Jan 1249[396]. Under the testament of "Jacobus…Rex Aragoniæ,
1 CONT Majoricarum et Valenciæ, Comes Barchinonæ et Urgelli, et Dominus
1 CONT Montispessulani", dated 26 Aug 1272, the king made bequests to "…filiam
1 CONT nostram Domnam Yolant…"[397]. After her eldest son died, she fled with his
1 CONT infant children to Aragon. She died returning from a pilgrimage to Rome. The
1 CONT Nobiliario of Pedro Conde de Barcelos records that "la Reina D. Violante" was
1 CONT buried "en Sevilla" with her husband[398]. m (Betrothed 26 Nov 1246, Papal
1 CONT dispensation 23 Jan 1249, Valladolid 29 Jan 1249) Infante don ALFONSO de
1 CONT Castilla, son of FERNANDO III "el Santo" King of Castile & his first wife
1 CONT Elisabeth von Hohenstaufen (Toledo 23 Nov 1221-Seville 4 Apr 1284, bur
1 CONT Seville, Cathedral Santa María). He succeeded his father in 1252 as ALFONSO X
1 CONT “el Sabio” King of Castile and León.
1 CONT
1 CONT >3\. Infante don PEDRO de Aragón (1239-Villafranca del Penedés 2 or 11 Nov
1 CONT 1285, bur Monasterio de Santa Cruz). The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña names
1 CONT "Pedro, Jayme et Sancho" as the three sons of King Jaime and his second
1 CONT wife[399]. Under the testament of "Jacobus…Rex Aragoniæ, Majoricarum et
1 CONT Valenciæ, Comes Barchinonæ et Urgelli, et Dominus Montispessulani", dated 26
1 CONT Aug 1272, the king made bequests to "…filium nostrum primogenitum Infantem
1 CONT P…"[400]. He succeeded his father in 1276 as PEDRO III "el Grande" King of
1 CONT Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT >4\. Infanta doña CONSTANZA de Aragón ([1240]-before 1266, bur Uclés). The
1 CONT Crónica de San Juan de la Peña names "la primera…Violant…la otra Costancia…et
1 CONT Isabel…la quarta…Maria" as the four daughters of King Jaime and his second
1 CONT wife, stating that Constanza married "Don Manuel hermano del…Alfonso rey de
1 CONT Castiella"[401]. The Nobiliario of Pedro Conde de Barcelos records that "El
1 CONT Infante D. Manuel" married "D. Costança de Aragon"[402]. Under the testament
1 CONT of "Jacobus…Rex Aragoniæ, Majoricarum et Valenciæ, Comes Barchinonæ et
1 CONT Urgelli, et Dominus Montispessulani", dated 26 Aug 1272, the king made
1 CONT bequests to "…filios Infantis Domnæ Constantiæ quondam filiæ nostræ et
1 CONT Infantis domini Emanuelis fratris…Regis Castellæ, nepotes nostros"[403]. m
1 CONT (Calatayud 1260) as his first wife, Infante don MANUEL de Castilla, Señor de
1 CONT Escalona, Peñafiel y Villena, son of FERNANDO III "el Santo" King of Castile &
1 CONT his first wife Elisabeth von Hohenstaufen (Carrión de los Condes 1234-Peñafiel
1 CONT 25 Dec 1283, bur Uclés, Santiago convent).
1 CONT
1 CONT >5 Infante don JAIME de Aragón (Montpellier 31 May 1243-Palma de Mallorca 29
1 CONT May 1311). The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña names "Pedro, Jayme et Sancho"
1 CONT as the three sons of King Jaime and his second wife[404]. The Chronicle of the
1 CONT Hôtel de Ville de Montpellier records the birth in 1243 "in vigilia
1 CONT Pentecosti" of "D. rex Jacobus et regina eius uxor...Jacobus filius" in
1 CONT Montpellier[405]. Under the projected partition of 1244, Jaime [Jaume] would
1 CONT receive the Balearic Islands, Valencia, and Montpellier. Under the further
1 CONT projected partition of 1262, Jaume would receive the Balearic Islands,
1 CONT Montpellier, Roussillon and Cerdaña. Under the testament of "Jacobus…Rex
1 CONT Aragoniæ, Majoricarum et Valenciæ, Comes Barchinonæ et Urgelli, et Dominus
1 CONT Montispessulani", dated 26 Aug 1272, the king made bequests to "filius noster
1 CONT Infans Jacobus…"[406]. He succeeded his father in 1276 as JAIME II King of
1 CONT Mallorca, Comte de Roussillon et de Cerdagne/Cerdaña, Seigneur de Montpellier,
1 CONT Barón de Ompelas.
1 CONT
1 CONT >6\. Infante don FERNANDO de Aragón ([1245]-1250). The primary source which
1 CONT confirms his parentage has not yet been identified.
1 CONT
1 CONT >7\. Infante don SANCHO de Aragón ([1246]-the Holy Land 1251). The primary
1 CONT source which confirms his parentage has not yet been identified.
1 CONT
1 CONT >8\. Infanta doña ISABEL de Aragón (1243-Cosenza, Calabria 28 Jan 1271, bur
1 CONT église de l'Abbaye royale de Saint-Denis). The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña
1 CONT names "la primera…Violant…la otra Costancia…et Isabel…la quarta…Maria" as the
1 CONT four daughters of King Jaime and his second wife, stating that Isabel married
1 CONT "Phelip filio primogenito del Rey de Francia"[407]. The marriage contract
1 CONT between "Ludovicus…Francorum Rex…filium nostrum Philippum" and "Isabellam
1 CONT filiam…Jacobi…Regis Aragonum, Maioricarum et Valentiæ, comitem Barchinonensem
1 CONT et Urgelli et dominum Montispessulani" is dated 11 May 1258[408]. The Flores
1 CONT historiarum of Adam of Clermont records the marriage "in civitate
1 CONT Claromontensi" in 1262 of "Philippus regis Franciæ filius" and "filiam regis
1 CONT Aragonum...Ysabellam neptem beatæ Helizabeth Teutonicæ", adding that his
1 CONT father-in-law granted Philippe his property "in civitate Bituricensi,
1 CONT Carcassona et in diœcesi Mimatensi" in exchange for property "in comitatibus
1 CONT de Besaudu et Rossilionis et Cataloniæ"[409]. The “Visitation” of Rigaud
1 CONT Archbishop of Rouen records “II Non Jul” 1262 that he conducted the marriage
1 CONT (“desponsavimus”) “in majori ecclesia dicti loci” (suggested in the edition
1 CONT consulted to be “Clari Montis”) of “dominum Philippum primogenitum domini
1 CONT regis Francorum” and “domicella Ysabelli filia...regis Aragonum”[410]. The
1 CONT Gesta Sancti Ludovici records “circa Pentecosten” 1262 the marriage “apud
1 CONT Claromontem in Avernia” of “Ludovicus rex Franciæ...Philippo filio suo
1 CONT primogenito” and “Ysabellam filiam regis Aragoniæ”[411]. She died, 6 months
1 CONT pregnant, after a fall from a horse on returning from the crusade in Tunis.
1 CONT The necrology of Sainte-Chapelle records the death "V Kal Feb" of "dominis
1 CONT Ysabellis de Aragonis quondam Francie regine"[412]. Under the testament of
1 CONT "Jacobus…Rex Aragoniæ, Majoricarum et Valenciæ, Comes Barchinonæ et Urgelli,
1 CONT et Dominus Montispessulani", dated 26 Aug 1272, the king made bequests to
1 CONT "…filios…Philippi…Regis Franciæ et Domnæ Elizabet bonæ memoriæ Regina Franciæ
1 CONT filiæ nostræ, nepotes nostras…"[413]. m (contract Corbès near Montpellier 11
1 CONT May 1258, Clermont-en-Auvergne 6 Jul 1262) as his first wife, PHILIPPE de
1 CONT France, son of LOUIS IX King of France & his wife Marguerite de Provence
1 CONT (Poissy, Yvelines 1 May 1245-Perpignan 5 Oct 1285, bur église de l'Abbaye
1 CONT royale de Saint-Denis). Heir to the throne in 1260 on the death of his older
1 CONT brother. He succeeded his father in 1270 as PHILIPPE III "le Hardi" King of
1 CONT France.
1 CONT
1 CONT >9\. Infanta doña MARÍA de Aragón ([1248]-Zaragoza 1267). The Crónica de San
1 CONT Juan de la Peña names "la primera…Violant…la otra Costancia…et Isabel…la
1 CONT quarta…Maria" as the four daughters of King Jaime and his second wife, stating
1 CONT that María was unmarried[414]. Nun at Sijena.
1 CONT
1 CONT >10\. Infante don SANCHO de Aragón ([1250]-killed in battle Martos 21 Oct
1 CONT 1275). The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña names "Pedro, Jayme et Sancho" as
1 CONT the three sons of King Jaime and his second wife, stating that Sancho was
1 CONT archbishop of Toledo[415]. Archdeacon at Belchite 1263. Abbot at Valladolid
1 CONT 1263. "Infante don Sancho, fijo del…Rey de Aragon, et Abbad de Valladolit"
1 CONT granted rights to the council of Tovilla by charter dated 28 Feb 1265[416].
1 CONT Archbishop of Toledo 21 Aug 1266. The Anales Toledanos record the death “XII
1 CONT Kal Nov” in 1275 of “Dñs Sanctius filius Regis Aragonum et Archiepiscopus
1 CONT Toletanus”[417]. He was killed in battle against the Moors.
1 CONT
1 CONT >11\. Infanta doña LEONOR de Aragón ([1251]-young). The primary source which
1 CONT confirms her parentage has not yet been identified.
1 CONT [https://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ARAGON%20&%20CATALONIA.htm#JaimeIdied1276B](https://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ARAGON%20&%20CATALONIA.htm#JaimeIdied1276B)
