1 CONT =Violante de Hungría=
1 CONT
1 CONT Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre
1 CONT Violante de Hungría, nacida alrededor de 1216 en Esztergom, Hungría y
1 CONT fallecida en Huesca en octubre de 1251, fue reina de Aragón tras casarse en
1 CONT 1235 con Jaime I de Aragón, el Conquistador, de quien fue la segunda esposa.
1 CONT
1 CONT Era hija del rey Andrés II de Hungría y de Violante de Courtenay. Su dote
1 CONT significaba una aportación de dinero y territorios, que nunca se hicieron
1 CONT efectivos.
1 CONT
1 CONT Impulsó de forma decisiva la conquista del reino de Valencia en 1238 y
1 CONT participó activamente en la política real. Se implicó sobre todo en las
1 CONT particiones de la herencia que quedarían a los hijos que tuvo con Jaime I,
1 CONT tratando de enemistar al rey con Alfonso, hijo de su primer matrimonio con
1 CONT Leonor de Castilla.
1 CONT
1 CONT Violante y Jaime I tuvieron cuatro hijos y cinco hijas:
1 CONT
1 CONT   1. Fernando, muerto joven.
1 CONT
1 CONT   2. Sancho, arzobispo de Toledo.
1 CONT
1 CONT   3. Violante, que se casaría con Alfonso X el Sabio, rey de Castilla.
1 CONT
1 CONT   4. Constanza, que se casaría con Manuel de Portugal.
1 CONT
1 CONT   5. María, que se haría religiosa.
1 CONT
1 CONT   6. Sancha, que moriría en peregrinaje a Tierra Santa.
1 CONT
1 CONT   7. Isabel, que se casaría con Felipe III de Francia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Sus restos y los de una hija, Sancha, yacen en el presbiterio del monasterio
1 CONT cisterciense de Santa María de Vallbona en Cataluña.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Violant of Hungary (Kingdom of Hungary, c. 1216 – October 1251 in Huesca) was
1 CONT Queen consort of James I of Aragon. She is also called Yolanda or Violante de
1 CONT Hungría in Spanish and Iolanda or Violant d'Hongria in Catalan .
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant was a daughter of Andrew II of Hungary and Violant of Courtenay.
1 CONT
1 CONT She married James I in 1235, being his second wife, and had several children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Violant of Aragon (1236-1301), queen of Castile by her marriage to Alfonso
1 CONT X.
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Constance of Aragon (1239-1269), infanta of Castile by her marriage to
1 CONT Juan Manuel of Castile, son of Ferdinand III of Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Peter III of Aragon (1240-1285).
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. James II of Majorca (1243-1311).
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. Ferdinand of Aragon (1245-1250).
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. Sancha of Aragon (1246-1251).
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. Isabella of Aragon (1247-1271), married Philip III of France
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. Maria of Aragon (1248-1267), nun.
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250-1279)
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. Elionor of Aragon (1251-?, young)
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant and her daughter Sancha's remains are at the monastery of Santa María
1 CONT de Vallbona in Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violant_of_Hungary>
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Violant of Hungary (Esztergom, Kingdom of Hungary, c. 1216 – 1253) was Queen
1 CONT consort of James I of Aragon. She is also called Jolánta in Hungarian, Iolanda
1 CONT or Violant d'Hongria in Catalan and Yolanda or Violante de Hungría in Spanish.
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant was a daughter of Andrew II of Hungary and Violant of Courtenay. Her
1 CONT paternal grandparents were Béla III of Hungary and his first wife Agnes of
1 CONT Antioch. Her maternal grandparents were Peter II of Courtenay and his second
1 CONT wife Yolanda of Flanders.
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant was a half-sister of Anne Marie, Empress of Bulgaria, Béla IV of
1 CONT Hungary, Saint Elisabeth of Hungary and Coloman of Lodomeria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant's mother died in 1233, when Violant was seventeen years old. Her
1 CONT father remarried, to Beatrice d'Este, they had a son called Stephen. Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant married James I in 1235, being his second wife. By the marriage,
1 CONT Violant became Queen Consort of Aragon. James already had one son, Alfonso by
1 CONT his first marriage to Eleanor of Castile. James however divorced Eleanor and
1 CONT decided to remarry, he chose Violant.
1 CONT
1 CONT James and Violant had ten children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Violant of Aragon (1236-1301), queen of Castile by her marriage to
1 CONT Alphonse X.
1 CONT 2\. Constance of Aragon (1239-1269), infanta of Castile by her marriage to
1 CONT Juan Manuel of Castile, son of Ferdinand III of Castile.
1 CONT 3\. Peter III of Aragon (1240-1285).
1 CONT 4\. James II of Majorca (1243-1311).
1 CONT 5\. Ferdinand of Aragon (1245-1250).
1 CONT 6\. Sancha of Aragon (1246-1251).
1 CONT 7\. Isabella of Aragon (1247-1271), married Philip III of France
1 CONT 8\. Maria of Aragon (1248-1267), nun.
1 CONT 9\. Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250-1275)
1 CONT 10\. Eleanor of Aragon (1251-?, young)
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant's daughter, Isabella became Queen of France by her marriage to Philip
1 CONT III of France. Isabella was mother of Philip IV of France and Charles of
1 CONT Valois.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles of Valois was father of Philip VI of France, Isabella, Duchess of
1 CONT Bourbon and Blanche, Queen of Germany.
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant died in 1253. Violant and her daughter Sancha's remains are at the
1 CONT Real Monasterio de Santa Maria de Vallbona in Vallbona de les Monges,
1 CONT Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her husband remarried one more time, to Teresa Gil de Vidaure, who was once
1 CONT James' mistress.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Violant of Hungary From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant of Hungary (Esztergom, Kingdom of Hungary, c. 1216 – 1253) was Queen
1 CONT consort of James I of Aragon. She is also called Jolánta in Hungarian, Yolanda
1 CONT or Violante de Hungría in Spanish and Iolanda or Violant d'Hongria in Catalan.
1 CONT Violant was a daughter of Andrew II of Hungary and Violant of Courtenay. She
1 CONT married James I in 1235, being his second wife, and had several children: 1.
1 CONT Violant of Aragon (1236-1301), queen of Castile by her marriage to Alfonso X.
1 CONT 2. Constance of Aragon (1239-1269), infanta of Castile by her marriage to Juan
1 CONT Manuel of Castile, son of Ferdinand III of Castile. 3. Peter III of Aragon
1 CONT (1240-1285). 4. James II of Majorca (1243-1311). 5. Ferdinand of Aragon
1 CONT (1245-1250). 6. Sancha of Aragon (1246-1251). 7. Isabella of Aragon
1 CONT (1247-1271), married Philip III of France 8. Maria of Aragon (1248-1267), nun.
1 CONT 9. Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250-1275) 10. Elionor of Aragon (1251-?,
1 CONT young) Violant and her daughter Sancha's remains are at the monastery of Santa
1 CONT María de Vallbona in Lerida.
1 CONT
