1 CONT Violant of Hungary (Esztergom, Kingdom of Hungary, c. 1216 – 1253) was Queen
1 CONT consort of James I of Aragon. She is also called Jolánta in Hungarian, Iolanda
1 CONT or Violant d'Hongria in Catalan and Yolanda or Violante de Hungría in Spanish.
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant was a daughter of Andrew II of Hungary and Violant of Courtenay.
1 CONT
1 CONT She married James I in 1235, being his second wife, and had several children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant of Aragon (1236-1301), queen of Castile by her marriage to Alphonse X.
1 CONT Constance of Aragon (1239-1269), infanta of Castile by her marriage to Juan
1 CONT Manuel of Castile, son of Ferdinand III of Castile. Peter III of Aragon
1 CONT (1240-1285). James II of Majorca (1243-1311). Ferdinand of Aragon (1245-1250).
1 CONT Sancha of Aragon (1246-1251). Isabella of Aragon (1247-1271), married Philip
1 CONT III of France Maria of Aragon (1248-1267), nun. Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo
1 CONT (1250-1275) Elionor of Aragon (1251-?, young)
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant and her daughter Sancha's remains are at the monastery of Santa Maria
1 CONT de Vallbona in Lleida, Catalonia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by Eleanor of Castile Queen Consort of Aragon 1235–1253 Succeeded by
1 CONT Teresa Gil de Vidaure
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Violant or Violante of Aragon, also known as Yolanda of Aragon (1236 - 1301)
1 CONT Queen consort of Castile and León (1252-1284).
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born in Zaragoza, the daughter of King James I of Aragon (1213-1276)
1 CONT and his second wife the queen Yolande of Hungary (ca.1215-1253). Her maternal
1 CONT grandparents were Andrew II of Hungary and Violant of Courtenay.
1 CONT
1 CONT On December 26, 1246 she married in Valladolid with the future King Alfonso X
1 CONT of Castile and Leon (1221-1284). Because of her youth (Violante was only 10
1 CONT years old at the time of the marriage), she produced no children for several
1 CONT years and it was feared that she was barren. The oft-repeated claim that
1 CONT Alfonso almost had their marriage annulled is untrue, and they went on to have
1 CONT twelve children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Fernando, died in infancy, and buried in Las Huelgas in Burgos. Berengaria of
1 CONT Castile (1253-after 1284). She was betrothed to Louis, the son and heir of
1 CONT King Louis IX of France, but her fiance died prematurely in 1260. She entered
1 CONT the convent in Las Huelgas, where she was living in 1284. Beatriz of Castile
1 CONT (1254-1280). She married William VII, Marquess of Montferrat. Ferdinand de la
1 CONT Cerda, Infante of Castile (October 23, 1255-July 25, 1275). He married
1 CONT Blanche, the daughter of King Louis IX of France, by whom he had two children.
1 CONT Because he predeceased his father, his younger brother Sancho inherited the
1 CONT throne. Leonor of Castile (1257-1275) Sancho IV of Castile (May 13, 1258-1295)
1 CONT Constanza of Castile (1258-August 22, 1280), a nun at Las Huelgas. Pedro of
1 CONT Castile (June 1260-October 10, 1283) Juan of Castile, Lord of Valencia (March
1 CONT or April, 1262-June 25, 1319). Isabella, died young. Violante of Castile
1 CONT (1265-1296). She married Diego Lopez de Haro Jaime of Castile (August
1 CONT 1266-August 9, 1284) She died at Roncevalles.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Wikipedia: <http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yolanda_von_Ungarn> Yolanda von
1 CONT Ungarn aus Wikipedia, der freien Enzyklopädie Wechseln zu: Navigation, Suche
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda von Ungarn (* 1219; † 9. Oktober 1251 in Huesca) war eine ungarische
1 CONT Adlige. Leben [Bearbeiten]
1 CONT
1 CONT Sie war die Tochter von Andreas II. von Ungarn aus zweiter Ehe mit Jolante
1 CONT Courtenay (Tochter von Kaiser Peter (Lateinisches Kaiserreich)).
1 CONT
1 CONT Sie war die zweite Ehefrau von Jakob I. von Aragonien. Sie hatten zehn Kinder.
1 CONT Ihre Tochter, Isabella von Aragon (* 1243; † 1271 in Cosenza) war von 1270 bis
1 CONT 1271 Königin von Frankreic
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Violant of Hungary (Esztergom, Kingdom of Hungary, c. 1216 – 1253) was Queen
1 CONT consort of James I of Aragon. She is also called Jolánta in Hungarian, Iolanda
1 CONT or Violant d'Hongria in Catalan and Yolanda or Violante de Hungría in Spanish.
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant was a daughter of Andrew II of Hungary and Violant of Courtenay.
1 CONT
1 CONT She married James I in 1235, being his second wife, and had several children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Violant of Aragon (1236-1301), queen of Castile by her marriage to Alfonso
1 CONT X.
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Constance of Aragon (1239-1269), infanta of Castile by her marriage to
1 CONT Juan Manuel of Castile, son of Ferdinand III of Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Peter III of Aragon (1240-1285).
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. James II of Majorca (1243-1311).
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. Ferdinand of Aragon (1245-1250).
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. Sancha of Aragon (1246-1251).
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. Isabella of Aragon (1247-1271), married Philip III of France
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. Maria of Aragon (1248-1267), nun.
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. Sancho, Archbishop of Toledo (1250-1275)
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. Elionor of Aragon (1251-?, young)
1 CONT
1 CONT Violant and her daughter Sancha's remains are at the monastery of Santa Maria
1 CONT de Vallbona in Lleida, Catalonia.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Her marriage produced 4 sons & 5 daughters.
1 CONT
1 CONT Buried ~ Tomb is white stone on top with a cross. The lower part is darker
1 CONT with a symbol. It sits on top of two small pillars which has a cross on each.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Yolante Arpád married Jaime I, Rey de Aragón, son of Pedro II, Rey de Aragón
1 CONT and Marie de Montpellier, on 8 September 1235. She died circa October 1251.
1 CONT She was the daughter of Andreas II Arpád, King of Hungary and Yolande de
1 CONT Courtney.1,2 She was also known as Yolande (?). Children of Yolante Arpád and
1 CONT Jaime I, Rey de Aragón
