0 @N00455@ NOTE geni:about_me *<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_I_of_Naples>
1 CONT
1 CONT **Charles I** (21 March 1226 – 7 January 1285), commonly called **Charles of
1 CONT Anjou** , was the King of Sicily by conquest from 1266, though he had received
1 CONT it as a papal grant in 1262 and was expelled from the island in the aftermath
1 CONT of the Sicilian Vespers of 1282. Thereafter, he continued to claim the island,
1 CONT though his power was restricted to the peninsular possessions of the kingdom,
1 CONT with his capital at Naples (and for this he is usually titled King of Naples
1 CONT after 1282, as are his successors). Charles was the youngest son of Louis VIII
1 CONT of France and Blanche of Castile, and hence younger brother of Louis IX of
1 CONT France and Alfonso II of Toulouse. He conquered the Kingdom of Sicily from the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen and began to acquire lands in the eastern Mediterranean. However,
1 CONT the War of the Sicilian Vespers forced him to abandon his plans to reassemble
1 CONT the Latin Empire.
1 CONT
1 CONT By marriage to Beatrice, heiress of Raymond Berengar IV of Provence, he was
1 CONT Count of Provence and Forcalquier from 1246.
1 CONT
1 CONT From : HISTOIRE de la Martre (83840-France)
1 CONT
1 CONT Au X° siècle, un seigneur « HUGO » fait établir sur le sommet d’une colline
1 CONT culminant à 1068m une construction dénommée « le Castellas de Pétra Longa »
1 CONT dotée d’une église dédiée à Notre-Dame. L’origine du nom pourrait venir de la
1 CONT présence de quelque mégalithe. Il fait don d’une partie de ses terres à
1 CONT l’abbaye Saint-Honorat de lérins.
1 CONT
1 CONT Au XII° siècle, la seigneurie est en apanage à la puissance famille des
1 CONT Castellanes-Salernes qui la conservera jusqu’au XVII° siècle. **Le 11 Avril
1 CONT 1248 Charles I Comte de Provence l’érigeait en fief en faveur de Raymond
1 CONT Geoffroy de Castellane**
1 CONT _[[http://www.lamartre.fr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=122&Itemid=184](http://www.lamartre.fr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=122&Itemid=184)]_.
1 CONT Pendant les guerres de religion, le village fut entièrement dévasté. Le site
1 CONT du Castellas fut abandonné et, Vincent-Anne de Forbin, nouveau seigneur du
1 CONT lieu par son mariage avec Aymare de Castellane en 1613 décida de reconstruire
1 CONT le nouveau village et le château dans la plaine.
1 CONT
1 CONT Le château fut détruit par un incendie, et depuis porte le nom de Châteaurima
1 CONT ce qui signifie en Provençal Château brûlé. Le 13 juin1674, Marie Charlotte de
1 CONT Forbin épouse François-Charles de Vintimille, comte du Luc, et lui apporte sa
1 CONT dot de la Martre. En 1755, elle devient propriété d’Augustin de Pélicot,
1 CONT originaire de Grasse, secrétaire du roi depuis 1754, qui fut le dernier
1 CONT seigneur du lieu avant la révolution. La famille a résidé à Châteaurima
1 CONT jusqu’au décès de l’avocat A PELICOT en 1879, il fut l’un des principaux
1 CONT insurgés du Var de 1852.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1247, his brother Louis IX made him Count of Anjou and Maine, as appanages
1 CONT of the French crown. By conquest and self-proclamation, he became King of
1 CONT Albania in 1272 and by purchase King of Jerusalem in 1277. By the testament of
1 CONT William II of Villehardouin, he inherited the Principality of Achaea in 1278.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was born in 1226, shortly before the death of his father, King Louis
1 CONT VIII. Like his immediate older brother, Philippe Dagobert (who died in 1232
1 CONT aged 10) he did not receive a county as appanage, as had his older brothers.
1 CONT Shortly after the death of Philippe Dagobert, his other brother, John Tristan,
1 CONT Count of Anjou and Maine, also died. Charles became the next in line to
1 CONT received the Counties, but was formally invested only in 1247. The affection
1 CONT of his mother Blanche seems largely to have been bestowed upon his brother
1 CONT Louis; and Louis tended to favour his other younger brothers, Robert of Artois
1 CONT and Alphonse of Toulouse. The self-reliance this engendered in Charles may
1 CONT account for the drive and ambition he showed in his later life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles' wife Beatrice died on 23 September 1267, and he immediately sought a
1 CONT new marriage to Margaret, daughter of Bela IV of Hungary. However, Margaret
1 CONT wished to be a nun (and was later canonized); Charles instead married (on 18
1 CONT November 1268), Margaret, Countess of Tonnerre (1250 – 4 September 1308,
1 CONT Tonnerre), the daughter of Eudes of Burgundy. However, he was able to make a
1 CONT marital alliance with the Hungarians: his son Charles, Prince of Salerno
1 CONT married Maria, daughter of crown prince Stephen, while Charles' daughter
1 CONT Elizabeth married Stephen's son Ladislas.
1 CONT
1 CONT On his death, Charles left all of his domains to his son Charles, then a
1 CONT prisoner in Catalonia. For the time being, they were held by a joint regency
1 CONT between a papal legate and Robert II of Artois. Charles had spent his life
1 CONT striving to assemble a Mediterranean empire out of whatever land he could get
1 CONT through law or force of arms. He did so, it seems, with a clear conscience; he
1 CONT regarded himself as God's instrument to uphold the Papacy and punish the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen. He ruled justly, but with the rigidity and severity that might
1 CONT be expected in one of his convictions. Ultimately, his unbending austerity
1 CONT could not inspire the devotion needed to hold his conquests together.
1 CONT
1 CONT Still, he was to leave a substantial legacy to his heirs. Henry II of Cyprus
1 CONT reclaimed the Kingdom of Jerusalem after his death, for the few short years
1 CONT left to it; but his possessions otherwise remained within the Angevin dynasty
1 CONT which he founded, or their descendants. Both the Angevins and their Aragonese
1 CONT rivals were to claim the title of "King of Sicily"; but the Angevins, confined
1 CONT to the mainland, would be known to history as "Kings of Naples". But the style
1 CONT of "King of Sicily" persisted; and when the two realms were reunited, it was
1 CONT under the style of "King of the Two Sicilies".
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles of Anjou contributed to the early medieval revival of learning, often
1 CONT referred to as the "Latin" Renaissance, through his employment of several
1 CONT Jewish scholars at the University of Salerno and Naples, who were expert
1 CONT translators. The most famous of these, Moses of Palermo, he had tutored in
1 CONT Latin, to enable direct translations of ancient classical and Arab texts.
1 CONT These Jewish scholars translated dozens of philosophical and medical treatises
1 CONT into Latin, bringing the heritage of classical antiquity and the great
1 CONT contemporary Muslim culture to pre-Renaissance Europe. [3]
1 CONT
1 CONT However, his wars resulted in an even more serious consequence than the
1 CONT partition of the Kingdom of Sicily. Pope Martin IV had hopelessly compromised
1 CONT the Papacy in his cause; and the botched secular "Crusades" against Sicily and
1 CONT (after Charles' death) Aragon greatly tarnished its spiritual power. The
1 CONT collapse of its moral authority and the rise of nationalism rang the death
1 CONT knell for Crusading, and would ultimately lead to the Avignon Papacy and the
1 CONT Western Schism. Charles was an able soldier and a good administrator; but his
1 CONT failure to understand the qualities of his diverse subjects, and his grasping,
1 CONT if pious, ambition, ultimately led him to failure.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the Divine Comedy Dante sees Charles outside the gates of Purgatory
1 CONT "singing in accord" with his former rival Peter.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and children
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was wedded to Beatrice of Provence on 31 January 1246, in Aix-en-
1 CONT Provence. Beatrice was the youngest daughter of Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of
1 CONT Provence and Forcalquier, who had died on 19 August 1245 by his wife Beatrice
1 CONT of Savoy. As his elder three daughters had all married kings and received
1 CONT substantial dowries, Raymond settled his entire inheritance upon Beatrice,
1 CONT making Charles Count of Provence and Forcalquier. They had the following
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Louis (1248, Nicosia)
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Blanche (1250 – July 1269), married 1265 Count Robert III of Flanders
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Beatrice of Sicily (1252–1275), married 15 October 1273 at Foggia to Philip of Courtenay, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Charles II of Naples (1254 – 1309)
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Philip of Sicily (1256 – 1 January 1277), titular King of Thessalonica from 1274, married 28 May 1271 to Isabella of Villehardouin
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Robert (1258–1265)
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Elizabeth of Sicily (1261 – c. 1300), married bef. September 1272 to Ladislas IV of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT After the death of Beatrice, he married Margaret of Burgundy in 1268. Their
1 CONT only daughter, Margaret, died in infancy.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT The Angevin era defined the decline of Sicily, and particularly Palermo, as a
1 CONT center of political and economic power. While acknowledging that Sicily was a
1 CONT kingdom in its own right, Charles ruled from Naples, which previously had been
1 CONT a prosperous but politically less important city than Palermo, Bari or
1 CONT Salerno.
1 CONT
1 CONT In Sicily, the changes were immediate. Thousands of French troops arrived, and
1 CONT taxes were increased. For the first time in centuries, Sicily was the
1 CONT "dominion" of a "foreign" ruler who saw no reason to visit the island. Worse,
1 CONT the Sicilians themselves were made to feel like subjects.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the years following 1268, Sicily was almost entirely Latinized. Except for
1 CONT a few monasteries in the Nebrodi region, the Christians were Catholic, and
1 CONT with Charles' help a later pope, Gregory X, attempted to subjugate the Eastern
1 CONT (Orthodox) Church of Constantinople. The new regime openly resented the Arabs
1 CONT of Lucera (in Puglia) and Sicily. Mosques were gradually abandoned; many were
1 CONT converted to churches. Jews were tolerated, though their communities became
1 CONT fewer outside the major cities.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Sicilian language had emerged as a Latin tongue, albeit with many Greek
1 CONT and Arabic words. In name, the Sicilian nobility had Norman, Swabian and
1 CONT Lombard roots. Truth be told, most Sicilian nobles had Arab or Byzantine
1 CONT ancestors, too. From the beginning, the nobility viewed the Angevin French in
1 CONT a negative light, initially as something of a nuisance and then as a
1 CONT repressive instrument of royal power. Charles of Anjou was anything but an
1 CONT enlightened ruler. His son, Charles "the Lame" of Salerno, was viewed by all,
1 CONT including his father, as weak and incompetent.
1 CONT
1 CONT Around Sicily a number of structures remain from the rather brief Angevin
1 CONT period. Palermo's Church of Saint Francis of Assisi (the portal is shown
1 CONT here), begun in 1255, exemplifies the "Italianate Gothic" style --Italian but
1 CONT not particularly Gothic.
1 CONT
1 CONT The expansionist policies of Charles were not limited to Italy. Apart from
1 CONT influence in northern Italy, he claimed the crown of Jerusalem borne by
1 CONT Frederick II. After Louis IX died on crusade in Tunisia in 1270, his son,
1 CONT Philip (who ruled France as Philip III), fell under the influence of Charles.
1 CONT
1 CONT By 1282, Charles ruled Sicily and southern Italy, Jerusalem, Albania,
1 CONT Provence, Anjou, Maine and part of Tunisia. He was preparing an invasion of
1 CONT Constantinople which would have finally brought the Byzantine world --and
1 CONT particularly its Church-- under Latin control. The new pope, Martin IV, a
1 CONT Frenchman, openly encouraged this. Charles was, without doubt, the most
1 CONT powerful European monarch.
1 CONT
1 CONT Two decades earlier, Manfred Hohenstaufen, an illegitimate son of Frederick II
1 CONT (but presumed heir to the thrones of Sicily and Germany) killed by Charles'
1 CONT Angevin forces at the Battle of Benevento in 1266, had betrothed his daughter,
1 CONT Constance, to Peter of Aragon. On this tenuous basis, a number of Sicilian
1 CONT nobles exiled from Charles' Kingdom since the 1260s sought the alliance of
1 CONT Peter I of Aragon, whose realm based at Barcelona included Catalonia and other
1 CONT prosperous regions of northeastern Spain. Based on the Sicilians' requests,
1 CONT but also on various other political issues, Peter soon began preparations for
1 CONT a war against Charles.
1 CONT
1 CONT Clearly, the rivalry between Guelphs (supporters of the Papacy and now the
1 CONT Angevins) and Ghibellines (supporters of the Holy Roman Emperor and Swabians)
1 CONT had not abated, but what followed was completely unexpected.
1 CONT
1 CONT On Easter Monday, 30 March, 1282, a popular revolt broke out, leading to the
1 CONT deaths of thousands of French, including numerous civilians. The uprising,
1 CONT later called the "Sicilian Vespers," spread across the island in a matter of
1 CONT days. The "War of the Vespers" was the first feudal revolt of this kind. Its
1 CONT efficiency and ruthlessness frightened monarchs far beyond Naples and Rome.
1 CONT Almost simultaneously, the French castellans and garrisons of Sicily's
1 CONT fortified cities were isolated and killed, in Palermo, Caccamo, Vicari,
1 CONT Caltanissetta, Girgenti (Agrigento), Caltanissetta, Milazzo, Castrogiovanni
1 CONT (Enna), Taormina, Catania... In September, Peter was formally nominated King
1 CONT of Sicily by the island's nobles. That, however, was not the end of the war.
1 CONT
1 CONT In a series of battles at sea and skirmishes on land, the Angevin forces were
1 CONT defeated by Aragonese-Sicilian ones. In one of the war's comical episodes,
1 CONT Charles and the younger Peter were to meet for a duel to decide the fate of
1 CONT Sicily, each accompanied by a hundred fighting knights. This was to take place
1 CONT in June 1283 at Bordeaux, capital of the neutral French territories of Edward,
1 CONT King of England. Each king agreed to appear with his suite but it was tacitly
1 CONT understood that each would arrive at a different time. Then each sovereign
1 CONT claimed that the other was a coward. In another incident, King Charles'
1 CONT incompetent son, Charles of Salerno, was taken prisoner at a sea battle in
1 CONT June 1284 and held in the citadel of Cefalù.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Charles died in January of 1285, Angevin power in Sicily had essentially
1 CONT vanished. The new king of Naples, Charles "the Lame," was still a prisoner,
1 CONT and Pope Martin at first refused to recognise him as the late monarch's heir.
1 CONT In the event, Martin himself died a few months after King Charles. In a
1 CONT gesture of alliance with his Angevin cousins, Philip III of France, attacked
1 CONT Aragon, his army soon defeated as much by malaria as by arms. Philip died in
1 CONT October 1285. Peter of Aragon died a month later.
1 CONT
1 CONT \---------
