1 CONT ES II:15 PED OF A.H.AYERS
1 CONT ! (1) King of Naples
1 CONT ! (1) King of Naples
1 CONT King of Sicily, Naples, and Albania;
1 CONT Prince of Achaea; Count of Provence, Forcalquier, Anjou, and Maine
1 CONT and by purchase King of Jerusalem in 1277
1 CONT Charles I (of Two Sicilies) (1226-85), king of the Two Sicilies (1266-85).
1 CONT He was the posthumous son of Louis VIII, king of France, and the brother
1 CONT of King Louis IX. He was given the countships of Anjou and Maine by his
1 CONT brother, and through marriage in 1246 he became count of Provence. In 1248
1 CONT he accompanied Louis on the Sixth Crusade. In 1250 he was captured and
1 CONT briefly imprisoned, but later returned to Provence. By 1264 he controlled
1 CONT much of Piedmont. Charles agreed to aid the pope in his struggle against
1 CONT the Ghibellines in return for the kingdom of the Two Sicilies. In 1265
1 CONT Charles invaded Italy; the following year the reigning monarch Manfred
1 CONT (1232?-66) was killed in battle and Charles became king. In 1268, Conradin
1 CONT (1252-68), nephew of Manfred and last of the Hohenstaufen dynasty, led a
1 CONT revolt against Charles but was captured and executed. The king brutally
1 CONT suppressed the Ghibelline nobles, seizing their estates to pay his French
1 CONT soldiers. In 1270 Charles participated in the disastrous Seventh Crusade.
1 CONT In 1282 he learned of a revolt in Sicily against the French. Charles tried
1 CONT to reestablish his authority over the island, but was routed by Pedro III,
1 CONT king of Aragón (1239-85), who destroyed his fleet. Charles died soon
1 CONT after, leaving his kingdom in a chaotic condition.
1 CONT Charles I (21 March 1226 - 7 January 1285), commonly called Charles of Anjou,
1 CONT was the King of Sicily by conquest from 1266, though he had received it as a
1 CONT papal grant in 1262 and was expelled from the island in the aftermath of the
1 CONT Sicilian Vespers of 1282. Thereafter, he continued to claim the island, though
1 CONT his power was restricted to the peninsular possessions of the kingdom, with
1 CONT his capital at Naples (and for this he is usually titled King of Naples after
1 CONT 1282, as are his successors). Charles was the youngest son of Louis VIII of
1 CONT France and Blanche of Castile, and hence younger brother of Louis IX of France
1 CONT and Alfonso II of Toulouse. He conquered the Kingdom of Sicily from the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen and began to acquire lands in the eastern Mediterranean. However,
1 CONT the War of the Sicilian Vespers forced him to abandon his plans to reassemble
1 CONT the Latin Empire.
1 CONT
1 CONT By marriage to Beatrice, heiress of Raymond Berengar IV of Provence, he was
1 CONT Count of Provence and Forcalquier from 1246. In 1247, his brother Louis IX
1 CONT made him Count of Anjou and Maine, as appanages of the French crown. By
1 CONT conquest and self-proclamation, he became King of Albania in 1272 and by
1 CONT purchase King of Jerusalem in 1277. By the testament of William II of
1 CONT Villehardouin, he inherited the Principality of Achaea in 1278.
1 CONT
1 CONT Early life
1 CONT Charles was born in 1226, shortly before the death of his father, King Louis
1 CONT VIII. Like his immediate older brother, Philippe Dagobert (who died in 1232
1 CONT aged 10) he did not receive a county as appanage, as had his older brothers.
1 CONT Shortly after the death of Philippe Dagobert, his other brother, John Tristan,
1 CONT Count of Anjou and Maine, also died. Charles became the next in line to
1 CONT received the Counties, but was formally invested only in 1247. The affection
1 CONT of his mother Blanche seems largely to have been bestowed upon his brother
1 CONT Louis; and Louis tended to favour his other younger brothers, Robert of Artois
1 CONT and Alphonse of Toulouse. The self-reliance this engendered in Charles may
1 CONT account for the drive and ambition he showed in his later life.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Accession in Provence
1 CONT Upon his accession as Count of Provence and Forcalquier in 1246, Charles
1 CONT rapidly found himself in difficulties. His sisters-in-law felt cheated by
1 CONT their father's will, and his mother-in-law the Dowager Countess Beatrice of
1 CONT Savoy claimed the entire County of Forcalquier and the usufruct of Provence as
1 CONT her jointure. Furthermore, while Provence was technically a part of the
1 CONT Kingdom of Burgundy and hence of the Holy Roman Empire, in practice it was
1 CONT free of central authority. The recent counts had governed with a light hand,
1 CONT and the nobilities and cities (three of which, Marseille, Arles, and Avignon
1 CONT were Imperial cities technically separate from the county) had enjoyed great
1 CONT liberties. Charles, in contrast, was disposed towards a rigid administration;
1 CONT he ordered inquests in 1252 and again in 1278 to ascertain his rights[1]
1 CONT Charles broke the traditional powers of the great towns (Nice, Grasse,
1 CONT Marseille, Arles, Avignon) and aroused considerable hostility by his
1 CONT punctilious insistence on enjoying his full rights and fees. In 1247, while
1 CONT Charles had gone to France to receive the Counties of Anjou and Maine, the
1 CONT local nobility (represented by Barral of Baux and Boniface of Castellane)
1 CONT joined with Beatrice and the three Imperial cities to form a defensive league
1 CONT against him. Unfortunately for Charles, he had promised to join his brother on
1 CONT the Seventh Crusade. For the time being, Charles' only recourse was to
1 CONT compromise with Beatrice, allowing her to have Forcalquier and a third of the
1 CONT Provençal usufruct.
1 CONT
1 CONT Rich Provence provided the funds that supported his wider career. His rights
1 CONT as landlord were on the whole of recent establishment, but his rights as
1 CONT sovereign entitled him to revenues on the gabelles (mainly salt), from alberga
1 CONT (commutation of gîte) and cavalcata (commutation of the duties of military
1 CONT service) and quista ("aids") (Baratier 1969). From the Church, unlike his
1 CONT brothers in the north, he received virtually nothing. Charles' agents were
1 CONT efficient, the towns were prosperous, the peasants were buying up the duties
1 CONT of corvée and establishing self-governing consulats in the villages: Provence
1 CONT flourished.
1 CONT
1 CONT Seventh Crusade and return
1 CONT Charles sailed with the rest of the Crusaders from Aigues-Mortes in 1248, and
1 CONT fought gallantly at Damietta and during the fighting around Mansourah.
1 CONT However, his piety does not seem to have matched that of his brother (Jean de
1 CONT Joinville relates a tale of Louis catching him gambling on the voyage from
1 CONT Egypt to Acre) and he returned with his brother Alphonse in May 1250. During
1 CONT his absence, open rebellion had broken out in Provence. Charles moved with his
1 CONT characteristic energy to suppress it, and Arles, Avignon, and Barral of Baux
1 CONT had surrendered to him by June 1251. Marseille held out until July 1252, but
1 CONT then sued for peace. Charles imposed a lenient peace, but insisted on the
1 CONT recognition of his full panoply of comital rights, and acknowledgement of his
1 CONT suzerainity by Marseille.[citation needed]
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Wider ambitions
1 CONT In November 1252, the death of his mother Blanche of Castile caused him to go
1 CONT north to Paris and assume the joint regency of the kingdom with his brother
1 CONT Alphonse. While in Paris, he was approached by envoys from Pope Innocent IV.
1 CONT Innocent was then seeking to detach the Kingdom of Sicily from the Holy Roman
1 CONT Empire (in the person of Conrad IV of Germany), and offered it to Charles,
1 CONT after his brother-in-law Richard, Earl of Cornwall had declined it. Alphonse,
1 CONT however, was cool to the idea; and King Louis forbade it outright. Balked,
1 CONT Charles took up the cause of Margaret II of Flanders against her son, John I,
1 CONT Count of Hainaut in the War of the Succession of Flanders and Hainault. She
1 CONT granted him the County of Hainaut for his service. King Louis again
1 CONT disapproved, and on his return from Outremer in 1254 he returned Hainaut to
1 CONT John. The disappointed Charles returned to Provence, which had become restive
1 CONT again. The mediation of King Louis led to a settlement with Beatrice of Savoy,
1 CONT who returned Forcalquier and relinquished her claims for a cash payment and a
1 CONT pension. Marseille had attempted to involve Pisa and Alfonso X of Castile in
1 CONT the quarrel, but they proved unreliable as allies, and a coup by the
1 CONT supporters of Charles resulted in the surrender of the city's political
1 CONT powers. Charles spent the next several years quietly increasing his power over
1 CONT various lordships on the borders of Provence. A final rebellion occurred in
1 CONT 1262, when he was absent in France; Boniface of Castellane rebelled yet again,
1 CONT as did Marseille and Hugh of Baux. However, Barral of Baux now remained loyal
1 CONT to Charles, and Charles quickly returned to scatter the rebels. The mediation
1 CONT of James I of Aragon brought about a settlement; while Marseille was forced to
1 CONT dismantle its fortifications and surrender its arms, it otherwise went
1 CONT unpunished. Surprisingly, this lenity worked to good effect; hereafter, the
1 CONT Provençals proved staunch supporters of Charles, providing money and troops
1 CONT for his further conquests. Many of them were to be rewarded with high posts in
1 CONT his new dominions.
1 CONT
1 CONT With the usurpation of the Sicilian throne from Conradin by Manfred of Sicily
1 CONT in 1258, the relationship between the Papacy and the Hohenstaufen had changed
1 CONT again. Instead of the boy Conradin, safely sequestered across the Alps, the
1 CONT Papacy now faced an able military leader in Italy. Accordingly, when
1 CONT negotiations broke down with Manfred in 1262, Pope Urban IV again took up the
1 CONT scheme of disseising the Hohenstaufen from the Kingdom, and offered the crown
1 CONT to Charles again. Manfred's own usurpation from Conradin told upon King Louis'
1 CONT scruples; this time, he was persuaded to admit the offer, and Charles ratified
1 CONT a treaty with the Pope in July 1263. The terms were heavily in favor of the
1 CONT Pope; the Kingdom must never be re-united with the Empire, and the King was
1 CONT never to hold Imperial or Papal office, or interfere with ecclesiastical
1 CONT matters in the Kingdom. Nevertheless, Charles accepted eagerly. For money, he
1 CONT called for help from the then-omnipotent Sienese banker, Orlando
1 CONT Bonsignori.[citation needed]
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Conquest of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Sicilian coin of Charles's, bearing the inscription Karolus Dei gracia Sicilie
1 CONT rex around the king's image and that of Ducatus Apulie / Pricipat Capue around
1 CONT his coat-of-arms, referring to the Duchy of Apulia and the Principality of
1 CONT Capua, the two mainland provinces of the kingdom.
1 CONT From the Cabinet des Médailles.Having endorsed the treaty, Charles could now
1 CONT play for time. With Manfred's troops advancing on the Papal States, Charles
1 CONT obtained an extensive renegotiation of the treaty on more favorable lines. As
1 CONT instructions went out to the clergy to submit contributions for the war, Urban
1 CONT IV died in October 1264 at Perugia, fleeing Manfred. This raised the
1 CONT possibility of a reversal of Papal policy. To underscore his resolve, he broke
1 CONT sharply with his previous policy of lenity and ordered the execution of
1 CONT several Provençal rebels, who had been in his hands for a year. Fortunately
1 CONT for Charles, the new Pope Clement IV was the former adviser of his brother
1 CONT Alphonse and strongly supported the accession of Charles. Charles entered Rome
1 CONT on 23 May 1265 and was proclaimed King of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was popular in Rome, where he was elected Senator, and his diplomacy
1 CONT had already undermined Manfred's support in northern Italy. While Charles'
1 CONT campaigns were delayed for lack of money, Manfred, curiously, idled away his
1 CONT time hunting in Apulia, while his support in the north of Italy dwindled.
1 CONT Charles was able to bring his main army through the Alps, and he and Beatrice
1 CONT were crowned on 6 January 1266. As Charles' army began an energetic campaign,
1 CONT Manfred suddenly shed his lethargy and moved to meet him. Worried that further
1 CONT delays might endanger the loyalty of his supporters, he attacked Charles'
1 CONT army, then in disarray from the crossing of the hills into Benevento, on 26
1 CONT February 1266. In the Battle of Benevento that followed, Manfred's army was
1 CONT defeated in detail and he was killed in the melee. Upon his death, resistance
1 CONT throughout the Kingdom collapsed, and Charles was master of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT While Charles' administration in his new Kingdom was generally fair and
1 CONT honest, it was also stringent. As in Provence, he insisted on maximizing the
1 CONT revenues and privileges he could obtain from his new subjects. Discontent was
1 CONT high; but for now, Charles could focus on extending his power in northern
1 CONT Italy (which alarmed the Pope, who feared a powerful king of all Italy as much
1 CONT as he did an Emperor). But the Pope was willing to allow this; for in
1 CONT September 1267 Conradin marched south to reclaim the rights of the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen, and one of his agents instigated a revolt in Sicily. He entered
1 CONT Rome on 24 July 1268, where his arrival was wildly celebrated. At the Battle
1 CONT of Tagliacozzo, on 23 August 1268, it appeared he might win the day; but a
1 CONT sudden charge of Charles' reserve discomfited his army and he was forced to
1 CONT flee to Rome. Told it was no longer safe, he attempted to escape to Genoa, but
1 CONT was arrested and imprisoned in the Castel dell'Ovo in Naples. In a trial
1 CONT carefully managed by Charles, Conradin was condemned for treason, and he was
1 CONT beheaded on 29 October 1268. By the end of 1270, he had captured Lucera[2] and
1 CONT put down the revolt in Sicily, executing many of the captured. With the whole
1 CONT kingdom cowed beneath his strict, if fair, rule, he was ready to consider
1 CONT greater conquests.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Ambitions in the Latin Empire
1 CONT After the defeat of Manfred at Benevento, Charles immediately began to plan
1 CONT his expansion into the Mediterranean. Historically, the Kingdom of Sicily had
1 CONT at times controlled parts of the eastern Adriatic seaboard, and Manfred had
1 CONT been possessed of the island of Corfu and the towns of Butrinto, Avlona and
1 CONT Suboto, which had formed the dowry of his wife Helena. Charles seized these at
1 CONT the end of 1266. From thence, he passed on to intrigue with the remaining
1 CONT nobility of the Latin Empire. In May 1267, he concluded the Treaty of Viterbo
1 CONT with the exiled Baldwin II of Constantinople and William II Villehardouin
1 CONT (through his chancellor Leonardo of Veruli). Taking advantage of the
1 CONT precarious situation of the remains of the Empire in the face of rising Greek
1 CONT power, he obtained confirmation of his possession of Corfu, the suzerain
1 CONT rights over Achaea, and sovereignty over most of the Aegean islands.
1 CONT Furthermore, the heirs of both the Latin princes were to marry children of
1 CONT Charles, and Charles was to have the reversion of the Empire and Principality
1 CONT should the couples have no heirs. With few options to check the Byzantine
1 CONT tide, he was well placed to dictate terms.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1277, he claims the Kingdom of JerusalemCharles' wife Beatrice died on 23
1 CONT September 1267, and he immediately sought a new marriage to Margaret, daughter
1 CONT of Bela IV of Hungary. However, Margaret wished to be a nun (and was later
1 CONT canonized); Charles instead married (on 18 November 1268), Margaret, Countess
1 CONT of Tonnerre (1250 - 4 September 1308, Tonnerre), the daughter of Eudes of
1 CONT Burgundy. However, he was able to make a marital alliance with the Hungarians:
1 CONT his son Charles, Prince of Salerno married Maria, daughter of crown prince
1 CONT Stephen, while Charles' daughter Elizabeth married Stephen's son Ladislas.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Eighth Crusade
1 CONT Having thus made secure his position in the East, he began to prepare a
1 CONT crusade to recover the Latin Empire. Michael VIII Palaeologus was greatly
1 CONT alarmed at the prospect: he wrote to King Louis, suggesting that he was open
1 CONT to a voluntary union of the Roman and Latin churches, and pointing out the
1 CONT interference a descent on Constantinople would pose to Louis' own crusading
1 CONT plans. Louis took a dim view of his sincerity; but he was eager to take up the
1 CONT cross again, and he notified Charles of his intentions. Charles continued with
1 CONT his preparations against Constantinople, hoping the crusade might be
1 CONT postponed, but he also prepared to turn his brother's crusade to his own
1 CONT advantage. The Caliph of Tunis, Muhammad I al-Mustansir had been a vassal of
1 CONT Sicily, but had shaken off his allegiance with the fall of Manfred.[citation
1 CONT needed] However, there were rumors he might be sympathetic to Christianity.
1 CONT Accordingly, Charles suggested to his brother that the arrival of a crusade in
1 CONT his support might bring about Mustansir's conversion. Thus it was that Louis
1 CONT directed the Eighth Crusade against Tunis. Charles did not arrive until late
1 CONT in the day on 25 August 1270, only to find that his brother had died of
1 CONT dysentery that morning. Charles took command, and after a few skirmishes,
1 CONT Mustansir concluded a peace treaty and agreed to pay tribute to Charles.
1 CONT Illness continued to plague the army, however, and a storm devastated the
1 CONT fleet of 18 men-of-war and innumerable smaller vessels as it returned to
1 CONT Sicily. Charles was forced to postpone his designs against Constantinople
1 CONT again.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Conquest of Albania and Genoese War
1 CONT In February 1271, Charles began to expand his Adriatic possessions by
1 CONT capturing Durazzo, and he soon controlled much of the Albanian interior. In
1 CONT February 1272, he proclaimed himself King of Albania and appointed Gazzo
1 CONT Chinardo as his Vicar-General. He hoped to take up his expedition against
1 CONT Constantinople again, but was delayed by the rise of Pope Gregory X,
1 CONT consecrated on 27 March 1272. Gregory had high hopes of reconciling Europe,
1 CONT unifying the Greek and Latin churches, and launching a new crusade: to that
1 CONT end, he announced the Council of Lyon, to be held in 1274, and worked to
1 CONT arrange the election of an Emperor.
1 CONT
1 CONT In November 1272, the strained relations between Charles and Ghibelline-ruled
1 CONT Genoa finally broke into war. Ghibelline revolts broke out across the north of
1 CONT Italy, and increasingly occupied the attention of Charles, even as Michael
1 CONT Palaeologus was negotiating a union of churches with the Pope. At the same
1 CONT time, he had made contact with Genoa and was sending money to encourage the
1 CONT revolts in the north. At the apparently successful conclusion of the Council
1 CONT of Lyon, a Union of Churches was declared, and Charles and Philip of Courtenay
1 CONT were compelled to extend a truce with Michael. This was a blessing in disguise
1 CONT for Charles, for the Ghibellines now controlled most of the north, and he was
1 CONT forced to retreat from Piedmont in late 1275. In truth, Pope Gregory was not
1 CONT entirely displeased; he regarded north Italy as best dealt with by its new
1 CONT Emperor, Rudolph of Habsburg, and preferred that Charles be confined to the
1 CONT south. If he wished to make war, let him look to Outremer; and to this end,
1 CONT Gregory endorsed the sale to Charles of the claims of Maria of Antioch on the
1 CONT Kingdom of Jerusalem, which had been rejected by the Haute Cour there. On 18
1 CONT March 1277, he bought her claim and assumed the title of King of Jerusalem,
1 CONT sending Roger of San Severino as his bailli to Acre. There Roger ousted Balian
1 CONT of Ibelin, the bailli of Hugh III and compelled the nobles to swear fealty. In
1 CONT the meantime, Gregory had been succeeded by Pope Innocent V, who arranged a
1 CONT peace between Charles and the Genoese.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Breakdown of the Union
1 CONT Meanwhile, in Constantinople, the Union of the Churches was proving difficult
1 CONT to arrange, and the Emperor Michael had great difficulty in imposing it on his
1 CONT people. Nevertheless, he persuaded Innocent of his sincerity in working
1 CONT towards it, and Charles was again forbidden to attack Constantinople. Knowing
1 CONT this, Michael began a campaign in Albania in late 1274, where he captured
1 CONT Berat and Butrinto. He also enjoyed some success in his campaigns in Euboea
1 CONT and the Peloponnese.
1 CONT
1 CONT Affairs dragged on for several years, until the accession of Pope Martin IV on
1 CONT 23 March 1280. Pope Martin was a Frenchman, and lacked the evenhandedness of
1 CONT some of his recent precursors. He brought the full power of the Papacy into
1 CONT line behind Charles' plans. The Union, which had proved impossible to impose
1 CONT upon Constantinople, was called off, and Charles given authorization for the
1 CONT restoration of the Latin Empire.
1 CONT
1 CONT He opened his campaign in Albania, where his general Hugh of Sully with 8,000
1 CONT men (including 2,000 cavalry) captured Butrinto from the Despotate of Epirus
1 CONT in 1280 and besieging Berat. A Byzantine army of relief under Michael
1 CONT Tarchaniotes arrived in March, 1281: Hugh of Sully was ambushed and captured,
1 CONT and his army put to flight. The Byzantines took possession of the interior of
1 CONT Albania. Nor was Charles particularly successful in Achaea, where he had
1 CONT become (by the Treaty of Viterbo) Prince of Achaea on the death of William II
1 CONT Villehardouin in 1278. His bailli Galeran of Ivry was defeated at Skorta in
1 CONT his one attempt to engage the Byzantines, and was recalled in 1280 and
1 CONT replaced by Philip of Lagonesse. Nonetheless, Charles was to launch the body
1 CONT of his crusade (400 ships carrying 27,000 mounted knights) against
1 CONT Constantinople in the spring of 1282.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Sicilian Vespers
1 CONT But Michael had not been working upon the military front alone. Many
1 CONT Ghibelline officials had fled the Kingdom of Sicily to the court of Peter III
1 CONT of Aragon, who had married Constance, the daughter and heir of Manfred.
1 CONT Manfred's former chancellor, John of Procida, had arranged contact between
1 CONT Michael, Peter and the refugees at his court, and conspirators on the island
1 CONT of Sicily itself. Peter began to assemble a fleet at Barcelona, ostensibly for
1 CONT another Crusade to Tunis. In fact, the master-plan of John of Procida was to
1 CONT place Peter on the throne of Sicily, his Hohenstaufen inheritance. The result
1 CONT was the uprising known as the Sicilian Vespers, which was initiated in Palermo
1 CONT on 29 March 1282. It rapidly grew into a general massacre of the French in
1 CONT Sicily. A few officials notable for their good conduct were spared; and the
1 CONT city of Messina still held for Charles. But through the diplomatic errors of
1 CONT Charles' Vicar, Herbert of Orleans, Messina, too, revolted on 28 April 1282.
1 CONT Herbert retreated to the castle of Mategriffon, but was forced to abandon the
1 CONT Crusading fleet, which was burnt.
1 CONT
1 CONT The news surprised Peter of Aragon, who had expected to intervene only after
1 CONT Charles had left for Constantinople. But the conspirators, aided by the
1 CONT Emperor Michael (who wished to see Charles balked in his expedition), had set
1 CONT the revolt in motion early. Peter did not immediately intervene; he sailed
1 CONT with the fleet to Tunis, where he discovered that the would-be convert on
1 CONT whose behalf the crusade had ostensibly been undertaken had been caught and
1 CONT executed. While he bided his time, the Sicilians made an appeal to Pope Martin
1 CONT to take the Communes of their cities under his protection. But Martin was far
1 CONT too deeply committed to Charles and French interests to heed them; instead, he
1 CONT excommunicated the rebels, the Emperor Michael, and the Ghibellines in north
1 CONT Italy. Charles gathered his forces in Calabria and made a landing near Messina
1 CONT and began a siege. Several attempts to assault the city were unsuccessful.
1 CONT Rejected by the Pope, the Sicilians now appealed to King Peter and Queen
1 CONT Constance; he duly accepted, and landed at Trapani on 30 August 1282. He was
1 CONT proclaimed King in Palermo on 4 September; as the Archibishopric of Palermo
1 CONT was vacant, he could not immediately be crowned. In the face of the Aragonese
1 CONT landing, Charles was compelled to withdraw across the Straits of Messina into
1 CONT Calabria in September; but the Aragonese moved swiftly enough to destroy part
1 CONT of his army and most of his baggage. The Angevin house was forever ousted from
1 CONT Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT War with Aragon
1 CONT Despite his retreat into Calabria, Charles remained in a strong position. His
1 CONT nephew, Philip III of France, was devoted to him; and Pope Martin regarded the
1 CONT rebellion as an affront both to French interests and his own rights as
1 CONT suzerain of the Kingdom. Both sides temporized; the expense of a long war
1 CONT might be disastrous for both, and Peter and Charles arranged for a judicial
1 CONT duel, with a hundred knights apiece, on 1 June 1283 at Bordeaux. Skirmishes
1 CONT and raids continued to occur: in January 1283, Aragonese guerillas attacked
1 CONT Catona and killed Count Peter I of Alençon in his hostel. In February, the
1 CONT Aragonese crossed into Calabria to face off with Charles of Salerno. However,
1 CONT tensions between the Aragonese and the Sicilians had begun to rise. Both men
1 CONT now hoped to turn the war to their advantage, and the judicial duel turned
1 CONT into a farce, the two kings arriving at different times, declaring a victory
1 CONT over their absent opponent, and departing. Now the war was to escalate: Pope
1 CONT Martin had excommunicated Peter and proclaimed the war against the Sicilians a
1 CONT Crusade in January, and in March, declared Peter to be deprived of his
1 CONT dominions. On 2 February 1284, Aragon and Valencia were officially conferred
1 CONT upon Charles of Valois. The war continued in Italy: while little progress had
1 CONT been made in Calabria, a detachment of the Aragonese fleet was blockading
1 CONT Malta. Charles of Salerno sent a newly raised Provençal fleet to the relief
1 CONT of Malta; but it was caught by the main Aragonese fleet under Roger of Lauria
1 CONT and destroyed in the Battle of Malta. The Aragonese were now, however, running
1 CONT quite short of money, and Peter was threatened by the prospect of a French
1 CONT attack on Aragon. King Charles planned to raise new troops and a fleet in
1 CONT Provence, and instructed Charles of Salerno to maintain a strict defensive
1 CONT posture until his return from France. However, Roger of Lauria continued to
1 CONT command the sea and launch harassing raids up and down the coast of Calabria,
1 CONT and in May 1284 he successfully blockaded Naples, basing a small squadron on
1 CONT the island of Nisida to do so. The Neapolitans were infuriated by the
1 CONT blockade; and in June, Charles of Salerno armed the newly launched fleet at
1 CONT Naples and embarked on 5 June to destroy the blockading squadron. Evidently
1 CONT believing the main Aragonese fleet was raiding down the coast, he hoped to
1 CONT destroy the blockading squadron and return to Naples before it returned.
1 CONT However, Roger of Lauria had learned of his plans, and Charles found himself
1 CONT engulfed by superior numbers. After a short, sharp, fight, most of his fleet
1 CONT was captured, and he himself was taken prisoner.
1 CONT
1 CONT News of the reverse caused anti-French riots in Naples, and Roger of Lauria
1 CONT was quick to take advantage of Charles' captivity to obtain the release of
1 CONT Beatrice, daughter of Manfred of Sicily, then held in Naples. King Charles
1 CONT arrived in Gaeta on 6 June and learned of the disaster. He was furious at his
1 CONT son and his disobedience; by the time he reached Naples, the riots had been
1 CONT quelled. He advanced on Calabria and attempted a landing in Sicily; but his
1 CONT main army was blocked at Reggio, and he retreated from Calabria entirely on 3
1 CONT August. He continued to make preparations for a campaign against Sicily in the
1 CONT new year; but his health failed. On 7 January 1285, he died in Foggia.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Death and legacy
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles I of Naples (or Anjou), Basilique Saint-Denis. Note he holds his heart
1 CONT in his left hand.On his death, Charles left all of his domains to his son
1 CONT Charles, then a prisoner in Catalonia. For the time being, they were held by a
1 CONT joint regency between a papal legate and Robert II of Artois. Charles had
1 CONT spent his life striving to assemble a Mediterranean empire out of whatever
1 CONT land he could get through law or force of arms. He did so, it seems, with a
1 CONT clear conscience; he regarded himself as God's instrument to uphold the Papacy
1 CONT and punish the Hohenstaufen. He ruled justly, but with the rigidity and
1 CONT severity that might be expected in one of his convictions. Ultimately, his
1 CONT unbending austerity could not inspire the devotion needed to hold his
1 CONT conquests together.
1 CONT
1 CONT Still, he was to leave a substantial legacy to his heirs. Henry II of Cyprus
1 CONT reclaimed the Kingdom of Jerusalem after his death, for the few short years
1 CONT left to it; but his possessions otherwise remained within the Angevin dynasty
1 CONT which he founded, or their descendants. Both the Angevins and their Aragonese
1 CONT rivals were to claim the title of "King of Sicily"; but the Angevins, confined
1 CONT to the mainland, would be known to history as "Kings of Naples". But the style
1 CONT of "King of Sicily" persisted; and when the two realms were reunited, it was
1 CONT under the style of "King of the Two Sicilies".
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles of Anjou contributed to the early medieval revival of learning, often
1 CONT referred to as the "Latin" Renaissance, through his employment of several
1 CONT Jewish scholars at the University of Salerno and Naples, who were expert
1 CONT translators. The most famous of these, Moses of Palermo, he had tutored in
1 CONT Latin, to enable direct translations of ancient classical and Arab texts.
1 CONT These Jewish scholars translated dozens of philosophical and medical treatises
1 CONT into Latin, bringing the heritage of classical antiquity and the great
1 CONT contemporary Muslim culture to pre-Renaissance Europe. [3]
1 CONT
1 CONT However, his wars resulted in an even more serious consequence than the
1 CONT partition of the Kingdom of Sicily. Pope Martin IV had hopelessly compromised
1 CONT the Papacy in his cause; and the botched secular "Crusades" against Sicily and
1 CONT (after Charles' death) Aragon greatly tarnished its spiritual power. The
1 CONT collapse of its moral authority and the rise of nationalism rang the death
1 CONT knell for Crusading, and would ultimately lead to the Avignon Papacy and the
1 CONT Western Schism. Charles was an able soldier and a good administrator; but his
1 CONT failure to understand the qualities of his diverse subjects, and his grasping,
1 CONT if pious, ambition, ultimately led him to failure.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the Divine Comedy Dante sees Charles outside the gates of Purgatory
1 CONT "singing in accord" with his former rival Peter.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and children
1 CONT Charles was wedded to Beatrice of Provence on 31 January 1246, in Aix-en-
1 CONT Provence. Beatrice was the youngest daughter of Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of
1 CONT Provence and Forcalquier, who had died on 19 August 1245 by his wife Beatrice
1 CONT of Savoy. As his elder three daughters had all married kings and received
1 CONT substantial dowries, Raymond settled his entire inheritance upon Beatrice,
1 CONT making Charles Count of Provence and Forcalquier. They had the following
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis (1248, Nicosia)
1 CONT Blanche (1250 - July 1269), married 1265 Count Robert III of Flanders
1 CONT Beatrice of Sicily (1252-1275), married 15 October 1273 at Foggia to Philip of
1 CONT Courtenay, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT Charles II of Naples (1254 - 1309)
1 CONT Philip of Sicily (1256 - 1 January 1277), titular King of Thessalonica from
1 CONT 1274, married 28 May 1271 to Isabella of Villehardouin
1 CONT Robert (1258-1265)
1 CONT Elizabeth of Sicily (1261 - c. 1300), married bef. September 1272 to Ladislas
1 CONT IV of Hungary
1 CONT After the death of Beatrice, he married Margaret of Burgundy in 1268. Their
1 CONT only daughter, Margaret, died in infancy.
1 CONT Foi o fundador da Casa capetiana de Anjou, conhecida como angevinos, que
1 CONT subiram aos tronos italianos de Nápoles, Sicília e Sardenha, e ao trono da
1 CONT Hungria.
1 CONT "OF ANJOU"; GIVEN THE COUNTSHIP OF ANJOU BY BROTHER LOUIS; BECAME (1266)
1 CONT CHARLES I OF NAPLES; KING OF SICILY; LEADER OF THE 7TH CRSUADE (1248-1254)
1 CONT WITH
1 CONT BROTHER LOUIS IX; LEADER OF THE 8TH CRUSADE (1270-1291) WITH BROTHER LOUIS IX
1 CONT AND EDWARD I, KING OF ENGLAND
1 CONT OF ANJOU
1 CONT "OF ANJOU"; KING OF NAPLES
1 CONT ! (1) King of Naples
1 CONT Charles I of Anjou (1226-85), youngest son of Louis VIII of France, and
1 CONT brother of Louis IX, the Saint. His brother gave him Anjou and Maine, and in
1 CONT 1246 he became by marriage Duke of Provence. In 1265 Pope Clement IV offered
1 CONT him the crown of Naples and Sicily; his government provoked great discontent
1 CONT in both Naples and Sicily, and in 1268 he had to cope with a revolt under
1 CONT Conradin. After the death of Louis IX he became the most important sovereign
1 CONT in Western Christendom, being all-powerful in France, and exercising great
1 CONT influence over the rest of Italy. A league was formed against Charles by the
1 CONT pope. Peter of Aragon came to the help of the Sicilians. Charles�s fleet was
1 CONT defeated by the Spanish fleet near Reggio in 1284, and the French lost Sicily
1 CONT forever. [World Wide Illustrated Encyclopedia, 1935]
1 CONT King of Jerusalem, Charles of Anjou
