1 CONT (Research):Charles I Charles I (Charles of Anjou), 1227-85, king of Naples and
1 CONT Sicily (1266-85), count of Anjou and Provence, youngest brother of King Louis
1 CONT IX of France. He took part in Louis's crusades to Egypt (1248) and Tunisia
1 CONT (1270). After obtaining Provence by marriage (1246), he extended his influence
1 CONT into Piedmont. He became senator of Rome (1263, 1265-78) and undertook to
1 CONT champion the papal cause against Manfred in the kingdom of Naples and Sicily.
1 CONT In reward, he was crowned king (1266) by Pope Clement IV. Charles defeated
1 CONT (1266) Manfred at Benevento and defeated and executed Conradin in 1268. As
1 CONT leader of the Guelphs, or papal faction, he gained political hegemony in Italy
1 CONT and won suzerainty over several cities in Tuscany, Piedmont, and Lombardy, but
1 CONT his overbearing policies led to a cooling of his relations with the papacy.
1 CONT Planning to establish his own empire, he allied himself with the deposed
1 CONT Byzantine emperor, Baldwin II, against Michael VIII and fought for years in
1 CONT the Balkans. Corfu, Epirus, and Albania were taken, but the crushing taxes
1 CONT necessitated by his wars and his appointment of oppressive French officials to
1 CONT exact them led to the Sicilian Vespers (1282). The ensuing war against the
1 CONT Sicilian rebels and Peter III of Aragón, chosen by the rebels as king of
1 CONT Sicily, continued under Charles's son and successor, Charles II. Charles I was
1 CONT the founder of the first Angevin dynasty in Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT Encyclopedia Charles I Charles I (Charles of Anjou), 1227-85, king of Naples
1 CONT and Sicily (1266-85), count of Anjou and Provence, youngest brother of King
1 CONT Louis IX of France. He took part in Louis's crusades to Egypt (1248) and
1 CONT Tunisia (1270). After obtaining Provence by marriage (1246), he extended his
1 CONT influence into Piedmont. He became senator of Rome (1263, 1265-78) and
1 CONT undertook to champion the papal cause against Manfred in the kingdom of Naples
1 CONT and Sicily. In reward, he was crowned king (1266) by Pope Clement IV. Charles
1 CONT defeated (1266) Manfred at Benevento and defeated and executed Conradin in
1 CONT 1268. As leader of the Guelphs, or papal faction, he gained political hegemony
1 CONT in Italy and won suzerainty over several cities in Tuscany, Piedmont, and
1 CONT Lombardy, but his overbearing policies led to a cooling of his relations with
1 CONT the papacy. Planning to establish his own empire, he allied himself with the
1 CONT deposed Byzantine emperor, Baldwin II, against Michael VIII and fought for
1 CONT years in the Balkans. Corfu, Epirus, and Albania were taken, but the crushing
1 CONT taxes necessitated by his wars and his appointment of oppressive French
1 CONT officials to exact them led to the Sicilian Vespers (1282). The ensuing war
1 CONT against the Sicilian rebels and Peter III of Aragón, chosen by the rebels as
1 CONT king of Sicily, continued under Charles's son and successor, Charles II.
1 CONT Charles I was the founder of the first Angevin dynasty in Naples. Source:
