1 CONT Charles of Anjou (1227–1285), also Charles I of Sicily. He was King of Sicily
1 CONT 1262–1282 (and under that title, King of Naples 1282–1285), King of Albania
1 CONT 1272–1285, King of Jerusalem 1277–1285, Prince of Achaea 1278–1285, Count of
1 CONT Provence and Forcalquier 1246–1285, and Count of Anjou and Maine 1247–1285. He
1 CONT was the posthumous son of Louis VIII of France and Blanche of Castile, and
1 CONT hence brother to Louis IX of France and Alphonse of Toulouse. He conquered the
1 CONT Kingdom of Sicily from the Hohenstaufen in 1266 and began to acquire lands in
1 CONT the eastern Mediterranean. However, the Sicilian Vespers freed Sicily from his
1 CONT control, and the resulting war forced him to abandon his plans to reassemble
1 CONT the Latin Empire.
1 CONT
