1 CONT On February 26, 1266, Charles defeated Manfred and his forces on the plain of
1 CONT Grandella near Benevento. This battle ended Hohenstaufen rule in Italy and
1 CONT began the Angevin dominance that lasted through most of the rest of the 13th
1 CONT century. Charles succeeded in Naples and asserted his leadership in Rome and
1 CONT in northern Italy. The papacy ruled the center, the Guelfs the north and the
1 CONT Angevins were in control of Sicily and Naples. Everything held together by
1 CONT the strong personality & ambitious dreams of Charles of Anjou. See Peter III.
1 CONT On February 26, 1266, Charles defeated Manfred and his forces on the plain of
1 CONT Grandella near Benevento. This battle ended Hohenstaufen rule in Italy and
1 CONT began the Angevin dominance that lasted through most of the rest of the 13th
1 CONT century. Charles succeeded in Naples and asserted his leadership in Rome and
1 CONT in northern Italy. The papacy ruled the center, the Guelfs the north and the
1 CONT Angevins were in control of Sicily and Naples. Everything held together by
1 CONT the strong personality & ambitious dreams of Charles of Anjou. See Peter III.
1 CONT On February 26, 1266, Charles defeated Manfred and his forces on the plain of
1 CONT Grandella near Benevento. This battle ended Hohenstaufen rule in Italy and
1 CONT began the Angevin dominance that lasted through most of the rest of the 13th
1 CONT century. Charles succeeded in Naples and asserted his leadership in Rome and
1 CONT in northern Italy. The papacy ruled the center, the Guelfs the north and the
1 CONT Angevins were in control of Sicily and Naples. Everything held together by
1 CONT the strong personality & ambitious dreams of Charles of Anjou. See Peter III.
1 CONT Charles I (March 1227 - January 7, 1285) was the posthumous son of Kin g Louis
1 CONT VIII of France, created Count of Anjou by his elder brother Ki ng Louis IX in
1 CONT 1246, thus founding the second Angevin dynasty. In 126 6 Charles was invested
1 CONT by Pope Clement IV with the kingship of Naplesa nd Sicily, in return for
1 CONT expelling Manfred, son of Holy Roman Emperor Frederick II. In 1261, Sicily
1 CONT alone had been entrusted to his rule.Man fred's defeat and death in battle
1 CONT were followed (1268) by the defeat a nd execution of his nephew Conradin, but
1 CONT in 1282 Sicily rose against F rench officialdom and taxes intended to finance
1 CONT Charles's struggleto r estore the Latin Empire at Constantinople. The island
1 CONT was taken by Ki ng Peter III of Arag??a>, who became also Peter I of Sicily,
1 CONT but Charl es remained in possession of mainland Naples until his death,
1 CONT acquirin g in addition the now empty title of King of Jerusalem in 1277. Charl
1 CONT es's dynasty went on to rule Hungary and Poland for a time in thefollo wing
1 CONT century, but lost Naples in 1442. The main line in Anjou ended i n 1481.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles I, Count of Anjou by appanage (originally intended for his old er
1 CONT brother Jean who d. bet 1227-1232), King of Sicily, 1266-1285, bor n in 1226,
1 CONT married on January 31, 1246, (1) Beatrice of Provence, 4th youngest daughter
1 CONT of Raymond Berenger V. of Provence, who died in 1267 . She was named heiress
1 CONT at her father's death, sister of Margaret of F rance. At Pentacost, 1246,
1 CONT Charles's knighthood was celebrated at the castle of Melun. After this
1 CONT ceremony he was styled Charles of Anjou, s ince the two holdings of Maine and
1 CONT Anjou, left to him by his father's will, were officially handed over to him at
1 CONT that time. In 1251, soon after his brother Alphonse of France's death, Charles
1 CONT laid claim to Al phonse's apanage of Poitiers and Auvengne, but was also
1 CONT forced with a decision by the French parliament that the said lands found
1 CONT without a n heir should revert to the crown. Later Charles married in 1268 (2)
1 CONT Margaret of Burgundy, who died in 1308.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles of Anjou (March 1226/7 - 1285), also Charles I of Sicily. He w as King
1 CONT of Sicily 1262-1282 (and under that title, King of Naples 1282 -1285), King of
1 CONT Albania 1272-1285, King of Jerusalem 1277-1285, Princ e of Achaea 1278-1285,
1 CONT Count of Provence and Forcalquier 1246-1285, an d Count of Anjou and Maine
1 CONT 1247-1285. He was the posthumous son of Lou is VIII of France and Blanche of
1 CONT Castile, and hence brother to Louis I X of France and Alphonse of Toulouse. He
1 CONT conquered the Kingdom of Sici ly from the Hohenstaufen in 1266 and began to
1 CONT acquire lands in the eas tern Mediterranean. However, the Sicilian Vespers
1 CONT freed Sicily from hi s control, and the resulting war forced him to abandon
1 CONT his plans to re assemble theLatin Empire. Charles was born in 1227, shortly
1 CONT after th e death of his father, King Louis VIII. In his will, his father had
1 CONT le ft to him (should he be male), the Counties of Anjou and Maine, with w hich
1 CONT he was invested in 1247. The affection of his mother Blanche seem s largely
1 CONT tohave been bestowed upon his brother Louis; and Louis tende d to favor his
1 CONT elder brothers Robert of Artois and Alphonse. The self- reliance this
1 CONT engendered in Charles may account for the drive and ambi tion he showed in his
1 CONT later life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was wedded to Beatrice of Provence on January 31, 1246, in Aix -en-
1 CONT Provence. Beatrice was the youngest daughter of Ramon Berenguer IV , Count of
1 CONT Provence and Forcalquier, who had died on August 19, 1245 b y his wife
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy. As his elder three daughters had all mar ried kings and
1 CONT received substantial dowries, Raymond settled his entir e inheritance upon
1 CONT Beatrice, making Charles Count of Provence and Forc alquier. They had the
1 CONT following children: Louis (1248, Nicosia); Blanc he (1250 - July 1269),
1 CONT married 1265 Count Robert III of Flanders; Beat rice (1252 - 1275), married
1 CONT October 15, 1273 at Foggia to Philip of Co urtenay, titular Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople; Charles II of Naples (125 4 - 1309); Philip of Sicily (1256 -
1 CONT January 1, 1277), titular King ofT hessalonica from 1274, married May 28, 1271
1 CONT to Isabella of Villehardou in; Robert (1258 - 1265);Elizabeth or Maria (1261 -
1 CONT c. 1300), married bef. September 1272 to Ladislas IV of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his accession as Count of Provence and Forcalquier in 1246, Charl es
1 CONT rapidly found himself in difficulties. His sisters-in-law felt chea ted by
1 CONT their father's will, and the Dowager Countess Beatrice of Savo y claimed the
1 CONT entire County of Forcalquier and the usufruct of Provenc e as her jointure.
1 CONT Furthermore, while Provence was technically a parto f the Kingdom of Burgundy
1 CONT and hence of the Holy Roman Empire, in pract ice it was free of central
1 CONT authority. The recent counts had governedwi th a light hand, and the
1 CONT nobilities and cities (three of which, Marsei lle, Arles, and Avignon were
1 CONT Imperial cities technically separate fro m the county) had enjoyed great
1 CONT liberties. Charles, in constrast, was disposed towards a rigid administration,
1 CONT and aroused considerable host ility by his punctilious insistence on enjoying
1 CONT his full rights andfee s. In 1247, while Charles had gone to France to receive
1 CONT the Counties o f Anjou and Maine, the local nobility (represented by Barral of
1 CONT Baux a nd Boniface of Castellane) joined with Beatrice and the three Imperia l
1 CONT cities to form a defensive league against him. Unfortunately for Cha rles, he
1 CONT had promised to join his brother on the Seventh Crusade. For the time being,
1 CONT Charles' only recourse was to compromise with Beatrice , allowing her to have
1 CONT Forcalquier and a third of the Provençal usufru ct.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles sailed with the rest of the Crusaders from Aigues-Mortes in 12 48, and
1 CONT fought gallantly at Damietta and during the fighting around Ma nsurah. Charles
1 CONT was captured with his brother during the fighting an d was a prisoner with
1 CONT him. However, his piety does not seem to have ma tched that of his brother
1 CONT (Jean de Joinville relates a tale of Louis c atching him gambling on the
1 CONT voyage from Egypt to Acre) and he returne d with his brother Alphonse in May
1 CONT 1250. During his absence, open rebe llion had broken out in Provence. Charles
1 CONT moved with his characteristi c energy to suppress it, and Arles, Avignon, and
1 CONT Barral of Baux had su rrendered to him by June 1251. Marseille held out until
1 CONT July 1252, bu t then sued for peace. Charles imposed a lenient peace, but
1 CONT insisted o n the recognition of his full panoply of comital rights, and
1 CONT acknowled gement of his suzerainity by Marseille.
1 CONT
1 CONT In November 1252, the death of his mother Blanche of Castile caused hi m to go
1 CONT north to Paris and assume the joint regency of the kingdom wit h his brother
1 CONT Alphonse. While in Paris, he was approached by envoys fr om Pope Innocent IV.
1 CONT Innocent was then seeking to detach the Kingdom o f Sicily from the Holy Roman
1 CONT Empire (in the person of Conrad IV of Ger many), and offered it to Charles,
1 CONT after his brother-in-law Richard, Ea rl of Cornwall had declined it. Alphonse,
1 CONT however, was cool to the ide a; and King Louis forbade it outright. Balked,
1 CONT Charles took up the cau se of Margaret II of Flanders against her son, John I,
1 CONT Count of Hainau t in the War of the Succession of Flanders and Hainault. She
1 CONT granted h im the County of Hainaut for his service. King Louis again
1 CONT disapproved , and on his return from Outremer in 1254 he returned Hainaut to
1 CONT John . The disappointed Charles returned to Provence, which had become rest
1 CONT ive again. The mediation of King Louis led to a settlement with Beatri ce of
1 CONT Savoy, who returned Forcalquier and relinquished her claims for a cash payment
1 CONT and a pension. Marseille had attempted to involve Pisaa nd Alfonso X of
1 CONT Castile in the quarrel, but they proved unreliable as allies, and a coup by
1 CONT the supporters of Charles resulted in the surren der of the city's political
1 CONT powers. Charles spent the next several yea rs quietly increasing his power
1 CONT over various lordships on the borders of Provence. A final rebellion occurred
1 CONT in 1262, when he was absentin France; Boniface of Castellaine rebelled yet
1 CONT again, as did Marseille a nd Hugh of Baux. However, Barral of Baux now
1 CONT remained loyal to Charles , and Charles quickly returned to scatter the
1 CONT rebels. The mediation o f James I of Aragon brought about a settlement; while
1 CONT Marseille was fo rced to dismantle its fortifications and surrender its arms,
1 CONT it otherw ise went unpunished. Surprisingly, this lenity worked to good
1 CONT effect; hereafter, the Provençals proved staunch supporters of Charles, provid
1 CONT ing money and troops for his further conquests. Many of them wereto b e
1 CONT rewarded with high posts in his new dominions.
1 CONT
1 CONT With the usurpation of the Sicilian throne from Conradin by Manfred o f Sicily
1 CONT in 1258, the relationship between the Papacy and the Hohensta ufen had changed
1 CONT again. Instead of the boy Conradin, safely sequestere d across the Alps, the
1 CONT Papacy now faced an able military leader in Ita ly. Accordingly, when
1 CONT negotiations broke down with Manfred in 1262, P ope Urban IV again took up the
1 CONT scheme of disseising the Hohenstaufen f rom the Kingdom, and offered the crown
1 CONT to Charles again. Manfred's ow n usurpation from Conradin told upon King
1 CONT Louis' scruples; this time, he was persuaded to admit the offer, and Charles
1 CONT ratified a treaty wit h the Pope in July 1263. The terms were heavily in favor
1 CONT of the Pope; the Kingdom must never be re-united with the Empire, and the King
1 CONT was never to hold Imperial or Papal office, or interfere with ecclesiastic al
1 CONT matters in the Kingdom. Nevertheless, Charles accepted eagerly. Ch arles felt
1 CONT he could control and reign as Roman Emperor of Constantinop le as well as the
1 CONT King of Sicily and southern Italy, with the support of the Pope.
1 CONT
1 CONT Having endorsed the treaty, Charles could now play for time, but he co uld not
1 CONT do any of this without the permission of his older brother Lou is IX, who,
1 CONT with his love of family could not resist the request of hi s younger brother.
1 CONT With Manfred's troops advancing on the Papal State s, Charles obtained an
1 CONT extensive renegotiation of the treaty on more f avorable lines. As
1 CONT instructions went out to the clergy to submit contr ibutions for the war,
1 CONT Urban IV died in October 1264 at Perugia, fleein g Manfred. This raised the
1 CONT possibility of a reversal of Papal policy. To underscore his resolve, he broke
1 CONT sharply with his previous policy o f lenity and ordered the execution of Hugh
1 CONT of Baux and several other P rovençal rebels, who had been in his hands for a
1 CONT year. Fortunately fo r Charles, the new Pope Clement IV was the former adviser
1 CONT of his broth er Alphonse and strongly supported the accession of Charles.
1 CONT Charles entered Rome on May 23, 1265 and was proclaimed King of Sicily. Charl
1 CONT es was crowned as King of Naples and Sicily in about June of 1265.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles was popular in Rome, where he was elected Senator, and his dip lomacy
1 CONT had already undermined Manfred's support in northern Italy. Whi le Charles'
1 CONT campaigns were delayed for lack of money, Manfred, curious ly, idled away his
1 CONT time hunting in Apulia, while his support in the no rth of Italy dwindled.
1 CONT Charles was able to bring his main army throug h the Alps, and he and Beatrice
1 CONT were crowned on January 6, 1266. As Ch arles' army began an energetic
1 CONT campaign, Manfred suddenly shed his let hargy and moved to meet him. Worried
1 CONT that further delays might endange r the loyalty of his supporters, he attacked
1 CONT Charles' army, then in di sarray from the crossing of the hills into
1 CONT Benevento, on February 26,1 266. In the Battle of Benevento that followed,
1 CONT Manfred handled his ar my poorly and was defeated in detail and he was killed
1 CONT in the melee. U pon his death, resistance throughout the Kingdom collapsed,
1 CONT and Charle s was master of Sicily. Charles laid a crushing taxiation ujpon the
1 CONT S icilian population to finance his plans, but the Sicilians remained st
1 CONT rongly attached to the House of Frederick II.
1 CONT
1 CONT While Charles' administration in his new Kingdom was generally fair an d
1 CONT honest, it was also stringent. As in Provence, he insisted on maximi zing the
1 CONT revenues and privileges he could obtain from his new subjects . Discontent was
1 CONT high; but for now, Charles could focus on extending h is power in northern
1 CONT Italy (which alarmed the Pope, who feared a power ful king of all Italy as
1 CONT much as he did an Emperor). But the Pope wasw illing to allow this; for in
1 CONT September 1267 Conradin marched south to reclaim the rights of the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen, and one of his agents instigat ed a revolt in Sicily. He entered
1 CONT Rome on July 24, 1268, where his arr ival was wildly celebrated. At the Battle
1 CONT of Tagliacozzo, Charles def eated the forces of Conradin,who was captured and
1 CONT taken to Genoa. Con radin was arrested and imprisoned in the Castello dell'Ovo
1 CONT in Naples. In a trial carefully managed by Charles, Conradin was condemned for
1 CONT tr eason, and he was beheaded on October 29, 1268. By the end of 1270, Ch
1 CONT arles had captured Lucera and put down the revolt in Sicily, executin g many
1 CONT of the captured. Charles now felt himself secure on the thron e of Naples and
1 CONT Sicily and with the whole kingdom powed beneath his st rict, if fair, rule, he
1 CONT was ready to consider greater conquests.
1 CONT
1 CONT After the defeat of Manfred at Benevento, Charles immediately began t o plan
1 CONT his expansion into the Mediterranean, particularly Constantinop le.
1 CONT Historically, the Kingdom of Sicily had at times controlled parts of the
1 CONT eastern Adriatic seaboard, and Manfred had been possessed of th e island of
1 CONT Corfu and the towns of Butrinto, Avlona, and Suboto, whic h had formed the
1 CONT dowry of his wife Helena. Charles seized these at th e end of 1266. From
1 CONT thence, he passed on to intrigue with the remainin g nobility of the Latin
1 CONT Empire. In May 1267, he concluded the Treaty o f Viterbo with the exiled
1 CONT Baldwin II of Constantinople and William II Villehardouin (through his
1 CONT chancellor Leonardo of Veruli). Taking adva ntage of the precarious situation
1 CONT of the remains of the Empire in the face of rising Greek power, he obtained
1 CONT confirmation of his possessio n of Corfu, the suzerain rights over Achaea, and
1 CONT sovereignty over mos t of the Aegean islands. Furthermore, the heirs of both
1 CONT the Latin prin ces were to marry children of Charles, and Charles was to have
1 CONT the rev ersion of the Empire and Principality should the couples have no heirs
1 CONT . With few options to check the Byzantine tide, he was well placed to dictate
1 CONT terms.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles' wife Beatrice died on September 23, 1267, and he immediately sought a
1 CONT new marriage to Margaret, daughter of Bela IV of Hungary. How ever, Margaret
1 CONT wished to be a nun (and was later canonized); Charles i nstead married (on
1 CONT November 18, 1268), Margaret, Countess of Tonnerre (1250 - September 4, 1308,
1 CONT Tonnerre), the daughter of Eudes of Burgund y. However, he was able to make a
1 CONT marital alliance with the Hungarians : his son Charles, Prince of Salerno
1 CONT married Maria, daughter of crownp rince Stephen, while Charles' daughter
1 CONT Elizabeth married Stephen's so n Ladislas.
1 CONT
1 CONT Having thus made secure his position in the East, he began to prepare a
1 CONT crusade to recover the Latin Empire. Michael VIII Palaeologus was gr eatly
1 CONT alarmed at the prospect: he wrote to King Louis, suggesting tha t he was open
1 CONT to a voluntary union of the Roman and Latin churches, an d poiting out the
1 CONT interference a descent on Constantinople would poset o Louis' own crusading
1 CONT plans. Louis took a dim view of his sincerity; but he was eager to take up the
1 CONT cross again, and he notified Charles o f his intentions. Charles continued
1 CONT with his preparations against Cons tantinople, hoping the crusade might be
1 CONT postponed, but he also prepare d to turn his brother's crusade to his own
1 CONT advantage. The Caliph of Tu nis, Muhammed I al-Mustansir had been a vassal of
1 CONT Sicily, but hadshake n off his allegiance with the fall of Manfred. However,
1 CONT there were rum ors he might be sympathetic to Christianity. Accordingly,
1 CONT Charles sugg ested to his brother that the arrival of a crusade in his support
1 CONT migh t bring about Mustansir's conversion. Thus it was that Louis directed the
1 CONT Eighth Crusade against Tunis. Charles did not arrive until late i n the day on
1 CONT August 25, 1270, only to find that his brother had died o f dysentery that
1 CONT morning. Charles took command, and after a few skirmi shes, Mustansir
1 CONT concluded a peace treaty and agreed to pay tribute to Charles. Illness
1 CONT continued to plague the army, however, and a storm de vastated the fleet as it
1 CONT returned to Sicily. Charles was forced to pos tpone his designs against
1 CONT Constantinople again.
1 CONT
1 CONT In February 1271, Charles began to expand his Adriatic possessions byc
1 CONT apturing Durazzo, and he soon controlled much of the Albanian interior . In
1 CONT February 1272, he proclaimed himself King of Albania and appointe d Gazzo
1 CONT Chinardo as his Vicar-General. He hoped to take up his expedit ion against
1 CONT Constantinople again, but was delayed by the rise Pope Gre gory X, consecrated
1 CONT on March 27, 1272. Gregory had high hopes of recon ciling Europe, unifying the
1 CONT Greek and Latin churches, and launchinga n ew crusade: to that end, he
1 CONT announced the Council of Lyon, to be held in 1274, and worked to arrange the
1 CONT election of an Emperor.
1 CONT
1 CONT In November 1272, the strained relations between Charles and Ghibellin e-ruled
1 CONT Genoa finally broke into war. Ghibelline revolts broke out acr oss the north
1 CONT of Italy, and increasingly occupied the attention of Cha rles, even as Michael
1 CONT Palaeologus was negotiating a union of churchesw ith the Pope. At the same
1 CONT time, he had made contact with Genoa and wa s sending money to encourage the
1 CONT revolts in the north. At the apparent ly successful conclusion of the Council
1 CONT of Lyon, a Union of Churches w as declared, and Charles and Philip of
1 CONT Courtenay were compelled to ext end a truce with Michael. This was a blessing
1 CONT in disguise for Charles , for the Ghibellines now controlled most of the
1 CONT north, and he was for ced to retreat from Piedmont in late 1275. In truth,
1 CONT Pope Gregory wasn ot entirely displeased; he regarded north Italy as best
1 CONT dealt with by its new Emperor, Rudolph of Habsburg, and preferred that Charles
1 CONT be co nfined to the south. If he wished to make war, let him look to Outrem
1 CONT er; and to this end, Gregory endorsed the sale to Charles of the claim s of
1 CONT Maria of Antioch on the Kingdom of Jerusalem, which had been reje cted by the
1 CONT Haute Cour there. Charles decided to attack the Byzantine empire directly, and
1 CONT crossed the southern Adriatic to land an army in the Balkans. By 1277, he had
1 CONT entrenched himself over a considerable p ortion of the Byzantine domain and
1 CONT himself proclaimed King of Jerusale m. On March 18, 1277, he bought Maria of
1 CONT Antioch's claim and assumed the title of King of Jerusalem, sending Roger of
1 CONT Sanseverino as his ba illi to Acre. There Roger ousted Balian of Ibelin, the
1 CONT bailli of Hugh I and compelled the nobles to swear fealty. In the meantime,
1 CONT Gregory h ad been succeeded by Pope Innocent V, who arranged a peace between
1 CONT Cha rles and the Genoese.
1 CONT
1 CONT Meanwhile, in Constantinople, the Union of the Churches was proving di fficult
1 CONT to arrange, and the Emperor Michael had great difficulty in im posing it on
1 CONT his people. Nevertheless, he persuaded Innocent of his si ncerity in working
1 CONT towards it, and Charles was again forbidden to atta ck Constantinople. Knowing
1 CONT this, Michael began a campaign in Albania i n late 1274, where he captured
1 CONT Berat and Butrinto. He also enjoyed som e success in his campaigns in Euboea
1 CONT and the Peloponnese. Affairs dra gged on for several years, until the
1 CONT accession of Pope Martin IV on Ma rch 23, 1280. Pope Martin was a Frenchman,
1 CONT and lacked the evenhandedne ss of some of his recent precursors. He brought
1 CONT the full power of theP apacy into line behind Charles' plans. The Union, which
1 CONT had proved imp ossible to impose upon Constantinople, was called off, and
1 CONT Charles giv en authorization for the restoration of the Latin Empire.
1 CONT
1 CONT He opened his campaign in Albania, where his general Hugh of Sully cap tured
1 CONT Butrinto from the Despotate of Epirus in 1280 and besieging Bera t. A
1 CONT Byzantine army of relief under Michael Tarchaniotes arrived in Ma rch, 1281:
1 CONT Hugh of Sully was ambushed and captured, and his army put t o flight. The
1 CONT Byzantines took possession of the interior of Albania. N or was Charles
1 CONT particularly successful in Achaea, where he had become( by the Treaty of
1 CONT Viterbo) Prince of Achaea on the death of William II Villehardouin in 1278.
1 CONT His bailli Galeran of Ivry was defeated at Skor ta in his one attempt to
1 CONT engage the Byzantines, and was recalled in128 0 and replaced by Philip of
1 CONT Lagonesse. Nonetheless, Charles was tolaun ch the body of his crusade against
1 CONT Constantinople in the spring of 128 2.
1 CONT
1 CONT But Michael had not been working upon the military front alone. Many G
1 CONT hibelline officials had fled the Kingdom of Sicily to the court of Pet er III
1 CONT of Aragon, who had married Constance, the daughter and heir of Manfred.
1 CONT Manfred's former chancellor, John of Procida, had arranged co ntact between
1 CONT Michael, Peter and the refugees at his court, and conspi rators on the island
1 CONT of Sicily itself. Peter began to assemble a flee t at Barcelona, ostensibly
1 CONT for another Crusade to Tunis. In fact, them aster-plan of John of Procida was
1 CONT to place Peter on the throne of Sici ly, his Hohenstaufen inheritance. The
1 CONT result was the uprising known a s the 'Sicilian Vespers', which was initiated
1 CONT in Palermo on March 29, 1282, possibly by Michael VIII of Constantinople. It
1 CONT rapidly grew int o a general massacre of the French in Sicily. A few officials
1 CONT notabl e for their good conduct were spared; and the city of Messina still he
1 CONT ld for Charles. But through the diplomatic errors of Charles' Vicar, Herbert
1 CONT of Orleans, Messina, too, revolted on April 28, 1282. Herbert retreated to the
1 CONT castle of Mategriffon, but was forced to abandon the Crusading fleet, which
1 CONT was burnt.
1 CONT
1 CONT The news surprised Peter (Pedro) of Aragon, who had expected to interv ene
1 CONT only after Charles had left for Constantinople. But the conspirato rs, aided
1 CONT by the Emperor Michael (who wished to see Charles balked in his expedition),
1 CONT had set the revolt in motion early. Peter did not imm ediately intervene; he
1 CONT sailed with the fleet to Tunis, where he discov ered that the would-be convert
1 CONT on whose behalf the crusade had ostensi bly been undertaken had been caught
1 CONT and executed. While he bided his t ime, the Sicilians made an appeal to Pope
1 CONT Martin to take the Communes of their cities under his protection. But Martin
1 CONT was far too deeply co mmitted to Charles and French interests to heed them;
1 CONT instead, he exco mmunicated the rebels, the Emperor Michael, and the
1 CONT Ghibellines in nor th Italy. Charles gathered his forces in Calabria and made
1 CONT a landing n ear Messina and began a siege. Several attempts to assault the
1 CONT city we re unsuccessful. Rejected by the Pope, the Sicilians now appealed to K
1 CONT ing Peter (Pedro III) and Queen Constance; he duly accepted, and lande d at
1 CONT Trapani on August 30, 1282. He was proclaimed King in Palermo on September 4;
1 CONT as the Archibishopric of Palermo was vacant, he could no t immediately be
1 CONT crowned. In the face of the Aragonese landing, Charle s was compelled to
1 CONT withdraw across the Straits of Messina into Calabri a in September; but the
1 CONT Aragonese moved swiftly enough to destroy par t of his army and most of his
1 CONT baggage. Charles and his fleet were def eated by Pedro III off Naples where
1 CONT Charles son Charles was captured b y the Aragonese. The Angevin house was
1 CONT forever ousted from Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT Despite his retreat into Calabria, Charles remained in a strong positi on. His
1 CONT nephew, Philip III of France, was devoted to Charles; and Pop e Martin
1 CONT regarded the rebellion as an affront both to French interest s andhis own
1 CONT rights as suzerain of the Kingdom. Both sides temporized ; theexpense of a
1 CONT long war might be disastrous for both, and Peter an d Charles arranged for a
1 CONT judicial duel, with a hundred knights apiece , on June 1, 1283 at Bordeaux.
1 CONT Skirmishes and raids continued to occur : in January 1283, Aragonese guerillas
1 CONT attacked Catona and killed Coun t Peter I of Alençon in his hostel. In
1 CONT February, the Aragonese crosse d intoCalabria to face off with Charles of
1 CONT Salerno. However, tensions between the Aragonese and the Sicilians had begun
1 CONT to rise. Both men no w hoped to turn the war to their advantage, and the
1 CONT judicial duel turn ed into a farce, the two kings arriving at different times,
1 CONT declaring a victory over their absent opponent, and departing. Now the war was
1 CONT t o escalate: Pope Martin had excommunicated Peter and proclaimed the wa r
1 CONT against the Sicilians a Crusade in January, and in March, declared P eter to
1 CONT be deprived of his dominions. On February 2, 1284, Aragon and Valencia were
1 CONT officially conferred upon Charles of Valois. The war con tinued in Italy:
1 CONT while little progress had been made in Calabria, a de tachment of the
1 CONT Aragonese fleet was blockading Malta. Charles of Saler no sent a newly raised
1 CONT Provençal fleet to the relief of Malta; but it was caught by the main
1 CONT Aragonese fleet under Roger of Lauria and destr oyedin the Battle of Malta.
1 CONT The Aragonese were now, however, running q uite short of money, and Peter was
1 CONT threatened by the prospect of a Fre nch attack on Aragon. King Charles planned
1 CONT to raise new troops and a f leet in Provence, and instructed Charles of
1 CONT Salerno to maintain a stri ct defensive posture until his return from France.
1 CONT However, Roger of L auria continued to command the sea and launch harassing
1 CONT raids up and d own the coast of Calabria, and in May 1284 he successfully
1 CONT blockaded N aples, basing a small squadron on the island of Nisida to do so.
1 CONT The N eapolitans were infuriated by the blockade; and in June, Charles of Sa
1 CONT lerno armed the newly launched fleet at Naples and embarked on June 5 to
1 CONT destroy the blockading squadron. Evidently believing the main Arago nese fleet
1 CONT was raiding down the coast, he hoped to destroy the blockad ing squadron and
1 CONT return to Naples before it returned. However, Roger o f Lauria had learned of
1 CONT his plans, and Charles found himself engulfed by superior numbers. After a
1 CONT short, sharp, fight, most of his fleet wa s captured, and he himself was taken
1 CONT prisoner.
1 CONT
1 CONT News of the reverse caused anti-French riots in Naples, and Roger of L auria
1 CONT was quick to take advantage of Charles' captivity to obtain ther elease of
1 CONT Beatrice, daughter of Manfred of Sicily, then held in Naples . King Charles
1 CONT arrived in Gaeta on June 6 and learned of the disaster . He was furious at his
1 CONT son and his disobedience; by the time he reach ed Naples, the riots had been
1 CONT quelled. He advanced on Calabria and att empted a landing in Sicily; but his
1 CONT main army was blocked at Reggio, a nd he retreated from Calabria entirely on
1 CONT August 3. He continued to ma ke preparations for a campaign against Sicily in
1 CONT the new year; but hi s health failed. On January 7, 1285, he died in Foggia.
1 CONT
1 CONT On his death, Charles left all of his domains to his son Charles, the n a
1 CONT prisoner in Catalonia. For the time being, they were held by a joi nt regency
1 CONT between a papal legate and Robert II of Artois. Charles ha d spent his life
1 CONT striving to assemble a Mediterranean empire out of wh atever land he could get
1 CONT through law or force of arms. He did so, it s eems, with a clear conscience;
1 CONT he regarded himself as God's instrumen t to uphold the Papacy and punish the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen. He ruled justly, b ut with the rigidity and severity that might
1 CONT be expected in one of hi s convictions. Ultimately, his unbending austerity
1 CONT could not inspire t he devotion needed to hold his conquests together.
1 CONT
1 CONT Still, he was to leave a substantial legacy to his heirs. Henry II ofC yprus
1 CONT reclaimed the Kingdom of Jerusalem after his death, for the few short years
1 CONT left to it; but his possessions otherwise remained within the Angevin dynasty
1 CONT which he founded, or their descendants. Both the A ngevins and their Aragonese
1 CONT rivals were to claim the title of "King o f Sicily"; but the Angevins,
1 CONT confined to the mainland, would be known to history as "Kings of Naples". But
1 CONT the style of "King of Sicily"pers isted; and when the two realms were
1 CONT reunited, it was under the style o f "King of the Two Sicilies".
1 CONT
1 CONT However, his wars resulted in an even more serious consequence that th e
1 CONT partition of the Kingdom of Sicily. Pope Martin IV had hopelessly co mpromised
1 CONT the Papacy in his cause; and the botched secular "Crusades"a gainst Sicily and
1 CONT (after Charles' death) Aragon greatly tarnished its spiritual power. The
1 CONT collapse of its moral authority and the rise of n ationalism rang the death
1 CONT knell for Crusading, and would ultimately le ad to the Avignon Papacy and the
1 CONT Western Schism. Charles was an able s oldier and a good administrator; but his
1 CONT failure to understand the qua lities of his diverse subjects, and his
1 CONT grasping, if pious, ambition, ultimately led him to failure. In the Divine
1 CONT Comedy Dante sees Charle s outside the gates of Purgatory "singing in accord"
1 CONT with his former r ival Peter.
1 CONT <http://www.dcs.hull.ac.uk/cgi-bin/gedlkup/n=royal?royal02484>
1 CONT GIVN Carlos, King Of
1 CONT SURN Sicily
1 CONT NSFX [King Of Jerusal
1 CONT AFN 8XJD-SM
