0 @N00457@ NOTE geni:about_me -<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_I_Komnenos_Doukas>
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael I Komnenos Doukas or Comnenus Ducas (Greek: Μιχαήλ Α΄ Κομνηνός Δούκας,
1 CONT Mikhaēl I Komnēnos Doukas), often inaccurately called Michael Angelos (a name
1 CONT he never used), was the founder and first ruler of the principality of Epirus
1 CONT from 1205 until his death in 1215.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael was the illegitimate son of the sebastokratōr John Doukas. He was thus
1 CONT a first cousin of the emperors Isaac II Angelos and Alexios III Angelos.
1 CONT
1 CONT Before 1204, he was governor of the Theme of Mylasa in Asia Minor. After the
1 CONT fall of Constantinople to the forces of the Fourth Crusade, Michael briefly
1 CONT entered into the service of Boniface of Montferrat, who received the Kingdom
1 CONT of Thessalonica and overlordship over Greece in the division of the spoils.
1 CONT Michael abandoned Boniface and may have attempted to resist the Crusaders in
1 CONT the Peloponnese, perhaps fighting at the Battle of the Olive Grove of
1 CONT Koundouros.
1 CONT
1 CONT Losing the battle, he fled to Epirus. There he founded a Byzantine successor
1 CONT state inaccurately called the Despotate of Epirus, with his capital in Arta,
1 CONT in the area of the old Theme of Nicopolis. Epirus became the new home of many
1 CONT Greek refugees from Constantinople, Thessaly, and the Peloponnese, and Michael
1 CONT was described as a second Noah, rescuing men from the Latin flood. John X
1 CONT Kamateros, the Patriarch of Constantinople, did not consider Michael a
1 CONT legitimate ruler and instead joined Theodore I Laskaris in Nicaea; Michael
1 CONT recognized the ecclesiastical authority of Pope Innocent III over Epirus,
1 CONT cutting his ties to the Orthodox Church at Nicaea.
1 CONT
1 CONT In Epirus, Michael resisted the attempts of Boniface of Montferrat to subdue
1 CONT him. The Latin Emperor Henry of Flanders demanded that Michael submit to the
1 CONT Latin Empire, and accepted an alliance, allowing his daughter to marry Henry's
1 CONT brother Eustace in 1209. Michael did not honour this alliance, assuming that
1 CONT mountainous Epirus would be mostly impenetrable by any Latins with whom he
1 CONT made and broke alliances. Meanwhile Boniface's relatives from Montferrat made
1 CONT claims to Epirus as well, and in 1210 Michael allied with the Republic of
1 CONT Venice and attacked Thessalonica. He is alleged to have been excessively cruel
1 CONT to his prisoners, in some cases crucifying Latin priests. Innocent III
1 CONT excommunicated him in response. Henry relieved the city later that year and
1 CONT forced Michael into a new nominal alliance.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, Michael turned his attention to capturing other strategically
1 CONT important towns, including Larissa in Thessaly from the Latins in 1212, and
1 CONT Dyrrhachium and Corfu from the Venetians in 1214. He also took control of the
1 CONT ports on the Gulf of Corinth. Drawn into a war against Serbia as an ally of
1 CONT the Latin Empire and Bulgaria, Michael was murdered by one of his servants in
1 CONT 1215 and was succeeded by his half-brother Theodore Komnenos Doukas.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael I married the daughter of an Epirote magnate, by whom he had:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Constantine Komnenos Doukas, who died young
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Theodora Komnene Doukaina
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Maria Komnene Doukaina, who married Constantine Maliassenos
1 CONT
1 CONT By an unnamed mistress, Michael I had at least one more son:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Michael II Komnenos Doukas, who succeeded as ruler of Epirus in 1230
1 CONT
1 CONT \----------
1 CONT
1 CONT -<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ALBANIA.htm#MikhaelAdied1215B>
1 CONT
1 CONT MIKHAEL Angelos, illegitimate son of IOANNES Doukas Angelos & his mistress ---
1 CONT (-murdered Berat [1215]). Niketas Choniates names "Michael…Iohannis
1 CONT sebastocratoris nothus filius" when recording that Emperor Alexios III sent
1 CONT him as missus to "Mylassenæ province"[43]. The Historia de Expeditione
1 CONT Friderici records that Emperor Isaakios II sent “domnum Michaelem filium
1 CONT patrui sui sevostratoris Ioannis Duca et domnum Michaelem filium alterius
1 CONT patrui eius domni Alexii Angeli et Manuel consobrinum imperii eius filium
1 CONT stratovasilum et domnum Alexium filium consobrini eius protostratoris Manuel
1 CONT Camizi et tertium Manuel sevaston Monomachii filium Uriennii Ioseph et
1 CONT pansevaston acolithon Eumathium Philocalim” as hostages to Emperor Friedrich
1 CONT I, dated to Feb 1190[44]. During his early career he served different masters
1 CONT depending on who was in the ascendant. He served Emperor Alexios III, who
1 CONT created him sébastos, dux and anagraphaos at Mylasa and Melanudion, until 1195
1 CONT and from 1201. After attempting rebellion against the emperor, Mikhael
1 CONT defected to the Seljuk Sultan by whom he was appointed governor in the regions
1 CONT of the Meander[45]. An act dated Jan [1204] names “o theios
1 CONT tis...basileias...o Komnenos Mikhael o Doukas, tin doukikin arkhin tou
1 CONT thematou Molassis kai Melanoudiou”[46]. Mikhael joined Bonifazio Marchese di
1 CONT Monferrato, newly installed as king of Thessaloniki, in the latter's conquest
1 CONT of Thessaly in 1204. According to the Chronicle of Geoffrey of Villehardouin,
1 CONT a "Greek named Michaelis who had come from Constantinople with the marquis"
1 CONT married "the daughter of a wealthy Greek who held his land from the emperor"
1 CONT at Arta, and "after seizing that land for himself, began to make war on the
1 CONT marquis"[47]. According to the late 13th century life of St Theodora
1 CONT Petraliphina of Arta, Mikhael helped suppress the rebellion in the theme of
1 CONT Nikopolis against its Governor Senacherim and, after the latter's murder,
1 CONT married his widow as his second wife[48]. Whichever version is correct,
1 CONT Mikhael obtained the government of territories in Epirus and expanded his
1 CONT control northwards to the outskirts of Durazzo and southwards to Naupaktos on
1 CONT the Gulf of Corinth, establishing himself as Lord of Epirus. According to
1 CONT Fine, no contemporary sources indicate that Mikhael was installed as despot (a
1 CONT title which was granted by an emperor)[49]. He added "Komnenos" and "Doukas"
1 CONT to his name to increase his authority[50]. He was opposed by Venice which had
1 CONT been assigned Epirus under the treaty agreed with the crusading armies in
1 CONT March 1204 before the capture of Constantinople, but sought protection from
1 CONT the Papacy in 1207, declaring himself willing to discuss church union[51]. He
1 CONT made a treaty with the Latin Empire of Constantinople in 1209, sealed by the
1 CONT marriage of his oldest daughter, although this did not prevent Mikhael from
1 CONT attacking Thessaloniki in 1210 for which he was excommunicated by Pope
1 CONT Innocent III. He was forced to retreat by Henri Latin Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople. On 20 Jun 1210, Mikhael concluded an alliance with Venice,
1 CONT recognising Venetian overlordship and granting the Venetians the right to free
1 CONT trade in Epirus. He invaded Thessaly in 1212, capturing Larissa. In 1213,
1 CONT Mikhael captured Durazzo from Venice in violation of his alliance. In 1214, he
1 CONT captured Corfu, also from Venice, and moved northwards to conquer Krüje and
1 CONT Shkodra in northern Albania. He was on campaign against Serbia in northern
1 CONT Albania when he was murdered by a servant[52].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** firstly --- Melissene, daughter of --- Melissenos. This marriage is
1 CONT recorded in the late 13th century life of St Theodora Petraliphina of
1 CONT Arta[53].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** secondly (1204) as her second husband, his first wife's cousin, ---
1 CONT Melissene, widow of SENACHERIM strategos of the theme of Nikopolis, daughter
1 CONT of --- Melissenos & his wife ---. This second marriage is recorded in the late
1 CONT 13th century life of St Theodora Petraliphina of Arta[54]. According to
1 CONT Geoffrey of Villehardouin, a "Greek named Michaelis who had come from
1 CONT Constantinople with the marquis" married "the daughter of a wealthy Greek who
1 CONT held his land from the emperor" at Arta, and "after seizing that land for
1 CONT himself, began to make war on the marquis"[55]. From the context, this
1 CONT marriage must be dated to mid-1204 and so presumably refers to Mikhael's
1 CONT second marriage. The primary source which identifies her relationship with her
1 CONT second husband's first wife and names her first husband has not been
1 CONT identified.
1 CONT
1 CONT **Mistress** (1): (before 1205) ---. The name of Ioannes's mistress is not
1 CONT known. She was banished to Peloponnesos with her son by the latter's half-
1 CONT brother Theodoros[56].
1 CONT
1 CONT Mikhael Komnenos Doukas Angelos & his [first] wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 1\. daughter. The primary source which confirms her parentage and marriage has not been identified. Her marriage, to the younger brother of the late Baudouin I Latin Emperor of Constantinople, was arranged by her father to seal his alliance wit
1 CONC h the Latin Empire[57]. It is assumed that she was the daughter of Mikhael's first marriage in view of the date of her betrothal, although it is not impossible that she was still an infant at the time and therefore born from his second marriage. m
1 CONC  (betrothed [Jun/Jul] 1209) EUSTACHE de Flandre, son of BAUDOUIN V Comte de Hainaut [BAUDOUIN VIII Count of Flanders] & his wife Marguerite I Ctss of Flanders (-after 1217).
1 CONT
1 CONT Mikhael Komnenos Doukas Angelos & his [first/second] wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 2\. THEODORA Komnene. Her betrothal is shown in Europäische Stammtafeln[58] but the primary source on which this is based has not been identified The betrothal was terminated because of the church's objections[59]. Europäische Stammtafeln[60] s
1 CONC uggests that Theodora was the same person as Anna Komnene Angelina, possible wife of Maio [II] Count of Kefalonia. The basis for this speculation is not known. As noted above, it would be chronologically more acceptable for Maio's wife to have been
1 CONC  the daughter of Mikhael [I] Lord of Epirus than his half-sister. However, the only source as yet identified points the other way. Betrothed (before 1217) to --- of Serbia, son of STEFAN Grand Župan of Serbia. Her betrothed has not been identified,
1 CONC  although he may have been Stefan Radoslav of Serbia, son of Stefan Grand Župan of Serbia & his first wife Evdokia Komnene Angelina ([1191/1201]-after 1235), who succeeded his father in [1224/27] as Radoslav "Krapalo" King of Serbia. If this is cor
1 CONC rect, the betrothal would have been agreed at the same time as that of Theodora's sister Maria to Radoslav's father.
1 CONT
1 CONT Mikhael Komnenos Doukas Angelos & his second wife had two children:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 3\. MARIA Komnene. Her first betrothal is shown in Europäische Stammtafeln[61] but the primary source on which this is based has not yet been identified. Georgius Akropolites names "Chabaronem Constantinum" as husband of "Michaele despota…soror
1 CONC is Mariæ", stating that she had previously been married to "viro Sphrantzæ cognomine"[62]. Betrothed (before 1217) to STEFAN Grand Župan of Serbia, son of STEFAN NEMANJA Grand Župan of Serbia & his wife Ana --- (-24 Sep 1227), who in [1217] was cro
1 CONC wned STEFAN "Prvovenčani/the First-Crowned" King [Kralj] of Serbia. m firstly --- Sphrantzes, son of ---. m secondly KONSTANTINOS Chabaron, son of ---. Maria & her [first/second] husband had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT     * a) daughter . Georgius Akropolites records that "Michael despota" send legates to the emperor "Xerum metropolitam Naupacti, Maliassenum sororis suæ generum, et Lampetem"[63]. m --- Melissenos, son of ---.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 4\. KONSTANTINOS Komnenos (-before 1214). The primary source which confirms his parentage has not yet been identified.
1 CONT
1 CONT Mikhael Komnenos Doukas Angelos had one illegitimate child by Mistress (1):
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 5\. KONSTANTINOS Komnenos Doukas Angelos ([1205]-[1267/68]). The primary source which confirms his parentage has not yet been identified. He was known as MIKHAEL after the death of his father. Lord of Epirus. - see below.
