1 CONT Peter II of Aragon (1174 – September 12, 1213), surnamed the Catholic, was the
1 CONT king of Aragon (as Pedro II) and count of Barcelona (as Pere I) from 1196 to
1 CONT 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the son of Alfonso II of Aragon and Sancha of Castile. In 1205 he
1 CONT acknowledged the feudal supremacy of the Papacy and was crowned in Rome by
1 CONT Pope Innocent III, swearing to defend the Catholic faith (hence his surname,
1 CONT "the Catholic"). He was the first king of Aragon to be crowned by the Pope.
1 CONT
1 CONT On June 15, 1204 he married (as her third husband) Marie of Montpellier,
1 CONT daughter and heiress of William VIII of Montpellier by Eudocia Comnena. She
1 CONT gave him a son, James, but Peter soon discarded her. Marie was popularly
1 CONT venerated as a saint for her piety and marital suffering, but was never
1 CONT canonized; she died in Rome in 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT He led the Christian forces to defeat the Moors at the Battle of Las Navas de
1 CONT Tolosa in 1212.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter returned from Las Navas in autumn 1212 to find that Simon de Montfort
1 CONT had conquered Toulouse, exiling Count Raymond VI of Toulouse, who was Peter's
1 CONT brother-in-law and vassal. Peter crossed the Pyrenees and arrived at Muret in
1 CONT September 1213 to confront Montfort's army. He was accompanied by Raymond of
1 CONT Toulouse, who tried to persuade Peter to avoid battle and instead starve out
1 CONT Montfort's forces. This suggestion was rejected.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Battle of Muret began on September 12, 1213. The Aragonese forces were
1 CONT disorganized and disintegrated under the assault of Montfort's squadrons.
1 CONT Peter himself was caught in the thick of fighting, and died as a result of a
1 CONT foolhardy act of bravado. He was thrown to the ground and killed. The
1 CONT Aragonese forces broke in panic when their king was slain and the crusaders of
1 CONT Montfort won the day.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon Peter's death the kingdom passed to his only son by Marie of Montpellier,
1 CONT the future James the Conqueror.
