1 CONT (Research):Peter II (Petro II) Encyclopædia Britannica Article born 1174 died
1 CONT Sept. 12, 1213, Muret, Fr. byname Peter The Catholic, Spanish Pedro El
1 CONT Católico king of Aragon from 1196 to 1213, the eldest son and successor of
1 CONT Alfonso II. Peter married (1204) Mary, lady of Montpellier, and thus greatly
1 CONT extended Aragonese power in southern France. Despite the violent objections of
1 CONT his subjects, he had himself crowned by Pope Innocent III in Rome and declared
1 CONT his kingdom a feudatory of the Holy See (1204). Peter, with other Spanish
1 CONT kings, took a prominent part in the victory over the Moors at Las Navas de
1 CONT Tolosa (July 16, 1212); but he then went to support his brother-in-law Raymond
1 CONT VI of Toulouse against the crusader Simon de Montfort in Languedoc. There he
1 CONT was killed in the Battle of Muret. His son James I succeeded him.
1 CONT
1 CONT Pedro II, King of Aragon 1195-1213 (1176-1213) Born 1176 Died 13 September
1 CONT 1213 Muret (in battle) Married 5 June 1204 Marie de Montpellier Dame de
1 CONT Montpellier, Dame de Muret Born circa 1183 Died 21 April 1213 Rome His armies
1 CONT contributed less to the *Reconquista* of Muslim Spain as he was involved with
1 CONT his wife's territories in southern France. There he dies in 1213 defending the
1 CONT cause of the Albigensians at the battle of Muret. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Peter II of Aragon
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT Jump to: navigation, search
1 CONT Peter II of Aragon (1174 – September 12, 1213), surnamed the Catholic, was the
1 CONT king of Aragon (as Pedro II) and count of Barcelona (as Pere I) from 1196 to
1 CONT 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the son of Alfonso II of Aragon and Sancha of Castile. In 1205 he
1 CONT acknowledged the feudal supremacy of the Papacy and was crowned in Rome by
1 CONT Pope Innocent III, swearing to defend the Catholic faith (hence his surname,
1 CONT "the Catholic"). He was the first king of Aragon to be crowned by the Pope.
1 CONT
1 CONT On June 15, 1204 he married (as her third husband) Marie of Montpellier,
1 CONT daughter and heiress of William VIII of Montpellier. She gave him a son,
1 CONT James, but Peter soon discarded her. Marie was popularly venerated as a saint
1 CONT for her piety and marital suffering, but was never canonized; she died in Rome
1 CONT in 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT He led the Christian forces to defeat the Moors at the Battle of Las Navas de
1 CONT Tolosa in 1212.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter returned from Las Navas in autumn 1212 to find that Simon de Montfort
1 CONT had conquered Toulouse, exiling Count Raymond VI of Toulouse, who was Peter's
1 CONT brother-in-law and vassal. Peter crossed the Pyrenees and arrived at Muret in
1 CONT September 1213 to confront Montfort's army. He was accompanied by Raymond of
1 CONT Toulouse, who tried to persuade Peter to avoid battle and instead starve out
1 CONT Montfort's forces. This suggestion was rejected as cowardly and unknightly.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Battle of Muret began on September 12, 1213. The Aragonese forces were
1 CONT disorganized and disintegrated under the assault of Montfort's squadrons.
1 CONT Peter himself was caught in the thick of fighting, and being clad in ordinary
1 CONT armor, was mistaken for a common knight. He was thrown to the ground and
1 CONT killed. The Aragonese forces broke in panic when their king was slain and the
1 CONT crusaders of Montfort won the day.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon Peter's death the kingdom passed to his only son by Marie of Montpellier,
1 CONT the future James the Conqueror.
1 CONT
