1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Provence (c.1234–23 September 1267, Nocera Inferiore) was the
1 CONT first wife and Queen consort of Charles I of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT The youngest daughter of Raymond Berenguer IV of Provence and Beatrice of
1 CONT Savoy, Beatrice was married on January 31, 1246 to Charles of France, Count of
1 CONT Anjou and Maine, the youngest brother of King Louis IX of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Contents [hide]
1 CONT
1 CONT 1 Family
1 CONT
1 CONT 2 Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT 3 Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT 4 Death
1 CONT
1 CONT 5 Sources
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Raymond Berenguer, the Count of Provence and Forcalquier, had four daughters,
1 CONT but no sons. His eldest daughter, Marguerite, had married King Louis IX of
1 CONT France and was Queen consort of France; his second daughter, Eleanor, had
1 CONT married King Henry III of England, and his third, Sanchia, had married the
1 CONT wealthy Richard, Earl of Cornwall, brother of King Henry. King Louis IX's
1 CONT marriage to Marguerite had been arranged by his mother, Blanche of Castile,
1 CONT with the hopes that he would inherit Provence and Forcalquier when Berenguer
1 CONT died. Berenguer, however, left everything to Beatrice. James I of Aragon, in
1 CONT the hopes of uniting Provence and Toulouse, had planned to marry Beatrice but
1 CONT when her father died the French court intervened, by getting the Pope to
1 CONT refuse the marriage.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT When Berenguer had died on August 19, 1245, Beatrice became one of the most
1 CONT attractive heiresses in medieval Europe. Various suitors had tried to seize
1 CONT her, so her mother, Beatrice of Savoy, placed the younger Beatrice in a safe
1 CONT fortress, secured the trust of its people then went to the Pope for his
1 CONT protection. In Cluny during December 1245, a secret discussion, between Pope
1 CONT Innocent IV, Louis IX of France, his mother Blanche of Castile and his brother
1 CONT Charles of Anjou, took place. It was decided that in return for Louis IX
1 CONT supporting the Pope militarily, the Pope would allow Charles of Anjou,
1 CONT youngest brother to the French King, to marry Beatrice of Provence. Provence,
1 CONT however, was to never go to France outright through Charles. It was agreed
1 CONT that if Charles and Beatrice had children, the county would go to them; if
1 CONT there was no issue, then the county would go to Sanchia of Provence. If
1 CONT Sanchia died without an heir, Provence would go to the King of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy who had been granted the usufruct of the county for her
1 CONT lifetime according to her husband's will, agreed to the marriage between
1 CONT Charles of Anjou and her youngest daughter, Beatrice. Charles, along with
1 CONT Philippe of Savoy and five hundred knights, rode from Lyon to Provence. On
1 CONT their way, they ran into Raymond VII Count of Toulouse, who also had an army
1 CONT on the way to Provence. However, Raymond of Toulouse had been deceived by
1 CONT knights in favour of Charles and for that reason he had brought fewer men and
1 CONT Charles and his army were quicker. When Charles got to Aix-en-Provence, James
1 CONT I of Aragon, who had been there all along but was not allowed to see Beatrice,
1 CONT had his soldiers surrounding the castle in which the young Beatrice and her
1 CONT mother were. There was a brief struggle, but the King of Aragon retreated with
1 CONT dignity. To the young Beatrice, Charles, who was described as "an admirable
1 CONT young man", was a satisfactory resolution to her problems. The marriage took
1 CONT place in Aix-en-Provence. They had soldiers on guard and the bride was
1 CONT escorted down the aisle by her uncle, Thomas of Savoy.
1 CONT
1 CONT As soon as Charles became Count of Provence, he brought in his own team of
1 CONT French lawyers and accountants. He excluded his mother in law from the running
1 CONT of the county and began taking castles, power and fees away from the nobles
1 CONT who had previously enjoyed a certain degree of independence in the running of
1 CONT their cities. Charles made himself very unpopular. Beatrice of Savoy moved
1 CONT herself to Forcalquier in protest and in Marseille, Charles's officials were
1 CONT thrown out of the city. In the family conflict the younger Beatrice sided with
1 CONT her husband.
1 CONT
1 CONT In May 1247, Charles and Beatrice were recorded as being in Melun where
1 CONT Charles was knighted by his brother Louis. Beatrice accompanied Charles on the
1 CONT seventh crusade in 1248. Led by Louis IX, the crusaders made an extended
1 CONT procession through France. Before they left, Charles and Beatrice met with her
1 CONT mother in Beaucaire to try to come to some terms of agreement concerning
1 CONT Provence. Whilst the more important matters were left until Charles and
1 CONT Beatrice returned, it was decided that Beatrice of Savoy would give up the
1 CONT rights to 'the castle at Aix in exchange for a percentage of the county's
1 CONT revenue.'
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice gave birth to her first child in Nicosia, 'a very elegant and
1 CONT wellformed son', which Robert of Artois wrote home to his mother, Blanche of
1 CONT Castile, about. Beatrice stayed with her sister Marguerite in Damietta, when
1 CONT they lost contact with the King and his army, both women gave birth whilst in
1 CONT Damietta. Later in 1250, they were reunited with the rest of the crusade at
1 CONT Acre, were the King's ransom was paid. Charles and Beatrice, along with
1 CONT several other nobles, left soon after. They journeyed to the court of Emporer
1 CONT Frederick II, to ask him to send the King of France more men for his crusade.
1 CONT However, the Emperor, who had been excommunicated, needed his army to fight
1 CONT the Pope, and refused. Charles and Beatrice were then forced to go Lyon to
1 CONT meet with the Pope.
1 CONT
1 CONT By the time they returned to Provence in 1251, open rebellion had broken out,
1 CONT spurred on by Beatrice's mother, who felt Charles had failed to respect her
1 CONT claims in Provence. However, by July 1252 Charles had managed to deafeat the
1 CONT revolt and was in the process of exercising his power as Count of Provence,
1 CONT when in November of the same year, Blanche of Castile died, and Charles and
1 CONT Beatrice had to go Paris, where Charles co-ruled France with his brother,
1 CONT Alphonse. The Pope offered Charles the Kingdom of Sicily in 1252, but Charles
1 CONT had to turn the offer down, as he was preoccupied with other affairs and he
1 CONT also did not have sufficient funds.
1 CONT
1 CONT The crusade returned in 1254. Charles and Beatrice spent Christmas in Paris
1 CONT that year, where all of Beatrice's sisters and their mother were present, it
1 CONT was noted that the other four women treated the younger Beatrice coldly, due
1 CONT to Raymond Berenguer's will.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marguerite, the Queen of France and Beatrice's sister, publicly offended her
1 CONT in 1259, by not seating her at the family table; she claimed because Beatrice
1 CONT was not a Queen like her sisters, she could not sit with them. Marguerite had
1 CONT hoped to provoke her sister in treacherous behaviour so she would have a valid
1 CONT reason to invade Provence. Beatrice "with great grief", went to Charles and he
1 CONT reportedly told her " Be at peace, for I will shortly make thee a greater
1 CONT Queen than them".
1 CONT
1 CONT When the new Pope granted Charles the Kingdom of Sicily, all he had to do was
1 CONT deafeat Manfred of Sicily. Another contender to win the throne of Sicily was
1 CONT Beatrice's nephew, Edmund Crouchback, but it soon became clear that Charles
1 CONT was the more promising candidate. In order to achieve his goal, Charles needed
1 CONT an army and Beatrice helped her husband raise one. She called on all her
1 CONT knights as well as the young men of France, and she pledged all her jewels, to
1 CONT make sure they joined her husbands army.
1 CONT
1 CONT "Beatrice, to aid him (Charles) in the gratification of her ambition, sold all
1 CONT her jewels and personal ornaments, and expended her private treasure in
1 CONT collecting round her standard, not only her own vassals, but the chivalric
1 CONT youth of France , who were attracted to her service not less by her personal
1 CONT solicitations than by her rich gifts." Angelo da Constanzo
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles went first to Rome, and Beatrice followed with the remaining army
1 CONT through the treacherous Alpine passes, during Autumn. It took them nearly six
1 CONT weeks to reach Rome, but once both Charles and Beatrice were in Rome, they
1 CONT were crowned King and Queen consort of Sicily, on 6 January 1266 .As soon as
1 CONT the coronation festivities had ended, Beatrice stayed in Rome with a small
1 CONT force to hold the city, whilst Charles rode out to the battle of Benevento.
1 CONT After her husbands victory, she chose the castle Melfi as their residence.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles and Beatrice had the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis (1248-1248 Nicosia)
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche (1250-1269), married in 1265 Robert III of Flanders (1249-1322), by
1 CONT whom she had a son, Charles who died young.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Sicily (1252-1275), married in 1273 Philip of Courtenay
1 CONT (1243-1283), titular emperor of Constantinople, by whom she had one daughter,
1 CONT Catherine I of Courtenay, titular Empress of Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II of Naples (1254-1309), Count of Anjou and of Provence, King of
1 CONT Naples, married Maria Arpad of Hungary, by whom he had issue. English Queen
1 CONT consort Philippa of Hainaut descended from their daughter, Marguerite of Anjou
1 CONT and Maine.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philippe (1256-1277), prince of Achaïea, married in 1271 Isabella of
1 CONT Villehardouin (1263-1312), princess of Achaïea and Morea
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert (1258-1265)
1 CONT
1 CONT Élisabeth (1261-1300), married to Ladislaus IV of Hungary (1262-1290). Their
1 CONT marriage was childless.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Death
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice died in 1267, a little over a year after becoming Queen. The cause of
1 CONT her death was not recorded. She was initially buried at Nocera, but Charles
1 CONT later moved her body to Aix-en-Provence were she was laid to rest with her
1 CONT father.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice, like her sisters, mother and grandmother was known for her beauty. A
1 CONT description of Beatrice said she "set men's hearts thumping and the fingers of
1 CONT troubadours to fevered twanging of lyres. Two of the balladists at the
1 CONT Provencal court were temporarily deprived of reason for love of the entrancing
1 CONT Beatrice", and like her sister Sanchia, she would eventually become a Queen
1 CONT before her death: Sanchia became 'Queen of the Romans' after the Earl of
1 CONT Cornwall was elected as King; Beatrice became Queen consort of Sicily, after
1 CONT that realm was bestowed upon Charles by the Pope.
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by
1 CONT
1 CONT Helena Angelina Doukaina Queen Consort of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT 26 February 1266–23 September 1267 Succeeded by
1 CONT
1 CONT Margaret of Burgundy
