1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Provence (1234 – 23 September 1267, Nocera) was the first wife and
1 CONT Queen of Charles I of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT The youngest daughter of Raymond Berenguer IV of Provence and Beatrice of
1 CONT Savoy, Beatrice was married in 1246 to Charles of France, Count of Anjou and
1 CONT Maine, the youngest brother of King Louis IX of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Raymond Berenguer, the Count of Provence and Forcalquier, had four daughters,
1 CONT but no sons. Of his daughters, apart from Beatrice, the eldest, Marguerite,
1 CONT had married King Louis and was Queen of France; the second, Eleanor, had
1 CONT married King Henry III of England, and the third, Sanchia, had married the
1 CONT wealthy Richard, Earl of Cornwall, brother of King Henry. Louis had originally
1 CONT been married to Marguerite by his mother, Blanche of Castile, in the belief
1 CONT that he would inherit Provence and Forcalquier; however, Raymond Berenguer
1 CONT decided to bequeath them instead to Charles, whom he viewed as having the
1 CONT least prospects.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles and Beatrice had the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis (1248-1248)
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche (1250-1269), married in 1265 Robert III of Flanders (1249-1322)
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice (1252-1275), married in 1273 Philip of Courtenay (1243-1283), titular
1 CONT emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles II of Naples (1254-1309), Count of Anjou and of Provence, King of
1 CONT Naples
1 CONT
1 CONT Philippe (1256-1277), prince of Achaïea, married in 1271 Isabella of
1 CONT Villehardouin (1263-1312), princess of Achaïea and Morea
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert (1258-1265)
1 CONT
1 CONT Élisabeth (1261-1300), married to Ladislaus IV of Hungary (1262-1290)
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice, like her sister Sanchia, would eventually become a Queen before her
1 CONT death: Sancha became 'Queen of the Romans' after the Earl of Cornwall was
1 CONT elected as King; Beatrice became Queen consort of Sicily, after that realm was
1 CONT bestowed upon Charles by the Pope.
