1 CONT \-------------------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT ANDRÁS II 1205-1235, ANDRÁS III 1290-1301
1 CONT
1 CONT ANDRÁS, son of BÉLA III King of Hungary & his first wife Agnès [Anna] de
1 CONT Châtillon-sur-Loing (1176-21 Sep 1235, bur Egrecz, Cistercian Abbey). The
1 CONT Chronicon Varadiense names "primus…dux Henricus…secundus dux Andreas…tertius
1 CONT dux Salamon et quartus…dux Stephanus" as the four sons of "rex Bela tertius
1 CONT filius Geysæ"[804]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines names (in
1 CONT order) "Haymericum et Andream…et duas reginas Constantiam de Boemia et
1 CONT Margaretam de Grecia" as children of "rex Bela de Hungaria" and his wife
1 CONT Agnes[805]. After the accession of his brother, András demanded Croatia and
1 CONT Dalmatia as an appanage but this was refused. He revolted, and by 1198
1 CONT obtained his demands and became Duke of Croatia and Dalmatia[806]. He and
1 CONT subsequent dukes acted as the king of Hungary's deputy in the kingdom of
1 CONT Croatia. "Andreas, tertii Belæ regis filius…Dalmatiæ, Croatiæ, Ramæ, Culmæque
1 CONT dux" appointed "Pharensi episcopum" by charter dated 1198, witnessed by
1 CONT "Andrea Bano, comite Macharia, comite Ioseph, comite Marco, comite Andronico
1 CONT filio Bani camerario ducis Wenceslao…"[807]. He conquered western Hum
1 CONT (Herzegovina) down to the river Neretva in 1198[808]. The Continuatio
1 CONT Admuntensis records that he was arrested in 1203, suspected of plotting to
1 CONT take over the kingdom, and imprisoned "in palacio Strigoniensi quod alio
1 CONT nomine Gran vocatur"[809]. He ousted his nephew in 1205 and succeeded as
1 CONT ANDRÁS II King of Hungary. He played an active part in the dismemberment of
1 CONT Galich-Volynia after the death of Roman Mstislavich Prince of Galich in 1205,
1 CONT Hungary and Poland eventually agreeing the division of the territories between
1 CONT them under the treaty of Spisz in 1214, although Hungary expelled Poland from
1 CONT Peremyshl and Lyubachev in 1215/1216[810]. In 1211, King András hired the
1 CONT Order of Teutonic Knights, who had been expelled back to Europe from
1 CONT Palestine, to defend the eastern frontier of Transylvania against the
1 CONT Kumans[811], but they attempted to establish their autonomy there under the
1 CONT protection of the Pope. King András expelled the Teutonic Knights in 1225[812]
1 CONT on the pretext of their having disobeyed his orders. King András set sail from
1 CONT Split for Palestine on crusade in Oct 1217, but left Acre in early 1218 having
1 CONT achieved little besides acquiring a small collection of religious relics[813].
1 CONT He returned by the land route, via Constantinople, but at the end of 1218 he
1 CONT was seized in Bulgarian territory and released only after agreeing the
1 CONT marriage of his daughter to Ivan Asen II Tsar of Bulgaria[814]. He threatened
1 CONT war with Serbia after Grand Župan Stefan was crowned King of Serbia by the
1 CONT papal legate in 1217, claiming that he alone had the right to this title, but
1 CONT did not carry out the threat[815]. King András's abuses caused the Hungarian
1 CONT nobles to rebel in 1222 and forced him to issue the Golden Bull, a charter
1 CONT defining the rights of the nobility and restricting the king's right to
1 CONT appoint foreigners to office without the consent of the Council[816], a reform
1 CONT forced by the rebellion of the lower nobility in Croatia according to
1 CONT Goldstein[817]. In 1227, Bortz Khan of the Kumans swore allegiance to the king
1 CONT of Hungary after ordering the baptism of his people, rex Cumaniæ being added
1 CONT to the titles of the Hungarian king soon after[818]. King András attacked
1 CONT north-west Bulgaria in 1232 and recaptured Beograd and Braničevo which he had
1 CONT been forced to cede as part of the dowry of his daughter Maria. He crossed the
1 CONT Danube into Wallachia where the Hungarians created a Banate in the Severin
1 CONT region[819]. The Chronicon Dubnicense records the death in 1235 of "Andreas
1 CONT filius Bele" and his burial "in monasterio de Egrus"[820]. The Chronicon
1 CONT Zagrabiense records the death "XI Kal Oct" in 1235 of "rex Andreas filius
1 CONT regis Belæ III" and his burial "in monasterio suo Egres"[821]. The Chronicle
1 CONT of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death in 1235 of "Andreas rex
1 CONT Hungarie" and his burial "in civitate Waradino"[822].
1 CONT
1 CONT m firstly (before 1203) GERTRUD von Andechs-Merano, daughter of BERTHOLD III
1 CONT Duke of Merano, Marchese of Istria, Graf von Andechs & his wife Agnes von
1 CONT Wettin (-murdered 8 Sep 1213). The Continuatio Admuntensis refers to "filiam
1 CONT Perhtoldi ducis Meranie" as wife of "Andream fratrem suum [=rex Heinricus
1 CONT Ungarorum]", recording that she was deprived of all her goods and sent back
1 CONT home when her husband was arrested in 1203, but recalled after the death of
1 CONT King Imre in 1204[823]. She was killed by a conspiracy of nobles shocked by
1 CONT the life of luxury she led and favouritism she showed to her German relatives,
1 CONT recounted in Józsel Katona's historical drama Bánk bán[824]. The Chronicon
1 CONT Dubnicense records that "Gerdrudis de Alamana" wife of "Andreas filius Bele"
1 CONT was killed by "Bankbanus de genere Bor oriundus" and buried "in monasterio
1 CONT griseorum monachorum de Pelys"[825]. The Continuatio Prædictorum
1 CONT Vindobonensium records that "Gerdrudis regina Ungarie" was killed "campestri
1 CONT tentorio IV Kal Oct 1213, eo quot fratri suo carnali patriarche Aquilegensi
1 CONT uxorem Bantzi procaverat, qui teutonice Prenger vocatur"[826]. The necrology
1 CONT of Diessen records the death "IV Kal Oct" of "Gerdrudis regina Ungarie ab
1 CONT hominibus illius terre interfecta…filia Berhtoldi ducis Meranie"[827]. The De
1 CONT Fundatoribus Monasterii Diessenses records that "Gerdrudis regina
1 CONT Ungarie…filia Pertoldi quondam ducis Meranie" was killed "IV Kal Oct" in 1200,
1 CONT although the year is incorrect[828].
1 CONT
1 CONT m secondly (Feb 1215) YOLANDE de Courtenay, daughter of PIERRE II de Courtenay
1 CONT Seigneur de Courtenay, Comte de Nevers, d’Auxerre et de Tonnerre, Marquis de
1 CONT Namur [later Latin Emperor of Constantinople] & his wife Yolande de Flandre
1 CONT ([1200]-1233, bur Egrecz Abbey). William of Tyre (Continuator) specifies that
1 CONT the queen of Hungary (unnamed) was the sister of the Latin Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople[829]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines names "unam
1 CONT filiarum eius [Namucensis comitis Petri] Hyolenz" as the wife of "Andreas rex
1 CONT Ungarie"[830]. Her marriage was arranged by her uncle, Henri Latin Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople, to obtain Hungarian support for his new ally Boril Tsar of
1 CONT Bulgaria[831]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death
1 CONT in 1233 of "regina Hoilanz de Hungaria" and her burial "in abbatia de
1 CONT Egis"[832].
1 CONT
1 CONT m thirdly (Székesfehérvár 14 May 1234) BEATRICE d'Este, daughter of
1 CONT ALDOBRANDINO I d'Este Marchese di Ancona & his wife --- (1215-1245 before 8
1 CONT May, bur Gemmola). Her origin is deduced from the Cronica Fratris Salimbene de
1 CONT Adam which refers to "domnus Stephanus filius regis Hungarie" as "nepos
1 CONT marchionis Hestensis"[833]. The Chronica of Rolandino Patavino records the
1 CONT marriage in 1235 of "dompna Beatrix olim filia marchionis Aldrevandini" and
1 CONT "regem Ungarie"[834]. The Annales S. Iustinæ Patavino record that "Beatrix
1 CONT filia quondam Aldrevandini marchionis Estensis" married "Andree regi Ungarie"
1 CONT in 1235, despite opposition from "filiis regis Bele…et Colomanno"[835]. A
1 CONT later passage in the same source records that Beatrix left Hungary "gravida"
1 CONT after her husband died, later gave birth "in Alemaniam" to "filium…Stephanum",
1 CONT and then returned with her child "ad paternam domum"[836].
1 CONT
1 CONT King András II & his first wife had five children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. MÁRIA ([1204]-Trnovo Autumn 1237). The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-
1 CONT Fontaines refers to the first wife of "Alsannus rex" as "soror Bele regis
1 CONT Hungarie et…sancta Elizabeth" but does not name her[837]. Ephræmius names
1 CONT "Maria de genus de populo Pæoanum" as the wife of "Asanes"[838]. Her father
1 CONT was forced to agree her marriage to effect his release from Bulgaria, where he
1 CONT had been captured on his return from Crusade in late 1218. The Historia
1 CONT Salonitanorum of Thomas Archdeacon of Split records that András II King of
1 CONT Hungary was detained in Bulgaria by "Oxano Bulgarorum rege" until he agreed
1 CONT the marriage of "suam filiam"[839]. Her dowry included the cities of Beograd
1 CONT and Braničevo[840]. She converted to Roman Catholicism[841]. Georgius
1 CONT Akropolites records the death of "Asano…uxorem Ungaram" at "citissime
1 CONT Trinobum" while her husband was besieging "Tzuruli castrum"[842]. m (Jan 1221)
1 CONT as his second wife, IVAN ASEN II Tsar of the Bulgarians, son of IVAN ASEN I
1 CONT "Stari/the Old" or "Belgun/the Bulgar" Tsar of the Bulgarians & his [first or
1 CONT second wife] --- ([1190]-Jun 1241).
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. BÉLA (Nov 1206-3 May 1270). The Chronicon Dubnicense names "Belam,
1 CONT Colomannum Andream et beatam Elyzabeth" as the children of "Andreas filius
1 CONT Bele" and his wife "domina Gerdrudis de Alemania"[843]. The Gesta Hungarorum
1 CONT names "Bela filius eius" when recording that he succeeded his father[844]. He
1 CONT succeeded his father in 1235 as BÉLA IV King of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT \- see below.
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. ELISABETH (Bratislava 1207-Marburg 10 Nov 1231, bur Marburg
1 CONT Elisabethenkirche). The Chronicon Dubnicense names "Belam, Colomannum Andream
1 CONT et beatam Elyzabeth" as the children of "Andreas filius Bele" and his wife
1 CONT "domina Gerdrudis de Alemania"[845]. The Altahenses Annales record that "Bela
1 CONT rex Ungarie" was brother of "sancte Elisabeth"[846]. She fell under the strong
1 CONT influence of her confessor, the Papal inquisitor Konrad von Marburg, and
1 CONT completely rejected secular life. After her husband's death, she was
1 CONT apparently evicted from Wartburg Castle by her brother-in-law. She settled in
1 CONT Marburg where she founded a Franciscan hospital for the poor and sick. She
1 CONT embraced a regime of extreme fasting, dressed in a grey penitential tunic
1 CONT supposedly sent to her by St Francis of Assisi. Konrad von Marburg built a
1 CONT finger-shaped church around her grave in her hospital chapel. Her cult became
1 CONT the object of intense political rivalry between the Teutonic Knights, allied
1 CONT with the Landgraf of Thuringia, and the Archbishop of Mainz. This resulted in
1 CONT her rapid canonisation by Pope Gregory IX in 1235[847]. The Chronicle of
1 CONT Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death in "XIII Kal Dec 1232" of
1 CONT "Elizabeth domna sancta…Ludovici Thuringie lantgravii" and her burial "apud
1 CONT hospitale de Maerbuch quod ipsa construxit"[848]. Her feast-day is 19
1 CONT Nov[849]. m (1221) LUDWIG IV "der Heilige" Landgraf of Thuringia, son of
1 CONT HERMANN I Landgraf of Thuringia, Pfalzgraf von Sachsen & his second wife
1 CONT Sophie of Bavaria [Wittelsbach] (28 Oct 1200-Otranto 11 Sep 1227).
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. KÁLMÁN (1208-killed in battle Sajó River 11 Apr 1241, bur Dominican church
1 CONT of St Mary Magdalene Čazma). The Chronicon Dubnicense names "Belam, Colomannum
1 CONT Andream et beatam Elyzabeth" as the children of "Andreas filius Bele" and his
1 CONT wife "domina Gerdrudis de Alemania"[850]. The Historia Salonitanorum of Thomas
1 CONT Archdeacon of Split records that "Colomannus filius Andree regis, dux
1 CONT Sclavonie" came to Dalmatia but "was…still quite young and nor did he do
1 CONT anything which would be thought worth recording", dated to [1229] from the
1 CONT context[851]. His father installed him as Prince of Galich after the 1214
1 CONT treaty of Spisz under which Hungary and Poland split Galich between them. He
1 CONT was arrested in 1216 and sent back to Hungary by Mstislav Mstislavich Prince
1 CONT of Novgorod. He re-established himself in Galich in 1219 after expelling
1 CONT Mstislav, but the latter expelled him again in 1221[852]. Kálmán was the
1 CONT Hungarian commander of the crusading forces in Bosnia in 1235. Duke of
1 CONT Slavonia, as shown by the charter dated 20 Jul 1244 (after Kálmán´s death)
1 CONT under which his brother Béla IV King of Hungary confirmed the donation by
1 CONT "fratris sui Colomani ducis Slavoniæ" to the church in Bosnia[853]. He was
1 CONT defeated and killed by the Mongols at the battle of Sajó River[854]. The
1 CONT Historia Salonitanorum of Thomas Archdeacon of Split records the death of
1 CONT "Colomannus rex" and his burial "in loco fratrum predicatorum apud Cesnam" in
1 CONT a hidden crypt to prevent his body being desecrated by the Tatars[855]. m
1 CONT (1214) SALOMEA of Poland, daughter of LESZKO I "Bialy/the White" Prince of
1 CONT Sandomir and Krakow & his wife Gremislava Ingvarovna of Luck and Dorogobuz
1 CONT [Rurikid] ([1211/12]-10 Nov 1268). The Annales Capituli Cracoviensis record
1 CONT the death "1269 IV Id Nov" of "Salomea regina relicta Colomanni regis
1 CONT Hungarorum, germana princeps Bolezlai ducis Cracovie et Sandomirie"[856]. The
1 CONT Annales Cracovienses Compilati clarify that she was "Salomena regina Galicie"
1 CONT and "soror ordinis Minorem"[857]. She became a nun after the death of her
1 CONT husband. "Bolezlaus…Dux Cracovie et Sudomirie" renewed the privileges of Busk
1 CONT monastery granted by "Principis domini Lestkonis quondam…Polonorum Ducis,
1 CONT patris nostri", at the request of "germane nostre…sororis Salomee, quondam
1 CONT Regine et consortis…Hungarorum Regis Colommani", by charter dated 1252[858].
1 CONT "Bolezlaus…Cracouie et Sandomirie dux" conferred privileges on the church of
1 CONT Krakow, for the soul of "patris nostri clare memorie Cracouie et Sandomirie
1 CONT ducis Leztconis" and for "nostre genitricis ducisse Grimizlaue et…consortis
1 CONT nostre Cungundis", at the request of "germane nostre sororis…Salomee, quondam
1 CONT Galacie regine", by charter dated 18 May 1255[859].
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. ANDRÁS ([1210/12]-1234). The Chronicon Dubnicense names "Belam, Colomannum
1 CONT Andream et beatam Elyzabeth" as the children of "Andreas filius Bele" and his
1 CONT wife "domina Gerdrudis de Alemania"[860]. He replaced his father-in-law as
1 CONT Prince of Galich in 1226, until 1234. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-
1 CONT Fontaines records the death in 1234 of "dux Andreas…regis Andree filius"[861].
1 CONT Betrothed ([27 Jan 1216/25 Jan 1217], contract broken 1219) to ZABEL of
1 CONT Armenia, daughter of LEO I King of Armenia [Rupenid] & his second wife Sibylle
1 CONT of Cyprus ([1216]-Ked 23 Jan 1252, bur Trazarg). Smbat Sparapet's Chronicle
1 CONT records that "the king of Hungary Andre…gave his son as a son-in-law to King
1 CONT Lewon and [this son] would inherit Lewon's throne", during a visit to Tarsus
1 CONT in [27 Jan 1216/25 Jan 1217][862]. It is not certain that András was the son
1 CONT who was betrothed to Zabel. However, the Hungarian king is unlikely to have
1 CONT betrothed his oldest son to this rather remote princess, especially with the
1 CONT prospect of his inheriting both thrones, while King András's second son Kálmán
1 CONT was already married at that date (assuming his marriage date is correct as
1 CONT stated above). Smbat Sparapet's Chronicle records that "the son of the
1 CONT Hungarian king was in the vicinity and came to become [Lewon's] son-in-law"
1 CONT while the king was dying, and that King Lewon "ordered his princes to
1 CONT implement the oaths they had sworn to him", in [26 Jan 1219/25 Jan 1220][863],
1 CONT but the proposed marriage must have been abandoned as soon as the king died as
1 CONT there no further mention of it in the Chronicle. m (1221) IELENA Mstislavna,
1 CONT daughter of MSTISLAV Mstislavich "Udaloi" ex-Prince of Novgorod, Prince of
1 CONT Galich & his wife --- Pss of the Kumans. Baumgarten names the wife of András
1 CONT and gives her origin citing sources in support[864]. Prince András & his wife
1 CONT had [one child]:
1 CONT
1 CONT a) [ERSZEBET (-[1295/96]). She and her husband are named in Europäische
1 CONT Stammtafeln[865], but the source on which this is based has not been
1 CONT identified. According to another table in Europäische Stammtafeln[866], the
1 CONT wife of Moys de Dáró was Ielisaveta Rostislavna of Galich, widow firstly of
1 CONT Mihail II Asen Tsar of the Bulgarians and secondly of Koloman II Tsar of the
1 CONT Bulgarians, daughter of Rostislav Mikhailovich ex-Grand Prince of Kiev, ex-
1 CONT Prince of Galich, Ban of Mačva & his wife Anna of Hungary. She became a nun as
1 CONT SABINA. m MOYS de Dáró, Judge of the Kumans (-end 1280). Palatine of Hungary,
1 CONT Gespan of Sopron.]
1 CONT
1 CONT i) ERSZEBET de Dáró. m as his second wife, MIKLOS Medgyesi, Voivoide of
1 CONT Transylvania, son of MÓRICZ Medgyesi (-before 1331).
1 CONT
1 CONT King András II & his second wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. IOLANDA ([1215]-Huesca 12 Oct 1251). The Crónica de San Juan de la Peña
1 CONT records the second marriage of Jaime I King of Aragon and "la filla del Rey de
1 CONT Vngria…Ardeura la qual depues huuo nombre Violant nieta del Emperador de
1 CONT Constantin noble"[867]. She was known as VIOLANT in Catalonia. The Anales
1 CONT Toledanos record the death “IV Non Oct” in 1251 of “Dña Yoles, Regina
1 CONT Aragonum”[868]. The Chronicle of the Hôtel de Ville de Montpellier records the
1 CONT death in 1251 "D. Yoles regina Aragoniæ"[869]. The Thalamus de Montpellier
1 CONT records the death in Sep 1251 at Lérida of "la dona Yoles regina dAragon
1 CONT molher del rei Jacme"[870]. m (Barcelona 8 Sep 1235) as his second wife, don
1 CONT JAIME I "el Conquistador" King of Aragon, Conde de Barcelona, son of don PEDRO
1 CONT II King of Aragon & his wife Marie de Montpellier (Montpellier 1 Feb
1 CONT 1208-Valencia 27 Jul 1276, bur Poblet, monastery of Nuestra Señora).
1 CONT
1 CONT King András II & his third wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. ISTVÁN (posthumously Swabia 1236-Venice 1271 shortly after 10 Apr). The
1 CONT Annales S. Iustinæ Patavino record that "Beatrix regina" left Hungary
1 CONT "gravida" after her husband died and later gave birth "in Alemaniam" to
1 CONT "filium…Stephanum"[871]. He was brought up in Italy. Duke of Slavonia.
1 CONT Patrician of Venice. The Cronica Fratris Salimbene de Adam records that
1 CONT "domnus Stephanus filius regis Hungarie" went to Venice after the death of her
1 CONT first wife and lived and died there "in altissima paupertate et summa
1 CONT miseria"[872]. m firstly (1263) as her second husband, ELISABETTA [Caterina]
1 CONT Traversari, widow of TOMASO de Foliano, legitimated daughter of PAOLO
1 CONT Traversari Patrician of Ravenna & his mistress --- (-[1264], bur Ravenna St
1 CONT Vitalis). The Annales S. Iustinæ Patavino record the marriage in 1262 of
1 CONT "Stephanus…Andree regis Ungarie et nobilis regine Beatricis generosa propago"
1 CONT and "Traversarium filiam Guielmi filii Pauli Traversarii, civis Ravennatis
1 CONT nobilissimi"[873]. Giovanni di Musso´s Chronicon Placentinum records that
1 CONT "Andreæ Regi Hungariæ…filium…Stephanum" married "neptem Pauli Traversarii de
1 CONT Ravenna"[874]. The Cronica Fratris Salimbene de Adam refers to "Paulus
1 CONT Traversarius…filium habuit…filia non legitime nata", her legitimation by Pope
1 CONT Innocent IV, her first marriage to "domno Thomasio de Foliano…de Regio", her
1 CONT second marriage to "domnus Stephanus filius regis Hungarie", and her death and
1 CONT burial in "ecclesia sancti Vitalis in Urtien apud Ravennam"[875]. The primary
1 CONT source which confirms her name has not so far been identified. m secondly
1 CONT TOMASINA Morosini, daughter of MICHELE Sbarra Morosini Patrician of Venice &
1 CONT his wife --- (-end 1300). The Chronicon Dubnicense records that "Stephanus"
1 CONT fled Ravenna for Venice where he married "vir quidam civis Venetensis
1 CONT civitatis…filiam"[876]. Giovanni di Musso´s Chronicon Placentinum records that
1 CONT "Andreæ Regi Hungariæ…filium…Stephanum" married secondly "Thomaxinam sororem
1 CONT Albertini Moresini"[877]. Duke István & his first wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT a) [ISTVÁN] (1264-young). The Cronica Fratris Salimbene de Adam refers to, but
1 CONT does not name, the son of "domnus Stephanus filius regis Hungarie" & his first
1 CONT wife who died young[878].
1 CONT
1 CONT Duke István & his second wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT b) ANDRÁS (Venice [1265/70]-Ofen 14 Jan 1301, bur Ofen Minoritenkirche). The
1 CONT Chronicon Dubnicense names "Andream" as the son of "Stephanus" and his wife
1 CONT "vir quidam civis Venetensis civitatis…filiam"[879]. He was brought up in
1 CONT Venice. On the death of King László IV in 1290, András was smuggled out of
1 CONT Venice disguised as a friar by Ladomer Archbishop of Esztergom and brought to
1 CONT Hungary[880]. He was elected to succeed in 1290 by the Hungarian nobles as
1 CONT ANDRÁS III "the Venetian" King of Hungary, crowned by the Archbishop. The Pope
1 CONT favoured the rival candidacy of Charles Martel d'Anjou, nephew of the previous
1 CONT monarch, claiming the right to name the Hungarian monarch for himself, on the
1 CONT basis that the first king István I had received his crown from the Pope[881].
1 CONT Opposition to King András was mainly centred in Croatia, although he was
1 CONT generally accepted as monarch after the death in 1295 of Charles Martel. He
1 CONT was able to restore some control over the Hungarian nobility, who had asserted
1 CONT their authority during the preceding reign, but also introduced constitutional
1 CONT reforms including a permanent Council whose consent was required for major
1 CONT decisions, although this was not implemented in practice[882]. He named his
1 CONT maternal uncle heir in 1299, triggering another revolt, but was succeeded by
1 CONT Charles Robert d'Anjou, son of Charles Martel[883]. Betrothed (6 Jun 1286) to
1 CONT CLARA EUPHEMIA von Görz, daughter of ALBRECHT [II] Graf von Görz & his first
1 CONT wife Euphemia von Glogau [Piast]. The marriage contract between "Dominum
1 CONT Albertum comitem Goricie…filiam suam dominam Claram" and "domino Andrea…duce
1 CONT Sclavonie nepote olim…domini Andree regis Hungarie" is dated 6 Jun 1286, and
1 CONT names "dominum Albertinum Mauroceno de Venecia…avunculus eiusdem domini
1 CONT ducis"[884]. m firstly ([19 Aug/24 Sep] 1290) FENENNA of Kujavia, daughter of
1 CONT ZIEMOMYSŁ Prince of Kujavia [Piast] & his wife Salome von Pommerellen
1 CONT ([1276]-[1295]). The primary source which confirms her name, parentage and
1 CONT marriage has not so far been identified. m secondly (Vienna 13 Feb 1296) AGNES
1 CONT von Habsburg, daughter of ALBRECHT I Duke of Austria [later King of Germany] &
1 CONT his wife Elisabeth von Görz-Tirol (18 May 1281-Königsfelden 10 Jun 1364, bur
1 CONT Königsfelden). Her parentage is confirmed by the necrology of Königsfelden
1 CONT which records the death "XIX Kal Feb" of "Andreas rex Ungarie…conthoralis
1 CONT domine Agnetis, Alberti regis Romanorum filia et domine Elizabeth…"[885].
1 CONT After the death of her husband, she returned to Austria. She founded Kloster
1 CONT Königsfelden with her mother, in memory of her murdered father, and lived
1 CONT there[886]. The mid-14th century Königsfelden chronicle depicts Agnes as a
1 CONT humble and pious individual. On the other hand, according to the 16th century
1 CONT Chronicon helveticum of Aegidius Tschudi, she avenged her father's murder by
1 CONT ordering the execution and expulsion of 1000 people (families and followers of
1 CONT his murderers), but it appears this was to a large extent based on Swiss anti-
1 CONT Habsburg propaganda[887]. It appears that Agnes acted as adviser to her
1 CONT brothers the Dukes of Austria and was politically active, in particular
1 CONT settling a conflict between Duke Albrecht II and the Swiss confederation[888].
1 CONT The necrology of Feldbach records the death "IV Id Jun" of "Agnes regina
1 CONT Ungario"[889]. The necrology of Wettingen records the death "IV Id 1364" of
1 CONT "Agnes quondam regina Ungarie, fundatrix monasterii in Campo Regis, inclite
1 CONT mater pauperum et religiosorum, celebratur in Künigsfelden"[890]. King András
1 CONT III & his first wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT i) ELISABETH (1292-1336). She was taken to Austria by her stepmother after the
1 CONT death of her father. Honemann refers to her betrothal to Wenzel of
1 CONT Bohemia[891]. She became a nun at the Dominican convent of Töß near Winterthur
1 CONT in 1308. The Tösser Schwesterbuch (lives of the nuns at Töß) suggests that
1 CONT Elisabeth was mistreated by her stepmother but this is not corroborated by
1 CONT other sources[892]. Her gravestone records her death in 1336 and that she
1 CONT lived in Töß for twenty-eight years[893]. According to the chronicle of Töß,
1 CONT she died 6 May 1338[894]. Betrothed to WENZEL of Bohemia, son of WENZEL II
1 CONT King of Bohemia & his first wife Guta of Austria [Habsburg] (6 Oct
1 CONT 1289-murdered Olmütz 4 Aug 1306, bur Olmütz, transferred to Prague Königsaal).
1 CONT He was chosen as King of Hungary in 1301 by part of the Hungarian nobility and
1 CONT crowned LÁSZLÓ V King of Hungary. He succeeded his father in 1305 as WENZEL
1 CONT III King of Bohemia.
1 CONT
1 CONT István Duke of Slavonia had two illegitimate children, shown in Europäische
1 CONT Stammtafeln[895] although the source on which this is based has not so far
1 CONT been identified:
1 CONT
1 CONT c) son. 1271.
1 CONT
1 CONT d) son. 1271.
