1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew II the Jerosolimitan (Hungarian: Jeruzsálemi II András/Endre, Croatian:
1 CONT Andrija I. Slovak: Ondrej) (c. 1177 – 21 September, 1235), King of
1 CONT Hungary[1](1205-1235). He was the younger son of King Béla III of Hungary, who
1 CONT invested him with the government of the Principality of Halych. However, the
1 CONT boyars of Halych rebelled against his rule and expelled the Hungarian troops.
1 CONT Following their father's death, Andrew continuously conspired against his
1 CONT brother, King Emeric of Hungary who had to grant him the government of Croatia
1 CONT and Dalmatia. When his brother and his infant son died, Andrew ascended the
1 CONT throne and started to grant royal domains to his partisans. He participated in
1 CONT the Fifth Crusade but he could not achieve any major military success. He was
1 CONT obliged to issue the Golden Bull confirming the privileges of the noblemen of
1 CONT Hungary and later he was also obliged to confirm the special privileges of the
1 CONT clergy. During his long reign, he had several quarrels with his sons.
1 CONT
