1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] The turbulent duke
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew was the second son of King Béla III and his first wife, Agnes of
1 CONT Antioch. As younger son, Andrew had no hope to inherite the Kingdom of Hungary
1 CONT from his father who wanted to ensure the inheritance of his elder son, Emeric
1 CONT and had him crowned already in 1182.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nevertheless, when Prince Volodymyr II of Halych, who had been expelled from
1 CONT his country by his subjects, fled to Hungary seeking for assistance in 1188,
1 CONT King Béla III had him arrested and occupied his principality and he invested
1 CONT Andrew with Halych. The child Andrew's rule in Halych must have been only
1 CONT nominal; he even did not visit his principality. Although, the young prince's
1 CONT troops could get the mastery in 1189 when the boyars of Halych rose against
1 CONT his rule, but shortly afterwards Prince Volodymyr II managed to escape from
1 CONT his captivity and he expelled the Hungarian troops from Halych.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 23 April 1196, King Béla III died and he left the Kingdom of Hungary
1 CONT unportioned to his eldest son, Emeric, while Andrew inherited a large amount
1 CONT of money in order to fulfill his father's Crusader oath. However, Andrew used
1 CONT the money to recruit followers among the barons and also sought the assistance
1 CONT of Leopold V, Duke of Austria. In December 1197, Andrew's troops defeated King
1 CONT Emeric's armies in a battle near to Macsek in December 1197. Following
1 CONT Andrew's victory, the king was obliged to transfer the government of the
1 CONT Duchies of Croatia and Dalmatia to Andrew.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the beginning of 1198, Pope Innocent III requested Andrew to fulfill his
1 CONT father's last will and lead a Crusade to the Holy Land. However, instead of a
1 CONT Crusade, Andrew made a campaign against the neighbouring provinces and
1 CONT occupied Zahumlje and Rama. Andrew also went on conspiring with some prelates
1 CONT against his brother, but King Emeric was informed on Andrew's plans and he
1 CONT personally arrested Bishop Boleszlo of Vác, one of Andrew's main supporters,
1 CONT and he also deprived his brother's followers (e.g., Palatine Mog) of their
1 CONT dignities. In the summer of 1199, King Emeric defeated Andrew in the Battle of
1 CONT Rád and Andrew had to fleed to Austria. Finally, the two brothers made peace
1 CONT with the mediation of the Papal Legate Gregory, and the king granted again the
1 CONT government of Croatia and Dalmatia to his brother.
1 CONT
1 CONT Around 1200, Andrew married Gertrude, a daughter of Berthold IV, Duke of
1 CONT Merania. It was probably his wife who persuaded him to conspire against his
1 CONT brother again, but when King Emeric, who had realised that Andrew's troops
1 CONT outnumbered his armies, went unarmed, wearing only the crown and the sceptre,
1 CONT to Andrew's camp near Varasd, Andrew surrendered voluntarily on the spur of
1 CONT the scene. The king had his brother arrested, but Andrew managed to escape
1 CONT shortly afterwards.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nevertheless, the king become more and more ill, and wanted to secure the
1 CONT ascension of his young son, Ladislaus, who had been crowned on 26 August 1204.
1 CONT Shortly afterwards, the king reconciled with Andrew whom he appointed to
1 CONT govern the kingdom during his son's minority. After his brother's death on 30
1 CONT September/November 1204, Andrew took over the government of the kingdom as his
1 CONT nephew's tutor and he also seized the money his brother had deposited on
1 CONT behalf of the child Ladislaus. The Dowager Queen Constance was anxious about
1 CONT her son's life and she escaped with King Ladislaus to the court of Leopold VI,
1 CONT Duke of Austria. Andrew made preparations for a war against Austria, but the
1 CONT child king died on 7 May 1205, thus Andrew inherited the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Novæ institutiones
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew was crowned by Archbishop John of Kalocsa on 29 May 1205 in
1 CONT Székesfehérvár, but before the coronation, he had to take an oath. Andrew made
1 CONT a radical alteration in the internal policy followed by his predecessors and
1 CONT he began to bestow the royal estates to his partisans. He called this new
1 CONT policy novæ institutiones in his deeds, and he declared that "Nothing can set
1 CONT bounds to generosity of the Royal Majesty, and the best measure of grants, for
1 CONT a monarch, is immeasurableness". He gave away everything - money, villages,
1 CONT domains, whole counties - to the utter impoverishment of the treasury. Andrew
1 CONT was generous primarily with his wife's German relatives and followers, which
1 CONT caused discontent among his subjects.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Struggles for Halych
1 CONT
1 CONT During the first years of his reign, Andrew was occupied with the discords
1 CONT within the Principality of Halych. In 1205, he led his armies to the
1 CONT principality to ensure the rule of the child Prince Danylo. Following his
1 CONT campaign, he adopted the title of "King of Galicia and Lodomeria" referring to
1 CONT his supremacy over the two neighbouring principalities. In the beginning of
1 CONT the next year, the child Danylo was again expelled from Halych but Andrew
1 CONT denied to give assistance to him because the child prince's opponent, Prince
1 CONT Volodymyr III Igorevych had bribed him. Nevertheless, in the same year, he
1 CONT made a campaign in Halych and gave assistance to Prince Roman Igorevych to
1 CONT acquire the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1208, taking advantage of the quarrel between Prince Roman Igorevych and
1 CONT his boyars, Andrew occupied Halych and appointed a regent to govern the
1 CONT principality in his name, but Prince Volodymyr III Igorevych managed to
1 CONT reconquer his principality already in the following year.
1 CONT
1 CONT A group of the aristocrats of his court, scandalised by Andrew's generosity
1 CONT towards his wife's relatives and followers, planned to offer the throne to his
1 CONT cousins, who had been living in the court of the Emperor Theodore I Lascaris
1 CONT of Nicea, but their envoy was arrested and Andrew could overcome the
1 CONT conspiracy. In 1211, he granted the Burzenland to the Teutonic Knights in
1 CONT order to ensure the security of the southeastern borders of his kingdom
1 CONT against the Cumans. However, the Teutonic Knights began to establish a country
1 CONT independent of the King of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1211, Andrew provided military assistance to Prince Danylo to reoccupy
1 CONT Halych. Moreover, in the following year, Andrew lead his armies personally to
1 CONT Halych to repulse the attack of Prince Mstilav of Peresopnytsia against Prince
1 CONT Danylo. Shortly afterwards, Prince Danylo, was obliged to leave his country
1 CONT and he sought again Andrew's assistance. Andrew left for his campaign in the
1 CONT summer 1213 when he was informed that a group of conspirators had murdered his
1 CONT queen on 28 September and he had to return.
1 CONT
1 CONT Following his return, he ordered the execution only the leader of the
1 CONT conspirators and he forgave the other members of the group, which resulted in
1 CONT the emerging antipaty of his son, Béla. Nevertheless, in 1214, Andrew had his
1 CONT son crowned.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the summer of 1214, Andrew had a meeting with Grand Duke Leszek I of Poland
1 CONT and they agreed that they would divide the Principality of Halych between
1 CONT Hungary and Poland. Their allied troops occupied the neighbouring principality
1 CONT which was granted to Andrew's younger son, Coloman. However, Andrew denied to
1 CONT transfer the agreed territories to Duke Leszek I who made an alliance with
1 CONT Prince Mstilav of Novgorod and they drove away Andrew's troops from the
1 CONT principality.
1 CONT
1 CONT Shortly afterwards, Andrew made an alliance again with Leszek I and they
1 CONT occupied Halych where again Andrew's son was appointed to prince.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] The Fifth Crusade
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime, Andrew began to deal with the problems of the southern
1 CONT borders of his kingdom. In 1214, the Hungarian troops annexed Belgrade and
1 CONT Braničevo from the Bulgarian Empire.
1 CONT
1 CONT In February 1215, Andrew married Yolanda, the niece of Henry I, the Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople. When the Emperor Henry I died on 11 July 1216, Andrew was
1 CONT planning to acquire the imperial throne, but the barons of the Latin Empire
1 CONT proclaimed his father-in-law, Peter of Courtenay their emperor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nevertheles, Andrew decided to fulfill his father's oath and made preparations
1 CONT for a Crusade. He agreed with the Republic of Venice to undertake the delivery
1 CONT of his troops to the Holy Land, in exchange he renounced the supremacy over
1 CONT Zára on behalf of the Republic. Andrew and his troops embarked on 23 August
1 CONT 1217 in Spalato. They landed on 9 October on Cyprus from where they sailed to
1 CONT Acre. The well-mounted army defeated sultan Al-Adil I ( Sultan of Egypt ) in
1 CONT Bethsaida at Jordan River on November 10. Muslim forces retreated in their
1 CONT fortress and towns. The catapults and trebuchets didn't arrived on time, so he
1 CONT had fruitless assaults on the fortresses of the Lebanon and on Mount Tabor.
1 CONT Afterwards, Andrew spent his time collecting alleged relics.
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew set home on (January 18, 1218). On the way home, he negotiated with
1 CONT King Levon I of Armenia, the Emperor Theodore I Laskaris of Nicaea and Tsar
1 CONT Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria and arranged several marriage contracts between his
1 CONT children and the courts he visited. When he was staying in Nicaea, his
1 CONT cousins, who had been living there, made an unsuccessful attempt to take his
1 CONT life.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] The Golden Bull and the Diploma Andreanum
1 CONT
1 CONT On his return, he found its kingdom in anarchy. While he had been away in the
1 CONT Holy Land, even his regent, Archbishop John of Esztergom had been obliged to
1 CONT leave the country and his treasury had been exhausted. He tried to collect
1 CONT money by using new instruments, such as introducing new taxes, undermining the
1 CONT currency and leasing his income to Jews and Muslims which increased his
1 CONT unpopularity.
1 CONT
1 CONT His foreign policy was also a total failure. In August 1219, his younger son,
1 CONT Coloman, who had been crowned King of Halych, was expelled from his kingdom by
1 CONT Prince Mstilav of Novgorod. Andrew had to make peace with the Prince of
1 CONT Novgorod and he also engaged his youngest son, Andrew with one of his
1 CONT opponent's daughter.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1220, Andrew entrusted the government of Slavonia, Dalmatia and Croatia to
1 CONT his son, Béla. Andrew also enforced Béla to separate from his wife.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the beginning of 1222, the discontent serviens (nobles) came to Andrew's
1 CONT court in large numbers, and they persuaded the king to issue the Golden Bull
1 CONT which confirmed their privileges, including the right to disobey the King if
1 CONT he acted not in line with the provisions of the Golden Bull (ius resistendi).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1223, the junior King Béla IV took back his wife and escaped to Austria
1 CONT fearing of Andrew's anger. Finally, Andrew made an agreement with his son with
1 CONT the mediation of Pope Honorius III and the junior king took over again the
1 CONT government of Slavonia, Dalmatia and Croatia. On 6 June 1224 Andrew made a
1 CONT peace with Duke Leopold VI of Austria.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1224, Andrew issued the Diploma Andreanum which unified and ensured the
1 CONT special privileges of the Transylvanian Saxons. It's considered the oldest
1 CONT Autonomy law in the world. In the same year, Andrew expelled the Teutonic
1 CONT Knights from Transylvania because they had ignored his overlordship.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Discords with his son
1 CONT
1 CONT The junior King Béla IV started, with the authorization of Pope Honorius III,
1 CONT to take back the royal domains in his provinces that Andrew had granted to his
1 CONT partisans during the first half of his reign. Andrew opposed his son's policy
1 CONT and he entrusted Béla with the government of Transylvania while his younger
1 CONT son, Coloman became the governor of Béla's former provinces.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the second half of 1226, Andrew lead his armies to Halych on the request of
1 CONT his youngest son, Andrew. Although, Prince Mstilav defeated the royal armies,
1 CONT but finally he agreed to cede the government of the principality to the
1 CONT Hungarian prince.
1 CONT
1 CONT During 1228, Andrew's two sons started again to take back the former royal
1 CONT domains in their provinces, and they persuaded Andrew to confiscate the
1 CONT estates of the barons who had taken part in the conspiracy against their
1 CONT mother. In 1229, Prince Danylo of Halych expelled Andrew's youngest son from
1 CONT his principality, while Frederick II, Duke of Austria started to attack the
1 CONT western borders of the kingdom in 1230.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] The Agreement of Bereg
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew, in contrast with the decisions of the Fourth Council of the Lateran,
1 CONT often employed Jews and Muslims in the royal household. Therefore, Pope
1 CONT Gregory IX requested him to give up this practise. Finally, Andrew was obliged
1 CONT to confirm the Golden Bull and supplement it with a provision that prohibited
1 CONT the employment of non-Christians and also authorised the Archbishop of
1 CONT Esztergom to punish the king in case he ignored his promise.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the second half of 1231, Andrew lead his armies to Halych and managed to
1 CONT ensure his youngest son's rule in the principality. On his return to Hungary,
1 CONT Archbishop Robert of Esztergom took his kingdom under interdict and
1 CONT excommunicated the king's major dignitaries because Andrew insisted on the
1 CONT employment of Jews and Muslims in his administration. Nevertheless, upon
1 CONT Andrew's request, the Archbishop withdrew the ecclesiastic punishments soon
1 CONT and the Pope promised that the dignitaries of the King of Hungary would never
1 CONT be excommunicated without his special authorization.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 20 August 1233, Andrew had a meeting with the legate of Pope Gregory IX in
1 CONT the woods of Bereg, and they made an agreement which ensured the privileges of
1 CONT the clergy. In the autumn of the year, he also met with Duke Frederick II of
1 CONT Austria and they agreed to stop the skirmishes on the border, but the Duke
1 CONT soon broke the agreement.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] His last years
1 CONT
1 CONT On 14 May 1234, Andrew, who had lost his second wife in the previous year,
1 CONT married Beatrice D'Este who was thirty years younger than himself. Because of
1 CONT the new marriage, his relationship enworthened with his sons.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the summer of 1234, the Bishop John of Bosnia excommunicated Andrew because
1 CONT he had not respected some provisions of the Agreement of Bereg. Andrew
1 CONT appealed to the Pope against the bishop's measure. In the autumn of 1234,
1 CONT Prince Danylo laid siege to the capital of Andrew's youngest son who died
1 CONT during the siege. Thus, the Hungarian supremacy over Halych disappeared.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the beginning of 1235, Andrew made a campaign against Austria and enforced
1 CONT Duke Frederick II to make a peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was still alive when one of his daughters, Elisabeth, who had died some
1 CONT years before, was canonized on 28 May 1235. Before his death, he was absolved
1 CONT from the excommunication; moreover, the Pope also promised that the King of
1 CONT Hungary and his relatives would not be excommunicated without the special
1 CONT permission of the Pope.
1 CONT
