1 CONT Andrew II of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew II the Jerosolimitan (Hungarian: Jeruzsálemi II András/Endre, Croatian:
1 CONT Andrija I. Slovak: Ondrej) (c. 1177 – 21 September 1235), King of Hungary and
1 CONT Croatia (1205-1235), Prince of Halych (1188-1189, 1208-1209), Duke of Croatia
1 CONT and Dalmatia (1197-1199, 1200-1203). He was the younger son of King Béla III
1 CONT of Hungary, who invested him with the government of the Principality of
1 CONT Halych. However, the boyars of Halych rebelled against his rule and expelled
1 CONT the Hungarian troops. Following their father's death, Andrew continuously
1 CONT conspired against his brother, King Emeric of Hungary who had to grant him the
1 CONT government of Croatia and Dalmatia. When his brother and his infant son died,
1 CONT Andrew ascended the throne and started to grant royal domains to his
1 CONT partisans. He participated in the Fifth Crusade but he could not achieve any
1 CONT major military success. He was obliged to issue the Golden Bull confirming the
1 CONT privileges of the noblemen of Hungary and later he was also obliged to confirm
1 CONT the special privileges of the clergy. During his long reign, he had several
1 CONT quarrels with his sons.
1 CONT
1 CONT The turbulent duke
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew was the second son of King Béla III and his first wife, Agnes of
1 CONT Antioch. As younger son, Andrew had no hope to inherite the Kingdom of Hungary
1 CONT from his father who wanted to ensure the inheritance of his elder son, Emeric
1 CONT and had him crowned already in 1182.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nevertheless, when Prince Volodymyr II of Halych, who had been expelled from
1 CONT his country by his subjects, fled to Hungary seeking for assistance in 1188,
1 CONT King Béla III had him arrested and occupied his principality and he invested
1 CONT Andrew with Halych. The child Andrew's rule in Halych must have been only
1 CONT nominal; he even did not visit his principality. In any case, his rule became
1 CONT unpopular soon, because the Hungarian soldiers were violent and they often
1 CONT violated the Eastern Orthodox churches. Although, the young prince's troops
1 CONT could get the mastery in 1189 when the boyars of Halych rose against his rule,
1 CONT but shortly afterwards Prince Volodymyr II managed to escape from his
1 CONT captivity and he expelled the Hungarian troops from Halych.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 23 April 1196, King Béla III died and he left the Kingdom of Hungary
1 CONT unportioned to his eldest son, Emeric, while Andrew inherited a large amount
1 CONT of money in order to fulfill his father's Crusader oath. However, Andrew used
1 CONT the money to recruit followers among the barons and also sought the assistance
1 CONT of Leopold V, Duke of Austria. In December 1197, Andrew's troops defeated King
1 CONT Emeric's armies in a battle near to Macsek in December 1197. Following
1 CONT Andrew's victory, the king was obliged to transfer the government of the
1 CONT Duchies of Croatia and Dalmatia to Andrew.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the beginning of 1198, Pope Innocent III requested Andrew to fulfill his
1 CONT father's last will and lead a Crusade to the Holy Land. However, instead of a
1 CONT Crusade, Andrew made a campaign against the neighbouring provinces and
1 CONT occupied Zahumlje and Rama. Andrew also went on conspiring with some prelates
1 CONT against his brother, but King Emeric was informed on Andrew's plans and he
1 CONT personally arrested Bish
