1 CONT (Research):Andras II, King of Hungary 1205-1235, (1176-1235) son of Bela III,
1 CONT King of Hungary 1173-1196 and Agnes de Chatillon Born 1176 Died 26 October
1 CONT 1235 Married 1215 Yolande de Courtenay Died 1233 He succeeded his nephew, the
1 CONT infant Ladislas III, in 1205. By his reckless generosity he impoverished the
1 CONT crown and made the monarchy dependent on the great feudatories, who reduced
1 CONT Hungary to a state bordering on anarchy. His first wife, Gertrude of Meran,
1 CONT was murdered on 24 September 1213 by rebellious nobles. In 1217 Andras II set
1 CONT out for the Holy Land with an army of 15,000 men, about 10,000 of whom sailed
1 CONT from Venice to Acre. One prize he captured was a large earthenware jar which
1 CONT was believed to be one of the waterpots which had been used at the marriage at
1 CONT Cana, when Christ had miraculously turned the water it held into wine. King
1 CONT Andras, who acquired this relic, was as delighted with it as if he had
1 CONT captured Jerusalem itself. However, he was getting more and more bored with
1 CONT the life in Acre and, welcoming the news that Bohemund IV of Antioch was
1 CONT planning to marry the half-sister of Hugh of Cyprus in Tripoli, he went off
1 CONT happily to join the wedding party there. But the festivities were cut short
1 CONT just after the New Year by the sudden and unexpected death of Hugh. This was
1 CONT too much for King Andras; he returned to Acre, gathered his men together and,
1 CONT having made arrangements with the Seljuk Sultan of Rum for safe passage
1 CONT through his land, marched them home again through Anatolia. On his return, the
1 CONT barons extorted from him the Golden Bull which has been called the Hungarian
1 CONT Magna Carta. Andras II was married three times. St.Elisabeth of Hungary was
1 CONT his daughter by his first wife. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Name Prefix: King Name Suffix: Ii, Of Hungary
1 CONT Still Living.
1 CONT Still Living.
1 CONT Andrew II of Hungary
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew II (Hungarian: II. András or II. Endre, Slovak: Ondrej II) (1175-1235)
1 CONT was a son of Béla III and succeeded his nephew, the infant Ladislaus III, as
1 CONT King of Hungary in 1205.
1 CONT
1 CONT Few other royal reigns were as detrimental to the Hungarian realm as Andrew's.
1 CONT Valiant, enterprising, pious as he was, all these fine qualities were ruined
1 CONT by a reckless good nature which never thought of the future. He declared in a
1 CONT decree that the generosity of a king should be limitless, and he followed this
1 CONT principle throughout his reign. He gave away everything - money, villages,
1 CONT domains, whole counties - to the utter impoverishment of the treasury, thereby
1 CONT rendering the crown, for the first time in Hungarian history, dependent upon
1 CONT the great nobility eager for personal gain. In all matters of government,
1 CONT Andrew was equally reckless and haphazard. He was directly responsible for the
1 CONT beginnings of the feudal anarchy which led to the extinction of the Árpád
1 CONT dynasty at the end of the 13th century. The great nobles did not even respect
1 CONT the lives of the royal family, for Andrew was recalled from a futile attempt
1 CONT to reconquer Galicia through the murder of his first wife Gertrude of Meran in
1 CONT 1213 by rebellious nobles jealous of the influence of her relatives.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1215 he married Iolanthe (Yolande) of France, but in 1217 was compelled by
1 CONT Pope Honorius III to lead the Fifth Crusade to the Holy Land, which he
1 CONT undertook in hopes of being elected Latin emperor of Constantinople. The
1 CONT crusade was not popular in Hungary, but Andrew contrived to collect 15,000 men
1 CONT together, whom he led to Venice. After the surrender of Hungarian claims on
1 CONT Zara (Zadar), about two-thirds of the crusaders were conveyed to Acre.
1 CONT Nevertheless the whole expedition was a forlorn hope. The Kingdom of Jerusalem
1 CONT was by this time reduced to a strip of coast about 440 mi² in extent, and
1 CONT after a drawn battle with the Turks on the Jordan River on November 10 1217
1 CONT and fruitless assaults on the fortresses of the Lebanon and on Mount Tabor,
1 CONT Andrew started home (January 18, 1218) through Antioch (Antakya), Iconium
1 CONT (Konya), Constantinople, and Bulgaria. On his return he found the feudal
1 CONT barons in the ascendant, and they extorted from him the Golden Bull.
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew's last exploit was to defeat an invasion of Frederick II of Austria in
1 CONT 1234. That same year he married his third wife, Beatrice of Este.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT Family
1 CONT Andrew had five children by his first wife, Gertrude:
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Hungary (1203-1221), married Tsar Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria
1 CONT Bela IV of Hungary (1206-1270)
1 CONT Saint Elizabeth of Hungary (1207-1231)
1 CONT Kálmán, Duke of Croatia (1208-1241)
1 CONT András, King of Galicia (1210-1234)
1 CONT From his second marriage to Yolande de Courtney, he had one daughter:
1 CONT
1 CONT Jolán (Yolande) of Hungary (1215-1251), married James I of Aragon
1 CONT Andrew's third marriage to Beatrice d'Este produced one posthumous son:
1 CONT
1 CONT István (1236-1271), who was himself father of King Andrew III of Hungary
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT References
1 CONT This article incorporates text from the 1911 Encyclopædia Britannica, which is
1 CONT in the public domain.
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT Ladislaus III King of Hungary
1 CONT 1205–1235 Succeeded by:
1 CONT Béla IV
1 CONT His reign was marked by controversy with barons and the great feudatories and
1 CONT by the issuance of the Golden Bull of 1222, which has been called the
1 CONT Hungarian Magna Carta. Powerful landed interests forced Andrew to spend royal
1 CONT funds so recklessly that the crown was soon impoverished and dependent on the
1 CONT feudatories, who soon reduced Hungary to a state of anarchy.
1 CONT His reign was marked by controversy with barons and the great feudatories and
1 CONT by the issuance of the Golden Bull of 1222, which has been called the
1 CONT Hungarian Magna Carta. Powerful landed interests forced Andrew to spend royal
1 CONT funds so recklessly that the crown was soon impoverished and dependent on the
1 CONT feudatories, who soon reduced Hungary to a state of anarchy.
1 CONT His reign was marked by controversy with barons and the great feudatories and
1 CONT by the issuance of the Golden Bull of 1222, which has been called the
1 CONT Hungarian Magna Carta. Powerful landed interests forced Andrew to spend royal
1 CONT funds so recklessly that the crown was soon impoverished and dependent on the
1 CONT feudatories, who soon reduced Hungary to a state of anarchy.
1 CONT His reign was marked by controversy with barons and the great feudatories and
1 CONT by the issuance of the Golden Bull of 1222, which has been called the
1 CONT Hungarian Magna Carta. Powerful landed interests forced Andrew to spend royal
1 CONT funds so recklessly that the crown was soon impoverished and dependent on the
1 CONT feudatories, who soon reduced Hungary to a state of anarchy.
1 CONT Colombia Encyclopedia (c) 1944 p.67 His reign was marked by controversy with
1 CONT barons and the great feudatories and by the issuance of the Golden Bull of
1 CONT 1222, which has been called the Hungarian Magna Carta. Powerful landed
1 CONT interests forced Andrew to spend royal funds so recklessly that the crown was
1 CONT soon impoverished and dependent on the feudatories, who soon reduced Hungary
1 CONT to a state of anarchy.
1 CONT After the accession of his brother, András demanded Croatia and Dalmatia as an
1 CONT appanage but this was refused. He revolted, and by 1198 obtained his demands
1 CONT and became Duke of Croatia and Dalmatia[571]. He and subsequent dukes acted as
1 CONT the king of Hungary's deputy in the kingdom of Croatia. He conquered western
1 CONT Hum (Herzegovina) down to the river Neretva in 1198[572]. The Continuatio
1 CONT Admuntensis records that he was arrested in 1203, suspected of plotting to
1 CONT take over the kingdom, and imprisoned "in palacio Strigoniensi quod alio
1 CONT nomine Gran vocatur"[573]. He ousted his nephew in 1205 and succeeded as
1 CONT ANDRÁS II King of Hungary. He played an active part in the dismemberment of
1 CONT Galich-Volynia after the death of Roman Mstislavich Prince of Galich in 1205,
1 CONT Hungary and Poland eventually agreeing the division of the territories between
1 CONT them under the treaty of Spisz in 1214, although Hungary expelled Poland from
1 CONT Peremyshl and Lyubachev in 1215/1216[574]. In 1211, King András hired the
1 CONT Order of Teutonic Knights, who had been expelled back to Europe from
1 CONT Palestine, to defend the eastern frontier of Transylvania against the
1 CONT Kumans[575], but they attempted to establish their autonomy there under the
1 CONT protection of the Pope. King András expelled the Teutonic Knights in 1225[576]
1 CONT on the pretext of their having disobeyed his orders. King András set sail from
1 CONT Split for Palestine on crusade in Oct 1217, but left Acre in early 1218 having
1 CONT achieved little besides acquiring a small collection of religious relics[577].
1 CONT He returned by the land route, via Constantinople, but at the end of 1218 he
1 CONT was seized in Bulgarian territory and released only after agreeing the
1 CONT marriage of his daughter to Ivan Asen II Tsar of Bulgaria[578]. He threatened
1 CONT war with Serbia after Grand Župan Stefan was crowned King of Serbia by the
1 CONT papal legate in 1217, claiming that he alone had the right to this title, but
1 CONT did not carry out the threat[579]. King András's abuses caused the Hungarian
1 CONT nobles to rebel in 1222 and forced him to issue the Golden Bull, a charter
1 CONT defining the rights of the nobility and restricting the king's right to
1 CONT appoint foreigners to office without the consent of the Council[580], a reform
1 CONT forced by the rebellion of the lower nobility in Croatia according to
1 CONT Goldstein[581]. In 1227, Bortz Khan of the Kumans swore allegiance to the king
1 CONT of Hungary after ordering the baptism of his people, rex Cumaniæ being added
1 CONT to the titles of the Hungarian king soon after[582]. King András attacked
1 CONT north-west Bulgaria in 1232 and recaptured Beograd and Branicevo which he had
1 CONT been forced to cede as part of the dowry of his daughter Maria. He crossed the
1 CONT Danube into Wallachia where the Hungarians created a Banate in the Severin
1 CONT region[583]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death in
1 CONT 1235 of "Andreas rex Hungarie" and his burial "in civitate Waradino"[584].
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT Andrew II (1175-1235) (Hungarian:II. András,Slovak:Ondrej II) was ason of Bela
1 CONT III of Hungary and succeeded his nephew, the infantLadislaus III, in 1205.
1 CONT
1 CONT No other king of Hungary, perhaps, was so mischievous to his country.Valiant,
1 CONT enterprising, pious as he was, all these fine qualities wereruined by a
1 CONT reckless good nature which never thought of the morrow. Hedeclares in one of
1 CONT his decrees that the generosity of a king should belimitless, and he acted up
1 CONT to this principle throughout his reign. Hegave away everything, money,
1 CONT villages, domains, whole counties, to theutter impoverishment of the treasury,
1 CONT thereby rendering the crown, forthe first time in Hungarian history, dependent
1 CONT upon the greatfeudatories, who, in Hungary as elsewhere, took all they could
1 CONT get andgave as little as possible in return. In all matters of
1 CONT government,Andrew was equally reckless and haphazard. He is directly
1 CONT responsiblefor the beginnings of the feudal anarchy which well-nigh led to
1 CONT theextinction of the monarchy at the end of the 13th century. The
1 CONT greatfeudatories did not even respect the lives of the royal family, forAndrew
1 CONT was recalled from a futile attempt to reconquer Galicia (whichreally lay
1 CONT beyond the Hungarian sphere of influence), through themurder of his first wife
1 CONT Gertrude of Meran (1185 - September 24,1213), by rebellious nobles jealous of
1 CONT the influence of her relatives.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1215 he married Iolanthe (Yolande) of France, but in 1217 wascompelled by
1 CONT the pope to lead the Fifth Crusade to the Holy Land,which he undertook in
1 CONT hopes of being elected Latin emperor ofConstantinople. The crusade excited no
1 CONT enthusiasm in Hungary, butAndrew contrived to collect 15,000 men together,
1 CONT whom he led toVenice; whence, not without much haggling and the surrender of
1 CONT all theHungarian claims upon Zara, about two-thirds of them were conveyed
1 CONT toAcre. Nevertheless the whole expedition was a forlorn hope. TheChristian
1 CONT kingdom of Palestine was by this time reduced to a strip ofcoast about 440 sq.
1 CONT m. in extent, and after a drawn battle with theTurks on the Jordan (November
1 CONT 10), and fruitless assaults on thefortresses of the Lebanon and on Mount
1 CONT Tabor, Andrew started home(January 18, 1218) through Antioch, Iconium,
1 CONT Constantinople andBulgaria. On his return he found the feudal barons in the
1 CONT ascendant,and they extorted from him the Golden Bull.
1 CONT
1 CONT Andrew's last exploit was to defeat an invasion of Frederick ofAustria in
1 CONT 1234. The same year he married his third wife, Beatrice ofEste.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT Family
1 CONT Andrew had five children by his first wife, Gertrude:
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Hungary (1203-1221), married Tsar Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria
1 CONT Bela IV of Hungary (1206-1270)
1 CONT Saint Elizabeth of Hungary (1207-1231)
1 CONT Kálmán, Duke of Croatia (1208-1241)
1 CONT András, King of Halicz (1210-1234)
1 CONT From his second marriage to Yolande de Courtney, he had one daughter:
1 CONT
1 CONT Jolán (Yolande) of Hungary (1215-1251), married James I of Aragon
1 CONT Andrew's third marriage to Beatrice d'Este produced one posthumousson:
1 CONT
1 CONT István (1236-1271), who was himself father of King Andrew III ofHungary
