1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda de Courtenay
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda de Courtenay (c. 1200–1233), Queen Consort of Hungary and Croatia was
1 CONT the second wife of King Andrew II of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda was the daughter of Count Peter II of Courtenay and his second wife,
1 CONT Yolanda of Flanders, the sister of Baldwin I and Henry I, the Emperors of
1 CONT Constantinople. Her marriage with King Andrew II, whose first wife, Gertrude
1 CONT had been murdered by conspirators on 24 September 1213, was arranged by her
1 CONT uncle, the Emperor Henry I.
1 CONT
1 CONT Their marriage was celebrated in February 1215 in Székesfehérvár and
1 CONT Archbishop John of Esztergom crowned her queen consort. However, Bishop Robert
1 CONT of Veszprém sent a complaint to Pope Innocent III, because the coronation of
1 CONT the queens consort in Hungary had been traditionally the privilege of his see.
1 CONT The Pope sent a legate to Hungary in order to investigate the complaint and
1 CONT confirmed the privilege of the See of Veszprém.
1 CONT
1 CONT Following her uncle's death on 11 July 1216, her husband was planning to
1 CONT acquire the imperial crown for himself, but the barons of the Latin Empire
1 CONT proclaimed her father emperor, instead.
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda maintained good relations with his husband's children from his first
1 CONT marriage. Her husband survived her. She was burried in the White Monks' Abbey
1 CONT in Egres.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Marriages and children
1 CONT
1 CONT February 1215: Andrew II of Hungary (c. 1177 – 21 September 1235)
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolanda (c. 1215 – 12 October 1251), wife of King James I of Aragon
1 CONT
