1 CONT Constance of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance of Sicily (1154 – November 27, 1198) was the heiress of the Norman
1 CONT kings of Sicily and the wife of Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor. She was Queen of
1 CONT Sicily 1194-1198, jointly with her husband from 1194-1197, and with her infant
1 CONT son Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor in 1198.
1 CONT
1 CONT Biography
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance was the posthumous daughter of Roger II of Sicily by his third wife
1 CONT Beatrix of Rethel.
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance was not betrothed until she was thirty, which is unusual for a
1 CONT princess whose marriage was an important dynastic bargaining chip. This later
1 CONT gave rise to stories that she had become a nun and required papal dispensation
1 CONT to forsake her vows and marry, or that she was impossibly ugly. Neither of
1 CONT these is consistent with the evidence.
1 CONT
1 CONT The death of her younger nephew Henry of Capua in 1172 made Constance heiress
1 CONT presumptive to the Sicilian crown, after her elder nephew King William II, who
1 CONT did not marry until 1177, and whose marriage remained childless. Abulafia
1 CONT (1988) points out that William did not foresee the union of German and
1 CONT Sicilian crowns as a serious eventuality; his purpose was to consolidate an
1 CONT alliance, with an erstwhile enemy of Norman power in Italy.
1 CONT
1 CONT But it is unclear why he delayed so in finding a husband for his aunt.
1 CONT Nevertheless, in 1184 Constance was betrothed to Henry (the future Emperor
1 CONT Henry VI), and they were married two years later, on January 27, 1186.
1 CONT
1 CONT The papacy, also an enemy of the emperors, would not want to see the great
1 CONT kingdom to the south of Rome in German hands, but Henry pressed Pope Celestine
1 CONT III to baptize and crown his son: the Pope put him off.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nor would the kingdom's Norman nobles welcome a Hohenstaufen king. William
1 CONT made his nobles and the important men of his court promise to recognize
1 CONT Constance's succession if he died without direct heirs. But after his
1 CONT unexpected death in 1189, his cousin (and Constance's nephew) Tancred seized
1 CONT the throne. Tancred was illegitimate, but he had the support of most of the
1 CONT great men of the kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance's father-in-law died in 1190, and the following year Henry and
1 CONT Constance were crowned Emperor and Empress. Constance then accompanied her
1 CONT husband at the head of a substantial imperial army to forcefully take the
1 CONT throne from Tancred. The northern towns of the kingdom opened their gates to
1 CONT Henry, including the earliest Norman strongholds Capua and Aversa. Salerno,
1 CONT Roger II's mainland capital, sent word ahead that Henry was welcome, and
1 CONT invited Constance to stay in her father's old palace to escape the summer
1 CONT heat. Naples was the first time that Henry met resistance on the whole
1 CONT campaign, holding well into the southern summer, by which time much of the
1 CONT army had succumbed to malaria and disease and the imperial army was forced to
1 CONT withdraw from the kingdom altogether. Constance remained in Salerno with a
1 CONT small garrison, as a sign that Henry would soon return.
1 CONT
1 CONT Once Henry had withdrawn with the bulk of the imperial army, the towns that
1 CONT had supposedly fallen to the Empire immediately declared their allegiance to
1 CONT Tancred, for the most part now fearing his retribution. The populace of
1 CONT Salerno saw an opportunity to win some favour with Tancred, and delivered
1 CONT Constance to him in Messina, an important prize given that Henry had every
1 CONT intention of returning. However, Tancred was willing to give up his
1 CONT negotiation advantage, that is, the Empress, in return for Pope Celestine III
1 CONT legitimising him as King of Sicily. In turn, the Pope was hoping that by
1 CONT securing Constance's safe passage back to Rome, Henry would be better disposed
1 CONT towards the papacy and he was still hoping to keep the Empire and the Kingdom
1 CONT from uniting. However, imperial soldiers were able to intervene before
1 CONT Constance made it to Rome, and they returned her safely across the Alps,
1 CONT ensuring that in the end, both the papacy and the kingdom failed to score any
1 CONT real advantage in having the Empress in their custody.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry was already preparing to invade Sicily a second time when Tancred died
1 CONT in 1194. Later that year he moved south, entered Palermo unopposed, deposed
1 CONT Tancred's young son William III, and had himself crowned instead.
1 CONT
1 CONT While Henry moved quickly south with his army, Constance followed at a slower
1 CONT pace, for she was pregnant. On December 26, the day after Henry's crowning at
1 CONT Palermo, she gave birth to a son, Frederick (the future Emperor and king of
1 CONT Sicily Frederick II) in the small town of Jesi, near Ancona.
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance was 40, and she knew that many would question whether the child was
1 CONT really hers. Thus she had the baby in a pavilion tent in the market square of
1 CONT the town, and invited the town matrons to witness the birth. A few days later
1 CONT she returned to the town square and publicly breast-fed the infant.
1 CONT
1 CONT Crowning of Frederick II
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry died in 1197. The following year Constance had the three-year-old
1 CONT Frederick crowned King of Sicily, and in his name dissolved the ties her late
1 CONT husband had created between the government of Sicily and of the Empire. She
1 CONT adopted very different policies from those of her last consort. She surrounded
1 CONT herself with local advisors and excluded the ambitious Markward von Anweiler
1 CONT from a position of power and attempted to restrict him to his fief in Molise.
1 CONT She made no mention of any claims to the German kingship and empire when her
1 CONT son was anointed and crowned at Palermo, May 1198; Constance made warm
1 CONT overtures to the new pope Innocent III, abandoning the long-contended
1 CONT principle that the king was the apostolic legate, a central principle of
1 CONT Norman autonomy in the regno. Faced with the dangers that surrounded any
1 CONT child-king, Constance placed Frederick under the protection of Pope Innocent
1 CONT III. She expected him to be raised as a Sicilian, and to be nothing more than
1 CONT King of Sicily, without distracting claims to Germany or even to the title
1 CONT "King of the Romans" to which her brother-in-law Philip of Swabia was
1 CONT acclaimed by the Roman nobles. That he became much more than that could not be
1 CONT predicted when she died in late November 1198. In her will she made Innocent,
1 CONT who was the child's feudal suzerain, his guardian, a reminder to all of the
1 CONT inviolability of his inheritance.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the Divine Comedy, Dante places Constance in Paradise (though he subscribed
1 CONT to the story that Constance had been a nun):
1 CONT
1 CONT "This other radiance that shows itself
1 CONT
1 CONT to you at my right hand, a brightness kindled
1 CONT
1 CONT by all the light that fills our heaven-- she
1 CONT
1 CONT has understood what I have said: she was
1 CONT
1 CONT a sister, and from her head, too, by force,
1 CONT
1 CONT the shadow of the sacred veil was taken.
1 CONT
1 CONT But though she had been turned back to the world
1 CONT
1 CONT against her will, against all honest practice,
1 CONT
1 CONT the veil upon her heart was never loosed.
1 CONT
1 CONT This is the splendor of the great Costanza,
1 CONT
1 CONT who from the Swabians' second gust engendered
1 CONT
1 CONT the one who was their third and final power."
1 CONT
1 CONT —Paradiso, Canto III, lines 109-120, Mandelbaum translation
1 CONT
1 CONT Primary Sources
1 CONT
1 CONT Giovanni Villani, Cronica, V.20, VI.16, VII.1
1 CONT
