1 CONT
1 CONT   * [<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_VIII_of_France> **Louis VIII of France** ]
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion
1 CONT
1 CONT King of the Franks and Count of Artois
1 CONT
1 CONT Reign 14 July 1223 – 8 November 1226
1 CONT
1 CONT Coronation 6 August 1223, Reims
1 CONT
1 CONT Titles Count of Artois (1189–1226)
1 CONT
1 CONT King of England (1216–17)
1 CONT
1 CONT Born 5 September 1187(1187-09-05)
1 CONT
1 CONT Paris, France
1 CONT
1 CONT Died 8 November 1226 (aged 39)
1 CONT
1 CONT Chateau Montpensier, France
1 CONT
1 CONT Buried Saint Denis Basilica
1 CONT
1 CONT Predecessor Philip II Augustus
1 CONT
1 CONT Successor Louis IX
1 CONT
1 CONT Consort Blanche of Castile (1188–1252)
1 CONT
1 CONT Issue Louis IX (1214–1270)
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert I, Count of Artois (1216–50)
1 CONT
1 CONT Alphonse, Count of Toulouse and Poitiers (1220–71)
1 CONT
1 CONT Saint Isabel of France (1225–69)
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles I of Sicily (1227–85)
1 CONT
1 CONT Royal House House of Capet
1 CONT
1 CONT Father Philip II of France (1165–1223)
1 CONT
1 CONT Mother Isabelle of Hainaut (1170–90)
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (5 September 1187 – 8 November 1226) reigned as King of
1 CONT France from 1223 to 1226. He was a member of the House of Capet. Louis VIII
1 CONT was born in Paris, France, the son of Philip II of France and Isabelle of
1 CONT Hainaut. He was also Count of Artois from 1190, inheriting the county from his
1 CONT mother.
1 CONT
1 CONT As Prince Louis:
1 CONT
1 CONT At the age of 12, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile on 23 May 1200,
1 CONT following prolonged negotiations between Philip Augustus and Blanche's uncle
1 CONT John of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1216 the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John of England (1199–1216) and offered the throne to Prince
1 CONT Louis. Louis invaded and was proclaimed King in London in May 1216, although
1 CONT he was not crowned. There was little resistance when the prince entered
1 CONT London. At St Paul's Cathedral, Louis was accepted as ruler with great pomp
1 CONT and celebration in the presence of all of London. Many nobles, as well as King
1 CONT Alexander II of Scotland (1214–49), gathered to give homage to him.
1 CONT
1 CONT On June 14 he captured Winchester and soon conquered over half of the English
1 CONT kingdom. After a year and a half of war, most of the rebellious barons had
1 CONT defected and so Louis had to give up his claim to be the King of England by
1 CONT signing the Treaty of Lambeth in 1217. The effect of the treaty was that Louis
1 CONT agreed he had never been the legitimate king of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT As King Louis VIII:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII succeeded his father on July 14, 1223; his coronation took place on
1 CONT August 6 of the same year in the cathedral at Reims. As King, he continued to
1 CONT seek revenge on the Angevins and seized Poitou and Saintonge from them in
1 CONT 1224\. There followed the seizure of Avignon and Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited his officials from
1 CONT recording debts owed to Jews, thus reversing the policies set by his father
1 CONT Philip II of France (1180–1223). Usury (lending money with interest) was
1 CONT illegal for Christians to practice, according to Church law it was seen as a
1 CONT vice in which people profited from others' misfortune (like gambling), and was
1 CONT punishable by excommunication, a severe punishment. However since Jews were
1 CONT not Christian, they could not be excommunicated, and thus fell in to a legal
1 CONT gray area which secular rulers would sometimes exploit by allowing (or
1 CONT requesting) Jews to provide usury services, often for personal gain to the
1 CONT secular ruler, and to the discontent of the Church. Louis VIII's prohibition
1 CONT was one attempt at resolving this legal problem which was a constant source of
1 CONT friction in Church and State courts.
1 CONT
1 CONT Twenty six barons accepted, but Theobald IV (1201–53), the powerful Count of
1 CONT Champagne, did not, since he had an agreement with the Jews that guaranteed
1 CONT him extra income through taxation. Theobald IV would become a major opposition
1 CONT force to Capetian dominance, and his hostility was manifest during the reign
1 CONT of Louis VIII. For example, during the siege of Avignon, he performed only the
1 CONT minimum service of 40 days, and left home amid charges of treachery
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1225, the council of Bourges excommunicated the Count of Toulouse, Raymond
1 CONT VII, and declared a crusade against the southern barons. Louis happily renewed
1 CONT the conflict in order to enforce his royal rights. Roger Bernard the Great,
1 CONT count of Foix, tried to keep the peace, but the king rejected his embassy and
1 CONT the counts of Foix and Toulouse took up arms against him. The king was largely
1 CONT successful, but he did not complete the work before his death.
1 CONT
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis VIII became ill with dysentery, and died
1 CONT on November 8, 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, Louis IX
1 CONT (1226–70), succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ancestors:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII's ancestors in three generations Louis VIII of France Father:
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II of France Paternal Grandfather:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VII of France Paternal Great-grandfather:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VI of France
1 CONT
1 CONT Paternal Great-grandmother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Adelaide of Maurienne
1 CONT
1 CONT Paternal Grandmother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Adèle of Champagne Paternal Great-grandfather:
1 CONT
1 CONT Theobald II, Count of Champagne
1 CONT
1 CONT Paternal Great-grandmother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Matilda of Carinthia
1 CONT
1 CONT Mother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut Maternal Grandfather:
1 CONT
1 CONT Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut Maternal Great-grandfather:
1 CONT
1 CONT Baldwin IV, Count of Hainaut
1 CONT
1 CONT Maternal Great-grandmother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Alice of Namur
1 CONT
1 CONT Maternal Grandmother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Margaret I, Countess of Flanders Maternal Great-grandfather:
1 CONT
1 CONT Thierry, Count of Flanders
1 CONT
1 CONT Maternal Great-grandmother:
1 CONT
1 CONT Sibylla of Anjou
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage:
1 CONT
1 CONT On May 23, 1200, at the age of twelve, Louis married Blanche of Castile (March
1 CONT 4, 1188 – November 26, 1252).
1 CONT
1 CONT Issue:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1) Blanche (1205–1206).
1 CONT
1 CONT 2) Agnes (b. and d. 1207).
1 CONT
1 CONT 3) Philippe (9 September 1209 – July 1218), married (or only betrothed) in
1 CONT 1217 to Agnes of Donzy.
1 CONT
1 CONT 4) Alphonse (b. and d. Lorrez-le-Bocage, 23 January 1213).
1 CONT
1 CONT 5) John (b. and d. Lorrez-le-Bocage, 23 January 1213), twin of Alphonse.
1 CONT
1 CONT 6) Louis IX (Poissy, 25 April 1214 – 25 August 1270, Tunis), King of France as
1 CONT succesor to his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT 7) Robert (25 September 1216 – 9 February 1250, killed in battle, Manssurah,
1 CONT Egypt)
1 CONT
1 CONT 8) Philippe (1218–1220).
1 CONT
1 CONT 9) John Tristan (21 July 1219 – 1232), Count of Anjou and Maine.
1 CONT
1 CONT 10) Alphonse (Poissy, 11 November 1220 – 21 August 1271, Corneto), Count of
1 CONT Poitou and Auvergne, and by marriage, of Toulouse.
1 CONT
1 CONT 11) Philippe Dagobert (20 February 1222 – 1232).
1 CONT
1 CONT 12) Isabel (14 April 1225 – 23 February 1269).
1 CONT
1 CONT 13) Charles Etienne (21 March 1226 – 7 January 1285), Count of Anjou and
1 CONT Maine, by marriage Count of Provence and Folcalquier, and King of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT On 23 May 1200, at the age of 12, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile,
1 CONT following prolonged negotiations between Philip Augustus and Blanche's uncle
1 CONT John of England (as represented in William Shakespeare's historical play King
1 CONT John).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1216, the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John of England (1199–1216) and offered the throne to Prince
1 CONT Louis. Louis and an army landed in England; he was proclaimed King in London
1 CONT in May 1216, although he was not crowned. There was little resistance when the
1 CONT prince entered London. At St Paul's Cathedral, Louis was accepted as ruler
1 CONT with great pomp and celebration in the presence of all of London. Many nobles,
1 CONT as well as King Alexander II of Scotland (1214–49), gathered to give homage.
1 CONT On 14 June 1216, Louis captured Winchester and soon controlled over half of
1 CONT the English kingdom.[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT After a year and a half of war, King John's death, and his replacement by a
1 CONT regency on behalf of the boy king Henry III (John's son), many of the
1 CONT rebellious barons deserted Louis. When his army was beaten at Lincoln, and his
1 CONT naval forces (led by Eustace the Monk) were defeated off the coast of
1 CONT Sandwich, he was forced to make peace under English terms.
1 CONT
1 CONT The principal provisions of the Treaty of Lambeth were an amnesty for English
1 CONT rebels, land possession to return to the status quo ante, the Channel Islands
1 CONT to be returned to the English crown, Louis to undertake not to attack England
1 CONT again, and to attempt to give Normandy back to the English crown, and 10,000
1 CONT marks to be given to Louis. The effect of the treaty was that Louis agreed he
1 CONT had never been the legitimate king of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII succeeded his father on 14 July 1223; his coronation took place on
1 CONT 6 August of the same year in the cathedral at Reims. As King, he continued to
1 CONT seek revenge on the Angevins and seized Poitou and Saintonge from them in
1 CONT 1229. There followed the seizure of Avignon and Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited his officials from
1 CONT recording debts owed to Jews, thus reversing the policies set by his father
1 CONT Philip II Augustus. Usury (lending money with interest) was illegal for
1 CONT Christians to practice, according to Church law it was seen as a vice in which
1 CONT people profited from others' misfortune (like gambling), and was punishable by
1 CONT excommunication, a severe punishment. However since Jews were not Christian,
1 CONT they could not be excommunicated, and thus fell in to a legal gray area which
1 CONT secular rulers would sometimes exploit by allowing (or requesting) Jews to
1 CONT provide usury services, often for personal gain to the secular ruler, and to
1 CONT the discontent of the Church. Louis VIII's prohibition was one attempt at
1 CONT resolving this legal problem which was a constant source of friction in Church
1 CONT and State courts.
1 CONT
1 CONT Twenty-six barons accepted, but Theobald IV (1201–53), the powerful Count of
1 CONT Champagne, did not, since he had an agreement with the Jews that guaranteed
1 CONT him extra income through taxation. Theobald IV would become a major opposition
1 CONT force to Capetian dominance, and his hostility was manifest during the reign
1 CONT of Louis VIII. For example, during the siege of Avignon, he performed only the
1 CONT minimum service of 40 days, and left home amid charges of treachery.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1225, the council of Bourges excommunicated the Count of Toulouse, Raymond
1 CONT VII, and declared a crusade against the southern barons. Louis happily renewed
1 CONT the conflict in order to enforce his royal rights. Roger Bernard the Great,
1 CONT count of Foix, tried to keep the peace, but the king rejected his embassy and
1 CONT the counts of Foix and Toulouse took up arms against him. The king was largely
1 CONT successful, but he did not complete the work before his death.
1 CONT
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis VIII became ill with dysentery, and died
1 CONT on 8 November 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, Louis IX
1 CONT (1226–70), succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
