1 CONT
1 CONT BIOGRAPHY: b. Sept. 5, 1187, Paris
1 CONT
1 CONT d. Nov. 8, 1226, Montpensier, Auvergne, Fr.
1 CONT
1 CONT byname LOUIS THE LION, OR THE LION-HEART, French LOUIS LE LION, OR LOUIS
1 CONT COEUR-DE-LION, Capetian king of France from 1223 who spent most of his short
1 CONT reign establishing royal power in Poitou and Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On May 23, 1200, Louis married Blanche of Castile, daughter of Alfonso VIII of
1 CONT Castile, who effectively acted as regent after Louis's death. In 1212 Louis
1 CONT seized Saint-Omer and Aire to prevent a powerful Flanders from being on the
1 CONT flank of his county of Artois. In 1216, after the barons rebelling against
1 CONT King John of England had offered the English throne to Louis in return for his
1 CONT aid, Louis went to England to aid the rebels. Initially he was successful, but
1 CONT eventually he was defeated at sea and suffered defections. In 1217, when peace
1 CONT was concluded at Kingston, Louis was secretly paid 10,000 marks. In 1224, now
1 CONT king, he seized Poitou and, in 1226, he launched a successful crusade against
1 CONT the Albigensian heretics, capturing the major fortress of Avignon before
1 CONT returning toward Paris because of illness.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis was the first Capetian to grant appanages on a large scale and to have a
1 CONT reversion clause that made alienation of royal property more difficult. Louis
1 CONT also developed other particular rights for the kingship, such as the concept
1 CONT that fealty was sworn not only to the individual king but also to the
1 CONT kingship. His eldest son, Louis IX (afterward St. Louis), peacefully succeeded
1 CONT him while his other sons received appanages.
1 CONT
1 CONT Copyright © 1994-2001 Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.
