1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (5 September 1187 – 8 November 1226) reigned as King of
1 CONT France from 1223 to 1226. He was a member of the House of Capet. Louis VIII
1 CONT was born in Paris, France, the son of Philip II Augustus and Isabelle of
1 CONT Hainaut. He was also Count of Artois, inheriting the county from his mother,
1 CONT from 1190–1237, when he gave the title as an appanage to his young son,
1 CONT Robert.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 23 May 1200, at the age of 12, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile,
1 CONT following prolonged negotiations between Philip Augustus and Blanche's uncle
1 CONT John of England (as represented in William Shakespeare's historical play King
1 CONT John). Wikipedia
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Source: The book, 'Eleanor of Aquitaine'.
1 CONT
1 CONT (plus many others)
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (5 September 1187 – 8 November 1226) reigned as King of
1 CONT France from 1223 to 1226. He was a member of the House of Capet. Louis VIII
1 CONT was born in Paris, France, the son of Philip II Augustus and Isabelle of
1 CONT Hainaut. He was also Count of Artois from 1190, inheriting the county from his
1 CONT mother.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the age of 12, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile on 23 May 1200,
1 CONT following prolonged negotiations between Philip Augustus and Blanche's uncle
1 CONT John of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1216 the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John of England (1199–1216) and offered the throne to Prince
1 CONT Louis. Louis invaded and was proclaimed King in London in May 1216, although
1 CONT he was not crowned. There was little resistance when the prince entered
1 CONT London. At St Paul's Cathedral, Louis was accepted as ruler with great pomp
1 CONT and celebration in the presence of all of London. Many nobles, as well as King
1 CONT Alexander II of Scotland (1214–49), gathered to give homage to him.
1 CONT
1 CONT On June 14, Louis captured Winchester and soon conquered over half of the
1 CONT English kingdom.[1] After a year and a half of war, however, most of the
1 CONT rebellious barons defected and so Louis had to give up his claim to be the
1 CONT King of England by signing the Treaty of Lambeth in 1217. The effect of the
1 CONT treaty was that Louis agreed he had never been the legitimate king of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT King Louis VIII, "the Lion," reigned as King of France from 1223 to 1226. He
1 CONT was a member of the House of Capet. He was also Count of Artois from 1190,
1 CONT inheriting the county from his mother.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the age of 12, in 1200, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile, who was
1 CONT only 11.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis was also King of England for a very short time: In 1216 the English
1 CONT barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the unpopular King John of
1 CONT England and offered the throne to Prince Louis. Louis invaded and was
1 CONT proclaimed King in London in May 1216, although he was not crowned. There was
1 CONT little resistance when the Prince entered London. At St Paul's Cathedral,
1 CONT Louis was accepted as ruler with great pomp and celebration in the presence of
1 CONT all of London. Many nobles, as well as King Alexander II of Scotland
1 CONT (1214–49), gathered to give homage to him. On 14 June, Louis captured
1 CONT Winchester and soon conquered over half of the English kingdom. However, after
1 CONT a year and a half of war, and after King John's death, most of the rebellious
1 CONT barons defected, so Louis had to give up his claim to be the King of England
1 CONT by signing the Treaty of Lambeth in 1217. The effect of the treaty was that
1 CONT Louis agreed he had never been the legitimate King of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII succeeded his father on 14 July 1223; his coronation took place on
1 CONT 6 August of the same year in the cathedral at Reims. As King, he continued to
1 CONT seek revenge on the Angevins (the ruling Plantagenet dynasty in England) and
1 CONT seized Poitou and Saintonge from them in 1224. There followed the seizure of
1 CONT Avignon and Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited his officials from
1 CONT recording debts owed to Jews. But Count Theobald IV did not accept this, since
1 CONT he had an agreement with the Jews that guaranteed him extra income through
1 CONT taxation.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1225, the council of Bourges excommunicated the Count Raymond VII of
1 CONT Toulouse, and declared a crusade against the southern barons (the bloody
1 CONT Albigensian Crusade). Louis happily welcomed the conflict in order to enforce
1 CONT his royal rights. Roger Bernard the Great, count of Foix, tried to keep the
1 CONT peace, but the King rejected his embassy and the counts of Foix and Toulouse
1 CONT took up arms against him. The King was largely successful, but he did not
1 CONT complete the work before his death.
1 CONT
1 CONT See <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_VIII_of_France> for more information.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (5 September 1187 – 8 November 1226) reigned as King of
1 CONT France from 1223 to 1226. He was a member of the House of Capet. Louis VIII
1 CONT was born in Paris, France, the son of Philip II Augustus and Isabelle of
1 CONT Hainaut. He was also Count of Artois from 1190, inheriting the county from his
1 CONT mother.
1 CONT
