1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Prince Louis
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT On 23 May 1200, at the age of 12, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile,
1 CONT following prolonged negotiations between Philip Augustus and Blanche's uncle
1 CONT John of England (as represented in William Shakespeare's historical play King
1 CONT John).
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Campaign of 1214
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1214 King John of England began his final campaign to reclaim Normandy from
1 CONT Philip II August. John was optimistic, as he had successfully built up
1 CONT alliances with the Emperor Otto IV, Count Renaud of Boulogne and Count
1 CONT Ferdinand of Flanders.[1] John's plan was to split Philip's forces by pushing
1 CONT north-east from Poitou towards Paris, whilst Otto, Renaud and Ferdinand,
1 CONT supported by William Longespée, marched south-west from Flanders.[2] Whereas
1 CONT Philip II August took personal command of the northern front against the
1 CONT Emperor and his allies, he gave his son Louis the command of the front against
1 CONT the Plantagenet possessions in middle France. The first part of the campaign
1 CONT went well for the English, with John out-manoeuvring the forces under the
1 CONT command of Prince Louis and retaking the county of Anjou by the end of
1 CONT June.[3][4] John besieged the castle of Roche-au-Moine, a key stronghold,
1 CONT forcing Louis to give battle against John's larger army.[5] The local Angevin
1 CONT nobles refused to advance with the king; left at something of a disadvantage,
1 CONT John retreated back to La Rochelle.[6] Shortly afterwards, Philip II August
1 CONT won the hard-fought battle of Bouvines in the north against Otto and John's
1 CONT other allies, bringing an end to John's hopes of retaking Normandy.[7]
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Pretender to the English throne
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1215, the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John of England (1199–1216). The barons offered the throne to
1 CONT Prince Louis, who landed unopposed on the Isle of Thanet in England at the
1 CONT head of an army on 21 May 1216. There was little resistance when the prince
1 CONT entered London and at St Paul's Cathedral, Louis was proclaimed King with
1 CONT great pomp and celebration in the presence of all of London. Even though he
1 CONT was not crowned, many nobles, as well as King Alexander II of Scotland
1 CONT (1214–49) for his English possessions, gathered to give homage.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 14 June 1216, Louis captured Winchester and soon controlled over half of
1 CONT the English kingdom.[8] But just when it seemed that England was his, King
1 CONT John's death in October 1216 caused many of the rebellious barons to desert
1 CONT Louis in favour of John's nine-year-old son, Henry III.
1 CONT
1 CONT With William Marshall acting as regent, a call for the English "to defend our
1 CONT land" against the French led to a reversal of fortunes on the battlefield.
1 CONT After his army was beaten at Lincoln on 20 May 1217, and his naval forces (led
1 CONT by Eustace the Monk) were defeated off the coast of Sandwich on 24 August
1 CONT 1217, he was forced to make peace on English terms.
1 CONT
1 CONT The principal provisions of the Treaty of Lambeth were an amnesty for English
1 CONT rebels, Louis to undertake not to attack England again, and 10,000 marks to be
1 CONT given to Louis. The effect of the treaty was that Louis agreed he had never
1 CONT been the legitimate King of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] As King Louis VIII
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII succeeded his father on 14 July 1223; his coronation took place on
1 CONT 6 August of the same year in the cathedral at Reims. As King, he continued to
1 CONT seek revenge on the Angevins and seized Poitou and Saintonge from them. There
1 CONT followed the seizure of Avignon and Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT Coronation of Louis VIII and Blanche of Castile at Reims in 1223; a miniature
1 CONT from the Grandes Chroniques de France, painted in the 1450s, (Bibliothèque
1 CONT nationale) On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited his
1 CONT officials from recording debts owed to Jews, thus reversing the policies set
1 CONT by his father Philip II Augustus. Usury (lending money with interest) was
1 CONT illegal for Christians to practice. According to Church law it was seen as a
1 CONT vice in which people profited from others' misfortune (like gambling), and was
1 CONT punishable by excommunication, a severe punishment. However since Jews were
1 CONT not Christian, they could not be excommunicated, and thus fell in to a legal
1 CONT grey area which secular rulers would sometimes exploit by allowing (or
1 CONT requesting) Jews to provide usury services, often for personal gain to the
1 CONT secular ruler, and to the discontent of the Church. Louis VIII's prohibition
1 CONT was one attempt at resolving this legal problem which was a constant source of
1 CONT friction in Church and State courts.
1 CONT
1 CONT French Monarchy
1 CONT
1 CONT Direct Capetians
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis IX
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert I, Count of Artois
1 CONT
1 CONT Alphonse, Count of Poitou and Toulouse
1 CONT
1 CONT Saint Isabel of France
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles I of Anjou and Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Twenty-six barons accepted, but Theobald IV (1201–53), the powerful Count of
1 CONT Champagne, did not, since he had an agreement with the Jews that guaranteed
1 CONT him extra income through taxation. Theobald IV would become a major opposition
1 CONT force to Capetian dominance, and his hostility was manifest during the reign
1 CONT of Louis VIII. For example, during the siege of Avignon, he performed only the
1 CONT minimum service of 40 days, and left home amid charges of treachery.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1225, the council of Bourges excommunicated the Count of Toulouse, Raymond
1 CONT VII, and declared a crusade against the southern barons. Louis happily renewed
1 CONT the conflict in order to enforce his royal rights. Roger Bernard the Great,
1 CONT Count of Foix, tried to keep the peace, but the king rejected his embassy and
1 CONT the counts of Foix and Toulouse took up arms against him. The king was largely
1 CONT successful, but he did not complete the work before his death.
1 CONT
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis VIII became ill with dysentery, and died
1 CONT on 8 November 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, Louis IX
1 CONT (1226–70), succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Ancestry
1 CONT
