1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (French: Louis VIII le Lion) (September 5, 1187 – November
1 CONT 8, 1226) reigned as King of France from 1223 to 1226. He was a member of the
1 CONT Capetian dynasty. Louis VIII was born in Paris, France, the son of Philip II
1 CONT of France and Isabelle of Hainaut.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1216 the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John of England (1199–1216) and offered the throne to Louis.
1 CONT Louis invaded and was proclaimed King in London inMay 1216, although he was
1 CONT not crowned. There was little resistance when the prince entered London. At St
1 CONT Paul's Cathedral, Louis was accepted as ruler with great pomp and celebration
1 CONT in the presence of all of London. Many nobles, including Alexander II of
1 CONT Scotland (1214–49), gathered to give homage to him.
1 CONT
1 CONT On June 14 he captured Winchester and soon conquered over half of the English
1 CONT kingdom. Since other English Kings such as Edward V (1483) and Edward VIII
1 CONT (1936) were not crowned but only proclaimed, there is a good case for
1 CONT including Louis VIII in the list of Kings of England. After a year and a half
1 CONT of war, most of the rebellious barons had defected and so Louis had to give up
1 CONT his claim to be theKing of England by signing the Treaty of Lambeth in 1217.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII succeeded his father on July 14, 1223; his coronation took place on
1 CONT August 6 of the same year in the cathedral at Reims. As King, he continued to
1 CONT seek revenge on the Angevins and seized Poitou and Saintonge from them in
1 CONT 1224\. There followed the seizure of Avignon and Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited his officials from
1 CONT recording debts owed to Jews, thus reversing the policies set by his father
1 CONT Philip II of France (1180–1223). Usury (lending money with interest) was
1 CONT illegal for Christians to practice, according to Church law it was seen as a
1 CONT vice in which people profited from others' misfortune (like gambling), and was
1 CONT punishable by excommunication, a severe punishment. However since Jews were
1 CONT not Christian, they could not be excommunicated, and thus fell in to a legal
1 CONT gray area which secular rulers would sometimes exploit by allowing (or
1 CONT requesting) Jews to provide usury services, often for personal gain to the
1 CONT secular ruler, and to the discontent of the Church. Louis VIII's prohibition
1 CONT was one attempt at resolving this legal problem which was a constant source of
1 CONT friction in Church and State courts.
1 CONT
1 CONT Twenty six barons accepted, but Theobald IV of Champagne (1201–53), a powerful
1 CONT baron from Champagne did not, since he had an agreement with the Jews that
1 CONT guaranteed him extra income through taxation.Theobald IV would become a major
1 CONT opposition force to Capetian dominance, and his hostility was manifest during
1 CONT the reign of Louis VIII. For example, during the siege of Avignon, he
1 CONT performed only theminimum service of 40 days, and left home amid charges of
1 CONT treachery.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1225, the council of Bourges excommunicated the count of Toulouse, Raymond
1 CONT VII, and declared a crusade against the southern barons. Louis happily renewed
1 CONT the conflict in order to enforce his royalrights. Roger Bernard the Great,
1 CONT count of Foix, tried to keep the peace, but the king rejected his embassy and
1 CONT the counts of Foix and Toulouse took up arms against him. The king was largely
1 CONT successful, but he did not complete the work before his death.
1 CONT
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis VIII became ill with dysentery, and died
1 CONT on November 8, 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, Louis IX
1 CONT (1226–70), succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT On May 23, 1200, at the age of twelve, Louis married Blanche of Castile (March
1 CONT 4, 1188 – November 26, 1252).
1 CONT
