1 CONT (Research):Louis VIII Encyclopædia Britannica Article born Sept. 5, 1187,
1 CONT Paris died Nov. 8, 1226, Montpensier, Auvergne, Fr. byname Louis The Lion, or
1 CONT The Lion-heart, French Louis Le Lion, or Louis Coeur-de-lion Capetian king of
1 CONT France from 1223 who spent most of his short reign establishing royal power in
1 CONT Poitou and Languedoc. On May 23, 1200, Louis married Blanche of Castile,
1 CONT daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile, who effectively acted as regent after
1 CONT Louis's death. In 1212 Louis seized Saint-Omer and Aire to prevent a powerful
1 CONT Flanders from being on the flank of his county of Artois. In 1216, after the
1 CONT barons rebelling against King John of England had offered the English throne
1 CONT to Louis in return for his aid, Louis went to England to aid the rebels.
1 CONT Initially he was successful, but eventually he was defeated at sea and
1 CONT suffered defections. In 1217, when peace was concluded at Kingston, Louis was
1 CONT secretly paid 10,000 marks. In 1224, now king, he seized Poitou and, in 1226,
1 CONT he launched a successful crusade against the Albigensian heretics, capturing
1 CONT the major fortress of Avignon before returning toward Paris because of
1 CONT illness. Louis was the first Capetian to grant appanages on a large scale and
1 CONT to have a reversion clause that made alienation of royal property more
1 CONT difficult. Louis also developed other particular rights for the kingship, such
1 CONT as the concept that fealty was sworn not only to the individual king but also
1 CONT to the kingship. His eldest son, Louis IX (afterward St. Louis), peacefully
1 CONT succeeded him while his other sons received appanages.
