1 CONT 1252 Paris At the age of twelve he married the formidable Blanche of Castile
1 CONT and they became the parents of ten children. In 1212 he took Saint Omer and
1 CONT Aire as he regarded Flanders too powerful and too near his own county of
1 CONT Artois. In 1216 the English King John offered him the English throne in
1 CONT exchange for support against the powerful English barons. Louis went to
1 CONT England to support the rebels but, after initial success, was defeated at sea.
1 CONT In 1217 peace was signed and Louis was secretly paid 10,000 marks. In 1223 he
1 CONT succeeded his father as King of France and, in 1224, seized Poitou. In 1226 he
1 CONT launched a successful crusade against the Albigensian heretics, capturing the
1 CONT major fortress of Avignon before returning towards Paris because of illness.
1 CONT He died at Montpensier shortly afterwards. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Name Prefix: King Name Suffix: Viii, Of France "The Lion"
1 CONT After succeeding his father as king, Louis continued his father's policy of
1 CONT destroying the power of the Plantagenets in France and bringing under royal
1 CONT authority the Provinces held by the Albigences in the south of France. On his
1 CONT death, his son Louis IX, not yet 13 years old, was taken to Reims by his
1 CONT mother to be crowned King of France. Mother Blanche was not a woman to be
1 CONT discouraged by adversity, such as was shown at the coronation by a lack of
1 CONT participation by many of the most powerful nobles.
1 CONT Basic Life Information
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion reigned as King of France from 1223 to 1226. He was a
1 CONT member of the House of Capet. Louis VIII was born in Paris, France, the son of
1 CONT Philip II Augustus and Isabelle of Hainaut. He was also Count of Artois from
1 CONT 1190, inheriting the county from his mother
1 CONT .
1 CONT Marriage and Children
1 CONT
1 CONT At the age of 12, Louis was married to Blanche of Castile on 23 May 1200,
1 CONT following prolonged negotiations between Philip Augustus and Blanche's uncle
1 CONT John of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis and England
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1216 the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John of England (1199-1216) and offered the throne to Prince
1 CONT Louis. Louis invaded and was proclaimed King in London in May 1216, although
1 CONT he was not crowned. There was little resistance when the prince entered
1 CONT London. At St Paul's Cathedral, Louis was accepted as ruler with great pomp
1 CONT and celebration in the presence of all of London. Many nobles, as well as King
1 CONT Alexander II of Scotland (1214-49), gathered to give homage to him.
1 CONT
1 CONT On June 14, Louis captured Winchester and soon conquered over half of the
1 CONT English kingdom.[1] After a year and a half of war, however, most of the
1 CONT rebellious barons defected and so Louis had to give up his claim to be the
1 CONT King of England by signing the Treaty of Lambeth in 1217. The effect of the
1 CONT treaty was that Louis agreed he had never been the legitimate king of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis VIII became ill with dysentery, and died
1 CONT on November 8, 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, Louis IX
1 CONT (1226-70), succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT After succeeding his father as king, Louis continued his father's policy of
1 CONT destroying the power of the Plantagenets in France and bringing under royal
1 CONT authority the Provinces held by the Albigences in the south of France. On his
1 CONT death, his son Louis IX, not yet 13 years old, was taken to Reims by his
1 CONT mother to be crowned King of France. Mother Blanche was not a woman to be
1 CONT discouraged by adversity, such as was shown at the coronation by a lack of
1 CONT participation by many of the most powerful nobles.
