1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (French: Louis VIII le Lion) (September 5, 1187 -November
1 CONT 8, 1226) reigned as King of France from 1223 to 1226. He wasa member of the
1 CONT Capetian dynasty. Louis was born in Paris, France, theson of King Philippe II
1 CONT Auguste and Isabelle of Hainaut.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a prince, Louis won battles against the armies of King John ofEngland. In
1 CONT 1216 the English barons rebelled against the veryunpopular King John and
1 CONT offered the throne to Louis. In May of 1216,Prince Louis of France and his
1 CONT army invaded England in what has becomeknown as the First Barons' War, but
1 CONT after a year and a half of war,Louis had to give up on his desire to become
1 CONT the King of England andsigned the Treaty of Lambeth.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis succeeded his father on July 14, 1223; his coronation took placeon
1 CONT August 6 of the same year in the cathedral at Reims. As king, hecontinued to
1 CONT seek revenge on the Angevins and seized Poitou andSaintonge from them in 1224.
1 CONT There followed the seizure of Avignon andLanguedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited hisofficials from
1 CONT recording debts owed to Jews, thus reversing thepolicies set by his father
1 CONT King Philippe II Auguste. Usuary (debt withinterest) was illegal for
1 CONT Christians to practice, according to Churchlaw it was seen as a vice to profit
1 CONT from others misfortune (likegambling), and was punishable by excommunication,
1 CONT a severe punishment.However since Jews were not Christian, they could not
1 CONT beexcommunicated, and thus fell in to a legal gray area which secularrulers
1 CONT would sometimes exploit by allowing (or requesting) Jews toprovide usuary
1 CONT services, often for personal gain to the secular ruler,and to the discontent
1 CONT of the Church. Louis' prohibition was oneattempt at resolving this legal
1 CONT problem which was a constant source offriction in Church and State courts.
1 CONT Twenty six barons accepted, butThibaut IV, a powerful baron from Champagne did
1 CONT not, since he had anagreement with the Jews that guaranteed him extra income
1 CONT throughtaxation. Thibaut IV would become a major opposition force to
1 CONT capetiandominance, and his hostility was manifest during the reign of
1 CONT LouisVIII. For example, during the siege of Avignon, he peformed only
1 CONT themiinimum service of 40 days, and left home amid charges of treachery.
1 CONT
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis became ill with dysentery, anddied on
1 CONT November 8, 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, LouisIX,
1 CONT succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage On May 23, 1200, at the age of twelve, Louis married Blancheof
1 CONT Castile (March 4, 1188 - November 26, 1252).
