1 CONT and received their submission, afteroverpowering Abignon.]
1 CONT Louis is described as short, thin and pale faced. He had a placid tem per and
1 CONT led a chaste life. As a child, Louis was not robust and had c ritical bout
1 CONT with disentery in 1191. He carried on the work of his fa ther, but lacked the
1 CONT stamina of his father. Though he left the reputa tion of a saint,he was also a
1 CONT warrior prince. He fought King John of England and Ferrand of Flander,
1 CONT defeating both in battle. In mid 1214 , Louis broke north from the area of
1 CONT Poitou and challenged the positio n of King John. His force included 1,200
1 CONT men-at-arms, 2,000 light hor se and 7,000 foot. In 1215, Louis laid claim to
1 CONT the English throne a s a result of his marriage to Blanche of Castile. At the
1 CONT time he was styled as a 'cold colourless - capable soldier with a streak of
1 CONT callou sness'. In November of 1215, Louis led a contingent of knights up th e
1 CONT Thames. Within a few months he came close to taking London, in asser tion of
1 CONT his fictional claim to the English crown. Louis maintained th at since he was
1 CONT no part of the truce between his father Phillippe and John, that he was still
1 CONT at war with King John whom he considered to b e a usuper. On 20 May 1216,
1 CONT Louis set sail for England and was sighte d off the coast of Thanet in East
1 CONT Kent on the 21st of May. His fleet numbered between 6 and 700 vessels
1 CONT commanded by Eustace the Monk - a w ell-to-do adventurer. They made landing,
1 CONT at Thanet on 22 March 1216 . Louis entered London on 2 June 1216, where he was
1 CONT received at St. P auls. He received homage from the mayor of London as well as
1 CONT Robert F itzWalter and then made for Winchester where John was held up. He ent
1 CONT ered Winchester on 14 June 1216 having already taken Reigate castle i n
1 CONT Surrey, Guildford castle and Farnham. Louis did not take the ruse o f John and
1 CONT stayed in the area of Winchester where he then turned back towards Oldham.
1 CONT Louis granted Marlborough castle to Robert de Dreux . During the negotiations
1 CONT during 1217 for the withdrawal from England , Louis promised to interced with
1 CONT his father Phillippe II in regard t o the restoration of Henry II's Angevin
1 CONT Continental fiefs.
1 CONT
1 CONT Throughout his reign as King of France, he was absorbed by two aims, t o
1 CONT destroy the power of the Plantagenets in England and to conquer sout hern
1 CONT France. After the death of his father, Louis retained all the co unselors of
1 CONT his father. Invited by English lords in rebellion agains t their king, Louis
1 CONT invaded England in 1216, although his action cause d his excommunication by
1 CONT Pope Innocent III. The death of John and the accession of Henry III as King of
1 CONT England lost Louis much support amon g the English nobility. After his defeat
1 CONT (1217) at Lincoln, he withdre w. In June of 1224, Louis bought the castle of
1 CONT Montreuil from Guillaum e de Masnieres. In 1224 he conquered Poitou from the
1 CONT English. To mak e his peace with the church, he pledged to go on crusade, and
1 CONT in 1226 he resumed the Albigensian Crusade and conquered most of Languedoc. H
1 CONT e also established royal power in the area of Poitou. He continued hi s
1 CONT father's policy of strong central authority.
