1 CONT Twenty six barons accepted, but Theobald IV of Champagne (1201 - 1253) , a
1 CONT powerful baron from Champagne did not, since he had an agreement w ith the
1 CONT Jews that guaranteed him extra income through taxation. Theoba ld IV would
1 CONT become a major opposition force to Capetian dominance, an d his hostility was
1 CONT manifest during the reign of Louis VIII. For examp le, during the siege of
1 CONT Avignon, he performed only the minimum servic e of 40 days, and left home amid
1 CONT charges of treachery. In 1225, the c ouncil of Bourges excommunicated the
1 CONT count of Toulouse, Raymond VII, a nd declared a crusade against the southern
1 CONT barons. Louis happily renew ed the conflict in order to enforce his royal
1 CONT rights. Roger Bernard th e Great, count of Foix, tried to keep the peace, but
1 CONT the king rejecte d his embassy and the counts of Foix and Toulouse took up
1 CONT arms agains t him. The king was largely successful, but he did not complete
1 CONT the wo rk before his death.
