1 CONT Louis VIII of France
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII the Lion (French: Louis VIII le Lion) (September 5, 1187 – November
1 CONT 8, 1226) reigned as King of France from 1223 to 1226. He was a member of the
1 CONT Capetian dynasty. Louis was born in Paris, France, the son of King Philippe II
1 CONT Auguste and Isabelle of Hainaut.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1216 the English barons rebelled in the First Barons' War against the
1 CONT unpopular King John and offered the throne to Louis. Louis invaded and was
1 CONT proclaimed king in London in May 1216, although he was not crowned. There was
1 CONT little resistance when the prince entered London. At St Paul's Cathedral,
1 CONT Louis was accepted as ruler with great pomp and celebration in the presence of
1 CONT all of London. Many nobles, including the King of Scotland, gathered to give
1 CONT homage to him. On June 14 he captured Winchester and soon conquered over half
1 CONT of the English kingdom. Since other English kings such as Edward V and Edward
1 CONT VIII were not crowned but only proclaimed, there is a good case for including
1 CONT Louis in the list of Kings of England. After a year and a half of war, most of
1 CONT the rebellious barons had defected and so Louis had to give up his claim to be
1 CONT the King of England by signing the Treaty of Lambeth in 1217.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Coronation of Louis VIII and Blanche of Castile at Reims in 1223; a miniature
1 CONT from the Grandes Chroniques de France, painted in the 1450s, kept at the
1 CONT National Library of FranceLouis succeeded his father on July 14, 1223; his
1 CONT coronation took place on August 6 of the same year in the cathedral at Reims.
1 CONT As king, he continued to seek revenge on the Angevins and seized Poitou and
1 CONT Saintonge from them in 1224. There followed the seizure of Avignon and
1 CONT Languedoc.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 1 November 1223, he issued an ordinance that prohibited his officials from
1 CONT recording debts owed to Jews, thus reversing the policies set by his father
1 CONT King Philippe II Auguste. Usury (lending money with interest) was illegal for
1 CONT Christians to practice, according to Church law it was seen as a vice in which
1 CONT people profited from others' misfortune (like gambling), and was punishable by
1 CONT excommunication, a severe punishment. However since Jews were not Christian,
1 CONT they could not be excommunicated, and thus fell in to a legal gray area which
1 CONT secular rulers would sometimes exploit by allowing (or requesting) Jews to
1 CONT provide usuary services, often for personal gain to the secular ruler, and to
1 CONT the discontent of the Church. Louis' prohibition was one attempt at resolving
1 CONT this legal problem which was a constant source of friction in Church and State
1 CONT courts.
1 CONT
1 CONT Twenty six barons accepted, but Thibaut IV, a powerful baron from Champagne
1 CONT did not, since he had an agreement with the Jews that guaranteed him extra
1 CONT income through taxation. Thibaut IV would become a major opposition force to
1 CONT Capetian dominance, and his hostility was manifest during the reign of Louis
1 CONT VIII. For example, during the siege of Avignon, he peformed only the minimum
1 CONT service of 40 days, and left home amid charges of treachery.
1 CONT
1 CONT While returning to Paris, King Louis became ill with dysentery, and died on
1 CONT November 8, 1226 in the chateau at Montpensier, Auvergne.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Saint Denis Basilica houses the tomb of Louis VIII. His son, Louis IX,
1 CONT succeeded him on the throne.
1 CONT
