1 CONT [from Rootsweb geneal database]
1 CONT Louis VIII, King of France 1223-26 was the son and successor of Philip II,
1 CONT (Philip Augustus). Before his succession he assisted his father in several
1 CONT campaigns to win control of French territories belonging to John, the Angevin,
1 CONT or Plantagenet, King of England. Philip II previously had conspired with John
1 CONT against John's brother, King Richard I, but later turned against him. in 1215
1 CONT Louis was offered the crown of England by a group of barons in rebellion
1 CONT against King John; Louis led an expedition to England but was unsuccessful in
1 CONT claiming the throne; John died in the midst of the struggle and was succeeded
1 CONT by his son Henry III. The French invaders were excommunicated by the papal
1 CONT legate in England and were defeated in battle at Lincoln. Louis returned to
1 CONT France in 1217 and there took part in crusades against a dissident religious
1 CONT sect called the Albigenses, or Cathars. After succeeding his father as King,
1 CONT Louis continued Philip's policy of destroying the power of the Plantagenets in
1 CONT France and bringing under royal authority the provinces held by the Albigenses
1 CONT in the south of France.
1 CONT Louis The Lion, or The Lion-heart, French Louis Le Lion, or Louis Coeur-de-
1 CONT lionCapetian king of France from 1223 who spent most of his short reign
1 CONT establishing royal power in Poitou and Languedoc.
1 CONT On May 23, 1200, Louis married Blanche of Castile, daughter of Alfonso VIII of
1 CONT Castile, who effectively acted as regent after Louis's death. In 1212 Louis
1 CONT seized Saint-Omer and Aire to prevent a powerful Flanders from being on the
1 CONT flank of his county of Artois. In1216, after the barons rebelling against King
1 CONT John of England had offered the English throne to Louis in return for his aid,
1 CONT Louis went to England to aid the rebels. Initially he was successful, but
1 CONT eventually he was defeated at sea and suffered defections. In 1217,when peace
1 CONT was concluded at Kingston, Louis was secretly paid 10,000 marks. In 1224, now
1 CONT king, he seized Poitou and, in 1226, he launched a successful crusade against
1 CONT the Albigensian heretics, capturing the major fortress of Avignon before
1 CONT returning toward Paris because of illness.
1 CONT Louis was the first Capetian to grant appanages on a large scale and to have a
1 CONT reversion clause that made alienation of royal property more difficult. Louis
1 CONT also developed other particular rights for the kingship, such as the concept
1 CONT that fealty was sworn not only to the individual king but also to the
1 CONT kingship. His eldest son, Louis IX (afterward St. Louis), peacefully succeeded
1 CONT him while his other sons received appanages.
