1 CONT Conrad IV of Germany
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad IV (25 April 1228 – 21 May 1254) was king of Jerusalem (as Conrad II)
1 CONT (1228–1254), of Germany (1237–1254), and of Sicily (as Conrad I) (1250–1254).
1 CONT
1 CONT He was a son of the Hohenstaufen Emperor Frederick II and the queen regnant of
1 CONT Jerusalem, Yolanda.
1 CONT
1 CONT Born in Andria, Conrad was the second but only surviving son of Frederick and
1 CONT Yolanda, who died while bearing him. Conrad lived in Italy until 1235, when he
1 CONT first visited Germany.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Frederick II deposed his eldest son, the rebellious Conrad's older
1 CONT brother Henry, in 1237 had Conrad elected King of the Romans in diet in
1 CONT Vienna. This title presumed a future as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire.
1 CONT Archbishop Siegfried III of Mainz acted as German regent until 1242, when
1 CONT Frederick chose Henry Raspe, Landgrave of Thuringia, and Wenceslaus I of
1 CONT Bohemia, to assume this function. Conrad intervened directly in German
1 CONT politics from around 1240.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, when Pope Innocent IV imposed a papal ban on Frederick in 1245 and
1 CONT declared Conrad deposed, Henry Raspe supported the pope and was in turn
1 CONT elected as anti-king of Germany on 22 May 1246. Henry Raspe defeated Conrad in
1 CONT the battle of Nidda in August 1246, but died several months later. He was
1 CONT succeeded as anti-king by William of Holland.
1 CONT
1 CONT Also in 1246, Conrad married Elisabeth of Bavaria, a daughter of Otto II
1 CONT Wittelsbach, Duke of Bavaria. They had a son, Conradin, in 1252. In 1250
1 CONT Conrad settled momentarily the situation in Germany by defeating William of
1 CONT Holland and his Rhenish allies.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Frederick II died in the same year, he passed Sicily and Germany, as well
1 CONT as the title of Jerusalem, to Conrad, but the struggle with the pope
1 CONT continued. Having been defeated by William in 1251, Conrad decided to invade
1 CONT Italy in 1251 in the hope to regain the rich reign of his father, and where
1 CONT his brother Manfred acted as vicar. He was however not able to subdue the
1 CONT pope's supporters, and the pope in turn offered Sicily to Edmund Crouchback,
1 CONT son of Henry III of England (1253).
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad was excommunicated in 1254, but died of a malaria in the same year at
1 CONT Lavello in Basilicata. Manfred first, and later his infant son Conradin,
1 CONT continued the struggle with the Papacy, although unsuccessfully.
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad's widow Elisabeth married second Meinhard II, Count of Tirol, who in
1 CONT 1286 became Duke of Carinthia.
1 CONT
1 CONT With Conrad's death in 1254 began the "Interregnum", during which no ruler
1 CONT managed to gain undisputed control of Germany. It would only be ended with the
1 CONT election of Rudolph of Habsburg as King of the Romans in 1273.[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT References
1 CONT
1 CONT ^ Judith Bennet and Clive Hollister, Medieval Europe, a Short History - p.
1 CONT 260.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conrad_IV_of_Germany>
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad IV (25 April 1228 – 21 May 1254) was king of Jerusalem (as Conrad II;
1 CONT 1228–1254), of Germany (1237–1254), and of Sicily (as Conrad I; 1250–1254).
1 CONT
1 CONT He was a son of the Hohenstaufen Emperor Frederick II and the queen regnant of
1 CONT Jerusalem, Yolanda. Born in Andria, Conrad was the second but only surviving
1 CONT son of Frederick and Yolanda, who died while bearing him. Conrad lived in
1 CONT Italy until 1235, when he first visited Germany. During this period his
1 CONT kingdom of Jerusalem, ruled by his father as regent through proxies, was
1 CONT racked by the War of the Lombards until Conrad declared his majority and his
1 CONT father's regency lost its validity.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Frederick II deposed his eldest son, Conrad's rebellious older brother
1 CONT Henry, in 1237 had Conrad elected King of the Romans in diet in Vienna. This
1 CONT title presumed a future as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire. Archbishop
1 CONT Siegfried III of Mainz acted as German regent until 1242, when Frederick chose
1 CONT Henry Raspe, Landgrave of Thuringia, and Wenceslaus I of Bohemia, to assume
1 CONT this function. Conrad intervened directly in German politics from around 1240.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, when Pope Innocent IV imposed a papal ban on Frederick in 1245 and
1 CONT declared Conrad deposed, Henry Raspe supported the pope and was in turn
1 CONT elected as anti-king of Germany on 22 May 1246. Henry Raspe defeated Conrad in
1 CONT the battle of Nidda in August 1246, but died several months later. He was
1 CONT succeeded as anti-king by William of Holland.
1 CONT
1 CONT Also in 1246, Conrad married Elisabeth of Bavaria, a daughter of Otto II
1 CONT Wittelsbach, Duke of Bavaria. They had a son, Conradin, in 1252. In 1250
1 CONT Conrad settled momentarily the situation in Germany by defeating William of
1 CONT Holland and his Rhenish allies.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Frederick II died in the same year, he passed Sicily and Germany, as well
1 CONT as the title of Jerusalem, to Conrad, but the struggle with the pope
1 CONT continued. Having been defeated by William in 1251, Conrad decided to invade
1 CONT Italy in 1251 in the hope to regain the rich reign of his father, and where
1 CONT his brother Manfred acted as vicar. In January 1252 he invaded Apulia with a
1 CONT Venetian fleet and successfully managed to restrain Manfred and to exercise
1 CONT control of the country. In October 1253 his troops conquered Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad was however not able to subdue the pope's supporters, and the pope in
1 CONT turn offered Sicily to Edmund Crouchback, son of Henry III of England (1253).
1 CONT Conrad was excommunicated in 1254 and died of malaria in the same year at
1 CONT Lavello in Basilicata. Manfred first, and later his infant son Conradin,
1 CONT continued the struggle with the Papacy, although unsuccessfully.
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad's widow Elisabeth married second Meinhard II, Count of Tirol, who in
1 CONT 1286 became Duke of Carinthia.
1 CONT
1 CONT With Conrad's death in 1254 began the "Interregnum", during which no ruler
1 CONT managed to gain undisputed control of Germany. It would only be ended with the
1 CONT election of Rudolph of Habsburg as King of the Romans in 1273.[1]
1 CONT KING OF GERMANY 1250-1254
1 CONT Conrad IV (1228-54), emperor of Germany, of the house of Hohenstaufen, was the
1 CONT second son of the Emperor Frederick II. Elected king of the Romans (1237), he
1 CONT governed Germany during the long absence of his father in Italy, and after his
1 CONT death (1250) became emperor. Confronted with the enmity of the Pope, who
1 CONT excommunicated him, he was preparing to invade Germany at the head of a great
1 CONT army to reestablish his authority there, when he died of fever at Lavello.
1 CONT [World Wide Illustrated Encyclopedia, 1935]
1 CONT Conrad IV (1228-54), king of Germany (1237-54), son of Frederick II, the
1 CONT last great Holy Roman emperor of the Hohenstaufen dynasty. During his
1 CONT father's lifetime, in 1237, Conrad was elected king of the Romans while
1 CONT Frederick ruled Italy and Sicily. Pope Innocent IV deposed Frederick II in
1 CONT 1245, and the papal faction of princes in Germany elected Henry Raspe,
1 CONT count of Thuringia (1202?-47), as antiking in 1246. Germany was beset by
1 CONT conflict, which continued after Raspe's death with the election in 1248 of
1 CONT another antiking, William of Holland. After the death of Frederick II in
1 CONT 1250, William and Conrad both claimed the succession as Holy Roman
1 CONT emperor, but neither was crowned. Conrad succeeded his father as king of
1 CONT Sicily and consolidated his position by conquering his native Apulia and
1 CONT the cities of Capua and Naples in Italy. Conrad was the last of the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen dynasty; his son, Conradin (1252-68), never became king.
1 CONT Germany and the empire had no recognized ruler for 19 years following his
1 CONT reign. The period has thus been designated the Great Interregnum of the
1 CONT Holy Roman Empire.
1 CONT Conrad was heir to the kingdom of Jerusalem through his mother, Isabella de
1 CONT Brenne, and duke of Swabia in 1235. He replaced his half-brother Henry VII as
1 CONT King of the Romans, Henry having rebelled against their father, Frederick II,
1 CONT in 1235. When his father died later in 1250, William of Holland forced Conrad
1 CONT to abandon Germany for Sicily, when he took the title of King of Sicily in
1 CONT 1251.
1 CONT Conrad IV of Germany
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad IV (25 April 1228 – 21 May 1254) was king of Jerusalem (as Conrad II)
1 CONT (1228–1254), of Germany (1237–1254), and of Sicily (as Conrad I) (1250–1254).
1 CONT
1 CONT He was a son of the Hohenstaufen Emperor Frederick II and the queen regnant of
1 CONT Jerusalem, Yolanda.
1 CONT
1 CONT Born in Andria, Conrad was the second but only surviving son of Frederick and
1 CONT Yolanda, who died while bearing him. Conrad lived in Italy until 1235, when he
1 CONT first visited Germany.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Frederick II deposed his eldest son, the rebellious Conrad's older
1 CONT brother Henry, in 1237 had Conrad elected King of the Romans in diet in
1 CONT Vienna. This title presumed a future as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire.
1 CONT Archbishop Siegfried III of Mainz acted as German regent until 1242, when
1 CONT Frederick chose Henry Raspe, Landgrave of Thuringia, and Wenceslaus I of
1 CONT Bohemia, to assume this function. Conrad intervened directly in German
1 CONT politics from around 1240.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, when Pope Innocent IV imposed a papal ban on Frederick in 1245 and
1 CONT declared Conrad deposed, Henry Raspe supported the pope and was in turn
1 CONT elected as anti-king of Germany on 22 May 1246. Henry Raspe defeated Conrad in
1 CONT the battle of Nidda in August 1246, but died several months later. He was
1 CONT succeeded as anti-king by William of Holland.
1 CONT
1 CONT Also in 1246, Conrad married Elisabeth of Bavaria, a daughter of Otto II
1 CONT Wittelsbach, Duke of Bavaria. They had a son, Conradin, in 1252. In 1250
1 CONT Conrad settled momentarily the situation in Germany by defeating William of
1 CONT Holland and his Rhenish allies.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Frederick II died in the same year, he passed Sicily and Germany, as well
1 CONT as the title of Jerusalem, to Conrad, but the struggle with the pope
1 CONT continued. Having been defeated by William in 1251, Conrad decided to invade
1 CONT Italy in 1251 in the hope to regain the rich reign of his father, and where
1 CONT his brother Manfred acted as vicar. He was however not able to subdue the
1 CONT pope's supporters, and the pope in turn offered Sicily to Edmund Crouchback,
1 CONT son of Henry III of England (1253).
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad was excommunicated in 1254, but died of a malaria in the same year at
1 CONT Lavello in Basilicata. Manfred first, and later his infant son Conradin,
1 CONT continued the struggle with the Papacy, although unsuccessfully.
1 CONT
1 CONT Conrad's widow Elisabeth married second Meinhard II, Count of Tirol, who in
1 CONT 1286 became Duke of Carinthia.
1 CONT
1 CONT With Conrad's death in 1254 began the "Interregnum", during which no ruler
1 CONT managed to gain undisputed control of Germany. It would only be ended with the
