1 CONT
1 CONT Maria Árpád de Hongrie (1257–1323)
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Arpad_of_Hungary>
1 CONT
1 CONT Mary of Hungary (c. 1257 – 25 March 1323) of the Árpád dynasty was Queen
1 CONT consort of Kingdom of Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was (possibly the eldest) daughter of Stephen V of Hungary (d. 1272) and
1 CONT his wife, Elizabeth the Cuman, who was daughter of Zayhan of Kuni, a chief of
1 CONT the Cuman tribe and had been a pagan before her marriage. Her brother
1 CONT Ladislaus IV of Hungary ruled as king from 1272 to 1290.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1270 when twelve, she married the future Charles II of Naples (1254 –
1 CONT 1309), the eldest son and heir of Charles I of Sicily and Beatrice of
1 CONT Provence. They had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1.Charles Martel of Anjou,(1271-1295) titular King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT 2.Saint Louis of Toulouse (February 9, 1275, Nocera – August 19, 1298, Chateau
1 CONT de Brignoles), Bishop of Toulouse
1 CONT
1 CONT 3.Robert I of Naples, (1277-1343) King of Naples
1 CONT
1 CONT 4.Philip I of Taranto, (1278-1331) Prince of Achaea and Taranto, Despot of
1 CONT Romania, Lord of Durazzo, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT
1 CONT 5.Raymond Berengar (1281–1307), Count of Provence, Prince of Piedmont and
1 CONT Andria
1 CONT
1 CONT 6.John (1283 – aft. March 16, 1308), a priest
1 CONT
1 CONT 7.Tristan (1284–bef. 1288)
1 CONT
1 CONT 8.Peter (1291 – August 29, 1315, Battle of Montecatini), Count of Gravina
1 CONT
1 CONT 9.John of Gravina (1294 – April 5, 1336, Naples), Duke of Durazzo, Prince of
1 CONT Achaea, and Count of Gravina, married March 1318 (divorced 1321) Matilda of
1 CONT Hainaut (November 29, 1293–1336), and married secondly November 14, 1321 Agnes
1 CONT of Périgord (d. 1345)
1 CONT
1 CONT 10.Marguerite of Anjou and Maine (1273– December 31, 1299), Countess of Anjou
1 CONT and Maine, married at Corbeil August 16, 1290 Charles of Valois, brother of
1 CONT king of France, and became ancestress of the Valois dynasty
1 CONT
1 CONT 11.Blanche of Anjou (1280 – October 14, 1310, Barcelona), married at
1 CONT Villebertran November 1, 1295 James II of Aragon
1 CONT
1 CONT 12.Eleanor of Anjou, (August 1289 – August 9, 1341, Monastery of St. Nicholas,
1 CONT Arene, Elis), married at Messina May 17, 1302 Frederick III of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT 13.Mary (Maria) (1290 – c. 1346), married at Palma de Majorca September 20,
1 CONT 1304 Sancho I of Majorca, married 1326 Jaime de Ejerica (1298 – April 1335)
1 CONT
1 CONT 14.Beatrice (1295 – c. 1321), married April 1305 Azzo VIII, Margrave d'Este
1 CONT (d. 1308), married 1309 Bertrand III of Baux, Count of Andria (d. 1351)
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 – 25 March 1323) of the Árpád dynasty was Queen
1 CONT consort of Kingdom of Naples. She was a daughter of Stephen V of Hungary and
1 CONT his wife Elizabeth the Cuman.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria's mother followed the Shamanist religion, like other Cumans. She was
1 CONT considered a Pagan by contemporary Christians of Europe. Elizabeth had to
1 CONT convert to the Roman Catholic faith in order to marry Maria's father, Stephen.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria was the second of six children. Her sisters Elizabeth and Catherine both
1 CONT became Queen of Serbia. Another sister, Anna married Andronikos II
1 CONT Palaiologos. Maria's only brother was Ladislaus IV of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandparents were Béla IV of Hungary and his wife Maria
1 CONT Laskarina. Her maternal grandparents were Köten, leader of a tribe of Cumans,
1 CONT his wife was Mstislawna, a Russian noblewomen who may have royal connections.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1270 when Maria was only twelve years of age, she married the future
1 CONT Charles II of Naples (1254–1309), the eldest son and heir of Charles I of
1 CONT Sicily and his wife Beatrice of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT On the 10 July 1290, Maria's brother, Ladislaus IV of Hungary died childless.
1 CONT The question now was who would succeed him? He had four sisters, three of them
1 CONT outlived him, all four had married powerful rulers and had had their own
1 CONT children. On the 21 September 1290, Maria claimed the throne of Hungary. She
1 CONT was up against her two sisters: Catherine, Elisabeth and their children, plus
1 CONT the children of her younger sister Anna. Maria was crowned Queen by a Papal
1 CONT legate in Naples 1291, but transferred her rights to her eldest son, Charles
1 CONT Martel of Anjou. The Pope confirmed her sole rights in Hungary on the 30
1 CONT August 1295. However, Catherine's son, Stefan Vladislav II of Syrmia was still
1 CONT a dangerous rival for Maria and Charles Martel. In the end, Charles Martel
1 CONT gave his cousin Slavonia as a compromise.
1 CONT
1 CONT Charles Martel was only titular King of Hungary, it was Maria's grandson who
1 CONT became King, Charles I of Hungary. Ultimately the claims of the sisters Mary
1 CONT and Catherine were united in a common descendant when the pair's great-great-
1 CONT granddaughter, Mary of Hungary, ascended to the Hungarian throne in 1382.
1 CONT
1 CONT During 1290, Maria's sister Elisabeth fled from Bohemia with her son because
1 CONT her husband had lost favour and was executed, Maria allowed Elisabeth and her
1 CONT son to stay in Naples with her, before she became a nun, but escaped and
1 CONT remarried to Stefan Uroš II Milutin of Serbia (brother of Catherine's husband)
1 CONT Elizabeth's stay in Naples is documented during July 1300.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria's husband died in August 1309, Maria was now a widow. She lived in
1 CONT Naples for the rest of her life, where she died on 25 March 1323, she was
1 CONT buried in Naples at the Santa Maria Donna Regina.
1 CONT
1 CONT Children
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria and her husband, Charles had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Charles Martel of Anjou,(1271-1295) titular King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Saint Louis of Toulouse (February 9, 1275, Nocera – August 19, 1298,
1 CONT Chateau de Brignoles), Bishop of Toulouse
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Robert I of Naples, (1277-1343)King of Naples
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. Philip I of Taranto, (1278-1331)Prince of Achaea and Taranto, Despot of
1 CONT Romania, Lord of Durazzo, titular Emperor of Constantinople
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. Raymond Berengar (1281–1307), Count of Provence, Prince of Piedmont and
1 CONT Andria
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. John (1283 – aft. March 16, 1308), a priest
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. Tristan (1284–bef. 1288)
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. Peter (1291 – August 29, 1315, Battle of Montecatini), Count of Gravina
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. John of Gravina (1294 – April 5, 1336, Naples), Duke of Durazzo, Prince of
1 CONT Achaea, and Count of Gravina, married March 1318 (divorced 1321) Matilda of
1 CONT Hainaut (November 29, 1293–1336), and married secondly November 14, 1321 Agnes
1 CONT of Périgord (d. 1345)
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. Marguerite of Anjou and Maine (1273– December 31, 1299), Countess of
1 CONT Anjou and Maine, married at Corbeil August 16, 1290 Charles of Valois, brother
1 CONT of king of France, and became ancestress of the Valois dynasty
1 CONT
1 CONT 11\. Blanche of Anjou (1280 – October 14, 1310, Barcelona), married at
1 CONT Villebertran November 1, 1295 James II of Aragon
1 CONT
1 CONT 12\. Eleanor of Anjou, (August 1289 – August 9, 1341, Monastery of St.
1 CONT Nicholas, Arene, Elis), married at Messina May 17, 1302 Frederick III of
1 CONT Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT 13\. Mary (Maria) (1290 – c. 1346), married at Palma de Majorca September 20,
1 CONT 1304 Sancho I of Majorca, married 1326 Jaime de Ejerica (1298 – April 1335)
1 CONT
1 CONT 14\. Beatrice (1295 – c. 1321), married April 1305 Azzo VIII, Margrave d'Este
1 CONT (d. 1308), married 1309 Bertrand III of Baux, Count of Andria (d. 1351)
1 CONT
1 CONT \-----------------------
