0 @N00521@ NOTE Saint Theodora of Arta
0 @N00522@ NOTE geni:about_me *<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodora_of_Arta>
1 CONT
1 CONT The holy and right-believing Empress Theodora of Arta was the wife of Michael
1 CONT II Komnenos Doukas who was the ruler (Emperor) of Epiros in the thirteenth
1 CONT century, during the time of Latin rule of Constantinople. She endured
1 CONT suffering from abuse by her husband, being forced into exile without
1 CONT complaint, and maintained a life of humility, asceticism, and charity. She is
1 CONT commemorated by the Church on March 11.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT What is known of the life of Theodora is from a vita contained in a fifteenth
1 CONT or sixteenth century manuscript attributed to a monk named Job. In view of the
1 CONT many errors of chronology and genealogy in the vita, as well as its style, the
1 CONT attribution of the vita to a Job Iasites has been questioned.
1 CONT
1 CONT Theodora was the daughter of John and Helena Petraliphas. John Petraliphas was
1 CONT a sebastokrator and ruler of Macedonia and Thessaly. Theodora is thought to
1 CONT have been born about 1225 as Theodora Dukaina Petraliphaina. She married
1 CONT Michael II Komnenos Doukas Notho Angelos shortly after he became ruler of
1 CONT Epiros about 1231 (about the age of 6, uncanonical for marriage). Through this
1 CONT marriage they had six children, including Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas, Anna
1 CONT (Agnes) Komnenodukaina, Lady of Kalamata and Clermont, who married Prince
1 CONT Guillaume II de Villehardouin of Achaea and then Nicholas II of Saint-Omer,
1 CONT Lord of Achaia.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was noted as a person who was not carried away with her new position as
1 CONT empress nor with her luxurious life. Early in their marriage, Michael II
1 CONT became enamored by a noblewoman, causing Michael to reject Theodora. She was
1 CONT banished under a decree that she was not to be supported. She existed in exile
1 CONT by living "off the land" in the open for five years, nobly enduring her life
1 CONT without complaint. During her exile she maintained her virtue, although
1 CONT reduced to picking wild greens for food and while caring for her son whom she
1 CONT bore in exile. A priest from the village of Preniste found her while she was
1 CONT collecting wild greens, and after getting her to identify herself, he took
1 CONT her, with her son, under his care and concealed her until court officials
1 CONT drove the wicked noblewoman out and returned Michael to his senses.
1 CONT
1 CONT Michael then took Theodora back into his house. Until Michael died, the couple
1 CONT lived virtuously in peace and love, raising their family of children. Michael
1 CONT established two monasteries, Pantanassa and Panagia, while Theodora founded a
1 CONT women's monastery dedicated to the great martyr George, that later was named
1 CONT for St. Theodora.
1 CONT
1 CONT After the death of her husband, about 1267 or 1268, Theodora entered
1 CONT monasticism and lived a pious life of praying, attending vigils, serving
1 CONT orphans and widows, and the other nuns. She is closely associated with Ss.
1 CONT Athanasia of Aegina and Theodora of Thessalonike, as well as Ss. Matrona of
1 CONT Chios, Thomais of Lesbos, and Mary the Younger who like her suffered abuse at
1 CONT the hands of their husbands.
1 CONT
1 CONT Theodora foresaw the time of her death; her tomb attracted popular veneration
1 CONT soon after her death and continues to do so to this day.
1 CONT
1 CONT \---------
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/BYZANTINE%20NOBILITY.htm#TheodoraDPetraliphainaMMikhaelIIEpirus>
1 CONT
1 CONT a) **THEODORA Doukaina Petraloifaina Basilissa** (bur Arta). Her parentage is
1 CONT indicated by Georgios Akropolites who names "Petraliphas…uxoris Michaelis
1 CONT frater"[532]. Ephræmius names "Theodora Michaelis coniux" when recording that
1 CONT she attended the marriage of her son Nikeforos[533]. Her husband banished her
1 CONT in favour of his mistress but restored her to favour[534]. After attending her
1 CONT son's marriage to the daughter of Theodoros II Emperor in Nikaia in 1256, she
1 CONT was kept a hostage and only released after her husband surrendered Durazzo to
1 CONT Nikaia[535]. She became a nun, known as Holy Theodora of Arta, and was the
1 CONT subject of a hagiography by the 13th century monk Job (Melias Iasites)[536].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** ( [1230], divorced Easter [1252/56] ) MIKHAEL [II] Komnenos Doukas
1 CONT Angelos Lord of Epirus, despot, illegitimate son of MIKHAEL Komnenos Doukas
1 CONT Lord of Epirus & his mistress --- ([1205]-[1267/68]).
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT \-----------
