1 CONT
1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV (1195 – 19 August 1245), Count of Provence and Forcalquier,
1 CONT was the son of Alfonso II of Provence and Garsenda of Sabran, heiress of
1 CONT Forcalquier. After his father's death (1209), Ramon was imprisoned in the
1 CONT castle of Monzón, in Aragon until he was able to escape in 1219 and claim his
1 CONT inheritance. He was a powerful and energetic ruler who added Forcalquier to
1 CONT his domain.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 5 June 1219, Ramon married Beatrice of Savoy, daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty was likened
1 CONT by Matthew Paris to that of a second Niobe. Along with two stillborn sons
1 CONT (1220 & 1225), Ramon and Beatrice had four daughters, all of whom married
1 CONT kings.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marguerite of Provence (1221–1295), wife of Louis IX of France
1 CONT
1 CONT Eleanor of Provence (1223–1291), wife of Henry III of England
1 CONT
1 CONT Sanchia of Provence (1228–1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Provence (1234–1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV died in Aix-en-Provence.
1 CONT
