1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV (1195 – 19 August 1245), Count of Provence and Forcalquier,
1 CONT was the son of Alfonso II of Provence and Garsenda of Sabran, heiress of
1 CONT Forcalquier. After his father's death (1209), Ramon was imprisoned in the
1 CONT castle of Monzón, in Aragon until he was able to escape in 1219 and claim his
1 CONT inheritance. He was a powerful and energetic ruler who added Forcalquier to
1 CONT his domain. Giovanni Villani in his Nuova Cronica had this to say about
1 CONT Raymond:
1 CONT
1 CONT Count Raymond was a lord of gentle lineage, and kin to them of the house of
1 CONT Aragon, and to the family of the count of Toulouse, By inheritance Provence,
1 CONT this side of the Rhone, was his; a wise and courteous lord was he, and of
1 CONT noble state and virtuous, and in his time did honourable deeds, and to his
1 CONT court came all gentle persons of Provence and of France and of Catalonia, by
1 CONT reason of his courtesy and noble estate, and he made many Provençal coblas and
1 CONT canzoni of great worth.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 5 June 1219, Ramon married Beatrice of Savoy, daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty was likened
1 CONT by Matthew Paris to that of a second Niobe. Along with two stillborn sons
1 CONT (1220 & 1225), Ramon and Beatrice had four daughters, all of whom married
1 CONT kings.
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Marguerite of Provence (1221–1295), wife of Louis IX of France
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Eleanor of Provence (1223–1291), wife of Henry III of England
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Sanchia of Provence (1228–1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. Beatrice of Provence (1234–1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV died in Aix-en-Provence. At least two planhs (Occitan
1 CONT funeral laments) of uncertain authorship (one possibly by Aimeric de Peguilhan
1 CONT and one falsely attributed to Rigaut de Berbezilh) were written in his honour.
1 CONT
