1 CONT From <http://www.rpi.edu/~holmes/Hobbies/Genealogy/ps03/ps03_415.htm>
1 CONT
1 CONT "Ancestral Roots..." (Balt., 1992) 111-29 states he b. 1198.
1 CONT
1 CONT Weis' "Ancestral Roots. . ." (101:28), (104:28), (111:29), (133:27).
1 CONT
1 CONT Stuart's "Royalty For Commoners" (54:26) & (164:27).
1 CONT
1 CONT By Ramon's time Provence had been at peace for two and a half centuries. There
1 CONT were few lands that had enjoyed peace and prosperity with so little
1 CONT interruption. Since the end of the tenth century Provence had grown more in
1 CONT population and wealth than any other part of Europe. Few men in history have
1 CONT been more successful in finding powerful and influential mates for their
1 CONT daughters than Ramon. His four daughters married two sets of brothers - all of
1 CONT them kings! Margaret married King Louis IX of France; ELEANOR married KING
1 CONT HENRY III OF ENGLAND; Sanchia married HENRY's brother, Richard of Cornwall,
1 CONT who was recognized for a
1 CONT
1 CONT time as the German Emporer; and Beatrice, the youngest and his appointed heir,
1 CONT married Louis' brother, Charles of Anjou, who at one time or another held the
1 CONT titles King of Sicily and King of Jerusalem and was
1 CONT
1 CONT briefly master of most of Italy and Greece. He was almost able to make an
1 CONT independent state of Burgundy.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ramon bequeathed to Beatrice an administrative machine to be rivaled only by
1 CONT those created by the Normans in England and Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT Europaische Stammtafeln ii, 190:
