1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV
1 CONT
1 CONT Count of Provence Reign 1209-1245 Predecessor Alfonso II Successor Beatrice
1 CONT Count of Forcalquier Reign 1217 or 1220-1245 Predecessor Garsenda Successor
1 CONT Beatrice
1 CONT
1 CONT Born 1198 Unknown Died 19 August 1245 (aged 47) Aix-en-Provence Burial Église
1 CONT Saint-Jean-de-Malte Spouse Beatrice of Savoy Issue Marguerite, Queen of France
1 CONT Eleanor, Queen of England Sanchia, Queen of Germany Beatrice, Queen of Sicily
1 CONT House Barcelona Father Alfonso II, Count of Provence Mother Garsenda, Countess
1 CONT of Forcalquier Religion Roman Catholicism Ramon Berenguer IV or V (1198 - 19
1 CONT August 1245), Count of Provence and Forcalquier , was the son of Alfonso II of
1 CONT Provence and Garsenda de Sabran , heiress of Forcalquier . He was the first
1 CONT Count of Provence to live in the county in more than one hundred years. Career
1 CONT After his father's death (1209), Ramon's mother sent him to the Templar castle
1 CONT of Monzón , in Aragon. He was accompanied by his cousin King Jaume I of Aragon
1 CONT whose life was also under threat. He left Monzon around 1217 to claim his
1 CONT inheritance, which included the county of Forcalquier--inherited from his
1 CONT mother. He and his wife were known for their support of troubadors , always
1 CONT having some around the court. He was known for his generosity, though his
1 CONT income did not always keep up. He wrote laws prohibiting nobles from
1 CONT performing menial work, such as farming or heavy labor. Ramon had many border
1 CONT disputes with his neighbors, the Counts of Toulouse . In 1226, Ramon began to
1 CONT reassert his right to rule in Marseille . The citizens there initially sought
1 CONT the help of Ramon's father-in-law Thomas, Count of Savoy in his role as
1 CONT imperial vicar . However, they later sought the help of Raymond VII, Count of
1 CONT Toulouse. In 1228, Ramon supported his father-in-law in a double-sided
1 CONT conflict against Turin and Guigues VI of Viennois . This small war was one of
1 CONT many rounds intended to more firmly establish control over trade from Italy
1 CONT into France, and Provence included several key routes. While the Albigensian
1 CONT Crusade worked in his favor against Toulouse, Ramon was concerned that its
1 CONT resolution in the Treaty of Paris left him in a precarious position. Raymond
1 CONT turned his troops from fighting France to attempting to claim lands from
1 CONT Provence. When Blanche of Castile sent her knight to both Toulouse and
1 CONT Provence in 1233, Ramon entertained him lavishly, and the knight left well
1 CONT impressed by both the count and his eldest daughter, Margaret . Soon after,
1 CONT Blanche negotiated the marriage between Margaret and her son, Louis , with a
1 CONT dowry of ten thousand silver marks. Ramon had to get contributions from allies
1 CONT for a portion, and had to pledge several of his castles to cover the rest.
1 CONT Ramon and Beatrice travelled with their daughter to Lyon in 1234 to sign the
1 CONT marriage treaty, and then Margaret was escorted to her wedding in Sens by her
1 CONT uncles from Savoy, William and Thomas. Shortly after, William began
1 CONT negotiating on Ramon's behalf with Henry III of England to marry his daughter
1 CONT Eleanor. Henry sent his own knight to Provence early in 1235, and again Ramon
1 CONT and his family entertained him lavishly. Henry wrote to William on June 22
1 CONT that he was very interested, and sent a delegation to negotiate the marriage
1 CONT in October. Henry was seeking a dowry of up to twenty thousand silver marks to
1 CONT help offset the dowry he had just paid for his sister, Isabella. However, he
1 CONT had drafted seven different versions of the marriage contract, with different
1 CONT amounts for the dowry, the lowest being zero. Ramon shrewdly negotiated for
1 CONT that option, offering as consolation a promise to leave her ten thousand marks
1 CONT when he died. In 1238, Ramon joined his brother-in-law, Amadeus IV at the
1 CONT court of Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor in Turin. Frederick was gathering
1 CONT forces to assert more control in Italy. Raymond VII of Toulouse was also
1 CONT summoned, and all expected to work together in the war. In January 1244, Pope
1 CONT Innocent IV decreed that no one but the pope could excommunicate Ramon. In
1 CONT 1245, Ramon sent representatives to the First Council of Lyon , to discuss
1 CONT crusades and the excommunication of Frederick. Ramon died in August 1245 in
1 CONT Aix-en-Provence , leaving the county to his youngest daughter, Beatrice.
1 CONT Marriage and children On 5 June 1219, Ramon married Beatrice of Savoy ,
1 CONT daughter of Thomas, Count of Savoy . She was a shrewd and politically astute
1 CONT woman, whose beauty was likened by Matthew Paris to that of a second Niobe .
1 CONT The wedding also provided the 21-year-old Ramon with a powerful father-in-law
1 CONT to aid him in establishing his authority and protecting his interests.[8] They
1 CONT had four daughters who reached adulthood, all of whom married kings .
1 CONT stillborn son (1220) Margaret of Provence (1221-1295), wife of Louis IX, King
1 CONT of France Eleanor of Provence (1223-1291), wife of Henry III, King of England
1 CONT stillborn son (1225) Sanchia of Provence (1228-1261), wife of Richard, King of
1 CONT the Romans , brother of the King of England Beatrice of Provence
1 CONT (1229-1267),[9] wife of Charles I, King of Sicily His daughters were all
1 CONT educated and literate. Death and legacy Ramon Berenguer IV died in Aix-en-
1 CONT Provence . At least two planhs (Occitan funeral laments) of uncertain
1 CONT authorship (one possibly by Aimeric de Peguilhan and one falsely attributed to
1 CONT Rigaut de Berbezilh ) were written in his honour. Giovanni Villani in his
1 CONT Nuova Cronica had this to say about Raymond: Count Raymond was a lord of
1 CONT gentle lineage, and kin to them of the house of Aragon, and to the family of
1 CONT the count of Toulouse, By inheritance Provence, this side of the Rhone, was
1 CONT his; a wise and courteous lord was he, and of noble state and virtuous, and in
1 CONT his time did honourable deeds, and to his court came all gentle persons of
1 CONT Provence and of France and of Catalonia, by reason of his courtesy and noble
1 CONT estate, and he made many Provençal coblas and canzoni of great worth.
