1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche of Castile (March 4, 1188 – November 26, 1252), wife of Louis VIII of
1 CONT France. She was born in Palencia, Spain, the third daughter of Alfonso VIII,
1 CONT king of Castile, and of Eleanor of England. Eleanor was a daughter of Henry II
1 CONT of England and his Queen consort Eleanor of Aquitaine.
1 CONT
1 CONT In consequence of a treaty between Philip Augustus and John of England,
1 CONT Blanche's sister Urraca was betrothed to the former's son, Louis. Their
1 CONT grandmother Eleanor, upon getting acquainted with the two sisters, judged that
1 CONT Blanche's personality was more fit for a queen of France. In the spring of
1 CONT 1200 she brought her to France instead. On May 22, 1200 the treaty was finally
1 CONT signed, John ceding with his niece the fiefs of Issoudun and Gracay, together
1 CONT with those that André de Chauvigny, lord of Châteauroux, held in Berry, of the
1 CONT English crown. The marriage was celebrated the next day, at Portmort on the
1 CONT right bank of the Seine, in John's domains, as those of Philip lay under an
1 CONT interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche first displayed her great qualities in 1216, when Louis, who on the
1 CONT death of John claimed the English crown in her right, invaded England, only to
1 CONT find a united nation against him. Philip Augustus refused to help his son, and
1 CONT Blanche was his sole support. The queen established herself at Calais and
1 CONT organized two fleets, one of which was commanded by Eustace the Monk, and an
1 CONT army under Robert of Courtenay; but all her resolution and energy were in
1 CONT vain. Although it would seem that her masterful temper exercised a sensible
1 CONT influence upon her husband's gentler character, her role during his reign
1 CONT (1223-1226) is not well known.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his death he left Blanche regent and guardian of his children. Of her
1 CONT twelve or thirteen children, six had died, and Louis, the heir – afterwards
1 CONT the sainted Louis IX – was but twelve years old. The situation was critical,
1 CONT for the hard-won domains of the house of Capet seemed likely to fall to pieces
1 CONT during a minority. Blanche had to bear the whole burden of affairs alone, to
1 CONT break up a league of the barons (1226), and to repel the attack of the king of
1 CONT England (1230). But her energy and firmness overcame all dangers. There was an
1 CONT end to the calumnies circulated against her, based on the poetical homage
1 CONT rendered her by Theobald IV of Champagne, and the prolonged stay in Paris of
1 CONT the papal legate, Romano Bonaventura, cardinal of Sant' Angelo.
1 CONT
1 CONT The nobles were awed by her warlike preparations or won over by adroit
1 CONT diplomacy, and their league was broken up. St Louis owed his realm to his
1 CONT mother, but he himself always remained somewhat under the spell of her
1 CONT imperious personality. After he came of age, in 1234, her influence upon him
1 CONT may still be traced. The same year, he was married, and Blanche became Queen
1 CONT mother. Louis IX married Marguerite of Provence, who was the eldest of four
1 CONT daughters of Ramon, count of Provence, and Beatrice of Savoy. In 1248 Blanche
1 CONT again became regent, during Louis IX's absence on the crusade, a project which
1 CONT she had strongly opposed. In the disasters which followed she maintained
1 CONT peace, while draining the land of men and money to aid her son in the East. At
1 CONT last her strength failed her. She fell ill into a bale of hay at Melun in
1 CONT November 1252, and was taken to Paris, but lived only a few days. She was
1 CONT buried at Maubuisson.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Literature
1 CONT
1 CONT Besides the works of Joinville and William of Nangis, see Élie Berger,
1 CONT "Histoire de Blanche de Castille, reine de France," in Bibliothèque des écoles
1 CONT francaises d’Athènes et de Rome, vol. lxx. (Paris, 1895); Le Nain de
1 CONT Tillemont, "Vie de Saint Louis," ed. by J. de Gaulle for the Société de
1 CONT l'histoire de France (6 vols., 1847-1851); and Paulin Paris, "Nouvelles
1 CONT recherches sur les mœurs de la reine Blanche et de Thibaud," in Cabinet
1 CONT historique (1858).
