1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche of Castile (Blanca de Castilla in Spanish; 4 March 1188 – 26 November
1 CONT 1252), wife of Louis VIII of France. She was born in Palencia, Spain, the
1 CONT third daughter of Alfonso VIII, king of Castile, and of Eleanor of England.
1 CONT Eleanor was a daughter of Henry II of England and his Queen consort Eleanor of
1 CONT Aquitaine.
1 CONT
1 CONT Biography
1 CONT
1 CONT In consequence of a treaty between Philip Augustus and John of England,
1 CONT Blanche's sister Urraca was betrothed to the former's son, Louis. Their
1 CONT grandmother Eleanor, upon getting acquainted with the two sisters, judged that
1 CONT Blanche's personality was more fit for a queen of France. In the spring of
1 CONT 1200 she brought her to France instead. On 22 May 1200 the treaty was finally
1 CONT signed, John ceding with his niece the fiefs of Issoudun and Gracay, together
1 CONT with those that André de Chauvigny, lord of Châteauroux, held in Berry, of the
1 CONT English crown. The marriage was celebrated the next day, at Portmort on the
1 CONT right bank of the Seine, in John's domains, as those of Philip lay under an
1 CONT interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche first displayed her great qualities in 1216, when Louis, who on the
1 CONT death of John claimed the English crown in her right, invaded England, only to
1 CONT find a united nation against him. Philip Augustus refused to help his son, and
1 CONT Blanche was his sole support. The queen established herself at Calais and
1 CONT organized two fleets, one of which was commanded by Eustace the Monk, and an
1 CONT army under Robert of Courtenay; but all her resolution and energy were in
1 CONT vain. Although it would seem that her masterful temper exercised a sensible
1 CONT influence upon her husband's gentler character, her role during his reign
1 CONT (1223-1226) is not well known.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his death he left Blanche regent and guardian of his children. Of her
1 CONT twelve or thirteen children, six had died, and Louis, the heir – afterwards
1 CONT the sainted Louis IX – was but twelve years old.
1 CONT
1 CONT The situation was critical, for the hard-won domains of the house of Capet
1 CONT seemed likely to fall to pieces during a minority. Blanche had to bear the
1 CONT whole burden of affairs alone, to break up a league of the barons (1226), and
1 CONT to repel the attack of the king of England (1230). But her energy and firmness
1 CONT overcame all dangers.
1 CONT
1 CONT There was an end to the calumnies circulated against her, based on the
1 CONT poetical homage rendered her by Count Theobald IV of Champagne, a.k.a.
1 CONT KingTheobald I of Navarre since 1234, and the prolonged stay in Paris of the
1 CONT papal legate, Romano Bonaventura , cardinal of Sant' Angelo. The nobles were
1 CONT awed by her warlike preparations or won over by adroit diplomacy, and their
1 CONT league was broken up. St Louis owed his realm to his mother, but he himself
1 CONT always remained somewhat under the spell of her imperious personality.
1 CONT
1 CONT After he came of age, in 1234, aged 20, her influence upon him may still be
1 CONT traced. The same year, he was married, and Blanche became Queen mother. Louis
1 CONT IX married Marguerite of Provence, who was the eldest of four daughters of
1 CONT Ramon, count of Provence, and Beatrice of Savoy. In 1248 Blanche again became
1 CONT Queen regent, during Louis IX's absence on the crusade, a project which she
1 CONT had strongly opposed. In the disasters which followed she maintained peace,
1 CONT while draining the land of men and money to aid her son in the East. At last
1 CONT her strength failed her. She fell ill into a bale of hay at Melun in November
1 CONT 1252, and was taken to Paris, but lived only a few days. She was buried at
1 CONT Maubuisson.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
