1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Blanche of Castile (Blanca de Castilla in Spanish; 4 March 1188 – 26 November
1 CONT 1252), wife of Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born in Palencia, Spain, the third daughter of Alfonso VIII, king of
1 CONT Castile, and of Eleanor of England. Eleanor was a daughter of Henry II of
1 CONT England and his Queen consort Eleanor of Aquitaine.
1 CONT
1 CONT Biography
1 CONT
1 CONT Early Life
1 CONT
1 CONT In consequence of a dangerous treaty between Philip Augustus and John of
1 CONT England, Blanche's sister Urraca was betrothed to the former's son, Louis.
1 CONT Their grandmother Eleanor, upon getting acquainted with the two sisters,
1 CONT judged that Blanche's personality was more fit for a queen of France. In the
1 CONT spring of 1200 she brought her to France instead.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT On 22 May 1200 the treaty was finally signed, John ceding with his niece the
1 CONT fiefs of Issoudun and Graçay, together with those that André de Chauvigny,
1 CONT lord of Châteauroux, held in Berry, of the English crown. The marriage was
1 CONT celebrated the next day, at Portmort on the right bank of the Seine, in John's
1 CONT domains, as those of Philip lay under an interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the English baron's rebellion 1215-16 against King John, it was
1 CONT Blanche's English ancestry as granddaughter to Henry II that led to Louis
1 CONT being offered the throne of England as Louis I. However, with the death of
1 CONT John in October 1216, the barons changed their allegiance to John's son, the
1 CONT nine-year-old Henry.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis continued to claim the English crown in her right, only to find a united
1 CONT nation against him. Philip Augustus refused to help his son, and Blanche was
1 CONT his sole support. The queen established herself at Calais and organized two
1 CONT fleets, one of which was commanded by Eustace the Monk, and an army under
1 CONT Robert of Courtenay; but all her resolution and energy were in vain. With
1 CONT French forces defeated at Lincoln in May 1217 and then routed on their way
1 CONT back to their London stronghold, Louis desperately needed the reinforcements
1 CONT from France. On 24 August, the English fleet destroyed the French fleet
1 CONT carrying those reinforcements off Sandwich and Louis was forced to sue for
1 CONT peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT Regency
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his death he left Blanche regent and guardian of his children. Of her
1 CONT twelve or thirteen children, six had died, and Louis, the heir — afterwards
1 CONT the sainted Louis IX — was but twelve years old.
1 CONT
1 CONT The situation was critical, for the hard-won domains of the house of Capet
1 CONT seemed likely to fall to pieces during a minority. Blanche had to bear the
1 CONT whole burden of affairs alone, to break up a league of the barons (1226), and
1 CONT to repel the attack of the king of England (1230). But her energy and firmness
1 CONT overcame all dangers.
1 CONT
1 CONT There was an end to the calumnies circulated against her, based on the
1 CONT poetical homage rendered her by Count Theobald IV of Champagne, a.k.a. King
1 CONT Theobald I of Navarre since 1234, and the prolonged stay in Paris of the papal
1 CONT legate, Romano Bonaventura, cardinal of Sant' Angelo. The nobles were awed by
1 CONT her warlike preparations or won over by adroit diplomacy, and their league was
1 CONT broken up. St Louis owed his realm to his mother, but he himself always
1 CONT remained somewhat under the spell of her imperious personality.
1 CONT
1 CONT She did not have a good relationship with her daughter-in-law Margaret of
1 CONT Provence, perhaps due to the strong relationship she had with her son. Jean de
1 CONT Joinville tells of the time when Queen Margaret was giving birth and Blanche
1 CONT entered the room telling her son to leave saying "Come ye hence, ye do naught
1 CONT here". Queen Margaret then allegedly fainted out of distress. When Queen
1 CONT Blanche was present in the royal household she did not like Margaret and Louis
1 CONT to be together "except when he went to lie with her".
1 CONT
1 CONT Queen Mother
1 CONT
1 CONT After Louis came of age, in 1234, aged 20, her influence upon him may still be
1 CONT traced. The same year, he was married, and Blanche became Queen mother. Louis
1 CONT married Margaret of Provence, who was the eldest of four daughters of Ramon,
1 CONT count of Provence, and Beatrice of Savoy. In 1248 Blanche again became regent,
1 CONT during Louis IX's absence on the crusade, a project which she had strongly
1 CONT opposed. In the disasters which followed she maintained peace, while draining
1 CONT the land of men and money to aid her son in the East. At last her strength
1 CONT failed her. She fell ill at Melun in November 1252, and was taken to Paris,
1 CONT but lived only a few days. She was buried at Maubuisson and the last surving
1 CONT grandchild of Henry II of England and Eleanor of Aquitaine to die.
1 CONT
1 CONT Literature
1 CONT
1 CONT Besides the works of Joinville and William of Nangis, see Élie Berger,
1 CONT "Histoire de Blanche de Castille, reine de France", in Bibliothèque des Ecoles
1 CONT françaises d'Athènes et de Rome, vol. lxx. (Paris, 1895); Le Nain de
1 CONT Tillemont, "Vie de Saint Louis", ed. by J. de Gaulle for the Société de
1 CONT l'histoire de France (6 vols., 1847–1851); and Paulin Paris, "Nouvelles
1 CONT recherches sur les mœurs de la reine Blanche et de Thibaud", in Cabinet
1 CONT historique (1858).
1 CONT
1 CONT In popular culture
1 CONT
1 CONT An image of Blanche of Castille has been used on the home kit of French Rugby
1 CONT Union team Stade Français since the 2008 season.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT .Margaret of Provence (Forcalquier , Spring 1221 – 21 December 1295, Paris )
1 CONT was the eldest daughter of Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence and Beatrice
1 CONT of Savoy .
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandparents were Alfonso II, Count of Provence and Gersende II
1 CONT de Sabran, Countess of Forcalquier . Her maternal grandparents were Thomas I
1 CONT of Savoy and Marguerite of Geneva , daughter of William I of Geneva and
1 CONT Beatrice de Faucigny.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her younger sisters were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Eleanor of Provence became the Queen consort of Henry III of England .
1 CONT
1 CONT Sanchia of Provence who became the Queen consort of Richard, Earl of Cornwall
1 CONT and rival King of the Germans .
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Provence who was the Queen consort of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT On 27 May 1234 at the age of thirteen, Margaret became the Queen consort of
1 CONT France and wife of Louis IX of France , by whom she had eleven children. She
1 CONT was crowned on the following day.
1 CONT
1 CONT Margaret, like her sisters, was noted for her beauty, she was said to be
1 CONT "pretty with dark hair and fine eyes", and in the early years of their
1 CONT marriage she and Louis enjoyed a warm relationship. Her Franciscan confessor,
1 CONT William de St. Pathus, related that on cold nights Margaret would place a robe
1 CONT around Louis' shoulders, when her deeply religious husband rose to pray.
1 CONT Another anecdote recorded by St. Pathus related that Margaret felt that Louis'
1 CONT plain clothing was unbecoming to his royal dignity, to which Louis replied
1 CONT that he would dress as she wished, if she dressed as he wished. However, the
1 CONT chronicler Joinville noted with disapproval that Louis rarely asked after his
1 CONT wife and children, and in later years Louis became vexed with Margaret's
1 CONT ambition.
1 CONT
1 CONT She accompanied Louis on his first crusade and was responsible for
1 CONT negotiations and ransom when he was captured. She was thus for a brief time
1 CONT the only woman ever to lead a crusade. During this period, while in Damietta ,
1 CONT she gave birth to Jean Tristran.
1 CONT
1 CONT After the death of Louis on his second crusade, during which she remained in
1 CONT France, she returned to Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was devoted to her sister Queen Eleanor of England, and they stayed in
1 CONT contact until Eleanor's death in 1291. Margaret herself died four and a half
1 CONT years after her sister, on 21 December 1295. She was seventy-four years old.
