1 CONT (Research):Blanche Of Castile Encyclopædia Britannica Article born 1188,
1 CONT Palencia, Castile [Spain] died Nov. 12, 1252, Paris, France French Blanche De
1 CONT Castille, Spanish Blanca De Castilla wife of Louis VIII of France, mother of
1 CONT Louis IX (St. Louis), and twice regent of France (1226-34, 1248-52), who by
1 CONT wars and marital alliances did much to secure and unify French territories.
1 CONT Blanche was the daughter of Alfonso VIII of Castile and Eleanor, who was the
1 CONT daughter of Henry II of England. Her grandmother Eleanor of Aquitaine, queen
1 CONT of England, traveled to Spain to take the 11-year-old Blanche to France, where
1 CONT a marriage treaty was concluded with Louis, the young son of King Philip II
1 CONT Augustus. This politically motivated marriage had been arranged by Blanche's
1 CONT uncle, King John of England, and was celebrated in 1200 at Portsmouth,
1 CONT Hampshire. It represented only a brief truce in the struggle between England
1 CONT and France for control over certain French territories. Blanche, who became
1 CONT French through marriage, was gradually to become French in spirit as well.
1 CONT Although she did not cease to be concerned for her family, among them her
1 CONT uncle John and his allies, her brother-in-law Ferrand of Portugal, and her
1 CONT cousin Otto of Brunswick (later Holy Roman emperor Otto IV), she rejoiced at
1 CONT the French victory over Otto and the English at Bouvines in 1214, marking the
1 CONT first stage of French unification, a goal for which she was constantly to
1 CONT strive. In the same year, she gave birth to Louis, the future king of France.
1 CONT Upon John of England's death, Blanche boldly tried to seize the English
1 CONT throne: in 1216 Louis of France invaded England on her behalf. The English
1 CONT stood firm against him, and John's nine-year-old son was finally crowned Henry
1 CONT III. A devout Roman Catholic, Blanche soon became involved in what she
1 CONT sincerely believed to be a holy war against the heretical Cathari, a sect
1 CONT founded on the belief that good and evil had two separate creators, which was
1 CONT flourishing throughout southern France. Her husband, who became Louis VIII in
1 CONT 1223, took part in a crusade against the Cathari but suffered a fatal attack
1 CONT of dysentery upon returning to the north of France in 1226. In accordance with
1 CONT her husband's will, Blanche became both guardian of the 12-year-old Louis and
1 CONT regent of France. She zealously pressed to have Louis crowned immediately, and
1 CONT the coronation took place at Reims three weeks after Louis VIII's death. Her
1 CONT most pressing problem was to deal with a rebellion of the great barons,
1 CONT organized by Philip Hurepel, the illegitimate son of King Philip II Augustus,
1 CONT and supported by King Henry III of England. In the face of such adversity,
1 CONT Blanche showed herself by turns a delicate diplomat, a clever negotiator, and
1 CONT a strong leader. Dressed in white, on a white palfrey draped in the same
1 CONT colour, she rode into battle at the head of her troops. After an attempted
1 CONT abduction of the young king, Blanche did not hesitate to replace rebel noble
1 CONT associates with commoners if she thought it necessary. She also created local
1 CONT militias. Blanche was gradually able to subdue the revolt, establish a new
1 CONT truce with England, and, in 1229, pacify the south of France by signing the
1 CONT Treaty of Paris with Raymond VII, count of Toulouse. France then entered an
1 CONT era of domestic stability, which saw the construction of many cathedrals
1 CONT throughout the country. On only one occasion did Blanche fail to exhibit
1 CONT diplomatic conduct. In 1229 a dispute between an innkeeper and some students
1 CONT took place in the Latin Quarter in Paris. The police were summoned, and the
1 CONT students were beaten and thrown into the Seine; such intervention in the Latin
1 CONT Quarter, however, was contrary to the prerogatives granted to the university,
1 CONT and the faculty and students threatened to strike if the university's
1 CONT privileges were not respected. Badly advised, Blanche held firm, but the
1 CONT university closed its doors, and the faculty and students left Paris for the
1 CONT provinces and abroad. It was to take four years and the intervention of the
1 CONT pope before the university would return to Paris with new prerogatives, this
1 CONT time granted by Blanche herself. Although Louis IX came of age on April 25,
1 CONT 1236, Blanche remained at his side as his most loyal and steadfast supporter.
1 CONT She lacked tact, however, with regard to her son's private life. Although
1 CONT Blanche herself had selected Margaret of Provence to be Louis's wife, she
1 CONT treated Margaret with considerable severity. In 1244, after Louis recovered
1 CONT from a serious illness, he and his wife, much against Blanche's wishes, made a
1 CONT vow to go on a crusade against the Muslims. They embarked in 1248, and once
1 CONT again the kingdom was entrusted to Blanche. Informed of Louis's defeat at Al-
1 CONT Mansurah, Egypt, and his subsequent imprisonment, Blanche herself went to seek
1 CONT his ransom and that of the French army. She petitioned her parents, her
1 CONT allies, and the pope for funds and supplies, but interest in the crusade had
1 CONT dwindled. Although weakened by a heart ailment, Blanche did not neglect her
1 CONT obligations as a regent. Continuing to preside over council meetings, she
1 CONT signed laws and watched over the poor of Paris. When some of the poor were
1 CONT mistreated by the cathedral chapter, she herself rode, as formerly, to open
1 CONT the gates to their prison. On her way to the Abbey of the Lys, one of her
1 CONT favourite retreats, Blanche suffered an attack of the heart ailment that was
1 CONT to take her life. She was returned to the palace of the Louvre, dressed in a
1 CONT nun's habit, and laid on a bed of hay. There, after begging forgiveness of all
1 CONT and having received the last sacraments, she died. She was buried at
1 CONT Maubuisson Abbey and her heart taken to the Abbey of the Lys. Louis IX was in
1 CONT Jaffa when he learned of his mother's death. The news distressed him greatly,
1 CONT for he was aware that he had lost not only an incomparable parent but also the
1 CONT strongest supporter of his kingship.
1 CONT ========================================================== Blanche of Castile
1 CONT Regent of France 1226-1236 Born before 4 March 1188 Palencia Died 27 November
1 CONT 1252 Paris Married 23 May 1200 Pont-Audemer, Normandy Louis VIII, King of
1 CONT France 1223-1226, son of Philippe II August, King of France 1180-1223 and
1 CONT Isabelle of Flanders, Countess of Artois Born 5 September 1187 Paris Died 8
1 CONT November 1226 Montpensier It was her formidable grandmother, Queen Eleanor of
1 CONT England, who took her to France to be married to its crown prince who, twenty-
1 CONT three years and ten children later, became King Louis VIII. However, after
1 CONT only three years Louis VIII died and Blanche became Regent for her son, the
1 CONT new King Louis IX, until 1234. In 1236 in London she attended the marriage of
1 CONT King Henry III to Eleanor de Provence. Together with her son she brought from
1 CONT the east the reputedly Holy Cross from Christ's crucifixion to Paris and they
1 CONT built the Sainte Chapelle to house it. In 1248 Louis IX went on crusade and
1 CONT Blanche again became Regent. In 1250 news reached her that Louis IX had been
1 CONT captured and she rewarded the messengers by having them hanged. When the
1 CONT Pastoureaux uprising in 1251 reached Paris, she at first held talks with its
1 CONT leaders but then imprisoned them and put them to death. She herself died in
1 CONT 1252. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Name Prefix: Princess Name Suffix: Of Castile
1 CONT [rolloD1.FTW]
1 CONT Louis VIII became King of France in 1223. He lead the crusade against th e
1 CONT Albigensians, thereby paving the way for the annexation of the county o f
1 CONT Toulouse. Blanche of Castile governed France as regent from 1226 to 12 36.
1 CONT Blanche of Castile
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT Jump to: navigation, search
1 CONT Blanche of Castile (1188-1252), wife of Louis VIII of France, third daughter
1 CONT of Alfonso VIII, king of Castile, and of Eleanor of England, daughter of Henry
1 CONT II, was born at Palencia.
1 CONT
1 CONT In consequence of a treaty between Philip Augustus and John of England, she
1 CONT was betrothed to the former's son, Louis, and was brought to France, in the
1 CONT spring of 1200, by John's mother Eleanor. On May 22, 1200 the treaty was
1 CONT finally signed, John ceding with his niece the fiefs of Issoudun and Gracay,
1 CONT together with those that André de Chavigny, lord of Châteauroux, held in
1 CONT Berry, of the English crown. The marriage was celebrated the next day, at
1 CONT Portmort on the right bank of the Seine, in John's domains, as those of Philip
1 CONT lay under an interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche first displayed her great qualities in 1216, when Louis, who on the
1 CONT death of John claimed the English crown in her right, invaded England, only to
1 CONT find a united nation against him. Philip Augustus refused to help his son, and
1 CONT Blanche was his sole support. The queen established herself at Calais and
1 CONT organized two fleets, one of which was commanded by Eustace the Monk, and an
1 CONT army under Robert of Courtenay; but all her resolution and energy were in
1 CONT vain. Although it would seem that her masterful temper exercised a sensible
1 CONT influence upon her husband's gentler character, her role during his reign
1 CONT (1223-1226) is not well known.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his death he left Blanche regent and guardian of his children. Of her
1 CONT twelve or thirteen children, six had died, and Louis, the heir--afterwards the
1 CONT sainted Louis IX--was but twelve years old. The situation was critical, for
1 CONT the hard-won domains of the house of Capet seemed likely to fall to pieces
1 CONT during a minority. Blanche had to bear the whole burden of affairs alone, to
1 CONT break up a league of the barons (1226), and to repel the attack of the king of
1 CONT England (1230). But her energy and firmness overcame all dangers. There was an
1 CONT end to the calumnies circulated against her, based on the poetical homage
1 CONT rendered her by Theobald IV of Champagne, and the prolonged stay in Paris of
1 CONT the papal legate, Romano Bonaventura, cardinal of Sant' Angelo.
1 CONT
1 CONT The nobles were awed by her warlike preparations or won over by adroit
1 CONT diplomacy, and their league was broken up. St Louis owed his realm to his
1 CONT mother, but he himself always remained somewhat under the spell of her
1 CONT imperious personality. After he came of age (1236) her influence upon him may
1 CONT still be traced. In 1248 she again became regent, during Louis IX's absence on
1 CONT the crusade, a project which she had strongly opposed. In the disasters which
1 CONT followed she maintained peace, while draining the land of men and money to aid
1 CONT her son in the East. At last her strength failed her. She fell ill at Melun in
1 CONT November 1252, and was taken to Paris, but lived only a few days. She was
1 CONT buried at Maubuisson.
1 CONT
1 CONT Besides the works of Joinville and William of Nangis, see Elie Berger,
1 CONT "Histoire de Blanche de Castille, reine de France," in Bibliothèque des écoles
1 CONT francaises d’Athènes et de Rome, vol. lxx. (Paris, 1895); Le Nain de
1 CONT Tillemont, "Vie de Saint Louis," ed. by J de Gaulle for the Société de
1 CONT l’histoire de France (6 vols., 1847-1851); and Paulin Paris, "Nouvelles
1 CONT recherches sur les mteurs de la reine Blanche et de Thibaud," in Cabinet
1 CONT historigue (1858).
1 CONT As regent for son Louis IX during his minority and again when Louis was
1 CONT in the Holy Lands on the Seventh Crusade, then captured in Egypt & remained
1 CONT in Patestine for 4 years before returning to France ( total from 1248-1252).
1 CONT Her first 3 children died at an early age (11 children in all in her family),
1 CONT with son Louis (IX) being the fourth child.
1 CONT Basic Life Information
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche of Castile was born in Palencia, Spain, the third daughter of Alfonso
1 CONT VIII, king of Castile, and of Eleanor of England. Eleanor was a daughter of
1 CONT Henry II of England and his Queen consort Eleanor of Aquitaine.
1 CONT
1 CONT In consequence of a treaty between Philip Augustus and John of England,
1 CONT Blanche's sister Urraca was betrothed to the former's son, Louis. Their
1 CONT grandmother Eleanor, upon getting acquainted with the two sisters, judged that
1 CONT Blanche's personality was more fit for a queen of France. In the spring of
1 CONT 1200 she brought her to France instead. On May 22, 1200 the treaty was finally
1 CONT signed, John ceding with his niece the fiefs of Issoudun and Gracay, together
1 CONT with those that André de Chauvigny, lord of Châteauroux, held in Berry, of the
1 CONT English crown. The marriage was celebrated the next day, at Portmort on the
1 CONT right bank of the Seine, in John's domains, as those of Philip lay under an
1 CONT interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche first displayed her great qualities in 1216, when Louis, who on the
1 CONT death of John claimed the English crown in her right, invaded England, only to
1 CONT find a united nation against him. Philip Augustus refused to help his son, and
1 CONT Blanche was his sole support. The queen established herself at Calais and
1 CONT organized two fleets, one of which was commanded by Eustace the Monk, and an
1 CONT army under Robert of Courtenay; but all her resolution and energy were in
1 CONT vain. Although it would seem that her masterful temper exercised a sensible
1 CONT influence upon her husband's gentler character, her role during his reign
1 CONT (1223-1226) is not well known.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his death he left Blanche regent and guardian of his children. Of her
1 CONT twelve or thirteen children, six had died, and Louis, the heir - afterwards
1 CONT the sainted Louis IX - was but twelve years old. The situation was critical,
1 CONT for the hard-won domains of the house of Capet seemed likely to fall to pieces
1 CONT during a minority. Blanche had to bear the whole burden of affairs alone, to
1 CONT break up a league of the barons (1226), and to repel the attack of the king of
1 CONT England (1230). But her energy and firmness overcame all dangers. There was an
1 CONT end to the calumnies circulated against her, based on the poetical homage
1 CONT rendered her by Theobald IV of Champagne, and the prolonged stay in Paris of
1 CONT the papal legate, Romano Bonaventura, cardinal of Sant' Angelo.
1 CONT
1 CONT The nobles were awed by her warlike preparations or won over by adroit
1 CONT diplomacy, and their league was broken up. St Louis owed his realm to his
1 CONT mother, but he himself always remained somewhat under the spell of her
1 CONT imperious personality. After he came of age, in 1234, her influence upon him
1 CONT may still be traced. The same year, he was married, and Blanche became Queen
1 CONT mother. Louis IX married Marguerite of Provence, who was the eldest of four
1 CONT daughters of Ramon, count of Provence, and Beatrice of Savoy. In 1248 Blanche
1 CONT again became regent, during Louis IX's absence on the crusade, a project which
1 CONT she had strongly opposed. In the disasters which followed she maintained
1 CONT peace, while draining the land of men and money to aid her son in the East. At
1 CONT last her strength failed her. She fell ill into a bale of hay at Melun in
1 CONT November 1252, and was taken to Paris, but lived only a few days. She was
1 CONT buried at Maubuisson.
