1 CONT
1 CONT GIVN Blanca Alphonsa
1 CONT NSFX Queen of France
1 CONT AFN 8XJ4-TP
1 CONT DATE 25 APR 2000
1 CONT TIME 20:45:48
1 CONT It is reported that Blanche could be quite domineering and as such pro tested
1 CONT when her son Louis IX went to the Crusades. Blanche of Castil e (March 4, 1188
1 CONT - November 26, 1252), wife of Louis VIII of France. S he was born at Palencia,
1 CONT the third daughter of Alfonso VIII, king of C astile, and of Eleanor of
1 CONT England. Eleanor was a daughter of Henry II of England and his Queen consort
1 CONT Eleanor of Aquitaine. Despite her An gevin ancestry, Blanche was completely
1 CONT French.
1 CONT
1 CONT In consequence of a treaty between Philip Augustus and John of England , she
1 CONT was betrothed to the former's son, Louis, and was brought to Fra nce, in the
1 CONT spring of 1200, by John's mother Eleanor. On May 22, 1200 the treaty was
1 CONT finally signed, John ceding with his niece the fiefs o f Issoudun and Gracay,
1 CONT together with those that André de Chauvigny, lo rd of Châteauroux, held in
1 CONT Berry, of the English crown. The marriage w as celebrated the next day, at
1 CONT Portmort on the right bank of the Seine , in John's domains, as those of
1 CONT Philip lay under an interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT Blanche first displayed her great qualities in 1216, when Louis, who o n the
1 CONT death of John claimed the English crown in her right, invaded En gland, only
1 CONT to find a united nation against him. It is reported that Blanche was in
1 CONT complete support of her husband (Louis VIII) in his inv asion of England. She
1 CONT took charge of attempts to send supplies acros s the channel. Philip Augustus
1 CONT refused to help his son, and Blanche w as his sole support. The queen
1 CONT established herself at Calais and organ ized two fleets, one of which was
1 CONT commanded by Eustace the Monk, and a n army under Robert of Courtenay; but all
1 CONT her resolution and energy we re in vain. Although it would seem that her
1 CONT masterful temper exercise d a sensible influence upon her husband's gentler
1 CONT character, her role during his brief reign (1223-1226) is not well known.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon Louis's death he left Blanche regent and guardian of his children . As
1 CONT regent she took over administration of the kingdom with a stron g hand. During
1 CONT her regency, Raimond VII of Toulouse, son of Raimond V I was defeated and the
1 CONT Albigensian hersey was wiped out. Blanche als o arrange that one of her
1 CONT younger sons would marry Raimond VI's daught er - his heir. But soon
1 CONT opposition began to arise against the Queen m other. As Queen, she played a
1 CONT more significant role in the governmen t of the realm than her predecessors.
1 CONT Of her twelve or thirteen child ren, six had died, and Louis, the heir-
1 CONT afterwards the sainted Louis I X - was but twelve years old. The situation was
1 CONT critical, for the hard -won domains of the house of Capet seemed likely to
1 CONT fall to pieces dur ing a minority. Blanche had to bear the whole burden of
1 CONT affairs alone , to break up a league of the barons (1226), and to repel the
1 CONT attack o f Henry III King of England at St. Malo in Bretagne on 3 May, 1230,
1 CONT th en in support of French barons opposed to Blanche. In the face of th e
1 CONT attack by Henry III, Blanche summoned the vassels of Louis IX (for w hom she
1 CONT was regent) to give assistance against Henry III. But her ene rgy and firmness
1 CONT overcame all dangers. There was an end to the calumni es circulated against
1 CONT her, based on the poetical homage rendered her b y Theobald IV of Champagne,
1 CONT and the prolonged stay in Paris of thepapa l legate, Romano Bonaventura,
1 CONT cardinal of Sant' Angelo.
1 CONT
1 CONT From 1226, until her death in 1252, she held great sway within the rea lm.
1 CONT After her husbands death, Blanche retained the services of her hu sbands
1 CONT Hospitaller Guerin and Renaud de Roye. Between 1226 and 1234, she acted as
1 CONT regent while Louis IX was a minor and again from 1248 unt il 1252 she acted as
1 CONT regent again during Louis's absence on the crusad e. During these years,
1 CONT Blanche is styled as having a 'severe personal ity' and was 'heroic in
1 CONT nature'. She was able to break up hte coaliti on of barons led by Peter
1 CONT Maruclerc - Count of Brittany and Raymond VI I - Count of Toulouse and was
1 CONT able to fend off Henry III of England wh o tried to reclaim his ancesteral
1 CONT lands lost by John Lackland. Durin g this period she was also able to
1 CONT establish French royal power in sou thern France. She was also responsible for
1 CONT the suppression of a revol t in the Languedoc region of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT The nobles were awed by her warlike preparations or won over by adroi t
1 CONT diplomacy, and their league was broken up. St Louis owed his realm t o his
1 CONT mother, but he himself always remained somewhat under the spello f her
1 CONT imperious personality. After he came of age (1236) her influenc e upon him may
1 CONT still be traced. In 1248 she again became regent, durin g Louis IX's absence
1 CONT on the crusade, a project which she had stronglyo pposed. In the disasters
1 CONT which followed she maintained peace, while dr aining the land of men and money
1 CONT to aid her son in the East. At lasthe r strength failed her. She fell ill into
1 CONT a bail of hay at Melun in Nov ember 1252, and was taken to Paris, but lived
1 CONT only a few days. She wa s buried at Maubuisson.
1 CONT
1 CONT Besides the works of Joinville and William of Nangis, see Elie Berger ,
1 CONT "Histoire de Blanche de Castille, reine de France," in Bibliothèqued es écoles
1 CONT francaises d’Athènes et de Rome, vol. lxx. (Paris, 1895); L e Nain de
1 CONT Tillemont, "Vie de Saint Louis," ed. by J de Gaulle for theS ociété de
1 CONT l’histoire de France (6 vols., 1847-1851); and Paulin Paris , "Nouvelles
1 CONT recherches sur les mteurs de la reine Blanche et de Thiba ud," in Cabinet
1 CONT historigue (1858).
