1 CONT TEXT Date of Import: Nov 26, 2000
1 CONT The daughter of Manfred, she was bethrothed to the infante Peter of Aragon in
1 CONT 1260\. This was a way of strengthening Manfred's position as King of Sicily as
1 CONT "protector of the Italian Ghibellines".
1 CONT (Research):Constance of Sicily (1249-1301) Born 1249 Died 1301 Barcelona
1 CONT Married 13 June 1262 Montpellier Pedro III "the Great", King of Aragon
1 CONT 1276-1285, King of Sicily, son of Jaime I "the Conqueror", King of Aragon
1 CONT 1213-1276 and Violante of Hungary Born 1236 Died 11 November 1285 Villafranca
1 CONT de Penadres Buried Villafranca, Holy Cross It was to the annoyance of the pope
1 CONT when in 1262 her father arranged her engagement and marriage to Infant Pedro
1 CONT of Aragon, son and heir of King Jaime "The Conqueror". However, this also
1 CONT upset King Louis IX of France who then almost broke off his son's engagement
1 CONT to Pedro's sister. It was only after Jaime "The Conqueror" promised never to
1 CONT assist Manfredo, Constance's father, that the marriage proceeded. However, due
1 CONT to papal interference, Manfredo lost his crown and life in 1266. As long as
1 CONT Constance's father-in-law had been alive, nothing was done about Sicily; and
1 CONT now, even though she was Sicily's heiress, it remained in the hands of Charles
1 CONT of Anjou, a brother of King Louis IX of France. Her husband---who loved her
1 CONT dearly, and even some years before he became king---gave her in her own right
1 CONT the title of queen. When her father-in-law died in 1276 he had left the
1 CONT Balearic Islands and Roussillon to a younger son, Jaime, who, as well as
1 CONT calling himself King of Majorca, for three years refused to acknowledge
1 CONT Constance's husband as his suzerain. In 1279 the Moors of Andalusia tried to
1 CONT reconquer Murcia and it took till the end of that year before the southern
1 CONT border was secure. Further intrigues within the Iberian peninsula prevented
1 CONT King Pedro III of Aragon from pursuing his wife's rights in Sicily. In 1275
1 CONT the elder son of King Alfonso X of Castile had died, leaving two young sons.
1 CONT Alfonso X decided to make his second son, Sancho, his heir to prevent a long
1 CONT minority for his grandson, the rightful heir. However, his widowed daughter-
1 CONT in-law, Blanche, a daughter of Louis IX of France, fled with her two sons to
1 CONT Pedro III of Aragon as she feared for her sons' lives. Pedro III of Aragon
1 CONT welcomed Blanche and her sons but kept them as hostages. Alfonso X of Castile
1 CONT soon regretted his decision as in 1281 the impatient Sancho rebelled against
1 CONT his father. However, in 1279 the plotting began in earnest with Emperor
1 CONT Michael of Constantinople and the Republic of Genoa, as these greatly feared
1 CONT that Charles of Anjou, the de-facto king of Sicily, might become too powerful.
1 CONT On 30 August 1282, the Aragonese, with King Pedro III at its head, disembarked
1 CONT at Trapani for Sicily, so that the local rebellion became a European war. On 2
1 CONT October Pedro III made a triumphant entry into Messina. Nevertheless he acted
1 CONT most cautiously as one night a ragged old man, Vitalis dei Guidici who was
1 CONT once a devoted friend of King Manfredo, warned him of the inconstancy of the
1 CONT volatile Sicilian nobles. Pedro III maintained that he had come to make
1 CONT friends with the Sicilians and not to offend them with recriminations about
1 CONT the past. However, the very next day he was reminded of the warning when Lady
1 CONT Machalda, one of those mentioned by name by Vitalis dei Guidici, came and made
1 CONT it clear that she wanted to become his mistress. He escaped only by a lengthy
1 CONT discourse about his loyalty to his wife Constance, the rightful queen of
1 CONT Sicily. Lady Machalda, not a graceful loser, then induced her own husband to
1 CONT intrigue against Pedro III and Constance. In the early spring of 1283 when her
1 CONT husband sent for her, Constance left Aragon for Sicily and, with her children
1 CONT ---Jaime, Fadrique and Yolanda---arrived on 16 April 1283. On 19 April it was
1 CONT announced that the Infant Jaime would be heir to Sicily as the elder son,
1 CONT Alfonso, would remain heir of Aragon. In the case of Jaime's minority,
1 CONT Constance would act as regent. Pedro III had to depart Sicily, leaving
1 CONT Constance in charge. Constance and her Italian-born ministers were careful to
1 CONT observe the rights of the Sicilians, but, soon short of money, she found it
1 CONT difficult to restrain the rapacious Aragonese soldiers. When Sicily was again
1 CONT attacked, it was only the brilliance of Admiral Roger of Lauria which saved it
1 CONT from an invasion. Soon the whole kingdom of Charles of Anjou was in turmoil
1 CONT and, with his having lost Sicily to Pedro III and Constance, riots broke out
1 CONT in Naples. Here, Frenchmen found in the streets were massacred. In November
1 CONT 1285 Constance's husband died at Villafranca de Penadres where he was buried.
1 CONT His being gracious had made a good impression in Sicily but he had also been
1 CONT too cautious. Pope Honorious IV now decided it was time to restore peace in
1 CONT Italy, but also wanted Sicily returned to the House of Anjou as it had been a
1 CONT previous pope who had made Charles of Anjou its king. The Sicilians, however,
1 CONT were distrustful of the generous promises of the pope and preferred their new
1 CONT king, Constance's son, Jaime, who would become known as "The Just". Jaime was
1 CONT about nineteen years old, whereas the new king of France, Philippe IV "The
1 CONT Fair", was only seventeen. In February 1286 Jaime was crowned at Palermo.
1 CONT Discovering two Dominican friars sent by the pope to start a revolt in Sicily,
1 CONT Jaime courteously sent them back unharmed, as well offering the pope both
1 CONT homage and asking for the confirmation of his title. The pope's response,
1 CONT however, was excommunication for both Constance and Jaime---and, for good
1 CONT measure, all the people of Sicily as well. Constance and Jaime had reached an
1 CONT honourable and just agreement with the imprisoned heir of Charles of Anjou;
1 CONT but the pope, disallowing this, ordered an offensive against Sicily in 1287, a
1 CONT disastrous affair for Honorious IV. When in 1291 her eldest son, Alfonso III
1 CONT "The Liberal", King of Aragon, died childless, it was Jaime, King of Sicily,
1 CONT who became the next King of Aragon. He remained king of both countries until
1 CONT 1296 when Fadrique, Constance's third son, became King of Sicily and Jaime
1 CONT remained King of Aragon alone. Constance, having returned to Spain, died in
1 CONT Barcelona in 1301. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT
