1 CONT
1 CONT =Beatrix de Savoie=
1 CONT
1 CONT [<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#Avoiedied1292> **From Medlands:**
1 CONT ]
1 CONT
1 CONT **BEATRIX de Savoie** ([1205]-Dec 1266 or 4 Jan 1267). Matthew of Paris names
1 CONT her as daughter of "comitis Sabaldiæ Thomæ iam mortui, sororem comitis
1 CONT Sabaldiæ adhuc viventis Amidei", when he records the marriage of her daughter
1 CONT to Henry III King of England[426]. It is improbable that she was born much
1 CONT later than 1205 as she gave birth to her first child in 1221. The contract of
1 CONT marriage between "Thomas…comes Sabaldie et marchio in Ytalia…filia sua" and
1 CONT "Raimundi Berengarii…comitis Provinciæ et Forcalquerii" is dated 5 Jun 1219,
1 CONT and names "A. et V. filii Thomæ comitis et A. cometissa uxor eius" as
1 CONT guarantors[427]. She transformed the court at Aix into one of the most
1 CONT celebrated in Europe. After quarrelling with her son-in-law Charles Comte
1 CONT d'Anjou over the usufruct of the county of Provence she retired to Echelles in
1 CONT Savoy[428]. The marriage of her daughter Eléonore with Henry III King of
1 CONT England in 1236 signalled the establishment of close ties between the English
1 CONT court and the house of Savoy, the foreign immigrants becoming increasingly
1 CONT unpopular in England and contributing to the difficulties experienced by the
1 CONT king with his barons. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii
1 CONT comitis Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, confirms her previous testaments
1 CONT appointing "Reginarum filiarum suarum Margarethæ Franciæ et Alienoræ Angliæ,
1 CONT fratrum suorum Bonifacii archiepiscopi Cantuar. et Petri comitis Sabaudiæ" as
1 CONT her heirs, chooses burial "in hospitali Scalarum", and adds bequests to
1 CONT "Philippo electo Lugdun. fratri suo altero…Agneti comitissæ Sabaudiæ dominiæ
1 CONT Fuciniaci, Cæciliæ relictæ Amedei Sabaudiæ comitis, Beatrici relictæ Thomæ de
1 CONT Sabaudia comitis...Contissoni…Eleonoræ aliæ filiæ Thomæ comitis…Contissoni
1 CONT dominæ Medullionis nepti suæ…Margarithæ matri marchionis Montisferrati nepti
1 CONT suæ, Rodulpho archiepiscopo Tarantas, A. episcopo de Dyone consanguineo
1 CONT testatricis, Petro episcopo Hereford…filiabus Rodolphi et Henrici de Gebennis,
1 CONT et filiæ domini de Camera" as well as numerous bequests to religious
1 CONT institutions, orders "Contissona filia Amedei comitis…Eleonoræ filiæ Thomæ
1 CONT fratris sui" to fulfil religious bequests, and appoints "Johannem
1 CONT archiepiscopum Viennensem et Rodulphum Tarantasiensem, Philippum electum
1 CONT Lugdun. fratrem suum, episcopum Gratianopolitanum, Humbertum abbatem Altacumbæ
1 CONT et Stephanum archidiaconum Cantaruensium" as her executors[429]. A second
1 CONT testament of "Beatrix relicta…Dom. Reymundi Berengarii comitis provinciæ",
1 CONT dated 22 Feb 1264, chooses burial "in ecclesia Hospitalis S. Joannis
1 CONT Hierosolymitani", adds bequests to "Thomam Amedeum et Ludovicum filios quondam
1 CONT Dom. Thome fratris mei…Alienore filie predicti comitis Thome…filie Contissone
1 CONT de Medullione…filie domini de Camera…Beringarie filie Dom. Benedicti de
1 CONT Castellione…Beatrice Andegavie comitisse"[430]. The testament of "Bonifacius
1 CONT archiepiscopus Cantuarensis", dated 11 Oct 1264, made bequests to "sorori suæ
1 CONT comitissæ Provinciæ…sorori suæ alteræ comitissæ de Quiborc…"[431]. A second
1 CONT necrology of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne records the death "II Non Jan" of "vidua
1 CONT dna comitssa Provincie"[432].
1 CONT
1 CONT m (Betrothed 5 Jun 1219, Dec 1220) RAIMOND BERENGER IV Comte de Provence, son
1 CONT of ALPHONSE II Comte de Provence [Aragon-Barcelona] & his wife Gersende de
1 CONT Sabran Ctss de Forcalquier ([1198]-19 Aug 1245, bur Aix-en-Provence, église de
1 CONT Saint Jean de Jérusalem).
1 CONT
1 CONT \-----
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1205 – 4 January 1267)[1], was the daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy and Marguerite of Geneva. She was Countess consort of Provence by her
1 CONT marriage to Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandparents were Humbert III, Count of Savoy and Beatrice of
1 CONT Viennois. Her maternal grandparents were William I, Count of Geneva and
1 CONT Beatrice de Faucigny.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was the tenth of fourteen children born to her parents. Her siblings
1 CONT included: Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy, Thomas II of Piedmont, Peter II, Count
1 CONT of Savoy, Philip I, Count of Savoy, Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop of
1 CONT Canterbury, Avita the Countess of Devon and Margherita of Savoy wife of
1 CONT Hartmann I of Kyburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage
1 CONT Beatrice married on 5 June 1219 Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence. She was
1 CONT a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty was likened to that of a
1 CONT second Niobe by Matthew Paris. Ramon and Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters,
1 CONT who all lived to adulthood, and married kings. Their only son, Raymond died in
1 CONT early infancy.[2]
1 CONT
1 CONT Marguerite, Queen of France (1221-1295), wife of Louis IX of France
1 CONT Eleanor, Queen of England (1223-1291), wife of Henry III of England Sanchia,
1 CONT Queen of Germany (1228-1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall Beatrice,
1 CONT Queen of Sicily (1234-1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily Raymond of Provence,
1 CONT died young References ^ Charles Cawley, Medieval Lands, Savoy ^ Cawley,
1 CONT Medieval Lands, Provence
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatriz de Saboya (1198-1266), era la hija de Tomás I de Saboya y de Margarita
1 CONT de Ginebra. Beatriz se casó el 5 de junio de 1219 con Ramón Berenguer V de
1 CONT Provenza. Beatriz era una mujer políticamente astuta, y con una belleza que
1 CONT fue comparada como una segunda Níobe por Mateo de París. Después de dos hijos
1 CONT gemelos, Ramón y Beatriz de Saboya tuvieron cuatro hijas, que todas se casaron
1 CONT con reyes:
1 CONT
1 CONT Margarita de Provenza (1221-1295), esposa de Luis IX de Francia Leonor de
1 CONT Provenza (1223-1291), esposa de Enrique III de Inglaterra Sancha de Provenza
1 CONT (1228-1261), esposa de Ricardo de Cornualles, Conde de Cornwall Beatriz I de
1 CONT Provenza (1231-1267), esposa de Carlos I de Sicilia Obtenido de
1 CONT "<http://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beatriz_de_Saboya>"
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1205 – 4 January 1267)[1], was the daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy and Marguerite of Geneva. She was Countess consort of Provence by her
1 CONT marriage to Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandparents were Humbert III, Count of Savoy and Beatrice of
1 CONT Viennois. Her maternal grandparents were William I, Count of Geneva and
1 CONT Beatrice de Faucigny. Beatrice of Savoy's mother, Marguerite was betrothed to
1 CONT Philip II of France. While Marguerite was travelling to France for her
1 CONT wedding, she was captured by Beatrice's father, Thomas. He took her back to
1 CONT Savoy and married her himself. Thomas' was excuse was that Philip II was
1 CONT already married, which was true.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was the tenth of fourteen children born to her parents. Her siblings
1 CONT included: Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy, Thomas II of Piedmont, Peter II, Count
1 CONT of Savoy, Philip I, Count of Savoy, Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop of
1 CONT Canterbury, Avita the Countess of Devon and Margherita of Savoy wife of
1 CONT Hartmann I of Kyburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 5 June 1219, Ramon married Beatrice of Savoy, daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty was likened
1 CONT by Matthew Paris to that of a second Niobe. Along with two stillborn sons
1 CONT (1220 & 1225), Ramon and Beatrice had four daughters, all of whom married
1 CONT kings.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marguerite of Provence (1221–1295), wife of Louis IX of France Eleanor of
1 CONT Provence (1223–1291), wife of Henry III of England Sanchia of Provence
1 CONT (1228–1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall Beatrice of Provence
1 CONT (1234–1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1198-1266), was the daughter of Thomas I of Savoy and
1 CONT Marguerite of Geneva. Beatrice married on (5 June 1219) Ramon Berenguer IV,
1 CONT Count of Provence. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty
1 CONT was likened to that of a second Niobe by Matthew Paris. After two stillborn
1 CONT sons, Ramon and Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all married kings.
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Marguerite of Provence (1221-1295), wife of Louis IX of France
1 CONT 2\. Eleanor of Provence (1223-1291), wife of Henry III of England
1 CONT 3\. Sanchia of Provence (1228-1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall
1 CONT 4\. Beatrice of Provence (1231-1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1205 – 4 January 1267), was the daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy and Marguerite of Geneva . She was Countess consort of Provence by her
1 CONT marriage to Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence . Family Her paternal
1 CONT grandparents were Humbert III, Count of Savoy and Beatrice of Viennois. Her
1 CONT maternal grandparents were William I, Count of Geneva and Beatrice de
1 CONT Faucigny. Beatrice of Savoy's mother, Marguerite was betrothed to Philip II of
1 CONT France . While Marguerite was travelling to France for her wedding, she was
1 CONT captured by Beatrice's father, Thomas. He took her back to Savoy and married
1 CONT her himself. Thomas' was excuse was that Philip II was already married, which
1 CONT was true. Beatrice was the tenth of fourteen children born to her parents. Her
1 CONT siblings included: Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy , Thomas II of Piedmont , Peter
1 CONT II, Count of Savoy , Philip I, Count of Savoy, Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop
1 CONT of Canterbury , Avita the Countess of Devon and Margherita of Savoy wife of
1 CONT Hartmann I of Kyburg. Life Marriage Beatrice married on 5 June 1219 Ramon
1 CONT Berenguer IV, Count of Provenc. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman,
1 CONT whose beauty was likened to that of a second Niobe by Matthew Paris . Ramon
1 CONT and Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all lived to adulthood, and
1 CONT married kings . Their only son, Raymond died in early infancy. Marguerite,
1 CONT Queen of France (1221-1295), wife of Louis IX of France Eleanor, Queen of
1 CONT England (1223-1291), wife of Henry III of England Sanchia, Queen of Germany
1 CONT (1228-1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall Beatrice, Queen of Sicily
1 CONT (1234-1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily Raymond of Provence, died young
1 CONT Widowhood When Berenguer had died on August 19, 1245, he left his youngest
1 CONT daughter, Provence. Beatrice became one of the most attractive heiresses in
1 CONT medieval Europe. Various suitors had tried to seize her, so Beatrice of Savoy
1 CONT placed the younger Beatrice in a safe fortress, secured the trust of its
1 CONT people then went to the Pope for his protection. In Cluny during December
1 CONT 1245, a secret discussion, between Pope Innocent IV Louis IX of France , his
1 CONT mother Blanche of Castile and his brother Charles of Anjou , took place. It
1 CONT was decided that in return for Louis IX supporting the Pope militarily, the
1 CONT Pope would allow Charles of Anjou, youngest brother to the French King,to
1 CONT marry Beatrice of Provence. But Provence was to never go to France outright
1 CONT through Charles. It was agreed that if Charles and Beatrice had children, the
1 CONT county would go to them, if there was no issue, then the county would go to
1 CONT Sanchia of Provence. If Sanchia died without an heir, Provence would go to the
1 CONT King of Aragon. Beatrice of Savoy who had been granted the usufruct of the
1 CONT county for her lifetime, according to her husbands will agreed to the marriage
1 CONT between Charles of Anjou and her youngest daughter, Beatrice.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1198 – 1266), was the daughter of Thomas I of Savoy and
1 CONT Marguerite of Geneva. Beatrice married on (5 June 1219) Ramon Berenguer IV,
1 CONT Count of Provence. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty
1 CONT was likened to that of a second Niobe by Matthew Paris. After two stillborn
1 CONT sons, Ramon and Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all married kings.
