1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1205 – 4 January 1267)[1], was the daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy and Marguerite of Geneva. She was Countess consort of Provence by her
1 CONT marriage to Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT Contents [hide] 1 Family 2 Life 2.1 Marriage 2.2 Widowhood 3 References
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Family Her paternal grandparents were Humbert III, Count of Savoy and
1 CONT Beatrice of Viennois. Her maternal grandparents were William I, Count of
1 CONT Geneva and Beatrice de Faucigny. Beatrice of Savoy's mother, Marguerite was
1 CONT betrothed to Philip II of France. While Marguerite was travelling to France
1 CONT for her wedding, she was captured by Beatrice's father, Thomas. He took her
1 CONT back to Savoy and married her himself. Thomas' was excuse was that Philip II
1 CONT was already married, which was true.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was the tenth of fourteen children born to her parents. Her siblings
1 CONT included: Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy, Thomas II of Piedmont, Peter II, Count
1 CONT of Savoy, Philip I, Count of Savoy, Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop of
1 CONT Canterbury, Avita the Countess of Devon and Margherita of Savoy wife of
1 CONT Hartmann I of Kyburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Life [edit] Marriage Beatrice married on 5 June 1219 Ramon Berenguer
1 CONT IV, Count of Provence. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose
1 CONT beauty was likened to that of a second Niobe by Matthew Paris. Ramon and
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all lived to adulthood, and married
1 CONT kings. Their only son, Raymond died in early infancy.[2]
