1 CONT which was true.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was the tenth of fourteen children born to her parents. Her siblings
1 CONT included: Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy, Thomas II of Piedmont, Peter II, Count
1 CONT of Savoy, Philip I, Count of Savoy, Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop of
1 CONT Canterbury, Avita the Countess of Devon and Margherita of Savoy wife of
1 CONT Hartmann I of Kyburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and issueBeatrice betrothed on 5 June 1219 to Ramon Berenguer IV,
1 CONT Count of Provence; they married in December 1220. She was a shrewd and
1 CONT politically astute woman, whose beauty was likened to that of a second Niobe
1 CONT by Matthew Paris. Ramon and Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all
1 CONT lived to adulthood, and married kings. Their only son, Raymond died in early
1 CONT infancy.[2]
1 CONT
1 CONT 1.Margaret, Queen of France (1221–1295), wife of Louis IX of France 2.Eleanor,
1 CONT Queen of England (1223–1291), wife of Henry III of England 3.Sanchia, Queen of
1 CONT Germany (1228–1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall 4.Beatrice, Queen of
1 CONT Sicily (1234–1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily 5.Raymond of Provence, died
1 CONT young Beatrice came to England to see her third daughter Sanchia wedded to
1 CONT Richard, 1st Earl of Cornwall, brother-in-law of Eleanor. Beatrice's husband
1 CONT Ramon Berenguer IV was detained by state difficulties which his wife solved by
1 CONT getting a loan from her son-in-law Henry III of four thousand marks.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] WidowhoodWhen Ramon Berenguer had died on 19 August 1245, he left
1 CONT Provence to his youngest daughter. Beatrice's daughter and namesake then
1 CONT became one of the most attractive heiresses in medieval Europe. Various
1 CONT suitors had tried to seize her, so Beatrice of Savoy placed the younger
1 CONT Beatrice in a safe fortress, secured the trust of its people then went to the
1 CONT Pope for his protection. In Cluny during December 1245, a secret discussion,
1 CONT between Pope Innocent IV, Louis IX of France, his mother Blanche of Castile
1 CONT and his brother Charles of Anjou, took place. It was decided that in return
1 CONT for Louis IX supporting the Pope militarily, the Pope would allow Charles of
1 CONT Anjou, youngest brother to the French King, to marry Beatrice of Provence. But
1 CONT Provence was to never go to France outright through Charles. It was agreed
1 CONT that if Charles and Beatrice had children, the county would go to them; if
1 CONT there was no issue, then the county would go to Sanchia of Provence. If
1 CONT Sanchia died without an heir, Provence would go to the King of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT The generally good relationship between the four sisters also did much to
1 CONT improve the relationship of the French and English kings. It brought about the
1 CONT Treaty of Paris, where differences were resolved.[3] Beatrice and all her four
1 CONT daughters participated in the talks.[4]
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy was granted the usufruct of the county of Provence for her
1 CONT lifetime, according to her husband's will. Beatrice outlived her third
1 CONT daughter Sanchia and came close to outliving her youngest daughter Beatrice,
1 CONT who died months after her mother (Beatrice the elder died in January, Beatrice
1 CONT the younger died in September). Beatrice of Savoy died on 4 January 1267
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1205 – 4 January 1267) was the daughter of Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy and Margaret of Geneva. She was Countess consort of Provence by her
1 CONT marriage to Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandparents were Humbert III, Count of Savoy, and Beatrice of
1 CONT Viennois. Her maternal grandparents were William I, Count of Geneva and
1 CONT Beatrice de Faucigny. Beatrice of Savoy's mother, Margaret was betrothed to
1 CONT Philip II of France. While Margaret was travelling to France for her wedding,
1 CONT she was captured by Beatrice's father, Thomas. He took her back to Savoy and
1 CONT married her himself. Thomas' excuse was that Philip II was already married,
1 CONT which was true.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was the tenth of fourteen children born to her parents. Her siblings
1 CONT included: Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy; Thomas II of Piedmont; Peter II, Count
1 CONT of Savoy; Philip I, Count of Savoy; Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop of
1 CONT Canterbury; Avita the Countess of Devon; and Margherita of Savoy wife of
1 CONT Hartmann I of Kyburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice betrothed on 5 June 1219 to Ramon Berenguer IV, Count of Provence;
1 CONT they married in December 1220. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman,
1 CONT whose beauty was likened to that of a second Niobe by Matthew Paris. Ramon and
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all lived to adulthood, and married
1 CONT kings. Their only son, Raymond died in early infancy.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Margaret, Queen of France (1221–1295), wife of Louis IX of France
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Eleanor, Queen of England (1223–1291), wife of Henry III of England
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Sanchia, Queen of Germany (1228–1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Beatrice, Queen of Sicily (1231–1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Raymond of Provence, died young
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1242, Beatrice's brother Peter was sent to Provence by Henry III to
1 CONT negotiate the marriage of Sanchia to Richard. Another brother, Philip,
1 CONT escorted Beatrice and Sanchia to the English court in Gascony, arriving in May
1 CONT 1243. There they joined Henry, Eleanor, and their baby, Beatrice of England.
1 CONT Henry was very happy at this occasion and gave many gifts to the various
1 CONT relatives.
1 CONT
1 CONT In November 1243, Beatrice and Sanchia travelled to England for the wedding.
1 CONT This wedding did much to strengthen the bond between Richard and Henry III.
1 CONT She further strengthened the unity of the English royal family by convincing
1 CONT Henry III to help pay the debts of his sister Eleanor and her husband Simon de
1 CONT Montfort, who had often been at odds with Henry. In January 1244, Beatrice
1 CONT negotiated a loan for her husband from Henry of four thousand marks, offering
1 CONT the king five Provençal castles as collateral.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Ramon Berenguer died on 19 August 1245, he left Provence to his youngest
1 CONT daughter, and his widow was granted the usufruct of the county of Provence for
1 CONT her lifetime. Beatrice's daughter and namesake then became one of the most
1 CONT attractive heiresses in medieval Europe. Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor sent
1 CONT a fleet and James I of Aragon sent an army to seize her, so Beatrice placed
1 CONT herself and her daughter in a safe fortress in Aix, secured the trust of its
1 CONT people then sent to the Pope for his protection. The Pope was also a target
1 CONT for Frederick's military incursions in France. In Cluny during December 1245,
1 CONT a secret discussion, between Pope Innocent IV, Louis IX of France, his mother
1 CONT Blanche of Castile, and his brother Charles of Anjou, took place. It was
1 CONT decided that in return for Louis IX supporting the Pope militarily, the Pope
1 CONT would allow Charles of Anjou, youngest brother to the French King, to marry
1 CONT Beatrice of Provence. Mother and daughter were satisfied with this selection.
1 CONT But Provence was to never go to France outright through Charles. It was agreed
1 CONT that if Charles and Beatrice had children, the county would go to them; if
1 CONT there was no issue, then the county would go to Sanchia of Provence. If
1 CONT Sanchia died without an heir, Provence would go to the King of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry protested the selection, arguing that he had not yet received the full
1 CONT dowry for Eleanor nor his brother for Sanchia. He also still had the castles
1 CONT in Provence against the loan he had made to the former count.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Charles took over the administration of Provence in 1246, he did not
1 CONT respect Beatrice's rights within the county. She sought the aid of Barral of
1 CONT Baux and the Pope in protecting her rights within the area. The citizens of
1 CONT Marseille, Avignon, and Arles joined this resistance to Capetian control. In
1 CONT 1248, Charles began to seek peace with her so that he could join his brother's
1 CONT crusade. A temporary truce was reached to allow this.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1248, she travelled back to England with her brother Thomas, to see their
1 CONT family there.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1254, as Louis was returning from his crusade by way of Provence, Beatrice
1 CONT petitioned him for a more permanent resolution of the dispute with Charles.
1 CONT The French queen Margaret joined the petition, noting that Charles had not
1 CONT respected her dowry either. Beatrice travelled with them back to Paris. As the
1 CONT year progressed, Henry and his wife were invited to travel to Paris, and
1 CONT eventually all four daughters joined their mother there for Christmas.
1 CONT
1 CONT The generally good relationship among the four sisters did much to improve the
1 CONT relationship of the French and English kings. It brought about the Treaty of
1 CONT Paris in 1259, where differences were resolved. Beatrice and all her four
1 CONT daughters participated in the talks. While the family was still gathered,
1 CONT Louis IX finally persuaded Beatrice to surrender her claims and control in
1 CONT Provence in exchange for a sizable pension to be paid to her. Charles also
1 CONT paid back the loan henry had made to the previous count, clearing his claims
1 CONT in the county.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1262, Beatrice was part of the family discussion to try again to bring
1 CONT peace between Henry and Simon de Montfort. When Henry was captured in 1264,
1 CONT Beatrice's brother Peter II, Count of Savoy took his army to join the efforts
1 CONT to free the king. He left Beatrice in charge of Savoy while he was gone.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice outlived her third daughter Sanchia and came close to outliving her
1 CONT youngest daughter Beatrice, who died months after her mother (Beatrice the
1 CONT elder died in January, Beatrice the younger died in September). Beatrice of
1 CONT Savoy died on 4 January 1267.
