1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (1198 – 1266), was the daughter of Thomas I of Savoy and
1 CONT Marguerite of Geneva. Beatrice married on (5 June 1219) Ramon Berenguer IV,
1 CONT Count of Provence. She was a shrewd and politically astute woman, whose beauty
1 CONT was likened to that of a second Niobe by Matthew Paris. After two stillborn
1 CONT sons, Ramon and Beatrice of Savoy had four daughters, who all married kings.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marguerite of Provence (1221-1295), wife of Louis IX of France
1 CONT Eleanor of Provence (1223-1291), wife of Henry III of England
1 CONT Sanchia of Provence (1228-1261), wife of Richard, Earl of Cornwall
1 CONT Beatrice of Provence (1231-1267), wife of Charles I of Sicily
1 CONT She was famous along with her husband for learning and literary taste.
1 CONT She was celebrated, with her husband, for her learning and literary taste.
1 CONT She was celebrated, with her husband, for her learning and literary taste.
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (d. 1258), married firstly in 1233 Manfred, Margrave of
1 CONT Saluzzo (d. 1244), married secondly on April 21, 1247 Manfred of Sicily.
1 CONT [Wikipedia]
