1 CONT illegitimate daughter of William II of Athens, son of Frederick II of Sicily."
1 CONT (wikipedia)
1 CONT
1 CONT _________
1 CONT
1 CONT Summary
1 CONT
1 CONT The earliest historical records on Margarita d’Aragona refer to her as the
1 CONT daughter of Guglielmo d’Aragona, Count of Malta. In her testament dated 1418
1 CONT she is referred to as Donna Margarita D'ARAGONA of the Regional ancestry of
1 CONT the King of Sicily. Meanwhile her father is listed as Guglielmo Count of Malta
1 CONT in 1377 and natural son of King Federico III of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT Margarita possessed a generous but also strong willed personality. She left
1 CONT several valuable legacies of money and land to her servants and innumerable
1 CONT gifts and endowments to the church.
1 CONT
1 CONT On the other hand she revoked the donation of Marnisi and Bahria she had made
1 CONT previously by public deed in the City of Agrigento in favour of her
1 CONT grandchildren Giovanni Antonio and Federico del Carretto, sons of her daughter
1 CONT Leonora on the grounds that the donation had been made by coercion and against
1 CONT her will while she was lying ill in her daughter’s house. She did however make
1 CONT some concessions, allowing Leonora to keep a proportion of her estate given to
1 CONT her as a dowry and also donating Marnisi to Giovanni del Carretto on condition
1 CONT that the will was not to be contested.
1 CONT
1 CONT Margarita, in accordance with her wish, was buried in the Cathedral of Mdina
1 CONT though no trace of her monument remains as the old Cathedral was destroyed in
1 CONT the earthquake of 1693. But the greatest monument to Margarita is the Lunziata
1 CONT Church near Rabat which she rebuilt and bequeathed together with other
1 CONT endowments to the Carmelites in her will and, for that reason, was
1 CONT instrumental in founding the first Carmelite community in Malta. This church,
1 CONT although altered over the years, still stands and is used to this day as a
1 CONT place of worship and retreat.
1 CONT
1 CONT Foundress of the Carmelite convent in Malta she possessed many properties
1 CONT including the territories of Marnisi, Baharia, Deyrlimara, and il 'Giardino e
1 CONT terre delle due fontane'
1 CONT \------------------
1 CONT She is not in any of her parents' Wiki and Medlands
1 CONT
1 CONT "[<https://www.geni.com/people/Guglielmo-de-Arag%C3%B3n-duke-of-Athens-
1 CONT Neopatras-regent-of-Sicily-count-of-Malta/6000000006727867916> Guglielmo] non
1 CONT ebbe alcun figlio da [<https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-d-Aragona-di-
1 CONT Ejerica/6000000006727876711?through=6000000006727867916> Maria] e di lui non
1 CONT si conosce alcuna discendenza."
1 CONT
1 CONT   * <https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guglielmo_d%27Aragona>
1 CONT \---------
1 CONT
1 CONT /!\
1 CONT -[https://gw.geneanet.org/jpbuhagiar?lang=en&pz=jean+pierre+baptiste+marcel&nz=buhagiar&p=marguerite+margarita&n=d+aragon](https://gw.geneanet.org/jpbuhagiar?lang=en&pz=jean+pierre+baptiste+marcel&nz=buhagiar&p=marguerite+margarita&n=d+aragon)
1 CONT
1 CONT **Please read the well researched background below that highlights the
1 CONT question of her paternity and provides a reasonable explanation.**
1 CONT
1 CONT \----------
1 CONT Background
1 CONT
1 CONT The 14th century in Malta was not an age when a woman would be expected to
1 CONT wield influence or power. They were turbulent times and, as part of the
1 CONT Aragonese kingdom of Sicily as well as its position on the centre of the
1 CONT Mediterranean, Malta was a hotbed of strife and intrigue which was to last at
1 CONT least until the Order of St John took over the island’s administration in
1 CONT 1530.
1 CONT
1 CONT Italy then was no more than a conglomeration of little states, principalities,
1 CONT bishoprics and duchies. Naples and Sicily, Venice and Genoa, the Papal states,
1 CONT when not trying to keep external forces such as Islam at bay, were continually
1 CONT warring and plotting against each other in the battle for supremacy and
1 CONT influence. It took only the slightest political upset or the merest hint of a
1 CONT threat to turn partners within an alliance into implacable foes.
1 CONT
1 CONT In such an atmosphere it was the man of action, the buccaneer and the soldier
1 CONT who dominated the scene. The man of letters was conspicuous by his absence and
1 CONT if any contemporary accounts were written during that period, none has come to
1 CONT light so far.
1 CONT
1 CONT The earliest historical records on Margarita d’Aragona refer to her as the
1 CONT daughter of Guglielmo d’Aragona, Count of Malta. In her testament dated 1418
1 CONT she is referred to as Donna Margarita D'ARAGONA of the Regional ancestry of
1 CONT the King of Sicily. Meanwhile her father is listed as Guglielmo Count of Malta
1 CONT in 1377 and natural son of King Federico III of Sicily. Fortunately, there is
1 CONT no scarcity of documentation as meticulous records of most transactions
1 CONT affecting the kingdom were kept in the Royal Chancery in Palermo. The Royal
1 CONT Archives in Palermo house a vast quantity of documents giving a wealth of
1 CONT detail on the Aragonese period of the Kingdom of Sicily and Malta. These
1 CONT records consist in royal decrees and grants, notarial deeds and a stream of
1 CONT correspondence between officials in Malta and Sicily. The archives of the
1 CONT cathedrals, monasteries and ecclesiastical foundations are also a fertile
1 CONT fount of information.
1 CONT
1 CONT But it was not until the 16th century that historians began to take an
1 CONT interest in Malta as a separate entity and sure enough the names of powerful
1 CONT men such as Artale d’Alagona, Manfredi Chiaramonte, Guglielmo Moncada and
1 CONT Giacomo Pellegrino loom large in their accounts.
1 CONT
1 CONT It is all the more surprising then that, in the midst of these swashbuckling
1 CONT heroes and anti-heroes, we keep coming across the name of one person who never
1 CONT handled a sword or tried to take on church and state. This person was
1 CONT Margarita d’Aragona.
1 CONT
1 CONT The earliest historical records on Margarita d’Aragona refer to her as the
1 CONT daughter of Guglielmo d’Aragona, Count of Malta and, as we shall see further
1 CONT along, there is ample evidence to prove that she was of royal blood. Who
1 CONT though was Guglielmo d’Aragona?
1 CONT
1 CONT Federico III was the first Aragonese monarch to visit Malta and some writers
1 CONT assumed that Margarita was the daughter of his natural son, Guglielmo who was
1 CONT created Count of Malta in 1377, the year of Federico’s death.
1 CONT
1 CONT However there was another Guglielmo d’Aragona and he too had been Count of
1 CONT Malta [1]. He was the third son of Federico II by his Queen, Eleonor of Anjou
1 CONT and was created Count in 1330. Guglielmo I was also Prince of Taranto and Duke
1 CONT of Athens and Neopatria. **He was married to Maria de Exercica without issue
1 CONT but during his visits to Malta, there is little doubt that he would have
1 CONT formed a liaison with some local lady** \- concubinage [2] was then
1 CONT established practice among the ruling classes. For instance, his father,
1 CONT Federico II spawned at least 4 natural children whom he later legitimised and
1 CONT gave important titles and positions in the kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT The question of Margarita’s paternity has perplexed historians over the years
1 CONT but, examined in its historical context, a reasonable explanation soon
1 CONT emerges. The confusion could well have arisen because of the ambiguous way in
1 CONT which the Aragonese Federicos were styled.
1 CONT
1 CONT The House of Aragon succeeded the House of Swabia (the Hohenstaufens) as
1 CONT rulers of Sicily as a result of the union of Pedro II of Aragon with
1 CONT Constance, daughter of Manfred, King of Sicily and heiress to the Sicilian
1 CONT throne. Manfred was the natural son of Frederick "Stupor Mundi" of Swabia,
1 CONT Holy Roman Emperor and King of Sicily. As Holy Roman Emperor, Frederick was
1 CONT second bearing that name, but first as King of Sicily. When Federico
1 CONT (Frederick) of Aragon succeeded to the Sicilian throne, he would have assumed
1 CONT the title of Federico II, King of Sicily but he was sometimes referred to as
1 CONT Federico III, adopting the imperial rather than the regal indication. His
1 CONT grandson would have been similarly styled Federico III or Federico IV
1 CONT depending on the writer’s point of view. A few modern historians persist in
1 CONT this misconception to this day and it is therefore not hard to understand that
1 CONT such conflicting references could have led to some confusion as to which of
1 CONT the two Aragonese Fredericks Federico III actually was.
1 CONT
1 CONT Evidence that Margarita would have been the daughter of **Guglielmo I** rather
1 CONT than [<https://www.geni.com/people/Guglielmo-d-Aragona-conte-di-Malta-e-
1 CONT Gozo/6000000015531215693> Guglielmo II] is corroborated by the dates gleaned
1 CONT from official documents relating to Margarita. In 1365 when Giacomo de
1 CONT Pellegrino was made Hakem [3] of Malta, the first since the Saracen held sway
1 CONT over the islands, Margarita was already his wife [4]. She would more likely
1 CONT have been closer to the age of Guglielmo II’s father King Federico III (born
1 CONT 1341), and could not possibly have been Guglielmo’s daughter.
1 CONT
1 CONT On the other hand, if she were the daughter of Guglielmo I, who was Count of
1 CONT Malta in 1330, her birth could be established at some time prior to his death
1 CONT in 1338, say 1336, which would be more consistent with the other factors and
1 CONT would also make her 82 years at the time of her death in 1418 [5].
1 CONT
1 CONT The Royal Grant appointing Giacomo de Pellegrino Hakem for life was issued in
1 CONT Malta and would have been made during the state visit of Federico III to the
1 CONT island. Pellegrino’s star was then very much in the ascendant assisted, in no
1 CONT small way, by the fact that he was married to the king’s kinswoman.
1 CONT
1 CONT Unfortunately the royal favour was not to last and seven years later
1 CONT Pellegrino was stripped of all his possessions and banished. It is unclear
1 CONT what caused the rupture between the king and Pellegrino, and conflicting
1 CONT accounts have been given of the events leading up to the crisis. The only
1 CONT facts that emerge with any degree of certainty are the following.
1 CONT
1 CONT # Giacomo Pellegrino was a sea captain and in all likelihood held a warrant to
1 CONT carry out acts of piracy against the infidel as well as the enemies of Aragon.
1 CONT Amongst the latter were Naples, the arch enemy, and their allies, the Genoese
1 CONT with whom Pellegrino had been involved in several skirmishes.
1 CONT
1 CONT # In 1368 Federico called a truce with the Angevin court of Naples and its
1 CONT allies, writing to the leading families of the kingdom including Pellegrino to
1 CONT prohibit further acts of piracy.
1 CONT
1 CONT # Pellegrino had incurred a substantial debt to the Genoese Commune. It is
1 CONT unknown whether this was in connection with his acts of piracy or for some
1 CONT legitimate commercial transaction.
1 CONT
1 CONT # Malta was invaded in 1371 by a fleet of Genoese ships under the command of
1 CONT Tommaso Morchio [6].
1 CONT
1 CONT # Pellegrino was exiled and his possessions confiscated in 1372.
1 CONT
1 CONT The theory mooted by Giovanni Francesco Abela, writing in the early 1600s, was
1 CONT that Pellegrino attacked the Genoese in reprisal to Morchio’s attack. But it
1 CONT seems more likely that the opposite was the case. In spite of the royal edict,
1 CONT Pellegrino’s hatred towards the Genoese was such that he persisted in his acts
1 CONT of piracy and Morchio’s invasion can be construed as the latter’s act of
1 CONT reprisal. The drastic consequences of the invasion must have been the major
1 CONT factor in arousing the king’s displeasure and his natural reaction would have
1 CONT been to punish Pellegrino for having provoked the invasion.
1 CONT
1 CONT However Federico’s anger dissipated hardly a year after he had banished
1 CONT Pellegrino from the kingdom. This indicates that the truce with Naples was
1 CONT superficial and, underlying it all, the king was secretly in sympathy with
1 CONT Pellegrino’s actions. The royal purse was much depleted in that period and
1 CONT Federico had been forced to borrow heavily. Some of his creditors had strong
1 CONT links with Genoa and may well have forced his hand in taking retributive
1 CONT action against Pellegrino. The enmity between Aragon and Genoa however was too
1 CONT ancient and deep seated to be swept away overnight.
1 CONT
1 CONT The chancery records provide the only certain evidence of the king’s feelings
1 CONT towards Pellegrino.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1372, Margarita d’Aragona appealed to Federico for clemency towards her
1 CONT husband. In his decree [7] of November 1372, the king ignored her plea. It was
1 CONT too soon after the conflict for the king to contemplate modifying his sentence
1 CONT on Giacomo but he ordered the Secreto to give Margarita, consanguineam fidelem
1 CONT nostram, an annual grant of 50 uncie in order to enable her to maintain the
1 CONT position expected of her rank.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1373, Margarita made a further plea for clemency. This time her appeal met
1 CONT with greater success. The king's decree [8] issued in Messina on 11 October
1 CONT 1373 stated that "… following the renewed humble supplications to Our
1 CONT Excellency by Our faithful kinswoman and friend, the noble Margarita
1 CONT d’Aragona, consort of Giacomo de Peregrino, Milite, We graciously grant the
1 CONT same noble lady that the said Giacomo, her husband (having first settled his
1 CONT debt to the Magnifico Doge and Commune of Genoa) may, freely and without fear
1 CONT of reprisal, come to the noble city of Messina……"
1 CONT
1 CONT It would seem however that the confiscated property was never restored, as
1 CONT none appears in Margarita’s will [9] of 5 June 1418. The will lists the
1 CONT following property [10] owned by Margarita in her own right:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Bahria (Bahrija) - Fief
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Deylimara (Delimara) - Fief
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Marnesi (Marnisi) (Zejtun) - Fief
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Marsa - Fief
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Deylbinet (Djar il-Bniet)- Garden
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Ghariexem (Gheriexem) - Vineyard or Garden
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Gnien el feres (Gnien il-Fieres) (Wied il-Qlejgha) - Garden
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Fiddeni iddenum (Fiddien) - Land
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Galabir il hal chadin el mula (Bubaqra) - Agricultural land
1 CONT
1 CONT   * La Arcata (Zurrieq) - Land
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Suatar (Swatar) - Cultivated and uncultivated land
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Weden - Agricultural land
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Panedes et Villa Franca (Vilafranca en Penedés) (Catalonia) - Property and rights
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Maymona - Land
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Gozo- property
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Guicobbira (Sancto Leonardo) - New Construction (Lunzjata Carmelite Church)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Two Store Rooms in Rabat
1 CONT
1 CONT The fiefs owned by Pellegrino prior to 1372 were:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Ajn Kajet (Ghajn Qajjed) 1361
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Ajn Teuzin (Ghajn Tewzin) 1360
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Ajn Toffieha (Ghajn Tuffieha) 1361
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Benuarrat (Benwarrad) 1361
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Chabelbelach 1361
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Gnien is-Sultan 1361
1 CONT
1 CONT   * la Hafe 1360
1 CONT
1 CONT   * ta Zaccari (lu Zacuni) 1372
1 CONT
1 CONT Margarita possessed a generous but also strong willed personality. She left
1 CONT several valuable legacies of money and land to her servants and innumerable
1 CONT gifts and endowments to the church.
1 CONT
1 CONT On the other hand she revoked the donation of Marnisi and Bahria she had made
1 CONT previously by public deed in the City of Agrigento in favour of her
1 CONT grandchildren Giovanni Antonio and Federico del Carretto, sons of her daughter
1 CONT Leonora on the grounds that the donation had been made by coercion and against
1 CONT her will while she was lying ill in her daughter’s house. She did however make
1 CONT some concessions, allowing Leonora to keep a proportion of her estate given to
1 CONT her as a dowry and also donating Marnisi to Giovanni del Carretto on condition
1 CONT that the will was not to be contested.
1 CONT
1 CONT Margarita, in accordance with her wish, was buried in the Cathedral of Mdina
1 CONT though no trace of her monument remains as the old Cathedral was destroyed in
1 CONT the earthquake of 1693. But the greatest monument to Margarita is the Lunziata
1 CONT Church near Rabat which she rebuilt and bequeathed together with other
1 CONT endowments to the Carmelites in her will and, for that reason, was
1 CONT instrumental in founding the first Carmelite community in Malta. This church,
1 CONT although altered over the years, still stands and is used to this day as a
1 CONT place of worship and retreat.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
