1 CONT
1 CONT /// Wikipedia : « He is the illegitimate son of King Frederick III of Sicily
1 CONT and an unknown mistress [1].
1 CONT
1 CONT Malta had been attributed in 1366 to Manfredi III Chiaromonte. But this
1 CONT appointment had been badly accepted by the strong man of the island, Giacomo
1 CONT de Pellegrino, both captain of the garrison and privateer. The revolt lasted
1 CONT several years until it was put down by a fleet of Genoese galleys and by the
1 CONT visit to the island of Frederick III in person. The king then decides to have
1 CONT the island administered by Jean Frédéric d'Aragon, asking him to stay and live
1 CONT there in order to calm the revolt durably [2].
1 CONT
1 CONT When the king died in 1377, the county of Malta returned by will to Guillermo
1 CONT [3]. But it seems that this appointment was virtual, Malta being attributed by
1 CONT King Peter IV of Aragon to Louis Frederick of Aragon [2]. In reality, it is
1 CONT likely that Malta continued to be administered by Manfredi III Chiaromonte,
1 CONT became the vicar and principal ruler of Sicily.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was married to Beatrice d'Aragón-Avola [4] (daughter of Giovanna and Juan
1 CONT de Aragón, Baron d'Avola, and granddaughter of Orlando of Aragon) from whom he
1 CONT had at least one daughter, Giovanna, who married Pietro di Gioeni, Baron
1 CONT d'Ardore [4].
1 CONT
1 CONT Another daughter is sometimes attributed to him, Margarita d'Aragon, who
1 CONT married Giacomo de Pellegrino [5]. but it is more likely that Margarita was
1 CONT the illegitimate daughter of William II of Athens, son of Frederick II of
1 CONT Sicily (6). »**
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT          ****
