0 @N00594@ NOTE geni:about_me <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/HUNGARY.htm#IstvanVB>
1 CONT
1 CONT **ISTVÁN** , son of BÉLA IV King of Hungary & his wife Maria Laskarina of
1 CONT Nikaia (18 Oct 1239-1 Aug 1272, Csepel Island, Dominican Monastery). The
1 CONT Chronicon Varadiense names "dux Stephanus postea rex, secundus…dux Bela" as
1 CONT the two sons of "rex Bela quartus"[970]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-
1 CONT Fontaines records the birth "in festo beati Luce 1239" of "regi Hungarie
1 CONT filius masculus…Stephanum"[971]. The Altahenses Annales name "Stephanum filium
1 CONT [Belæ regis Ungarie]" when recording his succession to his father[972]. His
1 CONT father appointed him Prince of Transylvania in 1257. He led the Hungarian
1 CONT troops which invaded Bulgaria in 1261, restoring his brother-in-law Rostislav,
1 CONT who was one of the claimants to the Bulgarian throne after Tsar Koloman II was
1 CONT deposed in 1258, at Vidin. Duke of Slavonia, Dalmatia and Croatia, his father
1 CONT transferred these territories to his younger brother Béla in 1262, whereupon
1 CONT István revolted, although peace was concluded 5 Dec 1262 under which the
1 CONT country was divided and István retained the territory north of the Danube
1 CONT along the border with Bulgaria with the titles "rex iunior" and "dominus
1 CONT Cumanorum". Civil war broke out again in 1264, peace once more being confirmed
1 CONT in István's favour in 1266[973]. He succeeded his father in 1270 as **ISTVÁN V
1 CONT King of Hungary**. The Altahenses Annales record the death "1272 circa Kal
1 CONT Aug" of "Stephanus rex Ungarie"[974]. The Chronicon Dubnicense records the
1 CONT death "in magna insula" of "Stephanus" and his burial "in ecclesia beate
1 CONT Virginis in insula Budensi in loco Beginarum"[975]. The Gesta Hungarorum
1 CONT records that King István was buried "in insula…Beatæ Virginis"[976]. m (1253)
1 CONT --- of the Kumans, daughter of --- Khan of the Kumans (1240-after 1290). This
1 CONT marriage was agreed as part of King Béla's arrangements for settling the
1 CONT Kumans on empty land on either side of the River Tisza[977]. She was baptised
1 CONT with the name ELISABETH. Regent for her son King László IV in 1272, she was
1 CONT hated by the Hungarians[978]. King István V & his wife had six children:
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 1\. ELISABETH (1255-[1313/26]). m firstly (1287) as his third wife, ZAVIŠ von Rosenberg zu Skalitz und Falkenstein m secondly ([1295], repudiated [1298/99]) as his third wife, STEFAN UROŠ II MILUTIN King of Serbia
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 2\. KATALIN ([1255/57]-). m ([1267/68]) STEFAN DRAGUTIN of Serbia
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 3\. MÁRIA ([1257]-25 Mar 1324, bur Naples, Santa Maria Donna Regina). m (Naples [May/Jun] 1270) CHARLES of Sicily Principe di Salerno. Maria & her husband had fourteen children: ...
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 4\. ANNA ([1260]-[1281]). m (1274) as his first wife, co-Emperor ANDRONIKOS Palaiologos He succeeded his father in 1282 as Emperor ANDRONIKOS II.
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 5\. LÁSZLÓ (1262-murdered Kereczeg [Körösszeg] Castle 10 Jul 1290, bur Csanad Cathedral). m (5 Sep 1272) ISABELLE of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT   * 6\. ANDRÁS (1268-1278).
1 CONT
1 CONT King Stephen V of Hungary (Hungarian: V. István, Slovak: Štefan V, Croatian:
1 CONT Stjepan VI.) (December 1239, Buda, Hungary – August 6, 1272, Csepel Island,
1 CONT Hungary), was the son of Bela IV of Hungary, whom he succeeded in 1270.
1 CONT
1 CONT His mother was Maria Laskarina, a daughter of Theodore I Lascaris of the
1 CONT Empire of Nicaea and Anna Angelina. Anna was a daughter of Alexius III Angelus
1 CONT and Euphrosyne Doukaina Kamaterina.
1 CONT
1 CONT As crown prince Stephen had exhibited considerable ability, but also a
1 CONT disquieting restlessness and violence. He was appointed duke of Transylvania,
1 CONT then duke of Styria. After the loss of Styria he became duke of Transylvania
1 CONT again. In 1262 Stephen convinced his father Béla to give him twenty-nine
1 CONT counties as a reward of assistance in the war against Bohemia; hence Hungary
1 CONT was virtually divided into two kingdoms. Stephen was crowned junior king of
1 CONT Hungary. Though Hungary was de facto divided into two kingdoms the legal unity
1 CONT remained, because Stephen theoretically ruled by the grace of God and his
1 CONT father. He subsequently seized the southern banate of Macsó and defeated his
1 CONT father in the ensuing civil war. In 1268 he undertook an expedition against
1 CONT the Bulgarians, penetrating as far as Veliko Tarnovo and styling himself as
1 CONT king of Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen's father, attempting to bind the powerful but pagan Cuman tribe more
1 CONT closely to the dynasty, arranged for Stephen's marriage, as a youth (about
1 CONT 1255), to Elizabeth, the daughter of the Cuman chieftain (named Koteny or
1 CONT Kuthens). Though Elizabeth, in preparation for the marriage, had been baptized
1 CONT and remained a Christian, Western Europe almost universally considered Stephen
1 CONT as a semi-pagan. This hostility was felt as Stephen declared himself that
1 CONT everyone was his enemy for his accession to the Hungarian throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT To secure foreign support, he formed a double matrimonial alliance with the
1 CONT Angevins, chief partisans of the pope. The first of these was the marriage in
1 CONT 1270 of his daughter Maria of Hungary to Charles II of Naples (they became
1 CONT grandparents of Charles I of Hungary). The second alliance was the marriage of
1 CONT Stephen's infant son Ladislaus to Charles II's sister Elisabeth.
1 CONT
1 CONT Byzantine Emperor Andronicus II Palaeologus married Anna, another of Stephen's
1 CONT daughters. Serbian king Stefan Dragutin married Katerina, yet another of
1 CONT Stephan's daughters.
1 CONT
1 CONT Adversaries of Stephen, especially Ottokar II of Bohemia, believed that
1 CONT Stephen was too great a friend of the mighty Cumans (who could field 16,000
1 CONT men) to be a true Catholic. Ottokar endeavoured with the aid of the Hungarian
1 CONT malcontents to conquer the western provinces of Hungary but they were utterly
1 CONT routed by Stephen in 1271 near Mosony. Ottokar relinquished all his conquests
1 CONT the same year in the peace of Pressburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen died suddenly as he was raising an army to rescue his kidnapped infant
1 CONT son Ladislaus from his rebellious vassals.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen V of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen V (Hungarian: V. István, Croatian: Stjepan VI., Slovak: Štefan V)
1 CONT (before October 18 1239, Buda, Hungary – August 6 1272, Csepel Island,
1 CONT Hungary), King of Hungary and Croatia (1246-1272), and Duke of Styria
1 CONT (1258-1260).
1 CONT
1 CONT Early years
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the elder son of King Béla IV of Hungary and his queen, Maria
1 CONT Laskarina, a daughter of the Emperor Theodore I Lascaris of Nicaea.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the second year following his birth, on April 11, 1241, the Mongolian
1 CONT troops defeated his father's army in the Battle of Mohi. After the disastrous
1 CONT battle, the royal family had to escape to Trau, a well-fortified city in
1 CONT Dalmatia. They could only return to Hungary after the unexpected withdrawal of
1 CONT the Mongol forces from Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT Junior King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1246 Stephen was crowned as junior King and his father entrusted him with
1 CONT the government of Croatia, Slavonia and Dalmatia, but the three provinces were
1 CONT de facto governed by the Ban Stephen Gut-Keled. Stephen's father, attempting
1 CONT to bind the powerful but pagan Cuman tribes more closely to the dynasty,
1 CONT arranged for Stephen's marriage, as a youth (about 1253), to Elizabeth, the
1 CONT daughter of a Cuman chieftain Köten.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1257, Stephen demanded his father to divide the kingdom between themselves
1 CONT and recruited an army against the senior king. Finally, in 1258, King Béla IV
1 CONT was obliged to cede him the government of Transylvania.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Duke of Styria
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen took part in his father's military campaign against the Styrians, who
1 CONT had rebelled against the rule of the King of Hungary, in 1258. After the
1 CONT successful campaign, King Béla IV appointed him to Duke of Styria.
1 CONT
1 CONT His government, however, was unpopular among his new subjects, who rebelled
1 CONT against him with the support of King Otakar II of Bohemia. Stephen and his
1 CONT father started an attack against Otakar II's lands, but their troops were
1 CONT defeated on July 12, 1260 in the Battle of Kroissenbrunn. Following the
1 CONT battle, the two Kings of Hungary ceded the Duchy of Styria to the King of
1 CONT Bohemia in the Peace of Pozsony (Slovak: Bratislava).
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Struggles with his father
1 CONT
1 CONT Shortly after the peace, Stephen took over again the government of
1 CONT Transylvania. In 1261, Stephen and his father made a joint military campaign
1 CONT against Bulgaria, but their relationship became more and more tense, because
1 CONT the senior king had been favouring his younger son, Duke Béla of Slavonia and
1 CONT his daughter, Anna, the mother-in-law of the King of Bohemia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Finally, with the mediation of Archbishops Fülöp of Esztergom and Smaragd of
1 CONT Kalocsa, Stephen and his father signed an agreement in the summer of 1262 in
1 CONT Pozsony. Based on their agreement, Stephen took over the government of the
1 CONT parts of the kingdom East of the Danube. However, the two kings'
1 CONT reconciliation was only temporary, because their partisans were continuously
1 CONT inciteting them against each other. In 1264, Stephen seized his mother's and
1 CONT sister's estates in his domains, but his father sent troops against him.
1 CONT Stephen's wife and son was captured by his father's partisans, and he had to
1 CONT retreat to the castle of Feketehalom. However, he managed to repeal the siege
1 CONT and to commence a counter-attack.
1 CONT
1 CONT In March 1265, he gained a strategic victory over his father's army in the
1 CONT Battle of Isaszeg. After his victory, he concluded a peace with King Béla IV.
1 CONT Based on the provisions of the peace, he received back the government of the
1 CONT Eastern parts of the kingdom. On March 23, 1266, father and son confirmed the
1 CONT peace in the Convent of the Blessed Virgin on the Nyulak szigete ('Rabbits'
1 CONT Island'). Shortly afterwards, Stephen V lead his army to Bulgaria and forced
1 CONT Despot Jakov Svetoslav of Vidin to accept his overlordship.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1267, the "prelates and nobles" of the Kingdom of Hungary held a joint
1 CONT assembly in Esztergom, and their decisions were confirmed by both Stephen and
1 CONT his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT To secure foreign support, he formed a double matrimonial alliance with the
1 CONT Angevins, chief partisans of the pope. The first of these was the marriage, in
1 CONT 1270, of his daughter Maria to the future King Charles II of Naples[1] The
1 CONT second alliance was the marriage of Stephen's infant son, Ladislaus to Charles
1 CONT II's sister Elisabeth.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT After his father's death (May 3, 1270), Stephen inherited the whole Kingdom of
1 CONT Hungary, although the deceased senior king had entrusted his daughter, Anna
1 CONT and his followers to King Otakar II of Bohemia in his last will, and they had
1 CONT escaped to Prague before Stephen arrived to Esztergom.
1 CONT
1 CONT Before his (second) coronation, Stephen granted the County of Esztergom to the
1 CONT Archbishop. In August 1270, Stephen had a meeting with his brother-in-law,
1 CONT Prince Bolesław V of Poland in Cracow where they concluded an alliance against
1 CONT the King of Bohemia. Stephen also had a meeting with King Otakar II on 16
1 CONT October on an island of the Danube near to Pozsony where they concluded a
1 CONT truce for two years.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, following smaller skirmishes on the border, the war broke out soon
1 CONT and the King of Bohemia lead his armies against Hungary. Stephen was defeated
1 CONT in two smaller battles, but finally he won a decisive victory on 21 May 1271
1 CONT over the Czech and Austrian troops of Otakar II. In the subsequent peace the
1 CONT King of Bohemia handed back the fortresses occupied during its campaign, while
1 CONT Stephen renounced its claim for the Hungarian royal treasury that his sister,
1 CONT Anna had brought to Prague after their father's death.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the summer of 1272, Stephen left for Dalmatia, where he wanted to meet King
1 CONT Charles I of Sicily, when he was informed that Joachim Gut-Keled kidnapped his
1 CONT infant son, Ladislaus. Stephen was planning to raise an army to rescue his
1 CONT infant son, when he died suddenly.
1 CONT
