1 CONT [edit] Early years
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the elder son of King Béla IV of Hungary and his queen, Maria
1 CONT Laskarina, a daughter of the Emperor Theodore I Lascaris of Nicaea.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the second year following his birth, on 11 April 1241, the Mongolian troops
1 CONT defeated his father's army in the Battle of Mohi. After the disastrous battle,
1 CONT the royal family had to escape to Trau, a well-fortified city in Dalmatia.
1 CONT They could only return to Hungary after the unexpected withdrawal of the
1 CONT Mongol forces from Europe..
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Junior King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1246 Stephen was crowned as junior King and his father entrusted him with
1 CONT the government of Croatia, Slavonia and Dalmatia, but the three provinces were
1 CONT de facto governed by the Ban Stephen Gut-Keled. Stephen's father, attempting
1 CONT to bind the powerful but pagan Cuman tribes more closely to the dynasty,
1 CONT arranged for Stephen's marriage, as a youth (about 1253), to Elizabeth, the
1 CONT daughter of a Cuman chieftain Köten.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1257, Stephen demanded that his father divide the kingdom between
1 CONT themselves and recruited an army against the senior king. Finally, in 1258,
1 CONT King Béla IV was obliged to cede to him the government of Transylvania.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Duke of Styria
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen took part in his father's military campaign against the Styrians, who
1 CONT had rebelled against the rule of the King of Hungary, in 1258. After the
1 CONT successful campaign, King Béla IV appointed him to Duke of Styria.
1 CONT
1 CONT His government, however, was unpopular among his new subjects, who rebelled
1 CONT against him with the support of King Otakar II of Bohemia. Stephen and his
1 CONT father started an attack against Otakar II's lands, but their troops were
1 CONT defeated on 12 July 1260 in the Battle of Kroissenbrunn. Following the battle,
1 CONT the two Kings of Hungary ceded the Duchy of Styria to the King of Bohemia in
1 CONT the Peace of Pressburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Struggles with his father
1 CONT
1 CONT Shortly after the peace, Stephen took over the government of Transylvania
1 CONT again. In 1261, Stephen and his father conducted a joint military campaign
1 CONT against Bulgaria, but their relationship became more and more tense, because
1 CONT the senior king had been favouring his younger son, Duke Béla of Slavonia and
1 CONT his daughter, Anna, the mother-in-law of the King of Bohemia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Finally, with the mediation of Archbishops Fülöp of Esztergom and Smaragd of
1 CONT Kalocsa, Stephen and his father signed an agreement in the summer of 1262 in
1 CONT Pozsony. Based on their agreement, Stephen took over the government of the
1 CONT parts of the kingdom East of the Danube. However, the two kings'
1 CONT reconciliation was only temporary, because their partisans were continuously
1 CONT inciting them against each other. In 1264, Stephen seized his mother's and
1 CONT sister's estates in his domains, but his father sent troops against him.
1 CONT Stephen's wife and son were captured by his father's partisans, and he had to
1 CONT retreat to the castle of Feketehalom. However, he managed to repeal the siege
1 CONT and to commence a counter-attack.
1 CONT
1 CONT In March 1265, he gained a strategic victory over his father's army in the
1 CONT Battle of Isaszeg. After his victory, he concluded a peace with King Béla IV.
1 CONT Based on the provisions of the peace, he received back the government of the
1 CONT Eastern parts of the kingdom. On 23 March 1266, father and son confirmed the
1 CONT peace in the Convent of the Blessed Virgin on the Nyulak szigete ('Rabbits'
1 CONT Island'). Shortly afterwards, Stephen V led his army to Bulgaria and forced
1 CONT Despot Jakob Svetoslav of Vidin to accept his overlordship.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1267, the "prelates and nobles" of the Kingdom of Hungary held a joint
1 CONT assembly in Esztergom, and their decisions were confirmed by both Stephen and
1 CONT his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT To secure foreign support, he formed a double matrimonial alliance with the
1 CONT Angevins, chief partisans of the pope. The first of these was the marriage, in
1 CONT 1270, of his daughter Maria to the future King Charles II of Naples[2] The
1 CONT second alliance was the marriage of Stephen's infant son, Ladislaus to Charles
1 CONT II's sister Elisabeth.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] King of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT After his father's death (3 May 1270), Stephen inherited the whole Kingdom of
1 CONT Hungary, although the deceased senior king had entrusted his daughter, Anna
1 CONT and his followers to King Otakar II of Bohemia in his last will, and they had
1 CONT escaped to Prague before Stephen arrived to Esztergom.
1 CONT
1 CONT Before his (second) coronation, Stephen granted the County of Esztergom to the
1 CONT Archbishop. In August 1270, Stephen had a meeting with his brother-in-law,
1 CONT Prince Bolesław V of Poland in Kraków where they concluded an alliance against
1 CONT the King of Bohemia. Stephen also had a meeting with King Otakar II on 16
1 CONT October on an island of the Danube near Pozsony where they concluded a truce
1 CONT for two years.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, following smaller skirmishes on the border, the war broke out soon
1 CONT after and the King of Bohemia lead his armies against Hungary. Stephen was
1 CONT defeated in two smaller battles, but finally won a decisive victory on 21 May
1 CONT 1271 over the Czech and Austrian troops of Otakar II. In the subsequent peace
1 CONT the King of Bohemia handed back the fortresses occupied during his campaign,
1 CONT while Stephen renounced his claim to the Hungarian royal treasury that his
1 CONT sister, Anna had brought to Prague after their father's death.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the summer of 1272, Stephen left for Dalmatia, where he wanted to meet King
1 CONT Charles I of Sicily, when he was informed that Joachim Gut-Keled had kidnapped
1 CONT his infant son, Ladislaus. Stephen was planning to raise an army to rescue his
1 CONT infant son when he died suddenly.
1 CONT
