1 CONT In the second year following his birth, on 11 April 1241, the Mongolian troops
1 CONT defeated his father's army in the Battle of Mohi. After the disastrous battle,
1 CONT the royal family had to escape to Trau, a well-fortified city in Dalmatia.
1 CONT They could only return to Hungary after the unexpected withdrawal of the
1 CONT Mongol forces from Europe..
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and children
1 CONT
1 CONT Around 1253: Elisabeth (1240 – after 1290), daughter of a chieftain of the
1 CONT Cuman tribes settled down in Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth (1255 – 1313/1326), wife firstly of Záviš of Falkenštejn and
1 CONT secondly of King Stefan Uroš II Milutin of Serbia
1 CONT
1 CONT Katarina (1255/1257 – after 1314), wife of King Stefan Dragutin of Serbia
1 CONT
1 CONT Mary (c. 1257 – 25 March 1325), wife of King Charles II of Naples
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna (c. 1260 – c. 1281), wife of the Emperor Andronikos II Palaiologos
1 CONT
1 CONT King Ladislaus IV (August 1262 – 10 July 1290)
1 CONT
1 CONT Duke Andrew of Slavonia (1268 – 1278)
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1246 Stephen was crowned as junior King and his father entrusted him with
1 CONT the government of Croatia, Slavonia and Dalmatia, but the three provinces were
1 CONT de facto governed by the Ban Stephen Gut-Keled. Stephen's father, attempting
1 CONT to bind the powerful but pagan Cuman tribes more closely to the dynasty,
1 CONT arranged for Stephen's marriage, as a youth (about 1253), to Elizabeth, the
1 CONT daughter of a Cuman chieftain Köten.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1257, Stephen demanded his father to divide the kingdom between themselves
1 CONT and recruited an army against the senior king. Finally, in 1258, King Béla IV
1 CONT was obliged to cede him the government of Transylvania.
1 CONT
