1 CONT Name Prefix: King Name Suffix: V, Of Hungary And Croatia
1 CONT Stephen V of Hungary
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT King Stephen V of Hungary (Hungarian: V. István, Slovak: Štefan V) (1239 or
1 CONT 1240 – August 6, 1272), was the eldest son of Bela IV of Hungary, whom he
1 CONT succeeded in 1270.
1 CONT
1 CONT As crown prince he had exhibited considerable ability, but also a disquieting
1 CONT restlessness and violence. In 1262 Stephen convinced his father Bela to give
1 CONT him twenty-nine counties as a reward of assistance in the war against Bohemia;
1 CONT hence Hungary was virtually divided into two kingdoms. He subsequently seized
1 CONT the southern banate of Macsó and defeated his father in the ensuing civil war.
1 CONT In 1268 he undertook an expedition against the Bulgarians, penetrating as far
1 CONT as Veliko Tarnovo and styling himself as king of Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen's father, attempting to bind the powerful but pagan Cumans tribe more
1 CONT closely to the dynasty, arranged for Stephen's marriage, as a youth (about
1 CONT 1255), to Elizabeth, the daughter of the Cuman chieftain (named Koteny or
1 CONT Kuthens). Though Elizabeth, in preparation for the marriage, had been baptized
1 CONT and remained a Christian, western Europe almost universally considered Stephen
1 CONT as a semi-pagan. This hostility was felt as Stephen declared himself that
1 CONT everyone was his enemy for his accession to the Hungarian throne.
1 CONT
1 CONT To secure foreign support, he formed a double matrimonial alliance with the
1 CONT Angevins, chief partisans of the pope. The first of these was the marriage in
1 CONT 1270 of his daughter Maria to Charles II of Naples (they became grandparents
1 CONT of Charles I of Hungary). The second alliance was the marriage of Stephen's
1 CONT infant son Ladislaus to Charles II's sister Elisabeth.
1 CONT
1 CONT Byzantine Emperor Andronicus II married Anna, another of Stephen's daughters.
1 CONT Serbian king Stefan Dragutin married Katerina, yet another of Stephan's
1 CONT daughters.
1 CONT
1 CONT Adversaries of Stephen, especially Ottokar II of Bohemia, believed that
1 CONT Stephen was too great a friend of the mighty Cumans (who could field 16,000
1 CONT men) to be a true Catholic. Ottakar endeavoured with the aid of the Hungarian
1 CONT malcontents to conquer the western provinces of Hungary but they were utterly
1 CONT routed by Stephen in 1271 near Mosony. Ottakar relinquished all his conquests
1 CONT the same year in the peace of Pressburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen died suddenly as he was raising an army to rescue his kidnapped infant
1 CONT son Ladislaus from his rebellious vassals.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT References
1 CONT This article incorporates text from the 1911 Encyclopædia Britannica, a
1 CONT publication in the public domain.
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT Bela IV King of Hungary
1 CONT 1270–1272 Succeeded by:
1 CONT Ladislaus IV
1 CONT In 1062, as crown prince, Stephen compelled his father, whom he had assisted
1 CONT in the Bohemian war, to surrended 29 counties to him, virtually dividing
1 CONT Hungary into two kingdoms. In 1268 he invaded Bulgaria and assumed the title
1 CONT of King of Bulgaria. On his accession to the throne of Hungary, he met almost
1 CONT universal hostility because of his alleged pagan leanings, due largely to the
1 CONT influence of his Cunan wife Elizabeth, to whom his father had married for
1 CONT political reasons. The malcontents invaded western Hungary but were routed.
1 CONT In 1062, as crown prince, Stephen compelled his father, whom he had assisted
1 CONT in the Bohemian war, to surrended 29 counties to him, virtually dividing
1 CONT Hungary into two kingdoms. In 1268 he invaded Bulgaria and assumed the title
1 CONT of King of Bulgaria. On his accession to the throne of Hungary, he met almost
1 CONT universal hostility because of his alleged pagan leanings, due largely to the
1 CONT influence of his Cunan wife Elizabeth, to whom his father had married for
1 CONT political reasons. The malcontents invaded western Hungary but were routed.
1 CONT In 1062, as crown prince, Stephen compelled his father, whom he had assisted
1 CONT in the Bohemian war, to surrended 29 counties to him, virtually dividing
1 CONT Hungary into two kingdoms. In 1268 he invaded Bulgaria and assumed the title
1 CONT of King of Bulgaria. On his accession to the throne of Hungary, he met almost
1 CONT universal hostility because of his alleged pagan leanings, due largely to the
1 CONT influence of his Cunan wife Elizabeth, to whom his father had married for
1 CONT political reasons. The malcontents invaded western Hungary but were routed.
1 CONT In 1062, as crown prince, Stephen compelled his father, whom he had assisted
1 CONT in the Bohemian war, to surrended 29 counties to him, virtually dividing
1 CONT Hungary into two kingdoms. In 1268 he invaded Bulgaria and assumed the title
1 CONT of King of Bulgaria. On his accession to the throne of Hungary, he met almost
1 CONT universal hostility because of his alleged pagan leanings, due largely to the
1 CONT influence of his Cunan wife Elizabeth, to whom his father had married for
1 CONT political reasons. The malcontents invaded western Hungary but were routed.
1 CONT In the second year following his birth, on 11 April 1241, the Mongolian troops
1 CONT defeated his father's army in the Battle of Mohi. After the disastrous battle,
1 CONT the royal family had to escape to Trau, a well-fortified city in Dalmatia.
1 CONT They could only return to Hungary after the unexpected withdrawal of the
1 CONT Mongol forces from Europe..
1 CONT In 1246 Stephen was crowned as junior King and his father entrusted him with
1 CONT the government of Croatia, Slavonia and Dalmatia, but the three provinces were
1 CONT de facto governed by the Ban Stephen Gut-Keled. Stephen's father, attempting
1 CONT to bind the powerful but pagan Cuman tribes more closely to the dynasty,
1 CONT arranged for Stephen's marriage, as a youth (about 1253), to Elizabeth, the
1 CONT daughter of a Cuman chieftain Köten. In 1257, Stephen demanded his father to
1 CONT divide the kingdom between themselves and recruited an army against the senior
1 CONT king. Finally, in 1258, King Béla IV was obliged to cede him the government of
1 CONT Transylvania. Stephen took part in his father's military campaign against the
1 CONT Styrians, who had rebelled against the rule of the King of Hungary, in 1258.
1 CONT After the successful campaign, King Béla IV appointed him to Duke of Styria.
1 CONT His government, however, was unpopular among his new subjects, who rebelled
1 CONT against him with the support of King Otakar II of Bohemia. Stephen and his
1 CONT father started an attack against Otakar II's lands, but their troops were
1 CONT defeated on 12 July 1260 in the Battle of Kroissenbrunn. Following the battle,
1 CONT the two Kings of Hungary ceded the Duchy of Styria to the King of Bohemia in
1 CONT the Peace of Pozsony (Slovak: Bratislava). Shortly after the peace, Stephen
1 CONT took over again the government of Transylvania. In 1261, Stephen and his
1 CONT father made a joint military campaign against Bulgaria, but their relationship
1 CONT became more and more tense, because the senior king had been favouring his
1 CONT younger son, Duke Béla of Slavonia and his daughter, Anna, the mother-in-law
1 CONT of the King of Bohemia.
1 CONT Finally, with the mediation of Archbishops Fülöp of Esztergom and Smaragd of
1 CONT Kalocsa, Stephen and his father signed an agreement in the summer of 1262 in
1 CONT Pozsony. Based on their agreement, Stephen took over the government of the
1 CONT parts of the kingdom East of the Danube. However, the two kings'
1 CONT reconciliation was only temporary, because their partisans were continuously
1 CONT inciteting them against each other. In 1264, Stephen seized his mother's and
1 CONT sister's estates in his domains, but his father sent troops against him.
1 CONT Stephen's wife and son was captured by his father's partisans, and he had to
1 CONT retreat to the castle of Feketehalom. However, he managed to repeal the siege
1 CONT and to commence a counter-attack.
1 CONT In March 1265, he gained a strategic victory over his father's army in the
1 CONT Battle of Isaszeg. After his victory, he concluded a peace with King Béla IV.
1 CONT Based on the provisions of the peace, he received back the government of the
1 CONT Eastern parts of the kingdom. On 23 March 1266, father and son confirmed the
1 CONT peace in the Convent of the Blessed Virgin on the Nyulak szigete ('Rabbits'
1 CONT Island'). Shortly afterwards, Stephen V lead his army to Bulgaria and forced
1 CONT Despot Jakov Svetoslav of Vidin to accept his overlordship. In 1267, the
1 CONT "prelates and nobles" of the Kingdom of Hungary held a joint assembly in
1 CONT Esztergom, and their decisions were confirmed by both Stephen and his father.
1 CONT To secure foreign support, he formed a double matrimonial alliance with the
1 CONT Angevins, chief partisans of the pope. The first of these was the marriage, in
1 CONT 1270, of his daughter Maria to the future King Charles II of Naples[1] The
1 CONT second alliance was the marriage of Stephen's infant son, Ladislaus to Charles
1 CONT II's sister Elisabeth. After his father's death (3 May 1270), Stephen
1 CONT inherited the whole Kingdom of Hungary, although the deceased senior king had
1 CONT entrusted his daughter, Anna and his followers to King Otakar II of Bohemia in
1 CONT his last will, and they had escaped to Prague before Stephen arrived to
1 CONT Esztergom.
1 CONT Before his (second) coronation, Stephen granted the County of Esztergom to the
1 CONT Archbishop. In August 1270, Stephen had a meeting with his brother-in-law,
1 CONT Prince Boleslaw V of Poland in Kraków where they concluded an alliance against
1 CONT the King of Bohemia. Stephen also had a meeting with King Otakar II on 16
1 CONT October on an island of the Danube near to Pozsony where they concluded a
1 CONT truce for two years. However, following smaller skirmishes on the border, the
1 CONT war broke out soon and the King of Bohemia lead his armies against Hungary.
1 CONT Stephen was defeated in two smaller battles, but finally he defeted a few
1 CONT important castels. In the subsequent peace the King of Bohemia handed back the
1 CONT fortresses occupied during its campaign, while Stephen renounced its claim for
1 CONT the Hungarian royal treasury that his sister, Anna had brought to Prague after
1 CONT their father's death.
1 CONT In the summer of 1272, Stephen left for Dalmatia, where he wanted to meet King
1 CONT Charles I of Sicily, when he was informed that Joachim Gut-Keled kidnapped his
1 CONT infant son, Ladislaus. Stephen was planning to raise an army to rescue his
1 CONT infant son, when he died suddenly.
1 CONT [Read about the Arpad Dynasty in
1 CONT Hungary](http://www.britannica.com/eb/article?idxref=411161)
