0 @N00599@ NOTE geni:about_me *<https://historytheinterestingbits.com/2017/01/15/the-
1 CONT unfortunate-wives-of-philip-ii-of-france/?fbclid=IwAR048J_P7VzlEyqz1krt-
1 CONT JjdzA0eJDBVP44IFsnPjpiqczAM66EPpdHymls>
1 CONT
1 CONT PHILIP II OF FRANCE
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_II_of_France>
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippe_Auguste>
1 CONT
1 CONT And in French: <http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippe_II_de_France>
1 CONT
1 CONT <https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filips_II_van_Frankrijk> (in Dutch)
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste) (21 August 1165 – 14 July 1223)
1 CONT was the King of France from 1180 until his death. A member of the House of
1 CONT Capet, Philip Augustus was born at Gonesse in the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis
1 CONT VII and his third wife, Adela of Champagne. He was originally nicknamed
1 CONT Dieudonné — the God-given — as he was the first son of Louis VII late in his
1 CONT father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals at the Battle of
1 CONT Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government, bringing financial stability
1 CONT to the country and thus making possible a sharp increase in prosperity. His
1 CONT reign was popular with ordinary people because he checked the power of the
1 CONT nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle class.
1 CONT
1 CONT In declining health, Louis VII had him crowned and anointed at Rheims by the
1 CONT Archbishop William Whitehands on 1 November 1179. He was married on 28 April
1 CONT 1180 to Isabelle of Hainaut, who brought the County of Artois as her dowry.
1 CONT His father died on 18 September.
1 CONT
1 CONT While the royal demesne had increased under Philip I and Louis VI, under Louis
1 CONT VII it had diminished slightly. In April 1182, Philip expelled all Jews from
1 CONT the demesne and confiscated their goods.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip's eldest son, Louis, was born on 5 September 1187 and inherited Artois
1 CONT in 1190, when Isabelle, his mother, died.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1181, Philip began a war with the Count of Flanders, Philip of Alsace.
1 CONT Philip managed to counter the ambitions of the count by breaking his alliances
1 CONT with Henry I, Duke of Brabant, and Philip of Heinsberg, Archbishop of Cologne.
1 CONT In July 1185, the Treaty of Boves confirmed to the king the possession of the
1 CONT Vermandois, Artois, and Amiénois.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1184, Stephen I of Sancerre and his Brabançon mercenaries ravaged the
1 CONT Orléanais. Philip defeated him with the aid of the Confrères de la Paix.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip also began to war with the Henry II of England, who was also Count of
1 CONT Anjou and Duke of Aquitaine in France. Two years of combat (1186–1188)
1 CONT followed, but the situation remained unchanged. Philip initially allied with
1 CONT Henry's young sons, Richard and John, who were in rebellion against their
1 CONT father. However, news of the fall of Jerusalem to Saladin, followed quickly by
1 CONT the death of Henry, diverted attention from the Franco-English war.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was close friends with all of Henry's sons and he used them to foment
1 CONT rebellion against their father, but turned against both Richard and John after
1 CONT their respective accessions to the throne. With Henry the Young King and
1 CONT Geoffrey of Brittany he maintained friendship until their deaths. Indeed, at
1 CONT the funeral of Geoffrey, he was so overcome with grief that he had to be
1 CONT forcibly restrained from casting himself into the grave.
1 CONT
1 CONT In May 1200, Philip signed the Treaty of Le Goulet with Richard's successor
1 CONT John. The treaty was meant to bring peace to Normandy by settling the issue of
1 CONT the boundaries of the duchy and the terms of John's vassalage for it and
1 CONT Anjou, Maine, and Touraine. John agreed to heavy terms, but Philip in turn
1 CONT recognised John as king, formally abandoning Arthur I of Brittany, whom he had
1 CONT thitherto supported, and recognised John's suzerainty over the Duchy of
1 CONT Brittany. To seal the treaty, a marriage between Blanche of Castile, John's
1 CONT niece, and Louis the Lion, Philip's son, was contracted.
1 CONT
1 CONT This did not stop the war, however. In 1202, disaffected barons petitioned the
1 CONT French king to summon John to answer their charges and, when the English king
1 CONT refused, Philip dispossessed him of his French lands. Within two years, most
1 CONT of Normandy and the Angevin lands, including much of Aquitaine, had been
1 CONT conquered. The war, called the "War of Bouvines," continued for the next
1 CONT decade until Philip won a decisive victory at Bouvines (1214) over a coalition
1 CONT of forces that included the Emperor Otto IV and Ferdinand, Count of Flanders.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip went on the Third Crusade with Richard I of England (1189–99) and the
1 CONT Holy Roman Emperor, Frederick I Barbarossa (1189–1192). His army left Vézelay
1 CONT on July 1, 1190. At first the French and English crusaders traveled together,
1 CONT but the armies split at Lyons, as King Richard I decided to go by sea, and
1 CONT Philip took the overland route through the Alps to Genoa. The French and
1 CONT English armies were reunited in Messina, where they wintered together. On
1 CONT March 30, 1191 the French set sail for the Holy Land, where they launched
1 CONT several assaults on Acre before King Richard I arrived. By the time Acre
1 CONT surrendered on July 12, Philip was severely ill with dysentery and had little
1 CONT more interest in further crusading. He decided to return to France, a decision
1 CONT that displeased King Richard I, who said, "It is a shame and a disgrace on my
1 CONT lord if he goes away without having finished the business that brought him
1 CONT hither. But still, if he finds himself in bad health, or is afraid lest he
1 CONT should die here, his will be done." So on July 31, 1191 the French army of
1 CONT 10,000 men (along with 5,000 silver marks to pay the soldiers) remained in
1 CONT Outremer under the command of Hugh III, duke of Burgundy. Philip and his
1 CONT cousin Peter of Courtenay, count of Nevers, made their way to Genoa and from
1 CONT there returned to France. This decision to return was also fuelled by the
1 CONT realization that with Richard campaigning in the Holy Land, English
1 CONT possessions in northern France (Normandy) would be open for attack. After
1 CONT Richard's delayed return home after the Third Crusade, war between England and
1 CONT France would ensue over possession of English-controlled territories in
1 CONT modern-day France.
1 CONT
1 CONT After Isabelle's early death in childbirth, in 1190, Philip decided to marry
1 CONT again. On August 15, 1193 he married Ingeborg (1175–1236), daughter of King
1 CONT Valdemar I of Denmark (1157–82). She was renamed Isambour, and Stephan of
1 CONT Dornik described her as "very kind, young of age but old of wisdom." For some
1 CONT unknown reason, Philip was repelled by her, and he refused to allow her to be
1 CONT crowned Queen. Ingeborg protested at this treatment; his response was to
1 CONT confine her to a convent. He then asked Pope Celestine III for an annulment on
1 CONT the grounds of non-consummation. Philip had not reckoned with Ingeborg,
1 CONT however; she insisted that the marriage had been consummated, and that she was
1 CONT his wife and the rightful Queen of France. The Franco-Danish churchman William
1 CONT of Paris intervened on the side of Ingeborg, drawing up a genealogy of the
1 CONT Danish kings to disprove the alleged impediment of consanguinity.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime Philip had sought a new bride. Initially agreement had been
1 CONT reached for him to marry Marguerite, daughter of William I, Count of Geneva,
1 CONT but the young bride's journey to Paris was interrupted by Thomas I of Savoy,
1 CONT who kidnapped Philip's intended new queen and married her instead, claiming
1 CONT that Philip was already bound in marriage Philip finally achieved a third
1 CONT marriage, on May 7, 1196, to Agnes of Merania from Dalmatia (c. 1180 – July
1 CONT 29, 1201). Their children were:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   1. Marie (1198 – October 15, 1224)
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   2. Philippe Hurepel (1200–1234), Count of Clermont and eventually, by marriage, Count of Boulogne
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   3. Pope Innocent III (1198–1216) declared Philip #Augustus's marriage to Agnes of Merania null and void, as he was still married to Ingeborg. He ordered the King to part from Agnès; when he did not, the Pope placed France under an interdict in 11
1 CONC 99. This continued until September 7, 1200. Due to pressure from the Pope and from Ingeborg's brother, King Valdemar II of Denmark (1202–41), Philip finally took Ingeborg back as his Queen in 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT Understandably, he turned a deaf ear when the Pope asked him to do something
1 CONT about the heretics in the Languedoc. When Innocent III called for a crusade
1 CONT against the Albigensians or Cathars, in 1208, Philip did nothing to support
1 CONT it, but neither did he hinder it. The war against the Cathars [in which more
1 CONT than a million people were killed] did not end until 1244, when finally their
1 CONT last strongholds were captured. The fruits of it, namely the submission of the
1 CONT south of France to the crown, were to be reaped by Philip's son, Louis VIII,
1 CONT and grandson, Louis IX.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus would play a significant role in one of the greatest
1 CONT centuries of innovation in construction and in education. With Paris as his
1 CONT capital, he had the main thoroughfares paved, built a central market, Les
1 CONT Halles, continued the construction begun in 1163 of the Gothic Notre-Dame de
1 CONT Paris Cathedral, constructed the Louvre as a fortress and gave a charter to
1 CONT the University of Paris in 1200. Under his guidance, Paris became the first
1 CONT city of teachers the medieval world had known. In 1224, the French poet Henry
1 CONT d'Andeli wrote of the great wine tasting competition that Philip II Augustus
1 CONT commissioned The Battle of the Wines.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus died July 14, 1223 at Mantes and was interred in Saint
1 CONT Denis Basilica. Philip's son by Isabelle de Hainaut, Louis VIII, was his
1 CONT successor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip is a character in James Goldman's historical play The Lion in Winter.
1 CONT The play maintains the historical theory that he and Richard the Lionhearted
1 CONT had previously had a homosexual relationship In the 1968 film of The Lion in
1 CONT Winter, which downplayed the homosexual aspect present in the stage play,
1 CONT Philip was played by Timothy Dalton. Jonathan Rhys Meyers played Philip in a
1 CONT 2003 television version which somewhat resurrected the matter.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT King Philippe II AUGUSTE de France was born on AUG 21 1165 in Gonesse, Kingdom
1 CONT of France. He was a King of France from SEP 18 1180 to JUL 14 1223. From
1 CONT father King Louis VII's death. His reign was characterized by a gigantic
1 CONT advance of the French monarchy. Before his time the King of France reigned
1 CONT only over the Ile de France and Berri, and had no communication with the sea.
1 CONT To this patrimony Philip II added Artois, Amienois, Valois, Vernandois, a
1 CONT large portion of Beauvaisis, Normandy, Maine, Anjou, Touraine, and a part of
1 CONT Poitou and Saintonge. His bailiffs and seneschals established the royal power
1 CONT firmly in those countries. Paris became a fortified city and attracted to its
1 CONT university students from different countries. Thanks to the possession of
1 CONT Dieppe, Rouen, and certain parts of Saintonge, the French monarchy became a
1 CONT maritime and commercial power, and Philip invited foreign merchants to France.
1 CONT Flanders, Ponthieu, and Auvergne became subject fiefs, supervised by agents of
1 CONT the king. He exercised a sort of protectorate over Champagne and Burgundy.
1 CONT Brittany was in the hands of Pierre de Dreux, a Capetian of the younger
1 CONT branch. "History", writes M. Luchaire, "does not present so many, such rapid,
1 CONT and such complete changes in the fortune of a State". Philip Augustus did not
1 CONT interfere in episcopal elections. In Normandy, where the Plantagenets had
1 CONT assumed the custom of directly nominating the bishops, he did not follow their
1 CONT example. Guillaume Le Breton, in his poem the "Philippide", makes him say: "I
1 CONT leave to the men of God the things that pertain to the service of God." He
1 CONT favoured the emancipation of communes, desiring to be liked by the middle
1 CONT classes of the districts he annexed. He often exacted a tax in exchange for
1 CONT the communal charter. But he did not allow the communes to infringe on the
1 CONT property of clerics or the episcopal right of jurisdiction. At Noyen he
1 CONT intervened formally in behalf of the bishop, who was threatened by the
1 CONT commune. He undertook a campaign in defence of the bishops and abbots against
1 CONT certain feudal lords whom he himself desired to humiliate or weaken. In 1180,
1 CONT before he was king, he undertook an expedition into Berri to punish the Lord
1 CONT of Charenton, the enemy of the monks, and into Burgundy where the Count of
1 CONT Chalon and the Lord of Beaujeu were persecuting the Church. In 1186, on the
1 CONT complaint of the monks, he took possession of Chatillon-sur-Seine, in the
1 CONT Duchy of Burgundy, and forced the duke to repair the wrongs he had committed
1 CONT against the Church. In 1210 he sent troops to protect the Bishop of Clermont,
1 CONT who was threatened by the Count of Auvergne. But on the other hand, in virtue
1 CONT of the preponderance which he wished royalty to have over feudalism, he
1 CONT exacted of the bishops and abbots the performance of all their feudal duties,
1 CONT including military service; although for certain territories he was the vassal
1 CONT of the bishops of Picardy, he refused to pay them homage. Moreover, he
1 CONT declared with regard to Manasses, bishop of Orléans, that the royal court was
1 CONT entitled to judge at the trials of bishops, and he made common cause with lay
1 CONT feudalism in the endless discussions regarding the province of ecclesiastical
1 CONT tribunals, which at the beginning of the thirteenth century were disposed to
1 CONT extend their jurisdiction. An ordinance issued about 1205 at the instance of
1 CONT the king, executed in Normandy and perhaps elsewhere, stipulated that in
1 CONT certain cases lay judges might arrest and try guilty clerics, that the right
1 CONT of asylum of religious buildings should be limited, that the Church might not
1 CONT excommunicate those who did business on Sunday or held intercourse with Jews,
1 CONT and that a citizen having several children should not give more than half of
1 CONT his estate to that one of his sons who was a cleric. Finally he imposed on the
1 CONT clergy heavy financial exactions. He was the first king who endeavoured to
1 CONT compel clerics to pay the king a tenth of their income. In 1188 the archdeacon
1 CONT Peter of Blois defeated this claim, but in 1215 and 1218 Philip renewed it,
1 CONT and by degrees the resistance of the clergy gave way. Philip, however, was
1 CONT pious in his own way, and in the advice which St. Louis gave to his son he
1 CONT said that Philip, because of "God's goodness and mercy would rather lose his
1 CONT throne than dispute with the servants of Holy Church". Thus the reputation
1 CONT left by Philip II was quite different from that of Philip IV, or Frederick II
1 CONT of Germany. He never carried out towards the Church a policy of trickery or
1 CONT petty vexations, on the contrary he regarded it as his collaborator in the
1 CONT foundation of French unity. He died on JUL 14 1223 in Mantes, Kingdom of
1 CONT France. (643) He has Ancestral File number 94480798. Was saved from a serious
1 CONT illness after a pilgrimage made by his father to the tomb of Thomas à Becket.
1 CONT His strife with Henry II of England in concert with the sons of that monarch,
1 CONT Henry, Richard, and John, resulted in 1189 in the Treaty of Azay-sur-Cher,
1 CONT which enhanced the royal power in the centre of France. The struggle with the
1 CONT Plantagenets was the ruling idea of Philip II's whole policy. Richard Coeur de
1 CONT Lion having become King of England, 6 July 1189, was at first on amicable
1 CONT terms with Philip. Together they undertook the Third Crusade, but quarreled in
1 CONT Palestine, and on his return Philip II accused Richard of having attempted to
1 CONT poison him. As Richard had supported in Sicily the claims of Tancred of Lecce
1 CONT against those of the Emperor Henry VI, the latter resolved to be avenged.
1 CONT Richard, having been taken captive on his return from the Crusade by the Duke
1 CONT of Austria, was delivered to Henry VI, who held him prisoner. Philip II sent
1 CONT William, Archbishop of Reims, to Henry VI to request that Richard should
1 CONT remain the captive of Germany or that he should be delivered to Philip as his
1 CONT prisoner. Without loss of time Philip reached an agreement with John Lackland,
1 CONT Richard's brother. Normandy was delivered up by a secret treaty and John
1 CONT acknowledged himself Philip's vassal. But, when in February 1194, Richard was
1 CONT set free by Henry VI, John Lackland became reconciled with him and endless
1 CONT conflict followed between Richard and Philip. On 13 January 1199, Pope
1 CONT Innocent III imposed on them a truce of five years. Shortly after this Richard
1 CONT died. Subsequently Philip defended against John, Richard's successor, the
1 CONT claims of the young Arthur of Brittany, and then those of Hugh de Lusignan,
1 CONT Count of La Marche, whose betrothed had been abducted by John. The war between
1 CONT Philip and John, interrupted by the truces imposed by the papal legates,
1 CONT became a national war; and in 1206 John lost his possessions in central
1 CONT France. Philip was sometimes displeased with the pontifical intervention
1 CONT between France and the Plantagenets, but the prestige of Innocent III forced
1 CONT him to accept it. Protracted difficulties took place between him and the pope
1 CONT owing to the tenacity with which Innocent III compelled respect for the
1 CONT indissolubility of even royal marriages. Another question which at first
1 CONT caused discord between Philip II and Innocent III, and regarding which they
1 CONT had later a common policy, was the question of Germany. Otto of Brunswick, who
1 CONT was Innocent III's candidate for the dignity of emperor, was the nephew of
1 CONT Richard and John Lackland. This was sufficient to cause Philip to interfere in
1 CONT favour of Philip of Suabia. They formed an alliance in June, 1198, and when
1 CONT Philip of Suabia was assassinated in 1208 Philip put forward the candidacy of
1 CONT Henry of Brabant. However, the whole of Germany rallied to Otto of Brunswick,
1 CONT who became emperor as Otto IV, and in 1209 Philip feared that the new emperor
1 CONT would invade France. But Otto IV quarrelled with Innocent III and was
1 CONT excommunicated and the pope by an unexpected move called upon Philip for
1 CONT subsidies and troops to aid him against Otto. They agreed to proclaim as
1 CONT emperor Frederick of Hohenstaufen, the future Frederick II, Philip giving
1 CONT Frederick 20,000 "marcs" to defray the cost of his election (November 1212).
1 CONT Thus was inaugurated the policy by which France meddled in the affairs of
1 CONT Germany and for the first time the French king claimed, like the pope, to have
1 CONT a voice in the imperial election. The accord established between Innocent and
1 CONT Philip with regard to the affairs of Germany subsequently extended to those of
1 CONT England. Throughout his reign Philip dreamed of a landing in England. As early
1 CONT as 1209 he had negotiated with the English barons who were hostile to John
1 CONT Lackland, and in 1212 with the Irish and the Welsh. When John lackland
1 CONT subjected to cruel persecution the English bishops who, in spite of him,
1 CONT recognized Stephen Langton as Archbishop of Canterbury. Innocent III in 1212
1 CONT placed England under interdict, and the legate, Pandulphus, declared that John
1 CONT Lackland had forfeited his throne. Then Philip, who received at his court all
1 CONT the exiles from England, consented to go to England in the name of Innocent
1 CONT III to take away the crown from John Lackland. It was to be given to his son,
1 CONT the future Louis VIII. On 22 May, 1213, the French expedition was to embark at
1 CONT Gravelines, when it was learned that John Lackland had become reconciled with
1 CONT Rome, and some months later he became a vassal of the pope. Thus failed, on
1 CONT the eve of its realization, the project of the French invasion of England. But
1 CONT the legate of Innocent III induced Philip to punish Ferrand, Count of
1 CONT Flanders, who was the ally of all the enemies of the king. At the battle of
1 CONT Bouvines (27 July 1214) Ferrand, who supported Otto IV, was taken prisoner.
1 CONT This battle is regarded as the first French national victory. Philip II,
1 CONT asserting that he had on both sides two great and terrible lions, Otto and
1 CONT John, excused himself from taking part in the Crusade against the Albigenses.
1 CONT He permitted his son Louis to make two expeditions into Languedoc to support
1 CONT Simon de Montfort in 1215, and Amaury de Montfort in 1219, and again in 1222
1 CONT he sent Amaury de Montfort two hundred knights and ten thousand foot soldiers
1 CONT under the Archbishop of Bourges and the Count of La Marche. He foresaw that
1 CONT the French monarchy would profit by the defeat of the Albigenses. Parents:
1 CONT King Louis VII CAPET de France, the Young and Adèle DE BLOIS de Champagne.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was married to Queen Isabelle de Hainaut in 1180 in The Kingdom of France.
1 CONT (64) His marriage with her, the niece of the Count of Flanders, the conflicts
1 CONT which he afterwards sustained against the latter, and the deaths of the
1 CONT Countess (1182) and Count of Flanders (1185), increased the royal power in the
1 CONT north of France. He married her in order to inherit Artois. Children were:
1 CONT King Louis CAPET VIII le Lion.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was married to Queen Ingeburga in 1193. (248) She was the sister of Canute
1 CONT VI, King of Denmark. As he immediately desired to repudiate her, an assembly
1 CONT of complaisant barons and bishops pronounced the divorce, but Ingeburga
1 CONT appealed to Rome. Even after the death of his wife Agnes, Philip persisted
1 CONT that Rome should pronounce his divorce from Ingeburga, whom he held prisoner
1 CONT at Etampes. Rome refused and Philip dismissed the papal legate (1209). In 1210
1 CONT he thought of marrying a princess of Thuringia, and in 1212 renewed his
1 CONT importunities for the divorce with the legate, Robert de Courçon. Then, in
1 CONT 1213, having need of the aid of the pope and the King of Denmark, he suddenly
1 CONT restored Ingeburga to her station as queen.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was married to Queen Agnès D'ANDECHS de Méranie in JUN 1196 in The Kingdom
1 CONT of France.(243) He married her despite the remonstrances of Pope Celestine
1 CONT III, and having imprisoned Ingeburga. She was the daughter of a Bavarian
1 CONT nobleman. Pope Innocent III, recently elected, called upon him to repudiate
1 CONT Agnes and take back Ingeburga, and on the king's refusal the legate, Peter of
1 CONT Capua, placed the kingdom under an interdict (1198). Most of the bishops
1 CONT refused to publish the sentence. The Bishops of Paris and Senlis, who
1 CONT published it, were punished by having their goods confiscated. At the end of
1 CONT nine months Philip appeared to yield; he feigned reconciliation with
1 CONT Ingeburga, first before the legate, Octavian, and then before the Council of
1 CONT Soissons (May 1201), but he did not dismiss Agnes de Méran. She died in August
1 CONT 1201, and Innocent III consented to legitimize the two children she had borne
1 CONT the king. Children were: Marie DE FRANCE , Count Philip AUGUSTE of Boulogne.
1 CONT
1 CONT info taken from:
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~chatweb/d38.htm#P16096>
1 CONT
