1 CONT Philip II (Augustus)
1 CONT
1 CONT King of France, born 22 or 25 August, 1165; died at Mantes, 14 July, 1223, son
1 CONT of Louis VII and Alix de Champagne.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was saved from a serious illness after a pilgrimage made by his father to
1 CONT the tomb of Thomas à Becket; he succeeded to the throne 18 September, 1180.
1 CONT His marriage with Isabella of Hainault, niece of the Count of Flanders, the
1 CONT conflicts which he afterwards sustained against the latter, and the deaths of
1 CONT the Countess (1182) and Count of Flanders (1185), increased the royal power in
1 CONT the north of France. His strife with Henry II of England in concert with the
1 CONT sons of that monarch, Henry, Richard, and John, resulted in 1189 in the Treaty
1 CONT of Azay-sur-Cher, which enhanced the royal power in the centre of France. The
1 CONT struggle with the Plantagenets was the ruling idea of Philip II's whole
1 CONT policy. Richard Cæur de Lion having become King of England, 6 July, 1189, was
1 CONT at first on amicable terms with Philip. Together they undertook the Third
1 CONT Crusade, but quarreled in Palestine, and on his return Philip II accused
1 CONT Richard of having attempted to poison him. As Richard had supported in Sicily
1 CONT the claims of Tancred of Lecce against those of the Emperor Henry VI, the
1 CONT latter resolved to be avenged. Richard, having been taken captive on his
1 CONT return from the Crusade by the Duke of Austria, was delivered to Henry VI, who
1 CONT held him prisoner. Philip II sent William, Archbishop of Reims, to Henry VI to
1 CONT request that Richard should remain the captive of Germany or that he should be
1 CONT delivered to Philip as his prisoner. Without loss of time Philip reached an
1 CONT agreement with John Lackland, Richard's brother. Normandy was delivered up by
1 CONT a secret treaty and John acknowledged himself Philip's vassal. But, when in
1 CONT February, 1194, Richard was set free by Henry VI, John Lackland became
1 CONT reconciled with him and endless conflict followed between Richard and Philip.
1 CONT On 13 January, 1199, Innocent III imposed on them a truce of five years.
1 CONT Shortly after this Richard died. Subsequently Philip defended against John,
1 CONT Richard's successor, the claims of the young Arthur of Brittany, and then
1 CONT those of Hugh de Lusignan, Count of La Marche, whose betrothed had been
1 CONT abducted by John. The war between Philip and John, interrupted by the truces
1 CONT imposed by the papal legates, became a national war; and in 1206 John lost his
1 CONT possessions in central France. Philip was sometimes displeased with the
1 CONT pontifical intervention between France and the Plantagenets, but the prestige
1 CONT of Innocent III forced him to accept it. Protracted difficulties took place
1 CONT between him and the pope owing to the tenacity with which Innocent III
1 CONT compelled respect for the indissolubility of even royal marriages.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1190 Philip lost his wife, Isabella of Hainault, whom he had married in
1 CONT order to inherit Artois, and in 1193 he married Ingeburga, sister of Canute
1 CONT VI, King of Denmark. As he immediately desired to repudiate her, an assembly
1 CONT of complaisant barons and bishops pronounced the divorce, but Ingeburga
1 CONT appealed to Rome. Despite the remonstrances of Celestine III, Philip, having
1 CONT imprisoned Ingeburga, married Agnes de Méran, daughter of a Bavarian nobleman.
1 CONT Innocent III, recently elected, called upon him to repudiate Agnes and take
1 CONT back Ingeburga, and on the king's refusal the legate, Peter of Capua, placed
1 CONT the kingdom under an interdict (1198). Most of the bishops refused to publish
1 CONT the sentence. The Bishops of Paris and Senlis, who published it, were punished
1 CONT by having their goods confiscated. At the end of nine months Philip appeared
1 CONT to yield; he feigned reconciliation with Ingeburga, first before the legate,
1 CONT Octavian, and then before the Council of Soissons (May, 1201), but he did not
1 CONT dismiss Agnes de Méran. She died in August, 1201, and Innocent III consented
1 CONT to legitimize the two children she had borne the king, but Philip persisted
1 CONT that Rome should pronounce his divorce from Ingeburga, whom he held prisoner
1 CONT at Etampes. Rome refused and Philip dismissed the papal legate (1209). In 1210
1 CONT he thought of marrying a princess of Thuringia, and in 1212 renewed his
1 CONT importunities for the divorce with the legate, Robert de Courçon. Then, in
1 CONT 1213, having need of the aid of the pope and the King of Denmark, he suddenly
1 CONT restored Ingeburga to her station as queen.
1 CONT
1 CONT Another question which at first caused discord between Philip II and Innocent
1 CONT III, and regarding which they had later a common policy, was the question of
1 CONT Germany. Otto of Brunswick, who was Innocent III's candidate for the dignity
1 CONT of emperor, was the nephew of Richard and John Lackland. This was sufficient
1 CONT to cause Philip to interfere in favour of Philip of Suabia. They formed an
1 CONT alliance in June, 1198, and when Philip of Suabia was assassinated in 1208
1 CONT Philip put forward the candidacy of Henry of Brabant. However, the whole of
1 CONT Germany rallied to Otto of Brunswick, who became emperor as Otto IV, and in
1 CONT 1209 Philip feared that the new emperor would invade France. But Otto IV
1 CONT quarrelled with Innocent III and was excommunicated and the pope by an
1 CONT unexpected move called upon Philip for subsidies and troops to aid him against
1 CONT Otto. They agreed to proclaim as emperor Frederick of Hohenstaufen, the future
1 CONT Frederick II, Philip giving Frederick 20,000 "marcs" to defray the cost of his
1 CONT election (November, 1212). Thus was inaugurated the policy by which France
1 CONT meddled in the affairs of Germany and for the first time the French king
1 CONT claimed, like the pope, to have a voice in the imperial election.
1 CONT
