1 CONT
1 CONT This did not stop the war, however. In 1202, disaffected patrons petitioned
1 CONT the French king to summon John to answer their charges and, when the English
1 CONT king refused, Philip dispossessed him of his French lands. Within two years,
1 CONT most of Normandy and the Angevin lands, including much of Aquitaine, had been
1 CONT conquered. The war, called the "War of Bouvines," continued for the next
1 CONT decade until Philip won a decisive victory at Bouvines (1214) over a coalition
1 CONT of forces that included the Emperor Otto IV and Ferdinand, Count of Flanders.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip went on the Third Crusade (1189–1192) with Richard I of England
1 CONT (1189–99) and the Holy Roman Emperor, Frederick I Barbarossa (1155–90). His
1 CONT army left Vézelay on July 1, 1190. At first the French and English crusaders
1 CONT traveled together, but the armies split at Lyons, as Richard decided to go by
1 CONT sea, and Philip took the overland route through the Alps to Genoa. The French
1 CONT and English armies were reunited in Messina, where they wintered together. On
1 CONT March 30, 1191 the French set sail for the Holy Land and Philip arrived on May
1 CONT 20. He then marched up to Acre which was already besieged by a lesser
1 CONT contingent of crusaders and started to construct large siege equipments before
1 CONT Richard arrived in June 8 (see Siege of Acre). By the time Acre surrendered on
1 CONT July 12, Philip was severely ill with dysentery which reduced his crusading
1 CONT zeal. Ties with Richard were further strained after the latter acted in a
1 CONT haughty manner after Acre had fallen. More importantly, the siege resulted in
1 CONT the death of Philip of Alsace, who held the county of Vermandois proper; an
1 CONT event that threatened to derail the Treaty of Gisors which Philip had
1 CONT orchestrated to isolate the powerful Blois-Champagne faction. Philip decided
1 CONT to return to France to settle the issue of succession in Flanders, a decision
1 CONT that displeased Richard, who said, "It is a shame and a disgrace on my lord if
