1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste; 21 August 1165 – 14 July 1223)
1 CONT was the King of France from 1180 until his death. A member of the House of
1 CONT Capet, Philip Augustus was born at Gonesse in the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis
1 CONT VII and his third wife, Adela of Champagne. He was originally nicknamed
1 CONT Dieudonné—the God-given—as he was the first son of Louis VII late in his
1 CONT father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals (German, Flemish and
1 CONT English) at the Battle of Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government,
1 CONT bringing financial stability to the country and thus making possible a sharp
1 CONT increase in prosperity. His reign was popular with ordinary people because he
1 CONT checked the power of the nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle
1 CONT class.
1 CONT
