1 CONT [edit] Early years
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle, Philip's first wife.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip, born in Gonesse on August 21, 1165, was surnamed Augustus in honor of
1 CONT the month he was born.[1] As soon as he was able, Louis planned to associate
1 CONT Philip with him on the throne, but it was delayed when Philip, at the age of
1 CONT thirteen, was separated from his companions during a royal hunt and became
1 CONT lost in the Forest of Compiegne. He spent much of the following night
1 CONT attempting to find his way out, but to no avail. Exhausted by cold, hunger and
1 CONT fatigue, he was eventually discovered by a peasant carrying a charcoal burner,
1 CONT but his exposure to the elements meant he soon succumbed to a dangerously high
1 CONT fever.[2] His father went on pilgrimage to the Shrine of Thomas Becket to pray
1 CONT for Philip’s recovery, and was told that his son had indeed recovered.
1 CONT However, on his way back to Paris, he suffered a stroke.
1 CONT
1 CONT In declining health, Louis VII had him crowned and anointed at Rheims by the
1 CONT Archbishop William Whitehands on 1st of November in 1179. He was married on 28
1 CONT April 1180 to Isabelle of Hainaut, who brought the County of Artois as her
1 CONT dowry. From his inauguration, all real power was transferred to Philip, as his
1 CONT father slowly descended into senility.[2] The great nobles were discontented
1 CONT with Philip’s advantageous marriage, while his mother and four uncles, all of
1 CONT whom exercised enormous influence over Louis, were extremely unhappy with his
1 CONT association to the throne, causing a diminishment in their power.[3]
1 CONT Eventually, Louis died on 18 September 1180.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Consolidation of royal demesne
1 CONT
1 CONT While the royal demesne had increased under Philip I and Louis VI, under Louis
1 CONT VII it had diminished slightly. In April 1182, Philip expelled all Jews from
1 CONT the demesne and confiscated their goods.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip's eldest son, Louis, was born on the 5th of September in 1187 and
1 CONT inherited Artois in 1190, when Isabelle, his mother, died.
1 CONT
1 CONT Remains of the wall of Philippe Auguste built around Paris before going to the
1 CONT Crusades. Today in rue des Jardins-Saint-Paul, Paris
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Wars with his vassals
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1181, Philip began a war with Philip of Alsace, Count of Flanders over the
1 CONT Vermandois, which King Philip claimed as his Queen’s dowry, which the Count
1 CONT was unwilling to give up. Finally the Count of Flanders invaded France,
1 CONT ravaging the whole district between the Somme and the Oise, before penetrating
1 CONT as far as Dammartin.[4] Notified of Philip’s impending approach, he turned
1 CONT around and headed back to Flanders. Philip chased him, and the two armies
1 CONT confronted each other near Amiens. By this stage, Philip had managed to
1 CONT counter the ambitions of the count by breaking his alliances with Henry I,
1 CONT Duke of Brabant, and Philip of Heinsberg, Archbishop of Cologne. This together
1 CONT with an uncertain outcome were he to engage the French in battle forced the
1 CONT Count to conclude a peace.[4] In July 1185, the Treaty of Boves left the
1 CONT disputed territory partitioned, with Amiénois, Artois and numerous other
1 CONT places passing to the King and the remainder, with the county of Vermandois
1 CONT proper, being left provisionally to Philip of Alsace.[5]
1 CONT
1 CONT Meanwhile in 1184, Stephen I of Sancerre and his Brabançon mercenaries ravaged
1 CONT the Orléanais. Philip defeated him with the aid of the Confrères de la Paix.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] War with Henry II
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip also began to wage war with Henry II of England, who was also Count of
1 CONT Anjou and Duke of Normandy and Aquitaine in France. The death of Henry’s
1 CONT eldest son, Henry the Young King in June of 1183 began a dispute over the
1 CONT dower of the widowed Margaret, who was Philip’s sister, who insisted that it
1 CONT should be returned to France as the marriage did not produce any children, as
1 CONT per the betrothal agreement.[6] The two kings would hold conferences at the
1 CONT foot of an elm tree near Gisors, which was so positioned that it would
1 CONT overshadow each monarch’s territory, but to no avail. Philip pushed the case
1 CONT further when King Béla III of Hungary asked for the widow’s hand in marriage,
1 CONT and thus her dowry had to be returned, to which Henry finally agreed.
1 CONT
1 CONT The death of Henry’s fourth son, Geoffrey II, Duke of Brittany in 1186 the
1 CONT began a new round of disputes, as Henry insisted that he retain the
1 CONT guardianship of the duchy for his unborn grandson Arthur I, Duke of
1 CONT Brittany.[6] Philip, as Henry’s liege lord, objected, stating that he should
1 CONT be the rightful guardian until the birth of the child. Philip then raised the
1 CONT issue of his other sister, Alys, Countess of the Vexin, and her delayed
1 CONT betrothal to Richard the Lionheart.
1 CONT
1 CONT With these grievances, two years of combat (1186–1188) followed, but the
1 CONT situation remained unchanged. Philip initially allied with Henry's young sons,
1 CONT Richard the Lionheart and John Lackland, who were in rebellion against their
1 CONT father. Philip II launched an attack on Berry in the summer of 1187 but then
1 CONT in June made a truce with Henry, which left Issoudun in his hands and also
1 CONT granted him Fréteval, in Vendômois.[5] Though the truce was for two years,
1 CONT Philip found grounds for resuming hostilities in the summer of 1188. He
1 CONT skillfully exploited the estrangement between Henry and Richard, and Richard
1 CONT did homage to him voluntarily at Bonmoulins in November 1188.[5]
1 CONT
1 CONT Then in 1189 Richard openly joined forces with Philip to drive Henry into
1 CONT abject submission. They chased him from Le Mans to Saumur, losing Tours in the
1 CONT process,[6] before forcing him to acknowledge Richard as his heir. Finally, by
1 CONT the Treaty of Azay-le-Rideau (July 4, 1189), Henry was forced to renew his own
1 CONT homage, to confirm the cession of Issoudun, with Graçay also, to Philip, and
1 CONT to renounce his claim to suzerainty over Auvergne.[5] Henry died two days
1 CONT later. His death, and the news of the of the fall of Jerusalem to Saladin,
1 CONT diverted attention from the Franco-English war.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was close friends with all of Henry's sons and he used them to foment
1 CONT rebellion against their father, but turned against both Richard and John after
1 CONT their respective accessions to the throne. With Henry the Young King and
1 CONT Geoffrey of Brittany he maintained friendship until their deaths. Indeed, at
1 CONT the funeral of Geoffrey, he was so overcome with grief that he had to be
1 CONT forcibly restrained from casting himself into the grave.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip (right) and Richard accepting the keys to Acre; from the Grandes
1 CONT Chroniques de France.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Third Crusade
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip went on the Third Crusade (1189 – 1192) with Richard I of England and
1 CONT the Holy Roman Emperor, Frederick I Barbarossa. His army left Vézelay on 1
1 CONT July 1190. At first the French and English crusaders traveled together, but
1 CONT the armies split at Lyon, as Richard decided to go by sea, and Philip took the
1 CONT overland route through the Alps to Genoa. The French and English armies were
1 CONT reunited in Messina, where they wintered together. On 30 March 1191 the French
1 CONT set sail for the Holy Land and Philip arrived on 20 May. He then marched up to
1 CONT Acre which was already besieged by a lesser contingent of crusaders and
1 CONT started to construct large siege equipments before Richard arrived in 8 June
1 CONT (see Siege of Acre). By the time Acre surrendered on 12 July, Philip was
1 CONT severely ill with dysentery which reduced his crusading zeal. Ties with
1 CONT Richard were further strained after the latter acted in a haughty manner after
1 CONT Acre had fallen.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ptolemais (Acre) given to Philip Augustus 1191
1 CONT
1 CONT More importantly, the siege resulted in the death of Philip of Alsace, who
1 CONT held the county of Vermandois proper; an event that threatened to derail the
1 CONT Treaty of Gisors which Philip had orchestrated to isolate the powerful Blois-
1 CONT Champagne faction. Philip decided to return to France to settle the issue of
1 CONT succession in Flanders, a decision that displeased Richard, who said, "It is a
1 CONT shame and a disgrace on my lord if he goes away without having finished the
1 CONT business that brought him hither. But still, if he finds himself in bad
1 CONT health, or is afraid lest he should die here, his will be done." So on 31 July
1 CONT 1191 the French army of 10,000 men (along with 5,000 silver marks to pay the
1 CONT soldiers) remained in Outremer under the command of Hugh III, Duke of
1 CONT Burgundy. Philip and his cousin Peter of Courtenay, count of Nevers, made
1 CONT their way to Genoa and from there returned to France. This decision to return
1 CONT was also fuelled by the realization that with Richard campaigning in the Holy
1 CONT Land, English possessions in northern France (Normandy) would be open for
1 CONT attack. After Richard's delayed return home after the Third Crusade, war
1 CONT between England and France would ensue over possession of English-controlled
1 CONT territories in modern-day France.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Conflict with England, Flanders and the Holy Roman Empire
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Conflict with King Richard 1192-1199
1 CONT
1 CONT The immediate cause of the conflict with Richard stemmed from Richard’s
1 CONT decision to break his betrothal with Philip’s sister Alice at Messina in
1 CONT 1191.[7] Part of Alice’s dowry that had been given over to Richard during
1 CONT their engagement was the territory of the Vexin which included the strategic
1 CONT fortress of Gisors. This should have reverted to Philip upon the end of the
1 CONT betrothal, but Philip, to prevent the collapse of the Crusade, agreed that
1 CONT this territory was to remain in Richard’s hands, and would be inherited by his
1 CONT male descendents. Should Richard die without an heir, the territory would
1 CONT return to Philip, and if Philip died without an heir, those lands would be
1 CONT considered a part of Normandy.[7]
1 CONT
1 CONT Returning to France in late 1191, he began plotting to find a way to have
1 CONT those territories restored to him. He was in a difficult situation, as he had
1 CONT taken an oath to Richard not to attack his lands while he was away,[8] and as
1 CONT Richard was still on Crusade, his territory was under the protection of the
1 CONT Church in any event. He had unsuccessfully asked Pope Celestine III to release
1 CONT him from his oath,[9] and so Philip was forced to build a causus belli from
1 CONT scratch.
1 CONT
1 CONT On January 20, 1192, Philip met with William of FitzRalph, Richard’s seneschal
1 CONT of Normandy. Presenting some documents purporting to be from Richard, Philip
1 CONT claimed that Richard had agreed at Messina to hand back the disputed lands to
1 CONT Philip. Not having heard anything directly from their sovereign, FitzRalph and
1 CONT the Norman barons rejected Philip’s claim to the Vexin.[7] Philip at this time
1 CONT also began spreading rumors about Richard’s action in the east to discredit
1 CONT the English king in the eyes of his subjects. Among the stories Philip
1 CONT invented included Richard was involved in treacherous communication with
1 CONT Saladin, that he had conspired to cause the fall of Gaza, Jaffa and Ashkelon,
1 CONT and that he had participated in the murder of Conrad of Montferrat.[9]
1 CONT Finally, Philip made contact with Prince John, Richard’s brother, whom he
1 CONT convinced to join him and overthrow his brother.[9]
1 CONT
1 CONT At the start of 1193, John paid a visit to Philip in Paris where he paid
1 CONT homage for Richard’s French lands. When word reached Philip that Richard had
1 CONT finished crusading and had been captured on his way back from Holy Land, he
1 CONT promptly invaded the Vexin. His first target was the fortress of Gisors,
1 CONT commanded by Gilbert de Vascoeuil, which surrendered without putting up a
1 CONT struggle.[10] Philip then penetrated deep into Normandy, reaching as far as
1 CONT Dieppe. To keep the duplicitous John on side, Philip entrusted the defense of
1 CONT the town of Evreux over to him.[11] Meanwhile, Philip was joined by Count
1 CONT Baldwin of Flanders, and together they laid siege to the ducal capital of
1 CONT Normandy, Rouen. Here, Philip’s advance was halted by a defense led by Earl
1 CONT Robert of Leicester.[10] Unable to penetrate their defenses, Philip moved on.
1 CONT
1 CONT At Mantes on July 9, 1193, Philip came to terms with Richard’s ministers who
1 CONT agreed that Philip could keep his gains and would be given some extra
1 CONT territories if he ceased all further aggressive actions in Normandy, along
1 CONT with the condition that Philip would hand back the captured territory if
1 CONT Richard would pay homage to Philip.[10] To prevent Richard from spoiling their
1 CONT plans, Philip and John attempted to bribe the Holy Roman Emperor Henry VI to
1 CONT keep the English king captive for a little while longer. He refused, and
1 CONT Richard was released from captivity on February 4, 1194. By March 13, Richard
1 CONT had returned to England, and by May 12, he had set sail for Normandy with some
1 CONT 300 ships, eager to take the war to Philip.[10]
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip had spent this time consolidating his territorial gains, and by now was
1 CONT controlling much of Normandy east of the Seine, and remaining within striking
1 CONT distance of Rouen. His next objective was the castle of Verneuil,[12], which
1 CONT had withstood an earlier siege. Once Richard arrived had at Barfleur, he was
1 CONT soon marching towards Verneuil. As his forces neared the castle, Philip, who
1 CONT had been unable to break through, decided to strike camp. Leaving a large
1 CONT force behind to prosecute the siege, he moved off towards Evreux, which Prince
1 CONT John had handed over to his brother to prove his loyalty.[12] Philip retook
1 CONT the town and sacked it, but during this time, his forces besieging Verneuil
1 CONT abandoned the siege, and Richard entered the castle unopposed on May 30.
1 CONT Throughout June, while Philip’s campaign ground to a halt in the north,
1 CONT Richard was taking a number of important fortresses to the south. Philip,
1 CONT eager to relieve the pressure off his allies in the south, marched to confront
1 CONT Richard’s forces at Vendôme. Refusing to risk everything in a major battle,
1 CONT Philip retreated, only to have his rear guard caught at Fréteval on July 4,
1 CONT which turned into a general encounter during which Philip only managed to
1 CONT avoid capture, as his army was put to flight.[12] Fleeing back to Normandy,
1 CONT Philip revenged himself on the English by attacking the forces of Prince John
1 CONT and the Earl of Arundel, seizing their baggage train.[12] By now both sides
1 CONT were tiring, and they agreed to the temporary Truce of Tillières.
1 CONT
1 CONT War continued in 1195 with Philip once again besieging Verneuil. Richard
1 CONT arrived to discuss the situation face to face. During negotiations, Philip
1 CONT secretly continued his operations against Verneuil, and when Richard
1 CONT discovered it, he left, swearing revenge.[12] Philip now pressed his advantage
1 CONT in northeastern Normandy, where he conducted a raid at Dieppe, during which he
1 CONT burnt the English ships in the harbor, repulsing an attack by Richard at the
1 CONT same time. Philip now marched southward into the Berry region, and his primary
1 CONT objective was the fortress of Issoudun, which had just been captured by
1 CONT Richard’s mercenary commander, Mercadier. The French king took the town and
1 CONT was besieging the castle when Richard stormed through French lines and made
1 CONT his way in to reinforce the garrison, while at the same time another army was
1 CONT approaching Philip’s supply lines. Philip called off his attack, and another
1 CONT truce was agreed to.[12]
1 CONT
1 CONT The war slowly turned against Philip over the course of the next three years.
1 CONT Though things looked promising at the start of 1196 when Arthur of Brittany
1 CONT ended up in Philip’s hands, and he won the Siege of Aumale, it would not last.
1 CONT Richard won over a key ally, Baldwin of Flanders in 1197. Then in 1198, Henry
1 CONT the Holy Roman Emperor died, and his successor was to be Otto IV, Richard’s
1 CONT nephew, who in turn put additional pressure on Philip.[13] Finally, many
1 CONT Norman lords were switching sides, and returning to Richard’s camp. This was
1 CONT the state of affairs when Philip launched his 1198 campaign with an attack on
1 CONT the Vexin. He was pushed back before then having to deal with the Flemish
1 CONT invasion of Artois.
1 CONT
1 CONT On September 27, Richard entered the Vexin, taking Courcelles-Chaussy and
1 CONT Boury-en-Vexin before returning to Dangu. Philip, believing that Courcelles-
1 CONT Chaussy was still holding out, went to its relief. Discovering what was
1 CONT happening, Richard decided to attack the French king’s forces, catching Philip
1 CONT by surprise.[13] Philip’s forces fled and attempted to reach the fortress of
1 CONT Gisors. Bunched together, the French knights and Philip attempted to cross the
1 CONT Epte River on a bridge that promptly collapsed under their weight, almost
1 CONT drowning Philip in the process. He was dragged out of the river and shut
1 CONT himself up in Gisors.[13]
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip soon began a new offensive, launching raids into Normandy and again
1 CONT targeting Evreux. Richard countered Philip’s offensive with a counterattack in
1 CONT the Vexin, while Mercadier led a raid on Abbeville. The upshot was that by the
1 CONT fall of 1198, Richard had regained almost all that had been lost in 1193.[13]
1 CONT Philip, now in desperate circumstances, offered a truce so that discussions
1 CONT could begin towards a more permanent peace, with the offer that he would
1 CONT return all of the territories except for Gisors.
1 CONT
1 CONT In mid-January 1199, the two kings met for a final meeting, Richard, standing
1 CONT on the deck of a boat, Philip, standing on the banks of the Seine River.[14]
1 CONT Shouting terms at each other, they could not reach agreement on the terms of a
1 CONT permanent truce, but did agree to further mediation, which resulted in a five
1 CONT year truce. The truce held and later that year, Richard was killed during a
1 CONT siege involving one of Richard’s vassals.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Conflict with King John 1200-1206
1 CONT
1 CONT In May 1200, Philip signed the Treaty of Le Goulet with Richard's successor
1 CONT king John of England, as youngest son of Henry called the Lackland, now also
1 CONT Duke of Normandy. The treaty was meant to bring peace to Normandy by settling
1 CONT the issue of the boundaries of the much reduced duchy and the terms of John's
1 CONT vassalage for it and Anjou, Maine, and Touraine. John agreed to heavy terms,
1 CONT including the abandonment of all the English possession in Berry and 20,000
1 CONT Marks of Silver, but Philip in turn recognised John as king, formally
1 CONT abandoning Arthur I of Brittany, whom he had thitherto supported, and
1 CONT recognised John's suzerainty over the Duchy of Brittany. To seal the treaty, a
1 CONT marriage between Blanche of Castile, John's niece, and Louis the Lion,
1 CONT Philip's son, was contracted.
1 CONT
1 CONT Map of Philip's conquests
1 CONT
1 CONT This did not stop the war, however. John’s mismanagement of Aquitaine saw that
1 CONT province erupt in rebellion later that year, which Philip secretly
1 CONT encouraged.[15] To disguise his ambitions, he invited John to a conference at
1 CONT Andely, and then entertained him at Paris, and both times he committed to
1 CONT complying with the Treaty.[15] Then in 1202, disaffected patrons petitioned
1 CONT the French king to summon John to answer their charges in his capacity as
1 CONT John’s feudal lord, and, when the English king refused to appear, Philip again
1 CONT took up the claims of Arthur, to whom he betrothed his six-year-old daughter,
1 CONT Marie. John crossed over into Normandy and his forces soon captured Arthur,
1 CONT and in 1203, the young man disappeared, with most people believing that John
1 CONT had Arthur murdered.
1 CONT
1 CONT The outcry over Arthur’s fate saw an increase in local opposition to John
1 CONT which Philip used to his advantage.[15] He took the offensive and, apart from
1 CONT a five month siege of Andely, he swept all before him. On the fall of Andely,
1 CONT John fled to England, and by the end of 1204, most of Normandy and the Angevin
1 CONT lands, including much of Aquitaine had fallen into Philip’s hands.[15]
1 CONT
1 CONT What Philip had gained through victory in war, he then sought to confirm by
1 CONT legal means. Philip, again acting as John’s liege lord, summoned his vassal to
1 CONT appear before the Court of the Twelve Peers of France, to answer for the
1 CONT murder of Arthur of Brittany.[16] John’s request for safe conduct only saw
1 CONT Philip agree to allow him to come in peace, but that his return would only
1 CONT occur if it were allowed after the judgment of his peers. Not willing to risk
1 CONT his life on such a guarantee, he refused to appear, so Philip summarily
1 CONT dispossessed him of his French lands.[16] Pushed by his barons, John
1 CONT eventually launched an invasion in 1206, disembarking with his army at La
1 CONT Rochelle during one of Philip’s absences, but the campaign was a disaster.[16]
1 CONT After backing out of a conference that he himself had demanded, John
1 CONT eventually bargained at Thouars for a two year truce, the price of which was
1 CONT his agreement to the chief provisions of the judgment of the Court of Peers,
1 CONT including the loss of his patrimony.[16]
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Alliances against Philip 1208-1213
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1208, Philip of Swabia, the successful candidate for becoming the next
1 CONT emperor of the Holy Roman Empire was assassinated, meaning that the imperial
1 CONT crown was given to his rival, Otto IV, the nephew of King John. Otto, prior to
1 CONT his accession, had promised to help John to recover his lost European
1 CONT possessions, but circumstances prevented them from making good their
1 CONT claims.[17] By 1212, both John and Otto were engaged in power struggles
1 CONT against Pope Innocent III, John over his refusal to accept the papal
1 CONT nomination for the Archbishop of Canterbury, and Otto over his attempt to
1 CONT strip Frederick II of his Sicilian crown. Philip decided to take advantage of
1 CONT this situation, firstly in Germany where he supported the rebellion of the
1 CONT German nobility in support of the young Frederick.[17] John immediately threw
1 CONT his support behind Otto, and Philip now saw his chance to launch a successful
1 CONT invasion of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT In order to secure the cooperation of all his vassals in his plans for the
1 CONT invasion, Philip denounced John as an enemy of the Church, thereby justifying
1 CONT his attack against him as being solely for religious reasons. He summoned an
1 CONT assembly of French barons at Soissons, which was well attended with the
1 CONT exception of Ferdinand, Count of Flanders. He refused to attend, still angry
1 CONT over the loss of the towns of Aire and Saint-Omer which had been captured by
1 CONT Philip’s son, Louis the Lion, and he would not participate in any campaign
1 CONT until they had been restored to him.[17]
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime, Philip, eager to prove his loyalty to Rome and thus secure
1 CONT Papal support for his planned invasion, announced at Soissons his
1 CONT reconciliation with his estranged wife Ingeborg of Denmark which the Popes had
1 CONT been pushing.[17] The Barons fully supported his plan, and they all gathered
1 CONT their forces and prepared to join with Philip at the agreed rendezvous. In all
1 CONT this, Philip remained in constant communication with Pandolfo, the Papal
1 CONT Legate, who was encouraging Philip to pursue his objective. Pandolfo however
1 CONT was also holding secret discussions with King John. Advising the English king
1 CONT of his precarious predicament, he persuaded John to abandon his opposition to
1 CONT Papal investiture and agreed to accept the Papal Legate’s decision in any
1 CONT ecclesiastical disputes as final.[18] In return, the Pope agreed to accept the
1 CONT Kingdom of England and the Lordship of Ireland as Papal fiefs, which John
1 CONT would rule as the Pope’s vassal, and for which John would do homage to the
1 CONT Pope.[18]
1 CONT
1 CONT No sooner had the treaty been ratified in May 1213 than Pandolfo announced to
1 CONT Philip that he would have to abandon his expedition against John, since to
1 CONT attack a faithful vassal of the Holy See would constitute a mortal sin. In
1 CONT vain did Philip argue that his plans had been drawn up with the consent of
1 CONT Rome, that his expedition was in support of papal authority which he only
1 CONT undertook on the understanding that he would gain a Plenary Indulgence, or
1 CONT that he had spent a fortune preparing for the expedition. The Papal Legate
1 CONT remained unmoved.[18] But Pandolfo did suggest an alternative. The Count of
1 CONT Flanders had denied Philip’s right to declare war on England while King John
1 CONT was still excommunicated, and that his disobedience needed to be punished.[18]
1 CONT Philip eagerly accepted the advice, and quickly marched at the head of his
1 CONT troops into the territory of Flanders.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] War of Bouvines 1213-1214
1 CONT
1 CONT The French fleet, reportedly numbering some 1,700 ships[19] proceeded first to
1 CONT Gravelines and then to the port of Dam. Meanwhile the army marched by Cassel,
1 CONT Ypres and Bruges, before laying siege to Ghent.[19] Hardly had the siege begun
1 CONT when Philip learned that the English fleet had captured a number of his ships
1 CONT at Dam, and that the rest were so closely blockaded in its harbor, that it was
1 CONT impossible for them to escape. After having obtained 30,000 Marks as a ransom
1 CONT for the hostages he had taken from the Flemish cities he had captured, Philip
1 CONT quickly retraced his steps in order to reach Dam. It took him two days, and he
1 CONT arrived in time to relieve the French garrison.[19] But he discovered that he
1 CONT could not rescue his fleet, and in order to prevent it from falling into enemy
1 CONT hands, he ordered it to be burnt before also commanding that the town of Dam
1 CONT also be burned to the ground. Determined to make the Flemish pay for his
1 CONT retreat, every district he passed through he ordered that all towns be razed
1 CONT and burned, and that the peasantry were either killed or sold as slaves.[19]
1 CONT
1 CONT But the destruction of the French fleet had once again raised John’s hopes up,
1 CONT and so he began preparing for an invasion of France and a reconquest of his
1 CONT lost provinces. Initially his barons were unenthusiastic about the expedition,
1 CONT which delayed his departure, and so it was not until February 1214 that he was
1 CONT able to disembark at La Rochelle.[19] John was to advance from the Loire
1 CONT (river), while his ally Otto IV made a simultaneous attack from Flanders,
1 CONT together with the Count of Flanders. Unfortunately, the three armies could not
1 CONT coordinate their efforts effectively. It was not until John, who had been
1 CONT disappointed in his hope for an easy victory after being driven from Roche-au-
1 CONT Moine and had retreated to his transports that the Imperial Army, with Otto at
1 CONT its head, assembled in the Low Countries.[19]
1 CONT
1 CONT On July 27, 1214, the opposing armies suddenly discovered they were in close
1 CONT proximity to each other, on the banks of a little tributary of the River Lys,
1 CONT near the Bridge of Bouvines. Philip’s army numbered some 15,000, while the
1 CONT allied forces possessed around 25,000 troops, and the armies clashed at the
1 CONT Battle of Bouvines. It was a tight battle; Philip was unhorsed by the Flemish
1 CONT pikemen in the heat of battle, and were it not for his plate mail armour in
1 CONT which he was encased, he would probably have been killed.[20] When Otto was
1 CONT carried off the field by his wounded and terrified horse,[20] and Ferdinand,
1 CONT Count of Flanders, severely wounded, was captured by the French, the Flemish
1 CONT and Imperial troops saw that the battle was lost, turned and fled from the
1 CONT battlefield. The French troop began pursuing them but with night approaching,
1 CONT and with the prisoners they already had being too many and, more importantly,
1 CONT too valuable to risk in a risky pursuit, Philip ordered a recall before his
1 CONT troops had moved little more than a mile from the battlefield.[20] Philip
1 CONT returned to Paris triumphant, marching his captive prisoners behind him in a
1 CONT long procession, as his grateful subjects came out to greet the victorious
1 CONT king. In the aftermath of the battle, Otto retreated to his castle of Harzburg
1 CONT and was soon overthrown as Holy Roman Emperor, and replaced by Frederick II.
1 CONT Count Ferdinand remained imprisoned following his defeat, while King John
1 CONT obtained a five year truce, on very lenient terms given the circumstances.[20]
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip’s decisive victory was crucial in ordering Western European politics in
1 CONT both England and France. In the former, so weakened was the defeated King John
1 CONT of England that he soon needed to submit to his barons demands and sign the
1 CONT Magna Carta, limiting the power of the crown and establishing the basis for
1 CONT common law. In the latter, the battle was instrumental in forming the strong
1 CONT central monarchy that would characterize France until the first French
1 CONT Revolution. It was also the first battle in the Middle Ages in which the full
1 CONT value of infantry was realised.[20]
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marital problems
1 CONT
1 CONT After Isabelle's early death in childbirth, in 1190, Philip decided to marry
1 CONT again. On the 15th of August in 1193 he married Ingeborg (1175–1236), daughter
1 CONT of King Valdemar I of Denmark (1157–82). She was renamed Isambour, and Stephan
1 CONT of Dornik described her as "very kind, young of age but old of wisdom." For
1 CONT some unknown reason, Philip was repelled by her, and he refused to allow her
1 CONT to be crowned Queen. Ingeborg protested at this treatment; his response was to
1 CONT confine her to a convent. He then asked Pope Celestine III for an annulment on
1 CONT the grounds of non-consummation. Philip had not reckoned with Ingeborg,
1 CONT however; she insisted that the marriage had been consummated, and that she was
1 CONT his wife and the rightful Queen of France. The Franco-Danish churchman William
1 CONT of Paris intervened on the side of Ingeborg, drawing up a genealogy of the
1 CONT Danish kings to disprove the alleged impediment of consanguinity.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime Philip had sought a new bride. Initially agreement had been
1 CONT reached for him to marry Margaret of Geneva, daughter of William I, Count of
1 CONT Geneva, but the young bride's journey to Paris was interrupted by Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy, who kidnapped Philip's intended new queen and married her instead,
1 CONT claiming that Philip was already bound in marriage. Philip finally achieved a
1 CONT third marriage, on the 7th of May in 1196, to Agnes of Merania from Dalmatia
1 CONT (c. 1180 – 29th of July in 1201). Their children were Marie (1198 – 15th of
1 CONT October in 1224) and Philippe Hurepel (1200–1234), Count of Clermont and
1 CONT eventually, by marriage, Count of Boulogne.
1 CONT
1 CONT Pope Innocent III (1198–1216) declared Philip Augustus's marriage to Agnes of
1 CONT Merania null and void, as he was still married to Ingeborg. He ordered the
1 CONT King to part from Agnès; when he did not, the Pope placed France under an
1 CONT interdict in 1199. This continued until the 7th of September in 1200. Due to
1 CONT pressure from the Pope and from Ingeborg's brother, King Valdemar II of
1 CONT Denmark (1202–41), Philip finally took Ingeborg back as his Queen in 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II, King of France, in a non-contemporary portrait
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Last years
1 CONT
1 CONT Understandably, he turned a deaf ear when the Pope asked him to do something
1 CONT about the heretics in the Languedoc. When Pope Innocent III called for a
1 CONT crusade against the Albigensians or Cathars, in 1208, Philip did nothing to
1 CONT support it, but neither did he hinder it. The war against the Cathars did not
1 CONT end until 1244, when finally their last strongholds were captured. The fruits
1 CONT of it, namely the submission of the south of France to the crown, were to be
1 CONT reaped by Philip's son, Louis VIII, and grandson, Louis IX. From 1216 to 1222
1 CONT Philip also arbitrated in the War of Succession in Champagne and finally
1 CONT helped the military efforts of Eudes III, Duke of Burgundy and Frederick II,
1 CONT Holy Roman Emperor to bring it to an end.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus would play a significant role in one of the greatest
1 CONT centuries of innovation in construction and in education. With Paris as his
1 CONT capital, he had the main thoroughfares paved, built a central market, Les
1 CONT Halles, continued the construction begun in 1163 of the Gothic Notre-Dame de
1 CONT Paris Cathedral, constructed the Louvre as a fortress and gave a charter to
1 CONT the University of Paris in 1200. Under his guidance, Paris became the first
1 CONT city of teachers the medieval world had known. In 1224, the French poet Henry
1 CONT d'Andeli wrote of the great wine tasting competition that Philip II Augustus
1 CONT commissioned The Battle of the Wines.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus died 14 July 1223 at Mantes-la-Jolie, and was interred in
1 CONT Saint Denis Basilica. Philip's son by Isabelle de Hainaut, Louis VIII, was his
1 CONT successor.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Portrayal in fiction
1 CONT
1 CONT King Philip appears in William Shakespeare's historical play King John. He is
1 CONT also a character in James Goldman's historical play The Lion in Winter, which
1 CONT maintains the historical theory that he and Richard the Lionhearted had
1 CONT previously had a homosexual relationship. In the 1968 film of Goldman's play,
1 CONT which downplayed the homosexual aspect present in the stage play, Philip was
1 CONT played by Timothy Dalton. Jonathan Rhys Meyers played Philip in a 2003
1 CONT television version which somewhat resurrected the matter.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Ancestry
1 CONT
1 CONT [show]
