1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste) (21 August 1165 – 14 July 1223)
1 CONT was the King of France from 1180 until his death. A member of the House of
1 CONT Capet, Philip Augustus was born at Gonesse in the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis
1 CONT VII and his third wife, Adela of Champagne. He was originally nicknamed
1 CONT Dieudonné — the God-given — as he was the first son of Louis VII late in his
1 CONT father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals (Flemish and English) at
1 CONT the Battle of Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government, bringing
1 CONT financial stability to the country and thus making possible a sharp increase
1 CONT in prosperity. His reign was popular with ordinary people because he checked
1 CONT the power of the nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle
1 CONT class.In May 1200, Philip signed the Treaty of Le Goulet with Richard's
1 CONT successor John. The treaty was meant to bring peace to Normandy by settling
1 CONT the issue of the boundaries of the duchy and the terms of John's vassalage for
1 CONT it and Anjou, Maine, and Touraine. John agreed to heavy terms, but Philip in
1 CONT turn recognised John as king, formally abandoning Arthur I of Brittany, whom
1 CONT he had thitherto supported, and recognised John's suzerainty over the Duchy of
1 CONT Brittany. To seal the treaty, a marriage between Blanche of Castile, John's
1 CONT niece, and Louis the Lion, Philip's son, was contracted.
1 CONT
1 CONT This did not stop the war, however. In 1202, disaffected patrons petitioned
1 CONT the French king to summon John to answer their charges and, when the English
1 CONT king refused, Philip dispossessed him of his French lands. Within two years,
1 CONT most of Normandy and the Angevin lands, including much of Aquitaine, had been
1 CONT conquered. The war, called the "War of Bouvines," continued for the next
1 CONT decade until Philip won a decisive victory at Bouvines (1214) over a coalition
1 CONT of forces that included the Emperor Otto IV and Ferdinand, Count of Flanders.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste; b. in Gonesse 21 August 1165 –
1 CONT 14 July 1223 in Mantes-la-Jolie) was the King of France from 1180 until his
1 CONT death. A member of the House of Capet, Philip Augustus was born at Gonesse in
1 CONT the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis VII and his third wife, Adela of Champagne.
1 CONT He was originally nicknamed Dieudonné—the God-given—as he was the first son of
1 CONT Louis VII late in his father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals (German, Flemish and
1 CONT English) at the Battle of Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government,
1 CONT bringing financial stability to the country and thus making possible a sharp
1 CONT increase in prosperity. His reign was popular with ordinary people because he
1 CONT checked the power of the nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle
1 CONT class.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste) (21 August 1165 – 14 July 1223)
1 CONT was the King of France from 1180 until his death. A member of the House of
1 CONT Capet, Philip Augustus was born at Gonesse in the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis
1 CONT VII and his third wife, Adela of Champagne. He was originally nicknamed
1 CONT Dieudonné — the God-given — as he was the first son of Louis VII late in his
1 CONT father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals (German, Flemish and
1 CONT English) at the Battle of Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government,
1 CONT bringing financial stability to the country and thus making possible a sharp
1 CONT increase in prosperity. His reign was popular with ordinary people because he
1 CONT checked the power of the nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle
1 CONT class.
1 CONT
1 CONT After Isabelle's early death in childbirth, in 1190, Philip decided to marry
1 CONT again. On August 15, 1193 he married Ingeborg (1175–1236), daughter of King
1 CONT Valdemar I of Denmark (1157–82). She was renamed Isambour, and Stephan of
1 CONT Dornik described her as "very kind, young of age but old of wisdom." For some
1 CONT unknown reason, Philip was repelled by her, and he refused to allow her to be
1 CONT crowned Queen. Ingeborg protested at this treatment; his response was to
1 CONT confine her to a convent. He then asked Pope Celestine III for an annulment on
1 CONT the grounds of non-consummation. Philip had not reckoned with Ingeborg,
1 CONT however; she insisted that the marriage had been consummated, and that she was
1 CONT his wife and the rightful Queen of France. The Franco-Danish churchman William
1 CONT of Paris intervened on the side of Ingeborg, drawing up a genealogy of the
1 CONT Danish kings to disprove the alleged impediment of consanguinity.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime Philip had sought a new bride. Initially agreement had been
1 CONT reached for him to marry Marguerite of Geneva, daughter of William I, Count of
1 CONT Geneva, but the young bride's journey to Paris was interrupted by Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy, who kidnapped Philip's intended new queen and married her instead,
1 CONT claiming that Philip was already bound in marriage. Philip finally achieved a
1 CONT third marriage, on May 7, 1196, to Agnes of Merania from Dalmatia (c. 1180 –
1 CONT July 29, 1201). Their children were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Marie (1198 – October 15, 1224)
1 CONT
1 CONT Philippe Hurepel (1200–1234), Count of Clermont and eventually, by marriage,
1 CONT Count of Boulogne
1 CONT
1 CONT Pope Innocent III (1198–1216) declared Philip Augustus's marriage to Agnes of
1 CONT Merania null and void, as he was still married to Ingeborg. He ordered the
1 CONT King to part from Agnès; when he did not, the Pope placed France under an
1 CONT interdict in 1199. This continued until September 7, 1200. Due to pressure
1 CONT from the Pope and from Ingeborg's brother, King Valdemar II of Denmark
1 CONT (1202–41), Philip finally took Ingeborg back as his Queen in 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II of France
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste) (21 August 1165 – 14 July 1223)
1 CONT was the King of France from 1180 until his death. A member of the House of
1 CONT Capet, Philip Augustus was born at Gonesse in the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis
1 CONT VII and his third wife, Adela of Champagne. He was originally nicknamed
1 CONT Dieudonné — the God-given — as he was the first son of Louis VII late in his
1 CONT father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals (Flemish and English) at
1 CONT the Battle of Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government, bringing
1 CONT financial stability to the country and thus making possible a sharp increase
1 CONT in prosperity. His reign was popular with ordinary people because he checked
1 CONT the power of the nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle class.
1 CONT
1 CONT Early years
1 CONT
1 CONT In declining health, Louis VII had him crowned and anointed at Rheims by the
1 CONT Archbishop William Whitehands on 1 November 1179. He was married on 28 April
1 CONT 1180 to Isabelle of Hainaut, who brought the County of Artois as her dowry.
1 CONT His father died on 20 September.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Consolidation of royal demesne
1 CONT
1 CONT While the royal demesne had increased under Philip I and Louis VI, under Louis
1 CONT VII it had diminished slightly. In April 1182, Philip expelled all Jews from
1 CONT the demesne and confiscated their goods.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip's eldest son, Louis, was born on 5 September 1187 and inherited Artois
1 CONT in 1190, when Isabelle, his mother, died.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Wars with his vassals
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1181, Philip began a war with the Count of Flanders, Philip of Alsace.
1 CONT Philip managed to counter the ambitions of the count by breaking his alliances
1 CONT with Henry I, Duke of Brabant, and Philip of Heinsberg, Archbishop of Cologne.
1 CONT In July 1185, the Treaty of Boves confirmed to the king the possession of the
1 CONT Vermandois, Artois, and Amiénois.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1184, Stephen I of Sancerre and his Brabançon mercenaries ravaged the
1 CONT Orléanais. Philip defeated him with the aid of the Confrères de la Paix.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]War with Henry II
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip also began to war with the Henry II of England, who was also Count of
1 CONT Anjou and Duke of Aquitaine in France. Two years of combat (1186–1188)
1 CONT followed, but the situation remained unchanged. Philip initially allied with
1 CONT Henry's young sons, Richard and John, who were in rebellion against their
1 CONT father. However, news of the fall of Jerusalem to Saladin, followed quickly by
1 CONT the death of Henry, diverted attention from the Franco-English war.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was close friends with all of Henry's sons and he used them to foment
1 CONT rebellion against their father, but turned against both Richard and John after
1 CONT their respective accessions to the throne. With Henry the Young King and
1 CONT Geoffrey of Brittany he maintained friendship until their deaths. Indeed, at
1 CONT the funeral of Geoffrey, he was so overcome with grief that he had to be
1 CONT forcibly restrained from casting himself into the grave.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]War with John Lackland
1 CONT
1 CONT In May 1200, Philip signed the Treaty of Le Goulet with Richard's successor
1 CONT John. The treaty was meant to bring peace to Normandy by settling the issue of
1 CONT the boundaries of the duchy and the terms of John's vassalage for it and
1 CONT Anjou, Maine, and Touraine. John agreed to heavy terms, but Philip in turn
1 CONT recognised John as king, formally abandoning Arthur I of Brittany, whom he had
1 CONT thitherto supported, and recognised John's suzerainty over the Duchy of
1 CONT Brittany. To seal the treaty, a marriage between Blanche of Castile, John's
1 CONT niece, and Louis the Lion, Philip's son, was contracted.
1 CONT
1 CONT This did not stop the war, however. In 1202, disaffected patrons petitioned
1 CONT the French king to summon John to answer their charges and, when the English
1 CONT king refused, Philip dispossessed him of his French lands. Within two years,
1 CONT most of Normandy and the Angevin lands, including much of Aquitaine, had been
1 CONT conquered. The war, called the "War of Bouvines," continued for the next
1 CONT decade until Philip won a decisive victory at Bouvines (1214)
1 CONT [FAVthomas.FTW]
1 CONT
1 CONT Byname Philip Augustus, French Philippe Auguste the first of the greatCapetian
1 CONT kings of medieval France (reigned 1179/1223), who graduallyreconquered the
1 CONT French territories held by the kings of England and alsofurthered the royal
1 CONT domains northward into Flanders and southward intoLanguedoc. He was a major
1 CONT figure in the Third Crusade to the Holy Land in1191.
1 CONT Philip was the son of Louis VII of France and Adela of Champagne. Inorder to
1 CONT be associated as king with his father, who had fallen mortallyill, he was
1 CONT crowned at Reims on Nov. 1, 1179. His uncles of the House ofChampagne, Henry
1 CONT I, count of Champagne; Guillaume, archbishop of Reims;and Thibaut V, count of
1 CONT Blois and Chartres, hoped to use the youthfulking to control France. To escape
1 CONT from their
1 CONT tutelage, Philip, on April 28, 1180, married Isabella, the daughter ofBaldwin
1 CONT V of Hainaut and the niece (through her mother) of Philip ofAlsace, the count
1 CONT of Flanders, who promised to give the King theterritory of Artois as her
1 CONT dowry. When Henry II of England arrived inNormandie, perhaps with the
1 CONT intention of responding to an appeal by theHouse of Champagne, Philip II
1 CONT entered into negotiations with him and, atGisors on June 28, 1180, renewed an
1 CONT understanding that Louis VII hadreached with him in 1177. As a result, the
1 CONT House of Champagne waspolitically isolated, and Philip II was making all
1 CONT decisions for himselfand acting as he saw fit when his father died, on Sept.
1 CONT 18, 1180, leavinghim sole king in name as well as in fact. When the Count of
1 CONT Flandersallied himself with the Champagne faction, there followed a
1 CONT seriousrevolt against the King. In the Peace of Boves, in July 1185
1 CONT (confirmedby the Treaty of Gisors in May 1186), the King and the Count of
1 CONT Flanderscomposed their differences (which had been chiefly over possession
1 CONT ofVermandois, in Picardy), so that the disputed territory was
1 CONT partitioned,Amiens and numerous other places passing to the King and the
1 CONT remainder,with the county of Vermandois proper, being left provisionally to
1 CONT Philipof Alsace. Thenceforward the King was free to run against Henry II
1 CONT ofEngland.
1 CONT Henry's French possessions, the so-called Angevin Empire, consistingof
1 CONT Normandie, Maine, Anjou, and Touraine, with Aquitaine in the hands ofhis son,
1 CONT the future Richard I the Lion-Heart of England, and Brittanyruled by another
1 CONT son, Geoffrey (died 1186), all were a constant menace tothe French royal
1 CONT domain. Furthermore, there were long-standing disputesover the Vexin (between
1 CONT Normandie and the Île-de-France), Berry, andAuvergne.
1 CONT Philip II launched an attack on Berry in the summer of 1187 but thenin June
1 CONT made a truce with Henry, which left Issoudun in his hands andalso granted him
1 CONT Fréteval, in Vendômois. Though the truce was for twoyears, Philip found
1 CONT grounds for resuming hostilities in the summer of1188. He skillfully exploited
1 CONT the estrangement between Henry and Richard,and Richard did homage to him
1 CONT voluntarily at Bonmoulins in November 1188.Finally, by the Treaty of Azay-le-
1 CONT Rideau, or of Colombières (July 4,1189), Henry was forced to renew his own
1 CONT homage, to confirm the cessionof Issoudun, with Graçay also, to Philip, and to
1 CONT renounce his claim tosuzerainty over Auvergne. Henry died two days later.
1 CONT Richard, who succeeded Henry as king of England, had alreadyundertaken to go
1 CONT on crusade (the Third Crusade) against Saladin in theHoly Land, and Philip now
1 CONT did likewise. Before his departure, he made theso-called Testament of 1190 to
1 CONT provide for the government of his kingdomin his absence. On his way to
1 CONT Palestine, he met Richard in Sicily, wherethey promptly found themselves at
1 CONT variance, though they made a treaty atMessina in March 1191. Arriving in
1 CONT Palestine, they cooperated against theMuslims at Acre, until Philip fell ill
1 CONT and made his illness a pretext forreturning to France, quite
1 CONT determined to settle the succession to Flanders (Philip of Alsace hadjust died
1 CONT on the crusade) while Richard was still absent. Thus, by theend of 1191,
1 CONT Philip II was back in France.
1 CONT In spite of promises he had made in the Holy Land, Philip at onceprepared to
1 CONT attack the Plantagenet possessions in France. Informed ofthis, Richard also
1 CONT left the crusade but was taken prisoner while on hisway back by the duke of
1 CONT Austria, Leopold V of Babenberg. Philip dideverything he could to prolong his
1 CONT rival's captivity, but Richard was atlast set free (1194) and went to war
1 CONT against Philip. The French kingsuffered a number of defeats (from that at
1 CONT Fréteval in July 1194 to thatat Courcelles in September 1198) in a series of
1 CONT campaigns that wereoccasionally punctuated by negotiations. It was fortuitous
1 CONT for Philip,however, when Richard was killed in April 1199.
1 CONT Richard's brother John was by no means as formidable a fighter.Moreover, his
1 CONT right to
1 CONT Richard's succession could be contested by Arthur de Brittany, whosefather had
1 CONT been senior to John. To secure the succession, therefore, Johncame to terms
1 CONT with Philip: by the Treaty of Le Goulet (May 22, 1200), inreturn for Philip's
1 CONT recognition of him as Richard's heir, he ceded Évreuxand the Norman Vexin to
1 CONT Philip; agreed that Issoudun and Graçay should bethe dowry of his niece
1 CONT Blanche de Castile, who was to marry the futureLouis VIII (Philip's son by
1 CONT Isabella of Hainaut); and renounced any claimto
1 CONT suzerainty over Berry and Auvergne.
1 CONT Shortly afterward, however, John entered into conflict with theLusignan family
1 CONT of Poitou (in Aquitaine), who appealed to Philip asoverlord. When he was
1 CONT summoned to appear before the royal court as avassal of the French crown, John
1 CONT did not present himself, and Philip, inApril 1202, pronounced John's French
1 CONT fiefs forfeit and undertook to carryout the sentence himself. He invaded
1 CONT Normandie, overran the northeast,and laid siege to Arques, while Arthur de
1 CONT Brittany, the son of Geoffrey,who died some years before, campaigned against
1 CONT John's supporters inPoitou; but John, marching south from Maine, captured
1 CONT Arthur at Mirebeau(August 1). In fury, Philip abandoned the siege of Arques
1 CONT and marchedsouthwestward to Tours, ravaging John's territory on his way
1 CONT beforereturning to Paris. Guillaume des Roches, the powerful seneschal
1 CONT ofAnjou, who had taken John's side, came to terms with Philip in March 1203.
1 CONT Resuming operations against Normandie, Philip occupied the townsaround the
1 CONT great fortress of Château-Gaillard, to which he laid siege inSeptember 1203,
1 CONT having overruled Pope Innocent III's attempts to mediate.John, who is reported
1 CONT to have murdered Arthur de Brittany in April,retired to England in December,
1 CONT and Château-Gaillard fell to Philip inMarch 1204. Rouen, the Norman capital,
1 CONT surrendered in June, after 40days' resistance.
1 CONT After his conquest of Normandie, Philip subdued Maine, Touraine,Anjou, and
1 CONT most of Poitou with less difficulty (1204/05), though thecastles of Loches and
1 CONT Chinon held out for a year. He sought to secure hisconquests by lavishing
1 CONT privileges on the towns and on the religioushouses but otherwise left the
1 CONT local barons in power. Unrest, however, wasendemic in Poitou, and in June 1206
1 CONT John landed at La Rochelle. After acampaign in the south, he turned north
1 CONT toward the Loire. At Thouars inOctober 1206, he and Philip made a two-year
1 CONT truce, leaving John inpossession of the reconquered Poitevin lands. In the
1 CONT following year,however, Philip invaded Poitou again; and, after a further
1 CONT campaign in1208, only the south and part of the west of Poitou remained loyal
1 CONT toJohn (with Saintonge, Guyenne, and Gascony).
1 CONT Philip next hoped to exploit the dispute between John and PopeInnocent III.
1 CONT While Innocent was threatening to declare John unfit toreign (1212), plans
1 CONT were being made for a French landing in England andfor the accession of
1 CONT Philip's son Louis to the English throne. The planshad to be dropped when John
1 CONT made his submission to the Pope (1213).Throwing himself into schemes for
1 CONT revenge, John formed a coalitionagainst France: the Holy Roman emperor Otto
1 CONT IV, the Count of Flanders(Ferrand, or
1 CONT Ferdinand, of Portugal), and the Count of Boulogne (Raynald, or Renaud,of
1 CONT Dammartin) were to invade the Capetian territory from the northeastwhile John
1 CONT attacked from the west, with the help of his Poitevin barons.
1 CONT John landed at La Rochelle in February 1214 and advanced into Anjoubut was put
1 CONT to flight by Louis at La Roche-aux-Moines on July 2; hisconfederates were
1 CONT completely defeated by Philip in the decisive Battle ofBouvines on July 27.
1 CONT The Anglo-Angevin power in France and the coalitionhad both been broken in one
1 CONT month. Thus Philip, who, in 1213, hadtransferred Brittany to his cousin Peter
1 CONT of Dreux, was left without anysignificant opposition to his rule in France.
1 CONT It was not only at the Plantagenets' expense that Philip enlarged theroyal
1 CONT domain. His claim to Artois through his first marriage and hisgains by the
1 CONT settlement of 1185/86 have been mentioned above, and hesubsequently proceeded,
1 CONT step by step, to acquire the rest of Vermandoisand Valois. His insistence on
1 CONT his suzerainty over vacant fiefs and on histutelage over minors and heiresses
1 CONT was particularly effective with regardto Flanders, where two successive
1 CONT Flemish counts, Philip of Alsace (died1191) and Baldwin IX (died c. 1205) had
1 CONT left no male issue.
1 CONT Though he did not personally take part in the crusade proclaimed byPope
1 CONT Innocent III against a Cathari religious sect in Languedoc, Philipallowed his
1 CONT vassals and knights to carry it out. Simon de Montfort'scapture of Béziers and
1 CONT Carcassonne (1209) and his victory at Muret overRaymond VI of Toulouse and
1 CONT Peter II of Aragón (1213) prepared the way forthe eventual annexation of
1 CONT eastern Languedoc to the royal domain sixyears after Philip's death and for
1 CONT the union of northern and southernFrance under Capetian rule.
1 CONT Several years before he tried to take advantage of the papacy'squarrel with
1 CONT John of England, Philip had himself been in dispute withRome. After the death
1 CONT (1190) of Isabella of Hainaut, he had marriedIngeborg, sister of the Danish
1 CONT king Canute IV, on Aug. 14, 1193, and onthe next day, for a private reason,
1 CONT had resolved to separate from her.Having procured the annulment of his
1 CONT marriage by an assembly of bishopsin November 1193, he took a Tirolese lady,
1 CONT Agnes, daughter of Bertold IVof Meran, as his wife in June 1196. Denmark,
1 CONT meanwhile, had complained toRome about the repudiation of Ingeborg, and Pope
1 CONT Celestine III hadcountermanded it in 1195; but Celestine died (1198) before he
1 CONT couldresort to coercion against Philip. The next pope, Innocent III,
1 CONT wassterner: in January 1200 he imposed an interdict on France.
1 CONT Philip,therefore, in September 1200, had to submit, pretending to be
1 CONT reconciledwith Ingeborg. In fact, he refused to cohabit with her and kept her
1 CONT insemicaptivity until 1213, when he accepted her beside him, not as hiswife
1 CONT but at least as his queen. Agnes had died in 1201, after bearing twochildren
1 CONT to Philip: Marie, countess of Namur (1211) and duchess ofBrabant (1213), by
1 CONT successive marriages; and Philip, called Hurepel,count of Clermont.
1 CONT Throughout his reign, Philip kept a close watch over the Frenchnobility, which
1 CONT he brought effectively to heel. He maintained excellentrelations with the
1 CONT French clergy, leaving the canons of the cathedralchapters free to elect their
1 CONT bishops and favouring the monastic orders.He knew, too, how to win the support
1 CONT of the towns, granting privilegesand liberties to merchants and frequently
1 CONT aiding their struggles to freethemselves from the seignorial authority of the
1 CONT nobles. In return, thecommunes helped financially and militarily. Most of all,
1 CONT Philip gave hisattention to Paris, not only fortifying it with a great
1 CONT also having its streets and thoroughfares put in order. For thecountryside, he
1 CONT multiplied the number of villes neuves (“new towns”), orenfranchised
1 CONT communities.
1 CONT The Capetian monarchy's hold on the huge royal domain as well as onthe kingdom
1 CONT as a whole was considerably strengthened by Philip'sinstitution of a new class
1 CONT of administrative officers, the royal baillisand the seneschals for the
1 CONT provinces, who were appointed by the king tosupervise the conduct of the local
1 CONT prévôts (“provosts”), to give justicein his name, to collect the revenues of
1 CONT the domain for him, and to callup the armed forces, in addition to other
1 CONT duties.
1 CONT Philip II died on July 14, 1223. Knowing his own strength, he was thefirst of
1 CONT the Capetians not to have his eldest son crowned and associatedwith him during
1 CONT his lifetime; in fact, his conquests and stronggovernment made him the richest
1 CONT and most powerful king in Europe andprepared the way for France's greatness in
1 CONT the 13th century.
1 CONT
1 CONT To cite this page: "Philip II" Encyclopædia Britannica
