1 CONT Filip II August (fransk Philippe II Auguste) (født 21. august 1165 i Gonesse,
1 CONT død 14. juli 1223 i Mantes, begravd i klosterkirken Saint-Denis) var konge av
1 CONT Frankrike fra 1180 til sin død. Han var sønn av Ludvig VII av Frankrike og
1 CONT Adèle av Champagne. Under sitt styre befestet han huset Capets stilling i
1 CONT Frankrike og styrket kronens makt, bl.a. gjennom svekkelse av adelens
1 CONT stilling. Han klarte også å erobre de fleste engelske besittelsene i
1 CONT Frankrike.
1 CONT Filip II var gift med:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1180 med Isabella av Hainaut, (1170-1190).
1 CONT 1193 med Ingeborg av Danmark, fransk dronning, 1175/1176-1236.
1 CONT 1196 med Agnes av Meran, (?-1201).
1 CONT Hans sønn fra første ekteskap var Ludvig VIII av Frankrike, gift med Blanka av
1 CONT Kastilien. Fra andre ekteskap (muligens født i det tredje ekteskapet) hadde
1 CONT han sønnen Philip Hurepel. Dessuten hadde han en datter, Marie.
1 CONT Philip II (of France) (1165-1223), king of France (1180-1223), one of the
1 CONT most powerful European monarchs of the Middle Ages. His full name was
1 CONT Philip Augustus.
1 CONT
1 CONT The son of King Louis VII, Philip was born on August 21, 1165, in Gonesse,
1 CONT near Paris. He became coregent with his father in 1179. From 1181 to 1186
1 CONT Philip combated a coalition of barons in Flanders, Burgundy, and Champagne
1 CONT and at their expense increased the royal domain. Philip allied himself
1 CONT with Richard, duke of Aquitaine, who in 1189 became Richard I of England,
1 CONT and in 1190 the two kings embarked on the Third Crusade. The kings
1 CONT quarreled, however, and Philip returned to France in 1191. Allied with
1 CONT Holy Roman Emperor Henry VI and Richard's brother, John, later king of
1 CONT England, Philip attacked Richard's territories in France. Richard returned
1 CONT in 1194 and went to war against Philip. By the time of Richard's death in
1 CONT 1199, Philip had been forced to surrender most of the territory he had
1 CONT annexed. Philip subsequently warred against John, who became king of
1 CONT England in 1199; between 1202 and 1205 Philip more than doubled his
1 CONT territory by annexing Normandy, Maine, Brittany, Anjou, Touraine, and
1 CONT Poitou.
1 CONT
1 CONT A coalition of European powers, including England, challenged the growing
1 CONT power of France in 1214. Philip's forces, however, decisively defeated the
1 CONT coalition at the Battle of Bouvines, establishing France as a leading
1 CONT country of Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip increased the royal power not only by extending the royal domain
1 CONT but also by reducing the power of the feudal lords. He replaced the noble
1 CONT officers at court with an advisory council appointed from the middle class
1 CONT and supported the communes against the nobles. France prospered from his
1 CONT judicial, financial, and administrative reorganization of the government;
1 CONT serfdom declined, towns grew, and commerce flourished. Philip established
1 CONT Paris as the fixed capital of France, paved the streets, and had many new
1 CONT buildings constructed in the city.
