1 CONT (Research):Philip II Encyclopædia Britannica Article Early life and kingship
1 CONT Philip was the son of Louis VII of France and Adela of Champagne. In order to
1 CONT be associated as king with his father, who had fallen mortally ill, he was
1 CONT crowned at Reims on Nov. 1, 1179. His uncles of the House of Champagne_Henry
1 CONT I, count of Champagne; Guillaume, archbishop of Reims; and Thibaut V, count of
1 CONT Blois and Chartres_hoped to use the youthful king to control France. To escape
1 CONT from their tutelage, Philip, on April 28, 1180, married Isabella, the daughter
1 CONT of Baldwin V of Hainaut and the niece (through her mother) of Philip of
1 CONT Alsace, the count of Flanders, who promised to give the King the territory of
1 CONT Artois as her dowry. When Henry II of England arrived in Normandy, perhaps
1 CONT with the intention of responding to an appeal by the House of Champagne,
1 CONT Philip II entered into negotiations with him and, at Gisors on June 28, 1180,
1 CONT renewed an understanding that Louis VII had reached with him in 1177. As a
1 CONT result, the House of Champagne was politically isolated, and Philip II was
1 CONT making all decisions for himself and acting as he saw fit when his father
1 CONT died, on Sept. 18, 1180, leaving him sole king in name as well as in fact.
1 CONT When the Count of Flanders allied himself with the Champagne faction, there
1 CONT followed a serious revolt against the King. In the Peace of Boves, in July
1 CONT 1185 (confirmed by the Treaty of Gisors in May 1186), the King and the Count
1 CONT of Flanders composed their differences (which had been chiefly over possession
1 CONT of Vermandois, in Picardy), so that the disputed territory was partitioned,
1 CONT Amiens and numerous other places passing to the King and the remainder, with
1 CONT the county of Vermandois proper, being left provisionally to Philip of Alsace.
1 CONT Thenceforward the King was free to run against Henry II of England.
1 CONT Territorial expansion Henry's French possessions_the so-called Angevin Empire,
1 CONT consisting of Normandy, Maine, Anjou, and Touraine, with Aquitaine in the
1 CONT hands of his son, the future Richard I the Lion-Heart of England, and Brittany
1 CONT ruled by another son, Geoffrey (died 1186)_all were a constant menace to the
1 CONT French royal domain. Furthermore, there were long-standing disputes over the
1 CONT Vexin (between Normandy and the Ile-de-France), Berry, and Auvergne. Philip II
1 CONT launched an attack on Berry in the summer of 1187 but then in June made a
1 CONT truce with Henry, which left Issoudun in his hands and also granted him
1 CONT Fréteval, in Vendômois. Though the truce was for two years, Philip found
1 CONT grounds for resuming hostilities in the summer of 1188. He skillfully
1 CONT exploited the estrangement between Henry and Richard, and Richard did homage
1 CONT to him voluntarily at Bonmoulins in November 1188. Finally, by the Treaty of
1 CONT Azay-le-Rideau, or of Colombières (July 4, 1189), Henry was forced to renew
1 CONT his own homage, to confirm the cession of Issoudun, with Graçay also, to
1 CONT Philip, and to renounce his claim to suzerainty over Auvergne. Henry died two
1 CONT days later. Richard, who succeeded Henry as king of England, had already
1 CONT undertaken to go on crusade (the Third Crusade) against Saladin in the Holy
1 CONT Land, and Philip now did likewise. Before his departure, he made the so-called
1 CONT Testament of 1190 to provide for the government of his kingdom in his absence.
1 CONT On his way to Palestine, he met Richard in Sicily, where they promptly found
1 CONT themselves at variance, though they made a treaty at Messina in March 1191.
1 CONT Arriving in Palestine, they cooperated against the Muslims at Acre, until
1 CONT Philip fell ill and made his illness a pretext for returning to France, quite
1 CONT determined to settle the succession to Flanders (Philip of Alsace had just
1 CONT died on the crusade) while Richard was still absent. Thus, by the end of 1191,
1 CONT Philip II was back in France. In spite of promises he had made in the Holy
1 CONT Land, Philip at once prepared to attack the Plantagenet possessions in France.
1 CONT Informed of this, Richard also left the crusade but was taken prisoner while
1 CONT on his way back by the duke of Austria, Leopold V of Babenberg. Philip did
1 CONT everything he could to prolong his rival's captivity, but Richard was at last
1 CONT set free (1194) and went to war against Philip. The French king suffered a
1 CONT number of defeats (from that at Fréteval in July 1194 to that at Courcelles in
1 CONT September 1198) in a series of campaigns that were occasionally punctuated by
1 CONT negotiations. It was fortuitous for Philip, however, when Richard was killed
1 CONT in April 1199. Richard's brother John was by no means as formidable a fighter.
1 CONT Moreover, his right to Richard's succession could be contested by Arthur of
1 CONT Brittany, whose father had been senior to John. To secure the succession,
1 CONT therefore, John came to terms with Philip: by the Treaty of Le Goulet (May 22,
1 CONT 1200), in return for Philip's recognition of him as Richard's heir, he ceded
1 CONT Évreux and the Norman Vexin to Philip; agreed that Issoudun and Graçay should
1 CONT be the dowry of his niece Blanche of Castile, who was to marry the future
1 CONT Louis VIII (Philip's son by Isabella of Hainaut); and renounced any claim to
1 CONT suzerainty over Berry and Auvergne. Shortly afterward, however, John entered
1 CONT into conflict with the Lusignan family of Poitou (in Aquitaine), who appealed
1 CONT to Philip as overlord. When he was summoned to appear before the royal court
1 CONT as a vassal of the French crown, John did not present himself, and Philip, in
1 CONT April 1202, pronounced John's French fiefs forfeit and undertook to carry out
1 CONT the sentence himself. He invaded Normandy, overran the northeast, and laid
1 CONT siege to Arques, while Arthur of Brittany, the son of Geoffrey, who died some
1 CONT years before, campaigned against John's supporters in Poitou; but John,
1 CONT marching south from Maine, captured Arthur at Mirebeau (August 1). In fury,
1 CONT Philip abandoned the siege of Arques and marched southwestward to Tours,
1 CONT ravaging John's territory on his way before returning to Paris. Guillaume des
1 CONT Roches, the powerful seneschal of Anjou, who had taken John's side, came to
1 CONT terms with Philip in March 1203. Resuming operations against Normandy, Philip
1 CONT occupied the towns around the great fortress of Château-Gaillard, to which he
1 CONT laid siege in September 1203, having overruled Pope Innocent III's attempts to
1 CONT mediate. John, who is reported to have murdered Arthur of Brittany in April,
1 CONT retired to England in December, and Château-Gaillard fell to Philip in March
1 CONT 1204. Rouen, the Norman capital, surrendered in June, after 40 days'
1 CONT resistance. After his conquest of Normandy, Philip subdued Maine, Touraine,
1 CONT Anjou, and most of Poitou with less difficulty (1204-05), though the castles
1 CONT of Loches and Chinon held out for a year. He sought to secure his conquests by
1 CONT lavishing privileges on the towns and on the religious houses but otherwise
1 CONT left the local barons in power. Unrest, however, was endemic in Poitou, and in
1 CONT June 1206 John landed at La Rochelle. After a campaign in the south, he turned
1 CONT north toward the Loire. At Thouars in October 1206, he and Philip made a two-
1 CONT year truce, leaving John in possession of the reconquered Poitevin lands. In
1 CONT the following year, however, Philip invaded Poitou again; and, after a further
1 CONT campaign in 1208, only the south and part of the west of Poitou remained loyal
1 CONT to John (with Saintonge, Guyenne, and Gascony). Philip next hoped to exploit
1 CONT the dispute between John and Pope Innocent III. While Innocent was threatening
1 CONT to declare John unfit to reign (1212), plans were being made for a French
1 CONT landing in England and for the accession of Philip's son Louis to the English
1 CONT throne. The plans had to be dropped when John made his submission to the Pope
1 CONT (1213). Throwing himself into schemes for revenge, John formed a coalition
1 CONT against France: the Holy Roman emperor Otto IV, the Count of Flanders
1 CONT (Ferrand, or Ferdinand, of Portugal), and the Count of Boulogne (Raynald, or
1 CONT Renaud, of Dammartin) were to invade the Capetian territory from the northeast
1 CONT while John attacked from the west, with the help of his Poitevin barons. John
1 CONT landed at La Rochelle in February 1214 and advanced into Anjou but was put to
1 CONT flight by Louis at La Roche-aux-Moines on July 2; his confederates were
1 CONT completely defeated by Philip in the decisive Battle of Bouvines on July 27.
1 CONT The Anglo-Angevin power in France and the coalition had both been broken in
1 CONT one month. Thus Philip, who, in 1213, had transferred Brittany to his cousin
1 CONT Peter of Dreux, was left without any significant opposition to his rule in
1 CONT France. It was not only at the Plantagenets' expense that Philip enlarged the
1 CONT royal domain. His claim to Artois through his first marriage and his gains by
1 CONT the settlement of 1185-86 have been mentioned above, and he subsequently
1 CONT proceeded, step by step, to acquire the rest of Vermandois and Valois. His
1 CONT insistence on his suzerainty over vacant fiefs and on his tutelage over minors
1 CONT and heiresses was particularly effective with regard to Flanders, where two
1 CONT successive Flemish counts, Philip of Alsace (died 1191) and Baldwin IX (died
1 CONT c. 1205) had left no male issue. Though he did not personally take part in the
1 CONT crusade proclaimed by Pope Innocent III against a Cathari religious sect in
1 CONT Languedoc, Philip allowed his vassals and knights to carry it out. Simon de
1 CONT Montfort's capture of Béziers and Carcassonne (1209) and his victory at Muret
1 CONT over Raymond VI of Toulouse and Peter II of Aragon (1213) prepared the way for
1 CONT the eventual annexation of eastern Languedoc to the royal domain six years
1 CONT after Philip's death and for the union of northern and southern France under
1 CONT Capetian rule. continued Philip II Encyclopædia Britannica Article Internal
1 CONT affairs Several years before he tried to take advantage of the papacy's
1 CONT quarrel with John of England, Philip had himself been in dispute with Rome.
1 CONT After the death (1190) of Isabella of Hainaut, he had married Ingeborg, sister
1 CONT of the Danish king Canute IV, on Aug. 14, 1193, and on the next day, for a
1 CONT private reason, had resolved to separate from her. Having procured the
1 CONT annulment of his marriage by an assembly of bishops in November 1193, he took
1 CONT a Tirolese lady, Agnes, daughter of Bertold IV of Meran, as his wife in June
1 CONT 1196. Denmark, meanwhile, had complained to Rome about the repudiation of
1 CONT Ingeborg, and Pope Celestine III had countermanded it in 1195; but Celestine
1 CONT died (1198) before he could resort to coercion against Philip. The next pope,
1 CONT Innocent III, was sterner: in January 1200 he imposed an interdict on France.
1 CONT Philip, therefore, in September 1200, had to submit, pretending to be
1 CONT reconciled with Ingeborg. In fact, he refused to cohabit with her and kept her
1 CONT in semicaptivity until 1213, when he accepted her beside him_not as his wife
1 CONT but at least as his queen. Agnes had died in 1201, after bearing two children
1 CONT to Philip: Marie, countess of Namur (1211) and duchess of Brabant (1213), by
1 CONT successive marriages; and Philip, called Hurepel, count of Clermont.
1 CONT Throughout his reign, Philip kept a close watch over the French nobility,
1 CONT which he brought effectively to heel. He maintained excellent relations with
1 CONT the French clergy, leaving the canons of the cathedral chapters free to elect
1 CONT their bishops and favouring the monastic orders. He knew, too, how to win the
1 CONT support of the towns, granting privileges and liberties to merchants and
1 CONT frequently aiding their struggles to free themselves from the seignorial
1 CONT authority of the nobles. In return, the communes helped financially and
1 CONT militarily. Most of all, Philip gave his attention to Paris, not only
1 CONT fortifying it with a great rampart but also having its streets and
1 CONT thoroughfares put in order. For the countryside, he multiplied the number of
1 CONT villes neuves ("new towns"), or enfranchised communities. The Capetian
1 CONT monarchy's hold on the huge royal domain as well as on the kingdom as a whole
1 CONT was considerably strengthened by Philip's institution of a new class of
1 CONT administrative officers, the royal baillis and the seneschals for the
1 CONT provinces, who were appointed by the king to supervise the conduct of the
1 CONT local prévôts ("provosts"), to give justice in his name, to collect the
1 CONT revenues of the domain for him, and to call up the armed forces, in addition
1 CONT to other duties. Conclusion. Philip II died on July 14, 1223. Knowing his own
1 CONT strength, he was the first of the Capetians not to have his eldest son crowned
1 CONT and associated with him during his lifetime; in fact, his conquests and strong
1 CONT government made him the richest and most powerful king in Europe and prepared
1 CONT the way for France's greatness in the 13th century. Philippe II August, King
1 CONT of France 1180-1223, (1165-1223) Born 22 August 1165 Gonesse Died 14 July 1223
1 CONT Mantes Married (1) 28 April 1180 Bapaume Isabelle of Flanders, Countess of
1 CONT Artois, daughter of Baudouin V-VIII, Count of Flanders & Hainault and
1 CONT Margarethe of Flanders Born April 1170 Valenciennes Died 15 March 1190 Paris
1 CONT Married (2) 15 August 1193 Amiens (Div.5-11-1193) Ingeborg (Isambour) of
1 CONT Denmark, daughter of Valdemar I den Store, King of Denmark 1157-1182 and Sofie
1 CONT of Polock Born 1175 Died 29 July 1236 Corbeil Buried Corbeil Married (3) June
1 CONT 1196 (forced to divorce in 1200) Agnes de Meran, daughter of Berthold VI von
1 CONT Andechs, Duke of Meran and Dalmatia and Agnes von Nieder-Lausitz Born 1180
1 CONT Died 29 July 1201 Chateau Poissy After having lost his child-wife, Isabelle of
1 CONT Flanders, he went on crusade, then hurried back to marry again for the sake of
1 CONT his dynasty as his son, Louis, was a sickly child. What he needed was the
1 CONT daughter of a king and, on 14 August 1193, he married Ingeborg (Isambour),
1 CONT daughter of King Valdemar of Denmark. Arrangements had been made for her to be
1 CONT crowned queen the day after the nuptials but, during the wedding night,
1 CONT Philippe's feelings changed to repulsion. In Compiegne, before an assembly,
1 CONT fifteen duly sworn witnesses, twelve of them from the king's family, solemnly
1 CONT calculated the degrees of consanguinity and showed that Philippe and Ingeborg
1 CONT were fourth cousins, a prohibiting degree for marriage. However, this solution
1 CONT was not accepted by Ingeborg's brother, the Danish king, who appealed to Pope
1 CONT Celestine III, claiming the genealogies to be wrong, but the pope gave
1 CONT Philippe no more than a warning. In June 1196, Philippe III married the
1 CONT beautiful Agnes de Meran. With Ingeborg still alive, this was bigamy. The new
1 CONT pope, Innocent III, ordered Philippe to part from Agnes and, laying France
1 CONT under an interdict, wanted to suspend all religious services. Negotiations
1 CONT were to last fifteen years and, because of the Cathar upsurge, the interdict
1 CONT was not applied. In 1201 in Soissons, the church confronted Philippe but,
1 CONT after a fortnight's arguing, he departed, taking Ingeborg with him. On 29 July
1 CONT 1201 Agnes de Meran died and Philippe could no longer be regarded as a
1 CONT bigamist; and so, in November of that year, the pope legitimised the two
1 CONT children of Philippe and Agnes. In 1205 a 'damsel from Arras' bore him a
1 CONT bastard son and, as Philippe would have nothing to do with Ingeborg, she was
1 CONT spared the perils of childbearing. As it had not been consummated, the pope
1 CONT was willing to declare the marriage with Ingeborg void. However, they had not
1 CONT counted on Ingeborg who maintained that she and Philippe had slept together.
1 CONT To satisfy pope, king and queen, the only solution seemed to be that the queen
1 CONT should take the veil and enter a convent; but then, in April 1213, Philippe
1 CONT announced he was taking back his wife. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Name Prefix: King Name Suffix: Ii, Of France
