1 CONT
1 CONT Interred
1 CONT St. Denis, France
1 CONT Basic Life Information
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus (French: Philippe Auguste) was the King of France from 1180
1 CONT until his death. A member of the House of Capet, Philip Augustus was born at
1 CONT Gonesse in the Val-d'Oise, the son of Louis VII and his third wife, Adela of
1 CONT Champagne. He was originally nicknamed Dieudonné - the God-given - as he was
1 CONT the first son of Louis VII late in his father's life.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip was one of the most successful medieval French monarchs in expanding
1 CONT the royal demesne and the influence of the monarchy. He broke up the great
1 CONT Angevin Empire and defeated a coalition of his rivals (German, Flemish and
1 CONT English) at the Battle of Bouvines in 1214. He reorganized the government,
1 CONT bringing financial stability to the country and thus making possible a sharp
1 CONT increase in prosperity. His reign was popular with ordinary people because he
1 CONT checked the power of the nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle
1 CONT class
1 CONT
1 CONT Crusade
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip went on the Third Crusade (1189-1192) with Richard I of England
1 CONT (1189-99) and the Holy Roman Emperor, Frederick I Barbarossa (1155-90). His
1 CONT army left Vézelay on July 1, 1190. At first the French and English crusaders
1 CONT traveled together, but the armies split at Lyons, as Richard decided to go by
1 CONT sea, and Philip took the overland route through the Alps to Genoa. The French
1 CONT and English armies were reunited in Messina, where they wintered together. On
1 CONT March 30, 1191 the French set sail for the Holy Land and Philip arrived on May
1 CONT 20. He then marched up to Acre which was already besieged by a lesser
1 CONT contingent of crusaders and started to construct large siege equipments before
1 CONT Richard arrived in June 8 (see Siege of Acre). By the time Acre surrendered on
1 CONT July 12, Philip was severely ill with dysentery which reduced his crusading
1 CONT zeal. Ties with Richard were further strained after the latter acted in a
1 CONT haughty manner after Acre had fallen. More importantly, the siege resulted in
1 CONT the death of Philip of Alsace, who held the county of Vermandois proper; an
1 CONT event that threatened to derail the Treaty of Gisors which Philip had
1 CONT orchestrated to isolate the powerful Blois-Champagne faction. Philip decided
1 CONT to return to France to settle the issue of succession in Flanders, a decision
1 CONT that displeased Richard, who said, "It is a shame and a disgrace on my lord if
1 CONT he goes away without having finished the business that brought him hither. But
1 CONT still, if he finds himself in bad health, or is afraid lest he should die
1 CONT here, his will be done." So on July 31, 1191 the French army of 10,000 men
1 CONT (along with 5,000 silver marks to pay the soldiers) remained in Outremer under
1 CONT the command of Hugh III, duke of Burgundy. Philip and his cousin Peter of
1 CONT Courtenay, count of Nevers, made their way to Genoa and from there returned to
1 CONT France. This decision to return was also fuelled by the realization that with
1 CONT Richard campaigning in the Holy Land, English possessions in northern France
1 CONT (Normandy) would be open for attack. After Richard's delayed return home after
1 CONT the Third Crusade, war between England and France would ensue over possession
1 CONT of English-controlled territories in modern-day France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriages and Children
1 CONT
1 CONT King Philip II married Isabelle of Hainaut, daughter of Baldwin V, Count of
1 CONT Hainaut and Countess Margaret I of Flanders on 28 April 1180 at Bapaume. She
1 CONT brought as her dowry the county of Artois. The marriage was arranged by her
1 CONT maternal uncle Count Philip of Alsace who was advisor to the King. They had
1 CONT one surviving child:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis VIII
1 CONT
1 CONT After Isabelle's early death in childbirth, in 1190, Philip decided to marry
1 CONT again. On August 15, 1193 he married Ingeborg (1175-1236), daughter of King
1 CONT Valdemar I of Denmark (1157-82). She was renamed Isambour, and Stephan of
1 CONT Dornik described her as "very kind, young of age but old of wisdom." For some
1 CONT unknown reason, Philip was repelled by her, and he refused to allow her to be
1 CONT crowned Queen. Ingeborg protested at this treatment; his response was to
1 CONT confine her to a convent. He then asked Pope Celestine III for an annulment on
1 CONT the grounds of non-consummation. Philip had not reckoned with Ingeborg,
1 CONT however; she insisted that the marriage had been consummated, and that she was
1 CONT his wife and the rightful Queen of France. The Franco-Danish churchman William
1 CONT of Paris intervened on the side of Ingeborg, drawing up a genealogy of the
1 CONT Danish kings to disprove the alleged impediment of consanguinity.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime Philip had sought a new bride. Initially agreement had been
1 CONT reached for him to marry Marguerite of Geneva, daughter of William I, Count of
1 CONT Geneva, but the young bride's journey to Paris was interrupted by Thomas I of
1 CONT Savoy, who kidnapped Philip's intended new queen and married her instead,
1 CONT claiming that Philip was already bound in marriage. Philip finally achieved a
1 CONT third marriage, on May 7, 1196, to Agnes of Merania from Dalmatia (c. 1180 -
1 CONT July 29, 1201). Their children were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Marie (1198 - October 15, 1224)
1 CONT Philippe Hurepel (1200-1234), Count of Clermont and eventually, by marriage,
1 CONT Count of Boulogne
1 CONT
1 CONT Pope Innocent III (1198-1216) declared Philip Augustus's marriage to Agnes of
1 CONT Merania null and void, as he was still married to Ingeborg. He ordered the
1 CONT King to part from Agnès; when he did not, the Pope placed France under an
1 CONT interdict in 1199. This continued until September 7, 1200. Due to pressure
1 CONT from the Pope and from Ingeborg's brother, King Valdemar II of Denmark
1 CONT (1202-41), Philip finally took Ingeborg back as his Queen in 1213.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus died July 14, 1223 at Mantes and was interred in Saint
1 CONT Denis Basilica. Philip's son by Isabelle de Hainaut, Louis VIII, was his
1 CONT successor.
1 CONT First of the great Capetian kings of medeval France, he gradually reconquered
1 CONT the French territories held by the kings of England, extending royal domains
1 CONT northward. He was a major figure in the Third Crusade to the Holy Land in
1 CONT 1191\. He was the first of the Capetians not to have his eldest son crowned
1 CONT and associated with him during his lifetime. His conquests and strong
1 CONT government made him the richest and most powerful king in Europe and prepared
1 CONT the way for France's greatness in the 13th century.
1 CONT First of the great Capetian kings of medeval France, he gradually reconquered
1 CONT the French territories held by the kings of England, extending royal domains
1 CONT northward. He was a major figure in the Third Crusade to the Holy Land in
1 CONT 1191\. He was the first of the Capetians not to have his eldest son crowned
1 CONT and associated with him during his lifetime. His conquests and strong
1 CONT government made him the richest and most powerful king in Europe and prepared
1 CONT the way for France's greatness in the 13th century.
1 CONT First of the great Capetian kings of medeval France, he gradually reconquered
1 CONT the French territories held by the kings of England, extending royal domains
1 CONT northward. He was a major figure in the Third Crusade to the Holy Land in
1 CONT 1191\. He was the first of the Capetians not to have his eldest son crowned
1 CONT and associated with him during his lifetime. His conquests and strong
1 CONT government made him the richest and most powerful king in Europe and prepared
1 CONT the way for France's greatness in the 13th century.
1 CONT First of the great Capetian kings of medeval France, he gradually reconquered
1 CONT the French territories held by the kings of England, extending royal domains
1 CONT northward. He was a major figure in the Third Crusade to the Holy Land in
1 CONT 1191\. He was the first of the Capetians not to have his eldest son crowned
1 CONT and associated with him during his lifetime. His conquests and strong
1 CONT government made him the richest and most powerful king in Europe and prepared
1 CONT the way for France's greatness in the 13th century.
1 CONT Philip II or Philip Augustus,1165–1223, king of France (1180–1223), son of
1 CONT Louis VII. During his reign the royal domains were more than doubled, and the
1 CONT royal power was consolidated at the expense of the feudal lords. Philip
1 CONT defeated a coalition of Flanders, Burgundy, and Champagne (1181–86), securing
1 CONT Amiens, Artois, and part of Vermandois from the count of Flanders. He then
1 CONT attacked (1187) the English territories in France. Allied (Nov., 1188) with
1 CONT Richard, the rebellious son of King Henry II of England, Philip compelled
1 CONT Henry to cede several territories to him. After Henry's death (1189), Philip
1 CONT and Richard, now king of England (see Richard I), left (1190) on the Third
1 CONT Crusade (see Crusades). They soon quarreled, and after the capture of Acre
1 CONT (see Akko) Philip returned (1191) to France. Richard also left the crusade but
1 CONT was captured on his way home by Leopold V of Austria. During Richard's
1 CONT captivity (1192–94), Philip conspired against him with Richard's brother John.
1 CONT After his release Richard made war (1194–99) on Philip, compelling him to
1 CONT surrender most of his annexations. When John acceded to the English throne on
1 CONT Richard's death (1199), Philip espoused the cause of Arthur I of Brittany and
1 CONT invaded John's French domains, forcing him to surrender (1204) Normandy,
1 CONT Brittany, Anjou, Maine, and Touraine. Philip later conquered Poitou. In 1214,
1 CONT at Bouvines, the French defeated the allied forces of John, Holy Roman Emperor
1 CONT Otto IV, and the count of Flanders; it was a victory that established France
1 CONT as a leading European power. When the English barons revolted against John
1 CONT (1215), they invited Philip's son Louis (later Louis VIII of France) to invade
1 CONT England and take the English throne; the venture failed.
1 CONT During Philip's reign the pope proclaimed the Crusade against the Albigenses.
1 CONT Although Philip did not participate directly in the crusade, he allowed his
1 CONT vassals to do so. Their victories prepared the ground for the annexation of S
1 CONT France by King Louis IX. In internal affairs Philip's most important reform
1 CONT was the creation of a class of salaried administrative officers, the baillis
1 CONT [bailiffs], to supervise local administration of the domain. Philip also
1 CONT systematized the collection of customs, tolls, fines, and fees due to the
1 CONT crown. He supported the towns of France against the royal barons, thereby
1 CONT increasing their power and prosperity. In Paris, he continued the construction
1 CONT of Notre-Dame de Paris, built the first Louvre, paved the main streets, and
1 CONT walled the city.
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT Philip II (French: Philippe II), called Philip Augustus (French:Philippe
1 CONT Auguste) (August 21, 1165 - July 14, 1223), was King ofFrance from 1180 to
1 CONT 1223.
1 CONT
1 CONT A member of the Capetian dynasty, Philip Augustus was born August 21,1165 at
1 CONT Gonesse, Val-d'Oise, France, the son of Louis VII of Franceand his third wife,
1 CONT Adèle of Champagne. In declining health, hisfather had him crowned at Reims in
1 CONT 1179.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was married on April 28, 1180 to Isabelle of Hainaut and they hadone son,
1 CONT Louis (later King Louis VIII), seven years later. A few yearsafter Isabelle's
1 CONT passing, on August 15, 1193 he married Ingeborg ofDenmark (1175-1236). The
1 CONT marriage produced no children and ended indivorce. Philip Augustus married for
1 CONT a third time on May 7, 1196 toPrincess Agnès of Méranie (c.1180 - July 29,
1 CONT 1201). Their childrenwere:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1) Philippe Hurepel (1200 - 1234)
1 CONT 2) Marie (1198 - October 15, 1224)
1 CONT As king, he would become one of the most successful in consolidatingFrance
1 CONT into one royal domain. He seized the territories of Maine,Touraine, Anjou,
1 CONT Brittany, and all of Normandy from King John ofEngland. His decisive victory
1 CONT at the Battle of Bouvines over King Johnand a coalition of forces that
1 CONT included Otto IV of Germany ended theimmediate threat of challenges to this
1 CONT expansion (1214) and leftPhilip Augustus as the most powerful monarch in all
1 CONT of Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT He reorganized the government, bringing to the country a financialstability
1 CONT which permitted a sharp increase in prosperity. His reignwas popular with
1 CONT ordinary people when he checked the power the noblesand passed some of it on
1 CONT to the growing middle class his reign hadcreated.
1 CONT
1 CONT He went on the Third Crusade with Richard the Lionhearted and the HolyRoman
1 CONT Emperor, Frederick I Barbarossa (1189-1192).
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip Augustus would play a significant role in one of the greatestcenturies
1 CONT of innovation in construction and in education. With Parisas his capital, he
1 CONT had the main thoroughfares paved, built a centralmarket, Les Halles, continued
1 CONT the construction begun in 1163 of theGothic Notre-Dame de Paris Cathedral,
1 CONT constructed the Louvre as afortress and gave a charter to the University of
1 CONT Paris (the Sorbonne)in 1200. Under his guidance, Paris became the first city
1 CONT of teachersthe medieval world had known.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip Augustus died July 14, 1223 at Mantes and was interred in SaintDenis
1 CONT Basilica. He was succeeded by his son by Isabelle of Hainaut,Louis VIII.
1 CONT At least one souce indicates that Philllippe was born in Paris, rathe r than
1 CONT at Gonesse. He was originally nicknamed Dieudonné 'God-given' . It is reported
1 CONT that he gained the name 'Augustus' for his capacity to enlarge and augment the
1 CONT size of his realm. As a youth, he was corp ulant, with vitality and very
1 CONT combative. At the time he came to the t hrone, he is described as 'short in
1 CONT stature, stocky, with a red face , unkept hair and primitive notions of
1 CONT personal hygiene' with little t ime for education and no knowledge of Latin.
1 CONT He proved to be no matc h for either Henry II or his son Richard when it came
1 CONT to military know ledge or as a warrior. By tempermant and choice he was a
1 CONT diplomat. H e is described as a hypochondriac with little or no sense of
1 CONT humor, h aving 'a fastidious fear of injury and disease'. He also possessed a
1 CONT burning sense of ambition. As a youth, he tried to free himself of th e
1 CONT tutlage of his mothers brothers. He was a political realist and pra gmatist,
1 CONT much more astute than his father, and is written of as the gr eat king of the
1 CONT Capetian dynasty. He came to the throne as a minor, a nd after a reign of
1 CONT forty-three years he left the house of Capet the r ichest in Europe. Phillippe
1 CONT is also styled as Count of Artois. He wa s the first of the Capetian Kings not
1 CONT to involve his wife in the gover nment of the realm. Starting during the reign
1 CONT of Phillippe, the roya l archives were deposited in Paris, and the royal
1 CONT treasury was thereaf ter kept at the Paris Temple under the guard of the
1 CONT Knights Templars.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1179, Louis VII, in the tradition of his forefathers going back to Hugh
1 CONT Capet, had his son Phillippe crowned king to assure his smooth su ccession.
1 CONT Phillippe ordered new city walls for the city of Paris and stone pavements. He
1 CONT was shrewd and eager for power and an unscrupulou s politician. On 1 November,
1 CONT Guillaume aux Blanches Mains, Archbisho p of Rheims, crowned and anointed the
1 CONT fourteen year-old prince in the cathedral there. His father died on 18
1 CONT September 1180. While the roya l power had been increased under Philip I and
1 CONT Louis VI, under Louis VI I it had diminished slightly. The first few years of
1 CONT his reign were m arked by bitter disputes with the Lords of Champagne, Blois
1 CONT and Flande rs and as such, he was happy to have Henry II as an ally during
1 CONT these years. In 1180, Phillippe's uncle Henry de Champagne took up arms in an
1 CONT attempt to gain control of the French realm during Phillippes youth . In June
1 CONT of 1180, Phillippe met with Henry II of England, joined for ces against Henry
1 CONT de Champagne and renewed the peace of 1177. As such , Phillippe's uncle Henry
1 CONT de Champagne quickly withdrew his forces. The first great fief that was
1 CONT brought to heel was Flanders at the ver y start of the reign of Phillippe.
1 CONT Another implementation of Phillipp e's early reign was that he created a new
1 CONT class of royal administrato r strictly responsible to him alone. He also would
1 CONT during his reign p ay a great deal of attentipon to his capital city Paris. He
1 CONT built ne w walls, began to pave the streets and began the structure that
1 CONT eventu ally became the Louvere and continued construction of a cathedral - No
1 CONT tre Dame the cornerstone having been laid by his father Louis VII.
1 CONT
1 CONT Phillippes major ambition was however the destruction of the Angevin e mpire,
1 CONT and as such he continued to support the son's of Henry II again st their
1 CONT father. From the beginning of his reign, Phillippe began th e harassment of
1 CONT the Jews, and in April 1182, expelled Jews from Franc e and confiscated their
1 CONT goods. The reasons given were, of course, a me re pretense to allow the crown
1 CONT to aggrandise itself at the expense of an unpopular sect of the population.
1 CONT Since 1181, conflict had been on going with the count of Flanders, Philippe of
1 CONT Alsace. Philip managed t o counter the ambitions of the count by breaking his
1 CONT alliances with He nry I, Duke of Brabant, and Philipp von Heinsberg,
1 CONT Archbishop of Colog ne. In 1183, Henry II of England and Phillippe met and
1 CONT discussed a re alignment of the Angevin territories. In July 1185, the Treaty
1 CONT of Bov esconfirmed to the king the possession of the Vermandois, Artois, and
1 CONT Amiénois. Philip also began to war with the Henry II of England, who was also
1 CONT count of Anjou and duke of Aquitaine in France; two years of combat
1 CONT (1186-1188) followed, but the situation remained unchanged. Phi lip initially
1 CONT allied and worked with the young sons of Henry, Richard and John, who were in
1 CONT rebellion against their father. The death of Hen ry and the fall of Jerusalem
1 CONT in 1187 diverted attention from the Franc o-English war.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his reign the royal domains were more than doubled, and the roy al
1 CONT power was consolidated at the expense of the feudal lords. In 1181 , Phillippe
1 CONT was supported by Henry, Richard and Geoffrey (sons of Henr y II) in a war
1 CONT against Philip de Alsace - count of Flanders. After He nry, 'the young King',
1 CONT had his requests turned down by his father in 1 182, Henry made his way to
1 CONT Paris and the court of Phillippe of France . There, Phillippe lent a
1 CONT sympathetic ear to young Henry's requests . Philip defeated a coalition of
1 CONT Flanders, Burgundy, and Champagne (1 181-86), securing Amiens, Artois, and
1 CONT part of Vermandois from the coun t of Flanders. He then attacked (1187) the
1 CONT English territories in Fran ce. Specifically, Phillippe concentrated his
1 CONT efforts in the area of B erry where he beseiged both Richard and John at
1 CONT Chateurox. By the tim e that Henry, 'the young King' died in 1183, the Norman
1 CONT Vexin passed t o Phillippe's half sister Alice who was then still betrothed to
1 CONT Richar d, then Prince of England. As Richard showed no interest in the marri
1 CONT age, Phillippe demanded that Alice and her dowry be returned to the co urt of
1 CONT France. Henry II however was loath to part with Alice.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1186, Phillippe gained the Vermandois, the county of Montdidier, To urette
1 CONT and Choisy and Amiens, augmented by Roye. The rest of Vermando is went by
1 CONT arrangement to Eleanor de Vermandois. In 1186, at the tim e of Geoffrey (son
1 CONT of Henry II), Phillippe took the side of Constance of Brittany and her son
1 CONT Arthur against henry II of England. Initiall y he supported Arthurs claim to
1 CONT the English throne, but later abandone d Arthur at teh Peace of Le Goulet on
1 CONT 22 May 1200. In 1187, Phillipp e marched into Berry and took Chateauraux.
1 CONT Richard and Henry II joine d forces to resist Phillip. On 23 June 1187 Henry
1 CONT II and Phillippe re ached a truce at Chateauraux (ref 'Ralph of Diceto').
1 CONT However Richar d soon deserted his father again and marched to Paris and
1 CONT allied himse lf with Phillip. In June of 1188, Phillippe again attacked
1 CONT Richard th e Lionheart's border strongholds in Touraine and near Berry. He
1 CONT also captured Chateaurous on 16 June 1188. In Nov 1188, he allied with Ric
1 CONT hard, the rebellious son of King Henry II of England, Philip compelle d Henry
1 CONT to cede several territories to him. After 1188, there was a g rowing sense of
1 CONT distrust between Henry II and Phillippe. At La Ferte- Bernard in June 1189,
1 CONT Phillippe demanded again that Henry II give up A lice, so that she and Richard
1 CONT could be married. After the death of He nry II, Phillippe soon developed
1 CONT almost a savage hatred of Richard.
1 CONT
1 CONT Phillippe soon abandoned the policies previously so successful for th e
1 CONT Capetian dynasty. He ceased to put himself forward as a champion o f the law.
1 CONT He ignored solemn promises he made to Henry II and to Rich ard. He violated
1 CONT feudal and canon law. After Henry's death (1189), P hilip and Richard, now
1 CONT king of England met at Vezelay on 1 April 1190 so as to arrange the logistics
1 CONT for traveling to the Holy Land on crusa de together. Phillippe, rather half-
1 CONT heartedly and reluctantly, joine d Richard in the fervor to make a crusade. As
1 CONT such Phillippe laid a n ew tax on his people - the 'Saladin tithe', which in
1 CONT time became the f orerunner of modern French taxatiation policy. During his
1 CONT absence, Ph illippe appointed a Council of Regency that included six burghers
1 CONT to r ule the realm in his absence. Together, Richard and Phillippe set ou t
1 CONT for the Holy Land from the area of Tours on 4 July 1190. Richard an d
1 CONT Phillippe followed different routes towards the Mediterranean. Phil lippe made
1 CONT his way to Genoa and contracted with the Genoese republic t o move his army
1 CONT across the Mediterranean. He arrived in Sicily in th e middle of September
1 CONT 1190.
1 CONT
1 CONT Phillippe had arrived at Sicily prior to Richard, and in conjunction w ith
1 CONT Tancred prevented Eleanor d'Aquitaine and Berengaria from landing at Sicily
1 CONT and forced them to land instead at Brendisi. While in Sicil y, Phillippe and
1 CONT Richard quarreled endlessly. Phillippe set sail fro m Sicily on 30 March 1191
1 CONT for Palestine. Phillippe landed with his tr oops in the environs of Acre on
1 CONT about 20 April 1191 at which time he t ook control of the army and began to
1 CONT reorganize the faltering seige o f Leopold. He was followed at the beginning
1 CONT of June 1191 by Richard t he Lionheart. Phillippe, against Richards advice,
1 CONT put forward an atta ck on Acre which proved to be a failure and with that
1 CONT disasterous even t, he lost any effective chance he had to resume a leadership
1 CONT role fo r the crusade. After the defenders of Acre were defeated, the city wa
1 CONT s partitioned between Richard and Phillippe. Phillippe took possessio n of the
1 CONT former palace of the Knights Templar. On 22 July 1191, afte r quarrelling with
1 CONT Richard, Phillippe announced that due to malaria h e was too ill to continue
1 CONT on with the crusade and would return to Fran ce. At the time, Phillippe had
1 CONT lent his support to Conrad de Montferr at as King of Jerusalem. He soon
1 CONT developed into a cynical and distrus tful man. On 31 July 1191, with Conrad of
1 CONT Montferrat Phillippe saile d first for Tyre and subsequently embarked for
1 CONT Brindisi. He made his way to Otranto and made the rest of the trip by land. In
1 CONT Rome, the Po pe released Phillippe from his oath as a crusader. He did leave
1 CONT his a rmy under the command of Hugh of Burgundy. Richard didn't what him to
1 CONT leave with the fear that Phillippe would take advantage of him not bei ng in
1 CONT France to protect his holdings. Philip was a great administrato r as he had
1 CONT been King of France for 8 years before he went to the crus ade. On his way
1 CONT home, Phillippe met with Henry VI - Holy Roman Empero r and discussed what to
1 CONT do about Richard once he returned from the cru sade.
1 CONT
1 CONT Richard also left the crusade but was captured on his way home by Leop old V
1 CONT of Austria. Phillippe was notified of Richards capture by Henr y VI - Holy
1 CONT Roman Emperor. Phillippe quickly urged Henry to keep Rich ard in close
1 CONT confinement. During Richard's captivity (1192-94), Philli ppe initially tried
1 CONT to buy the person of Richard, failing in that ambi tion he sought to pay
1 CONT Leopold to have Richard released into his hand . He continued to conspire
1 CONT against Richard with Richard's brother Joh n. In March of 1193, Phillippe
1 CONT urgently requested Henry VI - Holy Rom an Emperor not to release Richard after
1 CONT his trial at Speyer. On 12 Ap ril 1193, after invading Normandie with great
1 CONT success, Phillippe took Gisors and overran the Vixen. Having siezed Neaufles,
1 CONT he marched on R ouen on 23 April 1193 where he joined Flemish forces led by
1 CONT Baldwin VI I of Flanders (Baldwin de Hainault II) and demanded its surrender
1 CONT as w ell as the return of his sister Alice, held there in confinement by El
1 CONT eanor - dowager Queen of England. Phillippe also sought to have John marry the
1 CONT Princess Alice still at Winchester. At Rouen, Robert de Bea umont -3rd Earl
1 CONT Leicester refused to surrender Rouen to Phillippe and he subsequently marched
1 CONT back to Paris. Some of his forces did advanc e as far as Dippe, on the
1 CONT channel.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip married on August 15, 1193 (2) Ingeborg (Ingeburge or Isambour) ) of
1 CONT Denmark, sister of King Chanute VI. of Denmark. She was born in 1 175, died in
1 CONT 1236, but that marriage lasted but one day. For some unkn own reason, Philip
1 CONT totally rejected her after the first night together , and he had her shut up
1 CONT in a nunnery and later put in prison, attempt ing to obtain a divorced decree,
1 CONT in order to remarry. There were no ch ildren. On about 8 January 1193,
1 CONT Phillippe was notified of Richard's capture by envoys from Henry VI - Holy
1 CONT Roman Emperor. Between his sep aration from Ingebourg and his relationship
1 CONT with Agnes de Meran, Phill ippe set his eyes on Constance of Hohenstaufen, a
1 CONT cousin of Henry VI - Holy Roman Emperor. To his rage, he discovered that she
1 CONT had marrie d Henry of Brunswick, son and heir of Henry - the Lion of Saxony.
1 CONT
1 CONT In about January of 1194, it is reported that Phillippe of France and John
1 CONT Lackland outbid Eleanor d'Aquitaine for the person of Richard I, so as to
1 CONT continue his confinement. Phillippe was still intent on th e capture of Roeun
1 CONT and the liberation of Alice (Alys) of France. Some time after May of 1194, he
1 CONT laid siege to Verneuil, but quickly abandon ed the siege in the face of the
1 CONT threat posed by Richards return to th e area of Bayeux and Caen. Richard I
1 CONT made war on Phillippe, compellin g him to surrender most of his annexations.
1 CONT In June of 1194, Phillipp e lost a decisive battle to Richard I at the battle
1 CONT of Freteval and ca me close to being captured. On 23 July 1194, the church
1 CONT negotiated a truce between Phillippe and Richard until November of 1195. By
1 CONT the su mmer of 1195, Phillippe violated the truce and again invaded Normandie
1 CONT . By the end of 1195, both sides sought a more lastin peace and the T reaty of
1 CONT Louviers ceded Norman Vexin to Phillippe. By 1197, Phillipp e and Richard I
1 CONT were again at war over Normandie. Even though Phillip pe was able to take
1 CONT Aumale, Richard was able to regain much of the ter ritory that Phillippe had
1 CONT take during Richard's captivity. After Joh n Lackland was able to take Philip
1 CONT of Dreux captive, Phillippe was aga in forced to sue for peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1196, Phillippe quickly married his third wife Agnes of Meran, daug hter of
1 CONT the German Prince of the Holy Roman Empire, who ruled Merano, even though she
1 CONT was so closely related to Phillippe that their union w as automatically
1 CONT forbidden by canon law. Philip found some obliging ch urchmen to annul the
1 CONT first marriage and solemnize the second, on May 7 , 1196. The Pope Celestine
1 CONT III did not take action except to issue ap peals and warnings. In September of
1 CONT 1198, Baldwin of Flanders (de Hai nault) laid siege and captured the castle at
1 CONT Saint-Omer. Phillippe re tailiated by invading Normandie, burning towns and
1 CONT terriorizing the lo cal population. On 27 September 1198, Richard retailiated
1 CONT and invade d French territory. In 1198, Phillippe was pursued to the area of
1 CONT Gis ors by Richard's mercenary Captain Mercadier. When Innocent III. beca me
1 CONT Pope in 1198 the affair had been dragging on for two years. When P hilip
1 CONT refused to yield, Pope Innocent III. placed an interdict agains t all of
1 CONT France. Pope Innocent III also called for force and even a c rusade against
1 CONT Toulouse, but Phillippe declined the invitation and dee med it unjustified
1 CONT unless Raymond VI of Toulouse was first declared a heretic. The Popes
1 CONT interdict deprived the entire population of the sa craments of the Church.
1 CONT Phillippe finally in desperation agreed to a s eparation from Agnes, and the
1 CONT Pope lifted the ban. But not before sh e bore him a son, Philip Hurepel of
1 CONT Boulogne who died in 1234, and a d aughter, Mary (Marie), who died in 1224,
1 CONT married first Philip I of Nam ur, who died in 1212, and second Henry I, Duke
1 CONT of Brabant, who died i n 1235. There was issue by this second marriage.
1 CONT Another son (illegit imate) was born to Philip and "a maiden of Arras," Pierre
1 CONT Charlot, Bis hop of Noyon.
1 CONT
1 CONT Phillippe, upon hearing of Richards death, proclaimed Arthur the right ful
1 CONT heir to England and the Angevin empire. Phillippe marched west an d advanced
1 CONT on the area of Anjou and Maine. Arthur of Brittany and hi s mother had marched
1 CONT on Anjou and eventually made there way to LeMans . By June of 1199, now King
1 CONT John had crossed the channel and landed i n the area of Dieppe. Almost
1 CONT immediately there was a test of strengt h between Phillippe and John when John
1 CONT besieged a castle in the area, but was quickly driven off. By late 1199, a
1 CONT rift had developed betwee n Phillippe and Arthur of Brittany. In late 1199,
1 CONT Phillippe and John - King of England concluded a five year truce by whcih
1 CONT Phillippe's so n Louis would marry one of John's Castillian's nieces. John at
1 CONT the ti me had to return to England, so his then 71 year old mother Eleanor wa
1 CONT s sent to select the niece. In mid January 1200, Phillippe was impose d with
1 CONT an interdict on his kingdom by the vatican to punish him fro hi s marital
1 CONT discrepancies. On 22 May 1200, Phillippe and John of Englan d concluded the
1 CONT Treaty of Le Goulet which enshrined the terms of the p revious truce. By it,
1 CONT Arthur was to hold Brittany as a vassel of John . By it, Phillippes son Louis
1 CONT was to marry John's niece Blanche. By it, also, Phillippe invested John with
1 CONT the Angevin domains that includ ed Brittany and Arthur was produced to do
1 CONT homage to his uncle John fo r the duchy of Brittany. In 1201, Phillippe
1 CONT ordered Hugh and his brot her Raoul (Ralph) de Lusignan to cease their
1 CONT harrying of King John's l ands in Normandie. They ignored his command.
1 CONT Phillippe subsequently offered to act as a mediator between the warring
1 CONT parities.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1202, the Pope legitimized the children of Agnes and Phillippe. B y 1202,
1 CONT Phillippe was less than inclined to bow to the imperial preten sions of the
1 CONT Otto IV Holy Roman Emperor and was supported in his attit ude by the Papal
1 CONT Bull 'Per venerabilem' issued by Pope Innocent III. The Bull declared that he
1 CONT King of France recognised no temporal superi or. On 28 April 1202 Phillippe
1 CONT issued a final summons to John to pres ent himself at the French court and
1 CONT offer homage for his lands on the continent. When John refused to appear,
1 CONT Phillippe declared the truce of 1199 broken and marched on the frontier
1 CONT defenses of Normandie. By 8 July 1202, Phillippe had captured the stronghold
1 CONT at Gournay. He adv anced on Radepont, where he was met by John and chose to
1 CONT retire. Afte r Arthur was captured along with Hugh and Geoffrey de Lusignan at
1 CONT Mira beau in August of 1202, Phillippe then involved in a siege of Arques,
1 CONT broke off the siege and withdrew his forces from Normandie. He moved his army
1 CONT to the area of Tours, but when faced with the approach of Joh n, Phillippe
1 CONT withdrew. After news of Arthurs death reached him, and J ohn's allies quickly
1 CONT began to desert him, Phillippe advanced along th e Loire and took the fortress
1 CONT of Saumur, southwest of Fontevrault in A njou. Chinon held out against
1 CONT Phillippe at which time he swung north and marched unoppossed into Normandie.
1 CONT He took Domfront, Coutances, F alaise, Bayeux, Lisieux, Caen and Avranches. In
1 CONT 1203 Phillipps force s had moved against Castle Gaillard above Les Andelys on
1 CONT the great loo p of the Seine. Phillippe's army employed catapults, battering
1 CONT rams a nd south to undermine the walls by burning the support timbers. Phill
1 CONT ippe also sent troops into the drain pipes in hope of penetrating the interior
1 CONT of the castle By August of 1203, most of Normandie was in Ph illipps hands.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 6 March 1204, Chateau Gaillard fell into French hands. His soldier s were
1 CONT able to crawl in through the lavatory extension that King John had installed.
1 CONT Between late March and April of 1204, William 'the Pro tector' Marshall,
1 CONT Hubert Walter - Archbishop of Canterbury, Robert de Beaumont - Earl Leicester
1 CONT and the Bishops of Norwich and Ely were sen t by King John as a delegation to
1 CONT Phillippe. Phillippe was intereste d in nothing more than the complete
1 CONT surrender of John's French fiefs . He demanded that, if still alive, Arthur be
1 CONT returned and that his s ister Eleanor be turned over, and the complete
1 CONT surrender of the entir e continental aspect of the Angevin empire. After
1 CONT taking Chateau Gail lard, Phillippe avoided Rouen and swung southwest into the
1 CONT hills of so uthern Normandie and took Argentan, then veered north into the
1 CONT plains advancing boldly on Falaise and Caen. Cane surrendered without any re
1 CONT sistance. He detailed forces to Bayeux, Coutances and the Cherbourg p
1 CONT eninsula. In the early summer of 1204, Phillippe finally turned on Ro uen by
1 CONT way of Lisieux. On 1 June 1204, Peter of Preaux, maded terms with Phillippe.
1 CONT Phillippe entered Rouen which capitulated on 24 June 1204. by the end of 1204,
1 CONT Phllippe was in control of Normandie. In ab out May of 1205, instead of
1 CONT proceeding with plans for an invasion of E ngland, Phillippe turned his
1 CONT attention south and directed an offensiv e against Poitou and Touraine. By
1 CONT mid-summer of 1205, Phillippe had t aken Loches and Chinon. He subsequently
1 CONT possessed direct control of N ormandie, Maine, Anjou and Touraine. His allies
1 CONT additionally controle d Brittany, La Marche and most of Poitou. However, by
1 CONT August of 1206 with John making progress in the south, Phillippe became quite
1 CONT disquit ed and moved south, but stopped short of the southern border of Anjou
1 CONT . In October 1206, a truce that was to last two years was reached wit h John
1 CONT of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT In about 1209 Phillippe confiscated the estates and lands of Renaud - Count of
1 CONT Boulogne, when he switched his alligence to John - King of En gland. Phillippe
1 CONT was joined by Theobald - count of Bar and Ferrand - Count of Flanders. In
1 CONT 1212, Phillippe becan to consider an invasion o f England with the intent of
1 CONT raising his son Louis to the English thro ne. In 1213, at the time of the
1 CONT death of Eleanor de Vermandois, she l eft no collateral heirs and Phillippe
1 CONT moved and took Valois and Verman dois into his hands. In April 1213 at
1 CONT Soissons, Phillippe announced h is decision to invade England and his army was
1 CONT to assemble at Rouen b y 21 April 1213. Phillippe attempted to invade England,
1 CONT then ruled b y King John who had recently been excommunicated. But in May,
1 CONT John me t with the Papal legate at Dovert and immediately accepted the Popes t
1 CONT erms and the French invasion collapsed. Phillippe was furious and tur ned his
1 CONT wrath upon Ferrand of Flanders who had refused to join forces with the French
1 CONT against John. He ordered his fleet to the Swine estua ry on the northern
1 CONT seaway to Flanders. Phillippe crossed the border f rom the south and laid
1 CONT siege to Ghent. Ferrand appealed to John for h elp who sent 500 ships into the
1 CONT Swine estuary with some 700 knights an d a strong force of mercenaries
1 CONT commanded by William of Salisbury. Ph illippes fleet consisted of some 1700
1 CONT vessels and the guards had gone ashore to loot the area of Damme, Salisbury
1 CONT sailed straight into the harbor, cutting 300 of Phillippes vessels adrift and
1 CONT burning at least 100 more. Salisbury, with Ferrand landed his army and mounted
1 CONT an atta ck on Damme which was unsuccessful as Phillippe had learned of the Eng
1 CONT lish presence and withdrew from Ghent. As such William was forced bac k to his
1 CONT vessels and then by necessity withdrew from the harbor. In f ear of another
1 CONT raid, Phillippe ordered many of his remaining vessels b urned.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1214, Phillippe faced the most critical period of his reign when hi s many
1 CONT enemies, fearing his growing power, united against him in war . It was during
1 CONT this crisis that he displayed his marital ability an d foresight as a
1 CONT statesman. He favored the towns against his recalcit rant barons, and because
1 CONT of this, has been called the friend of the bo urgeoisie. In 1214 he moved his
1 CONT army to the area of Peronne on the S omme River. There he marched, advancing
1 CONT through Cambrai and Douai int o Flanders. By 27 July 1214, he realized that he
1 CONT had advanced to far a nd retraced his route to the area of the village of
1 CONT Bouvines. At Bouv ines, the French defeated the allied forces of John, Holy
1 CONT Roman Empero r Otto IV, and the count of Flanders; it was a victory that
1 CONT establishe d France as a leading European power. At Bouvines, Philippe was
1 CONT dragg ed from his horse by a German halbert. He was subsequently rescued b y
1 CONT his standard bearer Galon of Montigny. At Bouvines, Phillippe was a ble to
1 CONT capture 131 'men of importance' and five counts. He soon retur ned to Paris in
1 CONT a triumphal procession. In 1216, Phillippe accepted t he action of the Latern
1 CONT Council of 1216 that deprived Raymond VI of To ulouse of his lands and
1 CONT subsequently worked to turn them over to Simo n de Montfort.
1 CONT
1 CONT When the English barons revolted against John (1215), Phillippe offere d his
1 CONT help to the rebels. He supplied them with funds and ordinance . They, in turn,
1 CONT invited Philip's son Louis (later Louis VIII of Fran ce) to invade England and
1 CONT take the English throne; but the venture fai led. During Philip's reign the
1 CONT pope proclaimed the Crusade against th e Albigenses. Although Philip did not
1 CONT participate directly in the crus ade, he allowed his vassals to do so. Their
1 CONT victories prepared the gro und for the annexation of Southern France by King
1 CONT Louis IX. In interna l affairs Philip's most important reform was the creation
1 CONT of a class o f salaried administrative officers, the baillis [bailiffs], to
1 CONT supervi se local administration of the domain. Philip also systematized the co
1 CONT llection of customs, tolls, fines, and fees due to the crown. He suppo rted
1 CONT the towns of France againstthe royal barons, thereby increasing t heir power
1 CONT and prosperity. In Paris, he continued the construction of Notre-Dame de
1 CONT Paris, built the first Louvre, paved the main streets, a nd walled the city.
1 CONT An additional referenced includes: W. H. Hutton ( 1896, repr. 1970); J. W.
1 CONT Baldwin, The Government of Philip Augustus (1 986).
1 CONT
1 CONT Phillippe II was a younger half-brother of Marie, countess palatine o f
1 CONT Champagne, Alix, countess of Blois, Marguerite, queen of Hungary an d Alys,
1 CONT Countess of the Vexin. He was an older full brother of Agnes o f France,
1 CONT Empress of Constantinople. In declining health, his father had him crowned at
1 CONT Reims in 1179. He was married on April 28, 1180 to Isabelle of Hainaut, who
1 CONT brought the County of Artois as her dowry. Hi s father and co-ruler had died
1 CONT on September 18, 1180. Philip's eldest son Louis (later King Louis VIII), was
1 CONT born on September 5, 1187 and b ecame Count of Artois in 1190, when Isabelle,
1 CONT his mother, died.
1 CONT
1 CONT As King, Phillippe II would become one of the most successful in conso
1 CONT lidating northern France into one royal domain, but he never had more than
1 CONT limited influence in southern France. In 1221, Phillippe confisc ated
1 CONT Ponthieu, after Simon de Dammartin the husband of the heiress of the county,
1 CONT had joined the bouvines coalition. Phillippe made a conso lidated effort early
1 CONT in his reign to cury the favor of the three Engli sh princes, Richard,
1 CONT Geoffrey and John. He seized the territories of Maine, Touraine, Anjou,
1 CONT Brittany and all of Normandy from King John of England (1199-1216). His
1 CONT decisive victory at the Battle of Bouvines ov er King John and a coalition of
1 CONT forces that included Otto IV of German y ended the immediate threat of
1 CONT challenges to this expansion (1214) an d left Philip II Augustus as the most
1 CONT powerful monarch in all of Europ e. He reorganized the government, bringing
1 CONT financial stability to thec ountry and thus making possible a sharp increase
1 CONT in prosperity. His re ign was popular with ordinary people because he checked
1 CONT the power ofth e nobles and passed some of it on to the growing middle class
1 CONT that hi s reign had created.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip II Augustus would play a significant role in one of the greates t
1 CONT centuries of innovation in construction and in education. With Pari s as his
1 CONT capital, he had the main thoroughfares paved, built a centra l market, Les
1 CONT Halles, continued the construction begun in 1163 of theG othic Notre-Dame de
1 CONT Paris Cathedral, constructed the Louvre as a fortr ess and gave a charter to
1 CONT the University of Paris in 1200. Under hisgu idance, Paris became the first
1 CONT city of teachers the medieval world ha d known. In 1224, the French poet Henry
1 CONT d'Andeli wrote of the great wi ne tasting competition that Philip II Augustus
1 CONT commissioned The Battl e of the Wines. Philip II Augustus died July 14, 1223
1 CONT at Mantes and wa s interred in Saint Denis Basilica. He was succeeded by his
1 CONT son by Isa belle of Hainaut, Louis VIII (1223-26). At the time of Phllippes'
1 CONT dea th, his kingdom was twice the size of what it had been when he came t o
1 CONT power forty-three years earlier. He also left a substantial surplu s in the
1 CONT treasury.
1 CONT GIVN Phillip II Augustus Koenig
1 CONT SURN von Frankreich
