1 CONT [The Oxford Illustrated History of Medieval Europe] Kings of France:
1 CONT Capetian and Valois. Philip II Augustus (1180-1223).
1 CONT [Jeremiah Brown.FTW]
1 CONT
1 CONT [from Rootsweb geneal database]
1 CONT Philip II Augustus, King of France 1180-1223 became co-regent with his father
1 CONT Louis VII in 1179. From 1181 to 1186 Philip combated a coalition of barons in
1 CONT Flanders, Bourgogne, and Champagne and at their expense increased the royal
1 CONT domain. Philip allied himself with Richard, Duke of Aquitaine, who in 1189
1 CONT became Richard I of England, and in 1190 the two kings embarked on the Third
1 CONT Crusade. The kings quarreled, however, and Philip returned to France in 1191.
1 CONT Allied with Holy Roman Emperor Nenry VI and Richard's brother, John, later
1 CONT king of England, Philip attached Richard's territories in France. Richard
1 CONT returned in 1194 and went to war against Philip. By the time of Richard's
1 CONT death in 1199, Philip had been forced to surrender most of the territory he
1 CONT had annexed. Philip subsequently warred against John, who became King of
1 CONT England in 1199; between 1202 and 1205 Philip more than doubled his territory
1 CONT by annexing Normandy, Maine, Bretagne, Anjou, Touraine, and Poitou.
1 CONT A coalition of European powers, including England, challenged the growing
1 CONT power of France in 1214. Philip's forces, however, decisively defeated the
1 CONT coalition at the Battle of Bouvines, establishing France as a leading country
1 CONT of Europe.
1 CONT Philip increased the royal power not only by extending the royal domain but
1 CONT also by reducing the power of the feudal lords. He replaced the noble officers
1 CONT at court with an advisory council appointed from the middle class and
1 CONT supported the communes against the nobles. France prospered from his judicial,
1 CONT financial and administrative reorganization of the government; serfdom
1 CONT declined, towns grew, and commence flourished. Philip established Paris as the
1 CONT fixed capital of France, paved the streets, and had many new buildings
1 CONT constructed in the city.
