1 CONT Alfonso VIII (11 November 1155, Soria – 5 October 1214), called the Noble or
1 CONT el de las Navas, was the King of Castile from 1158 to his death and King of
1 CONT Toledo[1]. He is most remembered for his part in the Reconquista and the
1 CONT downfall of the Almohad Caliphate. After having suffered a great defeat with
1 CONT his own army at Alarcos against the Almohads,[2] he led the coalition of
1 CONT Christian princes and foreign crusaders who broke the power of the Almohads in
1 CONT the Battle of the Navas de Tolosa in 1212, an event which marked the arrival
1 CONT of an irreversible tide of Christian supremacy on the Iberian peninsula.
1 CONT
1 CONT His reign saw the domination of Castile over León and, by his alliance with
1 CONT Aragon, he drew those two spheres of Christian Iberia into close connection.
1 CONT
1 CONT Regency and civil war
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was born to Sancho III of Castile and Blanche, daughter of García
1 CONT Ramírez of Navarre, in Soria on 11 November 1155.[3] He was named after his
1 CONT grandfather Alfonso VII of Castile. His early life resembled that of other
1 CONT medieval kings. His father died in 1158 when his mother was also dead. Though
1 CONT proclaimed king when only three years of age, he was regarded as merely
1 CONT nominal by the unruly nobles to whom a minority was convenient. Immediately,
1 CONT Castile was plunged into conflicts between the various noble houses vying for
1 CONT ascendancy in the inevitable regency. The devotion of a squire of his
1 CONT household, who carried him on the pommel of his saddle to the stronghold of
1 CONT San Esteban de Gormaz, saved him from falling into the hands of the contending
1 CONT factions. The noble houses of Lara and Castro both claimed the regency, as did
1 CONT the boy's uncle, Ferdinand II of León. In 1159 the young Alfonso was put
1 CONT briefly in the custody of García Garcés de Aza, who was not wealthy enough to
1 CONT support him. In March 1160 the Castro and Lara met at the Battle of Lobregal
1 CONT and the Castro were victorious, but the guardianship of Alfonso and the
1 CONT regency fell to Manrique Pérez de Lara.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was put in the custody of the loyal village Ávila. At barely fifteen,
1 CONT he came forth to do a man's work by restoring his kingdom to order. It was
1 CONT only by a surprise that he recovered his capital Toledo from the hands of the
1 CONT Laras.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Reconquista
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1174, he ceded Uclés to the Order of Santiago and afterwards this became
1 CONT the order's principal seat. From Uclés, he began a campaign which culminated
1 CONT in the reconquest of Cuenca in 1177. The city surrendered on 21 September, the
1 CONT feast of Saint Matthew, ever afterwards celebrated by the citizens of the
1 CONT town.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso took the initiative to ally all the major Christian kingdoms of the
1 CONT peninsula — Navarre, León, Portugal, and Aragon — against the Almohads. By the
1 CONT Treaty of Cazola of 1179, the zones of expansion of each kingdom were defined.
1 CONT
1 CONT After founding Plasencia (Cáceres) in 1186, he embarked on a major initiative
1 CONT to unite the Castilian nobility around the Reconquista. In that year, he
1 CONT recuperated part of La Rioja from the Kingdom of Navarre.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1195, after the treaty with the Almohads was broken, he came to the defence
1 CONT of Alarcos on the river Guadiana, then the principal Castilian town in the
1 CONT region. At the subsequent Battle of Alarcos, he was roundly defeated by the
1 CONT caliph Abu Yaqub Yusuf al-Mansur. The reoccupation of the surrounding
1 CONT territory by the Almohads was quickly commenced with Calatrava falling first.
1 CONT For the next seventeen years, the frontier between Moor and Castilian was
1 CONT fixed in the hill country just outside Toledo.
1 CONT
1 CONT Finally, in 1212, through the mediation of Pope Innocent III, a crusade was
1 CONT called against the Almohads. Castilians under Alfonso, Aragonese and Catalans
1 CONT under Peter II, Navarrese under Sancho VII, and Franks under the archbishop
1 CONT Arnold of Narbonne all flocked to the effort. The military orders also lent
1 CONT their support. Calatrava first, then Alarcos, and finally Benavente were
1 CONT captured before a final battle was fought at Las Navas de Tolosa near Santa
1 CONT Elena on 16 July. The caliph Muhammad an-Nasir was routed and Almohad power
1 CONT broken.
1 CONT
1 CONT Cultural legacy
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the founder of the first Spanish university, a studium generale at
1 CONT Palencia, which, however, did not survive him. His court also served as an
1 CONT important instrument for Spanish cultural achievement. His marriage (Burgos,
1 CONT before 17 September 1177)[4] with Eleanor (Leonora), daughter of Henry II of
1 CONT England and Eleanor of Aquitaine, brought him under the influence of the
1 CONT greatest governing intellect of his time. Troubadours and sages were always
1 CONT present, largely due to the influence of Eleanor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso died at Gutierre-Muñoz and was succeeded by his eldest surviving son,
1 CONT Henry I, named after his maternal grandfather.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the subject for Lion Feuchtwanger's novel Die Jüdin von Toledo
1 CONT (The Jewess of Toledo), in which is narrated an affair with a Jewish subject
1 CONT in medieval Toledo in a time when Spain was known to be the land of tolerance
1 CONT and learning for Jews, Christians, and Muslims. The titular Jewish woman of
1 CONT the novel is based on Alfonso's historical paramour, Rahel la Fermosa.
1 CONT
