1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso VIII (11 November 1155 – 5 October 1214), called the Noble or Él de
1 CONT las Navas, was the King of Castile from 1158 to his death and King of
1 CONT Toledo[1]. He is most remembered for his part in the Reconquista and the
1 CONT downfall of the Almohad Caliphate. After having suffered a great defeat with
1 CONT his own army at Alarcos against the Almohads, he led the coalition of
1 CONT Christian princes and foreign crusaders who broke the power of the Almohads in
1 CONT the Battle of the Navas de Tolosa in 1212, an event which marked the arrival
1 CONT of an irreversible tide of Christian supremacy on the Iberian peninsula.
1 CONT
1 CONT His reign saw the domination of Castile over León and, by his alliance with
1 CONT Aragon, he drew those two spheres of Christian Iberia into close connection.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso VIII, called the Noble or el de las Navas, was the King of Castile
1 CONT from 1158 to his death and King of Toledo. He is most remembered for his part
1 CONT in the Reconquista and the downfall of the Almohad Caliphate. After having
1 CONT suffered a great defeat with his own army at Alarcos against the Almohads, he
1 CONT led the coalition of Christian princes and foreign crusaders who broke the
1 CONT power of the Almohads in the Battle of the Navas de Tolosa in 1212, an event
1 CONT that marked the arrival of an irreversible tide of Christian supremacy on the
1 CONT Iberian peninsula.
1 CONT
1 CONT His reign also saw the domination of Castile over León and, by his alliance
1 CONT with Aragon, he drew those two spheres of Christian Iberia into close
1 CONT connection.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1195, after the treaty with the Almohads was broken, he came to the defense
1 CONT of Alarcos on the river Guadiana, then the principal Castilian town in the
1 CONT region. At the subsequent Battle of Alarcos, he was roundly defeated by the
1 CONT caliph Abu Yaqub Yusuf al-Mansur (Arabic: ابو يوسف يعقوب المنصور‎). The
1 CONT reoccupation of the surrounding territory by the Almohads was quickly
1 CONT commenced with Calatrava falling first. For the next 17 years, the frontier
1 CONT between Moor and Castilian was fixed in the hill country just outside Toledo.
1 CONT
1 CONT Finally, in 1212, through the mediation of Pope Innocent III, a crusade was
1 CONT called against the Almohads. Castilians under Alfonso, Aragonese and Catalans
1 CONT under Peter II, Navarrese under Sancho VII, and Franks under the archbishop
1 CONT Arnold of Narbonne all flocked to the effort. The military orders also lent
1 CONT their support. Calatrava first, then Alarcos, and finally Benavente were
1 CONT captured before a final battle was fought at Las Navas de Tolosa near Santa
1 CONT Elena on 16 July. The caliph Muhammad an-Nasir (الناصر لدين الله محمد بن
1 CONT المنصور ) was routed and Almohad power broken.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the founder of the first Spanish university, a studium generale at
1 CONT Palencia, which, however, did not survive him. His court also served as an
1 CONT important instrument for Spanish cultural achievement. His marriage with
1 CONT Eleanor (Leonora), daughter of Henry II of England and Eleanor of Aquitaine,
1 CONT brought him under the influence of the greatest governing intellect of his
1 CONT time. Troubadours and sages were always present, largely due to the influence
1 CONT of Eleanor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the subject for Lion Feuchtwanger's novel Die Jüdin von Toledo
1 CONT (The Jewess of Toledo), in which is narrated an affair with a Jewish subject
1 CONT in medieval Toledo in a time when Spain was known to be the land of tolerance
1 CONT and learning for Jews, Christians, and Muslims. The titular Jewish woman of
1 CONT the novel is based on Alfonso's historical paramour, Rahel la Fermosa.
1 CONT
1 CONT See <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfonso_VIII_of_Castile> for more
1 CONT information.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso VIII (11 November 1155 – 5 October 1214), called the Noble or el de
1 CONT las Navas, was the King of Castile from 1158 to his death and King of
1 CONT Toledo[1]. He is most remembered for his part in the Reconquista and the
1 CONT downfall of the Almohad Caliphate. After having suffered a great defeat with
1 CONT his own army at Alarcos against the Almohads, he led the coalition of
1 CONT Christian princes and foreign crusaders who broke the power of the Almohads in
1 CONT the Battle of the Navas de Tolosa in 1212, an event which marked the arrival
1 CONT of an irreversible tide of Christian supremacy on the Iberian peninsula.
1 CONT
1 CONT His reign saw the domination of Castile over León and, by his alliance with
1 CONT Aragon, he drew those two spheres of Christian Iberia into close connection.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Alfonso VIII (11 November 1155 – 5 October 1214), called the Noble or el de
1 CONT las Navas, was the King of Castile from 1158 to his death and King of
1 CONT Toledo.[1][2] He is most remembered for his part in the Reconquista and the
1 CONT downfall of the Almohad Caliphate. After having suffered a great defeat with
1 CONT his own army at Alarcos against the Almohads,[3] he led the coalition of
1 CONT Christian princes and foreign crusaders who broke the power of the Almohads in
1 CONT the Battle of the Navas de Tolosa in 1212, an event which marked the arrival
1 CONT of a tide of Christian supremacy on the Iberian peninsula. His reign saw the
1 CONT domination of Castile over León and, by his alliance with Aragon, he drew
1 CONT those two spheres of Christian Iberia into close connection.
1 CONT
1 CONT Regency and civil war [edit]
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was born to Sancho III of Castile and Blanche, daughter of García
1 CONT Ramírez of Navarre, in Soria on 11 November 1155.[4] He was named after his
1 CONT grandfather Alfonso VII of Castile. His early life resembled that of other
1 CONT medieval kings. His father died in 1158 when his mother was also dead. Though
1 CONT proclaimed king when only three years of age, he was regarded as merely
1 CONT nominal by the unruly nobles to whom a minority was convenient. Immediately,
1 CONT Castile was plunged into conflicts between the various noble houses vying for
1 CONT ascendancy in the inevitable regency. The devotion of a squire of his
1 CONT household, who carried him on the pommel of his saddle to the stronghold of
1 CONT San Esteban de Gormaz, saved him from falling into the hands of the contending
1 CONT factions. The noble houses of Lara and Castro both claimed the regency, as did
1 CONT the boy's uncle, Ferdinand II of León. In 1159 the young Alfonso was put
1 CONT briefly in the custody of García Garcés de Aza, who was not wealthy enough to
1 CONT support him. In March 1160 the Castro and Lara met at the Battle of Lobregal
1 CONT and the Castro were victorious, but the guardianship of Alfonso and the
1 CONT regency fell to Manrique Pérez de Lara. Alfonso was put in the custody of the
1 CONT loyal village Ávila. At barely fifteen, he came forth to do a man's work by
1 CONT restoring his kingdom to order. It was only by a surprise that he recovered
1 CONT his capital Toledo from the hands of the Laras. Reconquista [edit]
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1174, he ceded Uclés to the Order of Santiago and afterwards this became
1 CONT the order's principal seat. From Uclés, he began a campaign which culminated
1 CONT in the reconquest of Cuenca in 1177. The city surrendered on 21 September, the
1 CONT feast of Saint Matthew, ever afterwards celebrated by the citizens of the
1 CONT town. Alfonso took the initiative to ally all the major Christian kingdoms of
1 CONT the peninsula — Navarre, León, Portugal, and Aragon — against the Almohads. By
1 CONT the Treaty of Cazola of 1179, the zones of expansion of each kingdom were
1 CONT defined. After founding Plasencia (Cáceres) in 1186, he embarked on a major
1 CONT initiative to unite the Castilian nobility around the Reconquista. In that
1 CONT year, he recuperated part of La Rioja from the Kingdom of Navarre. In 1195,
1 CONT after the treaty with the Almohads was broken, he came to the defence of
1 CONT Alarcos on the river Guadiana, then the principal Castilian town in the
1 CONT region. At the subsequent Battle of Alarcos, he was roundly defeated by the
1 CONT caliph Abu Yaqub Yusuf al-Mansur. The reoccupation of the surrounding
1 CONT territory by the Almohads was quickly commenced with Calatrava falling first.
1 CONT For the next seventeen years, the frontier between Moor and Castilian was
1 CONT fixed in the hill country just outside Toledo. Finally, in 1212, through the
1 CONT mediation of Pope Innocent III, a crusade was called against the Almohads.
1 CONT Castilians under Alfonso, Aragonese and Catalans under Peter II, Navarrese
1 CONT under Sancho VII, and Franks under the archbishop of Narbonne, Arnaud Amalric,
1 CONT all flocked to the effort. The military orders also lent their support.
1 CONT Calatrava first, then Alarcos, and finally Benavente were captured before a
1 CONT final battle was fought at Las Navas de Tolosa near Santa Elena on 16 July.
1 CONT The caliph Muhammad an-Nasir was routed and Almohad power broken. Cultural
1 CONT legacy [edit]
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the founder of the first Spanish university, a studium generale at
1 CONT Palencia, which, however, did not survive him. His court also served as an
1 CONT important instrument for Spanish cultural achievement. His marriage (Burgos,
1 CONT before 17 September 1177)[5] with Eleanor (Leonora), daughter of Henry II of
1 CONT England and Eleanor of Aquitaine, brought him under the influence of the
1 CONT greatest governing intellect of his time. Troubadours and sages were always
1 CONT present, largely due to the influence of Eleanor. Alfonso died at Gutierre-
1 CONT Muñoz and was succeeded by his eldest surviving son, Henry I, named after his
1 CONT maternal grandfather. Alfonso was the subject for Lion Feuchtwanger's novel
1 CONT Die Jüdin von Toledo (The Jewess of Toledo), in which is narrated an affair
1 CONT with a Jewish subject in medieval Toledo in a time when Spain was known to be
1 CONT the land of tolerance and learning for Jews, Christians, and Muslims. The
1 CONT titular Jewish woman of the novel is based on Alfonso's historical paramour,
1 CONT Rahel la Fermosa.
1 CONT
