1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Regency and civil war
1 CONT Alfonso was born to Sancho III of Castile and Blanca, daughter of García VI of
1 CONT Navarre, in Soria on 11 November 1155. He was named after his grandfather
1 CONT Alfonso VII. His early life resembled that of other medieval kings. His father
1 CONT died in 1158 when his mother was also dead. Though proclaimed king when only
1 CONT three years of age, he was regarded as a mere name by the unruly nobles to
1 CONT whom a minority was convenient. Immediately, Castile was plunged into
1 CONT conflicts between the various noble houses vying for ascendancy in the
1 CONT inevitable regency. The Lara and Castro both claimed the regency, as did the
1 CONT boy's uncle, Ferdinand II of León. The devotion of a squire of his household,
1 CONT who carried him on the pommel of his saddle to the stronghold of San Esteban
1 CONT de Gormaz, saved him from falling into the hands of the contending factions.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was put in the custody of the loyal village Ávila. At barely fifteen, he
1 CONT came forth to do a man's work by restoring his kingdom to order. It was only
1 CONT by a surprise that he recovered his capital Toledo from the hands of the
1 CONT Laras.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Reconquista
1 CONT In 1174, he ceded Uclés to the Order of Santiago and afterwards this became
1 CONT the order's principal seat. From Uclés, he began a campaign which culminated
1 CONT in the reconquest of Cuenca in 1177. The city surrendered on 21 September, the
1 CONT feast of Saint Matthew, ever afterwards celebrated by the citizens of the
1 CONT town.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso took the initiative to ally all the major Christian kingdoms of the
1 CONT peninsula — Navarre, León, Portugal, and Aragon — against the Almohads. By the
1 CONT Treaty of Cazorla of 1179, the zones of expansion of each kingdom were
1 CONT defined.
1 CONT
1 CONT After founding Plasencia (Cáceres) in 1186, he embarked on a major initiative
1 CONT to unite the Castilian nobility around the Reconquista. In that year, he
1 CONT recuperated part of La Rioja from the Kingdom of Navarre.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1195, after the treaty with the Almohads was broken, he came to the defence
1 CONT of Alarcos on the river Guadiana, then the principal Castilian town in the
1 CONT region. At the subsequent Battle of Alarcos, he was roundly defeated by the
1 CONT caliph Abu Yaqub Yusuf al-Mansur. The reoccupation of the surrounding
1 CONT territory by the Almohads was quickly commenced with Calatrava falling first.
1 CONT For the next seventeen years, the frontier between Moor and Castilian was
1 CONT fixed in the hill country just outside Toledo.
1 CONT
1 CONT Finally, in 1212, through the mediation of Pope Innocent III, a crusade was
1 CONT called against the Almohads. Castilians under Alfonso, Aragonese and Catalans
1 CONT under Peter II, Navarrese under Sancho VII, and Franks under the archbishop
1 CONT Arnold of Narbonne all flocked to the effort. The military orders also lent
1 CONT their support. Calatrava first, then Alarcos, and finally Benavente were
1 CONT captured before a final battle was fought at Las Navas de Tolosa near Santa
1 CONT Elena on 16 July. The caliph Muhammad an-Nasir was routed and Almohad power
1 CONT broken.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Cultural legacy
1 CONT
1 CONT Statue of Alfonso VIII at the Sabatini Gardens in Madrid (J. Villanueva,
1 CONT 1753).Alfonso was the founder of the first Spanish university, a studium
1 CONT generale at Palencia, which, however, did not survive him. His court also
1 CONT served as an important instrument for Spanish cultural achievement. His
1 CONT marriage (Burgos, September 1170) with Eleanor (Leonora), daughter of Henry II
1 CONT of England and Eleanor of Aquitaine, brought him under the influence of the
1 CONT greatest governing intellect of his time. Troubadours and sages were always
1 CONT present, largely due to the influence of Eleanor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso died at Gutierre-Muñoz and was succeeded by his eldest surviving son,
1 CONT Henry I, named after his maternal grandfather.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the subject for Lion Feuchtwanger's novel Die Jüdin von Toledo
1 CONT (The Jewess of Toledo), in which is narrated an affair with a Jewish subject
1 CONT in medieval Toledo in a time when Spain was known to be the land of tolerance
1 CONT and learning for Jews, Christians, and Muslims. The titular Jewish woman of
1 CONT the novel is based on Alfonso's historical paramour, Rahel la Fermosa.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Children
1 CONT With Eleanor, he had 12 children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Berenguela, or Berengaria, (August 1180 – 8 November 1246), married Alfonso IX
1 CONT of Leon
1 CONT Sancho (1181)
1 CONT Sancha (1182 – 3 February 1184)
1 CONT Henry (1184)
1 CONT Urraca (1186 – 1220), married Alfonso II of Portugal
1 CONT Blanch (4 March 1188 – 26 November 1252), married Louis VIII of France
1 CONT Ferdinand (29 September 1189 – 1211), on whose behalf Diego of Acebo and the
1 CONT future Saint Dominic travelled to Denmark in 1203 to secure a bride[
1 CONT Mafalda (1191 – 1204)
1 CONT Constance (1195 – 1198)
1 CONT Eleanor (1200 – 1244), married James I of Aragon
1 CONT Constance (1201 – 1243), abbess of Las Huelgas
1 CONT Henry I (14 April 1204 – 1217), successor
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Notes
1 CONT ^ Vicaire. pp 89–98.
1 CONT
