1 CONT [Wikipedia, "Alfonso VIII of Castile", retrieved 6 Oct 07]
1 CONT Alfonso VIII (11 November 1155 - 5 October 1214), called the Noble or Él de
1 CONT las Navas, was the King of Castile from 1158 to his death. He is most
1 CONT remembered for his part in the Reconquista and the downfall of the Almohad
1 CONT Caliphate. After having suffered a great defeat with his own army at Alarcos
1 CONT against the Almohads, he led the coalition of Christian princes and foreign
1 CONT crusaders who broke the power of the Almohads in the Battle of the Navas de
1 CONT Tolosa in 1212, an event which marked the arrival of an irreversible tide of
1 CONT Christian supremacy on the Iberian peninsula.
1 CONT
1 CONT His reign saw the domination of Castile over León and, by his alliance with
1 CONT Aragon, he drew those two spheres of Christian Iberia into close connection.
1 CONT
1 CONT Regency and civil war
1 CONT Alfonso was born to Sancho III of Castile and Blanca of Navarre, daughter of
1 CONT García VI of Navarre, in Soria on 11 November 1155. He was named after his
1 CONT grandfather Alfonso VII. His early life resembled that of other medieval
1 CONT kings. His father died in 1158 when his mother was also dead. Though
1 CONT proclaimed king when only three years of age, he was regarded as a mere name
1 CONT by the unruly nobles to whom a minority was convenient. Immediately, Castile
1 CONT was plunged into conflicts between the various noble houses vying for
1 CONT ascendancy in the inevitable regency. The Lara and Castro both claimed the
1 CONT regency, as did the boy's uncle, Ferdinand II of León. The devotion of a
1 CONT squire of his household, who carried him on the pommel of his saddle to the
1 CONT stronghold of San Esteban de Gormaz, saved him from falling into the hands of
1 CONT the contending factions.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was put in the custody of the loyal village Ávila. At barely fifteen, he
1 CONT came forth to do a man's work by restoring his kingdom to order. It was only
1 CONT by a surprise that he recovered his capital Toledo from the hands of the
1 CONT Laras.
1 CONT
1 CONT Children
1 CONT With Eleanor, he had 12 children:
1 CONT
1 CONT \- Berenguela, Queen of Castile (August 1180 - 8 November 1246), married King
1 CONT Alfonso IX of Leon
1 CONT \- Sancho of Castile (born & died 1181)
1 CONT \- Sancha of Castile (1182 - 3 February 1184)
1 CONT \- Henry of Castile (born & died 1184)
1 CONT \- Urraca, princess of Castile (1186-1220), married King Alfonso II of
1 CONT Portugal
1 CONT \- Blanca of Castile (4 March 1188 - 26 November 1252), married King Louis
1 CONT VIII of France
1 CONT \- Fernando of Castile (29 September 1189 - 1211)
1 CONT \- Mafalda of Castile (1191-1204)
1 CONT \- Constance of Castile (1195-1198)
1 CONT \- Leonor of Castile (1200-1244), married King James I of Aragon
1 CONT \- Constanza, nun at Las Huelgas (1201-1243)
1 CONT \- Henry I, King of Castile (14 April 1204 - 1217)
1 CONT 1 AUTH Sl
1 CONT The following is from the Brian Tompsett online royal genealogy, (Aug 4. 98):
1 CONT
1 CONT Sources conflict on whom Alfonso married and when.
1 CONT byname EL DE LAS NAVAS (Spanish: He of Las Navas) (b. 1155--d. Oct. 6, 1214,
1 CONT Burgos, Castile), king of Castile from 1158, son of Sancho III, whom he
1 CONT succeeded when three years old, and grandson of Alphonso VII, is a great name
1 CONT in Spanish history, for he led the coalition of Christian princes and foreign
1 CONT crusaders which broke the power of the Almohades at the battle of the Navas de
1 CONT Tolosa in 1212. His personal history is that of many mediaeval kings. He
1 CONT succeeded to the throne on the death of his father, Sancho, at the age of a
1 CONT year and a half. Before Alfonso came of age his reign was troubled by internal
1 CONT strife and the intervention of the kingdom of Navarre in Castilian affairs.
1 CONT Though proclaimed king, he was regarded as a mere name by the unruly nobles to
1 CONT whom a minority was convenient. The devotion of a squire of his household, who
1 CONT carried him on the pommel of his saddle to the stronghold of San Esteban de
1 CONT Gormaz, saved him from falling into the hands of the contending factions of
1 CONT Castro and Lara, or of his uncle, Ferdinand of Leon, who claimed the regency.
1 CONT The loyalty of the town of Avila protected his youth. He was barely 15 when he
1 CONT came forth to do a man's work by restoring his kingdom to order. Throughout
1 CONT his reign he maintained a close alliance with the kingdom of Aragon, and in
1 CONT 1179 he concluded the Pact of Cazorla, which settled the future line of
1 CONT demarcation between Castile and Aragon when the reconquest of Moorish Spain
1 CONT was completed. From 1172 to 1212 he was engaged in resistance to the Moorish
1 CONT Almohad invaders, who defeated him in 1195. In the same year the kings of Leon
1 CONT and Navarre invaded Castile, but Alfonso defeated them with the aid of King
1 CONT Peter II of Aragon. It was only by a surprise that he recovered the capital,
1 CONT Toledo, from the hands of the Laras. In 1212 Alfonso secured a great victory
1 CONT at Las Navas de Tolosa over the Almohad sultan and thereby broke Almohad power
1 CONT in Spain. His marriage with Leonora of Aquitaine, daughter of Henry II of
1 CONT England, brought him under the influence of the greatest governing intellect
1 CONT of his time. Alphonso VIII was the founder of the first Spanish university,
1 CONT the 'studium generale' of Palencia, which, however, did not survive him.
1 CONT [Encyclopaedia Britannica, 1961 ed., Vol. 1, p. 687-8, ALPHONSO VIII;
1 CONT Encyclopaedia Britannica CD
1 CONT king of Leon from 1188 to 1230, son of Ferdinand II of Leon and first cousin
1 CONT of Alphonso VIII of Castile, and numbered next to him as being a junior member
1 CONT of the family, is said by Ibn Khaldun to have been called the "Baboso" or
1 CONT Slobberer, because he was subject to fits of rage, during which he foamed at
1 CONT the mouth. Though he took a part in the work of the reconquest, this king is
1 CONT chiefly remembered by the difficulties into which his successive marriages led
1 CONT him with the pope. He was first married to his cousin, Teresa of Portugal, who
1 CONT bore him two daughters and a son who died young. The marriage was declared
1 CONT null by the pope, to whom Alphonso paid no attention till he was presumably
1 CONT tired of his wife. It cannot have been his conscience which constrained him to
1 CONT leave Teresa, for his next step was to marry Berengaria of Castile, who was
1 CONT his second cousin. For this act of contumacy the king and kingdom were placed
1 CONT under interdict. The pope was, however, compelled to modify his measures by
1 CONT the threat that if the people could not obtain the services of religion they
1 CONT would not support the clergy, and that heresy would spread. The king was left
1 CONT under interdict personally, but to that he showed himself indifferent, and he
1 CONT had the support of his clergy. Berengaria left him after the birth of five
1 CONT children, and the king then returned to Teresa, to whose daughters he left his
1 CONT kingdom by will. [Encyclopaedia Britannica, 1961 ed., Vol. 1, p. 688, ALPHONSO
1 CONT IX of Leon]
