1 CONT Alfonso IX of Leon
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso IX of León (August 15, 1171 – September 23 or 24, 1230; ruled from
1 CONT 1188–1230), first cousin of Alfonso VIII of Castile, and numbered next to him
1 CONT as being a junior member of the family, is said by Ibn Khaldun to have been
1 CONT called the Baboso or "Slobberer", because he was subject to fits of rage
1 CONT during which he foamed at the mouth.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso was the only son of King Ferdinand II of Leon and Urraca of Portugal.
1 CONT Though he took a part in the work of the reconquest, this king is chiefly
1 CONT remembered by the difficulties into which his successive marriages led him
1 CONT with the pope. He was first married in 1191 to his cousin Teresa of Portugal,
1 CONT who bore him two daughters, and a son who died young.
1 CONT
1 CONT The marriage was declared null by the pope, to whom Alfonso paid no attention
1 CONT till he was presumably tired of his wife. It cannot have been his conscience
1 CONT which constrained him to leave Teresa, for his next step was to marry
1 CONT Berenguela of Castile in 1197, who was his second cousin. For this act of
1 CONT contumacy the king and kingdom were placed under interdict.
1 CONT
1 CONT The pope was, however, compelled to modify his measures by the threat that if
1 CONT the people could not obtain the services of religion they would not support
1 CONT the clergy, and that heresy would spread. The king was left under interdict
1 CONT personally, but to that he showed himself indifferent, and he had the support
1 CONT of his clergy. Berenguela left him after the birth of five children, and the
1 CONT king then returned to Teresa, to whose daughters he left his kingdom by will.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso's children by Teresa of Portugal were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Sancha (c. 1192-1270)
1 CONT Dulce, also called Aldonza (c. 1195-c.1243)
1 CONT Fernando (1204-August 1214)
1 CONT His eldest daughter, Sancha, was engaged to her cousin King Henry I of
1 CONT Castile, but Henry died in 1217 before the marriage could be solemnized.
1 CONT Wanting to disinherit his eldest son, Fernando, King Alfonso invited John of
1 CONT Brienne to marry his daughter Sancha and thus inherit the Leonese throne.
1 CONT However, Queen Berenguela convinced John of Brienne to marry one of her
1 CONT daughters instead. Though she was the nominal heiress on her father's death in
1 CONT 1230, Sancha was easily set aside by Berenguela and Fernando. Sancha became a
1 CONT nun at Cozollos, where she died in 1270; she was later beatified. Her sister
1 CONT Dulce-Aldonza spent her life with their mother in Portugal.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alfonso's children by Berenguela of Castile were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Leonor (1198/99-October 31, 1210)
1 CONT King Fernando III (1200-1252)
1 CONT Berenguela (1201-1237), married John of Brienne
1 CONT Alfonso, Lord of Molina (1203-1272)
1 CONT Constanza (1205-September 7, 1242), became a nun at Las Huelgas
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT References
1 CONT Florez, Enrique. Reinas Catolicas, 1761
