1 CONT Elizabeth the Cuman
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth the Cuman was the Queen consort of Stephen V of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born c. 1239/40, a daughter of Kuthen, leader of the Kun (or Kuni)
1 CONT clan of Cumans and his Russian wife, Galicie of Halicz. The Cumans were the
1 CONT western tribes of the Kipchaks. The Kipchaks were a confederation of Turkic
1 CONT peoples who spoke the Kipchak language. Her people followed a Shamanist
1 CONT religion and were considered Pagans by their contemporary Christians of
1 CONT Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1238, Kuthen led the Kuni and a number of other clans in invading the
1 CONT Kingdom of Hungary while fleeing from the advancing hordes of the Mongol
1 CONT Empire. In time, Béla IV of Hungary negotiated an alliance with Kuthen and his
1 CONT people, granting them asylum in exchange for their conversion to the Roman
1 CONT Catholic Church and loyalty to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT The agreement was eventually sealed with the betrothal of Elizabeth to
1 CONT Stephen, oldest son Béla IV. The agreement seems to have occurred while
1 CONT Stephen was an infant. Elizabeth is considered unlikely to have been older
1 CONT than her future husband. In 1241, the Mongol invasion of Europe under the
1 CONT leadership of Batu Khan and Subutai begun with Hungary among its primary
1 CONT targets. Kuthen was assassinated by Hungarian nobles fearing he could lead a
1 CONT defection to the other side.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV and the Hungarian forces suffered a crushing defeat at the Battle of
1 CONT Mohi (11 April 1241). The King fled to the Duchy of Austria while Batu Khan
1 CONT and Subutai tried to set up the Mongol occupation of Hungary until the end of
1 CONT 1242\. However news eventually reached them that their overlord Ögedei Khan,
1 CONT Khagan of the Mongol Empire, had died in 1241. His widow Töregene Khatun was
1 CONT serving as regent until a successor could be elected in a Kurultai. Batu
1 CONT decided to return to Karakorum for the Kurultai. He called off the invasion
1 CONT and Mongol troops were withdrawn from most of Europe, in the process
1 CONT evacuating Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Princess of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV returned from Austria following the Mongol evacuation. Upon his return
1 CONT to power, Béla began rebuilding his country, including a massive construction
1 CONT campaign which produced the system of castles as a defense against the threat
1 CONT of a Mongol return.
1 CONT
1 CONT Kuthen was deceased but the betrothal was still in effect. Elizabeth was
1 CONT converted to Roman Catholicism in preparation of her marriage. The marriage of
1 CONT Stephen and Elizabeth occurred in 1253. The groom was twelve-years-old and the
1 CONT bride close in age to him.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1262, Stephen convinced his father to give him twenty-nine counties as a
1 CONT reward of assistance in the war against Ottokar II of Bohemia. He was crowned
1 CONT junior co-ruler and in practice ruled his regions as a separate kingdom,
1 CONT setting up his own capital and adopting foreign policies directly contrary to
1 CONT those of his father. Elizabeth was now his Queen.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Queen consort
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV died on 3 May 1270. Stephen succeeded him as senior King. Among his
1 CONT successes were the conclusion of the war against Ottokar II of Bohemia.
1 CONT According to the Peace of Pressburg (2 July 1271, Stephen renounced his claims
1 CONT on parts of present-day Austria and Slovenia while Ottokar renounced his
1 CONT claims on territories of Hungary briefly conquered by him during the war.
1 CONT
1 CONT Stephen died on 6 August 1272. Elizabeth became Regent for their ten-year-old
1 CONT son Ladislaus IV of Hungary. Her regency lasted until 1277 and saw palace
1 CONT revolutions and civil wars.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her upbringing of her son would cause further problems for his reign.
1 CONT Ladislaus favored the society of the "semi-pagan" Cumans, from whom he was
1 CONT descended through his mother. He wore Cuman dress as his court wear,
1 CONT surrounded himself with Cuman concubines and thus alienated the Hungarian
1 CONT nobility. His later attempts to regain Hungarian loyalty instead alienated
1 CONT parts of the Cumans. He was murdered in his tent by Cumans while camped in
1 CONT Bihar county on 10 July 1290.
1 CONT
1 CONT By that time Elizabeth herself seems to have also been deceased. There is no
1 CONT mention of her in the reign of his successor Andrew III of Hungary.There is a
1 CONT tradition that she died in the year 1290.
1 CONT
1 CONT Children
1 CONT
1 CONT She and her husband Stephen V of Hungary were parents to six known children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth of Hungary (c. 1255 - 1313). Married firstly Zavis Vítkovci, Lord of
1 CONT Rosenberg, Skalitz and Falkenstein. Married secondly Stefan Uroš II Milutin of
1 CONT Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Catherine of Hungary (c. 1256 - after 1314). Married Stefan Dragutin of
1 CONT Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 - 25 March 1323). Married Charles II of Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna of Hungary (c. 1260 - 1281). Married Andronikos II Palaiologos.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ladislaus IV of Hungary (August, 1262 - 10 July 1290).
1 CONT
1 CONT András, Duke of Slavonia (1268 - 1278).
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth the Cuman was the Queen consort of Stephen V of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born c. 1239/40, a daughter of Kuthen, leader of the Kun (or Kuni)
1 CONT clan of Cumans and his Russian wife, Galicie of Halicz. The Cumans were the
1 CONT western tribes of the Kipchaks. The Kipchaks were a confederation of Turkic
1 CONT peoples who spoke the Kipchak language. Her people followed a Shamanist
1 CONT religion and were considered Pagans by their contemporary Christians of
1 CONT Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT She and her husband Stephen V of Hungary were parents to six known children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth of Hungary (c. 1255 - 1313). Married firstly Zavis Vítkovci, Lord of
1 CONT Rosenberg, Skalitz and Falkenstein. Married secondly Stefan Uroš II Milutin of
1 CONT Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Catherine of Hungary (c. 1256 - after 1314). Married Stefan Dragutin of
1 CONT Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 - 25 March 1323). Married Charles II of Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna of Hungary (c. 1260 - 1281). Married Andronikos II Palaiologos.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ladislaus IV of Hungary (August, 1262 - 10 July 1290).
1 CONT
1 CONT András, Duke of Slavonia (1268 - 1278).
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born c. 1239/40, a daughter of Kuthen, leader of the Kun (or Kuni)
1 CONT clan of Cumans and his Russian wife, Galicie of Halicz. The Cumans were the
1 CONT western tribes of the Kipchaks. The Kipchaks were a confederation of Turkic
1 CONT peoples who spoke the Kipchak language. Her people followed a Shamanist
1 CONT religion and were considered Pagans by their contemporary Christians of
1 CONT Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1238, Kuthen led the Kuni and a number of other clans in invading the
1 CONT Kingdom of Hungary while fleeing from the advancing hordes of the Mongol
1 CONT Empire. In time, Béla IV of Hungary negotiated an alliance with Kuthen and his
1 CONT people, granting them asylum in exchange for their conversion to the Roman
1 CONT Catholic Church and loyalty to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT The agreement was eventually sealed with the betrothal of Elizabeth to
1 CONT Stephen, oldest son Béla IV. The agreement seems to have occurred while
1 CONT Stephen was an infant. Elizabeth is considered unlikely to have been older
1 CONT than her future husband. In 1241, the Mongol invasion of Europe under the
1 CONT leadership of Batu Khan and Subutai begun with Hungary among its primary
1 CONT targets. Kuthen was assassinated by Hungarian nobles fearing he could lead a
1 CONT defection to the other side.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV and the Hungarian forces suffered a crushing defeat at the Battle of
1 CONT Mohi (11 April 1241). The King fled to the Duchy of Austria while Batu Khan
1 CONT and Subutai tried to set up the Mongol occupation of Hungary until the end of
1 CONT 1242\. However news eventually reached them that their overlord Ögedei Khan,
1 CONT Khagan of the Mongol Empire, had died in 1241. His widow Töregene Khatun was
1 CONT serving as regent until a successor could be elected in a Kurultai. Batu
1 CONT decided to return to Karakorum for the Kurultai. He called off the invasion
1 CONT and Mongol troops were withdrawn from most of Europe, in the process
1 CONT evacuating Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth the Cuman was the Queen consort of Stephen V of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born c. 1239/40, a daughter of Kuthen, leader of the Kun (or Kuni)
1 CONT clan of Cumans and his Russian wife, Galicie of Halicz. The Cumans were the
1 CONT western tribes of the Kipchaks. The Kipchaks were a confederation of Turkic
1 CONT peoples who spoke the Kipchak language. Her people followed a Shamanist
1 CONT religion and were considered Pagans by their contemporary Christians of
1 CONT Europe.
1 CONT
1 CONT She and her husband Stephen V of Hungary were parents to six known children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth of Hungary (c. 1255 - 1313). Married firstly Zavis Vítkovci, Lord of
1 CONT Rosenberg, Skalitz and Falkenstein. Married secondly Stefan Uroš II Milutin of
1 CONT Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Catherine of Hungary (c. 1256 - after 1314). Married Stefan Dragutin of
1 CONT Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Hungary (c. 1257 - 25 March 1323). Married Charles II of Naples.
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna of Hungary (c. 1260 - 1281). Married Andronikos II Palaiologos.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ladislaus IV of Hungary (August, 1262 - 10 July 1290).
1 CONT
1 CONT András, Duke of Slavonia (1268 - 1278).
1 CONT
