0 @N00637@ NOTE geni:about_me Yolande of Jerusalem
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolande of Brienne (b. 1212 - d. Andria, Italy, 25 April 1228), also known as
1 CONT Yolanda or Isabella II of Jerusalem, was a princess of French origin who
1 CONT became Queen of Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT Infant Queen
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolande was the only child of Maria of Montferrat, Queen of Jerusalem, and
1 CONT John of Brienne. Maria was the daughter of Queen Isabella of Jerusalem by her
1 CONT second husband Conrad I, and heiress, on her mother's death, of the Kingdom of
1 CONT Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria died shortly after giving birth to her in 1212, possibly by puerperal
1 CONT fever. Because of this, Yolande was proclamed Queen of Jerusalem when she was
1 CONT only a few days old. Because her father John did not have a direct claim on
1 CONT the throne, he ruled as regent.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Marriage with Frederick II
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick II, King of Germany and Sicily, had involved himself broadly in the
1 CONT Fifth Crusade, sending troops from Germany, but he failed to accompany the
1 CONT army directly, despite the encouragement of the Popes Honorius III and later
1 CONT Gregory IX, as he needed to consolidate his position in Germany and Italy
1 CONT before embarking on a crusade. However, Frederick again promised to go on a
1 CONT Crusade after his coronation as Holy Roman Emperor in 1220 by Honorius III.
1 CONT
1 CONT During a meeting between John of Brienne, the Pope Honorius III and Frederick
1 CONT II in the city of Ferentino in 1223, Yolande's fate was decided: Frederick
1 CONT accepted to finally go to the Crusade, but only as the legitimate King of
1 CONT Jerusalem, and this was only possible if he take the young Queen Yolande as
1 CONT his wife (by this time, Frederick was a widower). This was planned by the
1 CONT Pope, who hoped by this bond to attach the Emperor firmly to the Sixth
1 CONT Crusade. The betrothal was confirmed, but the Emperor still delayed his
1 CONT departure until August 1225, when he and Yolande were married by proxy in the
1 CONT city of Acre. Days after, Yolande was crowned as Queen of Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT The now Crowned Queen was sent to Italy and married in person with Frederick
1 CONT II in the cathedral of Brindisi, on 9 November 1225. In the ceremony, he
1 CONT declared himself King Frederick of Jerusalem. Immediately Frederick II saw to
1 CONT it that his new father-in-law John of Brienne, the current King-Regent of
1 CONT Jerusalem, was dispossessed and his rights transferred to him. Despite his new
1 CONT capacity as King of Jerusalem, Frederick II continued to take his time in
1 CONT setting off, and in 1227, he was excommunicated by Pope Gregory IX for failing
1 CONT to honor his crusading pledge.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT
1 CONT Since the wedding, Yolande was kept in seclusion by her husband. She spent her
1 CONT time in Frederick's harem in Palermo. In November 1226, she gave birth to her
1 CONT first child, a daughter (called by some sources as Margareta); the baby died
1 CONT in August 1227.
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick finally sailed from Brindisi on 8 September 1227 for Jerusalem but
1 CONT fell ill at Otranto, where the Landgrave Ludwig IV of Thuringia had been put
1 CONT ashore and postponed his journey while he recovered.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meanwhile Yolande died after giving birth to her second child, a son,
1 CONT Conrad, in Andria, Bari on 25 April 1228. She was buried in the Cathedral of
1 CONT Bari. Frederick finally embarked to Jerusalem on 28 June.
1 CONT
1 CONT Although he crowned himself as King of Jerusalem in the Holy Sepulchre (18
1 CONT March 1229), he ruled as regent on behalf of his son, settling a truce with
1 CONT the Muslims in 1229 during the Sixth Crusade.
1 CONT
1 CONT References
1 CONT
1 CONT This article incorporates text from the Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh
1 CONT Edition, a publication now in the public domain.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Après la mort de Constenza, Friedrich II von Hohenstaufen prend un nouveau
1 CONT parti en la personne d' Isabelle Yolande de Brienne.(1225)
1 CONT
1 CONT Héritière de la maison de Jérusalem, Isabelle Yolande (1211-1228)est fille de
1 CONT Jean Ier de Brienne, Roi de Jérusalem, (ca 1147-1237) et de Maria de
1 CONT Montferrat, "Maria del Montferrato", Reine de Jérusalem (1191-1212)
1 CONT
1 CONT .
1 CONT
1 CONT Peu après sa naissance, sa mère contracte, une grave maladie, peut-être la
1 CONT fièvre puerpérale et meurt. Son père, qui n’était que roi à titre de prince
1 CONT consort, devient le bailli et le régent du royaume de Jérusalem au nom de sa
1 CONT fille[
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle sera effectivement Reine de Jérusalem de 1225 à sa mort.
1 CONT
1 CONT De son Union avec Friedrich II naîtra Konrad IV, (1228-1254), futur Empereur
1 CONT des Romains , Roi de Germanie , Re di Sicilia ...
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle Yolande de Brienne s'éteind en 1228.
1 CONT \--------------------
