1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella II (1212 – 25 April 1228 Andria, Italy) also known as Yolande of
1 CONT Brienne, was a princess of French origin who became monarch of Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT Infant Queen
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella II was the only child of Maria of Montferrat, Queen of Jerusalem, and
1 CONT John of Brienne. Maria was the daughter of Queen Isabella I of Jerusalem by
1 CONT her second husband Conrad I, and heiress, on her mother's death, of the
1 CONT Kingdom of Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria died shortly after giving birth to her in 1212, possibly by puerperal
1 CONT fever. Because of this, Isabella II was proclaimed Queen of Jerusalem when she
1 CONT was only a few days old. Because her father John did not have a direct claim
1 CONT on the throne, he ruled as regent.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage with Frederick II
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick II, King of Germany and Sicily, had involved himself broadly in the
1 CONT Fifth Crusade, sending troops from Germany, but he failed to accompany the
1 CONT army directly, despite the encouragement of the Popes Honorius III and later
1 CONT Gregory IX, as he needed to consolidate his position in Germany and Italy
1 CONT before embarking on a crusade. However, Frederick again promised to go on a
1 CONT Crusade after his coronation as Holy Roman Emperor in 1220 by Honorius III.
1 CONT
1 CONT During a meeting between John of Brienne, the Pope Honorius III and Frederick
1 CONT II in the city of Ferentino in 1223, Yolande's fate was decided: Frederick
1 CONT accepted to finally go to the Crusade, but only as the legitimate King of
1 CONT Jerusalem, and this was only possible if he agreed to take the young Queen
1 CONT Isabella II as his wife (by this time, Frederick was a widower). This was
1 CONT planned by the Pope, who hoped by this bond to attach the Emperor firmly to
1 CONT the Sixth Crusade. The betrothal was confirmed, but the Emperor still delayed
1 CONT his departure until August 1225, when he and Isabella were married by proxy in
1 CONT the City of Acre. Days after, Isabella II was crowned as Queen of Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT The now crowned Queen was sent to Italy and married in person to Frederick II
1 CONT in the cathedral of Brindisi, on 9 November 1225. In the ceremony, he declared
1 CONT himself King Frederick of Jerusalem. Immediately Frederick II saw to it that
1 CONT his new father-in-law John of Brienne, the current Regent of Jerusalem, was
1 CONT dispossessed and his rights transferred to him. Despite his new capacity as
1 CONT King of Jerusalem, Frederick II continued to take his time in setting off, and
1 CONT in 1227, he was excommunicated by Pope Gregory IX for failing to honour his
1 CONT crusading pledge.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT
1 CONT After the wedding, Isabella was kept in seclusion by her husband. She spent
1 CONT her time in Frederick's harem in Palermo. In November 1226, she gave birth to
1 CONT her first child, a daughter (referred to by some sources as Margaret); the
1 CONT baby died in August 1227. Frederick finally sailed from Brindisi on 8
1 CONT September 1227 for Jerusalem but fell ill at Otranto, where Louis IV,
1 CONT Landgrave of Thuringia, had been put ashore. Frederick postponed the journey
1 CONT while he recovered. In the meantime Isabella died after giving birth to her
1 CONT second child, a son, Conrad, in Andria, Bari, on 25 April 1228. She is buried
1 CONT in Andria Cathedral. Frederick finally embarked to Jerusalem on 28 June.
1 CONT Although he crowned himself as King of Jerusalem in the Holy Sepulchre on 18
1 CONT March 1229, he ruled as regent on behalf of his son, settling a truce with the
1 CONT Muslims in 1229 during the Sixth Crusade.
1 CONT "OF BRIENNE"
1 CONT She ruled from 1225 to 1228.
1 CONT Became Quuen of Jerusalem as regent.
1 CONT Source:
1 CONT WH Turton: Plantagenet Ancestry: Genealogical Publishing Co. 1928.
1 CONT Charles Mosley Edition Burkes Peerage and Baronage 106th Edition, Vol 1 pg
1 CONT 227.
1 CONT She was the heiress of the titular king of Jerusalem. upon the marriage to
1 CONT her, Frederick declared himself king of Jerusalem, which was the high point
1 CONT as well as the turning point of Frederick's conception of sovereignty.
1 CONT Eschatological prophecies concerning his rule were then made, and the Emperor
1 CONT considered himself to be the messiah, a new David! His entry into Jerusalem
1 CONT was compared with that of Christ on Palm Sunday, and, indeed, in a manifesto
1 CONT the Emperor compared himself to Christ!
1 CONT Yolande of Jerusalem
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Yolande of Brienne (1212 - 1228), also known as Yolanda or Isabella II, became
1 CONT Queen of Jerusalem as an infant in 1212.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT The death of Queen Isabella-Yolande (From MS of William of Tyre's Historia and
1 CONT Old French Continuation, painted in Acre, 13C. Bib. Nat. Française.)She was
1 CONT the only child of Maria of Montferrat, Queen of Jerusalem, and John of
1 CONT Brienne. Maria was the daughter of Queen Isabella of Jerusalem by her second
1 CONT husband Conrad I, and heiress, on her mother's death, of the Kingdom of
1 CONT Jerusalem. Because John did not have a direct claim on the throne, Yolande
1 CONT succeeded her mother Maria, who died giving birth to her in 1212. John ruled
1 CONT as regent until 1225, when Yolande married Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor
1 CONT with the encouragement of Pope Honorius III, who hoped by this bond to attach
1 CONT the emperor firmly to the Sixth Crusade.
1 CONT
1 CONT Frederick claimed the kingdom for himself; when Yolande died after giving
1 CONT birth to their son Conrad in 1228, Frederick ruled as regent, settling a truce
1 CONT with the Muslims in 1229 during the Sixth Crusade.
1 CONT
1 CONT See also: Other young rulers
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT Maria and John Queen of Jerusalem
1 CONT 1212–1228
1 CONT (with Frederick, 1225-1228) Succeeded by:
