1 CONT Isabelle de Hainaut <http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isabelle_de_Hainaut>
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT French Queen. Wife of Philipp II. Auguste. The marriage between the two was
1 CONT probably aranged by his advisors and celebrated without the consent of his
1 CONT mother Adele de Champagne and father Louis VII, who was so ill that he's
1 CONT unable to reign the kingdom at the time. On May 29th 1180 she was crowned in
1 CONT St. Denis and on September 19th, after the death of her father in law, she
1 CONT became queen. She gave birth to Louis in 1187 who would later succeed his
1 CONT father. She died after giving birth to twins. The two boys died a few days
1 CONT after their mother and were buried beside her.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (Valenciennes[1], 5 April 1170 – 15 March 1190, Paris) was
1 CONT queen consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Valenciennes, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut
1 CONT and Countess Margaret I of Flanders. She married King Philip II of France on
1 CONT 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought as her dowry the county of Artois. The
1 CONT marriage was arranged by her maternal uncle Count Philip of Flanders who was
1 CONT advisor to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the chroniclers
1 CONT of the time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian
1 CONT dynasties. Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists, she
1 CONT failed to win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him
1 CONT with an heir[2]. Meanwhile, King Philip in 1184, was waging war against
1 CONT Flanders, and angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, he called a
1 CONT council at Sens for the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle,
1 CONT successfully interposed. Finally, on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the
1 CONT needed heir, the future King Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. Due to complications in childbirth, Isabelle died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins lived
1 CONT only four days (14 March-18 March 1190)[3]. Her dowry of Artois eventually
1 CONT returned to the French Crown following the death of Philip.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
