1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella of Hainault (Valenciennes[1], 5 April 1170 – 15 March 1190, Paris)
1 CONT was queen consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella was born in Valenciennes, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of
1 CONT Hainaut, and Margaret I, Countess of Flanders. She married King Philip II of
1 CONT France on 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought as her dowry the county of
1 CONT Artois. The marriage was arranged by her maternal uncle Philip, Count of
1 CONT Flanders, who was advisor to the King[2].
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella was crowned Queen of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As Baldwin
1 CONT V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the chroniclers of the
1 CONT time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian dynasties.
1 CONT Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists, she failed to
1 CONT win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him with an
1 CONT heir[2]. Meanwhile, King Philip in 1184, was waging war against Flanders, and
1 CONT angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, he called a council at Sens for
1 CONT the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle, successfully
1 CONT interposed. Finally, on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the needed heir,
1 CONT the future King Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabella gave
1 CONT birth to twin boys named Robert and Philip. Due to complications in
1 CONT childbirth, Isabella died the next day, and was buried in the cathedral of
1 CONT Notre Dame in Paris. The twins lived only four days (14 March-18 March
1 CONT 1190)[3]. Her dowry of Artois eventually returned to the French Crown
1 CONT following the death of Philip.
1 CONT
