1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (5 April 1170, Lille - 15 March 1190, Paris) was queen
1 CONT consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Lille,on (5 April,1170) the daughter of Baldwin V, Count
1 CONT of Hainaut and Countess Margaret I of Flanders. She married King Philip II of
1 CONT France in 1180 and brought as her dowry the county of Artois.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on May 28, 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V claimed (correctly) to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the
1 CONT chroniclers of the time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and
1 CONT Capetian dynasties. Though she received extravagant praise from certain
1 CONT annalists, she failed to win the affections of Philip (possibly because he was
1 CONT supposedly engaged in an homosexual affair with Richard the Lionheart at that
1 CONT time), who, in 1184, waging war against Flanders, was angered at seeing
1 CONT Baldwin support his enemies, and called a council at Sens for the purpose of
1 CONT repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle, successfully interposed. Finally,
1 CONT on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the needed heir, the future King Louis
1 CONT VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy, was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. But the childbirth was too much for her: she died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins only
1 CONT lived four days (14 March-18 March 1190) [1].
1 CONT
