1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (Valenciennes , 5 April 1170 – 15 March 1190, Paris) was
1 CONT queen consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Valenciennes, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut
1 CONT and Countess Margaret I of Flanders . She married King Philip II of France on
1 CONT 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought as her dowry the county of Artois . The
1 CONT marriage was arranged by her maternal uncle Count Philip of Flanders who was
1 CONT advisor to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne , the chroniclers
1 CONT of the time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian
1 CONT dynasties. Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists , she
1 CONT failed to win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him
1 CONT with an heir. Meanwhile, King Philip in 1184, was waging war against Flanders
1 CONT , and angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, he called a council at
1 CONT Sens for the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle,
1 CONT successfully interposed. Finally, on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the
1 CONT needed heir, the future King Louis VIII of France .
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. Due to complications in childbirth, Isabelle died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins lived
1 CONT only four days (14 March-18 March 1190). Her dowry of Artois eventually
1 CONT returned to the French Crown following the death of Philip.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (Valenciennes , 5 April 1170 – 15 March 1190, Paris) was
1 CONT queen consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Valenciennes, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut
1 CONT and Countess Margaret I of Flanders . She married King Philip II of France on
1 CONT 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought as her dowry the county of Artois . The
1 CONT marriage was arranged by her maternal uncle Count Philip of Flanders who was
1 CONT advisor to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne , the chroniclers
1 CONT of the time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian
1 CONT dynasties. Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists , she
1 CONT failed to win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him
1 CONT with an heir. Meanwhile, King Philip in 1184, was waging war against Flanders
1 CONT , and angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, he called a council at
1 CONT Sens for the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle,
1 CONT successfully interposed. Finally, on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the
1 CONT needed heir, the future King Louis VIII of France .
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. Due to complications in childbirth, Isabelle died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins lived
1 CONT only four days (14 March-18 March 1190). Her dowry of Artois eventually
1 CONT returned to the French Crown following the death of Philip.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (Valenciennes , 5 April 1170 – 15 March 1190, Paris) was
1 CONT queen consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Valenciennes, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut
1 CONT and Countess Margaret I of Flanders . She married King Philip II of France on
1 CONT 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought as her dowry the county of Artois . The
1 CONT marriage was arranged by her maternal uncle Count Philip of Flanders who was
1 CONT advisor to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne , the chroniclers
1 CONT of the time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian
1 CONT dynasties. Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists , she
1 CONT failed to win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him
1 CONT with an heir. Meanwhile, King Philip in 1184, was waging war against Flanders
1 CONT , and angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, he called a council at
1 CONT Sens for the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle,
1 CONT successfully interposed. Finally, on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the
1 CONT needed heir, the future King Louis VIII of France .
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. Due to complications in childbirth, Isabelle died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins lived
1 CONT only four days (14 March-18 March 1190). Her dowry of Artois eventually
1 CONT returned to the French Crown following the death of Philip.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Isabella of Hainault (Valenciennes,[1] 5 April 1170[2] – 15 March 1190, Paris)
1 CONT was queen consort of France as the first wife of King Philip II of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Queen of France
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella was born in Valenciennes, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of
1 CONT Hainaut, and Margaret I, Countess of Flanders. She married King Philip II of
1 CONT France on 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought as her dowry the county of
1 CONT Artois. The marriage was arranged by her maternal uncle Philip, Count of
1 CONT Flanders, who was advisor to the King.[3]
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella was crowned Queen of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As Baldwin
1 CONT V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the chroniclers of the
1 CONT time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian dynasties.
1 CONT Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists, she failed to
1 CONT win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him with an heir;
1 CONT although she was only 14 years old at the time.[3] Meanwhile, King Philip in
1 CONT 1184, was waging war against Flanders, and angered at seeing Baldwin support
1 CONT his enemies, he called a council at Sens for the purpose of repudiating her.
1 CONT Robert, the king's uncle, successfully interposed. Finally, on 5 September
1 CONT 1187, she gave birth to the needed heir, the future King Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabella gave
1 CONT birth to twin boys named Robert and Philip. Due to complications in
1 CONT childbirth, Isabella died the next day, and was buried in the cathedral of
1 CONT Notre Dame in Paris. She was not quite 20 years old. The twins lived only four
1 CONT days, both having died on 18 March 1190.[4] Isabella's dowry of Artois
1 CONT eventually returned to the French Crown following the death of King Philip.
