1 CONT (Research):Isabelle of Flanders, Countess of Artois, (1170-1190) daughter of
1 CONT Baudouin V-VIII, Count of Flanders & Hainault and Margarethe of Flanders Born
1 CONT April 1170 Valenciennes Died 15 March 1190 Paris Married 28 April 1180 Bapaume
1 CONT Philippe II August, King of France 1180-1223 Born 22 August 1165 Gonesse Died
1 CONT 14 July 1223 Mantes In 1179 she was promised in marriage to the son of the
1 CONT Count of Champagne; but when the political scene changed, she became engaged
1 CONT to the son of the king. The nuptials were to take place when she was nubile
1 CONT and, in 1184, she was judged to be so. However, as the political alliances had
1 CONT again changed, Philippe II August, under the influence of his uncles, tried to
1 CONT break off the marriage before it was consummated. The reason given was
1 CONT consanguinity but then young Isabelle went barefoot through the streets of the
1 CONT city , followed by lepers and the poor, all of whom joined her in demanding
1 CONT her rights outside the palace. Philippe took her back 'out of marital duty and
1 CONT without communicating with her in bed'. In 1187 she gave birth to a son,
1 CONT Louis, but three years later, after also having given birth to stillborn twins
1 CONT in 1190, she died shortly afterwards. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.
1 CONT Jump to: navigation, search
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (1170 - 1190) was queen consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Lille, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut and
1 CONT Countess Margaret I of Flanders. She married King Philip II of France in 1180
1 CONT and brought as her dowry the county of Artois.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on May 28, 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the chroniclers of the
1 CONT time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian dynasties.
1 CONT Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists, she failed to
1 CONT win the affections of Philip, who, in 1184, waging war against Flanders, was
1 CONT angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, and called a council at Sens
1 CONT for the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle, successfully
1 CONT interposed.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabella died in childbirth in 1190, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre
1 CONT Dame in Paris. Her son became Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT References
