1 CONT Basic Life Information
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut was born in Valenciennes, on 5 April 1170, daughter of
1 CONT Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut and Countess Margaret I of Flanders.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and Children
1 CONT
1 CONT She married King Philip II of France on 28 April 1180 at Bapaume and brought
1 CONT as her dowry the county of Artois. The marriage was arranged by her maternal
1 CONT uncle Count Philip of Alsace who was advisor to the King.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on 28 May 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V rightly claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the chroniclers
1 CONT of the time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian
1 CONT dynasties. Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists, she
1 CONT failed to win the affections of Philip due to her inability to provide him
1 CONT with an heir. Meanwhile, King Philip in 1184, was waging war against Flanders,
1 CONT and angered at seeing Baldwin support his enemies, he called a council at Sens
1 CONT for the purpose of repudiating her. Robert, the king's uncle, successfully
1 CONT interposed. Finally, on 5 September 1187, she gave birth to the needed heir,
1 CONT the future King Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. Due to complications in childbirth, Isabelle died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins lived
1 CONT only four days (14 March-18 March 1190)[4]. Her dowry of Artois eventually
1 CONT returned to the French Crown following the death of Philip.
