1 CONT Isabelle of Hainaut (23 April 1170, Lille - 15 March 1190, Paris) was queen
1 CONT consort of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was born in Lille, the daughter of Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut and
1 CONT Countess Margaret I of Flanders. She married King Philip II of France in 1180
1 CONT and brought as her dowry the county of Artois.
1 CONT
1 CONT Isabelle was crowned consort of France at Saint Denis on May 28, 1180. As
1 CONT Baldwin V claimed to be a descendant of Charlemagne, the chroniclers of the
1 CONT time saw in this marriage a union of the Carolingian and Capetian dynasties.
1 CONT Though she received extravagant praise from certain annalists, she failed to
1 CONT win the affections of Philip (possibly because he was supposedly engaged in an
1 CONT homosexual affair with Richard the Lionheart at that time), who, in 1184,
1 CONT waging war against Flanders, was angered at seeing Baldwin support his
1 CONT enemies, and called a council at Sens for the purpose of repudiating her.
1 CONT Robert, the king's uncle, successfully interposed. Finally, on 5 September
1 CONT 1187, she gave birth the needed heir, the future King Louis VIII of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Her second pregnancy, was extremely difficult; on 14 March 1190, Isabelle gave
1 CONT birth to twin sons. But the childbirth was too much for her: she died the next
1 CONT day, and was buried in the cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. The twins only
1 CONT lived four days (14 March-18 March 1190).
