1 CONT
1 CONT \-----------
1 CONT
1 CONT   * <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas,_Count_of_Savoy>
1 CONT
1 CONT **Thomas Ι** (Tommaso I; 1178 – 1 March 1233) was Count of Savoy from 1189 to
1 CONT 1233. He is sometimes numbered "Thomas I" to distinguish him from his son of
1 CONT the same name, who governed Savoy but was not count.
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas was born in Aiguebelle, the son of Humbert III of Savoy and Beatrice of
1 CONT Viennois. His birth was seen as miraculous; his monkish father had despaired
1 CONT of having a male heir after three wives. Count Humbert sought counsel from St.
1 CONT Anthelm, who blessed Humbert three times, and it was seen as a prophecy come
1 CONT true when Thomas was born shortly before Anthelm himself died on 26 June 1178.
1 CONT He was named in honour of Saint Thomas Becket.
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas was still a minor when his father died on 4 March 1189, and a council
1 CONT of regency was established, composed of his mother Beatrice, his father's
1 CONT cousin Boniface I of Montferrat, and the Bishop of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne. He
1 CONT had reached his majority by August 1191. Thomas possessed the martial
1 CONT abilities, energy, and brilliance that his father lacked, and Savoy enjoyed a
1 CONT golden age under his leadership. Despite his youth he began the push northwest
1 CONT into new territories. In the same year he granted Aosta Valley the "Charte des
1 CONT Franchises", recognising the right to administrative and political autonomy.
1 CONT This right was maintained until the eve of the French Revolution. Later he
1 CONT conquered Vaud, Bugey, and Carignano. He supported the Hohenstaufens, and was
1 CONT known as "Thomas the Ghibelline" because of his career as Imperial Vicar of
1 CONT Lombardy.
1 CONT
1 CONT # [<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas,_Count_of_Savoy#Career> Career]
1 CONT # [<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas,_Count_of_Savoy#Family_and_children>
1 CONT Family and children] /!\
1 CONT \--------
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#ThomasIdied1233B>
1 CONT
1 CONT THOMAS de Maurienne, son of HUMBERT III Comte de Maurienne et de Savoie & his
1 CONT fourth wife Béatrix de Vienne [Bourgogne-Comté] (Château de Carbonara 1178
1 CONT after 26 Jun-Moncalieri 1 Mar 1233, bur Saint-Michel de la Cluse). An undated
1 CONT charter records a donation to Saint-Maurice by "felicis memorie
1 CONT Humbertus…Savoie comes" and the confirmation by "Thomas filius eiusdem
1 CONT comitis"[258]. He succeeded his father in 1189 as THOMAS I Comte de Maurienne
1 CONT et de Savoie, under the regency of Guglielmo V Marchese di Monferrato who
1 CONT brokered a favourable settlement to Comte Humbert III's dispute with the
1 CONT empire[259]. As Marchese Guglielmo was absent in Palestine at the time of the
1 CONT death of Comte Humbert III, the regency was presumably held and the
1 CONT negotiations carried out by his son Bonifazio, who succeeded as Marchese di
1 CONT Monferrato in 1192. This hypothesis appears confirmed by the following
1 CONT charter: "Thomas…Mauriannensis comes et marchio Italiæ" confirmed the
1 CONT donations made by "pater meus…[et] domini comitis Humberti…abavi mei" to the
1 CONT canons of Saint-Jean de Maurienne, with the advice of "B. matris mee et…tutore
1 CONT meo Bonifacio marchione Montisferrati", by charter dated 12 Jun 1189[260].
1 CONT "Thomæ comitis et marchionis…et…Nichola filia comitis Gebennarum" granted
1 CONT privileges to the citizen of Susa by charter dated 25 Feb 1198[261]. He used
1 CONT the title Comte de Savoie: "Thomas comes Sabaud. et Amedeus eius filius"
1 CONT granted rights to the abbey of San Marco by charter dated 5 Mar 1200[262].
1 CONT Comte Thomas supported the imperial party over the Guelfs, and was appointed
1 CONT Imperial Vicar in Italy. Philipp King of Germany granted him Moudon in Vaud,
1 CONT and Chieri and Testona in Piemonte in 1207. He also acquired Carignano,
1 CONT Pinerolo, Moncalieri, Vigone, Albenga and Savona in Piemonte. "Thomas
1 CONT Maurianensis comes et marchio" donated property to the abbey of Saint-Maurice,
1 CONT with the consent of "filiis suis Amedeo et Humberto", by charter dated 8 Nov
1 CONT 1217[263]. A charter dated 1224 records an agreement between "Thomæ com.
1 CONT Sabaud" and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by "ipse Thomas comes, Amedeus
1 CONT primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum quatuor filii
1 CONT clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[264]. He bought the town of
1 CONT Chambéry in 1232. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the
1 CONT death in 1232 of "comitis Thome de Sabaudia"[265]. An indication of the
1 CONT precarious financial position of the counts of Savoy is provided by a third
1 CONT testament, dated 2 Nov 1240, made by Thomas´s son "Amadeus com Sab. et marchio
1 CONT in Italia" who repeated the nomination of "Thomæ, Flandriæ comiti, fratri suo"
1 CONT as his heir to "totius comitatus sui Sabaudiæ marchionatus Italiæ et ducatus
1 CONT Chablasii" if he died without male children, on condition that he satisfied
1 CONT all the debts of "Thomæ comitis patris et Humberti fratris ipsorum"[266].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** ( [1196] ) MARGUERITE [Beatrix] de Genève, daughter of GUILLAUME [I]
1 CONT Comte de Genève & his second wife Béatrix de Faucigny (-8 Apr 1257, bur Abbaye
1 CONT de Hautecombe). .. ... ..... ......
1 CONT
1 CONT Comte Thomas I & his wife had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Comte Thomas I had [four] illegitimate children by unknown mistresses: /!\
1 CONT
