1 CONT
1 CONT =Thomas I, Count of Savoy=
1 CONT
1 CONT [<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#Avoiedied1292> **From Wikipedia,
1 CONT the free encyclopedia** ]
1 CONT
1 CONT **Thomas I or Tommaso I** (1178, Aiguebelle – 1 March 1233) was Count of Savoy
1 CONT from 1189-1233. He was the son of Humbert III of Savoy and Beatrice of
1 CONT Viennois. His birth was seen as miraculous; his monkish father had despaired
1 CONT of having a male heir after three wives. Count Humbert sought counsel from St.
1 CONT Anthelm, who blessed Humbert three times, and it was seen as a prophecy come
1 CONT true when Thomas was born shortly before Anthelm himself died on 26 June 1178.
1 CONT He was named in honour of Saint Thomas Becket.
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas was still a minor when his father died on 4 March 1189, and a council
1 CONT of regency was established, comprising of his mother Beatrice, his father's
1 CONT cousin Boniface I of Montferrat, and the Bishop of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne. He
1 CONT had reached his majority by August 1191. Thomas possessed the martial
1 CONT abilities, energy, and brilliance that his father lacked, and Savoy enjoyed a
1 CONT golden age under his leadership. Despite his youth he began the push northwest
1 CONT into new territories. In the same year he granted Aosta Valley the "Carta
1 CONT delle Franchigie", recognising the right to administrative and political
1 CONT autonomy. This right was maintained up until the eve of the French Revolution.
1 CONT Later he conquered Vaud, Bugey, and Carignano. He supported the Hohenstaufens,
1 CONT and was known as "Thomas the Ghibelline" because of his career as Imperial
1 CONT Vicar of Lombardy.
1 CONT
1 CONT ===Family and children===
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1195 he ambushed the party of Count William I of Geneva, which was
1 CONT escorting the count's daughter, Margaret of Geneva, to France for her intended
1 CONT wedding to King Philip II of France. Thomas carried off Marguerite and married
1 CONT her himself, producing some eight sons and six daughters.
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Amedeo, his immediate successor
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Umberto, d. between March and November 1223
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Tommaso, lord and then count in Piedmont and founder of a line that became
1 CONT the Savoy-Achaea
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. Aimone, d. 30 August 1237, Lord of Chablais
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. Guglielmo (William of Savoy), Bishop of Valence and Dean of Vienne
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. Amadeo of Savoy, Bishop of Maurienne
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. Pietro, who resided much in England, became Earl of Richmond, and
1 CONT ultimately in 1263 became the disputed count of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. Filippo, archbishop of Lyon, who resigned, through marriage became Count
1 CONT Palatine of Burgundy and ultimately in 1268 became the disputed count of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. Bonifacio who became archbishop of Canterbury
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. Beatrice of Savoy, d. 1265 or 1266, married in December 1219 to Ramon
1 CONT Berenguer IV, Count of Provence (1209-1245) and was mother of four Queens-
1 CONT consort
1 CONT
1 CONT 11\. Alasia of Savoy, abbess of the monastery of St Pierre in Lyon (d.1250)
1 CONT
1 CONT 12\. Ágatha of Savoy, abbess of the monastery of St Pierre in Lyon (d.1245)
1 CONT
1 CONT 13\. Margherita of Savoy, d. 1273, married in 1218 to Hartmann I of Kyburg
1 CONT
1 CONT 14\. Avita of Savoy (1215-92) who married Baldwin de Redvers, 7th Earl of
1 CONT Devon and Robert Aguillon (d.1286).
