1 CONT [<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ENGLISH%20NOBILITY%20MEDIEVAL1.htm#_Toc434831797>
1 CONT **From Medlands:** ]
1 CONT
1 CONT **THOMAS de Maurienne** , son of HUMBERT III Comte de Maurienne et de Savoie &
1 CONT his fourth wife Béatrix de Vienne [Bourgogne-Comté] (Château de Carbonara 1178
1 CONT after 26 Jun-Moncalieri 1 Mar 1233, bur Saint-Michel de la Cluse). An undated
1 CONT charter records a donation to Saint-Maurice by "felicis memorie
1 CONT Humbertus…Savoie comes" and the confirmation by "Thomas filius eiusdem
1 CONT comitis"[258]. He succeeded his father in 1189 as **THOMAS I Comte de
1 CONT Maurienne et de Savoie** , under the regency of Guglielmo V Marchese di
1 CONT Monferrato who brokered a favourable settlement to Comte Humbert III's dispute
1 CONT with the empire[259]. As Marchese Guglielmo was absent in Palestine at the
1 CONT time of the death of Comte Humbert III, the regency was presumably held and
1 CONT the negotiations carried out by his son Bonifazio, who succeeded as Marchese
1 CONT di Monferrato in 1192. This hypothesis appears confirmed by the following
1 CONT charter: "Thomas…Mauriannensis comes et marchio Italiæ" confirmed the
1 CONT donations made by "pater meus…[et] domini comitis Humberti…abavi mei" to the
1 CONT canons of Saint-Jean de Maurienne, with the advice of "B. matris mee et…tutore
1 CONT meo Bonifacio marchione Montisferrati", by charter dated 12 Jun 1189[260].
1 CONT "Thomæ comitis et marchionis…et…Nichola filia comitis Gebennarum" granted
1 CONT privileges to the citizen of Susa by charter dated 25 Feb 1198[261]. He used
1 CONT the title Comte de Savoie: "Thomas comes Sabaud. et Amedeus eius filius"
1 CONT granted rights to the abbey of San Marco by charter dated 5 Mar 1200[262].
1 CONT Comte Thomas supported the imperial party over the Guelfs, and was appointed
1 CONT Imperial Vicar in Italy. Philipp King of Germany granted him Moudon in Vaud,
1 CONT and Chieri and Testona in Piemonte in 1207. He also acquired Carignano,
1 CONT Pinerolo, Moncalieri, Vigone, Albenga and Savona in Piemonte. "Thomas
1 CONT Maurianensis comes et marchio" donated property to the abbey of Saint-Maurice,
1 CONT with the consent of "filiis suis Amedeo et Humberto", by charter dated 8 Nov
1 CONT 1217[263]. A charter dated 1224 records an agreement between "Thomæ com.
1 CONT Sabaud" and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by "ipse Thomas comes, Amedeus
1 CONT primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum quatuor filii
1 CONT clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[264]. He bought the town of
1 CONT Chambéry in 1232. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the
1 CONT death in 1232 of "comitis Thome de Sabaudia"[265]. An indication of the
1 CONT precarious financial position of the counts of Savoy is provided by a third
1 CONT testament, dated 2 Nov 1240, made by Thomas´s son "Amadeus com Sab. et marchio
1 CONT in Italia" who repeated the nomination of "Thomæ, Flandriæ comiti, fratri suo"
1 CONT as his heir to "totius comitatus sui Sabaudiæ marchionatus Italiæ et ducatus
1 CONT Chablasii" if he died without male children, on condition that he satisfied
1 CONT all the debts of "Thomæ comitis patris et Humberti fratris ipsorum"[266].
1 CONT
1 CONT m ([1196]) **MARGUERITE [Beatrix] de Genève** , daughter of GUILLAUME [I]
1 CONT Comte de Genève & his second wife Béatrix de Faucigny (-8 Apr 1257, bur Abbaye
1 CONT de Hautecombe). The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines names "Margareta
1 CONT filia domni de Fusceneis de matre Guilelmi, filii Humberti comitis Gebenensis"
1 CONT as wife of "comitis Thome de Sabaudia"[267]. As noted below, Marguerite is
1 CONT also called Beatrix in later sources. No explanation has been found for these
1 CONT dual names. The fact that "Beatrix" appears in a seal shows that it was not a
1 CONT transcription error. "Thomæ comitis et marchionis…et…Nichola [presumably a
1 CONT transcription error] filia comitis Gebennarum" granted privileges to the
1 CONT citizen of Susa by charter dated 25 Feb 1198[268]. The Complete Peerage[269]
1 CONT refers to unspecified "later writers" having evolved an incorrect theory that
1 CONT Thomas I Comte de Maurienne was married firstly to Béatrix and, after her
1 CONT death without issue, secondly to Marguerite, daughter of Guillaume de
1 CONT Faucigny, who was the mother of his children. The same source confirms that
1 CONT the two names in fact refer to the same person. A charter dated 1224 records
1 CONT an agreement between "Thomæ com. Sabaud" and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by
1 CONT "ipse Thomas comes, Amedeus primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum
1 CONT quatuor filii clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[270]. "M.
1 CONT comitissa Maurian. uxor Thomæ comitis Maurianensis et marchionis Italiæ"
1 CONT donated property, with the consent of "Thomas com. Maurianæ et filii mei
1 CONT Amedeus et Aymo", by charter dated Dec 1227[271]. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et
1 CONT marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus, Aymo, W. electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus,
1 CONT Bonifacius et Philippus filii Thome Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia"
1 CONT confirmed donations to Hautecombe abbey by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[272].
1 CONT "Beatrix uxor comitis Thomæ, Amadeus primogenitus et Aymo filii eius"
1 CONT confirmed the purchase of Chambéry by "Thoma comite" by charter dated 1232,
1 CONT with the seal of "Beatricis comitisse Sabaudie"[273]. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie
1 CONT et in Italie marchio…cum…genetrice sua et fratribus suis B. Bellicensi Electo
1 CONT et Philippo Metensi Primicerio" granted "villam S. Mauritii de Chablaisio"
1 CONT Saint-Maurice de Chablais to "soror illorum Margareta comitissa de Kiborch" by
1 CONT charter dated 24 Feb 1240[274]. "Contessa Margarita di Savoia Marchesa in
1 CONT Italia" donated property to "Tomaso suo figlio Conte di Fiandra e d'Hainaut"
1 CONT with the consent of "Conte Amedeo di Savoia suo figlio Primogenito", by
1 CONT charter dated 4 Jan 1244[275]. The Pingonio Chronicon records the death "VI Id
1 CONT Apr" in 1257 of "Domina Beatrix de Gebennis comitissa Sabaudie et domina de
1 CONT Narembors, parens comitum Sabaudie"[276].
1 CONT
1 CONT Comte Thomas I & his wife had fourteen children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. **AMEDEE de Savoie** (Montmélian, Savoie 1197-Montmélian 13 Jul 1253, bur
1 CONT Abbaye de Hautecombe). "Thomas comes Sabaud. et Amedeus eius filius" granted
1 CONT rights to the abbey of San Marco by charter dated 5 Mar 1200[277]. His
1 CONT parentage is confirmed by, inter alia, Matthew of Paris who specifies that
1 CONT Beatrix de Savoie was "soror comitis Sabaldiæ adhuc viventis Amidei", when he
1 CONT records the marriage of her daughter to Henry III King of England[278]. In a
1 CONT later passage, the same source records Amedée as "primogenitus" among the
1 CONT "filii comitis Sabaudiæ Thomæ avunculi dominæ reginæ Angliæ Alienoræ"[279].
1 CONT "Thomas Maurianensis comes et marchio" donated property to the abbey of Saint-
1 CONT Maurice, with the consent of "filiis suis Amedeo et Humberto", by charter
1 CONT dated 8 Nov 1217[280]. A charter dated 1224 records an agreement between
1 CONT "Thomæ com. Sabaud " and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by "ipse Thomas comes,
1 CONT Amedeus primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum quatuor filii
1 CONT clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[281]. "M. comitissa Maurian.
1 CONT uxor Thomæ comitis Maurianensis et marchionis Italiæ" donated property, with
1 CONT the consent of "Thomas com. Maurianæ et filii mei Amedeus et Aymo", by charter
1 CONT dated Dec 1227[282]. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus,
1 CONT Aymo, W. electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus, Bonifacius et Philippus filii
1 CONT Thome Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia" confirmed donations to Hautecombe
1 CONT abbey by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[283]. "Beatrix uxor comitis Thomæ, Amadeus
1 CONT primogenitus et Aymo filii eius" confirmed the purchase of Chambéry by "Thoma
1 CONT comite" by charter dated 1232, with the seal of "Beatricis comitisse
1 CONT Sabaudie"[284]. He succeeded his father in 1233 as AMEDEE IV Comte de Savoie,
1 CONT Marchese in Italy. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie et in Italia marchio" confirmed his
1 CONT father´s grant of privileges to Susa by charter dated 7 Mar 1233[285]. A
1 CONT charter dated 23 Jul 1234 records an agreement between "Amedeum comitem
1 CONT Sabaudie" and "Aymonem et Petrum fratres ipsius" in settlement of a dispute
1 CONT concerning their paternal inheritance[286]. The first testament of "Amedei
1 CONT comitis Sab. et marchionis Italie", dated 23 Sep 1235, appoints "Thomam
1 CONT fratrem suum" as his heir "in comitatu et marchionatu" in default of male
1 CONT children[287]. This document disinherits Thomas´s older brother Aimon. The
1 CONT second testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie", dated 19 Jul 1238, repeats the
1 CONT nomination of "Thomam fratrem suum" as his heir, substituting "Philippum, huic
1 CONT autem Petrum fratres suos" if Thomas died without male heirs[288]. He was an
1 CONT active supporter of Emperor Friedrich II. He acquired territories in Vaud and
1 CONT lower Valais. In 1238, Comte Amedée was created Duc de Chablais and Aosta, and
1 CONT nominated Imperial Vicar in northern Italy, by the emperor in reward for his
1 CONT support against the Lombards[289]. Under a third testament, dated 2 Nov 1240,
1 CONT "Amadeus com Sab. et marchio in Italia" repeated the nomination of "Thomæ,
1 CONT Flandriæ comiti, fratri suo" as his heir to "totius comitatus sui Sabaudiæ
1 CONT marchionatus Italiæ et ducatus Chablasii" if he died without male children, on
1 CONT condition that he satisfied all the debts of "Thomæ comitis patris et Humberti
1 CONT fratris ipsorum"[290]. A charter dated 1244 confirmed the peace agreement
1 CONT reached between the bishop of Lausanne and "Amadeus comes Sabaudie et in
1 CONT Italia marcho et…Petrus de Sabaudia…frater suus"[291]. Emperor Friedrich II
1 CONT recognised Amedée's rights over Turin in 1248. On the emperor's death in 1250,
1 CONT Comte Amedée's reconciliation with Pope Innocent IV was sealed by the marriage
1 CONT of the Pope's niece to Comte Amedée's brother Thomas[292]. A fourth testament
1 CONT of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium
1 CONT meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting
1 CONT "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam
1 CONT Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii
1 CONT marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea
1 CONT minor"[293]. A fifth testament of Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253,
1 CONT appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir,
1 CONT substitutes "filiæ Amedei comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et
1 CONT Margaretha Montisferrati", bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ
1 CONT comitissæ", and chooses to be buried at Hautecombe[294]. An epitaph in
1 CONT Hautecombe abbey records the death "III Id Jul" in 1253 of "Dominus
1 CONT Amedeus…comes Sabaudie"[295]. Betrothed (28 Apr 1213) to AGNESE di Saluzzo,
1 CONT daughter of BONIFAZIO Marchese di Saluzzo & his wife Maria di Torres [in
1 CONT Sardinia] (-after 1219). The marriage contract between "Thomam comitem
1 CONT Maurienne…Amedeo f. dicti comitis" and "Manfredum II marchionem de
1 CONT Saluciis…Agnetem f. quondam Bonefacii" is dated 28 Apr 1213[296]. m firstly
1 CONT (before 1221) MARGUERITE de Bourgogne, daughter of HUGUES III Duke of Burgundy
1 CONT [Capet] & his second wife Béatrix Dauphine de Viennois ([1192]-[1228/30] or
1 CONT [1242]). The testament of "Guigo Dalphinus, Vienn. et Albonis comitis", dated
1 CONT 27 Jun 1267, confirmed donations made by "…matertera Margarita vel Domina
1 CONT Ducissa avia mea…meæ amitæ quondam comitissæ Sabaudiæ"[297]. It is not clear
1 CONT from this document whether "matertera Margarita" and "meæ amitæ quondam
1 CONT comitissæ Sabaudiæ" refer to the same person as they are named in the context
1 CONT of two separate donations in different parts of the testament. The use of
1 CONT "matertera" and "amitæ" as two different terms to express the relationship
1 CONT "aunt" suggests that they may have been different individuals. Valbonnais
1 CONT assumes that they were the same person, "Marguerite sœur du dauphin André" who
1 CONT married "Amé fils de Thomas Comte de Savoie", and adds that "la duchesse
1 CONT Beatrix" named "son héritier le Dauphin André son fils…Matilde sa fille aînée
1 CONT femme de Jean Comte de Chalon…Marguerite son autre fille épouse d´Amedée fils
1 CONT du comte de Savoye" in her testament dated 1228[298]. If the suggested second
1 CONT marriage of Comte Amedée is correctly shown below, Marguerite de Bourgogne
1 CONT must have died in [1228/30]. If it is incorrect, her date of death is
1 CONT estimated to [1242]. [m secondly ([1228/30]) MARGUERITE de Viennois, daughter
1 CONT of ANDRE de Bourgogne [Capet] Comte d´Albon, Dauphin & his first wife Beatrix
1 CONT de Sabran ([1203/07]-[1242]). The Inventory of the State Archives of
1 CONT Turin[299] mentions a document dated 1230 which refers to the marriage of
1 CONT Comte Amedée with "Marguerite daughter of André dauphin, comte de Viennois",
1 CONT but without giving the context (marriage contract, appointment of proxy etc.).
1 CONT Although her mother is not named, the date of the document suggests that it is
1 CONT likely that Marguerite would have been born from her supposed father's first
1 CONT marriage. However, there is some doubt whether this reference can be correct.
1 CONT As noted above, two primary sources indicate that Comte Amedée IV married
1 CONT Marguerite de Bourgogne as his first wife, one source indicating that she was
1 CONT still alive in 1228. Marguerite de Viennois would therefore have been the
1 CONT niece of Comte Amedée´s first wife. Such a relationship by marriage would have
1 CONT necessitated a papal dispensation, which may not have been easily obtained
1 CONT given the closeness of the affinity. In addition, this supposed second
1 CONT marriage would have taken place during the papacy of Pope Gregory IX, who is
1 CONT recorded as granting only 11 dispensations during his 14 year reign (6 of
1 CONT which related to validating existing marriages), which suggests that he was
1 CONT "averse to dispensing from the impediments of relationship"[300]. Another
1 CONT possibility is that the Inventory of State Archives mistook "daughter" for
1 CONT "sister" in its extract, and that the 1230 document refers to Comte Amedée´s
1 CONT earlier marriage to Marguerite de Bourgogne. Since writing the above comment,
1 CONT an updated version of the online State Archives Inventory now suggests that
1 CONT this possibility may be correct: while the new summary still refers to
1 CONT “Matrimoni. Amedeo IV di Savoia e Margherita figlia di Andrea Delfino conte di
1 CONT Vienna”, a further extract states that the document records that “Margherita
1 CONT di Vienne” gave receipt “al fratello Andrea Delfino di Vienne” for the sum
1 CONT bequeathed to her “in testamento dalla madre Beatrice contessa di
1 CONT Vienne”[301]. The original document has not been consulted to verify how this
1 CONT conflict is resolved. Altogether, this possible second marriage, based only on
1 CONT this index entry, now looks unlikely to be correct.] m [secondly/thirdly]
1 CONT (contract 22 Nov 1244, by proxy Orange 18 Dec 1244) CECILE des Baux, daughter
1 CONT of BARRAL Seigneur des Baux & his wife Béatrice d'Anduze (-21 May 1275). The
1 CONT contract of marriage between "Amedeum comitem Sabaudiæ" and "Cæciliam Barralis
1 CONT domini Baucii filiam" is dated 18 Dec 1243, witnessed by "Humbertum de Seyssel
1 CONT dominum Aquarum…Raymundo de Baucio principe Aurasiæ, Guillelmo de Baucio
1 CONT nepote illius…"[302]. A charter dated 22 Nov 1244 records the agreement for
1 CONT the marriage of “dominum Amedeum comitem Sabaudie” and “dominam Ceciliam,
1 CONT neptem…domini R. comitis Tolosani, filiam…domini Barralli del Bauz”[303]. A
1 CONT charter dated 18 Dec 1244 confirms the celebration by proxy of the marriage
1 CONT between "Amedée IV Comte de Savoie, marquis d'Italie" (represented by "Humbert
1 CONT de Seyssel") and "Cécile fille de Barral de Baux" at the "chapelle Sainte-
1 CONT Marie d'Orange", in the presence of "Raymond de Baux I, son neveu Raymond II
1 CONT prince et co-prince d'Orange, Guillaume de Sabran, et B. de Baux chanoine
1 CONT d'Avignon"[304]. Raymond VII Comte de Toulouse, Marquis de Provence granted
1 CONT all his property beyond the Rhône to "sa niece Cécile de Baux, fille de
1 CONT Barral" by charter dated 24 Feb 1241[305], which may explain why Cécile was
1 CONT such a good marriage prospect for the comte de Savoie. A fourth testament of
1 CONT "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium
1 CONT meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting
1 CONT "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam
1 CONT Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii
1 CONT marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea
1 CONT minor"[306]. Her husband granted her the castles of Momigliano, La Rocchetta,
1 CONT e Terra della Tarantasia for life by charter dated 24 May 1253[307]. A fifth
1 CONT testament of Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253, appoints "Bonifacius filius
1 CONT suus, sub tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir, substitutes "filiæ Amedei
1 CONT comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et Margaretha Montisferrati",
1 CONT bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ", and chooses to be
1 CONT buried at Hautecombe[308]. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" granted "castrum Montis
1 CONT Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ conjugi suæ" for life, on condition that she
1 CONT allows "Bonifacium filium ex matrimonio eorum procreatum" to live with
1 CONT her[309]. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii comitis
1 CONT Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, adds bequests to "…Cæciliæ relictæ Amedei
1 CONT Sabaudiæ comitis…"[310]. "Cæciliæ comitissæ relictæ Amedei quondam comitis
1 CONT Sabaudiæ" donated property by charter dated 19 Jan 1268[311]. "Cecilia Vedova
1 CONT del Conte Amedeo di Savoia" granted property which she inherited after the
1 CONT death of "Bonifacio suo figlio" to "Filippo Conte di Savoia e di Borgonia" by
1 CONT charter dated Oct 1268[312]. Comte Amedée IV & his first wife had two
1 CONT children:
1 CONT a) BEATRIX de Savoie (before 4 Mar 1223-10 May before 1259). The marriage
1 CONT contract between "Alaxiam comitissam Saluciarum et Manfredum marchionem
1 CONT Saluciarum eius nepotem" and "Thomam comitem Maurianæ…neptem suam…Beatrix" is
1 CONT dated 4 Mar 1223[313]. A contract dated 2 Oct 1227 between "Marchese Enrico di
1 CONT Savona" and "il Marchese Manfredo di Saluzzo" refers to the dowry of "Marchese
1 CONT di Savona…sua Consorte, figlia di Amedeo figlio del Conte di Savoia"[314].
1 CONT Beatrix must have born in the early 1220s as she had three children by her
1 CONT first husband who died in 1244. The Istoria of Saba Malaspina records that
1 CONT "Manfredus" married "natam Amadei comitis Sabaudiæ…Beatricem"[315]. The
1 CONT Historia Sicula of Bartolomeo di Neocastro records that "Manfredus" married
1 CONT "dominam Beatricem filiam ducis Sex Viarum, qui prius in virum…marchionem de
1 CONT Salluciis"[316]. Her second marriage was arranged in recognition of the
1 CONT alliance between her father and Emperor Friedrich II. A charter dated 8 May
1 CONT 1246 records the restitution of "castri Ripolarum" by Emperor Friedrich II to
1 CONT "fratribus de Sabaudia, Amedeo comite et Thoma", confirmed by the betrothal of
1 CONT "Manfredum dictum Lancea, filium naturalem imperatoris" and "Beatricem filiam
1 CONT Amedei comitis, relictam Manfredi marchionis Salucensis"[317]. The proxy of
1 CONT marriage between "Manfredo Lanza di Lui [Imperator Federico secundo] figlio"
1 CONT and "la Contessa di Saluzzo figlia del Conte Amedeo di Savoia" is dated Mar
1 CONT 1247[318]. The contract of marriage between "Manfredi Lanceæ filii Friderici
1 CONT Rom. Imperatoris" and "Beatrice marchionissa Salutiensi, filia Amedei comitis
1 CONT Sabaudiæ et in Italia marchionis, relicta Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum" is
1 CONT dated 21 Apr 1247[319]. A fourth testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is
1 CONT dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium meum" as his heir, under the
1 CONT tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia
1 CONT comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et
1 CONT Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii marchionis Montisferrati", and names
1 CONT "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea minor"[320]. A fifth testament of
1 CONT Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253, appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub
1 CONT tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir, substitutes "filiæ Amedei
1 CONT comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et Margaretha Montisferrati",
1 CONT bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ", and chooses to be
1 CONT buried at Hautecombe[321]. The absence of any reference to Beatrix´s current
1 CONT husband King Manfred suggests a breakdown in their marriage. m firstly
1 CONT (betrothed 4 Mar 1223 and 2 Oct 1227, Mar 1233) MANFREDO III Marchese di
1 CONT Saluzzo, son of BONIFAZIO di Saluzzo & his wife Maria di Torres [in Sardinia]
1 CONT (-29 Oct 1244). m secondly (Betrothed 8 May 1246, by proxy Mar 1247, contract
1 CONT 21 Apr 1247, [Dec 1248/Jan 1249]) as his first wife, MANFRED von Hohenstaufen,
1 CONT illegitimate son of Emperor FRIEDRICH II King of Sicily & his mistress Bianca
1 CONT Lancia (Venosa 1232-killed in battle Benevento 26 Feb 1266). At the time of
1 CONT his marriage, his father constituted him Lord of territory from Pavia to
1 CONT Genoa. He succeeded as Principe di Tarento in 1250 on the death of his father.
1 CONT Regent of Sicily in 1254, he was crowned MANFREDO King of Sicily at Palermo 10
1 CONT Aug 1258. b) MARGUERITE de Savoie ([1224/28]-after 14 Jan 1264). "Thomas comes
1 CONT Maurianæ" donated property to "Bonifacio Marchioni Montisferrati" by way of
1 CONT dowry of "Margarethæ futuræ uxoris Bonifacii et filiæ Amedei Sabaudia
1 CONT primogeniti Thomæ comitis" by charter dated 18 Jan 1228[322]. It is unlikely
1 CONT that Marguerite was born much later than 1228 as her mother was at that date
1 CONT already at least 36 years old, and Marguerite herself had at least three
1 CONT children before she died in 1254. The date of her marriage is confirmed by a
1 CONT charter dated 18 Nov 1235, which confirmed a pact between her father and the
1 CONT bishop of Torino, approved by "domina Margarita eius filia…uxor dom. Bonifacii
1 CONT marchionis Montisferrati"[323]. "Bonifacius marchio Montisferrati" donated
1 CONT property to "uxori suæ Margarethæ, Amadei comitis Sab. filiæ" by charter dated
1 CONT 9 Dec 1235[324]. A fourth testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19
1 CONT Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of
1 CONT his brother Thomas, substituting "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia
1 CONT comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et
1 CONT Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii marchionis Montisferrati", and names
1 CONT "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea minor"[325]. A fifth testament of
1 CONT Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253, appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub
1 CONT tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir, substitutes "filiæ Amedei
1 CONT comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et Margaretha Montisferrati",
1 CONT bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ", and chooses to be
1 CONT buried at Hautecombe[326]. The testament of "Bonefacius Montisferrati
1 CONT marchio", dated 12 Jun 1253, bequeathes property to "Alaxinam filiam meam
1 CONT inpuberem", appoints "Guilelminum filium meum inpuberem" as his heir,
1 CONT substituting in turn "Alaxinam…filia mea" and "Tomam de Saluciis", if his son
1 CONT died childless, and appoints "dominam Margaritam comitissam uxorem mea matrem
1 CONT ipsius Guilelmini et dominum comitem de Sabaldia et dominum Tomam de Sabaldia
1 CONT fratrem suum et Dalfinum de Vianesio et dominum Jacobum de Careto et dominum
1 CONT Georgium et dominum Manuellem de Ceva et Bastardinum de Monteferrato" as
1 CONT guardians of his son[327]. Her second marriage is shown in Europäische
1 CONT Stammtafeln[328], although this is inconsistent with her dying in 1254 as
1 CONT shown in another table[329]. The primary source which confirms her second
1 CONT marriage has not yet been identified. The marriage is not given by Jules
1 CONT Chevalier[330]. It is possible that the dispensation was issued but that the
1 CONT marriage never actually took place. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ
1 CONT Raimundi Berengarii comitis Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, adds bequests to
1 CONT "…Margarithæ matri marchionis Montisferrati nepti suæ…"[331]. m [firstly]
1 CONT (Betrothed 18 Jan 1228, before 18 Nov 1235) BONIFACIO II Marchese di
1 CONT Monferrato, son of GUGLIELMO VI Marchese di Monferrato & his second wife Berta
1 CONT di Clavesana (-[12 Jun 1253/10 Dec 1255]). [m secondly (Papal dispensation 26
1 CONT Jan 1255) as his second wife, AYMAR [III] Comte de Valentinois, son of
1 CONT GUILLAUME II Comte de Valentinois & his wife Flotte de Royans (-[6 May/17 Jun]
1 CONT 1277, bur Bonlieu).] Comte Amedée IV & his [second/third] wife had four
1 CONT children: c) BONIFACE de Savoie (-Turin [7 Jun] 1263, bur Saint-Jean de
1 CONT Maurienne, transferred to Saint-Michel de la Cluse). A fourth testament of
1 CONT "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium
1 CONT meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting
1 CONT "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam
1 CONT Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii
1 CONT marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea
1 CONT minor"[332]. A fifth testament of Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253,
1 CONT appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir,
1 CONT substitutes "filiæ Amedei comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et
1 CONT Margaretha Montisferrati", bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ
1 CONT comitissæ", and chooses to be buried at Hautecombe[333]. "Amedeus comes
1 CONT Sabaudie" granted "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ conjugi suæ"
1 CONT for life, on condition that she allows "Bonifacium filium ex matrimonio eorum
1 CONT procreatum" to live with her He succeeded his father in 1253 as BONIFACE
1 CONT "Roland" Comte de Savoie. He led campaigns in Flanders and Piemonte which were
1 CONT disastrous for Savoy[334]. d) BEATRIX de Savoie (-Escalona Nov 1290 or 23 Feb
1 CONT 1292). A fourth testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252,
1 CONT appoints "Bonifacium filium meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his
1 CONT brother Thomas, substituting "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem
1 CONT filiam meam uxorem quondam Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam
1 CONT meam uxorem Bonifacii marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori
1 CONT nostre…Beatrix filia mea minor"[335]. Amedée IV Comte de Savoie granted money
1 CONT to "Beatrici juniori, filiæ suæ e Cecilia prognatæ", at the request of
1 CONT "Cæciliæ uxoris suæ", by charter dated 28 May 1253[336]. Zurita records the
1 CONT betrothal of “Infante Don Iayme” and “una hija del Conde Amadeo de
1 CONT Saboya...Beatriz” in 1263[337]. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi
1 CONT Berengarii comitis Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, orders "Contissona filia
1 CONT Amedei comitis…" to fulfil religious bequests[338]. The following reference
1 CONT shows that Beatrix was known as "Contesson". "Contessa Beatrice detta
1 CONT Contesson figlia del fu Conte Amedeo di Savoia e della Contessa Cecilia"
1 CONT renounced her rights of succession with the consent of her mother and "Pietro
1 CONT Boverio di Lei Marito" in favour of "Conte Filippo di Savoia di Lei Patruo" by
1 CONT contract dated 21 Oct 1268[339]. Pope Clement IV wrote 11 Aug 1266 to
1 CONT "Jacobo…filii…Regis Aragonum" requiring him to comply with the marriage
1 CONT contract with "filiam B. natam bonæ memoriæ Comitis Sabaudiæ"[340]. Although
1 CONT this document does not name the Comte de Savoie in question, Comte Amedée IV
1 CONT was the only one who was recently deceased ("bonæ memoriæ") at the date of the
1 CONT letter. If this is correct, the betrothed must have been his daughter Beatrix,
1 CONT the only one whose name began with the letter b. Under another testament dated
1 CONT 7 May 1268, "Petrus comes Sabaudia" granted bequests to "…B. filiam Amedei
1 CONT comitis…fratris nostri quondam…"[341]. "Pietro Bovero figlio del Conte Gioanni
1 CONT di Borgogna e Signore di Salins" donated property to "Beatrice figlia del
1 CONT Conte Amedeo di Savoia sua future Sposa" by contract dated "la Festa di S.
1 CONT Luca 1269"[342]. The primary source which confirms her second marriage has not
1 CONT yet been identified. The Chronicon Domini Joannis Emmanuelis records the
1 CONT marriage in 1275 of “Infans Dns Emmanuel cum Comitissa” in the same month as
1 CONT the death of his son Alfonso[343]. The Chronicon Domini Joannis Emmanuelis
1 CONT records the death in Nov 1290 of “Comitissa, mater Dni Joannis, in
1 CONT Escalona”[344]. Betrothed (1263, contract broken before 11 Aug 1266) to
1 CONT Infante don JAIME de Aragón, son of don JAIME I "el Conquistador" King of
1 CONT Aragon & his second wife Iolanda of Hungary (Barcelona [or Montpellier?]
1 CONT 1243-Palma de Mallorca 29 May 1311). He succeeded his father in 1276 as JAIME
1 CONT II King of Mallorca. m firstly (21 Oct 1268) PIERRE "le Bouvier" de Salins
1 CONT Seigneur de Châtelbelin, son of JEAN I "l'Antique/le Sage" Seigneur de Salins
1 CONT [Bourgogne-Comté] & his second wife Isabelle de Courtenay (-[21 Jul 1272/29
1 CONT Apr 1274]). m secondly (1275) as his second wife, Infante don MANUEL de
1 CONT Castilla y León, Señor de Escalona y Peñafiel, son of FERNANDO III “el Santo”
1 CONT King of Castile & his first wife Elisabeth von Hohenstaufen (Carrión de los
1 CONT Condes 1234-Peñafiel 25 Dec 1283, bur Uclés, Santiago convent). e) ELEONORE de
1 CONT Savoie. She is not mentioned in either the 19 Sep 1252 or 24 May 1253
1 CONT testaments of her father[345], which suggests that she may have born
1 CONT posthumously, in which case she must have been the twin of her sister
1 CONT Constance. The testament of "Beatrice Vedova del Re Berengario Conte di
1 CONT Provenza" dated 14 Jan 1264 makes bequests "…a Contesson…più ad Eleonora altra
1 CONT sua figlia…"[346]. The primary source which confirms her marriage has not yet
1 CONT been identified. m (1269) GUICHARD de Forez, son of RENAUD Comte de Forez
1 CONT [Albon] & his wife Isabelle Dame de Beaujeu. f) CONSTANCE de Savoie (-[before
1 CONT 14 Jan 1264]). Guichenon names Constance as daughter of Comte Amedée IV,
1 CONT adding that she died unmarried[347]. The primary source which confirms her
1 CONT parentage has not yet been identified. She is not mentioned in either the 19
1 CONT Sep 1252 or 24 May 1253 testaments of her father[348], which suggests that she
1 CONT may have born posthumously, in which case she must have been the twin of her
1 CONT sister Eléonore. She probably died before 14 Jan 1264, the date of the
1 CONT testament of "Beatrice Vedova del Re Berengario Conte di Provenza" under which
1 CONT her two older sisters received bequests and in which she is not named[349].
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. **HUMBERT de Savoie** ([1198]-in Hungary 1223). "Thomas Maurianensis comes
1 CONT et marchio" donated property to the abbey of Saint-Maurice, with the consent
1 CONT of "filiis suis Amedeo et Humberto", by charter dated 8 Nov 1217[350]. An
1 CONT indication of Humbert´s precarious financial position is provided by a third
1 CONT testament, dated 2 Nov 1240, made by Thomas´s son "Amadeus com Sab. et marchio
1 CONT in Italia" who repeated the nomination of "Thomæ, Flandriæ comiti, fratri suo"
1 CONT as his heir to "totius comitatus sui Sabaudiæ marchionatus Italiæ et ducatus
1 CONT Chablasii" if he died without male children, on condition that he satisfied
1 CONT all the debts of "Thomæ comitis patris et Humberti fratris ipsorum"[351]. The
1 CONT testament of "Thomas de Sabaudia comes" dated 26 Jun 1248 remembers the souls
1 CONT of "bonæ memoriæ Thoma quondam comite Sabaudiæ patre meo…fratribus meis
1 CONT Umberto…Aymone et Vuillermo quondam electo Valentinensi"[352]. Europäische
1 CONT Stammtafeln[353] shows two sons of Comte Thomas I both named Humbert, without
1 CONT any dates of birth or death for the second. The 26 Jun 1248 testament of
1 CONT Humbert's brother Thomas de Savoie[354] includes bequests for masses for the
1 CONT souls of his "late brothers Humbert, Aimon, Guillaume", indicating that there
1 CONT was only one brother of each name.
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. **AYMON de Savoie** ([1200]-1242). "M. comitissa Maurian. uxor Thomæ
1 CONT comitis Maurianensis et marchionis Italiæ" donated property, with the consent
1 CONT of "Thomas com. Maurianæ et filii mei Amedeus et Aymo", by charter dated Dec
1 CONT 1227[355]. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus, Aymo, W.
1 CONT electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus, Bonifacius et Philippus filii Thome
1 CONT Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia" confirmed donations to Hautecombe abbey
1 CONT by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[356]. "Beatrix uxor comitis Thomæ, Amadeus
1 CONT primogenitus et Aymo filii eius" confirmed the purchase of Chambéry by "Thoma
1 CONT comite" by charter dated 1232, with the seal of "Beatricis comitisse
1 CONT Sabaudie"[357]. "Haymo filius quondam bonæ memoriæ Thome com. Sab. et march.
1 CONT in Italia" donated property to Hautecombe by charter dated 1233[358]. A
1 CONT charter dated 23 Jul 1234 records an agreement between "Amedeum comitem
1 CONT Sabaudie" and "Aymonem et Petrum fratres ipsius" in settlement of a dispute
1 CONT concerning their paternal inheritance[359]. The disagreement must have
1 CONT persisted, at least in the case of Aymon, as he was disinherited under the
1 CONT testament of "Amedei comitis Sab. et marchionis Italie", dated 23 Sep 1235,
1 CONT which appointed his younger brother "Thomam fratrem suum" as his heir "in
1 CONT comitatu et marchionatu" in default of male children[360]. Seigneur d´Agaune.
1 CONT "Aymo dominus Agaunensis frater comitis Sabaudie" confirmed a donation to
1 CONT Hautecombe abbey by charter dated Oct 1235[361]. Seigneur de Chablais. "Aymo
1 CONT de Sabaudia dominus de Chablasio, filius bonæ mem. Thomæ, ill. Sabaud.
1 CONT comitis" founded the hospital of Villeneuve, for the souls of and with the
1 CONT support of his mother and four brothers (all named) by charter dated 25 Jun
1 CONT 1236[362]. The mention of his older brother suggests that the dispute with
1 CONT Aymon had been resolved by this date. Nevertheless, Aymon is also passed over
1 CONT as heir in the second testament of his older brother "Amedeus comes Sabaudie"
1 CONT dated 19 Jul 1238, which repeats the nomination of "Thomam fratrem suum" as
1 CONT his heir, substituting "Philippum, huic autem Petrum fratres suos" if Thomas
1 CONT died without male heirs[363]. An indication of the precarious financial
1 CONT position of the counts of Savoy is provided by a third testament, dated 2 Nov
1 CONT 1240, made by Thomas´s son "Amadeus com Sab. et marchio in Italia" who
1 CONT repeated the nomination of "Thomæ, Flandriæ comiti, fratri suo" as his heir to
1 CONT "totius comitatus sui Sabaudiæ marchionatus Italiæ et ducatus Chablasii" if he
1 CONT died without male children, on condition that he satisfied all the debts of
1 CONT "Thomæ comitis patris et Humberti fratris ipsorum"[364]. This charter suggests
1 CONT that financial considerations may have played their part in Aymon´s continued
1 CONT disinheritance in favour of his brother Thomas, the latter having made a
1 CONT profitable marriage with the Ctss of Flanders. The testament of "Thomas de
1 CONT Sabaudia comes" dated 26 Jun 1248 remembers the souls of "bonæ memoriæ Thoma
1 CONT quondam comite Sabaudiæ patre meo…fratribus meis Umberto…Aymone et Vuillermo
1 CONT quondam electo Valentinensi"[365]. Europäische Stammtafeln[366] shows two sons
1 CONT of Comte Thomas I both named Aymon, without any dates of birth or death for
1 CONT the second. Seigneur de Chillon, de Villeneuve et de Chablais. He died of
1 CONT leprosy.
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. **GUILLAUME de Savoie** ([1201]-poisoned Viterbo 1 Nov 1239, bur Abbaye de
1 CONT Hautecombe). A charter dated 1224 records an agreement between "Thomæ com.
1 CONT Sabaud " and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by "ipse Thomas comes, Amedeus
1 CONT primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum quatuor filii
1 CONT clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[367]. Elected Bishop of
1 CONT Valence 1224. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records that "alter
1 CONT filiorum eius [comitis Thome de Sabaudia] Guilelmus" was elected bishop of
1 CONT Valence[368]. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus, Aymo,
1 CONT W. electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus, Bonifacius et Philippus filii Thome
1 CONT Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia" confirmed donations to Hautecombe abbey
1 CONT by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[369]. He was named in the Feb 1233 testament of
1 CONT his brother Pierre[370]. The Annals of Dunstable record that “electus
1 CONT Valenciæ, avunculus reginæ nostræ” arrived in England in 1237 and was made the
1 CONT king´s principle adviser (“consiliarius regis principalis”) and granted the
1 CONT honor of Richmond[371]. Matthew of Paris records that he was adviser to Henry
1 CONT III King of England but left the country after quarrelling with the barons,
1 CONT but was permitted to return by the king[372], which represents the earliest
1 CONT reference in this source to the problems caused by relations of Queen
1 CONT Eléonore. The king proposed his election as Bishop of Winchester in 1238, but
1 CONT the church council elected Ralph Neville, whose election was quashed by the
1 CONT Pope after intervention by the king[373]. He was elected Bishop of Liège in
1 CONT 1238. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the election “in
1 CONT crastino sancti Iohannis” in 1238 of the new bishop of Liège, where
1 CONT “primicerius Metensis Iacobus...prepositus Leodiensis et frater ducis de
1 CONT Nanceio” supported the candidacy of “preposito Ottoni Aquensi”, while
1 CONT “archdyaconus...Galtherus frater comitis de Retest” supported “fratri comitis
1 CONT Flandrie...electo Valentie Guillelmo”. The same source records that “ille de
1 CONT Traiecto vel de Aquis” was elected first by “Conradum Coloniensem electum et
1 CONT per Conradum filium imperatoris et per ipsum imperatorem”, while “electus
1 CONT Valencie” was visiting Cremona where he also received “regalia sua ab
1 CONT imperatore”. Both candidates then went to Rome where the Pope annulled the
1 CONT election of “pontifex Traiectensem Ottonem” and confirmed “electum Valentie
1 CONT Guillelmum” as bishop of Liège[374]. Matthew Paris records the death "die
1 CONT omnium Sanctorum…venenatus Viterbii" in 1239 of "Guillelmus de Sabaudia
1 CONT electus Valentinus"[375]. The Chronicle of Hautecombe records the death in
1 CONT 1239 of "dominus Guillermus de Sabaudia electus Valencie" and his burial "III
1 CONT Non Mai" (presumably in 1240)[376]. The Aegidii Aurævallensis Gesta
1 CONT Episcoporum Leodiensium records the death “in partibus Transalpinis” in Oct
1 CONT 1239 of Bishop Guillaume and his burial “in civitate Florentia”[377]. The
1 CONT testament of "Philippi de Sabaudia electi Lugdunensis", dated 26 May 1256,
1 CONT names "Petrus de Sabaudia frater et Beatrix comitissa Provinciæ" as his heirs,
1 CONT chooses burial at Hautecombe, and founds an anniversary at Valence for the
1 CONT soul of "defuncti fratris sui Willelmi, electi illius ecclesiæ"[378].
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. **THOMAS de Savoie** (Château de Montmélian [1202]-Chambéry 7 Feb 1259,
1 CONT bur Aosta Cathedral). The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records that
1 CONT "tertius [filiorum comitis Thome de Sabaudia] Thomas" was "cassatus de
1 CONT episcopatu Laurensi et archiepiscopatu Lugdunensis"[379]. He succeeded in 1253
1 CONT as THOMAS II Comte de Savoie, as regent or co-ruler with his nephew.
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. **PIERRE de Savoie** (castle of Susa [1203]-Pierre Châtel [14] May 1268,
1 CONT bur 16 May 1268 Abbaye de Hautecombe). A charter dated 1224 records an
1 CONT agreement between "Thomæ com. Sabaud " and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by
1 CONT "ipse Thomas comes, Amedeus primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum
1 CONT quatuor filii clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[380]. Canon at
1 CONT Lausanne in Nov 1226. Provost at Aosta from before 2 May 1227. Provost at
1 CONT Geneva Apr 1229. Coadjutor at Lausanne. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et marchisa in
1 CONT Ytalia et…Amedeus, Aymo, W. electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus, Bonifacius et
1 CONT Philippus filii Thome Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia" confirmed
1 CONT donations to Hautecombe abbey by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[381]. The first
1 CONT testament of "Petrus filius quondam Thome comitis Sabaudie" dated Feb 1234
1 CONT (N.S.) appoints the children to be born from his marriage to "Annete filia
1 CONT nob. viri Ay. Dni Fuciniaci" and names "Dni Wi electi Valent. et Ay de
1 CONT Sabaudia fratrum"[382]. A charter dated 23 Jul 1234 records an agreement
1 CONT between "Amedeum comitem Sabaudie" and "Aymonem et Petrum fratres ipsius" in
1 CONT settlement of a dispute concerning their paternal inheritance[383]. He
1 CONT resigned his ecclesiastical appointments in 1236. He was seized and imprisoned
1 CONT in [1237] by the sons of Guillaume II Comte de Genève, for which Pierre was
1 CONT later compensated with the castle of Arlod and 20,000 marks of silver (reduced
1 CONT to 10,000 marks in 1250). The second testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie",
1 CONT dated 19 Jul 1238, repeats the nomination of "Thomam fratrem suum" as his
1 CONT heir, substituting "Philippum, huic autem Petrum fratres suos" if Thomas died
1 CONT without male heirs[384], although it is unclear why the youngest brother
1 CONT Philippe should have been given precedence over Pierre in this document.
1 CONT Matthew of Paris records that Henry III King of England, married to his niece
1 CONT Eléonore de Provence, gave him the honour of Richmond 20 Apr 1240, invited him
1 CONT to England towards the end of the same year and knighted him 5 Jan 1241[385].
1 CONT On the death of his brother Aymon in 1242, he received the towns of Milden and
1 CONT Romont[386]. "Peter de Sabaudia" was granted the "honour of Richemund" dated
1 CONT 20 Apr 1240[387]. Although known popularly as Earl of Richmond, this title was
1 CONT never accorded him officially. King Henry III made him numerous grants between
1 CONT 1241 and 1249, including creating him Constable of the castles of Lewes and
1 CONT Rochester and Warden of the Cinque Ports, and granting him a house in London,
1 CONT on the site of which the Savoy Hotel was later built[388]. "The king´s uncle
1 CONT Peter de Sabaudia" was granted numerous manors in Yorkshire, Lincolnshire,
1 CONT Norfolk, Suffolk, Cambridgeshire and Hertfordshire in the honour of Richmond,
1 CONT with the right to assign them to "any of his brothers or kinsmen", dated 6 May
1 CONT 1241[389]. A charter dated 1244 confirmed the peace agreement reached between
1 CONT the bishop of Lausanne and "Amadeus comes Sabaudie et in Italia marcho
1 CONT et…Petrus de Sabaudia…frater suus"[390]. "Peter de Sabaudia the king´s uncle"
1 CONT was granted "houses on the Thames…in the street called la Straunde"
1 CONT [presumably located on the site later occupied by the Savoy Hotel] dated 12
1 CONT Feb 1246[391]. Matthew of Paris records in 1246 that Pierre de Savoie brought
1 CONT foreign girls to England as brides for English nobles, which was widely
1 CONT criticised in England[392]. He invaded Dauphiné in 1250, forcing the Seigneur
1 CONT de la Tour du Pin to become his vassal. An arbitral judgment dated 16 Feb 1254
1 CONT settled a dispute between "Conte Amedeo di Savoia…Tomaso suo fratello, il
1 CONT Conte Bonifacio suo figlio pupillo, e Pietro di Savoia Zio di questo" under
1 CONT which the last-named claimed the fifth part of assets which belonged to "Conte
1 CONT Tomaso suo Padre, Aymone, e Guglielmo suoi fratelli, della di Lui Madre, e di
1 CONT di due Sorelle morte ab intestato", under which Chillon, Conthey, Saillon and
1 CONT lands in Chablais and Valais were awarded to Pierre[393]. The testament of
1 CONT "Petri de Sabaudia", dated 8 Jun 1255 at London, names "Beatrix filia
1 CONT sua…Eleonora Angliæ regina…Philippum electrum Lugdunensem fratrem suum,
1 CONT Agneti…Fuciniacensi uxori suæ", and names Henry III King of England as his
1 CONT executor[394]. Back in England, he at first supported the barons in their
1 CONT dispute with King Henry, but changed sides and reconciled the king with his
1 CONT son in 1260, helping to induce Henry to disregard the Provisions of Oxford in
1 CONT 1261. He was obliged to leave England in 1262 due to the growing hostility
1 CONT towards foreigners, his English lands were confiscated but later restored to
1 CONT him by the king[395]. He succeeded his nephew in 1263 as PIERRE II "le Petit-
1 CONT Charlemagne" Comte de Savoie. His great-nephew, Richard Earl of Cornwall,
1 CONT confirmed Comte Pierre as Imperial Vicar in Italy after his installation as
1 CONT King of the Romans in 1263[396]. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi
1 CONT Berengarii comitis Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, confirms her previous
1 CONT testaments appointing "…fratrum suorum Bonifacii archiepiscopi Cantuar. et
1 CONT Petri comitis Sabaudiæ" as her heirs[397]. Comte Pierre campaigned against the
1 CONT Bishop of Sion in 1265/66, and against Rudolf I Graf von Habsburg in 1265/67.
1 CONT Comte Pierre increased the family's domains considerably through conquests in
1 CONT western Switzerland, mainly at the expense of the Comte de Genève. He also
1 CONT increased his authority over many local seigneuries by appointing local
1 CONT châtelains and baillis who reported directly to him[398]. The testament of
1 CONT "Conte Pietro di Savoia", dated Sep 1264, chose his burial "in abbatial S.
1 CONT Mauricii Agaunensi" if he died at sea or "in ecclesia Londinensi" if he died
1 CONT in England, appointed "filiam suam Beatricem uxorem Guigonis Dalphini" as his
1 CONT heir, named "neptem suam Alienoram Angliæ reginam…Philippo electo Lugdun.
1 CONT fratri suo…filius quondam Thomæ de Sabaudia alterius fratris sui…major natu
1 CONT aliorum filiorum dicti Thomæ…Agneti conjugi suæ", and appointed "Philippi
1 CONT elect. Lugdun. fratris sui, Soffredi de Amaysino" as his executors[399]. Under
1 CONT another testament dated 7 May 1268, "Petrus comes Sabaudia" chose burial "in
1 CONT Alta Comba", appointed "filiam nostrum B. Dalphinam de Vienneisio" as his
1 CONT heir, granted bequests to "nepotibus nostris filiis Dom. Thome de
1 CONT Sabaudie…fratres nostri…domine nostre Alienore Regine Anglie…comitatum
1 CONT Richemundensem…in comitatu…Sabaudie…fratrem nostrum Philippum de Sabaudia
1 CONT comitem Burgundie…uxori nostre Agneti domine Fucigniaci…domine Margarete
1 CONT comitisse de Quiburgo…sorori nostre…B. filiam Amedei comitis…fratris nostri
1 CONT quondam…" as well as numerous bequests to religious institutions[400]. Under a
1 CONT codicil to his testament dated 14 May 1268, "Petrus comes Sabaudia" dated 7
1 CONT May 1268 appointed "fratri nostro Philippo de Sabaudia comiti Burgundie…[et]
1 CONT filiam nostrum B. Dalphinam de Vienneisio" as his heirs, and named "comitis
1 CONT Foren. et Dni de Turre et Dni de Jez" as his fief-holders[401]. m (Betrothed
1 CONT Feb 1234, after 25 Jun 1236) AGNES de Faucigny, daughter and heiress of AYMON
1 CONT [II] Seigneur de Faucigny & his first wife Béatrix de Bourgogne[-Comté] (-11
1 CONT Aug 1268, bur Faucigny, Abbaye de Contamine). The testament of "Aymo dominus
1 CONT Fuciniaci" is dated Feb 1234, appoints "Agnetem filiam suam", betrothed to
1 CONT "Petro de Sabaudia filio condam Thome Comit. Sabaud.", as his heir in default
1 CONT of male heirs, and reserves the dowry of "alterius filiarum suarum
1 CONT Beatricis"[402]. She succeeded her father in 1253 as Dame de Faucigny. The
1 CONT testament of "Petri de Sabaudia", dated 8 Jun 1255 at London, names "Beatrix
1 CONT filia sua…Eleonora Angliæ regina…Philippum electrum Lugdunensem fratrem suum,
1 CONT Agneti…Fuciniacensi uxori suæ", and names Henry III King of England as his
1 CONT executor[403]. The testament of "Agnetis dominæ Fuciniaci" dated 17 Oct 1262
1 CONT appoints "Petrum de Sabaudia maritum suum…et Beatricem filiam suam uxorem
1 CONT Guigonis Dalphini Viennensis" as her heirs[404]. A second testament of
1 CONT "Agnetis dominæ Fuciniaci conjugis Petri de Sabaudia" dated 16 Nov 1262 elects
1 CONT her burial "in ecclesia Contaminæ", and appoints "Beatricem filiam suam uxorem
1 CONT Guigonis Dalphini, Vienn. et Albon. comitis" as her heir in one third of her
1 CONT property and her husband as heir in the other two thirds[405]. The testament
1 CONT of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii comitis Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan
1 CONT 1264, adds bequests to "…Agneti comitissæ Sabaudiæ dominiæ Fuciniaci…"[406].
1 CONT The testament of "Conte Pietro di Savoia", dated Sep 1264, named "…Agneti
1 CONT conjugi suæ"[407]. Under another testament dated 7 May 1268, "Petrus comes
1 CONT Sabaudia" granted bequests to "…uxori nostre Agneti domine Fucigniaci…"[408].
1 CONT The testament of "Agnetis dominæ Fuciniaci", dated 9 Aug 1268, appointed
1 CONT "Beatricem comitissam Viennensem et Albonensem filiam suam" as her heir, chose
1 CONT her burial "in ecclesia Contaminæ in Fuciniaco", and made bequests to "dominæ
1 CONT Beatrici dominæ de Thoria et Villario sorori suæ et filiis suis…Simoni de
1 CONT Joinville dom. de Jaiz fratri suo"[409]. Comte Pierre & his wife had one
1 CONT child: a) BEATRIX de Savoie ([1237]-21 Apr 1310, bur Faucigny, Chartreuse
1 CONT convent of Melans). The marriage contract of "Guigoni Dalphino comiti
1 CONT Viennensi et Albonensi" and "Aymo dominus Fuciniaci…Beatricem filiam Agnetis
1 CONT filiæ suæ ex Petro de Sabaudie" is dated 4 Dec 1241[410]. The testament of
1 CONT "Petri de Sabaudia", dated 8 Jun 1255 at London, names "Beatrix filia
1 CONT sua…Eleonora Angliæ regina…Philippum electrum Lugdunensem fratrem suum,
1 CONT Agneti…Fuciniacensi uxori suæ", and names Henry III King of England as his
1 CONT executor[411]. The Aymari Rivalli De Allobrogibus records the marriage of
1 CONT "Guigonem quartum" and "Beatricem, Petri comitis Sabaudiæ filiam"[412]. The
1 CONT contract of marriage between "Guigone Delfino di Vienna e d'Albona" and
1 CONT "Beatrice figlia di Pietro di Savoia" is dated 4 Dec 1241[413]. The marriage
1 CONT between "Vienna e Beatrice figlia di Pietro di Savoia" was confirmed as valid
1 CONT despite a prior verbal agreement between "detto Delfino e Cecilia di Beaux
1 CONT figlia del Conte Barallo di Beaux, ed indi Moglie d'Amedeo quarto Conte di
1 CONT Savoia", by judgment dated 10 Mar 1261[414]. The testament of "Agnetis dominæ
1 CONT Fuciniaci" dated 17 Oct 1262 appoints "Petrum de Sabaudia maritum suum…et
1 CONT Beatricem filiam suam uxorem Guigonis Dalphini Viennensis" as her heirs[415].
1 CONT A second testament of "Agnetis dominæ Fuciniaci conjugis Petri de Sabaudia"
1 CONT dated 16 Nov 1262 elects her burial "in ecclesia Contaminæ", and appoints
1 CONT "Beatricem filiam suam uxorem Guigonis Dalphini, Vienn. et Albon. comitis" as
1 CONT her heir in one third of her property and her husband as heir in the other two
1 CONT thirds[416]. The testament of "Conte Pietro di Savoia", dated Sep 1264,
1 CONT appointed "filiam suam Beatricem uxorem Guigonis Dalphini" as his heir[417].
1 CONT The testament of "Guigo Dalphinus, Vienn. et Albonis comitis", dated 27 Jun
1 CONT 1267, appointed "Johannem filium meum" as his heir, and made bequests to
1 CONT "Annam et Catharinam filias meas…Beatrix uxor mea"[418]. Under another
1 CONT testament dated 7 May 1268, "Petrus comes Sabaudia" appointed "filiam nostrum
1 CONT B. Dalphinam de Vienneisio" as his heir[419]. She succeeded her mother in 1268
1 CONT as Dame de Faucigny, the territory strengthening considerably the power of the
1 CONT Dauphiné de Viennois. The testament of "Agnetis dominæ Fuciniaci", dated 9 Aug
1 CONT 1268, appointed "Beatricem comitissam Viennensem et Albonensem filiam suam" as
1 CONT her heir[420]. Regent in Dauphiné during the minority of her son 1269-1273.
1 CONT The marriage contract of "Beatrix Dalphina Viennensis domina de Fulciniaco
1 CONT filia quondam Dni Petri comitis Sabaudie" and "domino Gastoni vicecomiti
1 CONT Bearnensi" is dated 2 Apr 1273[421]. Her second marriage is confirmed by the
1 CONT agreement dated 15 Dec 1284 under which "Gastone Visconte di Bearn Signore di
1 CONT Montricher e Castelvecchio" and "Beatrice figlia del Conte Pietro di Savoia
1 CONT Dama di Faussign sua Consorte" reached agreement with "Umberto Signore di
1 CONT Thoire ed Anna Delfina sua Consorte" concering Comte Gaston's claim to the
1 CONT county of Vienne[422]. "Beatrice figlia di Pietro Conte di Savoia Dama di
1 CONT Faussign" transferred her husband's property to "Gioanni figlio d'Umberto
1 CONT Signore della Torre e di Cologny" by charter dated Sep 1282[423]. She
1 CONT transferred her lands between Seyssel and Freiburg to her cousin Amedée V
1 CONT Comte de Savoie 29 Apr 1294, and the barony of Faucigny 15 Sep 1296 to her
1 CONT son-in-law Humbert de La Tour, for the benefit of one of his sons, reserving
1 CONT the usufruct to herself[424]. A powerful force in the region, she claimed
1 CONT Savoy for her grandson Hugues. Allying herself with the Seigneur de Gex, the
1 CONT Comte de Genève and the Bishops of Lausanne and Geneva, she triggered
1 CONT conflicts within the family which were to last many generations[425]. m
1 CONT firstly (Betrothed 4 Dec 1241, [before 22 Apr 1253]) GUIGUES Dauphin de
1 CONT Viennois Comte d'Albon, son of ANDRE Comte d´Albon [Bourgogne-Capet] & his
1 CONT third wife Beatrice di Monferrato ([1225]-[Aug/Nov] 1269, bur Chartreuse
1 CONT Abbaye de Prémol). m secondly (contract 2 Apr 1273) as his second wife, GASTON
1 CONT VII Vicomte de Béarn, son of GUILLEN de Moncada Vicomte de Béarn & his wife
1 CONT Gersende de Provence [Aragon-Barcelona] (1225-26 Apr 1290).
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. **BEATRIX de Savoie** ([1205]-Dec 1266 or 4 Jan 1267). Matthew of Paris
1 CONT names her as daughter of "comitis Sabaldiæ Thomæ iam mortui, sororem comitis
1 CONT Sabaldiæ adhuc viventis Amidei", when he records the marriage of her daughter
1 CONT to Henry III King of England[426]. It is improbable that she was born much
1 CONT later than 1205 as she gave birth to her first child in 1221. The contract of
1 CONT marriage between "Thomas…comes Sabaldie et marchio in Ytalia…filia sua" and
1 CONT "Raimundi Berengarii…comitis Provinciæ et Forcalquerii" is dated 5 Jun 1219,
1 CONT and names "A. et V. filii Thomæ comitis et A. cometissa uxor eius" as
1 CONT guarantors[427]. She transformed the court at Aix into one of the most
1 CONT celebrated in Europe. After quarrelling with her son-in-law Charles Comte
1 CONT d'Anjou over the usufruct of the county of Provence she retired to Echelles in
1 CONT Savoy[428]. The marriage of her daughter Eléonore with Henry III King of
1 CONT England in 1236 signalled the establishment of close ties between the English
1 CONT court and the house of Savoy, the foreign immigrants becoming increasingly
1 CONT unpopular in England and contributing to the difficulties experienced by the
1 CONT king with his barons. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii
1 CONT comitis Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, confirms her previous testaments
1 CONT appointing "Reginarum filiarum suarum Margarethæ Franciæ et Alienoræ Angliæ,
1 CONT fratrum suorum Bonifacii archiepiscopi Cantuar. et Petri comitis Sabaudiæ" as
1 CONT her heirs, chooses burial "in hospitali Scalarum", and adds bequests to
1 CONT "Philippo electo Lugdun. fratri suo altero…Agneti comitissæ Sabaudiæ dominiæ
1 CONT Fuciniaci, Cæciliæ relictæ Amedei Sabaudiæ comitis, Beatrici relictæ Thomæ de
1 CONT Sabaudia comitis...Contissoni…Eleonoræ aliæ filiæ Thomæ comitis…Contissoni
1 CONT dominæ Medullionis nepti suæ…Margarithæ matri marchionis Montisferrati nepti
1 CONT suæ, Rodulpho archiepiscopo Tarantas, A. episcopo de Dyone consanguineo
1 CONT testatricis, Petro episcopo Hereford…filiabus Rodolphi et Henrici de Gebennis,
1 CONT et filiæ domini de Camera" as well as numerous bequests to religious
1 CONT institutions, orders "Contissona filia Amedei comitis…Eleonoræ filiæ Thomæ
1 CONT fratris sui" to fulfil religious bequests, and appoints "Johannem
1 CONT archiepiscopum Viennensem et Rodulphum Tarantasiensem, Philippum electum
1 CONT Lugdun. fratrem suum, episcopum Gratianopolitanum, Humbertum abbatem Altacumbæ
1 CONT et Stephanum archidiaconum Cantaruensium" as her executors[429]. A second
1 CONT testament of "Beatrix relicta…Dom. Reymundi Berengarii comitis provinciæ",
1 CONT dated 22 Feb 1264, chooses burial "in ecclesia Hospitalis S. Joannis
1 CONT Hierosolymitani", adds bequests to "Thomam Amedeum et Ludovicum filios quondam
1 CONT Dom. Thome fratris mei…Alienore filie predicti comitis Thome…filie Contissone
1 CONT de Medullione…filie domini de Camera…Beringarie filie Dom. Benedicti de
1 CONT Castellione…Beatrice Andegavie comitisse"[430]. The testament of "Bonifacius
1 CONT archiepiscopus Cantuarensis", dated 11 Oct 1264, made bequests to "sorori suæ
1 CONT comitissæ Provinciæ…sorori suæ alteræ comitissæ de Quiborc…"[431]. A second
1 CONT necrology of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne records the death "II Non Jan" of "vidua
1 CONT dna comitssa Provincie"[432]. m (Betrothed 5 Jun 1219, Dec 1220) RAIMOND
1 CONT BERENGER IV Comte de Provence, son of ALPHONSE II Comte de Provence [Aragon-
1 CONT Barcelona] & his wife Gersende de Sabran Ctss de Forcalquier ([1198]-19 Aug
1 CONT 1245, bur Aix-en-Provence, église de Saint Jean de Jérusalem).
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. **BONIFACE de Savoie** (Château de Sainte-Hélène du Lac [1206]-Château de
1 CONT Sainte-Hélène-des-Millières 14 Jul 1270, bur Abbaye de Hautecombe). A charter
1 CONT dated 1224 records an agreement between "Thomæ com. Sabaud " and the bishop of
1 CONT Sion, witnessed by "ipse Thomas comes, Amedeus primogenitus illius, Comitissa
1 CONT uxor Thomæ, eorum quatuor filii clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et
1 CONT Bonifacius"[433]. Europäische Stammtafeln[434] shows two sons of Comte Thomas
1 CONT I both named Boniface, the second being "prior at Nantua". As in the case of
1 CONT his other supposed brothers with duplicate names, it is likely that the
1 CONT references are to the same person. The absence of a second Boniface in the 26
1 CONT Jun 1248 testament of his supposed brother Thomas de Savoie[435] provides a
1 CONT good indication that this is correct. In addition, the 1224 agreement between
1 CONT his supposed father and the Bishop of Sion refers to "four clerical sons",
1 CONT whereas the second Boniface would have been a fifth. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et
1 CONT marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus, Aymo, W. electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus,
1 CONT Bonifacius et Philippus filii Thome Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia"
1 CONT confirmed donations to Hautecombe abbey by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[436]. The
1 CONT Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records that "unus filiorum comitis
1 CONT Thome de Sabaudia" was elected bishop of Belley in 1232 after the death of
1 CONT Bishop Bernard but does not name him[437]. Administrator of the bishopric of
1 CONT Belley 1234. Along with his brothers, he established himself at the English
1 CONT court soon after the marriage in 1236 of his niece Eléonore de Provence to
1 CONT Henry III King of England. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie et in Italie
1 CONT marchio…cum…genetrice sua et fratribus suis B. Bellicensi Electo et Philippo
1 CONT Metensi Primicerio" granted "villam S. Mauritii de Chablaisio" Saint-Maurice
1 CONT de Chablais to "soror illorum Margareta comitissa de Kiborch" by charter dated
1 CONT 24 Feb 1240[438]. He was confirmed as Archbishop of Canterbury, Primate of
1 CONT England, in 1243, consecrated in 1244 at Lyon by the Pope[439]. Bishop of
1 CONT Durham. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii comitis
1 CONT Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, confirms her previous testaments appointing
1 CONT "…fratrum suorum Bonifacii archiepiscopi Cantuar. et Petri comitis Sabaudiæ"
1 CONT as her heirs[440]. The testament of "Bonifacius archiepiscopus Cantuarensis",
1 CONT dated 11 Oct 1264, chose burial "infra ecclesiam Christi Cantuar" if he died
1 CONT in England and "Pontiniacum" if he died elsewhere overseas and if he died
1 CONT "circa Montem Cinisium…apud Altam Combam", made bequests to "sorori suæ
1 CONT comitissæ Provinciæ…sorori suæ alteræ comitissæ de Quiborc…fratri suo Dom. P.
1 CONT comiti Sabaudiæ…fratri suo Philippo elect. Lugdun…filios fratris testatoris
1 CONT Thomæ comitis" as well as to numerous religious foundations[441]. The
1 CONT Continuator of Florence of Worcester records the death "XV Kal Aug apud
1 CONT Baleys" of "Bonifacius Cantuarensis archiepiscopus"[442]. The necrology of La
1 CONT Cour-Dieu records the death “XV Kal Aug” of “Bonifacius Cantuarensis
1 CONT archiepiscopus, monachus”[443]. He was beatified in 1838.
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. **PHILIPPE de Savoie** (Aiguebelle [1207]-Château de Roussillon, Bugey 16
1 CONT Aug 1285, bur Abbaye de Hautecombe). His parentage is established, inter alia,
1 CONT by the 1264 testament of his brother Boniface[444]. Archdeacon of Metz 1229.
1 CONT "M. comitissa Sabaudie et marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus, Aymo, W. electus
1 CONT Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus, Bonifacius et Philippus filii Thome Comitis Sab.
1 CONT et marchionis in Ytalia" confirmed donations to Hautecombe abbey by charter
1 CONT dated 26 Feb 1231[445]. The second testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie",
1 CONT dated 19 Jul 1238, repeats the nomination of "Thomam fratrem suum" as his
1 CONT heir, substituting "Philippum, huic autem Petrum fratres suos" if Thomas died
1 CONT without male heirs[446], although it is unclear why the youngest brother
1 CONT Philippe should have been given precedence over Pierre in this document. He
1 CONT was elected Bishop of Lausanne in 1239. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie et in Italie
1 CONT marchio…cum…genetrice sua et fratribus suis B. Bellicensi Electo et Philippo
1 CONT Metensi Primicerio" granted "villam S. Mauritii de Chablaisio" Saint-Maurice
1 CONT de Chablais to "soror illorum Margareta comitissa de Kiborch" by charter dated
1 CONT 24 Feb 1240[447]. Bishop of Valence 1245. Archbishop of Lyon 1246. The
1 CONT testament of "Philippi de Sabaudia electi Lugdunensis", dated 26 May 1256,
1 CONT names "Petrus de Sabaudia frater et Beatrix comitissa Provinciæ" as his heirs,
1 CONT chooses burial at Hautecombe, and founds an anniversary at Valence for the
1 CONT soul of "defuncti fratris sui Willelmi, electi illius ecclesiæ"[448]. The
1 CONT testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii comitis Provinciæ", dated
1 CONT 14 Jan 1264, adds bequests to "Philippo electo Lugdun. fratri suo altero…",
1 CONT and appoints "…Philippum electum Lugdun. fratrem suum…" as her executors[449].
1 CONT The testament of "Conte Pietro di Savoia", dated Sep 1264 named "…Philippo
1 CONT electo Lugdun. fratri suo…" and appointed "Philippi elect. Lugdun. fratris
1 CONT sui, Soffredi de Amaysino" as his executors[450]. He resigned his
1 CONT ecclesiastical appointments in 1267. Comte Palatin de Bourgogne 1267-1279, by
1 CONT right of his wife. He succeeded his brother in 1268 as PHILIPPE I Comte de
1 CONT Savoie. He faced the continual opposition of his niece Beatrix Dauphine de
1 CONT Viennois, daughter of his predecessor, who claimed Savoy for her grandson
1 CONT Hugues de la Tour. Comte Philippe was able to reaffirm his authority over
1 CONT Turin by defeating Guglielmo VII Marchese di Monferrato[451]. Pope Gregory X
1 CONT awarded him the title Gonfalionere of the Holy Church. The testament of
1 CONT "Filippo Vescovo de Lione" dated 26 Jul 1256 names "Pietro di Savoia e
1 CONT Beatrice Contessa di Provenza, di Lui fratello e Sorella…Conte Tommaso di Lui
1 CONT fratello" and chooses to be buried "nella Chiesa de Haute Combe"[452]. The
1 CONT necrology of Saint-Rambert-en-Bugey records the death "XVI Kal Sep" of
1 CONT "Philippus comes Sabaudiæ"[453]. The necrology of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne
1 CONT records the death "XVI Kal Sep" of "dni Philippi quondam comitis
1 CONT Sabaudie"[454]. m (11 Jun 1267) as her second husband, ALIX [Adelheid] Ctss
1 CONT Palatine de Bourgogne, widow of HUGUES de Chalon Seigneur de Salins
1 CONT [Bourgogne-Comté], daughter of OTTO I von Andechs Comte Palatin de Bourgogne
1 CONT Duca di Merano & his first wife Beatrix von Hohenstaufen Ctss Palatine de
1 CONT Bourgogne (-Evian 8 Mar 1279). "Hugo dux Burgundie" requested the abbot of
1 CONT Cluny to recognise the rights of “Ph Sabaudie et Burgundie comiti et A.
1 CONT comitisse uxori sue” in “comitatu Burgundie…cessionis nobis facte a domina B,
1 CONT comitissa Orlemunde, sorore dicte A. comitissa”, by charter dated Apr
1 CONT 1270[455]. The testament of "Alis de Sauoye et de Bergoigne, Contesse
1 CONT Palatine" dated Nov 1278, made with the consent of "nostre…Signor et Mary
1 CONT Philippe de Sauoye et de Bergoigne Comte Palatin", appoints "nostre…fils
1 CONT ainsnés Messire Othes de Bourgoigone Sires de Salins soit Cuens de Bergoigne"
1 CONT as her heir in the county, makes bequests to "nostre…fil Renalt" and names
1 CONT "nostre…fils Iohans"[456].
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. **daughter** (-before 1254). The existence of two daughters who died
1 CONT young is confirmed by the arbitral judgment dated 16 Feb 1254 which settled a
1 CONT dispute between "Conte Amedeo di Savoia…Tomaso suo fratello, il Conte
1 CONT Bonifacio suo figlio pupillo, e Pietro di Savoia Zio di questo" under which
1 CONT the last-named claimed the fifth part of assets which belonged to "Conte
1 CONT Tomaso suo Padre, Aymone, e Guglielmo suoi fratelli, della di Lui Madre, e di
1 CONT due Sorelle morte ab intestato"[457].
1 CONT
1 CONT 11\. **daughter** (-before 1254). The existence of two daughters who died
1 CONT young is confirmed by the arbitral judgment dated 16 Feb 1254 which settled a
1 CONT dispute between "Conte Amedeo di Savoia…Tomaso suo fratello, il Conte
1 CONT Bonifacio suo figlio pupillo, e Pietro di Savoia Zio di questo" under which
1 CONT the last-named claimed the fifth part of assets which belonged to "Conte
1 CONT Tomaso suo Padre, Aymone, e Guglielmo suoi fratelli, della di Lui Madre, e di
1 CONT due Sorelle morte ab intestato"[458].
1 CONT
1 CONT 12\. [ **ALIX de Savoie** (-1277, bur Abbaye de Hautecombe). Guichenon names
1 CONT Alix as daughter of Comte Thomas I and his wife, stating that she was abbess
1 CONT of Saint-Pierre, Lyon in 1250, referring to "Titre de l´abbaye de Saint-Pierre
1 CONT de Lyon" with no precise citation reference[459]. The primary source which
1 CONT confirms her parentage has not yet been identified. She is not mentioned in
1 CONT the 11 Oct 1264 testament of her supposed brother Boniface Archbishop of
1 CONT Canterbury (which refers to his "sister the Ctss of Provence" and his "other
1 CONT sister the Ctss of Quibourc")[460], although this is not conclusive to dismiss
1 CONT her affiliation. One possibility is that Alix was the illegitimate daughter of
1 CONT Comte Thomas I.]
1 CONT
1 CONT 13\. [ **AGATHE de Savoie** (-after 1279). Guichenon names Agathe as daughter
1 CONT of Comte Thomas I and his wife, stating that she was nun and later abbess of
1 CONT Saint-Pierre, Lyon in 1279, referring to "Titre de l´abbaye de Saint-Pierre de
1 CONT Lyon" with no precise citation reference[461]. She is not mentioned in the 11
1 CONT Oct 1264 testament of her supposed brother Boniface Archbishop of Canterbury
1 CONT (which refers to his "sister the Ctss of Provence" and his "other sister the
1 CONT Ctss of Quibourc")[462], although this is not conclusive to dismiss her
1 CONT affiliation. One possibility is that Agathe was the illegitimate daughter of
1 CONT Comte Thomas I.]
1 CONT
1 CONT 14\. **MARGUERITE de Savoie** ([1212]-1/2 Sep 1270 or 1273[463]). The contract
1 CONT of marriage between "Thomas comes Savoyæ…filiam suam Margaritham…infra nubiles
1 CONT annos" and "comiti Hartmanno filio comitis Ulrici de Kyburg" is dated 1 Jun
1 CONT 1218, stating that "Dni Bertholdi comitis de Novocastro et Dni Wilhelmi de
1 CONT Stavayé" acted as guarantors, and with the consent of "Ulricus comes de Kyburg
1 CONT et comes Garnerius frater eius et comitissa uxor comitis de Kyburg"[464]. Her
1 CONT marriage date is confirmed by the charter dated 1230 under which her husband
1 CONT "H. comes de Kiburch" confirmed donations "propter nuptias uxori sue filie
1 CONT comitis Sabaudie", with the consent of "fratris sui Ul. Constantiensis
1 CONT canonici et H. filii fratris sui beate memorie Wer. quondam comitis de
1 CONT Kiburch"[465]. The Chronicon Colmarense records that "comes…[Kiburc]" married
1 CONT "filiam comitis de Sabaudia"[466]. "Conte Amedeo di Savoia Marchese in Italia"
1 CONT donated "Castello di Monteuz" to "Contessa di Kibourg Margarita di Savoia sua
1 CONT Sorella" by charter dated "Festa di S. Gallo 1239"[467]. "Amedeus comes
1 CONT Sabaudie et marchio Italie" granted "castrum…Monteys" Montheys to "sorori mee
1 CONT Margarete comitisse de Kiborch" by charter dated 16 Oct 1239[468]. "Amedeus
1 CONT comes Sabaudie et in Italie marchio…cum…genetrice sua et fratribus suis B.
1 CONT Bellicensi Electo et Philippo Metensi Primicerio" granted "villam S. Mauritii
1 CONT de Chablaisio" Saint-Maurice de Chablais to "soror illorum Margareta comitissa
1 CONT de Kiborch" by charter dated 24 Feb 1240[469]. "H. comes de Kyburch" granted
1 CONT "castra Windegge, Oltingen…advocatiam et predium in Shennis, Wizennanc et
1 CONT Kemanatvn" to "uxori mee" by way of dower, with the consent of "fratruelis mei
1 CONT H", by charter dated 28 May 1241[470]. The same collection includes several
1 CONT other charters relating to this grant, dated between 9 Jul 1241 and 1243[471].
1 CONT The testament of "Bonifacius archiepiscopus Cantuarensis", dated 11 Oct 1264,
1 CONT made bequests to "sorori suæ comitissæ Provinciæ…sorori suæ alteræ comitissæ
1 CONT de Quiborc…"[472]. Under another testament dated 7 May 1268, "Petrus comes
1 CONT Sabaudia" granted bequests to "…domine Margarete comitisse de Quiburgo…sorori
1 CONT nostre…"[473]. According to Europäische Stammtafeln[474], Marguerite de Savoie
1 CONT married secondly Eberhard von Habsburg-Laufenburg, son of Rudolf III Graf von
1 CONT Habsburg-Laufenburg & his wife Gertrud von Regensberg. Apart from the
1 CONT unlikelihood of Graf Eberhard (who at the time must have been at least 40
1 CONT years old) marrying as his first wife a lady over 50 years old, his marriage
1 CONT to Anna heiress of Kyburg is recorded[475] as having taken place in [30 Oct/12
1 CONT Dec] 1271 when Marguerite was still alive. In addition, the Chronicle of
1 CONT Hautecombe refers to Marguerite as "Margarita comitissa de Quiborch in
1 CONT Alemania" when she died, with no mention of Habsburg-Laufenburg. m (contract
1 CONT Mouden 1 Jun 1218, 1230) HARTMANN von Kiburg, son of ULRICH Graf von Kyburg &
1 CONT his wife Anna von Zähringen [Baden] (-27 Nov 1264, bur Wettingen). He
1 CONT succeeded in 1227 as HARTMANN III joint Graf von Kiburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT ===Comte Thomas I had [four] illegitimate children by unknown mistresses:===
1 CONT
1 CONT 15\. **BERAUD** (-after Jun 1263). Guichenon states that Berold and Benoît
1 CONT were illegitimate sons of Comte Thomas I, adding that they swore homage to
1 CONT Pierre I Comte de Savoie at Aiguebelle in Jun 1263 (without citing the
1 CONT corresponding primary source)[476].
1 CONT
1 CONT 16\. **BENOÎT** (-after Jun 1263). Guichenon states that Berold and Benoît
1 CONT were illegitimate sons of Comte Thomas I, adding that they swore homage to
1 CONT Pierre I Comte de Savoie at Aiguebelle in Jun 1263 (without citing the
1 CONT corresponding primary source)[477].
1 CONT
1 CONT 17\. [ **AMEDEE** (-19 Jan 1256). Europäische Stammtafeln[478] shows two sons
1 CONT of Comte Thomas I both named Amedée, the second one being a monk at Grenoble
1 CONT and Bishop of Maurienne in 1220. It is unlikely that this second Amedée was
1 CONT the legitimate son of Comte Thomas. He is not referred to in the 26 Jun 1248
1 CONT testament of his supposed brother Thomas de Savoie[479], unlike all the other
1 CONT known brothers whether deceased or alive. In addition, the 1224 agreement
1 CONT between his supposed father and the Bishop of Sion refers to "four clerical
1 CONT sons", whereas Amedée would have been a fifth. A possible explanation is that
1 CONT this second Amedée was an illegitimate son of Comte Thomas I. However, this
1 CONT hypothesis appears disproved by the charter dated 12 Jan 1270 which records
1 CONT donations by Pierre Bishop of Maurienne to found anniversaries for his
1 CONT predecessors "…dominus Amedeus Maurianensis episcopus frater quondam domini
1 CONT Villelmi de Miribello"[480], assuming that the latter refers to the bishop who
1 CONT died in 1256. The Pingonio Chronicon records the death "XIV Kal Feb" in 1256
1 CONT of "Amedeus episcopus Maurianensis"[481].]
1 CONT
1 CONT 18\. [ **AVOIE [Marguerite] de Savoie** (-shortly before 14 May 1292). Matthew
1 CONT of Paris reports that "Baldewinus de Ripariis, domina regina procurante,
1 CONT quondam alienigenam ducit in uxorem, Sabaudiensem, ipsius reginæ
1 CONT consanguineam"[482]. According to L'Art de vérifier les Dates[483], Avoie was
1 CONT the daughter of Thomas I Comte de Savoie. The primary source which confirms
1 CONT her name has not yet been identified. It is argued in the Complete
1 CONT Peerage[484] that the wife of Baldwin de Reviers, 7th Earl of Devon, could not
1 CONT have been the daughter of Comte Thomas because she was referred to as
1 CONT 'Margaret' in other sources, Comte Thomas I's daughter of that name being the
1 CONT wife of Hartmann III Graf von Kyburg at the time of the Earl's marriage. The
1 CONT Complete Peerage[485] also refers to a writ on the Patent Roll of 52 Henry III
1 CONT "from which it appears that the king had given to the daughter [unnamed] of
1 CONT Thomas, sometime Count of Savoy, 500 marks on her marriage", this presumably
1 CONT being the widowed Countess of Devon on the occasion of her second marriage.
1 CONT The date of the writ matches the supposed second marriage of Avoie de Savoie.
1 CONT The Complete Peerage[486] assumes that the Count Thomas in question must have
1 CONT been Thomas II. However, the latter's second marriage (from which all his
1 CONT known surviving legitimate children were born) took place in 1251. This would
1 CONT exclude the Earl and Countess of Devon having a son "John who died an
1 CONT infant"[487]. The possibilities therefore seem to be (a) that the Countess of
1 CONT Devon was the illegitimate daughter of either Comte Thomas I or of Comte
1 CONT Thomas II; (b) that she was the legitimate daughter of Comte Thomas I, called
1 CONT either Avoie or Marguerite despite his having another legitimate daughter
1 CONT named Marguerite; or (c) that 'Thomas' in the Patent Roll writ was an error
1 CONT for another Count of Savoy (although it is unclear who this might have been as
1 CONT all other possibilities appear to be excluded). It is recognised that Avoie
1 CONT could not have been born much later than 1220 if she was the legitimate
1 CONT daughter of Comte Thomas I, and therefore would have been at least 17 years
1 CONT older than her first husband the Earl of Devon. Avoie is not mentioned in the
1 CONT 11 Oct 1264 will of her supposed brother Boniface Archbishop of Canterbury
1 CONT which made bequests to "sorori suæ comitissæ Provinciæ…sorori suæ alteræ
1 CONT comitissæ de Quiborc…"[488]. Although this omission is not conclusive as the
1 CONT testator's other presumed two sisters, abbesses Alix and Agathe, were not
1 CONT mentioned either, it is somewhat surprising that he would not have mentioned a
1 CONT legitimate sister who was then living in England, if he had one. The most
1 CONT likely probability is that Avoie was illegitimate. For presentation purposes
1 CONT in this document she is shown as the illegitimate daughter of Comte Thomas I,
1 CONT but it is recognised that Comte Thomas II is an alternative possible father. m
1 CONT firstly (1257) BALDWIN de Reviers Earl of Devon, son of BALDWIN de Reviers
1 CONT Earl of Devon & his wife Amice de Clare (1 Jan 1236-in France 1262 before 13
1 CONT Sep, bur Breamore Priory, Hampshire). [489]m secondly (1269) as his second
1 CONT wife, Sir ROBERT Aguillon of Watton, Hertfordshire (-12 Feb 1286). Some
1 CONT details about the earlier history of the Aguillon family near Chartres are set
1 CONT out by the editor of the cartulary of Notre-Dame de Josaphat[490].]
1 CONT
