1 CONT 349px-CoA_fam_ITA_savoia
1 CONT [http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=image&guid=4c400bd2-f068-461e-aae7-24f169f3f678&tid=10145763&pid=-335552714](http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=image&guid=4c400bd2-f068-461e-aae7-24f169f3f678&tid=10145763&pid=-335552714)
1 CONT Thomas I or Tommaso I (c. 1176 - March 1, 1233) was Count of Savoy from
1 CONT 1189-1233. He was the son of Humbert III of Savoy and Beatrice of Viennois.
1 CONT His birth was seen as miraculous; his monkish father had despaired of having a
1 CONT male heir after three wives. Count Humbert sought counsel from St. Anthelm,
1 CONT who blessed Humbert three times, and it was seen as a prophecy come true when
1 CONT Thomas was born shortly before Anthelm himself died on June 26, 1178. He was
1 CONT named in honour of Saint Thomas Becket.
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas was still a minor when his father died on 4 March 1189, and a council
1 CONT of regency was established, comprising of his mother Beatrice, his father's
1 CONT cousin Boniface I of Montferrat, and the Bishop of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne. He
1 CONT had reached his majority by August 1191. Thomas possessed the martial
1 CONT abilities, energy, and brilliance that his father lacked, and Savoy enjoyed a
1 CONT golden age under his leadership. Despite his youth he began the push northwest
1 CONT into new territories. In the same year he granted Aosta Valley the "Carta
1 CONT delle Franchigie", recognising the right to administrative and political
1 CONT autonomy. This right was maintained up until the eve of the French Revolution.
1 CONT Later he conquered Vaud, Bugey, and Carignano. He supported the Hohenstaufens,
1 CONT and was known as "Thomas the Ghibelline" because of his career as Imperial
1 CONT Vicar of Lombardy.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Family and children
1 CONT In 1195 he ambushed the party of Count William I of Geneva, which was
1 CONT escorting the count's daughter, Marguerite of Geneva, to France for her
1 CONT intended wedding to King Philip II of France. Thomas carried off Marguerite
1 CONT and married her himself, producing some eight sons and six daughters.
1 CONT
1 CONT Amedeo, his immediate successor
1 CONT Umberto, d. between March and November 1223
1 CONT Tommaso, lord and then count in Piedmont and founder of a line that became the
1 CONT Savoy-Achaea
1 CONT Aimone, d. August 30, 1237, Lord of Chablais
1 CONT Guglielmo (William of Savoy), Bishop of Valence and Dean of Vienne
1 CONT Amadeo of Savoy, Bishop of Maurienne
1 CONT Pietro, who resided much in England, became Earl of Richmond, and ultimately
1 CONT in 1263 became the disputed count of Savoy
1 CONT Filippo, archbishop of Lyon, who resigned, through marriage became Count
1 CONT Palatine of Burgundy and ultimately in 1268 became the disputed count of Savoy
1 CONT Bonifacio who became archbishop of Canterbury
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy, d. 1265 or 1266, married in December 1219 to Ramon
1 CONT Berenguer IV, Count of Provence (1209-1245) and was mother of four Queens-
1 CONT consort
1 CONT Alasia of Savoy, abbess of the monastery of St Pierre in Lyon (d.1250)
1 CONT Ágatha of Savoy, abbess of the monastery of St Pierre in Lyon (d.1245)
1 CONT Margherita of Savoy, d. 1273, married in 1218 to Hartmann I of Kyburg
1 CONT Avita of Savoy (1215-92) who married Baldwin de Redvers, 7th Earl of Devon and
1 CONT Robert Aguillon (d.1286).
1 CONT
1 CONT Further reading
1 CONT Francesco Cognasso, Il Piemonte nell'Età Sveva (Turin, 1968)
