1 CONT Under Humbert II (1080) occurred the first clash of the House of Savoy with
1 CONT the Piedmontese communes, but he and his successors, Amadeus III (who died on
1 CONT his way home from the crusades) and Thomas I (1189), adopted a policy of
1 CONT conciliation towards them. Thomas, who reigned until 1222, acquired extensions
1 CONT of territory in the Bugey, Vaud and Romont to the west of the Alps, and
1 CONT Carignano, Pinerolo, Moncalieri and Vigone to the east; he also exercised sway
1 CONT over Geneva, Albenga, Savona and Saluzzo. At his death, these territories were
1 CONT divided among his sons, Thomas II obtaining Piedmont, Aimone the Chablais,
1 CONT Peter and Philip other fiefs, and Amadeus IV, the eldest, Savoy and a general
1 CONT overlordship over his brothers' estates. Thomas II, during the wars in
1 CONT Piedmont, was made prisoner by the citizens of Turin, but was afterwards
1 CONT liberated. [Encyclopaedia Britannica, 1961 ed., Vol. 20, p. 26, SAVOY, HOUSE
1 CONT OF]
