1 CONT Amadeus IV
1 CONT "The reign of HUMBERT's son, Count Thomas I (1189-1233), opened a golden age
1 CONT for Savoy for he started the great advance north-westwards which carried his
1 CONT successors' sway over the Rhone into Bresse and to the Saone between Macon and
1 CONT Chalon. Even more significant was his victory over Berthold V of Zahringen
1 CONT which cleared the way for the conquest by his son Peter II (1263-8) of what is
1 CONT now the cantons of Vaud and Fribourg. Thomas was also more successful than his
1 CONT father in reproducing his race for his
1 CONT bride, MARGARET, daughter of the COUNT OF GENEVOIS, who raised eight sons and
1 CONT six daughters. [Thomas m. MARGARET (abt 1180 - 8 Apr 1257), dau. of WILLIAM I,
1 CONT COUNT OF GENEVA (1130 - 27 Jul 1195) and heiress of Faucigni.]
1 CONT According to the chronicler of Hautecombe Abbey, the Westminster of Savoy,
1 CONT MARGARET was being taken in 1196 to France by her ambitious father to become
1 CONT the third wife of Richard Lionhart's enemy, PHILIP AUGUSTUS. Thomas had fallen
1 CONT passionately in love with her and, ambushing her party in a narrow gorge in
1 CONT Bugey, defied the KING OF FRANCE and carried her off to the altar."
1 CONT "From the time of Thomas I the counts were effectively rulers of a minor
1 CONT kingdom and there were very few states of any size in which the central power
1 CONT had so successfully established its authority."
1 CONT Cox, Eugene L. The Eagles of Savoy: The House of Savoy in Thirteenth-Century
1 CONT Europe. Princeton, New Jersey: Princeton University Press, 1974. Thomas, count
1 CONT of Savoy, died in 1233 a relatively obscure nobleman, but his seven sons and
1 CONT two daughters rose to fame, fortune, and involvement in almost every
1 CONT international conflict in western Europe during the next fifty years. From
1 CONT Scotland to Sicily, they gained access to and marriage within every important
1 CONT royal house in Europe. Observed Joseph Bedier, "They did not pride themselves
1 CONT upon their own prowess, but upon their lineage, and each of them rejoiced to
1 CONT contemplate in the others, as in so many mirrors, his own image multiplied."
1 CONT FROM CURT HOFEMANN:
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas (Tomaso) I Count of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT Name: Thomas C. of SAVOY [Ref: Turton pp. 4 & 60]
1 CONT Name: Thomas I, Count of Savoy [Ref: Weis AR7 28:31 & 133:26]
1 CONT Count of Savoy 1189-1233 [Ref: Tapsell p. 240]
1 CONT
1 CONT Tommaso I di SAVOIA, C of Savoy. Born 20 May 1178. Died 1 Mar 1233. He married
1 CONT Beatrix de GENEVE, About 1196. [ES II:190, XI:158] [Ref: Richard Borthwick 26
1 CONT Jan 1999 msg to SGM]
1 CONT
1 CONT Apparently the name Thomas was given to him in honour of St. Thomas Becket,
1 CONT whose cult was raging at the time of his birth. There had been a series of
1 CONT minorities in the line of the counts of Savoy, including the father and
1 CONT grandfather of Thomas, and his coming of age may well have been brought
1 CONT forward from experience of the activities of regents.
1 CONT As ruler Thomas I opened a golden age for Savoy, as he started the great push
1 CONT northwestwards which carried the area controlled by his successors over the
1 CONT Rhone into Bresse and to the Saone between Maçon and Chalon. Even more
1 CONT significant was his victory over Berthold V of Zähringen, which cleared the
1 CONT way for the conquest by his son Peter II of what are now the cantons of Vaud
1 CONT and Fribourg. Thomas was also more successful than his father in reproducing
1 CONT his line; with his wife Beatrice de Genève he raised eight sons and six
1 CONT daughters.
1 CONT From the time of Thomas I the counts were effectively rulers of a minor
1 CONT kingdom and there were very few states of any size in which the central power
1 CONT had so successfully established its authority. Savoy's greatest days were
1 CONT under Peter and Philip, the sons of Thomas. Savoy prospered and continued to
1 CONT expand from this time into the sixteenth century. [Ref: Leo van de Pas,
1 CONT _Genealogics_ citing Christopher Cope's, _The Lost Kingdom of Burgundy_, Paget
1 CONT p. 67, ES (Schwennicke) II:190 & ES (Isenburg) II:110 online at:
1 CONT [http://www.genealogics.org/getperson.php?personID=I00027292&tree=LEO](http://www.genealogics.org/getperson.php?personID=I00027292&tree=LEO)]
1 CONT
1 CONT "The reign of HUMBERT's son, Count Thomas I (1189-1233), opened a golden age
1 CONT for Savoy for he started the great advance north-westwards which carried his
1 CONT successors' sway over the Rhone into Bresse and to the Saone between Macon and
1 CONT Chalon. Even more significant was his victory over Berthold V of Zahringen
1 CONT which cleared the way for the conquest by his son Peter II (1263-8) of what is
1 CONT now the cantons of Vaud and Fribourg. Thomas was also more successful than his
1 CONT father in reproducing his race for his bride, MARGARET, daughter of the COUNT
1 CONT OF GENEVOIS, who raised eight sons and six daughters. [Thomas m. MARGARET (abt
1 CONT 1180 - 8 Apr 1257), dau. of WILLIAM I, COUNT OF GENEVA (1130 - 27 Jul 1195)
1 CONT and heiress of Faucigni.] According to the chronicler of Hautecombe Abbey, the
1 CONT Westminster of Savoy, MARGARET was being taken in 1196 to France by her
1 CONT ambitious father to become the third wife of Richard Lionhart's enemy, PHILIP
1 CONT AUGUSTUS. Thomas had fallen passionately in love with her and, ambushing her
1 CONT party in a narrow gorge in Bugey, defied the KING OF FRANCE and carried her
1 CONT off to the altar."
1 CONT "From the time of Thomas I the counts were effectively rulers of a minor
1 CONT kingdom and there were very few states of any size in which the central power
1 CONT had so successfully established its authority."
1 CONT Savoy's greatest days were under Thomas' sons, Peter and Philip. Savoy
1 CONT prospered and even continued to expand from this time on into the sixteenth
1 CONT century. [Ref: Jim Stevens 1 Nov 1996 msg to SGM, quoting Christopher Cope's,
1 CONT _The Lost Kingdom of Burgundy_]
