1 CONT 6\. Agnes de Savoy b: ABT 1205 in Savoy, France
1 CONT 7\. Philip Count of Savoy , Count of Burgundy b: 1207 in Evian-les-Bains,
1 CONT Haute-Savoie, Rhone-Alpes, France
1 CONT 8\. Guiscard I de Charron , Steward of Richmond b: ABT 1215 in Charron, Ain,
1 CONT Rhone-Alpes, France
1 CONT WIKIPEDIA:
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas I of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT Thomas I or Tommaso I (c. 1176 – March 1, 1233) was Count of Savoy from
1 CONT 1189-1233. He was the son of Humbert III of Savoy and Beatrice of Viennois.
1 CONT His birth was seen as miraculous; his monkish father had despaired of having a
1 CONT male heir after three wives. Count Humbert sought counsel from St. Anthelm,
1 CONT who blessed Humbert three times, and it was seen as a prophecy come true when
1 CONT Thomas was born shortly after Anthelm himself died on June 26, 1178. He was
1 CONT named in honour of Saint Thomas Becket.
1 CONT Thomas was still a minor when his father died on 4 March 1189, and a council
1 CONT of regency was established, comprising of his mother Beatrice, his father's
1 CONT cousin Boniface I of Montferrat, and the Bishop of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne. He
1 CONT had reached his majority by August 1191. Thomas possessed the martial
1 CONT abilities, energy, and brilliance that his father lacked, and Savoy enjoyed a
1 CONT golden age under his leadership. Despite his youth he began the push north-
1 CONT west into new territories. In the same year he granted Aosta Valley the "Carta
1 CONT delle Franchigie", recognising the right to administrative and political
1 CONT autonomy. This right was maintained up until the eve of the French Revolution.
1 CONT Later he conquered Vaud, Bugey, and Carignano. He supported the Hohenstaufens,
1 CONT and was known as "Thomas the Ghibelline" due to his career as Imperial Vicar
1 CONT of Lombardy.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family and children
1 CONT In 1195 he ambushed the party of Count William I of Geneva, which was
1 CONT escorting the count's daughter, Marguerite, to France for her intended wedding
1 CONT to King Philip II of France. Thomas carried off Marguerite and married her
1 CONT himself, producing some eight sons and six daughters.
1 CONT 1\. Amedeo, his immediate successor
1 CONT 2\. Umberto, d. between March and November 1223
1 CONT 3\. Tommaso, lord and then count in Piedmont and founder of a line that became
1 CONT the Savoy-Achaea
1 CONT 4\. Aimone, d. August 30, 1237, Lord of Chablais
1 CONT 5\. Guglielmo (William of Savoy), Bishop of Valence and Dean of Vienne
1 CONT 6\. Amadeo of Savoy, Bishop of Maurienne
1 CONT 7\. Pietro, who resided much in England, became Earl of Richmond, and
1 CONT ultimately in 1263 became the disputed count of Savoy
1 CONT 8\. Filippo, archbishop of Lyon, who resigned, through marriage became Count
1 CONT Palatine of Burgundy and ultimately in 1268 became the disputed count of Savoy
1 CONT 9\. Bonifacio who became archbishop of Canterbury
1 CONT 10\. Beatrice of Savoy, d. 1265 or 1266, married in December 1219 to Ramon
1 CONT Berenguer IV, Count of Provence (1209-1245) and was mother of four Queens-
1 CONT consort
1 CONT 11\. Alasia of Savoy, abbess of the monastery of St Pierre in Lyon
1 CONT 12\. Ágatha of Savoy, abbess of the monastery of St Pierre in Lyon
1 CONT 13\. Margherita of Savoy, d. 1273, married in 1218 to Hartmann I of Kyburg
1 CONT 14\. Avita of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT Further reading:
1 CONT • Francesco Cognasso, Il Piemonte nell’Età Sveva (Turin, 1968)
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by Humbert III
1 CONT Count of Savoy
1 CONT Succeeded by Amadeus IV
1 CONT Notes for Count Thomas I de Savoie:
1 CONT
1 CONT Count of Savoy ; Ct Tomaso I of Savoy (1189-1233) ; He supported
1 CONT theHohenstaufens and was appointed Imperial Vicar, a position he used toextend
1 CONT his lands both sides of the Alps. Towards France he gained Vaudand Bugey, and
1 CONT to the east Carignano and other lands.
1 CONT 1233
