0 @N00663@ NOTE (Garsenda de Sabran comtessa de Forcauquier)
0 @N00664@ NOTE geni:about_me Garsenda or Garsende (II) de Sabran (c. 1180 – c. 1242) was the
1 CONT Countess of Provence as the wife of Alfonso II from 1193 and the Countess of
1 CONT Forcalquier in her own right from 1209. She brought Forcalquier to the House
1 CONT of Barcelona and united it to Provence. She was also a patron of Occitan
1 CONT literature, especially the troubadours, and herself wrote some lyric poetry
1 CONT and is counted among the trobairitz as Garsenda de Proensa or Proença. She
1 CONT was, in the words of her most recent editors, "one of the most powerful women
1 CONT in Occitan history".
1 CONT
1 CONT Early life and marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT Garsenda was the daughter of Renier de Sabran, lord of Caylar and Ansouis, and
1 CONT Garsenda, daughter of William IV of Forcalquier. She was named after her
1 CONT mother, who was the heiress of William IV, but predeceased him. Garsenda
1 CONT therefore inherited Forcalquier from her grandfather. She was only thirteen
1 CONT years of age when, in 1193, her grandfather William IV and Alfonso II signed
1 CONT the Treaty of Aix whereby Garsenda would inherit William's county and would
1 CONT marry Alfonso, who was in line to become Count of Provence. The marriage took
1 CONT place at Aix-en-Provence in July 1193. They had at least two children, Raymond
1 CONT Berengar IV and Garsenda, who married Guillermo II de Montcada, and bore him
1 CONT two children, including Gaston VII, Viscount of Béarn.
1 CONT
1 CONT Regency and patronage
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1209 both William IV and Alfonso died and Garsenda became the natural
1 CONT guardian of their heir, her son, Raymond Berengar IV. Initially her brother-
1 CONT in-law, Peter II of Aragon, assigned the regency of Provence to his brother
1 CONT Sancho, but when Peter died in 1213 Sancho became regent of Aragon and passed
1 CONT Provence and Forcalquier to his son Nuño Sánchez. Dissension broke out between
1 CONT the Catalans and the partisans of the countess, who accused Nuño of attempting
1 CONT to supplant his nephew in the county. The Provençal aristocracy originally
1 CONT took advantage of the situation for their own ambitious ends, but eventually
1 CONT they lined up behind Garsenda and removed Nuño, who returned to Catalonia. The
1 CONT regency was passed to Garsenda and a regency council was established
1 CONT consisting of the native nobles.
1 CONT
1 CONT It was probably during her tenure as regent (1209/1213–1217/1220) that
1 CONT Garsenda became the focus of a literary circle of poets, though the _vida_ of
1 CONT Elias de Barjols refers to his patron as Alfonso. There is a _tenso_ between a
1 CONT _bona dompna_ (good lady), identified in one chansonnier as _la contessa de
1 CONT Proessa,_ and an anonymous troubadour. The two _coblas_ of the exchange are
1 CONT found in two different orders in the two chansonniers, called _F_ and _T_ ,
1 CONT that preserve them. It cannot be known therefore who spoke first, but the
1 CONT woman's half begins _Vos q'em semblatz dels corals amadors_. In the poem the
1 CONT countess declares her love for her interlocutor, who then responds courteously
1 CONT but carefully. Under some interpretations the troubadour is Gui de Cavaillon,
1 CONT whose _vida_ repeats the rumour (probably unfounded) that he was the countess'
1 CONT lover. Gui, however, was at the Provençal court between 1200 and 1209, pushing
1 CONT the date of the exchange forward a bit. Elias de Barjols apparently "fell in
1 CONT love" with her as a widow and wrote songs about her "for the rest of his
1 CONT life," until he entered a monastery. Raimon Vidal also praised her renowned
1 CONT patronage of troubadours.
1 CONT
1 CONT Poetry
1 CONT
1 CONT Vos q'em semblatz dels corals amadors,
1 CONT
1 CONT ja non volgra que fossetz tan doptanz;
1 CONT
1 CONT e platz me molt quar vos destreing m'amors,
1 CONT
1 CONT qu'atressi sui eu per vos malananz.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ez avetz dan en vostre vulpillatge
1 CONT
1 CONT quar no.us ausatz de preiar enardir,
1 CONT
1 CONT e faitz a vos ez a mi gran dampnatge;
1 CONT
1 CONT que ges dompna no ausa descobrir
1 CONT
1 CONT tot so qu'il vol per paor de faillir.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT You're so well-suited as a lover,
1 CONT
1 CONT I wish you wouldn't be so hesitant;
1 CONT
1 CONT but I'm glad my love makes you the penitent,
1 CONT
1 CONT otherwise I'd be the one to suffer.
1 CONT
1 CONT Still, in the long run it's you who stands to lose
1 CONT
1 CONT if you're not brave enough to state your case,
1 CONT
1 CONT and you'll do both of us great harm if you refuse.
1 CONT
1 CONT For a lady doesn't dare uncover
1 CONT
1 CONT her true will, lest those around her think her base.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Retirement and later life
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1220 Guillaume de Sabran, a nephew of William IV, who claimed Forcalquier
1 CONT and had been in revolt in the region of Sisteron, was neutralised in part
1 CONT through the mediation of the Archbishop of Aix, Bermond le Cornu. By 1217 or
1 CONT 1220 Garsenda had finally ceded Forcalquier to her son and handed the reins of
1 CONT government over.
1 CONT
1 CONT Garsenda retired to the monastery of La Celle in 1222 or 1225. In 1242, she
1 CONT went to visit her newly born great-granddaughter, Beatrice of England, and her
1 CONT parents in Bordeaux. As the father, Henry III of England, was engaged in a war
1 CONT in France at the time, she brought 60 knights to his service. Garsend may have
1 CONT been alive as late as 1257, when a certain woman of that name made a donation
1 CONT to a church of St-Jean on the condition that three priests be kept to pray for
1 CONT her soul and that of her husband.
1 CONT
1 CONT <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garsenda,_Countess_of_Forcalquier>
