1 CONT Eleanor of England (known in Castilian as Leonor; 13 October 1162 – 31 October
1 CONT 1214) was Queen of Castile and Toledo as wife of Alfonso VIII of Castile. She
1 CONT was a daughter of Henry II of England and his wife Eleanor of Aquitaine. Early
1 CONT life
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born in the castle at Domfront, Normandy, and was baptised by Henry of
1 CONT Marcy. She was the sixth child and second daughter of King Henry II of England
1 CONT and his wife Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Her godfather was the chronicler
1 CONT Robert of Torigny, who had a special interest in her and recorded her life as
1 CONT best he could. She received her first name as a namesake of her mother, whose
1 CONT name "Eleanor" (or Alienor) had previously been unrecorded though may have
1 CONT been related to the Greek Helen or the Italian Elena. Another view holds that
1 CONT in the Occitan language, Eleanor simply meant "the other Aenor," since Eleanor
1 CONT of Aquitaine was named for her mother, called Aenor. Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Eleanor was a younger maternal half-sister of Marie de Champagne and Alix of
1 CONT France. She was a younger sister of William IX, Count of Poitiers, Henry the
1 CONT Young King, Matilda, Duchess of Saxony, Richard I of England and Geoffrey II,
1 CONT Duke of Brittany. She was also an older sister of Joan of Sicily and John of
1 CONT England. Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT When she was 14 years old, in September 1176, she was married to Alfonso VIII.
1 CONT The marriage was arranged to secure the Pyrennean border, with Gascony offered
1 CONT as her dowry.
1 CONT
1 CONT Of all Eleanor of Aquitaine's daughters, her namesake Eleanor best inherited
1 CONT her mother's political influence. She was almost as powerful as her husband,
1 CONT who specified in his will that she was to rule alongside their son in the
1 CONT event of his death. It was she who persuaded him to marry their daughter
1 CONT Berenguela to the King of Leon in the interest of peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Alfonso died, his Queen was reportedly so devastated with grief that she
1 CONT was unable to preside over the burial. Their eldest daughter, Berenguela,
1 CONT instead performed these honors. Leonora then took sick and died only twenty-
1 CONT eight days after her husband, and was buried at Las Huelgas Abbey in Burgos.
1 CONT Children
1 CONT
1 CONT She and her husband had the following surviving issue:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Berenguela, Queen of Castile (August 1180 - 8 November 1246), married King Alfonso IX of Leon
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Sancho of Castile (born & died 1181)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Sancha of Castile (1182 - 3 February 1184)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Henry of Castile (born & died 1184)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Urraca of Castile (1186-1220), married King Alfonso II of Portugal
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Blanca of Castile (4 March 1188 – 26 November 1252), married King Louis VIII of France
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Fernando of Castile (29 September 1189 - 1211)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Mafalda of Castile (1191-1204)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Constance of Castile (1195-1198)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Constanza, Nun at Las Huelgas (1201-1243)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Eleanor of Castile (1202-1244), married King James I of Aragon
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Henry I, King of Castile (14 April 1204 - 1217)
