1 CONT Queen Leonora (October 13, 1162 – October 31, 1214), was born as Princess
1 CONT Eleanor of England (and Aquitaine) and became Leonora, Queen of Castile as
1 CONT wife of Alfonso VIII of Castile. She was born in the castle at Domfront,
1 CONT Normandy, and was baptised by Henry of Marcy. She was the sixth child and
1 CONT second daughter of King Henry II of England and his wife Queen Eleanor of
1 CONT Aquitaine. Her godfather was the chronicler Robert of Torigny, who had a
1 CONT special interest in her and recorded her life as best he could. She received
1 CONT her first name as a namesake of her mother, whose name "Eleanor" (or Alienor)
1 CONT had previously been unrecorded though may have been related to the Greek Helen
1 CONT or the Italian Elena. Another view holds that in the Occitan language, Eleanor
1 CONT simply meant "the other Aenor," since Eleanor of Aquitaine was named for her
1 CONT mother, called Aenor. Eleanor was a younger maternal half-sister of Marie de
1 CONT Champagne and Alix of France. She was a younger sister of William, Count of
1 CONT Poitiers, Henry the Young King, Matilda of England, Richard I of England and
1 CONT Geoffrey II, Duke of Brittany. She was also an older sister of Joan of Sicily
1 CONT and John of England. When she was eight years old, in 1170, she was married to
1 CONT Alfonso VIII. The marriage was arranged to secure the Pyrennean border, with
1 CONT Gascony offered as her dowry. Of all Eleanor of Aquitaine's daughters, her
1 CONT namesake Eleanor (who was called Leonor by her Spanish subjects) best
1 CONT inherited her mother's political influence. She reigned alongside her husband,
1 CONT who specified in his will that she was to rule alongside their son in the
1 CONT event of his death. It was she who persuaded him to marry their daughter
1 CONT Berenguela to the king of Leon in the interest of peace. When Alfonso died,
1 CONT his queen was reportedly so devastated with grief that she was unable to
1 CONT preside over the burial. Their daughter Berenguela instead performed these
1 CONT honors. Leonora then took sick and died only twenty-eight days after her
1 CONT husband, and was buried at Abbey de las Huelgas, in Burgos. [edit]Children of
