1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Eleanor of England (known in Castilian as Leonor; 13 October 1162 – 31 October
1 CONT 1214) was Queen of Castile and Toledo as wife of Alfonso VIII of Castile. She
1 CONT was a daughter of Henry II of England and his wife, Duchess Eleanor of
1 CONT Aquitaine.
1 CONT
1 CONT Contents [hide] 1 Early life 2 Family 3 Marriage 4 Children 5 Ancestors 6
1 CONT References 7 Sources 8 External links
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Early life She was born in the castle at Domfront, Normandy, and was
1 CONT baptised by Henry of Marcy. She was the sixth child and second daughter of
1 CONT King Henry II of England and his wife, Duchess Eleanor of Aquitaine.[1] Her
1 CONT godfather was the chronicler Robert of Torigny, who had a special interest in
1 CONT her and recorded her life as best he could. She received her first name as a
1 CONT namesake of her mother, whose name "Eleanor" (or Alienor) had previously been
1 CONT unrecorded though may have been related to the Greek Helen or the Italian
1 CONT Elena. Another view holds that in the Occitan language, Eleanor simply meant
1 CONT "the other Aenor", since Eleanor of Aquitaine was named for her mother, called
1 CONT Aenor.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Family Eleanor was a younger maternal half-sister of Marie de Champagne
1 CONT and Alix of France. She was a younger sister of William IX, Count of Poitiers,
1 CONT Henry the Young King, Matilda, Duchess of Saxony, Richard I of England and
1 CONT Geoffrey II, Duke of Brittany. She was also an older sister of Queen Joan of
1 CONT Sicily and King John of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marriage When she was 14 years old, before 17 September 1177, she was
1 CONT married to King Alfonso VIII of Castile in Burgos.[2][3] The marriage was
1 CONT arranged to secure the Pyrennean border, with Gascony offered as her dowry.
1 CONT
1 CONT Of all Eleanor of Aquitaine's daughters, her namesake Eleanor best inherited
1 CONT her mother's political influence. She was almost as powerful as her husband,
1 CONT who specified in his will that she was to rule alongside their son in the
1 CONT event of his death. It was she who persuaded him to marry their daughter
1 CONT Berengaria to the King of Leon in the interest of peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Alfonso died, his Queen was reportedly so devastated with grief that she
1 CONT was unable to preside over the burial. Their eldest daughter, Berengaria,
1 CONT instead performed these honors. Eleanor then took sick and died only twenty-
1 CONT eight days after her husband, and was buried at Las Huelgas Abbey in Burgos.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Children She and her husband had the following surviving issue:[3][4]
1 CONT
1 CONT Name Birth Death Notes Infanta Berenguela (Berengaria) Burgos, 1 January/ June
1 CONT 1180 Las Huelgas near Burgos, 8 November 1246 Married firstly in Seligenstadt
1 CONT on 23 April 1188 with Duke Conrad II of Swabia, but the union (only by
1 CONT contract and never solemnized) was later annulled. Married in Valladolid
1 CONT between 1/16 December 1197 with King Alfonso IX of León as her second wife.[5]
1 CONT After their marriage was dissolved on grounds of consanguinity in 1204, she
1 CONT returned to her homeland and became regent of her minor brother King Henry I.
1 CONT Queen of Castile in her own right after the death of Henry I in 1214,
1 CONT inmediately abdicated in favor of her son. Infante Sancho Burgos, 5 April 1181
1 CONT 26 July 1181 Heir of the throne since his birth, died aged three months.
1 CONT Infanta Sancha 20/28 March 1182 3 February 1184/ 16 October 1185 Died in
1 CONT infancy. Infante Enrique (Henry) 1184 1184? Heir of the throne since his
1 CONT birth, died either shortly after been born or in infancy. His existence is
1 CONT disputed among sources. Infanta Urraca 1186/ 28 May 1187 Coimbra, 3 November
1 CONT 1220 Married in 1206 to Prince Alfonso, who succeeded his father in 1212 as
1 CONT King Alfonso II of Portugal. Infanta Blanca (Blanche) Palencia, 4 March 1188
1 CONT Paris, 27 November 1252 Married in the Abbaye de Port-Mort near Pont-Audemer,
1 CONT Normandy on 23 May 1200 with Prince Louis, who succeeded his father in 1223 as
1 CONT King Louis VIII of France. Regent of the Kingdom of France during her son's
1 CONT minority (1226–1234) and during his absence on the Seventh Crusade. Infante
1 CONT Fernando (Ferdinand) Cuenca, 29 September 1189 Madrid, 14 October 1211 Heir of
1 CONT the throne since his birth. On whose behalf Diego of Acebo and the future
1 CONT Saint Dominic travelled to Denmark in 1203 to secure a bride[6] He died soon
1 CONT after returning from campaigning against the Moors. Infanta Mafalda Plasencia,
1 CONT 1191 Salamanca, 1211 Betrothed in 1204 to Infante Ferdinand of Leon, eldest
1 CONT son of King Alfonso IX and stepson of her oldest sister. Infanta Constanza
1 CONT (Constance) 1195 Las Huelgas, 1243 A nun at the Cistercian monastery of Santa
1 CONT María la Real at Las Huelgas in 1217, she later became Abbess of her
1 CONT community. Infanta Leonor (Eleanor) 1202 Las Huelgas, 1244 Married in Ágreda
1 CONT on 6 February 1221 with King James I of Aragon. After her marriage was
1 CONT dissolved on grounds of consanguinity in April 1229, she became a nun at the
1 CONT Cistercian monastery of Santa María la Real at Las Huelgas. King Enrique I
1 CONT (Henry I) of Castile Valladolid, 14 April 1204 Palencia, 6 June 1217 Only
1 CONT surviving son, he succeeded his father in 1214 aged ten under the regency
1 CONT firstly of his mother and later his oldest sister Berengaria. Married in
1 CONT Burgos before 29 August 1215 with Infanta Mafalda of Portugal, the union was
1 CONT unconsummated and disolved in 1216 on grounds of consanguinity. Soon after his
1 CONT divorce was betrothed with Infanta Sancha of León, eldest daughter of King
1 CONT Alfonso IX and stepdaughter of her oldest sister, but died killed by a tile
1 CONT coming off a roof before the marriage could be solemnized.
1 CONT
