1 CONT Spanish royalty Preceded by Richeza of Poland Queen consort of Castile
1 CONT 1177–1214 Succeeded by Mafalda of Portugal
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Princesa de Inglaterra y reina consorte de Castilla entre los años 1170 y
1 CONT 1214, por su matrimonio con el rey Alfonso VIII de Castilla. Fue hija del rey
1 CONT Enrique II de Inglaterra y de su esposa, la reina Leonor de Aquitania.
1 CONT
1 CONT Fue madre, entre otros, de los reyes Enrique I de Castilla y Berenguela I de
1 CONT Castilla.
1 CONT
1 CONT Fue hija del rey Enrique II de Inglaterra y de su esposa, la reina Leonor de
1 CONT Aquitania. Por parte paterna fueron sus abuelos Godofredo V de Anjou y su
1 CONT esposa Matilde de Inglaterra, hija del rey Enrique I de Inglaterra. Por parte
1 CONT materna fueron sus abuelos Guillermo X de Poitiers, conde de Poitiers, y su
1 CONT esposa Leonor de Châtellerault, duquesa de Aquitania.
1 CONT
1 CONT Fueron sus hermanos, entre otros, los reyes Ricardo Corazón de León y Juan sin
1 CONT Tierra, monarcas de Inglaterra.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nació en 1160 y en septiembre de 1170 se desposó en la ciudad de Tarazona con
1 CONT Alfonso VIII de Castilla, quien había sido coronado en la ciudad de Burgos un
1 CONT año antes, y antes del matrimonio, sus padres, los reyes de Inglaterra,
1 CONT concedieron como dote a su hija el ducado de Aquitania, que pertenecía a su
1 CONT madre, la reina Leonor de Aquitania. Alfonso VIII de Castilla concedió como
1 CONT dote a su esposa los castillos de Burgos y Castrojeriz, Amaya, Avia, Saldaña,
1 CONT Monzón de Campos, Carrión de los Condes, Dueñas, Tariego de Cerrato, Cabezón,
1 CONT Medina del Campo, Astudillo, Aguilar y Villaescusa, y las rentas del puerto de
1 CONT Santander, Cabedo, Besgo de Santillana, Tudela, Calahorra, Arnedo, Vigera,
1 CONT Metria, las del castillo y ciudad de Nájera, Logroño, Grañón, Belorado,
1 CONT Pancorbo, Piedralada, Poza de la Sal, monasterio de Rodilla, Atienza, Ciudad
1 CONT de Osma, Peñafiel, Curiel de Duero, Hita, Zurita y Peñanegra, y para su cámara
1 CONT la ciudad de Burgos y la villa de Castrojeriz, con todos sus derechos y
1 CONT rentas, y le donaría además la mitad de los territorios que conquistase a los
1 CONT musulmanes desde que su matrimonio fuera celebrado.
1 CONT
1 CONT El matrimonio sirvió para reforzar la frontera pirenaica, y Leonor Plantagenet
1 CONT aportó además como dote de boda el condado de Gascuña que Alfonso VIII nunca
1 CONT pudo anexionar a la corona de Castilla. Sin embargo, numerosos caballeros
1 CONT gascones vinieron a la península para ayudar a su señor en la lucha contra los
1 CONT almohades. Hacia 1180 el monarca castellano y su esposa decidieron fundar un
1 CONT monasterio de monjas cistercienses, el monasterio de las Huelgas de Burgos.
1 CONT Aquella fundación, dependiente en principio del Monasterio de Santa María de
1 CONT la Caridad de Tulebras, en (Navarra), se convirtió desde 1187, por deseo de
1 CONT los reyes, en casa madre de todas las abadías femeninas cistercienses en
1 CONT territorio de Castilla y fue elegido por Alfonso VIII y su esposa como panteón
1 CONT real para ellos y sus descendientes.
1 CONT
1 CONT La reina ordenó edificar en la catedral de Toledo una capilla dedicada a Santo
1 CONT Tomás Becket o Tomás Canturiense (de Canterbury), como era conocido entonces,
1 CONT que fue la primera dedicada al santo británico fuera de las Islas Británicas.
1 CONT La capilla no se conserva en la actualidad porque fue destruída y su espacio
1 CONT pasó a formar parte de la capilla de Santiago de la Catedral de Toledo, que
1 CONT fue edificada por el condestable Álvaro de Luna para construir su propia
1 CONT capilla funeraria. Asimismo en 1183, sobre el solar de la mezquita de Cuenca
1 CONT ordenó que se comenzase a construir una catedral para la ciudad manchega, que
1 CONT había sido reconquistada recientemente.
1 CONT
1 CONT La reina Leonor Plantagenet falleció el día 31 de octubre de 1214, varias
1 CONT semanas después de que falleciera su esposo, el rey Alfonso VIII de Castilla,
1 CONT quien falleció el día 6 de octubre de 1214.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Sources: See those of her descendants.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Queen Leonora (October 13, 1162 – October 31, 1214), was born as Princess
1 CONT Eleanor of England (and Aquitaine) and became Leonora, Queen of Castile as
1 CONT wife of Alfonso VIII of Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born in the castle at Domfront, Normandy, and was baptised by Henry of
1 CONT Marcy. She was the sixth child and second daughter of King Henry II of England
1 CONT and his wife Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Her godfather was the chronicler
1 CONT Robert of Torigny, who had a special interest in her and recorded her life as
1 CONT best he could. She received her first name as a namesake of her mother, whose
1 CONT name "Eleanor" (or Alienor) had previously been unrecorded though may have
1 CONT been related to the Greek Helen or the Italian Elena. Another view holds that
1 CONT in the Occitan language, Eleanor simply meant "the other Aenor," since Eleanor
1 CONT of Aquitaine was named for her mother, called Aenor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Eleanor was a younger maternal half-sister of Marie de Champagne and Alix of
1 CONT France. She was a younger sister of William, Count of Poitiers, Henry the
1 CONT Young King, Matilda of England, Richard I of England and Geoffrey II, Duke of
1 CONT Brittany. She was also an older sister of Joan of Sicily and John of England.
1 CONT
1 CONT When she was eighteen years old, in 1180, she was married to Alfonso VIII. The
1 CONT marriage was arranged to secure the Pyrennean border, with Gascony offered as
1 CONT her dowry.
1 CONT
1 CONT Of all Eleanor of Aquitaine's daughters, her namesake Eleanor (who was called
1 CONT Leonor by her Spanish subjects) best inherited her mother's political
1 CONT influence. She reigned alongside her husband, who specified in his will that
1 CONT she was to rule alongside their son in the event of his death. It was she who
1 CONT persuaded him to marry their daughter Berenguela to the king of Leon in the
1 CONT interest of peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Alfonso died, his queen was reportedly so devastated with grief that she
1 CONT was unable to preside over the burial. Their daughter Berenguela instead
1 CONT performed these honors. Leonora then took sick and died only twenty-eight days
1 CONT after her husband, and was buried at Las Huelgas abbey in Burgos.
1 CONT
1 CONT Children of Leonora and Alfonso Berenguela, Queen of Castile (August 1180 - 8
1 CONT November 1246), married King Alfonso IX of Leon Sancho of Castile (born & died
1 CONT 1181) Sancha of Castile (1182 - 3 February 1184) Henry of Castile (born & died
1 CONT 1184) Urraca, princess of Castile (1186-1220), married King Alfonso II of
1 CONT Portugal Blanca of Castile (4 March 1188 - 26 November 1252), married King
1 CONT Louis VIII of France Fernando of Castile (29 September 1189 - 1211) Mafalda of
1 CONT Castile (1191-1204) Constance of Castile (1195-1198) Leonor of Castile
1 CONT (1200-1244), married King James I of Aragon Constanza, nun at Las Huelgas
1 CONT (1201-1243) Henry I, King of Castile (14 April 1204 - 1217)
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Eleanor of England (also known as Leonora de Ingleterra) was Queen of Castile
1 CONT as wife of Alfonso VIII of Castile. When she was eighteen years old, she was
1 CONT married to Alfonso VIII. The marriage was arranged to secure the Pyrennean
1 CONT border, with Gascony offered as her dowry.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Alfonso died, his queen was reportedly so devastated with grief that she
1 CONT was unable to preside over the burial. Their daughter Berenguela instead
1 CONT performed these honors. Leonora then took sick and died only twenty-eight days
1 CONT after her husband.
1 CONT
1 CONT She bore 12 children with Alfonso, including our ancestor Blanche of Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT See <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonora_of_England> for more information.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Eleanor of England (later Leonora; 13 October 1162 – 31 October 1214) was
1 CONT Queen of Castile as wife of Alfonso VIII of Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT She was born in the castle at Domfront, Normandy, and was baptised by Henry of
1 CONT Marcy. She was the sixth child and second daughter of King Henry II of England
1 CONT and his wife Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Her godfather was the chronicler
1 CONT Robert of Torigny, who had a special interest in her and recorded her life as
1 CONT best he could. She received her first name as a namesake of her mother, whose
1 CONT name "Eleanor" (or Alienor) had previously been unrecorded though may have
1 CONT been related to the Greek Helen or the Italian Elena. Another view holds that
1 CONT in the Occitan language, Eleanor simply meant "the other Aenor," since Eleanor
1 CONT of Aquitaine was named for her mother, called Aenor.
1 CONT
1 CONT Eleanor was a younger maternal half-sister of Marie de Champagne and Alix of
1 CONT France. She was a younger sister of William IX, Count of Poitiers, Henry the
1 CONT Young King, Matilda, Duchess of Saxony, Richard I of England and Geoffrey II,
1 CONT Duke of Brittany. She was also an older sister of Joan of Sicily and John of
1 CONT England.
1 CONT
1 CONT When she was eighteen years old, in September 1180, she was married to Alfonso
1 CONT VIII. The marriage was arranged to secure the Pyrennean border, with Gascony
1 CONT offered as her dowry.
1 CONT
1 CONT Of all Eleanor of Aquitaine's daughters, her namesake Eleanor (who was called
1 CONT Leonor by her Spanish subjects) best inherited her mother's political
1 CONT influence. She reigned alongside her husband, who specified in his will that
1 CONT she was to rule alongside their son in the event of his death. It was she who
1 CONT persuaded him to marry their daughter Berenguela to the king of Leon in the
1 CONT interest of peace.
1 CONT
1 CONT When Alfonso died, his queen was reportedly so devastated with grief that she
1 CONT was unable to preside over the burial. Their daughter Berenguela instead
1 CONT performed these honors. Leonora then took sick and died only twenty-eight days
1 CONT after her husband, and was buried at Las Huelgas abbey in Burgos.
1 CONT
1 CONT \------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT También conocida como Leonor Plantagenet de Inglaterra y Leonor de Castilla,
1 CONT fue Reina de Castilla (1170-1214). Casada con Alfonso VIII de Castilla con
1 CONT solamente nueve años de edad, su dote fue el condado de Gascuña (lo que
1 CONT aseguraría el borde de los Pirineos), aunque su marido nunca lo pudo anexionar
1 CONT al reino de Castilla. Tuvo gran influencia política y reinó interviniendo
1 CONT junto al rey castellano, el cual especificó en su testamento que sería ella
1 CONT quien gobernaría Castilla durante la minoría de edad del heredero.
1 CONT
