1 CONT (Research):Eleanor Of Aquitaine Encyclopædia Britannica Article born c. 1122
1 CONT died April 1, 1204, Fontevrault, Anjou, Fr. also called Eleanor Of Guyenne,
1 CONT French Éléonore, or Aliénor, D'aquitaine, or De Guyenne queen consort of both
1 CONT Louis VII of France (in 1137-52) and Henry II of England (in 1152-1204) and
1 CONT mother of Richard I the Lion-Heart and John of England. She was perhaps the
1 CONT most powerful woman in 12th-century Europe. Eleanor was the daughter and
1 CONT heiress of William X, duke of Aquitaine and count of Poitiers, who possessed
1 CONT one of the largest domains in France_larger, in fact, than those held by the
1 CONT French king. Upon William's death in 1137 she inherited the Duchy of Aquitaine
1 CONT and in July 1137 married the heir to the French throne, who succeeded his
1 CONT father, Louis VI, the following month. Eleanor became queen of France, a title
1 CONT she held for the next 15 years. Beautiful, capricious, and adored by Louis,
1 CONT Eleanor exerted considerable influence over him, often goading him into
1 CONT undertaking perilous ventures. From 1147 to 1149 Eleanor accompanied Louis on
1 CONT the Second Crusade to protect the fragile Latin kingdom of Jerusalem, founded
1 CONT after the First Crusade only 50 years before, from Turkish assault. Eleanor's
1 CONT conduct during this expedition, especially at the court of her uncle Raymond
1 CONT of Poitiers at Antioch, aroused Louis's jealousy and marked the beginning of
1 CONT their estrangement. After their return to France and a short-lived
1 CONT reconciliation, their marriage was annulled in March 1152. According to feudal
1 CONT customs, Eleanor then regained possession of Aquitaine, and two months later
1 CONT she married the grandson of Henry I of England, Henry Plantagenet, count of
1 CONT Anjou and duke of Normandy. In 1154 he became, as Henry II, king of England,
1 CONT with the result that England, Normandy, and the west of France were united
1 CONT under his rule. Eleanor had only two daughters by Louis VII; to her new
1 CONT husband she bore five sons and three daughters. The sons were William, who
1 CONT died at the age of three; Henry; Richard, the Lion-Heart; Geoffrey, duke of
1 CONT Brittany; and John, surnamed Lackland until, having outlived all his brothers,
1 CONT he inherited, in 1199, the crown of England. The daughters were Matilda, who
1 CONT married Henry the Lion, duke of Saxony and Bavaria; Eleanor, who married
1 CONT Alfonso VIII, king of Castile; and Joan, who married successively William II,
1 CONT king of Sicily, and Raymond VI, count of Toulouse. Eleanor would well have
1 CONT deserved to be named the "grandmother of Europe." During her childbearing
1 CONT years, she participated actively in the administration of the realm and even
1 CONT more actively in the management of her own domains. She was instrumental in
1 CONT turning the court of Poitiers, then frequented by the most famous troubadours
1 CONT of the time, into a centre of poetry and a model of courtly life and manners.
1 CONT She was the great patron of the two dominant poetic movements of the time: the
1 CONT courtly love tradition, conveyed in the romantic songs of the troubadours, and
1 CONT the historical matière de Bretagne, or "legends of Britanny," which originated
1 CONT in Celtic traditions and in the Historia regum Britanniae, written by the
1 CONT chronicler Geoffrey of Monmouth some time between 1135 and 1139. The revolt of
1 CONT her sons against her husband in 1173 put her cultural activities to a brutal
1 CONT end. Since Eleanor, 11 years her husband's senior, had long resented his
1 CONT infidelities, the revolt may have been instigated by her; in any case, she
1 CONT gave her sons considerable military support. The revolt failed, and Eleanor
1 CONT was captured while seeking refuge in the kingdom of her first husband, Louis
1 CONT VII. Her semi-imprisonment in England ended only with the death of Henry II in
1 CONT 1189. On her release, Eleanor played a greater political role than ever
1 CONT before. She actively prepared for Richard's coronation as king, was
1 CONT administrator of the realm during his crusade to the Holy Land, and, after his
1 CONT capture by the Duke of Austria on Richard's return from the east, collected
1 CONT his ransom and went in person to escort him to England. During Richard's
1 CONT absence, she succeeded in keeping his kingdom intact and in thwarting the
1 CONT intrigues of his brother John Lackland and Philip II Augustus, king of France,
1 CONT against him. In 1199 Richard died without leaving an heir to the throne, and
1 CONT John was crowned king. Eleanor, nearly 80 years old, fearing the
1 CONT disintegration of the Plantagenet domain, crossed the Pyrenees in 1200 in
1 CONT order to fetch her granddaughter Blanche from the court of Castile and marry
1 CONT her to the son of the French king. By this marriage she hoped to insure peace
1 CONT between the Plantagenets of England and the Capetian kings of France. In the
1 CONT same year she helped to defend Anjou and Aquitaine against her grandson Arthur
1 CONT of Brittany, thus securing John's French possessions. In 1202 John was again
1 CONT in her debt for holding Mirebeau against Arthur, until John, coming to her
1 CONT relief, was able to take him prisoner. John's only victories on the Continent,
1 CONT therefore, were due to Eleanor. She died in 1204 at the monastery at
1 CONT Fontevrault, Anjou, where she had retired after the campaign at Mirebeau. Her
1 CONT contribution to England extended beyond her own lifetime; after the loss of
1 CONT Normandy (1204), it was her own ancestral lands and not the old Norman
1 CONT territories that remained loyal to England. She has been misjudged by many
1 CONT French historians who have noted only her youthful frivolity, ignoring the
1 CONT tenacity, political wisdom, and energy that characterized the years of her
1 CONT maturity. "She was beautiful and just, imposing and modest, humble and
1 CONT elegant"; and, as the nuns of Fontevrault wrote in their necrology: a queen
1 CONT "who surpassed almost all the queens of the world."
1 CONT Source #1: Frederick Lewis Weis, "Ancestral Roots of Certain American
1 CONT Colonists Who Came to America Before 1700" - Seventh Edition, with additions
1 CONT and corrections by Walter Lee Sheppard, Jr., assisted by Davis Faris
1 CONT (Baltimore, MD: Genealogical Publishing Co, 1995), pp. 102; 104
1 CONT Name Prefix: Princess Name Suffix: Of England Daughter of King Henry II.
