1 CONT DATE 9 SEP 2000
1 CONT TIME 13:15:39
1 CONT BIOGRAPHY: Princess Eleanor of England was the sixth child of Henry II
1 CONT ofEngland and his wife Eleanor of Aquitaine.
1 CONT Queen Eleanor of Aquataine personally escorted her daughter to Bordeux, where
1 CONT the evnoys of Alphonso VIII received the young Princess and led her off to a
1 CONT splendid marriage in Burgos. Princess Eleanor, in addition to her bridal
1 CONT furniture, took with her to Spain the old Authurian tales that so enthralled
1 CONT her mother's court. Princess Eleanor also took with her to Castile the
1 CONT distinctive Angevin style of building. at her request, the royal abbey of Las
1 CONT Huelgas in Spain was founded in 1187.
1 CONT The nuns there were drawn from the highest of Spanish aristocracy. The second
1 CONT abbess of the abbey was Princess Constance, one of Eleanor and Alphonso's
1 CONT daughters. Las Huelgas was a royal mausoleum for Eleanor and Alphonso. The
1 CONT abbey reflects the influence of France, but one feature is purely Plantagenet
1 CONT --the domed vaulting with small additional compartments or ribs of the
1 CONT transept. A Spanish troupador gives us a brief impression of the young Queen
1 CONT of Castile, Eleanor of England;
1 CONT
1 CONT And when the King had summoned to his court,
1 CONT Many a knight, rich baron, and jongleur,
1 CONT And the company had assembled, Then come Queen Leanore
1 CONT
1 CONT Modestly clad in a mantle of rich stuff,
1 CONT Red, with a silver border wrought with golden lions.
1 CONT She bows to the King and near him takes her seat.
1 CONT
1 CONT In her middle years, Queen Eleanor off Castile had grown into a gracious,
1 CONT pious, learned, wise, still-beautiful woman. She was the patroness of
1 CONT prelates, grandees, and troupadors and head of one of the most civilized
1 CONT courts in Europe.
