1 CONT <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beatrice_of_Savoy,_Marchioness_of_Saluzzo>
1 CONT
1 CONT \----------
1 CONT
1 CONT \- <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#Beatrixdiedbefore1259>
1 CONT
1 CONT a) BEATRIX de Savoie (before 4 Mar 1223-10 May before 1259). The marriage
1 CONT contract between "Alaxiam comitissam Saluciarum et Manfredum marchionem
1 CONT Saluciarum eius nepotem" and "Thomam comitem Maurianæ…neptem suam…Beatrix" is
1 CONT dated 4 Mar 1223[313]. A contract dated 2 Oct 1227 between "Marchese Enrico di
1 CONT Savona" and "il Marchese Manfredo di Saluzzo" refers to the dowry of "Marchese
1 CONT di Savona…sua Consorte, figlia di Amedeo figlio del Conte di Savoia"[314].
1 CONT Beatrix must have born in the early 1220s as she had three children by her
1 CONT first husband who died in 1244. The Istoria of Saba Malaspina records that
1 CONT "Manfredus" married "natam Amadei comitis Sabaudiæ…Beatricem"[315]. The
1 CONT Historia Sicula of Bartolomeo di Neocastro records that "Manfredus" married
1 CONT "dominam Beatricem filiam ducis Sex Viarum, qui prius in virum…marchionem de
1 CONT Salluciis"[316]. Her second marriage was arranged in recognition of the
1 CONT alliance between her father and Emperor Friedrich II. A charter dated 8 May
1 CONT 1246 records the restitution of "castri Ripolarum" by Emperor Friedrich II to
1 CONT "fratribus de Sabaudia, Amedeo comite et Thoma", confirmed by the betrothal of
1 CONT "Manfredum dictum Lancea, filium naturalem imperatoris" and "Beatricem filiam
1 CONT Amedei comitis, relictam Manfredi marchionis Salucensis"[317]. The proxy of
1 CONT marriage between "Manfredo Lanza di Lui [Imperator Federico secundo] figlio"
1 CONT and "la Contessa di Saluzzo figlia del Conte Amedeo di Savoia" is dated Mar
1 CONT 1247[318]. The contract of marriage between "Manfredi Lanceæ filii Friderici
1 CONT Rom. Imperatoris" and "Beatrice marchionissa Salutiensi, filia Amedei comitis
1 CONT Sabaudiæ et in Italia marchionis, relicta Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum" is
1 CONT dated 21 Apr 1247[319]. A fourth testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is
1 CONT dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium meum" as his heir, under the
1 CONT tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia
1 CONT comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et
1 CONT Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii marchionis Montisferrati", and names
1 CONT "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea minor"[320]. A fifth testament of
1 CONT Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253, appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub
1 CONT tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir, substitutes "filiæ Amedei
1 CONT comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et Margaretha Montisferrati",
1 CONT bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ", and chooses to be
1 CONT buried at Hautecombe[321]. The absence of any reference to Beatrix´s current
1 CONT husband King Manfred suggests a breakdown in their marriage.
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** firstly (betrothed 4 Mar 1223 and 2 Oct 1227, **Mar 1233** ) MANFREDO
1 CONT III Marchese di Saluzzo, son of BONIFAZIO di Saluzzo & his wife Maria di
1 CONT Torres [in Sardinia] (-29 Oct 1244).
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** secondly (Betrothed 8 May 1246, by proxy Mar 1247, contract **21 Apr
1 CONT 1247** , [Dec 1248/Jan 1249]) as his first wife, MANFRED von Hohenstaufen,
1 CONT illegitimate son of Emperor FRIEDRICH II King of Sicily & his mistress Bianca
1 CONT Lancia (Venosa 1232-killed in battle Benevento 26 Feb 1266). At the time of
1 CONT his marriage, his father constituted him Lord of territory from Pavia to
1 CONT Genoa. He succeeded as Principe di Tarento in 1250 on the death of his father.
1 CONT Regent of Sicily in 1254, he was crowned MANFREDO King of Sicily at Palermo 10
1 CONT Aug 1258.
1 CONT
1 CONT \---------
1 CONT \-----------
1 CONT \-----------
1 CONT \------------
1 CONT \-------------
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#_ftnref302>
1 CONT
1 CONT BEATRIX de Savoie (before 4 Mar 1223-10 May before 1259).
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * The marriage contract between "Alaxiam comitissam Saluciarum et Manfredum marchionem Saluciarum eius nepotem" and "Thomam comitem Maurianæ…neptem suam…Beatrix" is dated 4 Mar 1223[313].
1 CONT
1 CONT   * A contract dated 2 Oct 1227 between "Marchese Enrico di Savona" and "il Marchese Manfredo di Saluzzo" refers to the dowry of "Marchese di Savona…sua Consorte, figlia di Amedeo figlio del Conte di Savoia"[314].
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Beatrix must have born in the early 1220s as she had three children by her first husband who died in 1244.
1 CONT
1 CONT   * The Istoria of Saba Malaspina records that "Manfredus" married "natam Amadei comitis Sabaudiæ…Beatricem"[315]. The Historia Sicula of Bartolomeo di Neocastro records that "Manfredus" married "dominam Beatricem filiam ducis Sex Viarum, qui prius
1 CONC  in virum…marchionem de Salluciis"[316].
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Her second marriage was arranged in recognition of the alliance between her father and Emperor Friedrich II. A charter dated 8 May 1246 records the restitution of "castri Ripolarum" by Emperor Friedrich II to "fratribus de Sabaudia, Amedeo comi
1 CONC te et Thoma", confirmed by the betrothal of "Manfredum dictum Lancea, filium naturalem imperatoris" and "Beatricem filiam Amedei comitis, relictam Manfredi marchionis Salucensis"[317]. The proxy of marriage between "Manfredo Lanza di Lui [Imperator
1 CONC  Federico secundo] figlio" and "la Contessa di Saluzzo figlia del Conte Amedeo di Savoia" is dated Mar 1247[318]. The contract of marriage between "Manfredi Lanceæ filii Friderici Rom. Imperatoris" and "Beatrice marchionissa Salutiensi, filia Amede
1 CONC i comitis Sabaudiæ et in Italia marchionis, relicta Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum" is dated 21 Apr 1247[319].
1 CONT
1 CONT   * A fourth testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quonda
1 CONC m Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea minor"[320].
1 CONT
1 CONT   * A fifth testament of Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253, appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir, substitutes "filiæ Amedei comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et Margaretha Montisferrati", bequeathes "cast
1 CONC rum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ", and chooses to be buried at Hautecombe[321].
1 CONT
1 CONT   * The absence of any reference to Beatrix´s current husband King Manfred suggests a breakdown in their marriage.
1 CONT
1 CONT m firstly (betrothed 4 Mar 1223 and 2 Oct 1227, Mar 1233) MANFREDO III
1 CONT Marchese di Saluzzo, son of BONIFAZIO di Saluzzo & his wife Maria di Torres
1 CONT [in Sardinia] (-29 Oct 1244).
1 CONT
1 CONT Marchese Manfredo III & his wife had [four] children:
1 CONT
1 CONT a) ALASIA ([1236]-before 12 Jul 1311, bur Pontefract, Church of the Black
1 CONT Friars). "Mainfredus III marchio Salutiarum" appointed "Beatricem de Sabaudia
1 CONT suam uxorem" as co-tutor of "Thomæ et Alasinæ filiorum suorum" in his
1 CONT testament dated 1244[540]. Henry III King of England agreed that “unam
1 CONT filiarum filiæ...comitis [Sabaudiæ]” would marry “vel Johanni de Warenna qui
1 CONT si vixerit comes erit Warennæ, vel Edmundo de Lacy qui si vixerit comes erit
1 CONT Lincolniæ” by charter dated 1246[541]. A manuscript history of the Lacy family
1 CONT records that “Edmundum de Lacy comitem” married “dominam Aleciam filiam
1 CONT marchionis de Salves in Italia, cognatam reginæ Anglia ex parte Sabinensi”
1 CONT when she was “in juventute sua”[542]. “Edmundus de Lascy constabularius
1 CONT Cestriæ” donated property to Roche Abbey, for the souls of “…Alesiæ uxoris
1 CONT meæ”, by undated charter[543]. As Alasia gave birth to her first child in
1 CONT 1250, it is unlikely that she could have been born later than 1236, although
1 CONT at that date her own mother was probably only thirteen years old. Given this
1 CONT tight chronology, it is assumed that Alasia was her parents' first child. m
1 CONT (Woodstock early May 1247) EDMUND de Lacy Earl of Lincoln, son of JOHN de Lacy
1 CONT Earl of Lincoln & his second wife Margaret de Quincy (1230-2 Jun 1258, bur
1 CONT Stanlaw Abbey).
1 CONT
1 CONT b) TOMASO (-3 Dec 1296, bur Staffarda Santa Maria). "Mainfredus III marchio
1 CONT Salutiarum" appointed "Beatricem de Sabaudia suam uxorem" as co-tutor of
1 CONT "Thomæ et Alasinæ filiorum suorum" in his testament dated 1244[544]. He
1 CONT succeeded his father in 1244 as TOMASO I Marchese di Saluzzo.
1 CONT
1 CONT \- see below.
1 CONT
1 CONT c) [MARGHERITA (1245-). As she and her sister Agnese are not mentioned in
1 CONT their father´s testament dated 1244, it is assumed that they were born
1 CONT posthumously and that they were twins. However, Margherita is not mentioned in
1 CONT the charter dated 24 Aug 1251 which names Marchese Manfredo III´s three other
1 CONT children and their tutor Bonifazio Marchese di Monferrato. This raises doubts
1 CONT about the existence of Margherita. Nun.]
1 CONT
1 CONT d) AGNESE (1245-after 4 Aug 1265, bur Pontefract, Church of the Black Friars).
1 CONT Her parentage is confirmed by the charter dated 24 Aug 1251 under which
1 CONT Bonifazio Marchese di Montferrato "tutor Thome filii condam Manfredi
1 CONT marchionis Salutiarum et filiarum suarum Alaxine et Agnesine" donated property
1 CONT to Staffarda monastery in accordance with the last wishes of Manfredo III
1 CONT Marchese di Saluzzo[545]. As she and her supposed sister Margherita are not
1 CONT mentioned in their father´s testament dated 1244, it is assumed that they were
1 CONT born posthumously and that they were twins (assuming that Margherita in fact
1 CONT existed, about which there are doubts as discussed above). It is assumed that
1 CONT her marriage was arranged by Pierre Comte de Savoie who had been her husband's
1 CONT guardian from 12 Feb 1254, after the death of his father[546]. m ([before
1 CONT 1262][547]) as his first wife, JOHN de Vescy, son of WILLIAM de Vescy & his
1 CONT second wife Agnes de Ferrers of Derby (18 Jul 1244-Montpellier 10 Feb 1289,
1 CONT bur Alnwick Abbey). No children.
1 CONT
1 CONT m secondly (Betrothed 8 May 1246, by proxy Mar 1247, contract 21 Apr 1247,
1 CONT [Dec 1248/Jan 1249]) as his first wife, MANFRED von Hohenstaufen, illegitimate
1 CONT son of Emperor FRIEDRICH II King of Sicily & his mistress Bianca Lancia
1 CONT (Venosa 1232-killed in battle Benevento 26 Feb 1266). At the time of his
1 CONT marriage, his father constituted him Lord of territory from Pavia to Genoa. He
1 CONT succeeded as Principe di Tarento in 1250 on the death of his father. Regent of
1 CONT Sicily in 1254, he was crowned MANFREDO King of Sicily at Palermo 10 Aug 1258.
1 CONT
1 CONT King Manfred & his first wife had one child:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. CONSTANZA of Sicily (1249-Barcelona 1302). The Historia Sicula of
1 CONT Bartolomeo di Neocastro names "Constancia" as the daughter of "Manfredus" and
1 CONT his wife "dominam Beatricem", adding that she married "Petro regi
1 CONT Aragonum"[677]. The Chronicle of Ramon Muntaner records the marriage of "le
1 CONT seigneur infant Pierre" and "la fille de Mainfroi roi de Sicile…Constance",
1 CONT adding that the bride was aged 14[678]. "Infans Petrus filius…Jacobi…Regis
1 CONT Aragonum, Majoricarum et Valentiæ, Comitis Barchinonæ et Urgelli, et domini
1 CONT Montispessulani" granted dowry to "dominæ Constantiæ filiæ…Manfredi Regis
1 CONT Siciliæ…uxori nostræ" by charter dated 13 Jun 1262, which names "domino
1 CONT Bonifacio de Anglano…Comite Montisalbani…avunculo dicti domini Regis Siciliæ",
1 CONT countersigned 13 Nov 1264[679]. m (Montpellier 15 Jul 1262) Infante don PEDRO
1 CONT de Aragón, son of don JAIME I "el Conquistador" King of Aragon & his second
1 CONT wife Iolanda of Hungary (1239-Villafranca del Penedés 2 or 11 Nov 1285). He
1 CONT succeeded his father in 1276 as don PEDRO III "el Grande" King of Aragon,
1 CONT Conde de Barcelona and King of Valencia, crowned at Zaragoza Nov 1276. He
1 CONT landed at Trapani in Sicily Sep 1280, after the Sicilian revolt against the
1 CONT Angevins, and declared himself PIETRO King of Sicily. - see below, Chapter 3.
1 CONT KINGS of SICILY, HOUSE of BARCELONA.
1 CONT
1 CONT [<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beatrice_of_Savoy,_Marchioness_of_Saluzzo>
1 CONT Wikipedia]
1 CONT
1 CONT **Beatrice of Savoy, Marchioness of Saluzzo**
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy, Marchioness of Saluzzo
1 CONT
1 CONT Born before 4 March 1223
1 CONT
1 CONT Died 10 May before 1259
1 CONT
1 CONT Noble family House of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT Spouse(s)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Manfred III, Marquess of Saluzzo
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Manfred, King of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Thomas I, Marquess of Saluzzo
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Constance, Queen of Aragon
1 CONT
1 CONT Father Amadeus IV of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT Mother Marguerite of Burgundy
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice of Savoy (before 4 March 1223 – 10 May before 1259) was a daughter of
1 CONT Amadeus IV, Count of Savoy and his first wife Marguerite of Burgundy.[1] She
1 CONT was a member of the House of Savoy by birth and by her first marriage she was
1 CONT Marchioness consort of Saluzzo.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was the elder of two daughters; her younger sister Margaret was
1 CONT married to Boniface II, Marquess of Montferrat. After the death of their
1 CONT mother, their father married Cecile of Baux and had further children including
1 CONT Boniface, Count of Savoy and a younger Beatrice.
1 CONT
1 CONT Beatrice was first betrothed not long after her birth on 4 March 1223 to
1 CONT Manfred III, Marquess of Saluzzo. However, the contract was broken off but was
1 CONT then renewed on 2 October 1227; a contract signed on that date refers to the
1 CONT dowry of Beatrice.[2] The couple were married in March 1233. They were married
1 CONT for eleven years until Manfred's death in 1244, leaving Beatrice with two
1 CONT children and pregnant with twins. They had the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Alice (c. 1236 – before 12 Jul 1311), married Edmund de Lacy, Baron of Pontefract and had issue
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Thomas (1239–1296), succeeded Manfred as Marquess
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Agnes (1245 – after 4 August 1265), born posthumously, married John, son of Eustace de Vesci, no issue
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Margaret (born 1245), born posthumously, twin of Agnes
1 CONT
1 CONT Only two years after Manfred's death on 8 May 1246, Beatrice was betrothed a
1 CONT second time to Manfred, an illegitimate son of Frederick II, Holy Roman
1 CONT Emperor by his mistress and possibly wife Bianca Lancia. Her marriage was
1 CONT arranged to recognize an alliance between Beatrice's father and Frederick.[3]
1 CONT The couple were married by proxy in March 1247 and the marriage contract was
1 CONT signed on 21 April 1247. Manfred and Beatrice had one daughter, Constance
1 CONT (1249-1302) who went on to marry Peter III of Aragon and became mother Alfonso
1 CONT III of Aragon, James II of Aragon and Elizabeth of Aragon.
1 CONT
1 CONT In a testament from Beatrice's father dated 24 May 1253, the succession rights
1 CONT of Beatrice were bypassed in favor of her younger half-brother; the testament
1 CONT fails to mention Beatrice's second husband, possibly indicating a breakdown in
1 CONT the marriage.[4] Beatrice died before 1259. Her husband became King of Sicily
1 CONT in 1258 and went on to marry Helena Angelina Doukaina and father children with
1 CONT her.
1 CONT
1 CONT References
1 CONT # Cox, Eugene L. (1974). The Eagles of Savoy. Princeton University Press,
1 CONT Princeton. ISBN 0691052166.
1 CONT # State Archives, volume 25, page 13, fascicule 4.
1 CONT # Wurstenberger (1858), Vol. IV, 194, p. 106.
1 CONT # SAVOY, Medieval Lands
1 CONT
