0 @N00699@ NOTE (Bela IV Péter King of Hungary)
0 @N00700@ NOTE geni:about_me <http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/HUNGARY.htm#_Toc146273223>
1 CONT
1 CONT BÉLA IV 1235-1270, BÉLA V 1304-1308
1 CONT
1 CONT BÉLA, son of ANDRÁS II King of Hungary & his first wife Gertrud von Andechs-
1 CONT Merano (Nov 1206-Margaret Island, near Buda 2/3 May 1270, bur Esztergom). The
1 CONT Chronicon Dubnicense names "Belam, Colomannum Andream et beatam Elyzabeth" as
1 CONT the children of "Andreas filius Bele" and his wife "domina Gerdrudis de
1 CONT Alemania"[896]. The Gesta Hungarorum names "Bela filius eius" when recording
1 CONT that he succeeded his father[897]. Béla was governor of Hungary's eastern
1 CONT provinces as rex iunior, and represented his father at the mass baptism of the
1 CONT Kuman people which took place in 1227 in Moldavia on the orders of Bortz
1 CONT Khan[898]. He succeeded his father in 1235 as BÉLA IV King of Hungary. He did
1 CONT not go to Croatia for a second coronation, breaking the custom which had
1 CONT lasted 130 years[899]. In response to the Pope's call in 1234 for a crusade
1 CONT against 'heretics' in Bosnia, Hungary occupied large parts of Bosnia between
1 CONT 1235 and 1241, but was obliged to withdraw in the face of the threat from the
1 CONT Mongols. Kuthen [Kötöny] Khan of the Kumans and his followers sought refuge in
1 CONT Hungary after the battle of the Volga in 1239, which gave the Mongols the
1 CONT pretext to attack Hungary. The presence caused internal resentment in Hungary
1 CONT which culminated in the Khan's murder[900]. Batu Khan's forces passed the
1 CONT Carpathian mountains into Hungary in Feb 1241 and defeated Béla IV at Mohi on
1 CONT the river Sajó 11 Apr 1241[901]. King Béla fled to the castle of Knin in
1 CONT Dalmatia after this defeat, then to Trorig and finally to the island of
1 CONT Ciovo[902], but the Mongols withdrew in 1242 after learning of the death of
1 CONT Great Khan Ogedei 11 Dec 1241 at Karakoram[903]. Relations with Bulgaria
1 CONT improved in 1240, possibly because of the threat posed to both states by the
1 CONT Mongols[904]. Hungary was also attacked on its western borders by Friedrich
1 CONT Duke of Austria, although for a short time King Béla captured Styria in
1 CONT reprisal[905]. In order to protect his eastern frontier, King Béla contracted
1 CONT with the Knights of the Order of St John of Jerusalem [Knights Hospitalers] 2
1 CONT Jun 1247, granting them the Szörénység as far as south-eastern Transylvania in
1 CONT return for the promise of military support. They remained there until they
1 CONT relinquished the land in [1258/60][906]. King Béla allowed the Kumans to
1 CONT return to Hungary, settling them on uninhabited land on either side of the
1 CONT River Tisza, the agreement being sealed by the marriage of his son and heir to
1 CONT a Kuman princess in 1253[907]. He was embroiled in a war with Bohemia, and
1 CONT suffered a defeat in 1260 despite reinforcements from Bulgaria supplied by his
1 CONT son-in-law Rostislav Mikhailovich Ban of Mačva, who was one of the claimants
1 CONT to the Bulgarian throne after Tsar Koloman II was deposed in 1258[908]. Having
1 CONT made peace with Bohemia in Mar 1261, Hungary attacked Bulgaria, expelling
1 CONT Konstantin Tih (one of the rival claimants for the Bulgarian throne) from
1 CONT Vidin which he had captured from Rostislav's forces during the latter's
1 CONT temporary absence in Bohemia[909]. Stefan Uroš I King of Serbia declared war
1 CONT on Hungary in 1268, plundered Mačva but was himself captured and held for
1 CONT ransom, the marriage between his son and Béla IV's granddaughter probably
1 CONT being agreed as part of the terms for the Serbian king's release[910]. The
1 CONT Annales Cracovienses Compilati record the death in 1271 of "Bela rex Hungarie
1 CONT pater ducisse Cracoviensis"[911]. The necrology of Oberaltaich records the
1 CONT death "VI Non Mai" of "Bela rex Ungarie"[912]. The Chronicon Dubnicense
1 CONT records the death "V Non May…in insula Budensi" in 1270 of "rex Bela" and his
1 CONT burial "Strigony in ecclesia fratrum minorum"[913]. The Gesta Hungarorum
1 CONT records that King Béla was buried "apud Fratres Minores Strigonii"[914].
1 CONT
1 CONT m (1218) MARIA Laskarina, daughter of THEODOROS Laskaris Emperor in Nikaia &
1 CONT his first wife Anna Angelina (-16 or 24 Jul 1270, bur Esztergom). Georgius
1 CONT Akropolites names "Irene, Maria et Eudocia" as the three daughters of
1 CONT "Theodorum Lascarim imperatorem…ex Anna uxore", stating that "Mariam secundam"
1 CONT married "Ungariæ regis…filio", his father arranging the marriage on his
1 CONT journey back from Jerusalem[915]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines
1 CONT records that "rex Bela, regis Andree filius primogenitus" married one of the
1 CONT daughters (mentioned third) of "Lascarum Grecum"[916]. Ephræmius records that
1 CONT "Anna regina coniuge Lascario" had three daughters "Irene et Maria et
1 CONT Eudocia", recording that "Mariam…natu secundo" married "regis Paeoniæ
1 CONT filio"[917]. The Historia Salonitanorum of Thomas Archdeacon of Split records
1 CONT that András II King of Hungary arranged the marriage of "suo filio primogenito
1 CONT Bele" and "Lascaro rege Grecorum…filiam eius" while he was in Greece[918]. The
1 CONT Annales Polonorum record the death in 1270 of "regina Ungarorum Maria, mater
1 CONT domine Kinge"[919]. The necrology of Oberaltaich records the death "IX Kal
1 CONT Aug" of "Maria regina Ungarie"[920]. The necrology of Seligenthal records the
1 CONT death "XVII Kal Aug" of "Maria regina Ungarie"[921]. The Chronicon Dubnicense
1 CONT records that "consorte sua Maria…filia imperatoris Grecorum" was buried with
1 CONT her husband "rex Bela" in "Strigony in ecclesia fratrum minorum"[922]. The
1 CONT Altahenses Annales record that "Maria regina Ungarie" died after her husband
1 CONT "non post longum tempus"[923].
1 CONT
1 CONT King Béla IV & his wife had ten children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. KATHARINA (-Klis Castle 1242, bur Split St Domnius). She died during her
1 CONT family's escape to Dalmatia after the Tatar invasion[924]. The Historia
1 CONT Salonitanorum of Thomas Archdeacon of Split records the death of "Bela rex…due
1 CONT ipsius puelle virgines", while their parents were staying "in Clisse castro",
1 CONT and their burial "in ecclesia beati Domnii"[925].
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. MARGIT "the Elder" (-Klis Castle 20 Apr 1242, bur Split St Dominius). [Her
1 CONT marriage is shown in Europäische Stammtafeln[926]. It is not clear who
1 CONT "Guillaume de Saint Omer Lord of Thebes" refers to. The Lord of Thebes at that
1 CONT time was Bela (son of Margit of Hungary, daughter of Béla III King of Hungary,
1 CONT by her third husband Nicolas de Saint-Omer), who had married Bonne de la
1 CONT Roche-sur-l'Ognon co-heiress of Thebes. Lord Bela had a younger brother
1 CONT Guillaume who was not Lord of Thebes, but who lived first in Naples and later
1 CONT in Flanders[927]. The Historia Salonitanorum of Thomas Archdeacon of Split
1 CONT records the death of "Bela rex…due ipsius puelle virgines", while their
1 CONT parents were staying "in Clisse castro", and their burial "in ecclesia beati
1 CONT Domnii"[928]. m ([1240]) GUILLAUME de Saint Omer Lord of Thebes.]
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. KINGA [Kunigunde] (1224-24 Jul 1292). The Annales Cracovienses Compilati
1 CONT records the birth in 1234 of "Kinga filia Bolezlay"[929], the Annales
1 CONT Polonorum clarifying that she was "Kinga fila regis Ungarie Bele et de matre
1 CONT Maria" born "in dominica quinquagesima"[930]. The Annales Capituli
1 CONT Cracoviensis record the marriage in 1239 of "Blezlaus filius Lezstkonis" and
1 CONT "filiam regis Hungarie"[931]. Her name is confirmed by the Annales
1 CONT Cracovienses Compilati which record that "dux Boleslaus accepit Kingam" in
1 CONT 1238[932]. "Bolezlaus filius Lesconis…Dux Cracoviæ et Sandomiriæ" founded the
1 CONT monastery of Krzyzanowice, at the request of "matris nostræ Grzymislavæ", for
1 CONT the souls of "patris nostri Lesconis et uxoris nostræ Gunebundis", by charter
1 CONT dated 28 Jun 1254[933]. "Bolezlaus…Cracouie et Sandomirie dux" conferred
1 CONT privileges on the church of Krakow, for the soul of "patris nostri clare
1 CONT memorie Cracouie et Sandomirie ducis Leztconis" and for "nostre genitricis
1 CONT ducisse Grimizlaue et…consortis nostre Cungundis", by charter dated 18 May
1 CONT 1255[934]. The Annales Cracovienses Compilati record the deaths in 1279 of
1 CONT "Boleslaus dux maioris Polonie, Boleslaus dux Cracowie"[935]. She became a nun
1 CONT in 1270. The Annales Polonorum record the death in 1292 of "domina Kinga
1 CONT ducissa" at Krakow[936]. She was beatified 10 Jun 1690. m (1239) BOLESŁAV of
1 CONT Poland, son of LESZKO I "Bialy/the White" Prince of Sandomir and Krakow & his
1 CONT wife Gremislava Ingvarevna of Luck and Dorogobuz [Rurikid] (21 Jun 1226-7 Dec
1 CONT 1279). He succeeded in 1243 as BOLESŁAW V "Wstydliwy/the Modest" Prince of
1 CONT Krakow and Sandomir.
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. ANNA [Agnes] ([1226/27]-). Her parentage and marriage are indicated by
1 CONT Georgius Akropolites who names "Rosum Urum…Ungariæ regis generum" as father-
1 CONT in-law of "Bulgarorum…princeps"[937]. The name of the wife of Rostislav is
1 CONT confirmed by the Annales Polonorum recording the marriage in 1265 of their
1 CONT daughter Gryfina, in a later passage specifying that she was daughter of
1 CONT "ducis Roczislay et…Anna"[938]. A charter dated 15 Jul 1264 records the
1 CONT confirmation by "ipsius patris regis Belæ IV" of a donation by "Agnes, viduæ
1 CONT post Radislaum ducem Galitiæ, ducissæ Galitiæ, de Bosna et de Mazo, ac
1 CONT Michaeli et Belæ natis eius"[939]. Baumgarten names the wife of Prince
1 CONT Rostislav and gives her origin but only cites one secondary source in
1 CONT support[940]. m (1243) ROSTISLAV Mikhailovich ex-Prince of Galich, son of
1 CONT MIKHAIL Vsevolodich Grand Prince of Kiev & his wife Maria Romanovna of Galich
1 CONT ([1225]-1263). After the Mongol invasion, he sought refuge with Béla IV King
1 CONT of Hungary, married the king's daughter, and was appointed Ban of Mačva. He
1 CONT assumed the title ROSTISLAV Tsar of the Bulgarians, and was recognised as such
1 CONT by Hungary[941].
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. ELISABETH (1236-24 Oct 1271, bur Kloster Seligenthal). The Altahenses
1 CONT Annales record the marriage of "Heinricus filius O. ducis Bavarie" and
1 CONT "Elisabeth filia Bele regis Ungarie"[942]. The Altahenses Annales record the
1 CONT death "1271 IX Kal Nov" of "Elizabeth ducissa Bawarie"[943]. The necrology of
1 CONT Tegernsee records the death "IX Kal Nov" of "Elysabeth ducissa Bawarie filia
1 CONT regis Ungarie"[944]. The necrology of Windberg records the death "IX Kal Nov
1 CONT 1271" of "Elysabet ducissa Bawarie"[945]. The necrology of Seligenthal records
1 CONT the death "IX Kal Nov 1271" of "domina Elizabet filia regis Ungarie ducissa
1 CONT Bawarie"[946]. m (1250) HEINRICH von Bayern, son of OTTO II "der Erlauchte"
1 CONT Duke of Bavaria & his wife Agnes von Sachsen [Este] (Landshut 19 Nov
1 CONT 1235-Burghausen 3 Feb 1290, bur Kloster Seligenth al). He succeeded his father
1 CONT in 1253 as HEINRICH I Joint-Duke of Bavaria, jointly with his brother Ludwig
1 CONT II. He and his older brother divided the family's territories in 1255,
1 CONT whereupon Heinrich became Duke of Lower Bavaria (Niederbayern).
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. KONSTANZA. Baumgarten names the wife of Prince Lev and gives her origin
1 CONT citing sources in support[947]. m ([1251/52]) LEV Daniilovich of Galich, son
1 CONT of DANIIL Romanovich Grand Prince of Kiev, King of Galich & his first wife
1 CONT Anna Mstislavna of Novgorod ([1228]-1301). He succeed his uncle in 1269 as LEV
1 CONT King of Galich.
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. ISTVÁN (Dec 1239-1 Aug 1272). The Chronicon Varadiense names "dux
1 CONT Stephanus postea rex, secundus…dux Bela" as the two sons of "rex Bela
1 CONT quartus"[948]. He succeeded his father in 1270 as ISTVÁN V King of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT \- see below.
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. MARGIT "the Younger" (1242-18 Jan 1271). Abbess on the Island of Hares
1 CONT near Ofen, afterwards called Margaret Island, she refused an offer of marriage
1 CONT from Otakar II King of Bohemia[949].
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. IOLANDA [Helena] ([1238/44]-16/17 Jun after 1303). The Annales
1 CONT Cracovienses Compilati record the marriage in 1259 of "dux Boleslaus
1 CONT Polanorum" and "Iohelam filiam regis Hungarie"[950]. She was beatified 26 Sep
1 CONT 1827. m (1250) BOLESŁAW of Poland, son of WŁADYSŁAW Prince of Greater Poland &
1 CONT his wife Hedwig [von Pommerellen] (after 1221-13 Apr 1279). He succeeded in
1 CONT 1247 as BOLESŁAW "Poboźny/the Pious" Prince of Kalisch, until 1249 and 1253.
1 CONT He was Prince of Gnesen from 1249/50, and Prince of Greater Poland 1257.
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. BÉLA ([1245]-1269, bur Gran [Esztergom]). The Chronicon Varadiense names
1 CONT "dux Stephanus postea rex, secundus…dux Bela" as the two sons of "rex Bela
1 CONT quartus"[951]. The Historia Salonitanorum of Thomas Archdeacon of Split
1 CONT records that "domina Maria regina, Grecorum imperatorum stirpe progenita…filio
1 CONT suo Bele…secundus…regis filius" was appointed duke of Croatia while still a
1 CONT minor[952]. He was installed by his father as Duke of Slavonia, Dalmatia &
1 CONT Croatia in 1262, territories previously held by his older brother István, who
1 CONT immediately rebelled against their father[953]. The Annales Cracovienses
1 CONT Compilati record the death in 1270 of "Boleslaus filius Bele regis
1 CONT Hungarie"[954]. The Chronicon Dubnicense records that "duce Bela filio suo"
1 CONT was buried with his father "rex Bela" in "Strigony in ecclesia fratrum
1 CONT minorum"[955]. m (24/25 Oct 1264) as her first husband, KUNIGUNDE von
1 CONT Brandenburg, daughter of OTTO III Markgraf von Brandenburg [Askanier] & his
1 CONT wife Beatrix [Božena] of Bohemia ([1247/52]-after 8 Jun 1292). The Canonicorum
1 CONT Pragensium Continuationes Cosmæ records the marriage "IV Kal Oct 1264" of
1 CONT "filiam Ottoni marchioni" and "filio regis nominee Belæ"[956]. The Historia
1 CONT Annorum 1264-1279 records the marriage in 1264 of "Bela frater Stephani regis
1 CONT Ungarie" and "filiam marchionis Brannburgensis", but does not name her[957].
1 CONT The Altahenses Annales record the marriage "1262 in autumpno" of "filiam
1 CONT Ottonis marchionis de Brandenburch" and "Bele iuniore regi Ungarie"[958]. The
1 CONT Historia Annorum 1264-1279 records the marriage in 1264 of "Bela frater
1 CONT Stephani regis Ungarie" and "filiam marchionis Brannburgensis", but does not
1 CONT name her[959]. She is named in the Cronica Principum Saxonie which shows (in
1 CONT order) "Iohannem de Praga, Ottonem Magnum, Albertum, Ottonem, Conegundim,
1 CONT Mechtildim" as children of "Otto III" & his wife, specifying that Kunigund
1 CONT married "Bele filie Bele regis Ungarie, fratris beate Elisabet" in 1264, and
1 CONT also records her second marriage to "duci de Limburch"[960]. She married
1 CONT secondly ([10 Jan 1278]) as his second wife, Walram IV Duke of Limburg.
1 CONT
