1 CONT Béla IV of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT (Redirected from Bela IV of Hungary)
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV c.1270
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV (Hungarian: IV. Béla, Croatian: Bela III, Slovak: Belo IV), (1206 – 3
1 CONT May 1270), King of Hungary and Croatia (1214-1270), Duke of Styria
1 CONT (1254-1258). Béla was present, at the age of seven, when a group of
1 CONT conspirators killed his mother, and he could never forgive his father's
1 CONT generosity towards the conspirators' accomplices. Shortly afterwards, he was
1 CONT crowned junior king (rex iunior) and he governed several provinces of the
1 CONT Kingdom of Hungary during his father's reign. He endeavoured to restore the
1 CONT royal power that had declined since the death of his grandfather, King Béla,
1 CONT which resulted in permanent conflicts between Béla and his father. When he
1 CONT ascended the throne, he determined to revive his grandfather's internal policy
1 CONT which made him unpopular among his barons. However, he soon had to face the
1 CONT threat of the Mongol invasion of Europe; therefore he granted asylum to the
1 CONT Cumans in order to strengthen his military force. Nevertheless, the Mongol
1 CONT armies defeated his troops in the decisive battle and he had to escape to the
1 CONT farthest fortress of his kingdom while the Mongols were pillaging the country.
1 CONT When the Mongol troops were withdrawn unexpectedly, Béla returned and
1 CONT commenced to reconstruct his devasteted kingdom; he patronized the towns,
1 CONT persuaded the construction of fortresses and encouraged the immigration. His
1 CONT success is reflected by his popular epithet, "the Second Founder of our
1 CONT Country", in Hungary. During the second period of his reign, he could even
1 CONT expand his rule over the neighbouring countries. However, his last years were
1 CONT characterized by his permanent conflicts with his eldest son, Stephen.
1 CONT
