1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Early life
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla was the eldest son of King Andrew II of Hungary and his first wife,
1 CONT Gertrude of Merania. Upon Pope Innocent III request, the ecclesiastic and
1 CONT temporal dignitaries of the Kingdom of Hungary took an oath before his birth
1 CONT that they would accept him as his father's successor.
1 CONT
1 CONT The infant Béla was probably present when a group of conspirators murdered his
1 CONT mother on 28 September 1213. Following the murder, his father ordered only the
1 CONT execution of the conspirators' leader and forgave the other members of the
1 CONT group, which resulted in Béla's emerging antipathy against his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the beginning of 1214, Béla was engaged to a daughter of Tzar Boril of
1 CONT Bulgaria. Shortly afterwards, he was crowned junior king. When his father left
1 CONT for a Crusade in August 1217, his maternal uncle, Archbishop Berthold of
1 CONT Kalocsa took Béla to the fortress of Steyr in Styria and he returned to
1 CONT Hungary one year later, following his father's return from the Holy Land.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Rex iunior
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1220, Béla married Maria Laskarina, a daughter of the Emperor Theodore I
1 CONT Laskaris of Nicaea and his father entrusted him with the government of
1 CONT Slavonia. However, King Andrew II, who had arranged Béla's marriage during his
1 CONT return from the Crusade, persuaded Béla to separate from his wife in 1222.
1 CONT Pope Honorius III, however, denied to declare their marriage null and void;
1 CONT therefore Béla took back his wife and escaped to Austria fearing of his
1 CONT father's anger. Finally, King Andrew II made an agreement with his son with
1 CONT the mediation of the Pope and Béla took over again the government of Slavonia,
1 CONT Dalmatia and Croatia.
1 CONT
1 CONT As governor, Béla commenced, with the authorization of the Pope, to take back
1 CONT the royal domains that King Andrew II had granted to his partisans during the
1 CONT first half of his reign. He laid siege to Klis, the fortress of a turbulent
1 CONT Croatian baron who had to surrender.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1226, his father entrusted him with the government of Transylvania where he
1 CONT assisted the missionary work of the Blackfriars among the Cuman tribes who
1 CONT settled down in the territories west of the Dniester River. As a result of
1 CONT their missionary work, two chieftains of the Cumans, Bartz and Membrok were
1 CONT baptized and they acknowledged Béla's overlordship around 1228. In the
1 CONT meantime, Béla began to organise the Banat of Szörény, a march of the kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1228, he commenced to revise his father's "needless and fruitless"
1 CONT donations in the whole territory of the kingdom with the authorisation of his
1 CONT father. However, his military failure in Halych, when assisting his younger
1 CONT brother, Andrew, weakened his influence and King Andrew II put an end to the
1 CONT revision of his former donations. During the early 1230s, Béla took part in
1 CONT the military expeditions of his father against Halych and Austria.
1 CONT
1 CONT His relation with his father even worsened, when King Andrew II married, on 14
1 CONT May 1234, Beatrice D'Este, who was thirty years his younger.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]The first years of his reign
1 CONT
1 CONT When his father died on 21 September 1235, Béla ascended the throne without
1 CONT any opposition and Archbishop Robert of Esztergom crowned him on 14 October in
1 CONT Székesfehérvár. Shortly afterwards, he accused his young stepmother and his
1 CONT father's main advisor, Denis, Apud's son of adultery and ordered their arrest.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla's main purpose was to restore the royal power that had weakened during
1 CONT his father's rule; e.g., he ordered the burning of his advisors' seats,
1 CONT because he wanted to force them to stand in the presence of the king. As he
1 CONT also wanted to strengthen the position of the towns, he confirmed the charter
1 CONT of Székesfehérvár and granted new privileges to several key towns in the
1 CONT kingdom (Pest, Nagyszombat, Selmecbánya, Korpona, Zólyom, Bars, and
1 CONT Esztergom).[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT He sent Friar Julian to find the Magyar tribes who had remained in their
1 CONT eastern homeland. Friar Julian, after meeting with the eastern Magyars
1 CONT returned to Hungary in 1239 and informed Béla of the planned Mongol invasion
1 CONT of Europe. Béla wanted to take precautions against the Mongols; therefore he
1 CONT granted asylum, in Hungary, to the Cumans who had been defeated by the
1 CONT Mongols. However, the nomadic culture of the Cumans caused tensions between
1 CONT them and the Hungarians which became more and more acute.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla tried to reinforce the eastern borders of his kingdom, but the Mongol
1 CONT troops, lead by Batu Khan, managed to break through the frontier defenses on
1 CONT 12 March 1241. On hearing of the Mongols' successful attack, the citizens of
1 CONT Pest, who had been accusing the Cumans of cooperating with the Mongols,
1 CONT murdered Köten, the Khan of the Cumans; therefore the enraged Cumans began to
1 CONT plunder the countryside and they left the country.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Mongol invasion of Hungary (tatárjárás)
1 CONT
1 CONT After the Cumans' departure, Béla could lead only a small army against the
1 CONT Mongols who defeated him in the Battle of Mohi on 11 April 1241. After his
1 CONT disastrous defeat, Béla fled to Pozsony and then to Hainburg where Duke
1 CONT Frederick II of Austria seized his treasury and enforced him to cede three
1 CONT western counties of his kingdom to Austria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla fled from Hainburg to Zagreb and he sent his envoys to the Emperor
1 CONT Frederick II and Pope Gregory IX to seek their assistance against the Mongols.
1 CONT He even offered to accept the overlordship of the Holy Roman Emperor in case
1 CONT he sent troops to Hungary, but none of the Western powers provided him any
1 CONT assistance.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the meantime, the Mongols were plundering the territories of the kingdom
1 CONT west of the Danube River. Moreover, in January, they could cross the frozen
1 CONT Danube and Béla had to flee from the Mongol troops, the khan sent to capture
1 CONT him, to Trau.
1 CONT
1 CONT Finally, in March 1241, the Mongol troops retired unexpectedly from Hungary,
1 CONT but they left a country totally pillaged behind them.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]The "Second Founder of our Country"
1 CONT
1 CONT Following the Mongol invasion of Hungary, Béla broke with his former internal
1 CONT policy. Based on the experiences of the occupation, he began to grant estates
1 CONT to his partisans, but simultaneously he also obliged them to build up
1 CONT fortresses there, because only fortresses could resist the conquerors. He also
1 CONT encouraged the towns to protect themselves by erecting walls. He called back
1 CONT the Cumans to Hungary and granted them the deserted territories between the
1 CONT Rivers Danube and Tisza.
1 CONT
1 CONT Because of his successful internal policy, he is greatly respected in Hungary
1 CONT and commonly known as "the second founder" of the kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]External expansions
1 CONT
1 CONT Already in 1242, he could lead his troops against Duke Frederick II of
1 CONT Austria. During his campaign, he managed to reoccupy Sopron and Kőszeg and he
1 CONT compelled the duke to renounce the three counties he had occupied during the
1 CONT Mongol invasion.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 30 June 1244, Béla made a peace with the Republic of Venice and he
1 CONT surrendered his supremacy over Zára but he retained the 1/3 of the Dalmatian
1 CONT city's revenues of customs. In 1245, Béla provided military assistance to his
1 CONT son-in-law, Prince Rostislav against Prince Danylo of Halych, but the latter
1 CONT forced back the pretender's attacks.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his request, Pope Gregory IX absolved Béla of his oath he had taken to
1 CONT the Holy Roman Emperor during the Mongol invasion on 21 August 1245. Shortly
1 CONT afterwards, Duke Frederick II of Austria, who did not give up his claims to
1 CONT the western counties of the Kingdom of Hungary, launched an attack against
1 CONT Hungary. Although, he could defeate the Hungarian troops in a battle by the
1 CONT Leitha River, but he died in the battle. With his death, the male line of the
1 CONT House of Babenberg became extinct, and a struggle commenced for the rule over
1 CONT Austria and Styria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla granted the Banat of Szörény to the Knights Hospitaller in 1249, when a
1 CONT rumour was spreading that the Mongols were preparing a new campaign against
1 CONT Europe. In the same year, he assisted again his son-in-law against Halych, but
1 CONT Prince Danylo defeated his troops by the San River. Finally, Béla decided to
1 CONT make an agreement with the Prince of Halych and they had a meeting in Zólyom
1 CONT in 1250 where Béla promised that he would not assist his son-in-law against
1 CONT Prince Danylo.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla decided to intervene in the struggle for the inheritance of the House of
1 CONT Babenberg and arranged a marriage between Gertrude of Austria, the niece of
1 CONT the deceased Duke Frederick II of Austria, and Roman Danylovich, a son of
1 CONT Prince Danylo of Halych. In 1252, he lead his armies against Austria and
1 CONT occupied the Vienna Basin. However, King Ottokar II of Bohemia, whose wife was
1 CONT Margaret, the sister of Duke Frederick II, also declared his claim to the two
1 CONT duchies. Béla made a campaign against Moravia but he could not occupy Olomouc;
1 CONT therefore he started negotiating with the King of Bohemia with the mediation
1 CONT of the Papal legates. Finally, Béla had a meeting with King Ottokar II in
1 CONT Pozsony and they concluded a peace. Based on the provision of the peace Wiener
1 CONT Neustadt and the Duchy of Styria came under Béla's rule.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Struggles with his son
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla had had his eldest son, Stephen crowned junior king already in 1246, but
1 CONT he did not want to share the royal power with his son. However, Stephen
1 CONT recruited an army against his father and persuaded Béla to cede him the
1 CONT government of Transylvania in 1258.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the same year, the Styrians, who would have preferred the rule of the King
1 CONT of Bohemia, rose against Béla's reign, but his troops suppressed their
1 CONT rebellion. After his victory, Béla appointed his son to Duke of Styria.
1 CONT Nevertheless, the Styrians rebelled against the rule of the King of Hungary
1 CONT again with the support of King Otakar II. Béla and his son commenced a
1 CONT military campaign against King Otakar II's lands, but their troops were
1 CONT defeated on July 12, 1260 in the Battle of Kroissenbrunn. Following the
1 CONT battle, Béla renounced his claim to the Duchy of Styria on behalf of the King
1 CONT of Bohemia in the Peace of Pressburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Shortly after the peace, Stephen took over again the government of
1 CONT Transylvania. Béla and his son lead jointly their armies against Bulgaria in
1 CONT 1261. Nevertheless, Béla favoured his younger son, Duke Béla and his daughter,
1 CONT Anna, the mother-in-law of the King of Bohemia; therefore his relationship
1 CONT with his elder son was getting tense. The two kings (father and son) began to
1 CONT harass the other's partisans, and their clash seemed inevitable. Finally, the
1 CONT Archbishops Fülöp of Esztergom and Smaragd of Kalocsa commenced to mediate
1 CONT between them and the two kings signed an agreement in the summer of 1262 in
1 CONT Pozsony. Based on the agreement, Stephen V took over the government of the
1 CONT parts of the Kingdom East of the Danube.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, their reconciliation was only temporary, because their partisans were
1 CONT continuously inciting them against each other. In 1264, the junior king
1 CONT attached his mother's and sister's estates in his domains. Béla sent troops
1 CONT against his son, whose wife and son were soon captured, while Stephen had to
1 CONT retreat to the Castle of Feketehalom. However, the young king managed to repel
1 CONT the siege of his father's troops and to commence a counter-attack. Stephen V
1 CONT won a strategic victory over Béla's troops in the Battle of Isaszeg in March
1 CONT 1265 and in the subsequent peace Béla was obliged to cede the government of
1 CONT the Eastern parts of his kingdom again to his son. On March 23, 1266, they
1 CONT confirmed personally the peace in the Convent of the Blessed Virgin on the
1 CONT Nyulak szigete ('Rabbits' Island').
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1267, the "prelates and nobles" of the Kingdom of Hungary held a joint
1 CONT assembly in Esztergom, and their decisions were confirmed by both Béla and his
1 CONT son.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]His last years
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla lost his favourite son in the summer of 1269. Afterwards, his favourite
1 CONT daughter, Anna was exercising more and more influence over him. In his last
1 CONT will, Béla entrusted his daughter and his followers to her son-in-law, King
1 CONT Otakar II of Bohemia, because he did not trust his son.
1 CONT
