1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV (Hungarian: IV. Béla, (1206 – 3 May 1270), King of Hungary[1]
1 CONT (1235-1270). Béla was present, at the age of seven, when a group of
1 CONT conspirators killed his mother, and he could never forgive his father's
1 CONT generosity towards the conspirators' accomplices. Shortly afterwards, he was
1 CONT crowned junior king (rex iunior) and he governed several provinces of the
1 CONT Kingdom of Hungary during his father's reign. He endeavoured to restore the
1 CONT royal power that had declined since the death of his grandfather, King Béla,
1 CONT which resulted in permanent conflicts between Béla and his father. When he
1 CONT ascended the throne, he determined to revive his grandfather's internal policy
1 CONT which made him unpopular among his barons. However, he soon had to face the
1 CONT threat of the Mongol invasion of Europe; therefore he granted asylum to the
1 CONT Cumans in order to strengthen his military force. After the Tatar invasion he
1 CONT became one of the most famous Hungarian kings. Nevertheless, the Mongol armies
1 CONT defeated his troops in a decisive battle requiring his escape to the farthest
1 CONT fortress of his kingdom while the Mongols were pillaging the country. When the
1 CONT Mongol troops were withdrawn unexpectedly, Béla returned and commenced
1 CONT reconstruction of his devastated kingdom; he patronized towns, constructed new
1 CONT fortresses and encouraged immigration. His success is reflected by his popular
1 CONT epithet, "the Second Founder of our Country", in Hungary. During the second
1 CONT period of his reign, he proceeded to expand his rule over the neighbouring
1 CONT countries. However his last years were characterized by his permanent
1 CONT conflicts with his eldest son, Stephen.
1 CONT
