1 CONT Name Prefix: King Name Suffix: Iv, Of Hungary
1 CONT Béla IV of Hungary
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla IV c.1270Béla IV (1206–May 3, 1270) was the king of Hungary between 1235
1 CONT and 1270 and member of Arpad dynasty.
1 CONT
1 CONT Contents [hide]
1 CONT 1 Early life and family
1 CONT 2 Mongol invasions
1 CONT 3 Other wars
1 CONT 4 Sources
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Early life and family
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla was the son of King András II and Gertrude of Merania. In 1213 his mother
1 CONT was murdered by Hungarian magnates. His father failed to avenge Queen
1 CONT Gertrude's murder so it was left to Béla to track down and punish them, a
1 CONT campaign he finally completed some thirty years after her death.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1218 Béla was married to Maria Laskarina, a daughter of Emperor Theodore I
1 CONT Lascaris of Nicaea and Anna Angelina. They had two sons and seven daughters,
1 CONT of whom the most notable were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Kinga, married to King Boleslaus V of Poland; she was canonized by the Roman
1 CONT Catholic Church in 1999
1 CONT Stephen, future King István V
1 CONT Erzsébet, married to Duke Henry XIII of Lower Bavaria
1 CONT Constance, married to Knyaz Leo I of Halych in 1247.
1 CONT Margit, canonized by the Roman Catholic Church in 1943 as St. Margaret. She
1 CONT lent her name to Margaret Island.
1 CONT Béla's reputation as monarch, compared to that of his father, is generally
1 CONT perceived to have been good. He was a good administrator and on his accession,
1 CONT sought to counter corruption and to recover lost territory which had been
1 CONT given over to the magnates by his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Mongol invasions
1 CONT Béla IV flees from Mohi, detail from Chronicon PictumIn 1238, Hungary was
1 CONT invaded by Cuman tribes fleeing the advancing Mongol hordes. Béla sought an
1 CONT alliance with the Cumans, and so he granted them asylum and betrothed his son
1 CONT and heir, Stephen, to the daughter of a Cuman khan named Kuthen. The Cumans
1 CONT (originally a pagan shamanist people) converted to Christianity and were
1 CONT baptised.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla tried with little success to reestablish royal preeminence by reacquiring
1 CONT lost crown lands. His efforts, however, created a deep rift between the crown
1 CONT and the magnates just as the Mongols were sweeping westward across Russia
1 CONT toward Europe. Aware of the danger, Béla ordered the magnates and lesser
1 CONT nobles to mobilize. Few responded. Béla also sent messages to Pope Gregory IX
1 CONT and the Holy Roman Emperor Frederick II but to no avail. The Mongols
1 CONT eventually routed Béla's army at the Battle of Mohi on April 11, 1241. His
1 CONT ally Kuthen had been killed by mistrustful Hungarian lords in Pest just prior
1 CONT to the invasion.
1 CONT
1 CONT Béla fled to Austria, where Duke Frederick of Babenberg held him for ransom,
1 CONT then to Trogir in Dalmatia. The Mongols reduced Hungary's towns and villages
1 CONT to ashes and slaughtered half the population before news arrived in 1242 that
1 CONT the Great Ögedei Khan had died in Karakorum. The Mongols withdrew, sparing
1 CONT Béla and what remained of his kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT Upon his return to power, Béla began rebuilding his country, including a
1 CONT massive construction campaign which produced the system of castles as a
1 CONT defence against the threat of a Mongol return. This eventually happened in
1 CONT 1261 but this time Béla was successful in defeating them. He is greatly
1 CONT respected in Hungary and commonly known as "the second founder" of the
1 CONT kingdom.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Other wars
1 CONT Béla was determined to regain the western part of Hungary which had been
1 CONT seized by Frederick II as his price for giving Béla assistance in the first
1 CONT war against the Mongols (help which never came). Béla finally defeated
1 CONT Frederick in battle in 1246, Frederick being trampled to death by his own
1 CONT cavalry. Béla also engaged in a long war with Otakar II of Bohemia to gain
1 CONT control of Austria and Styria, but he finally had to give up all claims after
1 CONT a defeat in the first battle of Marchfeld (or battle of Kroisenbrunn) in 1260.
1 CONT He was regularly engaged in protecting the outer extremeties of his realm
1 CONT including Dalmatia, Bosnia and Serbia.
1 CONT
1 CONT The final years of Béla's reign were marred by the rebellion of his son
1 CONT Stephen. Béla was eventually forced to divide his kingdom in two, with Stephen
1 CONT crowned to junior king of Hungary, setting up his own capital, and adopting
1 CONT foreign policies directly contrary to those of his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Sources
1 CONT Parsons, John Carmi. Medieval Queenship, 1997
1 CONT This article incorporates text from the Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh
1 CONT Edition, a publication now in the public domain.
