1 CONT JEAN de Brienne, son of ERARD [II] de Brienne & his wife Agnès de Montbéliard
1 CONT [Montfaucon] ([1170/75]-27 Mar 1237). "Johan de Briene" is named as brother of
1 CONT Gauthier de Brienne by William of Tyre (Continuator), after his brother
1 CONT Guillaume[311]. "Gualterius comes Brene" donated property to Beaulieu (Aube)
1 CONT by charter dated 1194 with the consent of "Willelmi et Johannis fratrum
1 CONT eius"[312]. The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines names "Iohannis frater
1 CONT eiusdem comitis [Galteri comitis Briennensis" when recording that he succeeded
1 CONT as Comte de Brienne after the death of his brother[313]. "Johannes comes
1 CONT Brene" donated property to Basse-Fontaine by charter dated Apr 1210[314]. His
1 CONT first marriage was arranged by Philippe II King of France, who gave him a
1 CONT dower of 40,000 silver pounds, a sum which was equalled by Pope Innocent
1 CONT III[315]. He landed at Acre 13 Sep 1210, was married to his first wife the
1 CONT next day, and was crowned 3 Oct 1210 at Tyre as JEAN King of Jerusalem by
1 CONT Albert Patriarch of Jerusalem[316]. "Iohannes…Latinorum Ierusalem rex decimus
1 CONT et comes Brena et domina Maria uxor mea regina" donated property to the church
1 CONT of the Holy Sepulchre, Jerusalem by charter dated 1 Jul 1211[317]. He retained
1 CONT the bailiship of the kingdom of Jerusalem after the death of his first
1 CONT wife[318], nominally in the name of his daughter. After a long siege, and with
1 CONT the help of western armies which were part of the Fifth Crusade, Damietta in
1 CONT Egypt was captured 5 Nov 1219 and added to the territory of the kingdom of
1 CONT Jerusalem[319]. Jean left the crusade in Feb 1220, intending to visit Armenia
1 CONT to claim the throne in the name of his second wife following the death of her
1 CONT father, but as both she and their infant son died before he sailed for Cilicia
1 CONT he had no further claim and abandoned the journey[320]. He arrived back with
1 CONT the Fifth Crusade 6 Jul 1221, which proceeded to march further into Egypt but
1 CONT was forced to retreat and return Damietta 8 Sep 1221[321]. After appointing
1 CONT Eudes de Montbéliard as regent, King Jean sailed from Acre in autumn 1222, to
1 CONT find a suitable husband for his daughter. He agreed to her marriage with
1 CONT Friedrich II King of Germany on condition that he continued as regent of
1 CONT Jerusalem for life. Matthew Paris records that “Johannes de Brennes rex
1 CONT Jerusalem et magister superioris Hospitalis fratrum Jerusalem” visited England
1 CONT “circa octavas Apostolorum Petri et Pauli” to seek help for the relief of
1 CONT “Terræ Sanctæ”[322]. His son-in-law reneged on his promise relating to the
1 CONT throne of Jerusalem immediately after his wedding and declared himself king of
1 CONT Jerusalem in 1225[323]. He was appointed regent of the Latin empire of
1 CONT Constantinople, by agreement at Perugia in Apr 1229, and was crowned JEAN
1 CONT Emperor of Constantinople on his arrival in the city in 1231. The Chronicle of
1 CONT Alberic de Trois-Fontaines records the death in 1237 in Constantinople of "rex
1 CONT Iohannes"[324].
1 CONT
