1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia:
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne (c. 1170 – 27 March 1237) was a French nobleman who became
1 CONT John I King of Jerusalem by marriage, and was later invited to become John I
1 CONT Latin Emperor of Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the second son of Erard II, count of Brienne, in Champagne, and of
1 CONT Agnes de Montfaucon. Destined originally for the Church, he had preferred to
1 CONT become a knight, and in forty years of tournaments and fights he had won
1 CONT himself a considerable reputation, when in 1208 envoys came from the Holy Land
1 CONT to ask Philip Augustus, king of France, to select one of his barons as husband
1 CONT to the heiress and ruler of the Kingdom of Jerusalem. Philip selected John of
1 CONT Brienne, and promised to support him in his new dignity. In 1210, John married
1 CONT the heiress (Mary) Maria (daughter of Isabella and Conrad of Montferrat),
1 CONT assuming the title of king in right of his wife. In 1211, after some desultory
1 CONT operations, he concluded a five years' truce with Malik-el-Adil; in 1212 he
1 CONT lost his wife, who left him a daughter, Yolande (also known as Isabella); soon
1 CONT afterwards he married the princess Stephanie, daughter of Leo II of Armenia.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the Fifth Crusade (1218-1221) he was a prominent figure. The legate
1 CONT Pelagius of Albano, however, claimed the command; and insisting on the advance
1 CONT from Damietta, in spite of John's warnings, he refused to accept the
1 CONT favourable terms of the sultan, as the king advised, until it was too late.
1 CONT After the failure of the crusade, King John came to the West to obtain help
1 CONT for his kingdom. In 1223 he met Pope Honorius III and the emperor Frederick II
1 CONT at Ferentino, where, in order that he might be connected more closely with the
1 CONT Holy Land, Frederick was betrothed to John's daughter Isabella, now heiress of
1 CONT the kingdom. After the meeting at Ferentino, John went to France and England,
1 CONT finding little consolation; and thence he travelled to Santiago de Compostela,
1 CONT where King Alfonso IX of Leon offered him the hand of one of his daughters and
1 CONT the promise of his kingdom. John passed over Alfonso's eldest daughter and
1 CONT heiress in favor of a younger daughter, Berenguela of Leon. After a visit to
1 CONT Germany he returned to Rome (1225). Here he received a demand from Frederick
1 CONT II (who had now married Isabella) that he should abandon his title and dignity
1 CONT of king, which, so Frederick claimed, had passed to himself along with the
1 CONT heiress of the kingdom. John, though fifty or fifty-five years of age, was
1 CONT still vigorous enough to revenge himself on Frederick, by commanding the papal
1 CONT troops which attacked southern Italy during the emperor's absence on the Sixth
1 CONT Crusade (1228-1229).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1229, John was invited by the barons of the Latin Empire of Constantinople
1 CONT to become emperor-regent, on condition that Baldwin of Courtenay should marry
1 CONT his second daughter and succeed him. For nine years he ruled in
1 CONT Constantinople, and in 1235, with a few troops, he repelled a great siege of
1 CONT the city by John III Doukas Vatatzes, emperor of Nicaea, and Ivan Asen II of
1 CONT Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT After this last feat of arms, which has perhaps been exaggerated by the Latin
1 CONT chroniclers, who compare him to Hector and the Maccabees, John died in the
1 CONT habit of a Franciscan friar. An aged paladin, somewhat uxorious and always
1 CONT penniless, he was a typical knight errant, whose wanderings led him all over
1 CONT Europe, and planted him successively on the thrones of Jerusalem and
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriages and issue
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne married three times. By his first wife, Marie of Montferrat,
1 CONT he had one child, Yolande, later Queen of Jerusalem. He had also one child by
1 CONT his second wife, Stephanie of Armenia, a son named as successor in Armenia,
1 CONT but died in childhood. By his third wife, Berenguela of Leon, he had four
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Marie of Brienne (1225-1275), who married Emperor Baldwin II of
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Alphonso of Brienne (c. 1228-1270), who married Marie d'Issoudon, countess
1 CONT of Eu, and became count of Eu in right of his wife, and was also Great
1 CONT Chamberlain of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Jean (John) de Brienne (c. 1230-1296), who in 1258 became Grand Butler of
1 CONT France. Married as his first wife, Jeanne, daughter of Geoffrey VI, Viscount
1 CONT of Chateaudun, and as his second wife, Marie de Coucy, widow of King Alexander
1 CONT II of Scotland. Had one daughter, Blanche by his first marriage.
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. Louis of Acre (c. 1235-1263), who married Agnes of Beaumont and became
1 CONT Viscount of Beaumont in her right. His children included Henry de Beaumont,
1 CONT Earl of Buchan, an ancestor of England's Royal House of Lancaster.
1 CONT
1 CONT References
1 CONT
