1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Jean De Count De Brienne (Bryan)King of Jerusalem b. 1168 in Acre, Palenstine
1 CONT d. 1237 in Constantinople m. Beregaria Alfonsez b. 1195 in Leon, Spain
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne (né: Jean de Candia-Nevers, c. 1148 – 1237) was King of
1 CONT Jerusalem and Latin Emperor-Regent or Associate "Consort" Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the second son of Erard II de Candia, count of Brienne, in Champagne,
1 CONT and of Agnes de Montfaucon, countess of Montbéliard (né: Agnès de Nevers,
1 CONT daugther of Guillaume III de Nevers). Destined originally for the Church, he
1 CONT had preferred to become a knight, and in forty years of tournaments and fights
1 CONT he had won himself a considerable reputation, when in 1208 envoys came from
1 CONT the Holy Land to ask Philip Augustus, king of France, to select one of his
1 CONT barons as husband to the heiress and ruler of the Kingdom of Jerusalem. Philip
1 CONT selected John of Brienne, and promised to support him in his new dignity. In
1 CONT 1210, John married the heiress (Mary) Maria (daughter of Isabella and Conrad
1 CONT of Montferrat), assuming the title of king in right of his wife. In 1211,
1 CONT after some desultory operations, he concluded a six years' truce with Malik-
1 CONT el-Adil; in 1212 he lost his wife, who left him a daughter, Yolande (also
1 CONT known as Isabella); soon afterwards he married the princess Stephanie,
1 CONT daughter of Leo II of Armenia.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the Fifth Crusade (1218-1221) he was a prominent figure. The legate
1 CONT Pelagius of Albano, however, claimed the command; and insisting on the advance
1 CONT from Damietta, in spite of John's warnings, he refused to accept the
1 CONT favourable terms of the sultan, as the king advised, until it was too late.
1 CONT After the failure of the crusade, King John came to the West to obtain help
1 CONT for his kingdom. In 1223 he met Pope Honorius III and the emperor Frederick II
1 CONT at Ferentino, where, in order that he might be connected more closely with the
1 CONT Holy Land, Frederick was betrothed to John's daughter Isabella, now heiress of
1 CONT the kingdom. After the meeting at Ferentino, John went to France and England,
1 CONT finding little consolation; and thence he travelled to Santiago de Compostela,
1 CONT where King Alfonso IX of Leon offered him the hand of one of his daughters and
1 CONT the promise of his kingdom. John passed over Alfonso's eldest daughter and
1 CONT heiress in favor of a younger daughter, Berengaria of Castile. After a visit
1 CONT to Germany he returned to Rome (1225). Here he received a demand from
1 CONT Frederick II (who had now married Isabella) that he should abandon his title
1 CONT and dignity of king, which, so Frederick claimed, had passed to himself along
1 CONT with the heiress of the kingdom. John was now a septuagenarian "king in
1 CONT exile," but he was still vigorous enough to revenge himself on Frederick, by
1 CONT commanding the papal troops which attacked southern Italy during the emperor's
1 CONT absence on the Sixth Crusade (1228-1229).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1229, John, now eighty years of age, was invited by the barons of the Latin
1 CONT Empire of Constantinople to become emperor-regent, on condition that Baldwin
1 CONT of Courtenay should marry his second daughter and succeed him. For nine years
1 CONT he ruled in Constantinople, and in 1235, with a few troops, he repelled a
1 CONT great siege of the city by John III Doukas Vatatzes, emperor of Nicaea, and
1 CONT Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT After this last feat of arms, which has perhaps been exaggerated by the Latin
1 CONT chroniclers, who compare him to Hector and the Maccabees, John died in the
1 CONT habit of a Franciscan friar. An aged paladin, somewhat uxorious and always
1 CONT penniless, he was a typical knight errant, whose wanderings led him all over
1 CONT Europe, and planted him successively on the thrones of Jerusalem and
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT KINGS OF JERUSALEM
1 CONT
1 CONT 1099-1100 Godfrey of Bouillon
1 CONT
1 CONT 1100-1118 Baldwin of Le Bourg
1 CONT
1 CONT 1118-1131 Baldwin II
1 CONT
1 CONT 1131-1143 Fulk of Anjou
1 CONT
1 CONT 1143-1152 (Queen Melisende as Regent)
1 CONT
1 CONT 1143-1163 Baldwin III
1 CONT
1 CONT 1163-1174 Amalric I
1 CONT
1 CONT 1174-1185 Baldwin IV
1 CONT
1 CONT 1185-1191 Guy of Lusignan
1 CONT
1 CONT 1192-1197 Henry of Champagne
1 CONT
1 CONT 1197-1205 Amalric II,
1 CONT
1 CONT 1210-1225 Jean of Brienne, who ceded his rights to his daughter,
1 CONT
1 CONT 1225-1228 Isabella/Yolande, , who married Frederick II Hohenstaufen (d.=
1 CONT 1250).
1 CONT
1 CONT After this it gets complicated:
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cypriot Claim
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1243, the high court of St-Jean-d'Acre declared Frederick's son Conrad
1 CONT deposed and assigned the regency to the kings of Cyprus, and then (in 1268)
1 CONT the crown as well. Hence the following kings of Cyprus would claim the title:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1218-1253 Henry I
1 CONT
1 CONT 1253-1267 Hugh II
1 CONT
1 CONT 1267-1284 Hugh III
1 CONT
1 CONT 1284-1285 John
1 CONT
1 CONT 1285-1331 Henry II
1 CONT
1 CONT The kings of Cyprus go on to 1474, at which point Rene d'Anjou may have
1 CONT acquired the title
1 CONT
1 CONT The Neapolitan claim
1 CONT
1 CONT According to E. Leonard, Les Angevins de Naples, Presses Universitaires de
1 CONT France, 1954), Marie d'Antioche, petite-fille of the King of Jerusalem Amalric
1 CONT I, ceded, in 1269, to Charles I, King of Naples and Count of Provence, the
1 CONT right which she had to the Kingdom of Jerusalem. This cession was confirmed by
1 CONT the pope in 1277.
1 CONT
1 CONT It follows then, that the kings of Naples and Counts of Provence henceforth
1 CONT possessed the title of King of Jerusalem. Thus the list of later kings of
1 CONT Jerusalem would be as follows:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1277-1285 Charles I
1 CONT
1 CONT 1285-1309 Charles II
1 CONT
1 CONT 1309-1343 Robert I
1 CONT
1 CONT 1343-1382 Jeanne I
1 CONT
1 CONT 1382-1384 Louis I
1 CONT
1 CONT 1382-1417 Louis II
1 CONT
1 CONT 1427-1343 Louis III
1 CONT
1 CONT 1434-1480 René d'Anjou
1 CONT
1 CONT 1480-1481 Charles III
1 CONT
1 CONT See also: P. Durrieu. "Le titre de roi de Jerusalem et la France" in Travaux
1 CONT du Congres francais de la Syrie 2 (1919)
1 CONT
