1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne (né: Jean de Candia-Nevers, c. 1170/1175 – 27 March 1237) was
1 CONT Consort King of Jerusalem, Consort Presumptive Prince Heir of Armenia and
1 CONT Latin Emperor-Regent or Associate "Consort" Emperor of Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the second son of Erard II de Candia, count of Brienne, in Champagne,
1 CONT and of Agnes de Montfaucon, countess of Montbéliard (né: Agnès de Nevers,
1 CONT daughter of Guillaume III de Nevers). Destined originally for the Church, he
1 CONT had preferred to become a knight, and in forty years of tournaments and fights
1 CONT he had won himself a considerable reputation, when in 1208 envoys came from
1 CONT the Holy Land to ask Philip Augustus, king of France, to select one of his
1 CONT barons as husband to the heiress and ruler of the Kingdom of Jerusalem. Philip
1 CONT selected John of Brienne, and promised to support him in his new dignity. In
1 CONT 1210, John married the heiress (Mary) Maria (daughter of Isabella and Conrad
1 CONT of Montferrat), assuming the title of king in right of his wife. In 1211,
1 CONT after some desultory operations, he concluded a six years' truce with Malik-
1 CONT el-Adil; in 1212 he lost his wife, who left him a daughter, Yolande (also
1 CONT known as Isabella); soon afterwards he married the princess Stephanie,
1 CONT daughter of Leo II of Armenia.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the Fifth Crusade (1218-1221) he was a prominent figure. The legate
1 CONT Pelagius of Albano, however, claimed the command; and insisting on the advance
1 CONT from Damietta, in spite of John's warnings, he refused to accept the
1 CONT favourable terms of the sultan, as the king advised, until it was too late.
1 CONT After the failure of the crusade, King John came to the West to obtain help
1 CONT for his kingdom. In 1223 he met Pope Honorius III and the emperor Frederick II
1 CONT at Ferentino, where, in order that he might be connected more closely with the
1 CONT Holy Land, Frederick was betrothed to John's daughter Isabella, now heiress of
1 CONT the kingdom. After the meeting at Ferentino, John went to France and England,
1 CONT finding little consolation; and thence he travelled to Santiago de Compostela,
1 CONT where King Alfonso IX of Leon offered him the hand of one of his daughters and
1 CONT the promise of his kingdom. John passed over Alfonso's eldest daughter and
1 CONT heiress in favor of a younger daughter, Berenguela of Leon. After a visit to
1 CONT Germany he returned to Rome (1225). Here he received a demand from Frederick
1 CONT II (who had now married Isabella) that he should abandon his title and dignity
1 CONT of king, which, so Frederick claimed, had passed to himself along with the
1 CONT heiress of the kingdom. John was now a septuagenarian "king in exile," but he
1 CONT was still vigorous enough to revenge himself on Frederick, by commanding the
1 CONT papal troops which attacked southern Italy during the emperor's absence on the
1 CONT Sixth Crusade (1228-1229).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1229, John, now eighty years of age, was invited by the barons of the Latin
1 CONT Empire of Constantinople to become emperor-regent, on condition that Baldwin
1 CONT of Courtenay should marry his second daughter and succeed him. For nine years
1 CONT he ruled in Constantinople, and in 1235, with a few troops, he repelled a
1 CONT great siege of the city by John III Doukas Vatatzes, emperor of Nicaea, and
1 CONT Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT After this last feat of arms, which has perhaps been exaggerated by the Latin
1 CONT chroniclers, who compare him to Hector and the Maccabees, John died in the
1 CONT habit of a Franciscan friar. An aged paladin, somewhat uxorious and always
1 CONT penniless, he was a typical knight errant, whose wanderings led him all over
1 CONT Europe, and planted him successively on the thrones of Jerusalem and
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriages and issue
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne married three times. By his first wife, Marie of Montferrat,
1 CONT he had one child, Yolande, later Queen of Jerusalem. He had also one child by
1 CONT his second wife, Stephanie of Armenia, a son named as successor in Armenia,
1 CONT but died in childhood. By his third wife, Berenguela of Leon, he had four
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Marie of Brienne (1225-1275), who married Emperor Baldwin II of
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alphonso of Brienne (c. 1228-1270), who married Marie d'Issoudon, countess of
1 CONT Eu, and became count of Eu in right of his wife, and was also Great
1 CONT Chamberlain of France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Jean (John) de Brienne (c. 1230-1296), who in 1258 became Grand Butler of
1 CONT France. Married Marie de Coucy as his first wife. Second wife was Jeanne,
1 CONT daughter of Geoffrey VI, Viscount of Chateaudun.
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis of Acre (c. 1235-1263), who married Agnes of Beaumont and became
1 CONT Viscount of Beaumont in her right.
1 CONT
1 CONT References
1 CONT
1 CONT Ancestral Roots of Certain American Colonists Who Came to America Before 1700
1 CONT by Frederick Lewis Weis, Lines: 114-28, 120-29
1 CONT
