1 CONT John of Brienne (c. 1155 – 27 March 1237) was a French nobleman who became
1 CONT King of Jerusalem by marriage, and ruled the Latin Empire of Constantinople as
1 CONT regent.
1 CONT
1 CONT Jean de Candia-Nevers was the second son of Erard II, count of Brienne, in
1 CONT Champagne, and of Agnes de Montfaucon. Destined originally for a clerical
1 CONT career, he had preferred to become a knight, and in forty years of tournaments
1 CONT and fights he had won himself a considerable reputation, when in 1208 envoys
1 CONT came from the Holy Land to ask Philip Augustus, king of France, to select one
1 CONT of his barons as husband to the heiress and ruler of the Kingdom of Jerusalem.
1 CONT Philip selected John of Brienne, and promised to support him in his new
1 CONT dignity. In 1210, John married the heiress (Mary) Maria (daughter of Isabella
1 CONT and Conrad of Montferrat), assuming the title of king in right of his wife. In
1 CONT 1211, after some desultory operations, he concluded a five years' truce with
1 CONT Malik-el-Adil; in 1212 he lost his wife, who left him a daughter, Yolande
1 CONT (also known as Isabella); soon afterwards he married the princess Stephanie,
1 CONT daughter of Leo II of Armenia.
1 CONT
1 CONT During the Fifth Crusade (1218–1221) he was a prominent figure. The legate
1 CONT Pelagius of Albano, however, claimed the command; and insisting on the advance
1 CONT from Damietta, in spite of John's warnings, he refused to accept the
1 CONT favourable terms of the sultan, as the king advised, until it was too late.
1 CONT After the failure of the crusade, King John came to the West to obtain help
1 CONT for his kingdom. In 1223 he met Pope Honorius III and the emperor Frederick II
1 CONT at Ferentino, where, in order that he might be connected more closely with the
1 CONT Holy Land, Frederick was betrothed to John's daughter Isabella, now heiress of
1 CONT the kingdom. After the meeting at Ferentino, John went to France and England,
1 CONT finding little consolation; and thence he travelled to Santiago de Compostela,
1 CONT where King Alfonso IX of Leon offered him the hand of one of his daughters and
1 CONT the promise of his kingdom. John passed over Alfonso's eldest daughter and
1 CONT heiress in favor of a younger daughter, Berenguela of Leon. After a visit to
1 CONT Germany he returned to Rome (1225). Here he received a demand from Frederick
1 CONT II (who had now married Isabella) that he should abandon his title and dignity
1 CONT of king, which, so Frederick claimed, had passed to himself along with the
1 CONT heiress of the kingdom. John, though fifty or fifty-five years of age, was
1 CONT still vigorous enough to avenge himself on Frederick, by commanding the papal
1 CONT troops which attacked southern Italy during the emperor's absence on the Sixth
1 CONT Crusade (1228–1229).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1229, John was invited by the barons of the Latin Empire of Constantinople
1 CONT to become emperor-regent, on condition that Baldwin of Courtenay should marry
1 CONT his second daughter and succeed him. For nine years he ruled in
1 CONT Constantinople, and in 1235, with a few troops, he repelled a great siege of
1 CONT the city by John III Doukas Vatatzes, emperor of Nicaea, and Ivan Asen II of
1 CONT Bulgaria, killing around 10,000 of the enemy single-handedly at the age of
1 CONT eighty.[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT After this last feat of arms, which has perhaps been exaggerated by the Latin
1 CONT chroniclers, who compare him to Hector, Roland and the Maccabees, John died in
1 CONT the habit of a Franciscan friar. An aged paladin, he was around 80 years old,
1 CONT somewhat uxorious and always penniless, he was a typical knight errant, whose
1 CONT wanderings led him all over Europe, and planted him successively on the
1 CONT thrones of Jerusalem and Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne married three times. By his first wife, Marie of Montferrat,
1 CONT he had one child, Yolande, later Queen of Jerusalem. He had also one child by
1 CONT his second wife, Stephanie of Armenia, a son named as successor in Armenia,
1 CONT but died in childhood. By his third wife, Berenguela of Leon, he had four
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Marie of Brienne (1225–1275), who married Emperor Baldwin II of
1 CONT Constantinople. Alphonso of Brienne (c. 1228–1270), who married Marie
1 CONT d'Issoudon, countess of Eu, and became count of Eu in right of his wife, and
1 CONT was also Great Chamberlain of France. Jean (John) de Brienne (c. 1230–1296),
1 CONT who in 1258 became Grand Butler of France. Married as his first wife, Jeanne,
1 CONT daughter of Geoffrey VI, Viscount of Chateaudun, and as his second wife, Marie
1 CONT de Coucy, widow of King Alexander II of Scotland. Had one daughter, Blanche by
1 CONT his first marriage. Louis of Acre (c. 1235–1263), who married Agnes of
1 CONT Beaumont and became Viscount of Beaumont in her right. His children included
1 CONT Henry de Beaumont, Earl of Buchan, an ancestor of England's Royal House of
1 CONT Lancaster.
