1 CONT [http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=document&guid=bb9456c1-cacd-4500-92b9-0301b5a827d1&tid=9692367&pid=-524891591](http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=document&guid=bb9456c1-cacd-4500-92b9-0301b5a827d1&tid=9692367&pid=-524891591)
1 CONT John of Brienne
1 CONT [http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=document&guid=deaee736-a14b-4875-a034-6ed8f40c2c18&tid=9692367&pid=-524891591](http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=document&guid=deaee736-a14b-4875-a034-6ed8f40c2c18&tid=9692367&pid=-524891591)
1 CONT John of Brienne
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne (c. 1148-1237), king of Jerusalem and Latin emperor-regent of
1 CONT Constantinople, was a man of sixty years of age before he began to play any
1 CONT considerable part in history.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the second son of Erard II, count of Brienne, in Champagne, and of
1 CONT Agnes de Montfaucon, countess of Montbéliard. Destined originally for the
1 CONT Church, he had preferred to become a knight, and in forty years of tournaments
1 CONT and fights he had won himself a considerable reputation, when in 1208 envoys
1 CONT came from the Holy Land to ask Philip Augustus, king of France, to select one
1 CONT of his barons as husband to the heiress and ruler of the Kingdom of Jerusalem.
1 CONT Philip selected John of Brienne, and promised to support him in his new
1 CONT dignity. In 1210 John married the heiress Maria (daughter of Isabella and
1 CONT Conrad of Montferrat), assuming the title of king in right of his wife. In
1 CONT 1211, after some desultory operations, he concluded a six years' truce with
1 CONT Malik-el-Adil; in 1212 he lost his wife, who left him a daughter, Yolande
1 CONT (also known as Isabella); soon afterwards he married the Armenian princess
1 CONT Stephanie.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the Fifth Crusade (1218-1221) he was a prominent figure. The legate
1 CONT Pelagius of Albano, however, claimed the command; and insisting on the advance
1 CONT from Damietta, in spite of John's warnings, he refused to accept the
1 CONT favourable terms of the sultan, as the king advised, until it was too late.
1 CONT After the failure of the crusade, King John came to the West to obtain help
1 CONT for his kingdom. In 1223 he met Pope Honorius III and the emperor Frederick II
1 CONT at Ferentino, where, in order that he might be connected more closely with the
1 CONT Holy Land, Frederick was betrothed to John's daughter Isabella, now heiress of
1 CONT the kingdom. After the meeting at Ferentino, John went to France and England,
1 CONT finding little consolation; and thence he travelled to Santiago de Compostela,
1 CONT where King Alfonso IX of Leon offered him the hand of one of his daughters and
1 CONT the promise of his kingdom. John passed over Alfonso's eldest daughter and
1 CONT heiress in favor of a younger daughter, Berengaria of Castile. After a visit
1 CONT to Germany he returned to Rome (1225). Here he received a demand from
1 CONT Frederick II (who had now married Isabella) that he should abandon his title
1 CONT and dignity of king, which, so Frederick claimed, had passed to himself along
1 CONT with the heiress of the kingdom. John was now a septuagenarian "king in
1 CONT exile," but he was still vigorous enough to revenge himself on Frederick, by
1 CONT commanding the papal troops which attacked southern Italy during the emperor's
1 CONT absence on the Sixth Crusade (1228-1229).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1229 John, now eighty years of age, was invited by the barons of the Latin
1 CONT Empire of Constantinople to become emperor-regent, on condition that Baldwin
1 CONT of Courtenay should marry his second daughter and succeed him. For nine years
1 CONT he ruled in Constantinople, and in 1235, with a few troops, he repelled a
1 CONT great siege of the city by John III Ducas Vatatzes, emperor of Nicaea, and
1 CONT Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT After this last feat of arms, which has perhaps been exaggerated by the Latin
1 CONT chroniclers, who compare him to Hector and the Maccabees, John died in the
1 CONT habit of a Franciscan friar. An aged paladin, somewhat uxorious and always
1 CONT penniless, he was a typical knight errant, whose wanderings led him all over
1 CONT Europe, and planted him successively on the thrones of Jerusalem and
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT John of Brienne married three times. By his first wife, Marie of Montferrat,
1 CONT he had one child, Yolande, later Queen of Jerusalem. He had also one child by
1 CONT his second wife, Stephanie of Armenia, a son named as successor in Armenia,
1 CONT but died in childhood. By his third wife, Berengaria of Castile, he had 4
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Marie de Brienne (1225-1275), who married Emperor Baldwin II of
1 CONT Constantinople.
1 CONT 2\. Alphonso of Brienne (c.1228-1270), who married Marie d'Issoudon, countess
1 CONT of Eu, and became count of Eu in right of his wife, and was also Great
1 CONT Chamberlain of France.
1 CONT 3\. John II of Brienne (c.1230-1273), who in 1258 became Grand Butler of
1 CONT France.
1 CONT 4\. Louis of Acre (c.1235-1263), who married Agnes of Beaumont and became
1 CONT Viscount of Beaumont in her right.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT Maria King of Jerusalem
1 CONT 1210–1212
1 CONT (with Maria) Succeeded by:
1 CONT Yolande
1 CONT Basic Life Information
1 CONT John was King of Jeruselem and Emperor of Constantinople.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT From Plantagenet Ancestry:
1 CONT
1 CONT BÉRENGÈRE (or BERENGUELA) OF CASTILE-LEÓN, born in 1204. She married at Burgos
1 CONT in Castile in 1223 (as his 3rd wife) JEAN DE BRIENNE, Count of Brienne (as
1 CONT regent for his nephew), 1205-1221, King Consort of Jerusalem, 1210-1212, King-
1 CONT Regent of Jerusalem, 1212-1225, Emperor-Regent of Constantinople, son of Érard
1 CONT II de Brienne ... by Agnes. ... He was born 1169-74. They had three sons,
1 CONT Alphonse ..., Jean, and Louis, Knt. ... and one daughter, Marie. ... Jean
1 CONT married (1st) at Tyre 14 Sept. 1210 MARIE DE MONFERRAT [[sic]], Queen of
1 CONT Jerusalem. ... Marie was born at Tyre in the summer of 1191. They had one
1 CONT daughter, Isabel (wife of Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor). He was elected
1 CONT King of Jerusalem in 1210, in right of his wife, Marie, who died soon
1 CONT afterwards in 1212, leaving a daughter and heiress, in whose right he
1 CONT subsequently reigned. He married (2nd) in 1213 STÉPHANIE OF ARMENIA, daughter
1 CONT and heiress of Leo II, King of Armenia. They had one son, Jean. Stéphanie died
1 CONT in 1219 during the siege of Damietta. Jean was a legatee in the 1222 will of
1 CONT Philippe Auguste, King of France. In 1223 he went to France and assisted in
1 CONT the coronation of Louis VIII, King of France, at Paris. The same year he also
1 CONT visited Henry III, King of England, and received rich gifts from the king and
1 CONT English nobles. In 1228 he commanded the Papal troops that ravaged Emperor
1 CONT Frederick's lands in southern Italy. He was elected Latin Emperor of
1 CONT Constantinople in 1229, as colleague for the minor, Baldwin II. He was crowned
1 CONT Emperor in the Cathedral of St. Sophia in 1231. JEAN I (DE BRIENNE), Emperor-
1 CONT Regent of Constantinople, died at Constantinople 21 March 1237. His widow,
1 CONT Bérengère, died 12 April 1237.
1 CONT John, byname JOHN OF BRIENNE, French JEAN DE BRIENNE (b. c. 1148--d. March
1 CONT 1237, Constantinople), count of Brienne who became titular king of Jerusalem
1 CONT (1210-29) and Latin emperor of Constantinople (1231-37).
1 CONT A penniless younger son of the French count Erard II of Brienne and Agnes of
1 CONT Montbéliard, John passed most of his life as a minor noble until befriended by
1 CONT King Philip II Augustus of France, who arranged for him to marry Mary (Marie)
1 CONT of Montferrat, queen of the crusader state of Jerusalem, in 1210. John reached
1 CONT the Palestinian town of Acre on Sept. 13, 1210, married Mary the following
1 CONT day, and was crowned at Tyre on October 3. Mary died in 1212, and John was
1 CONT named regent for their infant daughter, Yolande de Brienne, who inherited the
1 CONT crown as Isabella II. In 1214 John married Princess Stephanie of Armenia,
1 CONT daughter of the Armenian king Leo II, and later had a son by her.
1 CONT As regent, John arranged a five-year truce with al-Malik al-'Adil, sultan of
1 CONT Egypt and Syria, in July 1212, and during the truce he persuaded Pope Innocent
1 CONT III to launch the Fifth Crusade in support of his daughter's kingdom. In 1218
1 CONT he joined the crusading force from the West in an expedition against the
1 CONT Egyptian port of Damietta. After quarrelling with the crusade leader, the
1 CONT cardinal legate Pelagius, John left Egypt in February 1220, returning in July
1 CONT 1221 to witness the humiliating defeat of the crusaders and the abandonment of
1 CONT the siege of Damietta.
1 CONT Stephanie died in 1219; John then married Berengaria, daughter of Ferdinand
1 CONT III of Castile, and in 1225 gave his daughter Isabella in marriage to the Holy
1 CONT Roman emperor Frederick II, trying to retain his rights as regent of the
1 CONT kingdom of Jerusalem. Immediately following the marriage, however, Frederick
1 CONT began to contest these rights.
1 CONT In 1228 John was invited to Constantinople to be regent and co-emperor with
1 CONT the young Baldwin II and arranged a match between Baldwin and his four-year-
1 CONT old daughter by Berengaria. Crowned in 1231, John helped fend off attacks by
1 CONT the Bulgarian tsar Ivan Asen II and the Nicaean emperor John III Vatatzes, but
1 CONT shortly before his death he was forced to appeal to the West for help.
1 CONT [Encyclopaedia Britannica CD '97]
