0 @N00708@ NOTE geni:about_me KOTEN / KOTIAN, KHAN OF THE CUMANS
1 CONT
1 CONT Khan Koten (Jonas) Sutoiovych, SON OF KHAN KONCHEK. He is Mstislav
1 CONT Mstislavich's father in law. Koten was of the Terteroba (Tertrobichi in
1 CONT Russian) Clan. He participated in the power struggles between the princes of
1 CONT Kyivan Rus' in 1202, 1225, and 1228. After the defeat of the Mongols in 1222,
1 CONT he convinced the princes of Kyivan Rus' to forge an alliance against the
1 CONT Mongols. He fought in the war against the Mongols (allied with the Russians)
1 CONT in the Battle of Kalka River, where the Rus' - Cuman alliance was defeated. In
1 CONT 1238 he was again defeated by Batu Khan on the Astrakhan steppes. Afterwards,
1 CONT Koten led 40,000 "huts" (families -- around 70 - 80,000 people) to Hungary to
1 CONT escape the Mongols. In Hungary, he was later assassinated by the Hungarians
1 CONT and Germans in concert. The Cumans then left Hungary, pillaging along the way
1 CONT and emigrating to the Second Bulgarian Empire. Some of the Cumans were later
1 CONT asked to come back to Hungary and help rebuild it after Mongol devastation. He
1 CONT was possibly the most notable of Cumans, together with Baibars. Koten was from
1 CONT the Terteroba clan that ruled Cumania in the late 11th century, as well as in
1 CONT the mid 13th century.
1 CONT
1 CONT Khan Koten's daughter, married Mstislav Mstislavich, Prince of Halych (r.
1 CONT 1219–1228).
1 CONT
1 CONT Khan Koten's second daughter, married Narjot de Toucy. After her husband died,
1 CONT she became a nun.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------------------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%B6ten>
1 CONT
1 CONT Köten (variously Kutan, Kuthen, Kuthens, Kotyan, Kotjan, Koteny, Kötöny,
1 CONT Kuethan, Zayhan, or Jonas) was a Cuman khan and member of the Terter(oba)
1 CONT clan. This Köten is the same Prince Kotjan Sutoevic of the Russian annals, who
1 CONT forged the Russian-Cuman alliance against the Tatars.
1 CONT
1 CONT ...
1 CONT
1 CONT At the start of Köten's reign the religion of the Kuman-Kipchaks was
1 CONT Tengriism. In 1238 Köten led his tribes into Hungary in flight from the
1 CONT advancing Mongol hordes. In return for their alliance and conversion to
1 CONT Christianity, Bela IV of Hungary granted them asylum.
1 CONT
1 CONT Köten was baptised in 1239 and his daughter Elizabeth married Bela's son, the
1 CONT future Stephen V of Hungary. The Hungarian nobles, however, distrusted the
1 CONT Kuman-Kipchaks and just prior to the disastrous Mongol invasion which led to
1 CONT the rout of Mohi, they had Köten assassinated in Pest. The enraged Kuman-
1 CONT Kipchak masses began to plunder the countryside, and moved southwards in the
1 CONT country. They crossed the Danube and reached Srem (called Marchia by
1 CONT Rogerius). After causing much destruction and havoc in Hungary they left the
1 CONT country for Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Köten left another daughter who married Narjot III de Toucy.
1 CONT
1 CONT \---------
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuman>
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans (Greek: Κο(υ)μάνοι, Ko(u)manoi;[1] Hungarian: kun / plural
1 CONT kunok;[2] Turkic: kuman / plural kumanlar[3], Russian: Половцы - Polovtsi)
1 CONT were a nomadic people who inhabited a shifting area north of the Black Sea
1 CONT known as Cumania along the Volga River. They eventually settled to the west of
1 CONT the Black Sea, influencing the politics of Kievan Rus', Bulgaria, Serbia,
1 CONT Hungary, Moldavia, and Wallachia. Cuman is a separate name to Kipchak; the two
1 CONT nations were not the same, but different - they joined politically to create a
1 CONT confederation known as the Cuman-Kipchak confederation [4]
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans were nomadic warriors of the Eurasian steppe who exerted an
1 CONT enduring impact on the medieval Balkans. The basic instrument of Cuman
1 CONT political success was military force, which none of the warring Balkan
1 CONT factions could resist. As a consequence, groups of the Cumans settled and
1 CONT mingled with the local population in various regions of the Balkans. According
1 CONT to many historians Cumans were the founders of three successive Bulgarian
1 CONT dynasties (Asenids, Terterids, and Shishmanids), and the Wallachian dynasty
1 CONT (Basarabids)."[5] However, in the case of the Basarab dynasty, some Medieval
1 CONT documents refer to them as a Vlach (Romanian) dynasty[6], so some historians
1 CONT attribute a Romanian origin to this dynasty.[7] They also played an active
1 CONT role in Byzantium, Hungary, and Serbia, with Cuman immigrants being integrated
1 CONT into each country's elite.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans were called Folban and Vallani by Germans, Kun (Qoun) by the
1 CONT Hungarians and Polovtsy by the Russians. It is rather confusing to know who
1 CONT historians from the past referred to when the name Kipchak was used - they
1 CONT either referred to the Kumans only, the Kipchaks only or both; this is due to
1 CONT the two nations joining and living together (and possibly exchanging weaponry,
1 CONT culture and with possible fusion of languages). This confederation and them
1 CONT living together might have made it tricky at times for historians to write
1 CONT exclusively about either nation.
1 CONT
1 CONT Etymology
1 CONT
1 CONT A variety of sources from different countries (such as Germany, Hungary and
1 CONT Russia) explain that the different names for the Cumans all pin point to the
1 CONT meaning 'blond', 'sallow' and 'yellow' in reference to the color of the
1 CONT Kumans' hair. The Russian word 'Polovtsy'(Пóловцы) means "blond", since the
1 CONT old Russian word "polovo" means "straw". Another explanation was given by O.
1 CONT Suleymenov as "men of the field, steppe" from the Russian word "pole" - open
1 CONT ground, field, not to be confused with "polyane" (cf. Greek "polis" - city). A
1 CONT third explanation of the word was also made by O. Suleymenov which stated that
1 CONT the name "polovtsy" came from a word for "blue-eyed," since the Serbo-Croatian
1 CONT word "plav" literally means "blue". [citation needed] The German word for
1 CONT Cumans was 'Folban' which also means blond.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Ethnicity
1 CONT
1 CONT Most scholars believe that the Cumans were Turkic, ethnically speaking. This
1 CONT hypothesis is treated almost as proven fact, but there is no definitive
1 CONT evidence to prove that theory. That their language was Turkic does not
1 CONT necessarily prove that the Cumans themselves were Turkic (another case which
1 CONT is similar is that the Bulgarians speak a Slavic language, but they
1 CONT themselves, according to genetic studies, are not fully Slavic; also in a
1 CONT similar context and vein is that Iran uses the Arabic alphabet, while they
1 CONT themselves are not Arabic) To the contrary, another idea is that the Cumans
1 CONT were an Iranic people, this hypothesis being taught in Bulgarian schools. The
1 CONT Turkic theory has a flaw - the problem being that the Cumans were mostly blond
1 CONT (fully documented evidence by a variety of countries proves this), but there
1 CONT aren't many blond Turkic people (blond hair color in Turkic ethnic groups is
1 CONT quite rare; it usually appears when mixture with another ethnic group has
1 CONT occurred, such as Caucasian). That suggests that the Cumans might not have
1 CONT been Turkic; but could rather have been Iranic (there is blond hair among
1 CONT Iranian people). Some researchers also suggests that the Bulgars (who also
1 CONT might have been Iranic, with some elements of Turkic culture) and Cumans were
1 CONT one and the same people, as there were some similarities between them to
1 CONT suggest that.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] History
1 CONT
1 CONT Originally inhabiting eastern China (east of the Hunag He river) [8], they
1 CONT later migrated to the prairies of southern Siberia and northern Kazakhstan.
1 CONT The Cumans entered the grassland of Eastern Europe in the 11th century, from
1 CONT where they continued to assault the Byzantine Empire, the Kingdom of Hungary,
1 CONT and Rus.
1 CONT
1 CONT Ladislaus I of Hungary defeated the Cumans who attacked the Kingdom of Hungary
1 CONT in 1089.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1091 the Pechenegs, a semi-nomadic Turkic people of the prairies of
1 CONT southwestern Eurasia, were decisively defeated as an independent force at the
1 CONT Battle of Levounion by the combined forces of a Byzantine army under Byzantine
1 CONT Emperor Alexios I Komnenos and a Cuman army under Togortok and Bunaq. Attacked
1 CONT again in 1094 by the Cumans, many Pechenegs were again slain. The remnants of
1 CONT the Pechenegs fled to Hungary, as the Cumans themselves would do a few decades
1 CONT later: fearing the Mongol invasion, in 1229, they asked asylum from Béla IV of
1 CONT Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT In alliance with the Bulgarians and Vlachs[9][10] during the Vlach-Bulgar
1 CONT Rebellion by brothers Asen and Peter of Tarnovo, the Cumans are believed to
1 CONT have played a significant role in the rebellion's final victory over Byzantium
1 CONT and the restoration of Bulgaria's independence (1185). [11] The Cumans were
1 CONT allies with Bulgaria's emperor Kaloyan, who was also descended from the
1 CONT Cumans, in the Bulgarian-Latin Wars.
1 CONT
1 CONT Although the Cumans initially had managed to defeat the Great Prince Vladimir
1 CONT Monomakh of Kievan Rus in the 12th century (at the Battle of the Stugna River)
1 CONT later they were defeated by the combined forces of Russian principalities
1 CONT leaded by Monomakh and forced out of the Rus borders to Caucasus. Many Cumans
1 CONT at that time resettled into Georgia were they achieved prominent positions and
1 CONT helped Georgians to stop the advance of Seljuks. After the death of warlike
1 CONT Monomakh in 1125 Cumans returned to the steppe along the Rus borders.
1 CONT
1 CONT Like most other peoples of medieval Eastern Europe, they put up resistance
1 CONT against the relentlessly advancing Mongols, but they were finally crushed in
1 CONT 1238. Previously, in 1229, they had asked for asylum from king Béla IV of
1 CONT Hungary, who in 1238 finally offered refuge to the remainder of the Cuman
1 CONT people under their leader Kuthen (Hungarians spelled his name Kötöny). Kuthen
1 CONT in turn vowed to convert his 40,000 families to Christianity. King Béla hoped
1 CONT to use the new subjects as auxiliary troops against the Mongols, who were
1 CONT already threatening Hungary. The king assigned various parts of central
1 CONT Hungary to the Cuman tribes. A tense situation erupted when Mongol troops
1 CONT burst into Hungary. The Hungarians, frustrated by their own helplessness, took
1 CONT revenge on the Cumans, whom they accused of being Mongol spies. After a bloody
1 CONT fight the Hungarians killed Kuthen and his bodyguards, and the remaining
1 CONT Cumans fled to the Balkans. After the Mongol invasion Béla IV of Hungary
1 CONT recalled the Cumans to Hungary to populate settlements devastated by war. The
1 CONT nomads subsequently settled throughout the Great Hungarian Plain. Throughout
1 CONT the following centuries the Cumans in Hungary were granted various rights, the
1 CONT extent of which depended on the prevailing political situation. Some of these
1 CONT rights survived until the end of the 19th century, although the Cumans had
1 CONT long since assimilated with Hungarians.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans who remained scattered in the prairie of what is now southwest
1 CONT Russia joined the Golden Horde khanate and their descendants became
1 CONT assimilated with local Tatar populations.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans who remained east and south of the Carpathian Mountains established
1 CONT a country named Cumania, in an area consisting of Moldavia and Walachia. The
1 CONT Hungarian kings claimed supremacy on the territory of Cumania, among the nine
1 CONT titles of the Hungarian kings of the Árpád and Anjou dynasties were rex
1 CONT Cumaniae.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cuman influence in Wallachia and Moldavia was very strong, according to
1 CONT some historians who claim that the earliest Wallachian rulers bore Cuman names
1 CONT (Tihomir and Bassarab). This hypothesis is though disputed. In lack of
1 CONT convincing archaeological evidence of a Cuman civilisation, it appears the
1 CONT Cumans were just a minority within the local population, but they made up part
1 CONT of the ruling elite in Wallachia. As in the case of Bulgaria, they were
1 CONT assimilated by the majority, the present-day Romanians.
1 CONT
1 CONT Basarab I, son of the Wallachian prince Tihomir of Wallachia obtained
1 CONT independence from Hungary at the beginning of the 14th century. The name
1 CONT Basarab is considered by some authors as being of Cuman origin, and meaning
1 CONT "Father King".
1 CONT
1 CONT It is generally believed by Bulgarian historians that the Bulgarian mediaеval
1 CONT dynasties Asen, Shishman and Terter were Cumanian.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Caucasian mummies found in China a while ago could have been Cumans, as it
1 CONT is stated that the Cumans originally came from eastern China before migrating
1 CONT to Europe [12].
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Ethnicity
1 CONT
1 CONT Most scholars believe that the Cumans were Turkic, ethnically speaking. This
1 CONT hypothesis is treated almost as proven fact, but there is no definitive
1 CONT evidence to prove that theory. That their language was Turkic does not
1 CONT necessarily prove that the Cumans themselves were Turkic (another case which
1 CONT is similar is that the Bulgarians speak a Slavic language, but they
1 CONT themselves, according to genetic studies, are not fully Slavic; also in a
1 CONT similar context and vein is that Iran uses the Arabic alphabet, while they
1 CONT themselves are not Arabic) To the contrary, another idea is that the Cumans
1 CONT were an Iranic people, this hypothesis being taught in Bulgarian schools. The
1 CONT Turkic theory has a flaw - the problem being that the Cumans were mostly blond
1 CONT (fully documented evidence by a variety of countries proves this), but there
1 CONT aren't many blond Turkic people (blond hair color in Turkic ethnic groups is
1 CONT quite rare; it usually appears when mixture with another ethnic group has
1 CONT occurred, such as Caucasian). That suggests that the Cumans might not have
1 CONT been Turkic; but could rather have been Iranic (there is blond hair among
1 CONT Iranian people). Some researchers also suggests that the Bulgars (who also
1 CONT might have been Iranic, with some elements of Turkic culture) and Cumans were
1 CONT one and the same people, as there were some similarities between them to
1 CONT suggest that.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Culture
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert de Clari described Cumans as nomadic warriors, who did not use houses,
1 CONT or farm, but rather lived in tents, and ate milk, cheese and meat. The horses
1 CONT had a sack for feeding attached to the bridle, and in a day and a night they
1 CONT can ride seven days of walking (Mansio), they go on campaign without any
1 CONT baggage, and when they return they take everything they can carry, they wear
1 CONT sheepskin and were armed with composite bows and arrows. They pray to the
1 CONT first animal they see in the morning.[13][14] The Cumans, like the Bulgars,
1 CONT were also known to drink blood from their horse (they would cut a vein) when
1 CONT they ran out of water and were far from an available source. Another
1 CONT interesting feature of the Cumans was their elaborate masks which they used in
1 CONT battle (they were shaped like and worn over the face. Some of the masks had
1 CONT mustaches).
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Religion
1 CONT
1 CONT In the 13th century, the Western Cumans adopted Roman Catholicism (in Hungary
1 CONT they all(all of them?) later became Calvinist) and the Gagauzes
1 CONT Pravoslav/Orthodox, while the Eastern Cumans converted to Islam. The Catholic
1 CONT Diocese of Cumania founded in Milcov in 1227 and including what is now Romania
1 CONT and Moldova, retained its title until 1523. It was a suffragan of the
1 CONT Archdiocese of Esztergom in Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Legacy
1 CONT
1 CONT While the Cumans were gradually absorbed into eastern European populations,
1 CONT their trace can still be found in place names as widespread as the city of
1 CONT Kumanovo in the Northeastern part of the Republic of Macedonia; a Slavic
1 CONT village named Kumanichevo in the Kostur (Kastoria) district of Greece, which
1 CONT was changed to Lithia after Greece obtained this territory in the 1913 Treaty
1 CONT of Bucharest, Comăneşti in Romania, Comana in Dobruja (also Romania) and the
1 CONT small village of Kumanite in Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT As the Mongols pushed westwards and devastated their state, most of the Cumans
1 CONT fled to the Bulgarian Empire as they were major military allies. The Bulgarian
1 CONT Tsar Ivan-Asen II (who was descended from Cumans) settled them in the southern
1 CONT parts of the country, bordering the Latin Empire and the Thessallonikan
1 CONT Despotate. [citation needed] Those territories are present-day Turkish Europe
1 CONT and the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia. [citation needed] The Cumans
1 CONT also settled in Hungary and had their own self-government there in a territory
1 CONT that bore their name, Kunság, that survived until the 19th century. There, the
1 CONT name of the Cumans (Kun) is still preserved in county names such as Bács-
1 CONT Kiskun and Jász-Nagykun-Szolnok and town names such as Kiskunhalas and
1 CONT Kunszentmiklós.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans were organized into four tribes in Hungary: Kolbasz/Olas in the big
1 CONT Cumania around Karcag, and the other three in the lesser Cumania.
1 CONT
1 CONT Unfortunately, the Cuman language disappeared from Hungary in the 17th
1 CONT century, possibly following the Turkish occupation. Their 19th century
1 CONT biographer, Gyárfás István, in 1870 was of the opinion that they originally
1 CONT spoke Hungarian, together with the Iazyges population. Despite this mistake,
1 CONT he has the best overview on the subject concerning details of material used.
1 CONT
1 CONT In addition, toponyms of Cuman language origin can be found especially in the
1 CONT Romanian counties of Vaslui and Galaţi, including the names of both counties.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the countries where the Cumans were assimilated, family surnames derived
1 CONT from the words for "Cuman" (such as coman or kun, "kuman") are not uncommon.
1 CONT Traces of the Cumans are the Bulgarian surnames Kunev or Kumanov (feminine
1 CONT Kuneva, Kumanova), its Macedonian variants Kunevski, Kumanovski (feminine
1 CONT Kumanovska), and the widespread Hungarian surname Kun. This name was also used
1 CONT as a magyarized version of the Jewish-German name Kohn/Cohen, like for the
1 CONT communist leader Béla Kun. The names "Coman" in Romania and its derivatives
1 CONT however do not appear to have any connection to the medieval Cumans, as it was
1 CONT unrecorded until very recent times and the places with the highest frequency
1 CONT of such names has not produced any archaeological evidence of Cuman
1 CONT settlement.[15]
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans appear in Rus culture in the The Tale of Igor's Campaign and are
1 CONT the Rus' military enemies in Alexander Borodin's opera Prince Igor, which
1 CONT features a set of "Polovtsian Dances".
1 CONT
1 CONT The name Cuman is still the name of several villages in different parts of
1 CONT Turkey, including the Black Sea region.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Köten (variously Kutan, Kuthen, Kuthens, Kotyan, Kotjan, Koteny, Kötöny,
1 CONT Kuethan, Zayhan, or Jonas) was a Kipchak khan and member of the Terter(oba)
1 CONT clan. Kipchaks were a Turkic people also called Cumans by the Byzantines, Kun
1 CONT by the Hungarians, and Polovtsy by the Russians. This Köten is the same Prince
1 CONT Kotjan Sutoevic of the Russian annals, who forged the Russian-Cuman alliance
1 CONT against the Tatars. Kipchaks under Köten and a Russian army of 80,000 men
1 CONT under his son-in-law Mstislav -the Bold- of Galich fought a battle against a
1 CONT Mongol assault led by Jebe and Sübötäi. The action took place near the Kalka
1 CONT or Kalmius, a small coastal river flowing into the Sea of Azov near Mariupol.
1 CONT The prince of Galich and the Kipchaks were routed and had to flee (May 31,
1 CONT 1222). Köten was deposed from power in that year, but he remained leader of
1 CONT the clan.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the early spring of 1237, the Mongols attacked the Kuman-Kipchaks. Some of
1 CONT the Kuman-Kipchaks surrendered; it was this element that was later to form the
1 CONT ethnic and geographic basis of the Mongol khanate known to the former lords of
1 CONT the country as the "Kipchak khanate". Known also as the Golden Horde, the
1 CONT Kipchak khanate belonged to one of the branches of Jochi’s house -Genghis
1 CONT Khan’s eldest son. A Kipchak chief named Batchman lay in hiding for some time
1 CONT on the banks of the Volga, but was captured at last on an island in the lower
1 CONT part of the river (winter 1236-37). Möngke had him cut in half. According to
1 CONT the evidence of Rashid al-Din, Berke led a third campaign in 1238 which
1 CONT inflicted final defeat on the Kipchaks. It was then that the Kipchak chief
1 CONT Köten emigrated with forty thousand "huts" to Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the start of Köten's reign the religion of the Kuman-Kipchaks was
1 CONT Tengriism. In 1238 Köten led his tribes into Hungary in flight from the
1 CONT advancing Mongol hordes. In return for their alliance and conversion to
1 CONT Christianity, Bela IV of Hungary granted them asylum. Köten was baptised in
1 CONT 1239 and his daughter Elizabeth married Bela's son, the future Stephen V of
1 CONT Hungary. Elizabeth's mother was a Russian princess of the family de Halicz,
1 CONT whose first name is not known.The Hungarian nobles, however, distrusted the
1 CONT Kuman-Kipchaks and just prior to the disastrous Mongol invasion which led to
1 CONT the route of Mohi, they had Köten assassinated in Pest. The enraged Kuman-
1 CONT Kipchak masses began to plunder the countryside, and moved southwards in the
1 CONT country. They crossed the Danube and reached Srem (called Marchia by
1 CONT Rogerius). After causing much destruction and havoc in Hungary they left the
1 CONT country for Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT Köten left another daughter who married Narjot III de Toucy.
1 CONT
1 CONT According to Rogenus' description the Kuman-Kipchaks' last halt in Hungary was
1 CONT Srem, a territory between the Danube and the Sava, so the first Bulgarian
1 CONT territories they entered must have been Branicevo and Vidin. This supposition
1 CONT is in perfect agreement with our knowledge of the later history of these
1 CONT regions. The Bulgarian boyar families, the Şişmans in Vidin and Dormans in
1 CONT Braniċevo, were of Kuman-Kipchak extraction, and must have settled in these
1 CONT regions after the large immigration of 1241. Köten's relatives and the leading
1 CONT figures of his royal clan settled in Bulgaria.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
