1 CONT <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_people_of_Cuman_descent>
1 CONT
1 CONT Khan Köten Sutoiovych (Kuthen/Kotian/Kotony/Zayhan or Jonas), son of Khan
1 CONT Konchek.[6] He is Mstislav Mstislavich's father-in-law. Köten was of the
1 CONT Terteroba clan. He participated in the power struggles between the princes of
1 CONT Kyivan Rus' in 1202, 1225 and 1228. After the defeat by the Mongols in 1222,
1 CONT he convinced the princes of Kyivan Rus' to forge an alliance against the
1 CONT Mongols. He fought in the war against the Mongols (allied with the Russians)
1 CONT in the Battle of Kalka River, where the Rus'-Cuman alliance was defeated. In
1 CONT 1238 he was again defeated by Batu Khan on the Astrakhan steppes.[7]
1 CONT Afterwards, Koten led 40,000 "huts" (families) (around 70 - 80,000 people) to
1 CONT Hungary (to escape from the Mongols), where he was later assassinated by the
1 CONT Hungarian and Germans in concert. The Cumans then left Hungary, pillaging
1 CONT along the way and emigrated to the Second Bulgarian Empire. Some of the Cumans
1 CONT were later asked to come back to Hungary and help rebuild it after Mongol
1 CONT devastation. He was possibly the most notable of Cumans (together with
1 CONT Baibars). Koten was from the Terteroba clan that ruled Cumania in the late
1 CONT 11th century, as well as in the mid-13th century.[8]
1 CONT
