1 CONT Cumans
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Cumans, also called Polovtsy, Polovtsians, or the Anglicized Polovzians
1 CONT (Russian: ??????? Polovcy, Ukrainian: ??????i Polovci, Romanian: Cumani,
1 CONT Hungarian: Kunok), is a Western European exonym for the western Kipchaks.
1 CONT
1 CONT Cuman steppe art, as exibited in Dnepropetrovsk.Cumans were a nomadic, West
1 CONT Turkic tribe who inhabited a shifting area north of the Black Sea, along the
1 CONT Volga River known as Cumania.
1 CONT
1 CONT Contents [hide]
1 CONT 1 History
1 CONT 2 Legacy
1 CONT 3 Further reading
1 CONT 4 See also
1 CONT 5 External links
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] History
1 CONT The Cumans entered the lands of present-day southern Ukraine, as well as
1 CONT historic Moldavia, Wallachia, and part of Transylvania, in the 11th century.
1 CONT Having conquered the area, they continued their assaults by attacking and
1 CONT plundering the Byzantine Empire, the Kingdom of Hungary, and the principality
1 CONT of Kievan Rus'.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1089, they were defeated by Ladislaus I of Hungary. In alliance with the
1 CONT Vlachs and the Bulgarians during the Vlach-Bulgar Rebellion by brothers Asen
1 CONT and Peter of Tarnovo, the Cumans are believed to have played a significant
1 CONT role in the rebellion's final victory over Byzantium and the restoration of
1 CONT Bulgaria's independence (1185). The Cumans suffered a severe defeat by Great
1 CONT Prince Vladimir Monomakh of Kievan Rus in the 12th century (at the Battle of
1 CONT the Stugna River) and were crushed by the Mongols in 1238, after which most of
1 CONT them fled Wallachia and Moldova and took refuge in Hungary, Bulgaria, and the
1 CONT Byzantine Empire. After many clashes with the Hungarians, the Cumans were
1 CONT eventually evicted from Hungary to join their kin who lived in Bulgaria.
1 CONT Later, however, a large segment of them were re-invited back to Hungary. The
1 CONT Cumans who remained scattered in the steppe of what is now Russia joined the
1 CONT Golden Horde khanate.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the 13th century, the Western Cumans adopted Roman Catholicism, while the
1 CONT Eastern Cumans converted to Islam. The Catholic Diocese of the Cumania founded
1 CONT in Milcov in 1227 and including what is now Romania and Moldova, retained its
1 CONT title until 1523.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cuman influence in the region of Wallachia and Moldavia was so strong that
1 CONT the earliest Wallachian rulers bore Cuman names. But, given that the rulers
1 CONT Tihomir and Bassarab I governed territories formerly ruled by Romanian leaders
1 CONT (mentioned in the Diploma of the Joannites of 1247), and given that there is
1 CONT no archeological evidence to sustain the continuous presence of a Cuman
1 CONT population (only Hungarian documents mentioning a toll-paying Wallachian
1 CONT population), most historians have concluded that the two rulers were, like the
1 CONT population they governed, Romanian.
1 CONT
1 CONT Basarab I, son of the Wallachian prince Tihomir of Wallachia obtained
1 CONT independence from Hungary at the beginning of the 14th century. The name
1 CONT Basarab is considered as being of Cuman origin, meaning "Father King".
1 CONT
1 CONT Cuman influence also persisted in the Kingdom of Hungary with the Cuman
1 CONT language and customs persisting in autonomous Cuman territories (Kunság) until
1 CONT the 17th century.
1 CONT
1 CONT It is generally believed that the Bulgarian media?val dynasties Asen, Shishman
1 CONT and Terter had some Cumans' roots.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Legacy
1 CONT The field of Igor Svyatoslavich's battle with the Kypchaks, by Viktor
1 CONT Vasnetsov.While the Cumans in Europe have been assimilated into other
1 CONT population groups, their name can still be encountered in placenames as far as
1 CONT the city of Kumanovo in the Northeastern part of the Republic of Macedonia,
1 CONT Comanesti in Romania and Comana in Dobruja. The Cumans settled in Hungary had
1 CONT their own self-government there in a territory that bore their name, Kunság,
1 CONT that survived until the 19th century. There, the name of the Cumans (Kun) is
1 CONT still preserved in county names such as Bács-Kiskun and Jász-Nagykun-Szolnok
1 CONT and town names such as Kiskunhalas and Kiskunszentmiklós.
1 CONT
1 CONT Also, toponyms of Cuman language origin can be found especially in the
1 CONT Romanian counties of Vaslui and Galati, including the names of both counties.
1 CONT
1 CONT In the countries where the Cumans were assimilated, family surnames derived
1 CONT from the words for "Cuman" (such as coman or kun, "kuman") are not uncommon.
1 CONT Among the people that have such a name are Romanian gymnast Nadia Comaneci,
1 CONT Romanian poet Otilia Coman (Ana Blandiana) and Romanian football player Gigel
1 CONT Coman. Traces of the Cumans are also the Bulgarian surname Kumanov (feminine
1 CONT Kumanova), its Macedonian variant Kumanovski (feminine Kumanovska) and the
1 CONT widespread Hungarian surname Kun.
1 CONT
1 CONT The Cumans appear in Russian culture in the The Tale of Igor's Campaign and a
1 CONT set of "Polovtsian Dances" in Alexander Borodin's opera Prince Igor.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Further reading
1 CONT Vasary, Istvan (2005) "Cumans and Tatars", Cambridge University Press.
