1 CONT Maria of Montferrat
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Montferrat, Queen of Jerusalem (1192 – 1212) was the daughter of
1 CONT Conrad of Montferrat and Isabella, Queen of Jerusalem. Her father was murdered
1 CONT on 28 April 1192 in Tyre by the Hashshashin. Her mother married Henry II of
1 CONT Champagne on 5 May, when already noticeably pregnant (The Old French
1 CONT Continuation of William of Tyre and Imad ad-Din al-Isfahani remarked on this).
1 CONT Maria was thus born posthumously.
1 CONT
1 CONT On her mother's death in 1205, Maria became Queen of Jerusalem, aged thirteen.
1 CONT Her mother's half-brother John of Ibelin, Lord of Beirut, acted as regent for
1 CONT Maria.
1 CONT
1 CONT On September 14, 1210, Maria married John of Brienne (c. 1150–1237) in Acre in
1 CONT an arranged marriage. Their daughter Yolande of Jerusalem (also known as
1 CONT Isabella) was born in 1212, but Maria died shortly after, probably from
1 CONT puerperal fever. John became regent for his daughter Yolande, now Queen of
1 CONT Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria's line died out in 1268, when her great-grandson Conrad III of Jerusalem
1 CONT was executed in Southern Italy. After that, her next half-sister's (Alice of
1 CONT Champagne's) descendants became heirs-general of Queen Isabella of Jerusalem.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_of_Montferrat>
1 CONT
1 CONT Maria of Montferrat (or Maria of Jerusalem) (1192–1212) was Queen of
1 CONT Jerusalem, the daughter of Conrad of Montferrat and Isabella, Queen of
1 CONT Jerusalem. She was known in her youth as The Marquise, because of her father's
1 CONT title.
1 CONT
1 CONT On April 28, 1192, while the rivalry between Guy de Lusignan and Maria's
1 CONT father was about to find a term and Richard I of England was about to finish
1 CONT Third Crusade and return to England, Conrad was assassinated. Her mother
1 CONT remarried in haste on May 5 to Henry II, Count of Champagne, nephew of King
1 CONT Richard and Philip II of France. At the time of the wedding, Isabella was
1 CONT already visibly pregnant with Maria. Maria, the posthumous child was born
1 CONT during the summer of 1192.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry II of Champagne died in 1197, from this marriage Maria had gained three
1 CONT half-sisters. Amalric II of Cyprus married Isabella, he became joint ruler of
1 CONT Jerusalem with Isabella. He died on April 1, 1205. Isabella died shortly
1 CONT thereafter and Marie became queen of Jerusalem, at the age of thirteen, while
1 CONT her stepbrother Hugh, from the first marriage of Amalric, became King of
1 CONT Cyprus and married Maria's half-sister, Alice of Champagne. The half-brother
1 CONT of her mother, John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut, acted as regent on
1 CONT behalf of Maria, wisely and to the satisfaction of the inhabitants of the
1 CONT kingdoms. Failing to conduct operations to reconquer the territories lost in
1 CONT 1187, he maintained the kingdom within its limits, a policy of peace with Al-
1 CONT Adil I, brother of Saladin, who had come to his estate by eliminating the
1 CONT other heirs[2].
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1209, Maria was seventeen and the regency expired, so the government
1 CONT believed it best for Maria to marry so she could secure her post as queen. The
1 CONT assembly of barons and prelates decided to seek advice from Philip II of
1 CONT France, who offered one of his followers, John of Brienne. However John was
1 CONT not a very rich man. To overcome his lack of fortune and to enable him to fund
1 CONT his sovereign obligations (court and army) King Philip and Pope Innocent III
1 CONT each paid him the sum of 40 000 livres[3].
1 CONT
1 CONT The marriage was celebrated on September 4, 1210, then the couple were crowned
1 CONT King and Queen of Jerusalem on October 3, 1210 in Tyre Cathedral. John
1 CONT continued the peace policy of John of Ibelin. In 1212, Maria of Montferrat
1 CONT gave birth to a daughter, Isabelle (1212–1228) or Yolande, but died shortly
1 CONT afterwards, probably from puerperal fever. John retained the crown but only as
1 CONT regent on behalf of his daughter who married (in 1225) to Frederick II, Holy
1 CONT Roman Emperor.
1 CONT
1 CONT The lineage of Maria died out in 1268, with the death of her great-grand-
1 CONT grandson Conradin (or Conrad III of Jerusalem). He was executed in southern
1 CONT Italy on the orders of Charles of Anjou, who took the Kingdom of Sicily. After
1 CONT him, the descendants of Maria's younger half-sister (Alice of Champagne)
1 CONT inherit her kingdom.
1 CONT Died during labor, child bearing.
