1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amadeus_IV,_Count_of_Savoy>
1 CONT
1 CONT **Amadeus IV** (1197 – June 24 or July 13, 1253) was Count of Savoy from 1233
1 CONT to 1253.
1 CONT
1 CONT The legitimate heir of Thomas I of Savoy and Marguerite of Geneva, he had
1 CONT however to fight with his brothers for the inheritance of Savoy lands after
1 CONT their father's death. His brothers Pietro and Aimone spurred a revolt in Aosta
1 CONT Valley against Amadeus, but he was able to crush it with the help of Manfred
1 CONT III of Saluzzo and Boniface II of Montferrat, who were his sons-in-law.
1 CONT Together with his brother Thomas, he fought against the communes of Turin and
1 CONT Pinerolo, but with uncertain results.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was succeeded by his young son Boniface, who died soon. Child of Count
1 CONT Amadeus & Princess Ana is Count of Savoy - Aimon, born 15 Dec 1291, died Jun
1 CONT 22, 1343:married Princess of Montfierrat, Yolande 01, May 1330
1 CONT
1 CONT Child of Count Aimon and Princess Yolande is Count of Savoy Amadeus VI, born
1 CONT 94 Jan. 1333/34 died 01 March 1382/83, married Bonne De Bourbon
1 CONT
1 CONT Family and children
1 CONT
1 CONT He married twice, and each marriage produced children
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * c. 1217,[11] he married Marguerite of Burgundy, daughter of Hugh III, Duke of Burgundy.
1 CONT
1 CONT     * Beatrice of Savoy (d. 1258), married firstly in 1233 Manfred III of Saluzzo (d. 1244),[12] married secondly on 21 April 1247 Manfred of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT     * Margaret of Savoy (d. 1254), married firstly on 9 December 1235 Boniface II of Montferrat, married secondly Aymar III, Count of Valentinois
1 CONT
1 CONT   * on 18 Dec 1244, he married Cecilia of Baux, "Passerose", daughter of Barral of Baux[13]
1 CONT
1 CONT     * Boniface, Count of Savoy
1 CONT
1 CONT     * Beatrice of Savoy (1250 – 23 February 1292) married Peter of Chalon and Infante Manuel of Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT     * Eleonor of Savoy, married in 1269 Guichard de Beaujeu
1 CONT
1 CONT     * Constance of Savoy, died after 1263
1 CONT
1 CONT \-----
1 CONT
1 CONT [<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#AmedeeIVdied1253> **From
1 CONT Medlands:** ]
1 CONT
1 CONT **AMEDEE de Savoie** (Montmélian, Savoie 1197-Montmélian 13 Jul 1253, bur
1 CONT Abbaye de Hautecombe). "Thomas comes Sabaud. et Amedeus eius filius" granted
1 CONT rights to the abbey of San Marco by charter dated 5 Mar 1200[277]. His
1 CONT parentage is confirmed by, inter alia, Matthew of Paris who specifies that
1 CONT Beatrix de Savoie was "soror comitis Sabaldiæ adhuc viventis Amidei", when he
1 CONT records the marriage of her daughter to Henry III King of England[278]. In a
1 CONT later passage, the same source records Amedée as "primogenitus" among the
1 CONT "filii comitis Sabaudiæ Thomæ avunculi dominæ reginæ Angliæ Alienoræ"[279].
1 CONT "Thomas Maurianensis comes et marchio" donated property to the abbey of Saint-
1 CONT Maurice, with the consent of "filiis suis Amedeo et Humberto", by charter
1 CONT dated 8 Nov 1217[280]. A charter dated 1224 records an agreement between
1 CONT "Thomæ com. Sabaud " and the bishop of Sion, witnessed by "ipse Thomas comes,
1 CONT Amedeus primogenitus illius, Comitissa uxor Thomæ, eorum quatuor filii
1 CONT clerici…Willelmus, Thomas, Petrus et Bonifacius"[281]. "M. comitissa Maurian.
1 CONT uxor Thomæ comitis Maurianensis et marchionis Italiæ" donated property, with
1 CONT the consent of "Thomas com. Maurianæ et filii mei Amedeus et Aymo", by charter
1 CONT dated Dec 1227[282]. "M. comitissa Sabaudie et marchisa in Ytalia et…Amedeus,
1 CONT Aymo, W. electus Valentinus, Thomas, Petrus, Bonifacius et Philippus filii
1 CONT Thome Comitis Sab. et marchionis in Ytalia" confirmed donations to Hautecombe
1 CONT abbey by charter dated 26 Feb 1231[283]. "Beatrix uxor comitis Thomæ, Amadeus
1 CONT primogenitus et Aymo filii eius" confirmed the purchase of Chambéry by "Thoma
1 CONT comite" by charter dated 1232, with the seal of "Beatricis comitisse
1 CONT Sabaudie"[284]. He succeeded his father in 1233 as AMEDEE IV Comte de Savoie,
1 CONT Marchese in Italy. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie et in Italia marchio" confirmed his
1 CONT father´s grant of privileges to Susa by charter dated 7 Mar 1233[285]. A
1 CONT charter dated 23 Jul 1234 records an agreement between "Amedeum comitem
1 CONT Sabaudie" and "Aymonem et Petrum fratres ipsius" in settlement of a dispute
1 CONT concerning their paternal inheritance[286]. The first testament of "Amedei
1 CONT comitis Sab. et marchionis Italie", dated 23 Sep 1235, appoints "Thomam
1 CONT fratrem suum" as his heir "in comitatu et marchionatu" in default of male
1 CONT children[287]. This document disinherits Thomas´s older brother Aimon. The
1 CONT second testament of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie", dated 19 Jul 1238, repeats the
1 CONT nomination of "Thomam fratrem suum" as his heir, substituting "Philippum, huic
1 CONT autem Petrum fratres suos" if Thomas died without male heirs[288]. He was an
1 CONT active supporter of Emperor Friedrich II. He acquired territories in Vaud and
1 CONT lower Valais. In 1238, Comte Amedée was created Duc de Chablais and Aosta, and
1 CONT nominated Imperial Vicar in northern Italy, by the emperor in reward for his
1 CONT support against the Lombards[289]. Under a third testament, dated 2 Nov 1240,
1 CONT "Amadeus com Sab. et marchio in Italia" repeated the nomination of "Thomæ,
1 CONT Flandriæ comiti, fratri suo" as his heir to "totius comitatus sui Sabaudiæ
1 CONT marchionatus Italiæ et ducatus Chablasii" if he died without male children, on
1 CONT condition that he satisfied all the debts of "Thomæ comitis patris et Humberti
1 CONT fratris ipsorum"[290]. A charter dated 1244 confirmed the peace agreement
1 CONT reached between the bishop of Lausanne and "Amadeus comes Sabaudie et in
1 CONT Italia marcho et…Petrus de Sabaudia…frater suus"[291]. Emperor Friedrich II
1 CONT recognised Amedée's rights over Turin in 1248. On the emperor's death in 1250,
1 CONT Comte Amedée's reconciliation with Pope Innocent IV was sealed by the marriage
1 CONT of the Pope's niece to Comte Amedée's brother Thomas[292]. A fourth testament
1 CONT of "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium
1 CONT meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting
1 CONT "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam
1 CONT Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii
1 CONT marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea
1 CONT minor"[293]. A fifth testament of Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253,
1 CONT appoints "Bonifacius filius suus, sub tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir,
1 CONT substitutes "filiæ Amedei comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et
1 CONT Margaretha Montisferrati", bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ
1 CONT comitissæ", and chooses to be buried at Hautecombe[294]. An epitaph in
1 CONT Hautecombe abbey records the death "III Id Jul" in 1253 of "Dominus
1 CONT Amedeus…comes Sabaudie"[295].
1 CONT
1 CONT Betrothed (28 Apr 1213) to **AGNESE di Saluzzo** , daughter of BONIFAZIO
1 CONT Marchese di Saluzzo & his wife Maria di Torres [in Sardinia] (-after 1219).
1 CONT The marriage contract between "Thomam comitem Maurienne…Amedeo f. dicti
1 CONT comitis" and "Manfredum II marchionem de Saluciis…Agnetem f. quondam
1 CONT Bonefacii" is dated 28 Apr 1213[296].
1 CONT
1 CONT m firstly (before 1221) **MARGUERITE de Bourgogne** , daughter of HUGUES III
1 CONT Duke of Burgundy [Capet] & his second wife Béatrix Dauphine de Viennois
1 CONT ([1192]-[1228/30] or [1242]). The testament of "Guigo Dalphinus, Vienn. et
1 CONT Albonis comitis", dated 27 Jun 1267, confirmed donations made by "…matertera
1 CONT Margarita vel Domina Ducissa avia mea…meæ amitæ quondam comitissæ
1 CONT Sabaudiæ"[297]. It is not clear from this document whether "matertera
1 CONT Margarita" and "meæ amitæ quondam comitissæ Sabaudiæ" refer to the same person
1 CONT as they are named in the context of two separate donations in different parts
1 CONT of the testament. The use of "matertera" and "amitæ" as two different terms to
1 CONT express the relationship "aunt" suggests that they may have been different
1 CONT individuals. Valbonnais assumes that they were the same person, "Marguerite
1 CONT sœur du dauphin André" who married "Amé fils de Thomas Comte de Savoie", and
1 CONT adds that "la duchesse Beatrix" named "son héritier le Dauphin André son
1 CONT fils…Matilde sa fille aînée femme de Jean Comte de Chalon…Marguerite son autre
1 CONT fille épouse d´Amedée fils du comte de Savoye" in her testament dated
1 CONT 1228[298]. If the suggested second marriage of Comte Amedée is correctly shown
1 CONT below, Marguerite de Bourgogne must have died in [1228/30]. If it is
1 CONT incorrect, her date of death is estimated to [1242].
1 CONT
1 CONT [m secondly ([1228/30]) **MARGUERITE de Viennois** , daughter of ANDRE de
1 CONT Bourgogne [Capet] Comte d´Albon, Dauphin & his first wife Beatrix de Sabran
1 CONT ([1203/07]-[1242]). The Inventory of the State Archives of Turin[299] mentions
1 CONT a document dated 1230 which refers to the marriage of Comte Amedée with
1 CONT "Marguerite daughter of André dauphin, comte de Viennois", but without giving
1 CONT the context (marriage contract, appointment of proxy etc.). Although her
1 CONT mother is not named, the date of the document suggests that it is likely that
1 CONT Marguerite would have been born from her supposed father's first marriage.
1 CONT However, there is some doubt whether this reference can be correct. As noted
1 CONT above, two primary sources indicate that Comte Amedée IV married Marguerite de
1 CONT Bourgogne as his first wife, one source indicating that she was still alive in
1 CONT 1228. Marguerite de Viennois would therefore have been the niece of Comte
1 CONT Amedée´s first wife. Such a relationship by marriage would have necessitated a
1 CONT papal dispensation, which may not have been easily obtained given the
1 CONT closeness of the affinity. In addition, this supposed second marriage would
1 CONT have taken place during the papacy of Pope Gregory IX, who is recorded as
1 CONT granting only 11 dispensations during his 14 year reign (6 of which related to
1 CONT validating existing marriages), which suggests that he was "averse to
1 CONT dispensing from the impediments of relationship"[300]. Another possibility is
1 CONT that the Inventory of State Archives mistook "daughter" for "sister" in its
1 CONT extract, and that the 1230 document refers to Comte Amedée´s earlier marriage
1 CONT to Marguerite de Bourgogne. Since writing the above comment, an updated
1 CONT version of the online State Archives Inventory now suggests that this
1 CONT possibility may be correct: while the new summary still refers to “Matrimoni.
1 CONT Amedeo IV di Savoia e Margherita figlia di Andrea Delfino conte di Vienna”, a
1 CONT further extract states that the document records that “Margherita di Vienne”
1 CONT gave receipt “al fratello Andrea Delfino di Vienne” for the sum bequeathed to
1 CONT her “in testamento dalla madre Beatrice contessa di Vienne”[301]. The original
1 CONT document has not been consulted to verify how this conflict is resolved.
1 CONT Altogether, this possible second marriage, based only on this index entry, now
1 CONT looks unlikely to be correct.] m [secondly/thirdly] (contract 22 Nov 1244, by
1 CONT proxy Orange 18 Dec 1244) CECILE des Baux, daughter of BARRAL Seigneur des
1 CONT Baux & his wife Béatrice d'Anduze (-21 May 1275). The contract of marriage
1 CONT between "Amedeum comitem Sabaudiæ" and "Cæciliam Barralis domini Baucii
1 CONT filiam" is dated 18 Dec 1243, witnessed by "Humbertum de Seyssel dominum
1 CONT Aquarum…Raymundo de Baucio principe Aurasiæ, Guillelmo de Baucio nepote
1 CONT illius…"[302]. A charter dated 22 Nov 1244 records the agreement for the
1 CONT marriage of “dominum Amedeum comitem Sabaudie” and “dominam Ceciliam,
1 CONT neptem…domini R. comitis Tolosani, filiam…domini Barralli del Bauz”[303]. A
1 CONT charter dated 18 Dec 1244 confirms the celebration by proxy of the marriage
1 CONT between "Amedée IV Comte de Savoie, marquis d'Italie" (represented by "Humbert
1 CONT de Seyssel") and "Cécile fille de Barral de Baux" at the "chapelle Sainte-
1 CONT Marie d'Orange", in the presence of "Raymond de Baux I, son neveu Raymond II
1 CONT prince et co-prince d'Orange, Guillaume de Sabran, et B. de Baux chanoine
1 CONT d'Avignon"[304]. Raymond VII Comte de Toulouse, Marquis de Provence granted
1 CONT all his property beyond the Rhône to "sa niece Cécile de Baux, fille de
1 CONT Barral" by charter dated 24 Feb 1241[305], which may explain why Cécile was
1 CONT such a good marriage prospect for the comte de Savoie. A fourth testament of
1 CONT "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" is dated 19 Sep 1252, appoints "Bonifacium filium
1 CONT meum" as his heir, under the tutelage of his brother Thomas, substituting
1 CONT "fratri meo Thome de Sabaudia comitis…Beatricem filiam meam uxorem quondam
1 CONT Manfredi marchionis Salutiarum et Margaretam filiam meam uxorem Bonifacii
1 CONT marchionis Montisferrati", and names "Cecilie…uxori nostre…Beatrix filia mea
1 CONT minor"[306]. Her husband granted her the castles of Momigliano, La Rocchetta,
1 CONT e Terra della Tarantasia for life by charter dated 24 May 1253[307]. A fifth
1 CONT testament of Comte Amedée IV is dated 24 May 1253, appoints "Bonifacius filius
1 CONT suus, sub tutela Thomæ comitis" as his heir, substitutes "filiæ Amedei
1 CONT comitis…marchionissæ Beatrix Salutiarum et Margaretha Montisferrati",
1 CONT bequeathes "castrum Montis Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ", and chooses to be
1 CONT buried at Hautecombe[308]. "Amedeus comes Sabaudie" granted "castrum Montis
1 CONT Meliani" to "Cæciliæ comitissæ conjugi suæ" for life, on condition that she
1 CONT allows "Bonifacium filium ex matrimonio eorum procreatum" to live with
1 CONT her[309]. The testament of "Beatricis relictæ Raimundi Berengarii comitis
1 CONT Provinciæ", dated 14 Jan 1264, adds bequests to "…Cæciliæ relictæ Amedei
1 CONT Sabaudiæ comitis…"[310]. "Cæciliæ comitissæ relictæ Amedei quondam comitis
1 CONT Sabaudiæ" donated property by charter dated 19 Jan 1268[311]. "Cecilia Vedova
1 CONT del Conte Amedeo di Savoia" granted property which she inherited after the
1 CONT death of "Bonifacio suo figlio" to "Filippo Conte di Savoia e di Borgonia" by
1 CONT charter dated Oct 1268[312].
