1 CONT <http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henryk_V_Brzuchaty>
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry V, Duke of Legnica
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry V the Fat (German: Heinrich V der Dicke, Polish: Henryk V Brzuchaty; b.
1 CONT ca. 1248 - d. 22 February 1296) was a Duke of Jawor (Jauer) from 1273, of
1 CONT Legnica (Liegnitz) from 1278 and also Duke of Wroclaw (Breslau) from 1290.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the eldest son of Bolesław II the Bald, Duke of Legnica by his first
1 CONT wife Hedwig, daughter of Henry I, Count of Anhalt.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Early Years. Duke of Jauer, Battle of Stolec
1 CONT
1 CONT Little is known about the earliest years of Henry's life. As a youth, he was
1 CONT present at the court of King Ottokar II of Bohemia in Prague, where he became
1 CONT a knight.[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1273, Henry's father give to him the town of Jawor (Jauer) as an
1 CONT independent Duchy. Four years later Henry's father Bolesław II the Bald,
1 CONT acting on behalf of his ally, king Rudolph of Habsburg, kidnapped his own
1 CONT nephew Henry IV, the ruler of Duchy of Wrocław. This act aroused the anger of
1 CONT the nobility in Lesser Poland and the neighbors of Henry IV, who then
1 CONT organized an expedition to free him and punish Bolesław. At the head of the
1 CONT Greater Poland-Głogów-Wroclaw coalition were the Dukes Przemysł II of Greater
1 CONT Poland and Henry III of Głogów. The armies fought at Ząbkowice Śląskie near
1 CONT Stolec. This was one of the most bloody battles of the Polish Middle Ages. In
1 CONT the course of battle, Bolesław, suspecting that the battle is to be lost, fled
1 CONT the field. However, at this point the young Henry led a charge and obtained a
1 CONT great victory, taking both Dukes Przemysł II and Henry III as prisoners.
1 CONT Thanks to the action of the young Duke of Jauer, his father and family were
1 CONT saved from disastrous defeat.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Death of Bolesław II the Bald. Henry V, Duke of Legnica
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław II died on 26 December 1278 and Henry was now able to succeeded him
1 CONT as a Duke in Legnica. Shortly afterwards, Henry in turn gave lands to his
1 CONT younger brothers: Bolko I and Bernard received Jawor and Lwówek as co-rulers,
1 CONT but Henry retaining the town of Środa Śląska, a town obtained in 1277 in
1 CONT exchange of Henry IV's freedom.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry continued the hostile relations with the other Piast Silesian Dukes
1 CONT characteristic of his father's rule. In 1281 he committed the mistake of
1 CONT accepting the invitation of Henry IV Probus to a meeting in Sądowel. Henry IV
1 CONT imprisoned the Duke of Legnica together with his former allies Henry III of
1 CONT Głogów and Przemysł II of Greater Poland, in order to obtain political
1 CONT concessions from them. Henry regained his freedom only in return for the
1 CONT recognition of Henry IV as Duke of Wrocław. However, Henry IV couldn't
1 CONT maintain his sovereignty for too long, because immediately the Duke of Legnica
1 CONT entered in close contacts with the King Wenceslaus II of Bohemia, who asserted
1 CONT his own claim to that land.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Henry V, Duke of Wroclaw. War with Henry III of Głogów
1 CONT
1 CONT On 23 June 1290 Henry IV Probus died suddenly, supposedly poisoned. In his
1 CONT testament, the late Duke named Henry III of Głogów as his heir. That decision,
1 CONT however, was opposed by Wrocław nobility and townspeople, who feared that the
1 CONT Duke of Głogów would be a harsh ruler. The power of the city was sufficient
1 CONT enough to force Henry III to flee. Thereafter, the citizens invited Henry V to
1 CONT take the place of Henry III.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry III, however, refused to step aside and began to take by force his
1 CONT inheritance, and war followed with saw territories change hands back and
1 CONT forth.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry couldn't prevent the next move of the Duke of Głogów. On 11 November
1 CONT 1293 Henry was betrayed by Lutka Zdzieszyca, son of Wrocław noble whom Henry
1 CONT had earlier sentenced to death. Lutka captured him and gave to Duke Henry III,
1 CONT who put him in prison for almost six months. Henry V only obtained his freedom
1 CONT after surrendering the towns of Namysłów, Bierutów, Oleśnica, Kluczbork,
1 CONT Byczyna, Wołczyn, Olesno, Chojnów and Bolesławiec with their respectives
1 CONT fortresses to Henry III, paying of a ransom of 30,000 pieces and promising to
1 CONT assist the Duke of Głogów for the next five years in all his wars.
1 CONT
1 CONT During his imprisonment in Głogów, Henry's brother Bolko I was named regent of
1 CONT his states. In 1291, Henry V already give him the towns of Świdnica
1 CONT (Schweidnitz), Ziębice, Ząbkowice Śląskie and Strzelin as a price for his help
1 CONT against Henry III.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Death and Legacy
1 CONT
1 CONT Because of the conditions of his confinement (he was locked in an iron cage),
1 CONT Henry was ill after his release and indeed until his death. He never recovered
1 CONT his health, and seems to have known that he was not going to live much longer.
1 CONT Fearing for the future of his Duchy, in 1294 he decided to put himself under
1 CONT the protection of the Holy See.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry died on 22 February 1296 and was buried in the Clare monastery of
1 CONT Wroclaw. At this time, all his sons were minors, and because of this, they
1 CONT were put under the tutelage of his brother Bolko.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Marriage and Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT Around 1273, Henry married with Elisabeth (b. ca. 1263 - d. 28 September
1 CONT 1304), daughter of Boleslaw the Pious, Duke of Greater Poland. They had eight
1 CONT children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Hedwig (b. ca. 1277 - d. aft. 3 February 1347), married by 1289/95 to Prince
1 CONT Otto of Brandenburg-Salzwedel, second son of Margrave Otto V. After her
1 CONT husband died, she became a nun in St. Klara, Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Euphemia (b. ca. 1278 - d. June 1347), married in 1300 to Otto II of Görz,
1 CONT Duke of Carinthia. Through this union, Henry was a direct ancestor of the
1 CONT Kings of Sicily, Aragon and Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna (b. 1284 - d. 2/3 October 1343), Abbess of St. Klara, Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth (b. ca. 1290 - d. Nov 1357/58), Abbess of St. Klara, Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław III the Generous (b. 23 September 1291 - d. 21 April 1352).
1 CONT
1 CONT Helena (b. ca. 1293 - d. aft. 1300), nun in St. Klara, Gniezno.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry VI the Good (b. 18 March 1294 - d. 24 November 1335).
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław (b. posthumously, 6 June 1296 - d. 13 January aft. 1352).
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Notes
1 CONT
1 CONT ^ Menzel, s.v. Heinrich V der Dicke, p. 396.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]References
1 CONT
