0 @N00763@ NOTE geni:about_me -<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meinhard,_Duke_of_Carinthia>
1 CONT
1 CONT Meinhard II (c. 1238 - end of October 1295) was Count of Tirol, Duke of
1 CONT Carinthia and Carniola, and Count of Gorizia (as Meinhard IV) He was the son
1 CONT of Meinhard I of Gorizia-Tyrol and Adelheid, Countess of Tirol (died 1275/79).
1 CONT
1 CONT His younger son was count Henry VI, sometime king of Bohemia and his eldest
1 CONT daughter Elisabeth became Queen-consort of Holy Roman Empire.
1 CONT
1 CONT His wife since 1258 was Elisabeth of Bavaria (c 1227-73), the daughter of Duke
1 CONT Otto II and widow of King Conrad IV, King of the Romans. Thus he was the
1 CONT stepfather of Conrad III of Jerusalem, Duke of Swabia and claimant of the
1 CONT Kingdom of Sicily who was killed in 1268.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1259, he emerged from the custody of the Archbishop of Salzburg to claim
1 CONT his heritage. When the inheritance rights to, and properties of, Gorizia and
1 CONT Tyrol were divided in 1271 between him and his younger brother, he received
1 CONT Tirol starting the Tyrolean line of the Meinhardinian dynasty. He struggled to
1 CONT acquire Trento and acquired several territories in the Inn valley. He is known
1 CONT as the creator of Tyrol as an independent territory. He also had roads built
1 CONT and coins minted, especially the silver coin "Zwainziger" (twenty). The type
1 CONT was copied elsewhere in Europe and became widely known as Groschen.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a supporter of King Rudolf I of Germany, he received Carinthia and
1 CONT Carniola, as a pledge, in 1276 and as fief in 1286, thus becoming the 1st Duke
1 CONT of Carinthia in his dynasty. As far as can be ascertained, he has no ancestry
1 CONT in earlier Carinthian ducal families, whereas he distantly descended from some
1 CONT early Meranian lords of Istria and Carniola. His investiture of the duchy
1 CONT included a provision that in extinction of his male line, the Habsburgs will
1 CONT be its heirs. This materialized in 1335.
1 CONT
1 CONT Meinhard died in 1295 at Greifenburg, Carinthia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Children
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Elisabeth of Tirol (1262-1312), wife of Albert I, Duke of Austria (1248-1308), became queen-consort of the Romans in 1298
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Otto of Gorizia-Tyrol (d 1310), father of Elisabeth of Carinthia, queen-consort of sicily as wife of Peter II of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Albrecht von Kärnten, died 1292
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Louis of Gorizia-Tyrol, died 1305
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Henry I of Bohemia (c 1270-1335), king of Bohemia 1306 and 1307-10, Duke of Carnithia 1310-35, Count of Tirol, father of Margarete Maultasch of Tirol
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Agnes of Carinthia (died 1293), wife of Frederick I, Margrave of Meissen (1257-1323), grandson of Emperor Frederick II, her only son Frederick of Meissen predeceased his father.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT
1 CONT Wikipedia:
1 CONT
1 CONT Meinhard II. (* um 1238; † 1. November 1295 in Greifenburg) aus dem Geschlecht
1 CONT der Meinhardiner war Graf (als Meinhard IV.) von Görz und Tirol und Herzog von
1 CONT Kärnten (1286-1295). Er war einer der bedeutendsten Fürsten des 13.
1 CONT Jahrhunderts und der Begründer Tirols als eigenständiges Land.
1 CONT
1 CONT Als Sohn des Grafen Meinhard I. fiel ihm durch Erbteilung 1271 die Grafschaft
1 CONT Tirol zu. Sein Bruder Albert I. erhielt die Besitzungen in Friaul, Istrien,
1 CONT Kärnten und im Pustertal.
1 CONT
1 CONT Berühmt wurde er durch die Prägung des „Zwainzigers“, der ersten deutschen
1 CONT Silbergroßmünze, die vielfach nachgeahmt wurde. Er unterstützte Rudolf I. von
1 CONT Habsburg in der Auseinandersetzung mit König Ottokar II. von Böhmen und wurde
1 CONT dafür 1286 zum Reichsfürsten erhoben und mit dem Herzogtum Kärnten belehnt.
1 CONT
1 CONT Gemeinsam mit seiner Gemahlin Elisabeth von Bayern, der Witwe des Staufers
1 CONT Konrad IV., stiftete er 1284 das Zisterzienserkloster Stams in Tirol, wo er
1 CONT auch sein Grab fand. Seine Tochter Elisabeth heiratete Albrecht I., den
1 CONT deutschen König der Jahre von 1298 bis 1308, und wurde zur Stammmutter aller
1 CONT späteren Habsburger. Durch seine Unterwerfung der Fürstbistümer Trient und
1 CONT Brixen gilt er als der eigentliche Begründer des Landes Tirol.
1 CONT
1 CONT Nachkommen [Bearbeiten]
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Albert II., Graf von Tirol († 1292);
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Agnes († 14. Mai 1293); (heiratete 1286 Friedrich I. (Meißen))
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Elisabeth von Kärnten, Görz und Tirol (1262–1313) (heiratete König Albrecht I.);
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Otto III. (um 1265–1310), Graf von Görz und Tirol, Herzog von Kärnten;
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Heinrich VI. (um 1270–1335), Herzog von Kärnten, Graf von Tirol, König von Böhmen und Polen;
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Ludwig († 1305).
1 CONT
1 CONT Literatur [Bearbeiten]
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Hermann Wiesflecker: Meinhard der Zweite. Tirol, Kärnten und ihre Nachbarländer des 13. Jahrhunderts (Schlern-Schriften 124). Wagner, Innsbruck 1995. ISBN 3703002875
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Wilhelm Baum: Die Grafen von Görz in der europäischen Politik des Mittelalters. Kitab-Verlag, Klagenfurt 2000. ISBN 3-902005-04-1
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Alfons Huber: Meinhard II.. In: Allgemeine Deutsche Biographie (ADB). Band 21. Duncker & Humblot, Leipzig 1885, S. 229–231.
