1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Meinhard II (born around 1238; died in the end of October 1295, Greifenburg,
1 CONT Carinthia) was Count of Tyrol, Duke of Carinthia and Carniola, and Count of
1 CONT Gorizia (as Meinhard IV) He was the son of Meinhard I of Gorizia-Tyrol and
1 CONT father of Henry VI.
1 CONT
1 CONT His wife was Elisabeth of Bavaria, the widow of King Conrad IV.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1259, he emerged from the custody of the Archbishop of Salzburg to claim
1 CONT his heritage. When the heirloom of Gorizia and Tyrol was divided in 1271, he
1 CONT received Tyrol and thus founded the Tyrolean line of the Meinhardiner dynasty.
1 CONT He struggled to acquire Trento and acquired several territories in the Inn
1 CONT valley. He also had roads built and coins minted. He is known as the creator
1 CONT of Tyrol as an independent territory.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a supporter of King Rudolf I of Germany, he received Carinthia and Carniola
1 CONT as pawns in 1276 and as fiefs in 1286.
1 CONT
