1 CONT
1 CONT Humbert III (1136, Avigliana, Piedmont – 4 March 1189, Chambéry, Savoy),
1 CONT surnamed the Blessed, was Count of Savoy from 1148 to 1188. His parents were
1 CONT Amadeus III of Savoy and Mathilde d'Albon the daughter of Guigues III of
1 CONT Albon. He ceded rights and benefits to monasteries and played a decisive role
1 CONT in the organization of Hautecombe Abbey. It is said that he would rather have
1 CONT been monk than a sovereign. On the death of his third wife he retired to
1 CONT Hautecombe, but then changed his mind and, by his fourth wife finally had son,
1 CONT Thomas. He sided with the Guelph party of Pope Alexander III against the
1 CONT Ghibelline Emperor Frederick Barbarossa. The result was an invasion of his
1 CONT states twice: in 1174 Susa was set on fire, and in 1187 Henry VI banished him
1 CONT from the Holy Roman Empire and wrested away most of his domains, of which he
1 CONT was left only with the valleys of Susa and Aosta. He died at Chambéry in 1189.
1 CONT He was the first prince buried at Hautecombe. His memorial day is March 4.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT === Life and reign ===
1 CONT
1 CONT Early life
1 CONT
1 CONT Humbert III was born around 1136 in the castle of Avigliana, near Turin, to
1 CONT Count Amadeus III and Mathilde d'Albon, Countess of Albon and Vienne. He is an
1 CONT important figure in medieval society, as attested in the history of House of
1 CONT Savoy. His life was characterized by certain key features, including
1 CONT mysticism, borne of a vocation and tradition of the contemplative life, which
1 CONT came about in the events of his time as warrior and politician, which he
1 CONT undertook exclusively for dynastic reasons.
1 CONT
1 CONT He inherited from his father, as well as from his grandfather, Humbert II, the
1 CONT dream of reconstituting the fragmented Kingdom of Burgundy, in stark
1 CONT opposition to the centralizing policy of the French royal family. In his
1 CONT efforts he was supported by Frederick I Barbarossa, and found himself induced
1 CONT to play a shrewd political subjugation of neighboring feudal lords or settled
1 CONT among his domains. Like his father, Humbert II, who died young when he was
1 CONT still a minor, Amadeus III entrusted the education of his son, Humbert III, to
1 CONT St. Amedeus of Lausanne, former abbot of Hautecombe, and under his guidance
1 CONT the young Humbert made great progress in studies and spiritual formation,
1 CONT despising the apparent splendor of worldly things, and giving himself to
1 CONT prayer, meditation and penance.[1] To better achieve his lofty goals, he
1 CONT frequently withdrew Hautecombe Abbey, on the banks of Lake Bourget in Savoy,
1 CONT founded by his father. He always left the abbey with regret, every time the
1 CONT family and the Savoyard nobility called him back for occupy himself with
1 CONT political matters.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriages
1 CONT
1 CONT Amadeus III was a pilgrim in the Holy Land in 1122. He went there through the
1 CONT offices of Pope Callixtus II, and in 1146 he participated in the Second
1 CONT Crusade, and died on the island of Cyprus in Nicosia on 1 April 1148, where he
1 CONT was buried, leaving the twelve-year old Humbert as heir. Although still at an
1 CONT early age, in 1151 Humbert was bethrothed to Faidiva, daughter of Alphonse
1 CONT Jourdain, Count of Toulouse. She soon died without issue. He later married
1 CONT Gertrude, daughter of Thierry, Count of Flanders and Sibylla of Anjou. This
1 CONT second marriage was annulled.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1164, Humbert married Clementia of Zähringen,[2] by whom he had two
1 CONT daughters: Alice and Sofia. She died in 1173, and he decided to retire to
1 CONT Hautecombe, but not for long. In 1177, the nobility in 1177 convinced him
1 CONT marry for the fourth time. As wife, he took Beatrice, daughter Géraud I of
1 CONT Mâcon and Maurette de Salins. At last he had a male heir, Thomas, to continue
1 CONT the dynasty. Beatrice also bore him a daughter who died at the age of seven.
1 CONT
1 CONT Reign
1 CONT
1 CONT Humbert's reign was long. It lasted forty years, and was characterized by
1 CONT struggles with the Holy Roman Emperor, various lords and count-bishops. The
1 CONT main reason for conflict consisted in the patronage of the Bishop of Turin by
1 CONT Frederick Barbarossa, who dreamed of undisturbed dominance of the capital of
1 CONT Piedmont. This led to a gradual reduction of the possessions and authority of
1 CONT Humbert III on the Italian side, leaving him with the rump territories of the
1 CONT valleys of Susa and Aosta. In 1187, he was banished from the Holy Roman Empire
1 CONT by Henry VI, for supporting the emperor's opponents. He did not retire, as has
1 CONT been said, to his Alpine domains, devoting himself in particular to the
1 CONT practice of personal virtues and fraternal charity. He also promoted the
1 CONT foundation of Precettoria of St. Anthony of Ranverso at Buttigliera Alta, not
1 CONT far from the town of Avigliana, entrusting it to Antoniani from Vienne,
1 CONT France.
1 CONT
1 CONT Death
1 CONT
1 CONT The death of Humbert III, March 4, 1189 in Chambéry, at the age of fifty-two,
1 CONT was mourned sincerely by all the people. He was the first prince of Savoy to
1 CONT be buried in Hautecombe Abbey, which has since become a burial place for the
1 CONT dynasty.
1 CONT
1 CONT Veneration
1 CONT
1 CONT The spirituality of Humbert undoubtedly blossomed in an environment of ancient
1 CONT Christian traditions, favored especially by the example of his father, a
1 CONT pilgrim and crusader in the Holy Land, and of his tutor, St. Amadeus, Bishop
1 CONT of Lausanne. However, Humbert's life was full of contradictions: He was a
1 CONT lover of peace, but had frequent hostilities and wars. He was penitent,
1 CONT ascetic, contemplative, but was forced to take the reins of government, during
1 CONT which time he had a life of action, and found himself forced in marriage in
1 CONT order to have an heir. However, he let unmistakable signs of great moral
1 CONT balance, severity with himself and indulgence and love of neighbor. He was a
1 CONT benefactor to churches, monasteries, and charitable causes, the care of the
1 CONT poor. Throughout his life, he supported Hautecombe Abbey. In 1188 he founded
1 CONT the Monastery of Sant'Antonio di Ranverso.
1 CONT
1 CONT Humbert was venerated by many immediately after his death. Miracles were
1 CONT reportedly wrought through his intercession. In Aosta, he is depicted on the
1 CONT facade of the city's cathedral. He is mentioned by St. Alphonsus Ligouri as a
1 CONT particularly pious monk.[3]
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1838, Charles Albert, King of Sardinia and his descendant, tried and failed
1 CONT to have him beatified by Pope Gregory XVI. The king's efforts on behalf of
1 CONT Boniface of Savoy, Archbishop of Canterbury, also failed.[citation needed] In
1 CONT Italy, Humbert is still remembered in particular at Racconigi, where the Royal
1 CONT Sanctuary of the Madonna delle Grazie houses a picture of him.
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Humbert had four wives:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1.Faidiva of Toulouse (Italian) (d. c.1154) daughter of Alphonse Jourdain,
1 CONT Count of Toulouse[4]
1 CONT
1 CONT 2.Gertrude of Flanders (m. abt 1155). The marriage was annulled, she was
1 CONT confined to a convent, later freed, and returned to the court of her brother,
1 CONT Philip of Flanders[5]
1 CONT
1 CONT 3.Clementia of Zähringen (married 1164), daughter of Conrad I, Duke of
1 CONT Zähringen.[2] They had 2 daughters:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Sofia, (1165–1202), married Azzo VI of Este[6]
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Alicia, (1166–1178), betrothed to John of England[7]
1 CONT
1 CONT 4.Beatrice of Viennois[6] and had one son:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Thomas, (born 1178)[6]
1 CONT
1 CONT \----------
1 CONT
1 CONT -<http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SAVOY.htm#HumbertIIIdied1189>
1 CONT
1 CONT HUMBERT de Savoie, son of AMEDEE III Comte de Maurienne et de Savoie & his
1 CONT second wife Mathilde d'Albon [Viennois] (Avigliana 4 Aug 1136-Chambéry 4 Mar
1 CONT 1189, bur Abbaye de Hautecombe). Robert of Torigny names "Humbertus comes
1 CONT Moriennæ" as "filius Amati comitis"[226]. "A. comes et marchio cum uxore sua
1 CONT M." donated property to the monastery of Ripalta, with the support of "eorum
1 CONT filio Umberto", by charter dated 9 Jan 1137[227]. "Amedeus comes et marchio et
1 CONT Maies comitissa uxor eius et Umbertus eorum filius" donated property to the
1 CONT monastery of Saint-Maurice by charter dated 30 Mar 1143[228]. "Amedeus comes
1 CONT et marchio et Majes comitissa uxor eius et Umbertus eorum filius" confirmed
1 CONT the rights of the monastery of Saint-Maurice d´Agaune by charter dated 30 Mar
1 CONT 1148[229]. He succeeded in 1150 as HUMBERT III Comte de Maurienne et de
1 CONT Savoie. "Humbertus Mauriacensis comes et marchio" donated "locum de Tyneres"
1 CONT Tinières to the abbey of Hautcrêt by charter dated 1150[230]. He established
1 CONT close relations with Henry II King of England, negotiating the marriage of one
1 CONT of his daughters with the king's son John[231]. He attempted to regain control
1 CONT over Turin and the surrounding lands, but came into conflict with Emperor
1 CONT Friedrich I "Barbarossa" who was also extending his power in northern Italy.
1 CONT Although the emperor was obliged to withdraw in 1168, he returned in 1174,
1 CONT burned the town of Susa in revenge for its opposition during his first Italian
1 CONT expedition, and deprived Comte Humbert of supremacy over the bishoprics of
1 CONT Turin, Belley and Tarentaise, placing them under the direct control of the
1 CONT empire. Comte Humbert continued to fight and, after refusing a summons to
1 CONT attend an imperial tribunal, was condemned in his absence to banishment from
1 CONT the empire and confiscation of his lands. Heinrich VI King of Germany was
1 CONT attempting to enforce the sentence on behalf of his father the emperor, when
1 CONT Comte Humbert died. "Umbertus comes de Morienna" granted privileges to the
1 CONT monastery of Santa Maria di Staffarda by charter dated 28 Jun 1172, witnessed
1 CONT by "Rodulfus Alaman, Poncius de Confluent…"[232]. The dating clause of a
1 CONT charter dated 20 Oct 1188, which records an agreement between the bishop of
1 CONT Maurienne and the canons of his cathedral, names "Humberto comite
1 CONT presidente"[233]. The necrology of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne records the death
1 CONT "IV Non Mar" in 1189 of "dognus Humbertus…comes Maur. et marchio Italie"[234].
1 CONT He was beatified in 1836.
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** firstly (before 3 Jan 1151) FAYDIVE, daughter of --- (-[1154]).
1 CONT "Umbertus comes, Amedei comitis filius…cum uxore sua…Faidiva" donated property
1 CONT by charter dated 3 Jan 1151[235]. The origins of Faydive are not known. Her
1 CONT unusual name suggests that she was Faydive de Toulouse, daughter of Alphonse I
1 CONT Jourdain Comte de Toulouse & his wife Faydive [Faydide] d'Uzès (-[1154]).
1 CONT However, she was not the only noble recorded with this name in south-western
1 CONT France during the early 12th century so this co-identity is not without doubt.
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** secondly ([1155], divorced before 1162) as her first husband, GERTRUDE
1 CONT de Flandre, daughter of THIERRY I Count of Flanders & his second wife Sibylle
1 CONT d'Anjou (-3 Mar after 1186). The Genealogica Comitum Flandriæ Bertiniana names
1 CONT (in order) "Philippum, Matheum, Petrum et tres filias" as the children of
1 CONT "Theodericus filius ducis Alsatie [et] Sibillam", not naming the daughters but
1 CONT specifying that "quarum primogenita nupsit Amico comiti Intermontano"[236].
1 CONT The Flandria Generosa names (in order) "Gertrudem et Margaretam" as the two
1 CONT daughters of Count Thierry & his second wife[237]. The Flandria Generosa, in a
1 CONT later manuscript, names "Gertrudis primogenita" and her first husband "comiti
1 CONT de Moriana", from whom she was separated, and her second husband "Hugoni de
1 CONT Oisi", specifying that she later became a nun at "Mencinis"[238]. She married
1 CONT secondly (after 1158) as his first wife, Hugues [III] d'Oisy Châtelain de
1 CONT Cambrai, and became a nun at Messines in [1177]. Philippe Count of Flanders,
1 CONT on the point of leaving on crusade, declared that "sororis mee Gertrudis
1 CONT quondam Morianensis comitisse" had renounced her inheritance before becoming a
1 CONT nun, by charter dated [24 Apr/12 Jun] 1177[239].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** thirdly (1164) as her second husband, KLEMENTIA von Zähringen, divorced
1 CONT wife of HEINRICH “der Löwe” Duke of Saxony and Bavaria, daughter of KONRAD
1 CONT Herzog von Zähringen & his wife Clémence de Namur (-[1173/75]). The Chronicon
1 CONT Sancti Michaelis Luneburgensis names "filiam ducis Zaringie, Clementiam" as
1 CONT wife of "Heinricus dux"[240]. The Chronicon Hanoniense refers to "filiam
1 CONT [uxorem]…dux Saxonum Henricus" as the daughter of "ducissam…Ciringiorum
1 CONT [filiam Godefridi comitis Namurcensi]"[241]. Heiress of Badenweiler, although
1 CONT her first husband sold these Swabian estates to Friedrich I "Barbarossa" King
1 CONT of Germany in 1158, receiving in exchange Herzberg, Scharzfels and Pöhlde
1 CONT south of the Harz[242]. Her first marriage was arranged to confirm her
1 CONT father's alliance with the Welf party in southern Germany[243]. The Annales
1 CONT Palidenses record the repudiation by "Heinricus dux" of his first wife
1 CONT "Bertoldi ducis Zaringe sorore"[244]. Her first husband repudiated Klementia
1 CONT because of the growing difficulties between her brother Duke Berthold IV and
1 CONT Emperor Friedrich I "Barbarossa", with whom Duke Heinrich was by then in close
1 CONT alliance[245]. Her second marriage is confirmed by Ralph de Diceto´s Ymagines
1 CONT Historiarum which record in 1173 the betrothal of “Henricus rex Angliæ,
1 CONT Johanni filio suo cognomento sine terra” and [her daughter] “septenni filiam
1 CONT primogenitam Humberti comitis de Moriana...ex relicta Henrici Saxonis
1 CONT ducis”[246].
1 CONT
1 CONT **m** fourthly ([1175]) BEATRIX de Vienne, daughter of GERARD Comte de Mâcon
1 CONT et de Vienne [Bourgogne-Comté] & his wife Maurette de Salins (-8 Apr 1230).
1 CONT The Chronicle of Alberic de Trois-Fontaines refers to one of the unnamed
1 CONT sisters of "comitem Guilelmum Matisconensem sive Viennensem et Galterum de
1 CONT Salins et quemdam Gerardum et Stephanum Bisuntinensem electum" as mother of
1 CONT "comes Thomas de Sabaudia"[247]. "Thomas…Mauriannensis comes et marchio
1 CONT Italiæ" confirmed the donations made by "pater meus…[et] domini comitis
1 CONT Humberti…abavi mei" to the canons of Saint-Jean de Maurienne, with the advice
1 CONT of "B. matris mee et…tutore meo Bonifacio marchione Montisferrati", by charter
1 CONT dated 12 Jun 1189[248]. The necrology of Hautecombe records the death of
1 CONT "Beatrix comitissa" 8 Apr 1230[249].
1 CONT
