1 CONT Humbert III (b. 1135 - d. 1189), surnamed the Blessed, was Count of Savoy from
1 CONT 1148 to 1189. According to Cope, "Humbert III, who reigned from 1149 to
1 CONT 1189...was a man of irresolute spirit who was disconsolate at being born a
1 CONT prince and preferred the seclusion of a monestery. He only renounced his
1 CONT chosen state of celibacy so as to give his land an heir."
1 CONT
1 CONT His first wife died young; his second marriage ended in divorce. Humbert gave
1 CONT up and became a Carthusian monk. However, the nobles and common people of
1 CONT Savoy begged him to marry yet again, which he reluctantly did. This third wife
1 CONT gave him two more daughters, and Humbert attempted to return to the monastic
1 CONT life yet again. Finally he was prevailed upon to marry for a fourth time, and
1 CONT this wife, Beatrice, produced the son who would ultimately succeed him.
1 CONT
1 CONT He married four times:
1 CONT
1 CONT Faidiva (Italian) daughter of Alphonse I of Toulouse
1 CONT Gertrude of Flanders, whom he divorced and confined. She was freed thanks to
1 CONT Robert, bishop of Cambrai and returned to the court of her brother, Philip of
1 CONT Flanders
1 CONT Clemenza of Zähringen (married 1164), daughter of Conrad I of Zähringen. They
1 CONT had 2 daughters:
1 CONT Sofia, (1165-1202), married Azzo IV of Este
1 CONT Alicia, (1166-1178), betrothed to John of England
1 CONT Beatrice of Viennois and had 1 son
1 CONT Tommaso (born 1178)
1 CONT [edit]
1 CONT Sources
1 CONT Cope, Christopher. The Lost Kingdom of Burgundy.
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT Amadeus III Count of Savoy Succeeded by:
1 CONT Thomas I
1 CONT who reigned from 1149 to 1189, . . . was a man of irresolute spirit who was
1 CONT disconsolate at being born a prince and preferred the seclusion of a
1 CONT monestery. He only renounced his chosen state of celibacy so as to give his
1 CONT land an heir . . . " Two wives produced only a daughter. "Humbert gave up and
1 CONT became a Carthusian monk . . . As the ancient chronicle
1 CONT narrates, the barons, knights, and people of Savoy went to the abbot to beg
1 CONT him to restore their count to them, but his marriage . . . again only produced
1 CONT a daughter; Humbert was about to withdraw to the abbey of Aulps when he was
1 CONT prevailed on to marry yet again, and his fourth wife [GERTUDE, dau. of
1 CONT THIERRY, COUNT OF FLANDERS] gave him an heir who fortunately had the kingly
1 CONT qualities which Humbert lacked."
1 CONT Weis' "Ancestral Roots . . ." (133:36), however, has the third wife, BEATRIX
1 CONT dau. of GIRARD, COUNT OF VIENNE/MACON (as THOMAS' mother.
1 CONT On a close call, I have chosen to go with Weis.
