1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT **Elżbieta** – **księżniczka wielkopolska** , **księżna legnicko-wrocławska**
1 CONT z dynastii Piastów.
1 CONT <http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/El%C5%BCbieta_Boles%C5%82aw%C3%B3wna>
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth of Greater Poland
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth of Greater Poland (1263- 28 September 1304) was the eldest child of
1 CONT Boleslaw the Pious and his wife Jolenta of Poland. Her younger sister was
1 CONT Jadwiga of Greater Poland.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1273, Elisabeth married Henry V the Fat, Duke of Legnica (1248-1296) who
1 CONT was the son of Bolesław II the Bald and Hedwig of Anjou.
1 CONT
1 CONT The couple had eight children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Hedwig (b. ca. 1277 - d. aft. 3 February 1347), married by 1289/95 to Prince
1 CONT Otto of Brandenburg-Salzwedel, second son of Margrave Otto V. After her
1 CONT husband died, she became a nun in St. Klara, Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Euphemia (b. ca. 1278 - d. June 1347), married in 1300 to Otto II of Görz,
1 CONT Duke of Carinthia. Through this union, Elisabeth and Henry were a direct
1 CONT ancestor of the Kings of Sicily, Aragon and Castile.
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna (b. 1284 - d. 2/3 October 1343), Abbess of St. Klara, Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth (b. ca. 1290 - d. Nov 1357/58), Abbess of St. Klara, Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław III the Generous (b. 23 September 1291 - d. 21 April 1352).
1 CONT
1 CONT Helena (b. ca. 1293 - d. aft. 1300), nun in St. Klara, Gniezno.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry VI the Good (b. 18 March 1294 - d. 24 November 1335).
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław (b. posthumously, 6 June 1296 - d. 13 January aft. 1352).
1 CONT
1 CONT Her husband went to war with Henry III, Duke of Silesia-Glogau, he was
1 CONT captured and imprisoned in Glogau until he was released. Henry was ill by the
1 CONT time of his release; this was due to the conditions of his confinement (he was
1 CONT locked in an iron cage).
1 CONT
1 CONT He never recovered his health, and seems to have known that he was not going
1 CONT to live much longer. Fearing for the future of his Duchy, in 1294 he decided
1 CONT to put himself under the protection of the Holy See.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry died on 22 February 1296 and was buried in the Clare monastery of
1 CONT Wroclaw. At this time, all his sons were minors, and because of this, they
1 CONT were put under the tutelage of his brother Bolko.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Later life
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth's mother and younger sister, Anna had gone to live in a nunnery
1 CONT after the death of Anna, Jadwiga and Elisabeth's father. Jadwiga was married
1 CONT to Władysław I the Elbow-high, they had many children; among them were
1 CONT Elizabeth of Poland and Casimir III of Poland.
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth and her children went to live with Wenceslaus II of Bohemia and his
1 CONT family. Here, Wenceslaus and Elisabeth arranged for her son Bolesław to marry
1 CONT Wenceslaus' youngest daughter Margaret.
1 CONT
1 CONT Since Bolesław's arrival to the Bohemian court and after his betrothal to
1 CONT Margaret, the King clearly favored him; this attitude caused fear between the
1 CONT closest male relatives of the King, who seen the young Duke of Legnica in a
1 CONT potential rival for the throne. Although Wenceslaus II had a son seemed him
1 CONT irrelevant, the sudden death of the King in 1305 and one year later the
1 CONT murdered of his son and successor Wenceslaus III in Olomouc gained him an
1 CONT unexpectedly importance. Bolesław began his fight for the Bohemian throne
1 CONT taking the title of "haeres Regni Poloniae" (heir of the Polish Kingdom).
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław and Margaret were married in 1308 and had three children. By this
1 CONT time, Elisabeth had died. She died on 28 September 1304 and was buried
1 CONT alongside her husband in the Clare monastery of Wroclaw.
