1 CONT Meinhard I of Gorizia-Tyrol
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT Jump to: navigation, search
1 CONT Meinhard I (born c. 1200 or 1205, died in January/February of 1258), was Count
1 CONT of Gorizia and Tyrol.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was also father of Meinhard II of Tyrol and Albert II of Gorizia.
1 CONT
1 CONT He came in control over his family's Gorizian possessions in 1232, but it his
1 CONT father-in-law Albert III of Tyrol as a fief. Between 1248 and 1250, he
1 CONT operated as the imperial governor of Styria and Carniola, from 1250 onwards
1 CONT also in Austria. In 1252, he was forced to take certain possessions in Lienz
1 CONT as fiefs from the Philipp, Archbishop of Salzburg, in the Treaty of
1 CONT Lieserhofen and to give his sons to him as hostages. After the death of Albert
1 CONT III, Meinhard, and his brother-in-law, Gebhard of Hirschberg, split Tyrol, of
1 CONT which Meinhard took the southern part.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT Albert III Count of Tyrol Succeeded by:
1 CONT Meinhard II
1 CONT Preceded by:
1 CONT ??? Count of Gorizia
