0 @N00814@ NOTE geni:about_me **Bolesław II Rogatka** , także **Łysy** i **Cudaczny** (ur.
1 CONT między 1220 a 1225, zm. 26 grudnia 1278) – **książę krakowski** w 1241, w
1 CONT latach 1241-1247 **książę południowo-zachodniej Wielkopolski** , **książę
1 CONT śląski** w latach 1241-1248, **legnicko-głogowski** w latach 1248-1249/1251, w
1 CONT 1249 strata Lubusza, od 1249 tylko w Legnicy, od 1277 także w Środzie
1 CONT Śląskiej. <http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boles%C5%82aw_II_Rogatka>
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław II the Bald
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław II the Bald known also as the Horned (Polish: Bolesław II Łysy or
1 CONT Rogatka; b. ca. 1220/5 - d. 26/31 December 1278), was a Duke of Krakow briefly
1 CONT in 1241, of Southern Greater Poland during 1241 - 1247, and Duke of all
1 CONT Silesia-Wroclaw since 1241 until 1248, when was divided between him and his
1 CONT brothers. He was Duke of Neumarkt in Silesia (Środa Śląska) from 1277 and
1 CONT during his reign the second Mongol raid against Poland, led by Nogai Khan
1 CONT occured.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the eldest son of Henry II the Pious, Duke of Wroclaw, by his wife
1 CONT Anna, daughter of King Ottokar I of Bohemia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Beginning of his Reign and Fight over the Greater Poland Inheritance
1 CONT (1241-47)
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław, in contrast to his father, doesn't have to wait too much for reign,
1 CONT because on 9 April 1241, during the Battle of Legnica against the Mongols,
1 CONT Duke Henry II was killed after only three years of government. At the time of
1 CONT these tragic events, of the five sons of the Silesian Duke, only Bolesław and
1 CONT his inmediate younger brother Mieszko could be considered adults and capables
1 CONT to ruled without a regency. However, during the first and difficult months of
1 CONT government, their mother Anna would help them. Some sources even speak
1 CONT directly to her regency. Whatever was the case, this "regency" wasn't to too
1 CONT long and even in the same year Bolesław formally began his personal reign,
1 CONT whose beginning wasn't successful. Although the Mongols, after conquest
1 CONT considerable areas of Silesia soon withdrew to Hungary, with any intention to
1 CONT retain that lands permanently, for Bolesław the situation wasn't too easiest.
1 CONT The paternal inheritance included the Southern Greater Poland and Krakow, but
1 CONT soon erupted the revolts from others Piast Dukes who wanted these lands. In
1 CONT Lesser Poland, by July 1241 appeared to eternal pretender to Krakow: Konrad I
1 CONT of Masovia. The war was not yet a defeat, thanks to the effective resistance
1 CONT against the Masovians organized by the Governor of Krakow, Clement of Ruszczy;
1 CONT however, the complete inaction of Bolesław dissapointed the nobility, who
1 CONT quickly found a new candidate for the Krakow throne in Bolesław V the Chaste.
1 CONT In Greater Poland, the situation was not very different. After hear the news
1 CONT of the defeat of Henry II in Legnica, Przemysł I and Bolesław the Pious,
1 CONT decided to retaken the district once belonging to their father Władysław
1 CONT Odonic. The Greater Poland nobility and knighthood strongly supported them,
1 CONT because under their eyes, as a chronicler stated, they were the true heirs of
1 CONT that lands. This time, Bolesław decided to avoid any fight and renounce to all
1 CONT his Greater Poland lands, but obtained in exchange some district as Santok and
1 CONT Międzyrzecz. But the uncompromising attitude of the Greater Poland Dukes and
1 CONT the increasing problems who this caused in the family, ultimately forced
1 CONT Bolesław to resign the lands and with this all his pretentions over Greater
1 CONT Poland, in 1247.
1 CONT
1 CONT The First Division of Lower Silesia (1248)
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław initially didn't any intended to made a division of his father's
1 CONT Silesian Duchy, and wanted to concentrate all the power in his hands. In 1242,
1 CONT after the unexpectedly death of his next brother Mieszko (who had received
1 CONT Lubusz as a Duchy) without issue, his lands reverted to him. Bolesław's
1 CONT resistance to share the government with his younger brothers only caused
1 CONT revolts against him; shortly after the young Silesian princes were able to
1 CONT imprison his older brother. These incidents caused in Bolesław, until the end
1 CONT of his life very suspicious to his environment and a further difficults to
1 CONT deal with the government. As an interim of the revolts, Bolesław made an
1 CONT agreement with his brother Henry III the White in 1247, when he was declared
1 CONT co-ruler of Silesia. The cooperation between the brothers wasn't too good and
1 CONT a year later, they decided to made a division of the districts Legnica-Głogów-
1 CONT Lubusz and Wrocław. In addition, the brothers have pledged to offer
1 CONT hospitality to the younger brothers, Bolesław to Konrad, and Henry to
1 CONT Władysław. Bolesław, as the older brother, had the opportunity to choose his
1 CONT district; he decided to Legnica, because there was found gold in the Kaczawa
1 CONT and Wierzbiak Rivers.
1 CONT
1 CONT The choice of Legnica can also be dictated by the growing conflict between
1 CONT Bolesław and the powerful Wrocław nobility, a problem who Henry III didn't
1 CONT had; shortly after he could took control over the duchy. But now Bolesław
1 CONT began to regret his choice and tried to recover Wroclaw. Henry III, of course,
1 CONT refused to voluntarily give up his new duchy. The war was only a matter of
1 CONT time.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]War against Henry III the White and Sale of Lubusz (1248-49)
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry and Bolesław began his preparations for the war, but, didn't have
1 CONT adequate funds. In these circumstances, there was a most common practices
1 CONT during the period of regional divisions. Bolesław had married in 1242 with
1 CONT Hedwig of Anhalt, daughter of Count Henry I and niece of the Landgraves of
1 CONT Thuringia, and now he decided to use this family connections to find allies in
1 CONT his fight against his brother. The price for troops was putting by the
1 CONT Archbishop of Magdeburg: half of Lubusz, who passed then to the hands of
1 CONT Brandenburg, because at that time, Magdeburg was part of them.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Bolesław II, Duke of Legnica (1249-51)
1 CONT
1 CONT The German aid only give to Bolesław a temporary advantage in the war against
1 CONT his brother. In 1249 unexpectedly returned to the country (after concluded his
1 CONT studies in Paris) his younger brother Konrad, whose Bolesław unsuccessfully
1 CONT tried to convince to entered to the Church. He proposed him as Bishop of
1 CONT Passau but Konrad refused and began his own claims over Silesia. Bolesław
1 CONT obviously refused his consent, so that the young prince took refuge at the
1 CONT court of Bolesław's long-time enemies, the Dukes of Greater Poland. Shortly
1 CONT after, Konrad reforced his bonds with Duke Przemysł I after a double marriage:
1 CONT the Greater Poland Duke with Konrad's sister Elizabeth, and himself with Duke
1 CONT Przemysł's sister, Salome. The final crash occurred two years later, when the
1 CONT Legnica Duke was defeated by the combined forces of Przemysł I and Henry III
1 CONT the White, who supported the pretentions of his brother. Bolesław was finally
1 CONT forced to agree on the division of his own lands and give Głogów to Konrad.
1 CONT After this, the elder Duke of the Silesian branch only retained the small
1 CONT district of Legnica.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Agreement with Henry III the White (1252-56)
1 CONT
1 CONT However, Bolesław needed other two years and the help of Henry III (who in
1 CONT this difficult situation he eventually decided to give him his support) to
1 CONT recover in 1253 the full authority over his Principality. Finally the
1 CONT brotherly cooperation was imposed and for the next years was quite specific.
1 CONT With Henry III wasn't the case, and the eventual struggles for the main power
1 CONT led to a major clashes. But during this time, Bolesław made some agreements
1 CONT with the others Piast Dukes, especially with the princes of Greater Poland and
1 CONT with Thomas I, Bishop of Wroclaw, althought Bolesław never forgive the Bishop
1 CONT that in the disputes with his brothers he always supported the younger
1 CONT princes.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Conflict with Bishop Thomas of Wrocław (1257-61)
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław's conflict with the Bishop of Wrocław reached his point more critical
1 CONT in 1257, when the Duke of Legnica decided to desposed and incarcerate him at
1 CONT the Castle Wleń. It is unknown if Bolesław wanted to this act take control
1 CONT over the local Church, but the inmediate and direct consecuence of his
1 CONT behavior was the excommunication to him (Bolesław was already excommunicated
1 CONT twice, in 1248 and 1249, but was later forgive by the Bishop. Both
1 CONT excomnications were removed only after approval of the Church) and the call to
1 CONT all his neighbors to a crusade against him. In an unexpected way, were only
1 CONT his brothers who quickly intervene and who began to work in a settlement
1 CONT between both parties. The price for Bolesław's return to the Church was high:
1 CONT the Duke was finally forced in 1261 to pay a huge monetary compensation and
1 CONT made a public penitance at the gates of the Cathedral in Wroclaw. The victory
1 CONT of Bishop Thomas was complete.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Relations with Konrad of Głogów (1262-71)
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław, who was finally able to mantain an agreement with Henry III until
1 CONT his death, remained in the hostile relations with his Konrad of Głogów, thanks
1 CONT in great part to the rebellious and obstinate character of the young Duke.
1 CONT Thanks to the absence of sources, is only know two specifics events of the
1 CONT conflict. In 1257 Konrad made an dangerous move and kidnaped Bolesław from his
1 CONT castle in Legnica. The Duke regained his freedom after a few months, but is
1 CONT unknown for what price. It can therefore say that since them the Duke never
1 CONT left a moment of happiness to Bolesław, but in 1271 the Duke of Legnica
1 CONT managed to taken the town of Bolesławiec near Bóbr.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Abduction of Henry IV and Battle of Stolec (1272-77)
1 CONT
1 CONT In the decade of 1270 was clear the political decline of Bolesław. He began to
1 CONT give more and more power to his adolescent sons. In 1273 he granted Jawor
1 CONT (Jauer) as a Duchy to his oldest son Henry V and it seemed that Bolesław
1 CONT resigned definitively to adventurous politics. But in 1277, he surprised
1 CONT everyone. Bolesław signed an alliance with the King Rudolph I of Germany (who
1 CONT with this tried to break the alliance of the other Piast Dukes with the King
1 CONT Ottokar II of Bohemia) and for Rudolph's insistence, he decided to kidnap
1 CONT Ottokar's ally, Henry IV -who also was Bolesław's nephew-. The pretext of this
1 CONT was the young prince's requests of one third of Wroclaw after the death in
1 CONT 1270 of his uncle Władysław, Bolesław's youngest brother. Henry IV was an
1 CONT important prisoner and shortly after was imprisoned in a castle in Legnica. In
1 CONT order to obtain his freedom, was made a coalition between the Bohemian King
1 CONT and the Dukes Henry III of Głogów and Przemysł II of Greater Poland; however,
1 CONT they soon failed. Although Bolesław's forces were notoriously smaller than the
1 CONT coalition's army in the Battle of Stolec and seemingly start to lost,, his son
1 CONT Henry V unexpectedly began to win and finally defeated the allied dukes. The
1 CONT dispute ended with a settlement; Henry IV obtain his freedom in exchange for
1 CONT 1/3 of the Duchy of Środa Śląska (German: Neumarkt), which was granted to
1 CONT Bolesław.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Death and Succession (1278)
1 CONT
1 CONT This was last the success of the Duke of Legnica. Bolesław II died on 26/31
1 CONT December 1278 and was buried in the Dominican monastery of Legnica. His three
1 CONT sons, Henry V the Fat, Bolko I and Bernhard, inherited their lands and divided
1 CONT between them.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Marriage and Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT Around 8 May 1242, Bolesław married firstly with Hedwig (d. 21 December 1259),
1 CONT daughter of Henry I, Count of Anhalt. They had ten children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Agnes (b. ca. 1243/50 - d. 13 March 1265), married ca. 1260/64 to Count Ulrich
1 CONT I of Württemberg.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry V the Fat (b. ca. 1248 - d. 22 February 1296).
1 CONT
1 CONT Hedwig (b. ca. 1250/55 - d. aft. 1280), married ca. 1265/70 to Duke Konrad II
1 CONT of Masovia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolko I the Strict (b. ca. 1252/56 - d. Grissow, 9 November 1301).
1 CONT
1 CONT Bernard the Lightsome (b. ca. 1253/57 - d. 25 April 1286).
1 CONT
1 CONT Konrad (d. young).
1 CONT
1 CONT Jarosław (d. young).
1 CONT
1 CONT Katharina (b. ca. 1255 - d. aft. 1270), Abbess of Trebnicz.
1 CONT
1 CONT Elizabeth (b. ca. 1259 - d. aft. 1268), married in 1268 to Louis of Hakeborn.
1 CONT
1 CONT After 1260, Bolesław married secondly with Eufemia (also called Alenta or
1 CONT Iolanta) (b. ca. 1245 - d. ca. 15 February 1309), daughter of Sambor II, Duke
1 CONT of Pomerania. This union was unsuccessfully, thanks to the infidelities and
1 CONT scandals of Eufemia, who even fled to Gdansk with her lover. However, she
1 CONT appears in Silesia after the death of her husband, who was maybe an indication
1 CONT that they were reconcilied shortly after. They had no children.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]References
1 CONT
