0 @N00819@ NOTE (Otto II "der Erlauchte" von der Pfalz Herzog in Bayern)
0 @N00820@ NOTE geni:about_me Otto II of Bavaria (German: Otto II der Erlauchte, Herzog von
1 CONT Bayern, Pfalzgraf bei Rhein, 7 April 1206 in Kelheim – 29 November 1253) known
1 CONT as Otto the Illustrious was the Duke of Bavaria and Count Palatine of the
1 CONT Rhine (see Electorate of the Palatinate). He was the son of Louis I and
1 CONT Ludmilla of Bohemia and a member of the Wittelsbach dynasty.
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT Otto was born at Kelheim.
1 CONT
1 CONT At the age of sixteen, he was married to Agnes of the Palatinate, a
1 CONT granddaughter of Duke Henry the Lion and Conrad of Hohenstaufen. With this
1 CONT marriage, the Wittelsbach inherited the Palatinate and kept it as a
1 CONT Wittelsbach possession until 1918. Since that time also the lion has become a
1 CONT heraldic symbol in the coat of arms for Bavaria and the Palatinate.
1 CONT
1 CONT Otto acquired the rich regions of Bogen in 1240, and Andechs and Ortenburg in
1 CONT 1248 as possessions for the Wittelsbach and extended his power base in Bavaria
1 CONT this way. With the county of Bogen, the Wittelsbach acquired also the white
1 CONT and blue coloured lozenge flag which since that time has been the flag of
1 CONT Bavaria (and of the Palatinate).
1 CONT
1 CONT After a dispute with emperor Frederick II was ended, he joined the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen party in 1241. His daughter, Elizabeth, was married to
1 CONT Frederick's son Conrad IV. Because of this, Otto was excommunicated by the
1 CONT pope.
1 CONT
1 CONT He died in Landshut in 1253. Like his forefathers, Otto was buried in the
1 CONT crypt of Scheyern Abbey.
1 CONT Family and children
1 CONT
1 CONT Otto married Agnes, the daughter of Henry V, Count Palatine of the Rhine (a
1 CONT son of Henry the Lion) and Agnes of Hohenstaufen, in Worms in 1222. Their
1 CONT children were:
1 CONT
1 CONT Louis II, Duke of Bavaria (13 April 1229, Heidelberg – 2 February 1294,
1 CONT Heidelberg).
1 CONT Henry XIII, Duke of Bavaria (19 November 1235, Landshut – 3 February 1290,
1 CONT Burghausen.
1 CONT Elisabeth of Bavaria, Queen of Germany (c. 1227, Landshut – 9 October 1273)
1 CONT Sophie (1236, Landshut – 9 August 1289, Castle Hirschberg), married 1258 to
1 CONT Count Gerhard IV of Sulzbach and Hirschberg.
1 CONT Agnes (c. 1240–c. 1306), Nun in Segenstal Abbey
1 CONT
1 CONT References
1 CONT
1 CONT Citations
1 CONT
1 CONT Bibliography
1 CONT
1 CONT Arnold, Benjamin (1985). German Knighthood 1050 - 1300. Oxford: Clarendon
1 CONT Press. ISBN 0-19-821960-1.
1 CONT Arnold, Benjamin (1991). Count and Bishop in Medieval Germany: A Study of
1 CONT Regional Power, 1100 - 1350. Pennsylvania: University of Pennsylvania Press.
1 CONT Arnold, Benjamin (1991). Princes and territories in medieval Germany.
1 CONT Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. ISBN 0-521-39085-0.
1 CONT Bachrach, David S. (2016). The Histories of a Medieval German City, Worms c.
1 CONT 1000-c.1300. New York: Routledge. ISBN 9781472436412.
1 CONT Holzfurtner, Ludwig (2005). Die Wittelsbacher: Staat und Dynastie in acht
1 CONT Jahrhunderten (Urban-Taschenbucher). Kohlhammer Verlag. ISBN 978-3170181915.
1 CONT Hubensteiner, Benno (2013). Bayerische Geschichte. Munich: Rosenheimer
1 CONT Verlagshaus. ISBN 978-3475537561.
1 CONT Stevens, John (1706). The History of Bavaria: From the First Ages, to This
1 CONT Present Year.
1 CONT Peltzer, Jörg (2013). Die Wittelsbacher und die Kurpfalz im Mittelalter: Eine
1 CONT Erfolgsgeschichte?. Schnell & Steiner. ISBN 978-3795426453.
1 CONT Reiss-Engelhorn-Museen, Mannheim (2013). Die Wittelsbacher am Rhein. Die
1 CONT Kurpfalz und Europa: 2 Bände. Schnell & Steiner. ISBN 978-3795426446.
1 CONT Schmid, Gregor M. (2014). Die Familie, die Bayern erfand: Das Haus
1 CONT Wittelsbach: Geschichten, Traditionen, Schicksale, Skandale. Munich: Stiebner.
1 CONT ISBN 978-3830710608.
1 CONT Vogel, Susanne (2012). Die Wittelsbacher: Herzöge - Kurfürsten - Könige in
1 CONT Bayern von 1180 bis 1918. Biografische Skizzen. Staackmann. ISBN
1 CONT 978-3886752485
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT
