1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT =Boleslaw the Pious=
1 CONT
1 CONT Bolesław the Pious (Polish: Bolesław Pobożny) (1224/27 – 14 April 1279) was a
1 CONT Duke of Greater Poland during 1239–1247 (according to some historians during
1 CONT 1239–1241 sole Duke of Ujście), Duke of Kalisz during 1247–1249, Duke of
1 CONT Gniezno during 1249–1250, Duke of Gniezno-Kalisz during 1253–1257, Duke of
1 CONT whole Greater Poland and Poznań during 1257–1273, in 1261 ruler over Ląd,
1 CONT regent of the Duchies of Masovia, Płock and Czersk during 1262–1264, ruler
1 CONT over Bydgoszcz during 1268–1273, Duke of Inowrocław during 1271–1273, and Duke
1 CONT of Gniezno-Kalisz since 1273 until his death.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the second son of Władysław Odonic, Duke of Greater Poland by his wife
1 CONT Hedwig, who was probably daughter of Duke Mestwin I of Pomerania, or a member
1 CONT of the Premyslid dynasty. His name was very popular in the Piast dynasty, so
1 CONT it's unknown exactly after whom he was named. Very soon Bolesław received the
1 CONT nickname of "the Pious" (Latin: Pius), given to him during his lifetime by the
1 CONT Chronicle of the Chapter of Poznań.
1 CONT
1 CONT ...
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and issue
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1258 Bolesław married with Jolenta (Helena) (b. 1244 - d. 16/17 June aft.
1 CONT 1304), daughter of King Béla IV of Hungary. They had three daughters:[1][2][3]
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth (b. 1261/63 - d. September 1304), married in 1273 to Henry V, Duke
1 CONT of Legnica.
1 CONT
1 CONT Hedwig (b. 1270/75 - d. 10 December 1339), married in January 1293 to
1 CONT Władysław I the Elbow-high, Duke of Kuyavia and since 1320 King of Poland.
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna (b. 1276/78 - d. bef. 1300), a nun in Gniezno.
1 CONT
1 CONT After his death without male heirs, all the Greater Poland Duchy passed to his
1 CONT only nephew Przemysł II. Crowned King of Poland in 1295 but murdered the next
1 CONT year, with his death the Greater Poland branch of the Piast dynasty became
1 CONT extinct.
1 CONT
1 CONT Source / Forrás:
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boleslaw_the_Pious>
1 CONT
1 CONT [http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolesław_Pobożny](http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boles%C5%82aw_Pobo%C5%BCny)
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Współrządził z bratem w latach 1239-47.
1 CONT
1 CONT Książę kaliski w latach 1247-49, 1253r.
1 CONT
1 CONT Książę gnieźnieński w latach 1249-50r.
1 CONT
1 CONT Książę wielkopolski (jako opiekun bratanka) od 1257r.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT **Bolesław Pobożny** – **książę wielkopolski** w latach 1239–1247 (według
1 CONT niektórych historyków tylko książę na Ujściu w latach 1239–1241), **książę
1 CONT kaliski** w latach 1247–1249, **książę gnieźnieński** w latach 1249–1250, w
1 CONT latach 1250–1253 usunięty, **książę gnieźnieńsko-kaliski** w latach 1253–1257,
1 CONT **w całej Wielkopolsce** w latach 1257–1273, od 1261 roku **w Lądzie** ,
1 CONT **książę regent na Mazowszu** w latach 1262–1264, **w Bydgoszczy** w latach
1 CONT 1268–1273, **w Inowrocławiu** w latach 1271–1273, od 1273 roku **książę
1 CONT gnieźnieńsko-kaliski**.
1 CONT <http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boles%C5%82aw_Pobo%C5%BCny>
1 CONT Boleslaw V the Chaste
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Boleslaw WstydliwyBoleslaus the Chaste or the Shy (Polish: Boleslaw Wstydliwy)
1 CONT (21 June 1226 O.S. – 7 December 1279 O.S.) was the son of Leszek the White.
1 CONT Several years after the death of Henry the Pious at the battle of Legnica
1 CONT (1241), he became king in Kraków, and thereby the predominant prince of the
1 CONT deeply partitioned Poland.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was married to Kinga or Cunegunda, daughter of the Hungarian king Béla IV.
1 CONT According to medieval chronicles the marriage was never consummated. Kinga,
1 CONT being extremely pious, was averse to fulfilling her marital duties. At first
1 CONT Boleslaw tried to convince her to change her mind, but she did not accept.
1 CONT Then he reluctantly accepted the situation. His religious convictions forbade
1 CONT him to take a mistress. That is why he obtained the nick name "the Chaste" or
1 CONT "the Shy".
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT The Majestatic Seal of Boleslaw WstydliwyUnder his reign the town of Kraków,
1 CONT destroyed by the Tartars in 1241, was refounded, and mainly settled with
1 CONT German colonists. The new town was built according to a regular chess board
1 CONT pattern (the "location" of 1257).
