0 @N00833@ NOTE geni:about_me <http://hu.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boldog_Jol%C3%A1n>
1 CONT
1 CONT <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jolenta_of_Poland>
1 CONT
1 CONT Jolenta (Jolanta) of Poland (also known as Blessed Yolande (Yolanda) of Poland
1 CONT and Blessed Helen of Hungary (or of Poland); Polish: Bł. Jolenta) (1235–1298)
1 CONT was the daughter of Béla IV of Hungary and Maria Laskarina. She was the sister
1 CONT of Saint Margaret of Hungary and Saint Kinga (Cunegunda). One of her father's
1 CONT sisters was the great Franciscan saint, Elizabeth of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a young girl, Jolenta was sent to Poland, to be tutored under the
1 CONT supervision of her sister, Kinga, who was married to the Duke of Poland.
1 CONT There, she was encouraged to marry Boleslaus of Greater Poland, which she did
1 CONT in 1257. They had three daughters:
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth of Kalisz (1263 – 28 September 1304). Married Henry V, Duke of
1 CONT Legnica
1 CONT
1 CONT Hedwig of Kalisz (1266 – 10 December 1339). Married Władysław I the Elbow-
1 CONT high, King of Poland
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna of Kalisz (born 1278, date of death unknown). A nun in Gniezno
1 CONT
1 CONT During the time of her marriage, she was noted for her great services to the
1 CONT poor and needy of the country, as well as being a major benefactor of the
1 CONT monasteries, friaries and hospitals connected to them. Her husband gave her so
1 CONT much support in her charities, that he earned the nickname, "the Pious." She
1 CONT was widowed in 1279.
1 CONT
1 CONT Religious work
1 CONT
1 CONT Following Boleslaus' death, Jolenta and Kinga, along with one of Jolenta's
1 CONT daughters, retired to the Poor Clare monastery Kinga had founded in Sandez.
1 CONT Forced to relocate due to armed conflict in the region, Jolenta founded a new
1 CONT monastery in Gniezno. She was persuaded to become Abbess of the community
1 CONT shortly before her death.
1 CONT
1 CONT Veneration
1 CONT
1 CONT She has been declared as a candidate for sainthood. Her sisters, Kinga and
1 CONT Margaret, have already been canonized.
1 CONT
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Beatyfikowana 26.09.1827r.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Jolenta (Jolanta) of Poland (also known as Blessed Yolande (Yolanda) of Poland
1 CONT and Blessed Helen of Hungary (or of Poland); Polish: Bł. Jolenta) (1235–1298)
1 CONT was the daughter of Béla IV of Hungary and Maria Laskarina. She was the sister
1 CONT of Saint Margaret of Hungary and Saint Kinga (Cunegunda). One of her father's
1 CONT sisters was the great Franciscan saint, Elizabeth of Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT As a young girl, Jolenta was sent to Poland, to be tutored under the
1 CONT supervision of her sister, Kinga, who was married to the Duke of Poland.
1 CONT There, she was encouraged to marry Boleslaus of Greater Poland, which she did
1 CONT in 1257. They had three daughters:
1 CONT
1 CONT Elisabeth of Kalisz (1263 – 28 September 1304). Married Henry V, Duke of
1 CONT Legnica Hedwig of Kalisz (1266 – 10 December 1339). Married Władysław I the
1 CONT Elbow-high, King of Poland Anna of Kalisz (born 1278, date of death unknown).
1 CONT A nun in Gniezno
1 CONT
1 CONT During the time of her marriage, she was noted for her great services to the
1 CONT poor and needy of the country, as well as being a major benefactor of the
1 CONT monasteries, friaries and hospitals connected to them. Her husband gave her so
1 CONT much support in her charities, that he earned the nickname, "the Pious." She
1 CONT was widowed in 1279.
1 CONT
1 CONT Following Boleslaus' death, Jolenta and Kinga, along with one of Jolenta's
1 CONT daughters, retired to the Poor Clare monastery Kinga had founded in Sandez.
1 CONT Forced to relocate due to armed conflict in the region, Jolenta founded a new
1 CONT monastery in Gniezno. She was persuaded to become Abbess of the community
1 CONT shortly before her death.
1 CONT
1 CONT She has been declared as a candidate for sainthood. Her sisters, Kinga and
1 CONT Margaret, have already been canonized.
