0 @N00840@ NOTE geni:about_me **Henryk II Pobożny** (ur. 1196/1207, zm. 9 kwietnia 1241[1]) –
1 CONT **książę śląski, krakowski i wielkopolski** 1238–1241 (do 1239 tylko w
1 CONT południowej Wielkopolsce po linię rzeki Warty). Przez cały okres panowania nad
1 CONT ziemią kaliską i wieluńską (rudzką) sprawował wyłącznie opiekę nad małoletnimi
1 CONT książętami. W latach 1238–1239 rządził w księstwie opolskim i był regentem w
1 CONT sandomierskim. W 1238 odziedziczył po ojcu księstwo krakowskie. Kontynuował
1 CONT starania o koronę królewską. W czasie najazdu mongolskiego w 1241 stanął na
1 CONT czele koalicji wojsk wielu księstw polskich. Poległ w bitwie pod Legnicą.
1 CONT <http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henryk_Pobo%C5%BCny>
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry II the Pious From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry II the Pious (Polish: Henryk II Pobożny, German: Heinrich II der Fromme;
1 CONT b. ca. 1196 – d. 9 April 1241), was a Piast Duke of Silesia (Wroclaw), Krakow
1 CONT and Southern Greater Poland from 1238 until his death. During 1238 - 1239 he
1 CONT served as a regent of two Piast Duchies: Sandomierz and Opole-Raciborz. He was
1 CONT a son of Henry I the Bearded, Duke of Wroclaw, by his wife (and later Saint)
1 CONT Hedwig, daughter of Berthold IV, Duke of Merania.
1 CONT
1 CONT Life
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Heir of Wroclaw. Co-Ruler of his father
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry was the second son of the Ducal couple, but soon he became in the eldest
1 CONT child of the family when the first-born Bolesław died in 1206. Seven years
1 CONT later (1213) the tragic death of his younger surviving brother Konrad during a
1 CONT hunt let Henry as the sole heir of Lower Silesia. Around 1218 his father
1 CONT arranged his marriage with Princess Anna, daughter of King Ottokar I of
1 CONT Bohemia; this union allowed Henry to interfere actively in the international
1 CONT politics. Henry the Bearded quickly began his efforts to let his sole
1 CONT surviving son as the universal heir of his patrimony, and since 1222, the
1 CONT young prince appears signed documents along with his father. Two years later,
1 CONT he had already a separate stamp and his own notary. In 1227 during a meeting
1 CONT of Piast Dukes in Gąsawa, Henry the Bearded and the High Duke Leszek the White
1 CONT were trapped in an ambush, as a result of which Leszek was killed and the
1 CONT Silesian Duke was seriously wounded; then was the first time that the
1 CONT government resting on the shoulders of young Henry. The second time happened
1 CONT two years later, when Henry the Bearded was capture by Konrad I of Masovia.
1 CONT During these regencies Henry II's performance was perfect, thanks to the early
1 CONT years when his father entrusted him with this tipe of responsibilities. During
1 CONT 1229-30, the Regent led a military expedition in order to recover and secure
1 CONT the possession of Lubusz, and in 1233-34 Henry actively support his father's
1 CONT affairs in Prussia and Greater Poland. The increasing and close cooperation
1 CONT with his father derived in the official nomination of Henry as co-rule of his
1 CONT father in 1234. Since them, were a formal separation of powers: Henry the
1 CONT Bearded styled as Duke of Krakow and Silesia, and Henry as Duke of Silesia and
1 CONT Greater Poland. However, his reign alone had to wait until the death of Henry
1 CONT the Bearded on 19 March 1238. [edit]Reign Alone
1 CONT
1 CONT Although at the time of his father's death Henry was about forty-years-old, he
1 CONT took possesion over his inheritance with some complications. Actually, the
1 CONT first problem was the issue of his succession. The strong authority of Henry
1 CONT the Bearded could secure the hereditary rule in his bloodline only over Lower
1 CONT Silesia. In the Southern Greater Poland and Krakow was ruled by the election
1 CONT between the Piast princes (although exist a testament of former Duke of
1 CONT Greater Poland and Krakow, Władysław III Spindleshanks, who left all his lands
1 CONT to Henry the Bearded, but this was ignored by Konrad of Masovia and Władysław
1 CONT Odonic). In the case of Opole-Raciborz and Sandomierz, Henry could retain his
1 CONT authority as a regent during the minority of their rulers Mieszko II and
1 CONT Bolesław V; however one year later (1239) Henry was compelled to resign to the
1 CONT regency, although he remained on good terms with the Dukes of Opole and
1 CONT Sandomierz, but also managed to retain Kalisz and Rudzka. However, the in the
1 CONT north was more complicated. The Margrave Otto III of Brandenburg, using the
1 CONT death of Henry the Bearded as a pretext, took an important fortress in Santok
1 CONT and sieged Lubusz. Among this, he also inherited from his father the disputes
1 CONT with Konrad of Masovia and Władysław Odonic and with the Church, leaded Pełka,
1 CONT Archbishop of Gniezno, who claimed the benefits promised by Henry the Bearded.
1 CONT But fortunately for Henry, the situation changed unexpectedly after the death
1 CONT of Władysław Odonic on 5 June 1239, leaving two minor sons, Przemysł I and
1 CONT Bolesław. Using these circumstances, the Silesian Duke took the majority of
1 CONT Odonic's possessions (including Gniezno), leaving to Odonic's sons Nakło nad
1 CONT Notecią and Ujście. Henry's next steps however, were dangerous: he abandoned
1 CONT the tradicional alliance of his family with the House of Hohenstaufen and
1 CONT supported Pope Gregory IX, which immediately finished his disputes with the
1 CONT Church[1]. Then, to ended his conflicts with Konrad of Masovia, Henry arranged
1 CONT the marriages of two of his daughters with two Konrad's sons: the eldest,
1 CONT Gertrude, with Bolesław, and the second, Constance, with Casimir. In 1239,
1 CONT Henry lost the fortress occupied in Santok by Brandenburg after his defeat in
1 CONT the Battle of Lubusz. [edit]Mongol invasion. Battle of Legnica and Death It
1 CONT seemed that the most difficult moments for Henry are done. But the worst was
1 CONT yet to come. At the East, a new dangerous opponent appeared: the Mongols,
1 CONT under the leadership of Batu Khan, who, after the defeat and destruction of
1 CONT Russian Grand Principality of Kiev chose as the next target Hungary. Batu Khan
1 CONT rightly recognized that in the event of war with Hungary firstly he had to
1 CONT take control over Poland. So he send there an army of 10 000 men under the
1 CONT leadership of Orda. Already in January 1241 Batu send to Lublin and Zawichost
1 CONT some reconnaissance troops, but the real invasion was launched a month later.
1 CONT In Lesser Poland the Mongols didn't have an equal opponent, defeating and
1 CONT killed almost all the Krakow and Sandomierz nobilty in the Battle of Turskiem
1 CONT (13 February) and the Battles of Tarczkiem and Chmielnikiem(18 March) were,
1 CONT among the casualties, were the voivode of Kraków, Włodzimierz and the
1 CONT castellan Clement of Brzeźnicy. After this all Lesser Poland, including Krakow
1 CONT and Sandomierz, were in the hands of the Mongols. Henry didn't wait for the
1 CONT promised aid from Western rulers and began to concentrate the survived Lesser
1 CONT Poland troops and his own Silesian and Greater Poland troops in Legnica.
1 CONT Europe's rulers, more interested in the struggles between Empire and Papacy,
1 CONT ignored Henry's requests for help. The only foreign troops who joined him were
1 CONT of King Wenceslaus I of Bohemia and the combined forced of both Knights
1 CONT Templars and Hospitallers, but at the last moment they stopping his troops
1 CONT close to Legnica, probably feared that the Christian Army will become an easy
1 CONT prey to the Mongolians troops). The battle took place on 9 April 1241; Henry
1 CONT was defeated and killed in battle. For the defeat, were widely blamed on the
1 CONT Europeans monarchs, who refused to help, and the unexpected and humilliated
1 CONT escape from the battle of Mieszko II the Fat. There are two descriptions of
1 CONT Henry's death, one submitted by Jan Długosz (today considered dubious), and
1 CONT the second by C. de Brigia in his Historii Tartatorum, who, based on relates
1 CONT of direct witnesses, is now considered more reliable. Fortunately for Poland,
1 CONT the Mongols don't intend to occupy the country, since shortly went through
1 CONT Moravia to Hungary, wanting to connect with the main army of Batu Khan.
1 CONT Henry's naked and decapitated body could only be identified by his wife,
1 CONT thanks to a unique anatomical defect: in his left foot, he had six toes, which
1 CONT was confirmed at the opening of his tomb in 1832. Henry was buried in his
1 CONT Franciscan Church of St. Jakub in Wroclaw. Despite only three years of rule,
1 CONT Henry remained in the memories of Greater Poland and Krakow as the perfect
1 CONT Christian Knight and Lord, whose brilliant career was stopped by his early
1 CONT death. [edit]Marriage and Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT By 1218, Henry married with Anna (b. ca. 1204 - d. 23 June 1265), daughter of
1 CONT King Ottokar I of Bohemia. They had ten children: Gertrude (b. ca. 1218/20 -
1 CONT d. 23/30 April 1247), married by 1232 with Bolesław I of Masovia. Constance
1 CONT (b. ca. 1221 - d. ca. 21 February 1257), married by 1239 to Casimir I of
1 CONT Kuyavia. Bolesław II the Bald (b. ca. 1220/25 - d. 25/31 December 1278).
1 CONT Mieszko (b. ca. 1223/27 - d. 1242). Henry III the White (b. 1227/30 - d. 3
1 CONT December 1266). Konrad (b. 1228/31 - d. 6 August ca. 1274). Elizabeth (b. ca.
1 CONT 1232 - d. 16 January 1265), married in 1244 to Przemysł I of Greater Poland.
1 CONT Agnes (b. ca. 1236 - d. 14 May aft. 1278), Abbess of St.Clara in Trebnitz
1 CONT (aft. 1277). Władysław (b. 1237 - d. 27 April 1270), Chancelor of Bohemia
1 CONT (1256), Bishop of Passau (1265) and Archbishop of Salzburg (1265-70). Hedwig
1 CONT (b. ca. 1238/41 - d. 3 April 1318), Abbess of St.Clara in Trebnitz. [edit]
1 CONT
