1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Henry II the Pious (Polish : Henryk II Pobożny, German : Heinrich II der
1 CONT Fromme; ca. 1196 – 9 April 1241 ), was a Piast Duke of Silesia -Wroclaw ,
1 CONT Krakow and Southern Greater Poland from 1238 until his death. During 1238–1239
1 CONT he served as a regent of two Piast Duchies: Sandomierz and Opole -Raciborz .
1 CONT He was a son of Henry I the Bearded , Duke of Wroclaw , by his wife (and later
1 CONT Saint) Hedwig , daughter of Berthold IV, Duke of Merania . Heir of Wrocław.
1 CONT Co-Ruler of his father Monarchy of the Silesian Henries Henry was the second
1 CONT son of the Ducal couple, but soon he became the eldest child of the family
1 CONT when the first-born Bolesław died in 1206. Seven years later (1213) the death
1 CONT of his younger surviving brother Konrad during a hunt left Henry as the sole
1 CONT heir of Lower Silesia. Around 1218 his father arranged his marriage with
1 CONT Princess Anna, daughter of King Ottokar I of Bohemia ; this union allowed
1 CONT Henry to participate actively in international politics. Henry the Bearded
1 CONT quickly began his efforts to designate his sole surviving son as the universal
1 CONT heir of his patrimony, and from 1222, the young prince appears to have signed
1 CONT documents along with his father. Two years later, he had already a separate
1 CONT stamp and his own notary. In 1227 during a meeting of Piast Dukes in Gasawa ,
1 CONT Henry the Bearded and the High Duke Leszek the White were trapped in an
1 CONT ambush, as a result of which Leszek was killed and the Silesian Duke was
1 CONT seriously wounded; this was the first time that the government rested on the
1 CONT shoulders of young Henry. The second time happened two years later, when Henry
1 CONT the Bearded was captured by Konrad I of Masovia. During these regencies Henry
1 CONT II's performance was perfect, thanks to the early years when his father
1 CONT entrusted him with this type of responsibility. During 1229–30, the Regent led
1 CONT a military expedition in order to recover and secure the possession of Lubusz
1 CONT , and in 1233–34 Henry actively supported his father's affairs in Prussia and
1 CONT Greater Poland. The increasing and close cooperation with his father resulted
1 CONT in the official nomination of Henry as co-ruler with his father in 1234. After
1 CONT that came a formal separation of powers: Henry the Bearded was styled as Duke
1 CONT of Krakow and Silesia, and Henry as Duke of Silesia and Greater Poland.
1 CONT However, his sole reign had to wait until the death of Henry the Bearded on 19
1 CONT March 1238 . Reign Alone Although at the time of his father's death Henry was
1 CONT about forty-years-old, he took possession of his inheritance with some
1 CONT complications. Actually, the first problem was the issue of his succession.
1 CONT The strong authority of Henry the Bearded could secure hereditary rule in his
1 CONT bloodline only over Lower Silesia. Southern Greater Poland and Krakow were
1 CONT ruled by election among the Piast princes (although there existed a testament
1 CONT of former Duke of Greater Poland and Krakow, Wladyslaw III Spindleshanks , who
1 CONT left all his lands to Henry the Bearded, but this was ignored by Konrad of
1 CONT Masovia and Władysław Odonic). In the case of Opole -Raciborz and Sandomierz ,
1 CONT Henry could retain his authority as a regent during the minority of their
1 CONT rulers Mieszko II and Boleslaw V ; however one year later (1239) Henry was
1 CONT compelled to resign the regency, although he remained on good terms with the
1 CONT Dukes of Opole and Sandomierz, but also managed to retain Kalisz and Wielun .
1 CONT However, the situation in the north was more complicated. The Margrave Otto
1 CONT IIIof Brandenburg , using the death of Henry the Bearded as a pretext, took an
1 CONT important fortress in Santok and besieged Lubusz. As well as this, he also
1 CONT inherited from his father the disputes with Konrad of Masovia and Władysław
1 CONT Odonic and with the Church, led by Pelka , Archbishop of Gniezno , who claimed
1 CONT the benefits promised by Henry the Bearded. Fortunately for Henry, however,
1 CONT the situation changed unexpectedly after the death of Władysław Odonic on 5
1 CONT June 1239 , leaving two minor sons, Przemysl I and Boleslaw . Using these
1 CONT circumstances, the Silesian Duke took the majority of Odonic's possessions
1 CONT (including Gniezno), leaving to Odonic's sons Naklo nad Notecia and Ujscie .
1 CONT Henry's next moves, however, were dangerous: he abandoned the traditional
1 CONT alliance of his family with the House of Hohenstaufen and supported Pope
1 CONT Gregory IX , which immediately finished his disputes with the Church. Then, to
1 CONT ended his conflicts with Konrad of Masovia, Henry arranged the marriages of
1 CONT two of his daughters to two of Konrad's sons: the eldest, Gertrude, to
1 CONT Boleslaw , and the second, Constance, to Casimir . In 1239, Henry lost the
1 CONT fortress occupied in Santok by Brandenburg after his defeat in the Battle of
1 CONT Lubusz. Mongol invasion. Battle of Legnica and Death It seemed that the most
1 CONT difficult times for Henry were done - but the worst was yet to come. In the
1 CONT East, a new dangerous opponent appeared: the Mongols , under the leadership of
1 CONT Batu Khan , who, after the defeat and destruction of Russian Grand
1 CONT Principality of Kiev chose as the next target Hungary . Batu Khan rightly
1 CONT recognized that in the event of war with Hungary firstly he had to take
1 CONT control over Poland. So he sent there an army of 10 000 men under the
1 CONT leadership of Orda . Already in January 1241 Batu had sent some reconnaissance
1 CONT troops to Lublin and Zawichost , but the real invasion was launched a month
1 CONT later. In Lesser Poland the Mongols didn't have an equal opponent, defeating
1 CONT and killing almost all the Krakow and Sandomierz nobility in the Battle of
1 CONT Tursko (13 February) and the Battles of Tarczek and Chmielnik(18 March) where,
1 CONT among the casualties, were the voivode of Kraków, Wlodzimierz and the
1 CONT castellan Clement of Brzeznica . After this all Lesser Poland, including
1 CONT Krakow and Sandomierz, was in the hands of the Mongols. Henry didn't wait for
1 CONT the promised aid from Western rulers and began to concentrate the surviving
1 CONT Lesser Poland troops and his own Silesian and Greater Poland troops in Legnica
1 CONT . Europe's rulers, more interested in the struggles between Empire and Papacy,
1 CONT ignored Henry's requests for help. The only foreign troops who joined him were
1 CONT of King Wenceslaus I of Bohemia and the combined forced of both Knights
1 CONT Templars and Hospitallers , but at the last moment they stopped their troops
1 CONT close to Legnica, probably fearing that the Christian Army would become an
1 CONT easy prey to the Mongolian troops. The battle took place on 9 April 1241 ;
1 CONT Henry was defeated and killed in battle. The defeat was widely blamed on the
1 CONT European monarchs, who refused to help, and the unexpected and humiliating
1 CONT escape from the battle of Mieszko II the Fat. There are two descriptions of
1 CONT Henry's death, one submitted by Jan Dlugosz (today considered dubious), and
1 CONT the second by C. de Brigia in his Historii Tartatorum, which, based on reports
1 CONT of direct witnesses, is now considered more reliable. Fortunately for Poland,
1 CONT the Mongols didn't intend to occupy the country, since shortly afterward they
1 CONT went through Moravia to Hungary, wanting to connect with the main army of Batu
1 CONT Khan. Henry's naked and decapitated body could only be identified by his wife,
1 CONT thanks to a unique anatomical defect: on his left foot, he had six toes ,
1 CONT which was confirmed at the opening of his tomb in 1832. Henry was buried in
1 CONT his Franciscan Church of St. Jakub in Wroclaw. Despite ruling for only three
1 CONT years, Henry remained in the memories of Greater Poland and Krakow as the
1 CONT perfect Christian Knight and Lord, whose brilliant career was stopped by his
1 CONT early death. Marriage and Issue By 1218, Henry married Anna (ca. 1204 – 23
1 CONT June 1265 ), daughter of King Ottokar I of Bohemia . They had ten children:
1 CONT Gertrude (ca. 1218/20 – 23/30 April 1247 ), married by 1232 to Boleslaw I of
1 CONT Masovia . Constance (ca. 1221 – ca. 21 February 1257 ), married by 1239 to
1 CONT Casimir I of Kuyavia . Boleslaw II the Bald (ca. 1220/25 – 25/31 December 1278
1 CONT ). Mieszko (ca. 1223/27 – 1242). Henry III the White (1227/30 – 3 December
1 CONT 1266 ). Konrad (1228/31 – 6 August ca. 1274 ). Elizabeth (ca. 1232 – 16
1 CONT January 1265 ), married in 1244 to Przemysl I of Greater Poland . Agnes (ca.
1 CONT 1236 – 14 May aft. 1278 ), Abbess of St.Clara in Trebnitz (aft. 1277).
1 CONT Wladyslaw (1237 – 27 April 1270 ), Chancellor of Bohemia (1256), Bishop of
1 CONT Passau (1265) and Archbishop of Salzburg (1265-70). Hedwig (ca. 1238/41 – 3
1 CONT April 1318 ), married Konrad II of Masovia , then became Abbess of St.Clara in
1 CONT Trebnitz.
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT ttp://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SILESIA.htm#HeinrichIIdied1241A HEINRICH of
1 CONT Lower Silesia, son of HEINRICH I Duke of Lower Silesia, Krakow and Greater
1 CONT Poland & his wife Hedwig von Andechs-Merano ([1196]-killed in battle near
1 CONT Liegnitz 9 Apr 1241, bur Breslau Franciscan Church). The Annales Capituli
1 CONT Cracoviensis record that "Henricus suus [=Heinrici ducis Zlesie] filius"
1 CONT succeeded his father in 1238[106]. He succeeded his father in 1238 as HEINRICH
1 CONT II Duke of Lower Silesia, Krakow and Greater Poland. The Annales
1 CONT Wratislavienses record that "dux Heinricus II" was killed by the Tartars who
1 CONT devastated the whole of Silesia and Poland[107]. The Chronicon Polono-
1 CONT Silesiacum record his burial "1241 V Id Apr" at "fratres minores
1 CONT Wratislavie"[108]. The Epytaphia ducum Slezie add that he was killed against
1 CONT the Tartars "Wolstat prope Legnitcz" and buried "in Wratislavia in claustro
1 CONT fratrem Minoruum aput Sanctum Iacobum"[109].
1 CONT
1 CONT m ([1214/18]) ANNA of Bohemia, daughter of PŘEMYSL OTAKAR I King of Bohemia &
1 CONT his second wife Constanza of Hungary ([1201/04]-23 Jun 1265, bur St Clara,
1 CONT Treibnitz). The Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum names "Anna sorore regis Boemie
1 CONT monoculi" as wife of Duke Heinrich II[110]. The Notæ Sanctæ Claræ name "Anna
1 CONT ducissa, filia regis Bohemis, coniunx ducis Henrici", specify that she found
1 CONT the monastery of St Clara, died in 1265 and was buried in the monastery[111].
1 CONT
1 CONT Heinrich II & his wife had ten children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. GERTRUD ([1218/20]-[23/30] Apr [1244/47]). The Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum
1 CONT names "Boleslao et Casimiro" as sons of Konrad, specifying that they married
1 CONT two sisters descended from St Hedwig (wife of Heinrich I Duke of Silesia), a
1 CONT later passage clarifying that they were daughters of Heinrich[112]. The
1 CONT Chronica principum Polonie record that "Conradi filiis…Boleslao et Kazimiro"
1 CONT married "Heynricus…duas neptes" but that the former died childless[113]. The
1 CONT primary source which confirms her name has not yet been identified. m ([1232])
1 CONT as his first wife, BOLESŁAW I Prince of Sandomir, son of KONRAD I Prince of
1 CONT Mazovia & his wife Agafia Sviatoslavna of Novgorod-Sieviersk ([1208]-1248
1 CONT after 25 Feb). Prince of Mazovia 1234.
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. KONSTANZE ([1221/27]-[1253/3 May 1257]). The Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum
1 CONT names "Boleslao et Casimiro" as sons of Konrad, specifying that they married
1 CONT two sisters descended from St Hedwig (wife of Heinrich I Duke of Silesia), a
1 CONT later passage clarifying that they were daughters of Heinrich[114]. The
1 CONT Chronica principum Polonie record that "Conradi filiis…Boleslao et Kazimiro"
1 CONT married "Heynricus…duas neptes"[115]. The primary source which confirms her
1 CONT name has not yet been identified. m (1239) as his second wife, KASIMIERZ Duke
1 CONT of Kujavia, son of KONRAD I Prince of Mazovia & his wife Agafia Sviatoslavna
1 CONT of Novgorod-Sieviersk ([1211]-14 Nov 1267)
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. BOLESLAW ([1220/25]-[26/31] Dec 1278, bur Liegnitz Dominikanerkirche). The
1 CONT Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum names (in order) "Boleslaum Calvum Legniczcensem,
1 CONT Henricum Wratislaviensem, Conradum Glogoviensem duces…et Vlodislaum
1 CONT Salczburgensem archiepiscopum" as the four sons of Heinrich II & his
1 CONT wife[116]. He succeeded his father in 1241 as BOLESLAW II "Rogatka/Calvus"
1 CONT Duke of Lower Silesia.
1 CONT
1 CONT \- see below.
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. MIESZKO ([1223/27]-[1241/42]). The primary source which confirms his
1 CONT parentage has not yet been identified.
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. HEINRICH ([1222/30]-3 Dec 1266, bur Treibnitz St Clara). The Chronicon
1 CONT Polono-Silesiacum names (in order) "Boleslaum Calvum Legniczcensem, Henricum
1 CONT Wratislaviensem, Conradum Glogoviensem duces…et Vlodislaum Salczburgensem
1 CONT archiepiscopum" as the four sons of Heinrich II & his wife[117]. He succeeded
1 CONT in 1248 as HEINRICH III "White" Duke of Breslau. The Chronica principum
1 CONT Polonie records that "Heinrico" inherited "Legnicz et Glogoviam"[118]. The
1 CONT Annales Wratislavienses record the death "1266 III Non Dec" of "dux Heinricus
1 CONT frater Wizlai, nepos beate Hedwigis"[119]. The Epytaphia ducum Slezie add that
1 CONT he was poisoned[120]. The Chronica principum Polonie records that "Heinricus
1 CONT tercius" was buried "apud sanctam Claram in Wratislavia"[121]. m firstly
1 CONT (1252) as her second husband, JUDYTA of Mazovia, widow of MIESZKO I Herzog von
1 CONT Oppeln und Ratibor [Piast], daughter of KONRAD I Prince of Mazovia [Piast] &
1 CONT his wife Agafia Sviatoslavna of Novgorod-Sieviersk ([1222/25]-[4 Dec
1 CONT 1257/65]). The Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum refers to the wife of "Mesico
1 CONT Crassus [dux] Ratheborgensis" as "filiam ducis Cuiavie et Mazovie Conradi",
1 CONT without naming her, and records her second marriage with "Heinricus tercius
1 CONT Wratislaviensis"[122]. The Chronica principum Polonie records that "Heinricus
1 CONT tercius" married "filia Conradi Coyaviensis ducis, relicta Mesiconis
1 CONT Rathiboriensis" who was the mother of his children[123]. The primary source
1 CONT which confirms her name has not yet been identified. m secondly (before 3 Dec
1 CONT 1266) as her first husband, HELENE von Sachsen, daughter of ALBRECHT I Duke of
1 CONT Saxony [Askanier] & his third wife Helene von Braunschweig (-12 Jun 1309, bur
1 CONT Nürnberg Barfüsserkirche). The Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum refers to the
1 CONT second wife of Duke Heinrich III as "filiam ducis Saxonie" specifying that she
1 CONT married secondly "burgravio de Nurenberg"[124]. The Chronica principum Polonie
1 CONT records that "tercius Heinricus" married secondly "filiam…ducis Saxonie", who
1 CONT later married "Burgravio Nurenbergensi"[125]. The primary source which names
1 CONT her and more specifically confirms her second marriage has not so far been
1 CONT identified. She married secondly (before 10 Apr 1280) as his second wife,
1 CONT Friedrich III Burggraf von Nürnberg. Heinrich III & his first wife had [four
1 CONT or more] children:
1 CONT
1 CONT a) HEDWIG ([1252/56]-before 14 Dec 1300). m firstly ([1271/72]) HEINRICH von
1 CONT Meissen Herr des Pleissenlandes, son of ALBRECHT II "der Entartete" Markgraf
1 CONT von Meissen, Landgraf of Thuringia [Wettin] & his wife Margareta von
1 CONT Hohenstaufen (21 Mar 1256-[25 Jan/23 Jul] 1282). m secondly ([6 May/23 Jul]
1 CONT 1283, dispensation Rome 18 Dec 1289) OTTO I Fürst von Anhalt Graf von
1 CONT Aschersleben, son of HEINRICH II Fürst von Anhalt in Aschersleben & his wife
1 CONT Mechtild von Braunschweig-Lüneburg (-[25 Jun 1304/25 Jan 1305]).
1 CONT
1 CONT b) HEINRICH ([1257/58]-murdered 23 Jun 1290, bur Breslau Kloster
1 CONT Heiligenkreuz). The Chronicon Polono-Silesiacum refers to the children of
1 CONT "Heinricus tercius Wratislaviensis" and his wife "filiam ducis Cuiavie et
1 CONT Mazovie Conradi" as "filiam et filium Heinricum quartum Wratislaviensem
1 CONT ducem"[126]. He was brought up at the court of Přemysl Ottokar II King of
1 CONT Bohemia[127]. He succeeded in 1270 as HEINRICH IV "Probus" Duke of Breslau. On
1 CONT the death without heirs in 1288 of Leszek II "Czarny/the Black" Prince of
1 CONT Krakow, Sandomir, Sieradz and Łęczyca, he inherited Krakow and Sandomir on the
1 CONT basis of a prior agreement between the major Polish princes[128]. Duke of
1 CONT Poland 1288. He aimed to reunite the Polish crown but the other princes
1 CONT refused to accept him as their leader. His distant cousin Władysław "Lokietek"
1 CONT occupied Krakow but was expelled within a few months[129]. The Annales
1 CONT Cracovienses Compilati record that "Henricus dux Wratizlavienisis intoxicatus
1 CONT est veneno et obiit" in 1291[130]. The Epytaphia ducum Slezie record the death
1 CONT "1290 XI Kal Aug" of "dux Wratislawiensis Henricus quartus qui dictus est
1 CONT Probus, filius tercii Henrici", specifying that he too was poisoned and was
1 CONT buried "Wratislawie ad Sanctam Crucem" which he had founded[131]. He appointed
1 CONT Przemysł II Duke of Greater Poland as his successor[132]. m firstly
1 CONT ([1277/80]) --- von Oppeln, daughter of WLADISLAW Duke of Oppeln [Piast] & his
1 CONT wife Euphemia of Poland [Piast] ([1265]-[1287/88]). The primary source which
1 CONT confirms her parentage and marriage has not yet been identified. m secondly
1 CONT ([1287/88]) MECHTILD von Brandenburg, daughter of OTTO V Markgraf von
1 CONT Brandenburg & his wife Judith von Henneberg (-before 1 Jun 1298, bur Kloster
1 CONT Lehnin). Pulcawa's Bohemian Chronicle names "Beatricem…Mechthildim…
1 CONT Gitam…Gunegundim" as the four daughters of "Otto longus filius Ottonis tercii"
1 CONT & his wife, specifying that Mechtild married "Henrico…duci Wratislauie" and
1 CONT survived her husband and was buried in "Lenynensi monasterio"[133].
1 CONT
1 CONT c) other children ([1262/65]-before 1267).
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. ELISABETH ([1224/32]-16 Jan 1265). The Chronica principum Polonie names
1 CONT "Elisabeth et Agnethem" as two daughters of "Henricus occisus a Thartharis"
1 CONT and his wife "domina Anna sorore regis Bohemie monoculi"[134]. The Chronicon
1 CONT Polono-Silesiacum specifies that one of the four daughters of Heinrich married
1 CONT "duci Gnesnensi Primisloni" but does not specify which one[135]. m (1244)
1 CONT PRZEMYSŁ of Poland, son of WŁADYSŁAW Prince of Kalisch, Poznan and Greater
1 CONT Poland & his wife Hedwig von Pommerellen ([4 Jun/9 Aug] [1221]-4 Jun 1257). He
1 CONT succeeded in 1247 as PRZEMYSŁ I Prince of Poznan.
1 CONT
1 CONT 7\. KONRAD ([1228/31]-[6 Aug 1273/1274], bur Glogau St Marie). The Chronicon
1 CONT Polono-Silesiacum names (in order) "Boleslaum Calvum Legniczcensem, Henricum
1 CONT Wratislaviensem, Conradum Glogoviensem duces…et Vlodislaum Salczburgensem
1 CONT archiepiscopum" as the four sons of Heinrich II & his wife[136]. He succeeded
1 CONT in 1241 as KONRAD I Duke of Glogau. Bishop of Passau, resigned 1250.
1 CONT
1 CONT \- DUKES of GLOGAU.
1 CONT
1 CONT 8\. WLADISLAW (1237-27 Apr 1270, bur Salzburg). The Chronicon Polono-
1 CONT Silesiacum names (in order) "Boleslaum Calvum Legniczcensem, Henricum
1 CONT Wratislaviensem, Conradum Glogoviensem duces…et Vlodislaum Salczburgensem
1 CONT archiepiscopum" as the four sons of Heinrich II & his wife, specifying in a
1 CONT later passage that he was buried in Salzburg[137]. Archbishop of Salzburg.
1 CONT
1 CONT 9\. AGNES ([1230/36]-14 May after 1277). The Chronica principum Polonie names
1 CONT "Elisabeth et Agnethem" as two daughters of "Henricus occisus a Thartharis"
1 CONT and his wife "domina Anna sorore regis Bohemie monoculi"[138]. The Chronicon
1 CONT Polono-Silesiacum specifies that one of the four daughters of Heinrich was
1 CONT "infirma corpore…sed robusta, mento infirme" and left by her mother with the
1 CONT Franciscans at "Sanctam Claram Wratizlavie"[139]. The daughter is unnamed in
1 CONT this passage. However, by process of elimination it must refer either to Agnes
1 CONT or Hedwig. Abbess of St Clara, Trebnitz.
1 CONT
1 CONT 10\. HEDWIG ([1238/41]-3 Apr 1318). The Notæ Sanctæ Claræ record that
1 CONT "Hedwigis, filia ducis Henrici secundi" was second abbess of St Clara,
1 CONT Trebnitz[140].
1 CONT Henry II the Pious (Polish: Henryk II Pobozny, German: Heinrich II der Fromme;
1 CONT ca. 1196 - 9 April 1241), was a Piast Duke of Silesia-Breslau, Krakow and
1 CONT Southern Greater Poland from 1238 until his death. During 1238-1239 he served
1 CONT as a regent of two Piast Duchies: Sandomierz and Opole-Raciborz.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was a son of Henry I the Bearded, Duke of Breslau, by his wife (and later
1 CONT Saint) Hedwig, daughter of Berthold IV, Duke of Merania.
1 CONT
1 CONT Heir of Breslau. Co-Ruler of his father
1 CONT
1 CONT Monarchy of the Silesian HenriesHenry was the second son of the Ducal couple,
1 CONT but soon he became in the eldest child of the family when the first-born
1 CONT Boleslaw died in 1206. Seven years later (1213) the tragic death of his
1 CONT younger surviving brother Konrad during a hunt let Henry as the sole heir of
1 CONT Lower Silesia. Around 1218 his father arranged his marriage with Princess
1 CONT Anna, daughter of King Ottokar I of Bohemia; this union allowed Henry to
1 CONT interfere actively in the international politics.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry the Bearded quickly began his efforts to let his sole surviving son as
1 CONT the universal heir of his patrimony, and since 1222, the young prince appears
1 CONT signed documents along with his father. Two years later, he had already a
1 CONT separate stamp and his own notary. In 1227 during a meeting of Piast Dukes in
1 CONT Gasawa, Henry the Bearded and the High Duke Leszek the White were trapped in
1 CONT an ambush, as a result of which Leszek was killed and the Silesian Duke was
1 CONT seriously wounded; then was the first time that the government resting on the
1 CONT shoulders of young Henry. The second time happened two years later, when Henry
1 CONT the Bearded was capture by Konrad I of Masovia. During these regencies Henry
1 CONT II's performance was perfect, thanks to the early years when his father
1 CONT entrusted him with this type of responsibility. During 1229-30, the Regent led
1 CONT a military expedition in order to recover and secure the possession of Lubusz,
1 CONT and in 1233-34 Henry actively support his father's affairs in Prussia and
1 CONT Greater Poland. The increasing and close cooperation with his father derived
1 CONT in the official nomination of Henry as co-rule of his father in 1234. Since
1 CONT them, were a formal separation of powers: Henry the Bearded styled as Duke of
1 CONT Krakow and Silesia, and Henry as Duke of Silesia and Greater Poland. However,
1 CONT his reign alone had to wait until the death of Henry the Bearded on 19 March
1 CONT 1238.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Reign Alone
1 CONT
1 CONT Coat of arms of Silesian PiastsAlthough at the time of his father's death
1 CONT Henry was about forty-years-old, he took possession over his inheritance with
1 CONT some complications. Actually, the first problem was the issue of his
1 CONT succession. The strong authority of Henry the Bearded could secure the
1 CONT hereditary rule in his bloodline only over Lower Silesia. In the Southern
1 CONT Greater Poland and Krakow was ruled by the election between the Piast princes
1 CONT (although exist a testament of former Duke of Greater Poland and Krakow,
1 CONT Wladyslaw III Spindleshanks, who left all his lands to Henry the Bearded, but
1 CONT this was ignored by Konrad of Masovia and Wladyslaw Odonic). In the case of
1 CONT Opole-Raciborz and Sandomierz, Henry could retain his authority as a regent
1 CONT during the minority of their rulers Mieszko II and Boleslaw V; however one
1 CONT year later (1239) Henry was compelled to resign to the regency, although he
1 CONT remained on good terms with the Dukes of Opole and Sandomierz, but also
1 CONT managed to retain Kalisz and Wielun. However, the in the north was more
1 CONT complicated. The Margrave Otto III of Brandenburg, using the death of Henry
1 CONT the Bearded as a pretext, took an important fortress in Santok and sieged
1 CONT Lubusz. Among this, he also inherited from his father the disputes with Konrad
1 CONT of Masovia and Wladyslaw Odonic and with the Church, leaded Pelka, Archbishop
1 CONT of Gniezno, who claimed the benefits promised by Henry the Bearded.
1 CONT
1 CONT But fortunately for Henry, the situation changed unexpectedly after the death
1 CONT of Wladyslaw Odonic on 5 June 1239, leaving two minor sons, Przemysl I and
1 CONT Boleslaw. Using these circumstances, the Silesian Duke took the majority of
1 CONT Odonic's possessions (including Gniezno), leaving to Odonic's sons Naklo nad
1 CONT Notecia and Ujscie. Henry's next steps however, were dangerous: he abandoned
1 CONT the traditional alliance of his family with the House of Hohenstaufen and
1 CONT supported Pope Gregory IX, which immediately finished his disputes with the
1 CONT Church[1]. Then, to ended his conflicts with Konrad of Masovia, Henry arranged
1 CONT the marriages of two of his daughters with two Konrad's sons: the eldest,
1 CONT Gertrude, with Boleslaw, and the second, Constance, with Casimir. In 1239,
1 CONT Henry lost the fortress occupied in Santok by Brandenburg after his defeat in
1 CONT the Battle of Lubusz.
1 CONT
1 CONT Mongol invasion. Battle of Legnica and Death
1 CONT It seemed that the most difficult moments for Henry are done. But the worst
1 CONT was yet to come. At the East, a new dangerous opponent appeared: the Mongols,
1 CONT under the leadership of Batu Khan, who, after the defeat and destruction of
1 CONT Russian Grand Principality of Kiev chose as the next target Hungary. Batu Khan
1 CONT rightly recognized that in the event of war with Hungary firstly he had to
1 CONT take control over Poland. So he send there an army of 10 000 men under the
1 CONT leadership of Orda. Already in January 1241 Batu send to Lublin and Zawichost
1 CONT some reconnaissance troops, but the real invasion was launched a month later.
1 CONT In Lesser Poland the Mongols didn't have an equal opponent, defeating and
1 CONT killed almost all the Krakow and Sandomierz nobility in the Battle of Tursko
1 CONT (13 February) and the Battles of Tarczek and Chmielnik(18 March) where, among
1 CONT the casualties, were the voivode of Kraków, Wlodzimierz and the castellan
1 CONT Clement of Brzeznica. After this all Lesser Poland, including Krakow and
1 CONT Sandomierz, were in the hands of the Mongols.
1 CONT
1 CONT Henry didn't wait for the promised aid from Western rulers and began to
1 CONT concentrate the survived Lesser Poland troops and his own Silesian and Greater
1 CONT Poland troops in Legnica. Europe's rulers, more interested in the struggles
1 CONT between Empire and Papacy, ignored Henry's requests for help. The only foreign
1 CONT troops who joined him were of King Wenceslaus I of Bohemia and the combined
1 CONT forced of both Knights Templars and Hospitallers, but at the last moment they
1 CONT stopped their troops close to Legnica, probably fearing that the Christian
1 CONT Army would become an easy prey to the Mongolian troops. The battle took place
1 CONT on 9 April 1241; Henry was defeated and killed in battle.
1 CONT
1 CONT The defeat was widely blamed on the Europeans monarchs, who refused to help,
1 CONT and the unexpected and humiliating escape from the battle of Mieszko II the
1 CONT Fat. There are two descriptions of Henry's death, one submitted by Jan Dlugosz
1 CONT (today considered dubious), and the second by C. de Brigia in his Historii
1 CONT Tartatorum, who, based on relates of direct witnesses, is now considered more
1 CONT reliable. Fortunately for Poland, the Mongols didn't intend to occupy the
1 CONT country, since shortly afterward they went through Moravia to Hungary, wanting
1 CONT to connect with the main army of Batu Khan. Henry's naked and decapitated body
1 CONT could only be identified by his wife, thanks to a unique anatomical defect: on
1 CONT his left foot, he had six toes, which was confirmed at the opening of his tomb
1 CONT in 1832. Henry was buried in his Franciscan Church of St. Jakub in Wroclaw.
1 CONT
1 CONT Despite only three years of rule, Henry remained in the memories of Greater
1 CONT Poland and Krakow as the perfect Christian Knight and Lord, whose brilliant
1 CONT career was stopped by his early death.
1 CONT
1 CONT Marriage and Issue
1 CONT By 1218, Henry married with Anna (ca. 1204 - 23 June 1265), daughter of King
1 CONT Ottokar I of Bohemia. They had ten children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Gertrude (ca. 1218/20 - 23/30 April 1247), married by 1232 with Boleslaw I of
1 CONT Masovia.
1 CONT Constance (ca. 1221 - ca. 21 February 1257), married by 1239 to Casimir I of
1 CONT Kuyavia.
1 CONT Boleslaw II the Bald (ca. 1220/25 - 25/31 December 1278).
1 CONT Mieszko (ca. 1223/27 - 1242).
1 CONT Henry III the White (1227/30 - 3 December 1266).
1 CONT Konrad (1228/31 - 6 August ca. 1274).
1 CONT Elizabeth (ca. 1232 - 16 January 1265), married in 1244 to Przemysl I of
1 CONT Greater Poland.
1 CONT Agnes (ca. 1236 - 14 May aft. 1278), Abbess of St.Clara in Trebnitz (aft.
1 CONT 1277).
1 CONT Wladyslaw (1237 - 27 April 1270), Chancellor of Bohemia (1256), Bishop of
1 CONT Passau (1265) and Archbishop of Salzburg (1265-70).
1 CONT Hedwig (ca. 1238/41 - 3 April 1318), Abbess of St.Clara in Trebnitz.
1 CONT
1 CONT See also
