0 @N00850@ NOTE geni:about_me **Anna Czeska** – **królewna czeska** z rodu Przemyślidów,
1 CONT **księżna śląska** , żona Henryka II Pobożnego.
1 CONT <http://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anna_Przemy%C5%9Blidka>
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna of Bohemia (Czech: Anna Lehnická, polish: Anna Przemyślidka (1204 – 26
1 CONT June 1265)) was the Duchess consort of Silesia (1238-1241); she was the
1 CONT daughter of Ottokar I , King of Bohemia and his second wife Constance of
1 CONT Hungary . Her maternal grandparents were Béla III of Hungary and his first
1 CONT wife Agnes of Antioch. Life Anna was born in Prague. Around the age of twelve
1 CONT she was married (1216) to Henry II the Pious , Duke of Silesia , to whom she
1 CONT bore ten children before he succeeded to the dukedom in 1238. During the Tatar
1 CONT invasions, the duchess was sent with the other female members of the royal
1 CONT family to the safety of the fortress of Krossen . Duke Henry was killed at
1 CONT Wahlstatt near Liegnitz during the Battle of Legnica (9 April 1241), his body
1 CONT being so diminished that the duchess had to tell those searching for his body
1 CONT to recognize him by the peculiarity of a sixth toe on his left foot. Anna
1 CONT buried her husband in the Franciscan convent at Breslau , which Henry had
1 CONT begun to build, and which, in 1242, the duchess completed. During her lengthy
1 CONT widowhood, Anna suffered greatly from the violent temper of her son Boleslaw
1 CONT II the Bald (1241-1278).
1 CONT \--------------------
1 CONT Anne of Bohemia (1204–1265) From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT For other uses, see Anne of Bohemia (disambiguation). Anna of Bohemia (czech:
1 CONT Anna Lehnická, polish: Anna Przemyślidka (1204 – 26 June 1265)) was the
1 CONT Duchess consort of Silesia (1238-1241), she was the daughter of Ottokar I,
1 CONT King of Bohemia and his second wife Constance of Hungary. Her maternal
1 CONT grandparents were Béla III of Hungary and his first wife Agnes of Antioch Anna
1 CONT was born in Prague. Around the age of twelve she was married (1216) to Henry
1 CONT II the Pious, Duke of Silesia, to whom she bore eleven children before he
1 CONT succeeded to the dukedom in 1238. During the Tatar invasions, the duchess was
1 CONT sent with the other female members of the royal family to the safety of the
1 CONT fortress of Krossen. Duke Henry was killed at Wahlstatt near Liegnitz during
1 CONT the Battle of Legnica (9 April 1241), his body being so diminished that the
1 CONT duchess had to tell those searching for his body to recognize him by the
1 CONT peculiarity of a sixth toe on his left foot. Anna buried her husband in the
1 CONT Franciscan convent at Breslau, which Henry had begun to build, and which, in
1 CONT 1242, the duchess completed. During her lengthy widowhood, Anna suffered
1 CONT greatly from the violent temper of her son Boleslav II (1241-1278). Anna's
1 CONT younger sons included Henry III, duke of Silesia-Breslau, Conrad I, duke of
1 CONT Glogau, and Vladislav (1237-1270), who became Bishop of Bamberg (1257) and
1 CONT elector of Passau and Salzburg. Of her daughters, Gertrude (1219-1246) became
1 CONT the first wife of Boleslav I, duke of Masovia, whilst Agnes (c. 1233-1278) and
1 CONT Hedwig (c. 1240-1318) both served as abbess of Santa Clara at Treibnitz, the
1 CONT convent founded by their paternal grandmother, St Hedwig (1174-1243). Anne
1 CONT died on 26 June 1265, aged sixty-one. [edit]References
1 CONT
1 CONT A.P.C. Dunbar, (1904) A Dictionary of Saintly Women, Vol I, (Anna 19), London
1 CONT Detlev Schwennicke, (1980) Europaische Stammtafeln, Vol VIII - Part I, Table
1 CONT 9, Marburg
1 CONT \--------------------
