1 CONT Władysław Odonic
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Jump to:navigation, search
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław Odonic's seal, dated from 1231.
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław (also named Włodzisław) Odonic (nicknamed Plwacz) (Polish: Władysław
1 CONT (Włodzisław) Odonic (Plwacz); b. ca. 1190 - d. 5 June 1239), was a Duke of
1 CONT Kalisz during 1207-1217, Duke of Poznań during 1216-1217, in 1223 ruler over
1 CONT Ujście, from 1225 ruler over Nakło, Duke of all Greater Poland during
1 CONT 1229-1234, and since 1234 until his death ruler over only the north and east
1 CONT of the Warta river (some historians believed that shortly before his death, he
1 CONT lost Ujście and Nakło).
1 CONT
1 CONT He was the eldest son of Odon, Duke of Kalisz, by his wife Viacheslava,
1 CONT daughter of Yaroslav Vladimirovich "Osmomysl", Prince of Halych. Władysław
1 CONT probably received his name after either his paternal uncle Władysław III
1 CONT Spindleshanks or his ancestor Władysław I Herman.
1 CONT
1 CONT The nickname "Plwacz" (English: the Spitter) was already given to him in the
1 CONT 13th century chronicles. It's unknown if he was named in that way for a
1 CONT disease who affected his throat or because he had bad manners. Another
1 CONT nickname used in the contemporary sources was "Odonic", a corruption of his
1 CONT patronymic Odowic ("son of Odon"); here is also unknown why the sources
1 CONT persisted in the erroneus form instead to used the correct.[1]
1 CONT
