1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Life
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Early Years
1 CONT
1 CONT Duke Odon of Kalisz died on 20 April 1194. Władysław (then only a four years
1 CONT old child) and his siblings were placed under the care of his paternal uncle
1 CONT Władysław III Spindleshanks (half-brother of Odon), who acted as regent over
1 CONT the south of Greater Poland (Duchy created to Odon by his father in 1182). The
1 CONT Duchy of Kalisz was directly annexed by his grandfather Mieszko III the Old to
1 CONT his domains.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] First War against Władysław III Spindleshanks
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1206 Władysław was declared an adult and began to claim the government of
1 CONT his domains. For him was especially hard to accept the surrender of the Duchy
1 CONT of Kalisz (which the young prince believed to be part of his rightful
1 CONT heritage) by his uncle to Henry I the Bearded, Duke of Wrocław, in exchange of
1 CONT Lubusz.
1 CONT
1 CONT Unable to reach a favorable agreement with his uncle, Władysław decided to
1 CONT declared the open war against Władysław III Spindleshanks. His attempt to
1 CONT overthrow the High Duke was strongly supported by part of the Greater Poland
1 CONT nobility and the Archbishop of Gniezno Henryk Kietlicz, who also wanted to
1 CONT obtain more independence and benefits for the Church.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Duke of Kalisz
1 CONT
1 CONT However, despite the efforts of both Władysław and Archbishop Kietlicz (who
1 CONT even launched an anathema against Władysław III), the rebellion was short-
1 CONT lived and unsuccessfully. Both were banished from the country; Władysław took
1 CONT refuge in Wrocław in the court of Henry I the Bearded, who, despite his good
1 CONT relations with Władysław III Spindleshanks, decided to fully supported the
1 CONT rebel prince. One year later, in 1207, Henry I the Bearded gave to Władysław
1 CONT the Duchy of Kalisz, but with the condition that, in case he could recover the
1 CONT south Greater Poland lands, Kalisz returns to Silesia.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Congress of Głogów. Attempt to reconcile with Władysław III
1 CONT Spindleshanks
1 CONT
1 CONT Despite these gestures, Henry I the Bearded refused to support militarily
1 CONT Władysław, trying to reconcile both princes through diplomatic channels. In
1 CONT 1208 was arranged a meeting in Głogów, where the Duke of Wrocław and the
1 CONT Bishops of Lubusz and Poznań discovered that the resolution of this situation
1 CONT was a difficult task. The meeting ended with a partial success, because
1 CONT Władysław III Spindleshanks managed to reach an agreement with the Archbishop
1 CONT Kietlicz, who could return to Gniezno, and the promise of restitution of all
1 CONT his goods, in exchange for lifting the anathema. However, Władysław was left
1 CONT with nothing.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Close cooperation with the Church
1 CONT
1 CONT In July 1210, was organizated at Borzykowa a meeting between local Bishops and
1 CONT princes, in order to solve the problematic issue of the Pope Innocent III
1 CONT Bull, who restored the idea of a unificated Seniorate Province. Then, was
1 CONT formed a coalition between Władysław, Leszek I the White (High Duke of Poland
1 CONT since 1206) and Konrad I of Masovia against the politics of Władysław III
1 CONT Spindleshanks and Mieszko I Tanglefoot, Duke of Opole-Racibórz. Also, during
1 CONT the meeting were confirmed the privileges obtained by the Polish church at
1 CONT Łęczyca in 1180, included that of exemption from secular tribunals.
1 CONT
1 CONT Leszek I the White, wanting to ensure the support of the Church, along with
1 CONT other Piast princes, then gave a Great Privilege, which ensured the integrity
1 CONT of territorial possession of the Bishops (the privilege wasn't signed by Henry
1 CONT I the Bearded and Władysław III Spindleshanks, who later was complied to
1 CONT accept the provisions established there). Mieszko I Tanglefoot wasn't present
1 CONT in Borzykowa; with the support of the Gryfici family, he decided to lead his
1 CONT army and marched against Kraków, where the confusion among the citizens left
1 CONT him in total control over the capital without fighting and became in the new
1 CONT High Duke.
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław's policy of full cooperation with the Church resulted in the issue
1 CONT of a Bull by Pope Innocent III on 13 May 1211, in which the Pope declared him
1 CONT under his protection. Also, he actively supported the monastic orders, notably
1 CONT the Cistercians, whose on 29 July 1210 gave lands in the district of Przemęt.
1 CONT On 20 October 1213 was founded a newly Cistercian monastery in Ołobok over
1 CONT Prosna, who was richly furnished by Władysław.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1215 Władysław took part in the congress of princes and Bishops in Wolbórz,
1 CONT where the Duke of Kalisz, together with the other Piast rulers (the meeting
1 CONT was also attended by Leszek I the White, Konrad I of Masovia and Casimir I of
1 CONT Opole) agreed to extend the economic and legal benefits for the Church.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Duke of Southern Greater Poland. Conflict with Henry I the Bearded
1 CONT
1 CONT A year later, Archbishop Kietlicz supported the provisions of the IV Lateran
1 CONT Council, were the papal authority was reforced and the Fifth Crusade was
1 CONT organizated. Also, and with the support of other Polish princes, the
1 CONT Archbishop promoted the surrender of the southern Greater Poland lands to
1 CONT Władysław. Finally, in 1216 Władysław III Spindleshanks gave to his nephew the
1 CONT rule over southern Greater Poland.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, the receipt of lands near Obra River created a new problem to
1 CONT Władysław. In accordance with the treaty of 1206 between him and Henry I the
1 CONT Bearded, the Duchy of Kalisz had to return to Silesia if Władysław recover his
1 CONT heritage. In addition, the previous excellent relations with the Archbishop
1 CONT Kietlicz also began to deteriorate, and this caused that Władysław managed to
1 CONT get a new protectionist Bull from the Pope (issued on 9 February 1217), this
1 CONT time to protect him against the claims of the local Church hierarchy.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1217 the congress in Danków proved to be very dangerous for Władysław,
1 CONT because there his uncle and Leszek I the White signed an agreement for mutual
1 CONT succession, which obviously reduced considerably the chances of the young
1 CONT prince to acquired, by peaceful means, his uncle's inheritance.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Second War against Władysław III Spindleshanks. Escape from the country
1 CONT
1 CONT The agreement of Danków (were Henry I the Bearded soon joined) and the death
1 CONT of Archbishop Kietlicz caused that Władysław III Spindleshanks decided to
1 CONT attack his nephew, with the benevolent neutrality of the other Piast rulers.
1 CONT Władysław wasn't able to defend himself and his lands; shortly after he escape
1 CONT to Hungary.
1 CONT
1 CONT From the first stage of Władysław's exile from Poland, almost nothing is
1 CONT known. There are some assumptions that the prince attended the expedition of
1 CONT King Andrew II of Hungary to Palestine. Subsequently, he probably went to
1 CONT Bohemia and Germany, where he tried to encourage the help of local rulers.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Arrival to Pomerania. Conquest of Ujście and Nakło
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1218 Władysław finally arrived to the court of Swantopolk II of Pomerania
1 CONT (probably his brother-in-law),[2] who wanted to his own political emancipation
1 CONT and broke his homage to Leszek I the White. Swantopolk II promised Władysław
1 CONT his support in the reconquer his heritage.
1 CONT
1 CONT Thanks to the help of the Pomeranian Duke, in 1223 Władysław could capture the
1 CONT north-eastern fortress of Ujście. Two years later (in 1225), he could repelled
1 CONT the counter-attack of his uncle and could obtain the district of Nakło.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] New phase in the War against Władysław III Spindleshanks. Defeat of
1 CONT voivode Dobrogost
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1227 Władysław III Spindleshanks finally decided to directly attack his
1 CONT nephew. For this purpose, he sent troops under the command of a strong voivode
1 CONT Dobrogost, who besieged Ujście. Surprisingly, the voivode not only failed to
1 CONT conquer the strongly fortified city, but Władysław made a surprise over
1 CONT Dobrogost's troops and on 15 July, the voivode was completey defeated and
1 CONT killed. Thanks to this victory, Władysław was able to take most of Greater
1 CONT Poland.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] The Congress of Gąsawa and his tragic consecuences. Responsability over
1 CONT Leszek I the White's death
1 CONT
1 CONT Feared that he could lost all his domains, Władysław III Spindleshanks decided
1 CONT to find a peaceful solution to the dispute with his nephew. For this purpose,
1 CONT was convened in November 1227 a solemn convention of the Piast princes,
1 CONT bishops and nobles in the Kuyavian district of Gąsawa. Among the princes who
1 CONT assisted to the meeting were Leszek I the White, Henry I the Bearded, Konrad I
1 CONT of Masovia and Władysław Odonic. For unknown reasons, at the end Władysław III
1 CONT Spindleshanks didn't appear in the Congress, perhaps because his interests
1 CONT here probably watched by Paul, Bishop of Poznań. In addition of this conflict
1 CONT in Gąsawa were also discuss proposals for a solution to the usurpation of the
1 CONT Ducal title by Swantopolk II of Pomerania (who used the confusion in Greater
1 CONT Poland to seized Nakło, who belonged to Władysław).
1 CONT
1 CONT To the tragic end of the meeting took place on the morning of 24 November,
1 CONT when during a short break from the deliberations the princes were attacked by
1 CONT Pomeranians, who killed Leszek I the White and seriously injured Henry I the
1 CONT Bearded. By sources and historiography, the main culprit in the murder rested
1 CONT on Duke Swantopolk II, although there are some who believe that Władysław
1 CONT Odonic was also involved in the crime (however, contemporary historians were
1 CONT inclined to absolved Władysław from any part in the attack).
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Friendly relations with Konrad I of Masovia. New struggles with
1 CONT Władysław III Spindleshanks
1 CONT
1 CONT The events of Gąsawa led a very complicated situation in Poland, and brought
1 CONT little benefits to Władysław in his conflict with his uncle. At the beginning
1 CONT of 1228 Władysław III Spindleshanks, with the help of Silesian forces, managed
1 CONT to defeat his nephew under unknown circumstances, taking him prisoner.
1 CONT However, the Duke of Greater Poland couldn't used this success, because even
1 CONT in the same year, Władysław, thanks to the absence of his uncle in Lesser
1 CONT Poland, managed to escape to Płock, where he established friendly relations
1 CONT with Konrad I of Masovia.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Deposition of Władysław III Spindleshanks from Greater Poland and his
1 CONT death
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1229 took place a concerted action of Władysław and Konrad I of Masovia
1 CONT against Władysław III Spindleshanks. Odonic then managed to control his
1 CONT uncle's domains. A much less successful was the participation of Konrad I,
1 CONT whose troops unsuccessfully besieged Kalisz. Władysław III Spindleshanks
1 CONT ultimately couldn't defend himself and soon after he escaped to Racibórz in
1 CONT Silesia. Władysław Odonic's success was complete, but the risk still remains:
1 CONT in the spring of 1231 Henry I the Bearded launched an expedition against
1 CONT Greater Poland with the purprose of restored Władysław III Spindleshanks, but
1 CONT soon after the Silesian troops were defeated at the walls of Gniezno.
1 CONT
1 CONT On 3 November 1231 Władysław III Spindleshanks died unexpectedly, apparently
1 CONT killed by a German girl whom he tried to rape. This brought a slight change in
1 CONT the situation of Władysław, because before his uncle's death, all his rights
1 CONT to inheritance passed to Henry I the Bearded.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Policy of cooperation with the Church. Rebellion of the local nobility
1 CONT
1 CONT Desiring to neutralize the influence of Silesia, Władysław began a approached
1 CONT policy to the Church. In 1232, he granted the Bishop of Poznań a privilege
1 CONT under which all the subjects of the Bishopric with goods were excluded from
1 CONT homage to the Duchy. Also, Bishop Paul was allowed to mint his own coin.
1 CONT
1 CONT However, this policy of submission against the church brought a negative
1 CONT effect among the nobility, who in 1233 rebelled against him, and also offered
1 CONT the Duchy of Greater Poland to Henry I the Bearded. Thanks to the passivity of
1 CONT Henry I, the revolt failed. Henry I's indifference to Greater Poland was
1 CONT extremely beneficial for Władysław, who obtain from the Silesian Duke the
1 CONT formal resignation from all his claims over the inheritance of Władysław III
1 CONT Spindleshanks.
1 CONT
1 CONT The conclusion of peace enabled Władysław and Henry (Henry I's son and heir)
1 CONT to participate jointly with Konrad I of Masovia in the expedition organized by
1 CONT the Teutonic Knights against the Prussians during 1233-1234.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] War against Henry I the Bearded. Loss of half of Greater Poland
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1234 their recently concluded peace was suddenly broken, and the
1 CONT hostilities between Henry I the Bearded and Władysław Odonic were renewed.
1 CONT This time, the Silesian Duke was well prepared, and without major obstacles he
1 CONT seized the southern part of Greater Poland. Władysław was then forced to enter
1 CONT into peace talks with the mediation of Bishop Paul of Poznań and Archbishop
1 CONT Pełka of Gniezno. The terms of the agreement, published on 22 September 1234
1 CONT were very unfavorable for Odonic, who had to relinquish all the territories
1 CONT from the south and west of the Warta River, which included Kalisz, Santok,
1 CONT Międzyrzecz and Śrem.
1 CONT
1 CONT In gratitude for his mediation, Władysław extended to Archbishop Pełka the
1 CONT immunity given to the Poznań church in 1232 also to the Archbishopric of
1 CONT Gniezno.
1 CONT
1 CONT With the ratification of the unfavorable agreement on 26 June 1235, both sides
1 CONT seemed aware, however, that the outbreak of a new war would be just a matter
1 CONT of time.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Second Part of the War against Henry I the Bearded
1 CONT
1 CONT The war broke again by the end of 1235, when Władysław (using the unrest
1 CONT caused by the brutal government in Śrem of the Governor appointed by Henry I
1 CONT the Bearded, Prince Borzivoj of Bohemia), deceitfully tried to recover that
1 CONT part of Greater Poland. The expedition ended with some success (Śrem was
1 CONT recovered and Borzivoj killed during the battle); however, a retaliatory
1 CONT expendition of the Silesian army soon arrived at Gniezno.
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław, having good relations with the Church, began his efforts to Rome
1 CONT with Pope Gregory IX for the annulment of the 1234 treaty and Henry I's
1 CONT decision to withdraw him of Greater Poland by force. In 1236 the Pope ordered
1 CONT the Archbishop Pełka to create a committee in order to resolved the dispute
1 CONT once for all. Their decision was favorable to Henry, and after the protests by
1 CONT Władysław, another college produced a document invalidating the treaty of
1 CONT 1234, who in turn was repudied by Henry I.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1237 the hostilities were resumed. As a result, Władysław lost the
1 CONT castellanie of Ladzka. Only after the intervention of the Papal envoy, William
1 CONT of Modena, both sides agreed to a truce.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Relations with Henry II the Pious. Death
1 CONT
1 CONT The death of Henry I the Bearded on 19 March 1238 didn't end the conflict with
1 CONT the Silesian princes, because Henry I's son and successor Henry II the Pious
1 CONT maintain his pretensions over Greater Poland. In 1239 broke a new war, and
1 CONT once again, Władysław was defeated; this time, he lost the rest of Greater
1 CONT Poland, with the exception of Ujście and Nakło (however, later historians like
1 CONT Kasimir Jasiński and Krzysztof Ożóg denies these facts, believing that after
1 CONT the war of 1239 Władysław remained in Gniezno and Poznań until his death but
1 CONT lost Ujście and Nakło).
1 CONT
1 CONT Władysław Odonic died on 5 June 1239 and was buried in the Archcathedral
1 CONT Basilica of St. Peter and St. Paul, Poznań.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Marriage and Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT Between 1218/20 Władysław married with Hedwig (d. 29 December 1249), whose
1 CONT origins are disputed among historians and sources. According to some
1 CONT sources,[3] her parentage is unknown; however, other historians believed that
1 CONT she had a Pomeranian or Moravian origin: she could be the daughter of Duke
1 CONT Mestwin I of Pomerania,[4][5] or a member of the Premyslid dynasty.[6][7] They
1 CONT had six children:
1 CONT
1 CONT 1\. Hedwig (b. 1218/20 - d. 8 January aft. 1234), married ca. 1233 to Duke
1 CONT Casimir I of Kuyavia.[8]
1 CONT
1 CONT 2\. Przemysł I (b. 5 June 1220/4 June 1221 - d. 4 June 1257).
1 CONT
1 CONT 3\. Bolesław the Pious (b. 1224/27 - d. 14 April 1279).
1 CONT
1 CONT 4\. Salomea (b. ca. 1225 - d. April 1267?) married in 1249 to Duke Konrad I of
1 CONT Głogów.
1 CONT
1 CONT 5\. Ziemomysł (b. 1228/32 - d. 1235/36).[9]
1 CONT
1 CONT 6\. Euphemia (b. ca. 1230 - d. 15 February aft. 1281), married in 1251 to Duke
1 CONT Władysław of Opole.
1 CONT
