1 CONT
1 CONT   * Constance was a daughter of Béla III of Hungary and his first wife Agnes of Antioch. Her older siblings included Emeric of Hungary, Margaret of Hungary and Andrew II of Hungary. Two other siblings, Solomon and Stephen, are mentioned in the "Eur
1 CONC opäische Stammtafeln: Stammtafeln zur Geschichte der Europäischen Staaten" (1878) by Detlev Schwennicke. They reportedly died young. [2]
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Her paternal grandparents were Géza II of Hungary and Euphrosyne of Kiev. [3] Her maternal grandparents were Raynald of Chatillon and Constance of Antioch (joint princes of Antioch). [4]
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT ===Marriage and children===
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1199, Ottokar I divorced his first wife, Adelheid of Meissen, on grounds of
1 CONT consanguinity. He married Constance later in the same year. They had nine
1 CONT children.[1]
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance is regularly noted as a co-donator with her husband in various
1 CONT documents of his reign. Her petitions to her husband for various donations are
1 CONT also recorded. She is considered to have sold the city Boleráz to her nephew
1 CONT Béla IV of Hungary. In 1247, Béla conferred said city to the nuns of Trnava.
1 CONT An epistle by which Constance supposedly grants freedom to the cities of
1 CONT Břeclav and Olomouc is considered a false document. The same epistle grants
1 CONT lands in Ostrovany to the monastery of St. Stephen of Hradište. Another
1 CONT epistle has Constance settling "honorable Teutonic men" (viros honestos
1 CONT Theutunicos) in the city of Hodonín and is also considered a forgery. [5] On
1 CONT 15 January 1230, Ottokar I died and their son Wenceslaus succeeded him.
1 CONT Constance survived her husband by a decade. [1]
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1231, Pope Gregory IX set Constance and her dowry possessions under the
1 CONT protection of the Holy See. His letter to Constance clarifies said possessions
1 CONT to include the provinces of Břeclav (Brecyzlaviensem), Pribyslavice
1 CONT (Pribizlavensem), Dolni Kunice (Conowizensem), Godens (Godeninensem), Bzenec
1 CONT (Bisenzensem) and Budějovice (Budegewizensem). [6] In 1232, Constance founded
1 CONT Cloister Tichnowitz and retired to it as a nun. She died within the Cloister.
1 CONT [1]
1 CONT
1 CONT ===Issue===
1 CONT
1 CONT -1. Vratislav of Bohemia (c. 1200 - before 1209).
1 CONT
1 CONT -2. Judith of Bohemia (c. 1202 - 2 June 1230). Married -Bernhard von Spanheim, Duke of Carinthia
1 CONT
1 CONT -3. Anna of Bohemia (c. 1204 - 23 June 1265). Married Henry II the Pious, Duke of Wrocław
1 CONT
1 CONT -4. Agnes of Bohemia. Considered to have died young.
1 CONT
1 CONT -5. Wenceslaus I of Bohemia (c. 1205 - 23 September 1253).
1 CONT
1 CONT -6. Vladislaus, Margrave of Moravia (1207 - 10 February 1228).
1 CONT
1 CONT -7. Přemysl, Margrave of Moravia (1209 - 16 October 1239). Married Margaret of Andechs-Merano. His wife was a daughter of Otto I, Duke of Merania and Beatrice II, Countess of Burgundy.
1 CONT
1 CONT -8. Bozena (Wilhelmina) of Bohemia (1210 - 24 October 1281).
1 CONT
1 CONT -9. Agnes of Bohemia (20 January 1211 – 6 March 1282). Mother Superior of the Franciscan Poor Clares nuns of Prague. In 1989, Agnes was canonized as a saint by Pope John Paul II. [7]
1 CONT
