1 CONT Constance of Hungary
1 CONT
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance of Hungary (c. 1180 - 6 December 1240) was the second Queen consort
1 CONT of Ottokar I of Bohemia. [1]
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance was a daughter of Béla III of Hungary and his first wife Agnes of
1 CONT Antioch. Her older siblings included Emeric of Hungary, Margaret of Hungary
1 CONT and Andrew II of Hungary. Two other siblings, Solomon and Stephen, are
1 CONT mentioned in the "Europäische Stammtafeln: Stammtafeln zur Geschichte der
1 CONT Europäischen Staaten" (1878) by Detlev Schwennicke. They reportedly died
1 CONT young. [2]
1 CONT
1 CONT Her paternal grandparents were Géza II of Hungary and Euphrosyne of Kiev. [3]
1 CONT Her maternal grandparents were Raynald of Chatillon and Constance of Antioch
1 CONT (joint princes of Antioch). [4]
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Marriage and children
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1199, Ottokar I divorced his first wife, Adelheid of Meissen, on grounds of
1 CONT consanguinity. He married Constance later in the same year. They had nine
1 CONT children.[5]
1 CONT
1 CONT Constance is regularly noted as a co-donator with her husband in various
1 CONT documents of his reign. Her petitions to her husband for various donations are
1 CONT also recorded. She is considered to have sold the city Boleráz to her nephew
1 CONT Béla IV of Hungary. In 1247, Béla conferred said city to the nuns of Trnava.
1 CONT An epistle by which Constance supposedly grants freedom to the cities of
1 CONT Břeclav and Olomouc is considered a false document. The same epistle grants
1 CONT lands in Ostrovany to the monastery of St. Stephen of Hradište. Another
1 CONT epistle has Constance settling "honorable Teutonic men" (viros honestos
1 CONT Theutunicos) in the city of Hodonín and is also considered a forgery. [6] On
1 CONT 15 January 1230, Ottokar I died and their son Wenceslaus succeeded him.
1 CONT Constance survived her husband by a decade. [7]
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1231, Pope Gregory IX set Constance and her dowry possessions under the
1 CONT protection of the Holy See. His letter to Constance clarifies said possessions
1 CONT to include the provinces of Břeclav (Brecyzlaviensem), Pribyslavice
1 CONT (Pribizlavensem), Dolni Kunice (Conowizensem), Godens (Godeninensem), Bzenec
1 CONT (Bisenzensem) and Budějovice (Budegewizensem). [8] In 1232, Constance founded
1 CONT Cloister Tichnowitz and retired to it as a nun. She died within the Cloister.
1 CONT [9]
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit]Issue
1 CONT
1 CONT Vratislav of Bohemia (c. 1200 - before 1209).
1 CONT
1 CONT Judith of Bohemia (c. 1202 - 2 June 1230). Married Bernhard von Spanheim, Duke
1 CONT of Carinthia
1 CONT
1 CONT Anna of Bohemia (c. 1204 - 23 June 1265). Married Henry II the Pious, Duke of
1 CONT Wrocław
1 CONT
1 CONT Agnes of Bohemia. Considered to have died young.
1 CONT
1 CONT Wenceslaus I of Bohemia (c. 1205 - 23 September 1253).
1 CONT
1 CONT Vladislaus, Margrave of Moravia (1207 - 10 February 1228).
1 CONT
1 CONT Přemysl, Margrave of Moravia (1209 - 16 October 1239). Married Margaret of
1 CONT Andechs-Merano. His wife was a daughter of Otto I, Duke of Merania and
1 CONT Beatrice II, Countess of Burgundy.
1 CONT
1 CONT Wilhelmina of Bohemia? (1210 - 24 October 1281).
1 CONT
1 CONT Agnes of Bohemia (20 January 1211 – 6 March 1282). Mother Superior of the
1 CONT Franciscan Poor Clares nuns of Prague. In 1989, Agnes was canonized as a saint
1 CONT by Pope John Paul II. [10]
