1 CONT
1 CONT **Duke and King of Bohemia:** Reign I. 1192–1193 II. 1197–1230 Coronation
1 CONT 1203, Prague
1 CONT Ottokar I (Czech: Premysl I. Otakar; c. 1155 - 15 December 1230), king of
1 CONT Bohemia (1198 - 1230), was a younger son of King Vladislav II and a member of
1 CONT the Premyslid dynasty.
1 CONT
1 CONT Early years
1 CONT His early years were passed amid the anarchy which prevailed everywhere in the
1 CONT country, after several struggles, in which he took part, he was recognized as
1 CONT ruler of Bohemia by the emperor Henry VI in 1192. He was, however, soon
1 CONT overthrown for joining a conspiracy of German princes to bring down the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen monarchy. In 1197 Otakar forced his brother, duke Vladislav
1 CONT Jindrich, to abandon Bohemia to him and to content himself with Moravia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Taking advantage of the German civil war between the Hohenstaufen claimant
1 CONT Philip of Swabia and the Welf candidate Otto IV, Ottokar declared himself King
1 CONT of Bohemia. This title was supported by Philip of Swabia who needed Czech
1 CONT military support against Otto (1198).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1199 he divorced his wife, Adelheid of Meissen, a member of the Wettin
1 CONT dynasty for a marriage with Constance of Hungary, the young daughter of the
1 CONT Hungarian King Bela III.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1200 - with Otto IV in the ascendancy, Otakar abandoned his pact with
1 CONT Philip and declared for the Welf faction. Both Otto and Pope Innocent III
1 CONT subsequently accepted Otakar as hereditary King of Bohemia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Golden Bull of Sicily
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip's consequent invasion of Bohemia was successful. Otakar, having been
1 CONT compelled to pay a fine, again ranged himself among Philip's partisans and
1 CONT still later was among the supporters of the young king, Frederick II. In 1212
1 CONT Frederick granted the Golden Bull of Sicily to Bohemia. This document
1 CONT recognised Otakar and his heirs as Kings of Bohemia. The King was no longer
1 CONT subject to appointment by the Emperor, and was only required to attend Diets
1 CONT close to the Bohemian border. Although a subject of the Holy Roman Empire, the
1 CONT Bohemian King was to be the leading electoral prince of the empire and to
1 CONT furnish all subsequent Emperors with a bodyguard of 300 knights when they went
1 CONT to Rome for their coronation.
1 CONT
1 CONT Otakar's reign was also notable for the start of German immigration into
1 CONT Bohemia and the growth of towns in what had until that point been forest
1 CONT lands. In 1226 Otakar went to war against Frederick II of Austria after the
1 CONT latter wrecked a deal which would have seen Otakar's daughter (Saint Agnes of
1 CONT Bohemia) married to Emperor Frederick II's son, Henry II of Sicily. Otakar
1 CONT then planned for the same daughter to marry Henry III of England, but this was
1 CONT vetoed by the Emperor who knew Henry to be an opponent of the Hohenstaufen
1 CONT dynasty. Then widowed Emperor himself wanted to marry Agnes, but by then she
1 CONT didn't want to play a role in an arranged marriage anymore. With the help of
1 CONT the pope, Agnes entered the convent.
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT Family
1 CONT Ottokar was married first in 1178 to Adelheid of Meissen (after 1160 -
1 CONT February 2, 1211), who gave birth to the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Vratislav (before 1181 - after 1225)
1 CONT Dagmar (Markéta) (ca 1186 - May 24, 1213), married to Valdemar II of Denmark,
1 CONT King of Denmark
1 CONT Bo?islava
1 CONT Hedvika
1 CONT In 1199, he married Constance of Hungary (1181 - December 6, 1240), who gave
1 CONT birth to the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT Vratislav (ca 1200 - ?)
1 CONT Judith (- June 2, 1230), married to Bernhard von Spanheim, Duke of Carinthia
1 CONT Anne (Anna Lehnická) (1204 - June 23, 1265), married to Henry II the Pious,
1 CONT Duke of Wroclaw
1 CONT Ane?ka
1 CONT Wenceslaus I of Bohemia (ca 1205 - September 23, 1253), King of Bohemia
1 CONT Vladislaus (Vratislav) (1207 - February 18, 1227), Margrave of Moravia
1 CONT Premyslid (Premysl) (1209 - October 16, 1239), Margrave of Moravia, married to
1 CONT Margaret of Meran
1 CONT Wilhelmina of Bohemia (Vilemína Ceská, Guglielmina Boema) (1210 - October
1 CONT 24, 1281)
1 CONT Saint Agnes of Bohemia (January 20, 1211 - March 6, 1282)
1 CONT (Research):Ottocar I Ottocar I Pronounced As: otkär or Premysl Ottocar I
1 CONT przhemisl ôtôkär , d. 1230, duke (1197-98) and king (1198-1230) of Bohemia.
1 CONT The struggle within the Holy Roman Empire for the imperial crown enabled
1 CONT Ottocar to obtain (1198) from Philip of Swabia the royal title. Holy Roman
1 CONT Emperor Frederick II confirmed the title (1212) and the election (1216) of
1 CONT Ottocar's son (later Wenceslaus I) as his successor. In 1221, Ottocar was
1 CONT forced to surrender disciplinary rights over the clergy to the bishop of
1 CONT Prague but retained control over secular church affairs.
1 CONT ======================================================== Przemysl Ottokar I,
1 CONT King of Bohemia 1198-1230 (1155-1230) Born circa 1155 Died 15 December 1230
1 CONT Married circa 1198 Konstanze of Hungary Died 4 December 1240 Initially
1 CONT confirmed as Duke of Bohemia in 1192 by Emperor Heinrich VI, he was deposed
1 CONT the following year but regained possession of Bohemia in 1197. In 1198 he was
1 CONT acknowledged as King of Bohemia by Emperor Philipp and had almost total
1 CONT autonomy for Bohemia. His title was later confirmed by Emperor Friedrich II in
1 CONT 1212 and this extinguished the control of the Empire over Bohemian affairs.
1 CONT Przemysl Ottokar I then established a basis for a strong Bohemian state and
1 CONT the hereditary rights of his family. Source: Leo van de Pas
1 CONT Ottokar I of Bohemia
1 CONT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
1 CONT
1 CONT Otakar I (also spelled Ottokar or Premysl I. Otakar) (c. 1155 – December 15,
1 CONT 1230), king of Bohemia (1198 - 1230), was a younger son of King Vladislav II
1 CONT (d. 1174) and a member of the Premyslid dynasty.
1 CONT
1 CONT His early years were passed amid the anarchy which prevailed everywhere in the
1 CONT country, after several struggles, in which he took part, he was recognized as
1 CONT ruler of Bohemia by the emperor Henry VI in 1192. He was, however, soon
1 CONT overthrown for joining a conspiracy of German princes to bring down the
1 CONT Hohenstaufen monarchy. In 1197 Otakar forced his brother, duke Vladislav
1 CONT Jindrich, to abandon Bohemia to him and to content himself with Moravia.
1 CONT Taking advantage of the German civil war between the Hohenstaufen claimant
1 CONT Philip of Swabia and the Welf candidate Otto IV, Ottokar declared himself King
1 CONT of Bohemia. This title was supported by Philip of Swabia who needed Czech
1 CONT military support against Otto (1198).
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1199 he divorced his wife, Adelheid of Meissen, a member of the Wettin
1 CONT (dynasty) for a marriage with Constance of Hungary, the young daughter of the
1 CONT Hungarian King Bela III.
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1200 - with Otto IV in the ascendancy, Otakar abandoned his pact with
1 CONT Philip and declared for the Welf faction. Both Otto and Pope Innocent III
1 CONT subsequently accepted Otakar as hereditary King of Bohemia.
1 CONT
1 CONT Philip's consequent invasion of Bohemia was successful. Otakar, having been
1 CONT compelled to pay a fine, again ranged himself among Philip's partisans and
1 CONT still later was among the supporters of the young king, Frederick II. In 1212
1 CONT Frederick granted the Golden Bull of Sicily to Bohemia. This document
1 CONT recognised Otakar and his heirs as Kings of Bohemia. The King was no longer
1 CONT subject to appointment by the Emperor, and was only required to attend Diets
1 CONT close to the Bohemian border. Although a subject of the Holy Roman Empire, the
1 CONT Bohemian King was to be the leading electoral prince of the empire and to
1 CONT furnish all subsequent Emperors with a bodyguard of 300 knights when they went
1 CONT to Rome for their coronation.
1 CONT
1 CONT Otakar's reign was also notable for the start of German immigration into
1 CONT Bohemia and the growth of towns in what had until that point been forest
1 CONT lands. In 1226 Otakar went to war against Frederick II of Austria after the
1 CONT latter wrecked a deal which would have seen Otakar's daughter (Saint Agnes of
1 CONT Bohemia) married to Emperor Frederick II's son, Henry II of Sicily. Otakar
1 CONT then planned for the same daughter to marry Henry III of England, but this was
1 CONT vetoed by the Emperor who knew Henry to be an opponent of the Hohenstaufen
1 CONT dynasty. Then widowed Emperor himself wanted to marry Agnes, but by then she
1 CONT didn't want to play a role in an arranged marriage anymore. With the help of
1 CONT the pope, Agnes entered the convent.
1 CONT
1 CONT [edit] Family
1 CONT
1 CONT Ottokar was married first in 1178 to Adelheid of Meissen (after 1160 -
1 CONT February 2, 1211), who gave birth to the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Vratislav (before 1181 - after 1225)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Dagmar (Markéta) (ca 1186 - May 24, 1213), married to Valdemar II of Denmark, King of Denmark
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Božislava
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Hedvika
1 CONT
1 CONT In 1199, he married Constance of Hungary (1181 – December 6, 1240), who gave
1 CONT birth to the following children:
1 CONT
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Vratislav (ca 1200 – ?)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Judith (- June 2, 1230), married to Bernard of Carinthia, Duke of Carinthia
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Anne (Anna Lehnická) (1204 - June 23, 1265), married to Henry II the Pious, Duke of Wroclaw
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Anežka
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Wenceslaus I of Bohemia (ca 1205 - September 23, 1253), King of Bohemia
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Vladislaus (Vratislav) (1207 - February 18, 1227), Margrave of Moravia
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Premyslid (Premysl) (1209 - October 16, 1239), Margrave of Moravia, married to Margaret of Meran
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Wilhelmina of Bohemia (Vilemína Ceská, Guglielmina Boema) (1210 - October 24, 1281)
1 CONT
1 CONT   * Saint Agnes of Bohemia (January 20, 1211 – March 6, 1282)
1 CONT
